<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-ISLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL ISLAND FORGES NETWORK TO DELIVER STREAMING AUDIO, VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares of Digital Island Inc. jumped 31 percen
Tuesday after the company said that it was working with Compaq
Computer, Intel Corp. and Microsoft Corp. to create a network for
delivering real-time audio and video over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, called streaming and made popular by Real
Networks' Real Player, Apple Computer's QuickTime and Microsoft's
Windows Media Player, allows the distribution of full motion video
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, Intel and Microsoft said they would make a combined
equity investment of $45 million in Digital Island, which is based
here. Digital Island is the No. 2 provider, after Akamai
Technologies Inc., of Internet content delivery services, which
seek to speed Web pages by distributing the content from servers
closer to the user. Digital Island has focused on electronic
commerce; its e-Business Delivery Network offers hosting, network,
content delivery and application services. Akamai has not
specialized, instead going after the entire market.
</P>
<P>
   Both Digital Island and Akamai moved into streaming media
services earlier this year, when Digital Island acquired Live On
Line and Akamai bought Network24 Communications, both of which
provide streaming production services for corporate and
entertainment clients. Digital Island, Akamai and Intervu, which
has an alliance with Microsoft, want their streaming services to
become the foundation for Internet television, but competition will
be intense as AT&AMP;T, UUNet and Intel also enter the market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Digital Island rose $10.6875 on Tuesday, to $45.1875
in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Island said it would roll out the network over the next
two years and that it would ultimately support up to 7.5 million
simultaneous media streams over the Internet. Digital Island has
committed to deploying 8,000 Compaq ProLiant servers with Intel
Pentium III microprocessor and running Windows Media Player.
Compaq's Financial Services unit will provide $50 million in
equipment lease financing to Digital Island and an additional $50
million in financing to qualified customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The target customer here is the enterprise or corporation that
wants to do real business using the Internet and sees the value of
a rich media experience in doing that,'' RuAnn Ernst, Digital
Island's chairman and chief executive, said in a telephone
interview. ``That kind of rich media experience creates more
transactions, creates the decision to push the `buy button' and
that has been demonstrated with customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Intel's hosting service also offers streaming media,
Ernst said she saw no conflict. Howard High, an Intel spokesman,
said that while the two services competed on some fronts, they
could collaborate on others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
