<SLUG> BC-BIG-BROTHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS PLANS TO KEEP PEOPLE INDOORS THIS SUMMER WITH `BIG BROTHER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIA KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Come July 5, the same San Fernando Valley that
gave the world ``The Brady Bunch'' could become home to yet another
pop culture icon.
</P>
<P>
   CBS showed off its custom-built ``Big Brother'' house in the
Studio City neighborhood on Tuesday, and executives are optimistic
it can attract the kind of voyeuristic audience that has made
``Survivor'' the television hit of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, everybody said the networks were guilty, and
rightly so, of not putting on original programming in the summer,''
CBS Television President Leslie Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there's nothing more original than `Big Brother.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, the day before the first broadcast, while the rest of
the country is celebrating its independence, 10 strangers will
surrender theirs. Inside the ``house'' - a prefabricated structure
tossed up in under seven weeks - 140 producers and technicians will
monitor the contestants' every move and utterance with 28 cameras
and 60 microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Every blemish - the physical ones and the personality ones -
will be exposed for their housemates and the American audience to
judge.
</P>
<P>
   In the pursuit of cash awards and celebrity, they will give up
all contact with the outside world - no phones, no TV, no radio, no
newspapers, no mail - until they are voted out or quit the contest.
They could suffer intense stress from being constantly on guard or
humiliate themselves if they are too relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS isn't interested in making their stay particularly
inviting. The front yard of the house is a sea of bark chips
scattered across asphalt - no flowers or shrubs - but the
contestants won't see it again until they leave the show, one way
or another.
</P>
<P>
   Every other week, one of the contestants will be ejected from
the house during the broadcast, based on nominations from residents
and call-in votes from viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The last resident wins the tangible prize of $500,000 and the
less certain benefits of fame.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they can survive the 89-day stay inside the home
decorated in a riot of unpleasant colors - canary yellow, saturated
lavender, bright blue and, in one room, blood red - probably chosen
for their ability to keep participants lively or agitated as much
as to look good on camera.
</P>
<P>
   The furnishings, provided by Ikea, are spartan, mainly raw pine
tables, dressers and beds.
</P>
<P>
   Microphones dangle at regular intervals from the acoustic
ceilings, and cameras perched in the corners cover those zones not
visible from the dozens of lenses behind one-way windows
surrounding the 1,800-square-foot interior. There even is a camera
in the small toilet chamber - the only room with a door - both to
prevent ``secret meetings'' and to ensure the security of all the
residents.
</P>
<P>
   There is a courtyard in which they will grow vegetables and
gather eggs laid by seven Rhode Island reds, hand-wash and wring
their laundry, exercise with free weights, and get wet in a
4-foot-deep pool that measures 5 by 8 feet.
</P>
<P>
   There are two bedrooms, each arranged to sleep five, each
holding a bunk bed, three twins and one dresser.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which premieres July 5, will run 24 hours a day on
four Internet sites and five nights a week on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour program at 8 p.m. every Monday, Tuesday and Friday
will highlight the previous day's events of living in a one-way
fishbowl. Thursday will be a live hourlong discussion among family
members and psychologists, who will examine the give and take, the
romances and the friendships, the quarrels and grudges, and the
spirit of cooperation evident or lacking in the corps.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the previous week will be recapped with fresh
highlights from Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're enjoying our best summer in many, many years
because of ... `Survivor,' '' Moonves said. ``Survivor'' has
stranded a number of contestants on a Malaysian island to compete
for a $1 million prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when you add to that `Big Brother,' which we think could
be an even bigger event, you could see why we say to everybody this
is going to be CBS's most adventurous summer ever. And we are
indeed excited and nervous about putting on a project that is this
ambitious, this demanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The contestant roster, which includes 10 alternates, is almost
set, but producers are keeping their identities secret until the
night of the first telecast. The idea, they say, is to ensure that
the inhabitants know nothing about each other until they meet on
the red carpet leading up to the front door. Moonves said only that
they range in age from their 20s to their 40s and ``there are no
professional entertainers in this group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' launched last year by John de Mol's Endemol
Entertainment in the Netherlands, has been a major hit in Europe,
with audiences growing with each new country's program. And in each
case, the 10 residents have become major celebrities. In Germany,
three of the participants recorded a CD together that has sold 3.5
million copies.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is almost guaranteed a hit with viewers and advertisers,
particularly in light of its smashing success with the tropical
island-based ``Survivor!''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves, who usually squirms uncomfortably or sometimes growls
to television reporters when discussing ratings, was almost giddy
Tuesday while reveling in ``Survivor'' mania, which delivered 12
percent more 18- to 49-year-old viewers last week than the other
five broadcast networks combined.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Big Brother'' is likely to be bashed by social
scientists and media pundits who see such voyeuristic broadcasts
and Webcasts as a societal ill, Moonves sees the show as a good
answer to the summer rerun doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it is voyeuristic TV and I don't necessarily think
it's bad,'' Moonves said. ``I think there is a desire to see this
kind of programming. I think people are interested in what other
people will do in this situation. They imagine themselves in this
situation ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And as I always say, there are 500 channels. You don't like
it, change the channel.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 0007EDT &QL; 
