r a BC-LAKERS-RIOT-LADN     06-21 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-RIOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CHIEF, MAYOR DEFEND RESPONSE TO POSTGAME MAYHEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writers Troy Anderson and Jordan Smith contributed to this
report 
BY ALEXA HAUSSLER and LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; With Los Angeles' image once again tarnished,
Police Chief Bernard C. Parks and Mayor Richard Riordan defended
the handling of rioters outside Staples Center after the Lakers'
NBA championship victory.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with an uproar over nationally televised scenes of police
cars and private vehicles torched and smashed and other mayhem,
Parks and Riordan insisted on Tuesday the Los Angeles Police
Department's failure to move into the swirling mob was prudent and
effective and prevented violence from escalating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there to protect life and to reduce and eliminate any
potential of harm to the people who attended that event,'' Parks
said. ``And although there was some property damage, we believe
that it was a successful event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only mistake was those who showed up not to celebrate, but
to create havoc and vandalism in their city. Life was the No. 1
priority and the safety of those attending also was a top
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor called the police response ``strategic and measured.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their disciplined restraint minimized any possible escalation
of violence,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``There is much to be learned from (Monday)
night's incident, so that we can do a better job of keeping our
city safe.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's 11 a.m. parade down Figueroa Street to Staples
Center, officials pledged ``zero tolerance'' for violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to stand for any law violation by any
person,'' said LAPD Capt. Stuart Maislin.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also offered assurance that their strategy to handle
what are expected to be thousands of protesters during Democratic
National Convention on Aug. 14-17 at Staples Center will maintain
peace and prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   But criticism came from many quarters. The Police Protective
League was harshly critical, saying many officers were horrified
and embarrassed at what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever tactical plan they put into effect, it failed,'' said
police union Vice President Dennis Zine. ``They didn't take action
at the appropriate time. They waited too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the LAPD's response at the start of the 1992 riots, he
added: ``I was looking (at TV) and saying, Where are the officers?
... In my mind, we were reliving Reginald Denny being beaten at
Florence and Normandy (avenues).''
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall on Tuesday, the council called upon Parks to
deliver an impromptu report on the events of the previous night.
Several members were critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the situation should have been allowed to
escalate to the extent that it did last night and the stain on the
city from those images will last indefinitely,'' said City
Councilman Mike Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   Added Councilman Rudy Svorinich Jr.: ``What concerned me is that
the entire nation, and maybe across the world, saw individuals ...
running amok for approximately two hours after this event.''
</P>
<P>
   Some City Council members applauded the police response,
questioning only the failure of officers to cite people for
drinking beer and alcohol outside the arena where thousands watched
the game on a giant TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nick Pacheco, who was stuck in traffic trying to
leave the game, said the situation was different than it had seemed
on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no point did I feel threatened by anyone; they were
celebrating, primarily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nate Holden chastised council critics, saying they
would have blasted the LAPD if it had used force against the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be applauding the Police Department for a job well
done,'' he said. ``It's not what did happen, it's what could have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Business owners cleaning up the damage along the Figueroa
Corridor area worried about a recurrence during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   At Winston Tires on Olympic Boulevard, where crews replaced
numerous broken windows and smashed garage doors, manager Tony
Alfaro said: ``The police say they've got everything covered. But
if they have everything covered this time, why did this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the zero tolerance policy at Wednesday's parade
does not conflict with their statements defending the police
reaction Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the mayor and the police chief said that things
went as well as things could have gone under the circumstances,
that doesn't mean that one can't sit down and assess what could we
have done better so that we can learn from all of this,'' said
Deputy Mayor Manuel Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Cmdr. Dave Kalish, the chief spokesman, added: ``Every time
we have an occurrence, we learn from it. Even though they are crowd
control issues, they are very different types of events.''
</P>
<P>
   At his morning press conference, Riordan set the tone of
defending the LAPD response while adding that lessons can be
learned and promising violence would not occur again.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said the violence and looting were confined to a
small area and were less serious than other cities have experienced
after national sports victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not fans. They are losers who only know how to trash
their city,'' Riordan said. ``We are not going to let a few
hoodlums ruin a glorious celebration for millions of Angelenos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors voted 5-0 Tuesday to
authorize a $5,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of those responsible for inciting the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What began as a tremendous victory on the basketball court
became a black eye for Los Angeles County as the result of
senseless, irresponsible behavior,'' Supervisor Michael D.
Antonovich said. ``There is no excuse for threatening people's
safety and damaging their property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
