<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR THE STARS TO SHINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ A baby step here, a baby step there and the
Los Angeles Galaxy could be off and running again.
</P>
<P>
   The team ended a winless streak at four games with a 2-1 victory
over Tampa Bay on Saturday. It was a satisfying victory considering
that Mexican striker Luis Hernandez is without a point after five
MLS matches and Cobi Jones hasn't scored since April 15.
</P>
<P>
   The two franchise strikers are knocking on the door and
providing good chances for one another. But they need to find the
back of the net _ and fairly soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created a number of dangerous opportunities,'' Galaxy coach
Sigi Schmid said. ``I thought the combinations of Luis, Cobi and
Mauricio (Cienfuegos) playing balls into them was a lot more
dangerous than it has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're starting to understand the system we're playing. Now,
it's just a matter of fine-tuning.''
</P>
<P>
   This would be a good time for Hernandez and Jones to get on
track as the Galaxy faces the two best teams in MLS this week.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, L.A. plays host to the Central Division-leading Chicago
Fire (9-7-1, 28 points) at the Rose Bowl, before challenging MLS
and Western Division leader Kansas City (10-2-3, 33 points) on
Saturday at Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Two victories and a Kansas City loss to Dallas tonight would
leave the Galaxy (7-3-6, 27 points) tied with the Wizards at the
end of the week. That would provide a big lift, considering the
team's 1-3-4 stretch before Saturday's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a victory in the U.S. Open Cup last week, so now we've
got two wins in a row and we're starting to score goals again,''
Schmid said. ``We still haven't scored off the flow of play, but
we're getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defender Danny Califf has been a nice surprise since
getting a chance when central defender Robin Fraser went down with
an ankle injury at the same time Jones and defender Greg Vanney
were called to the U.S. national team for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Califf scored his first MLS goal in Saturday's victory when he
finished a header off a Vanney cross. But he did his best work on
big Mutiny forward Mamadou Diallo (10 goals this season), as he
held the African striker scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Califf was named MLS player of the week for his performance and
will need a similar effort against the Fire, which boasts speedy
forwards Ante Razov and Josh Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny has always shown a very good ability at being able to
mark fast players, even though he's not a fast guy,'' Schmid said.
``When he marks a fast player, he concentrates better. As a result,
he's more focused in the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
