<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPAIRING SECURTY AT LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 21:
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department officials from Secretary Bill Richardson on
down have failed to provide adequate explanations for the
disappearance and mysterious reappearance of two computer hard
drives containing sensitive nuclear bomb information from the Los
Alamos nuclear weapons laboratory. More than a year after charges
that a Los Alamos scientist, Wen Ho Lee, removed and copied secret
nuclear weapons data brought the lab's lax security procedures to
national attention, management there remains shockingly
lackadaisical.
</P>
<P>
   Tighter oversight cannot come soon enough. Primary
responsibility must now go to the National Nuclear Security
Administration, created by Congress in response to the Wen Ho Lee
fiasco. Its newly confirmed director, Gen. John Gordon, a physicist
who currently serves as deputy director of the CIA, appears ideally
qualified for the job. Richardson, who initially resisted the
creation of this semiautonomous agency within the Energy
Department, must give Gordon his fullest cooperation. Senate
Republicans are pressing for Richardson's resignation, but for the
moment we see a greater value in continuity, provided the secretary
will really take on the flawed security culture that he has blamed
for the lapses.
</P>
<P>
   The new security administration was designed to establish clear
lines of authority over the department's nuclear weapons agencies,
replacing the current tangle of overlapping bureaucratic
responsibilities. This structure will allow Gordon to ensure that
stricter security guidelines are drawn up and followed at all
nuclear weapons laboratories. At a minimum he will have to
establish stricter safeguards such as continuous camera monitoring
of all areas where sensitive work is performed, more rigorous
procedures for signing people and materials in and out, and more
consistent use of safes and secure storage vaults for data not in
current use. Equally important is making sure that lab employees
become more aware of security issues themselves. They should know
at all times what kind of data is on their computers and what
precautions must be taken to protect it.
</P>
<P>
   The work of Los Alamos combines scientific inquiry, which needs
a degree of openness, with weapons work, which requires strict
secrecy. Over the years some scientists have clearly grown
complacent about the security side of the equation. That may be
partly because too much scientific research is overclassified,
diminishing respect for security and making it harder to focus on
protecting real secrets like bomb miniaturization formulas and
computer programs for simulating nuclear weapons tests. Richardson
and Gordon will need to generate wholesale change in lax security
attitudes at the national laboratories.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
