<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAELXXX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ISRAEL'S POLITICAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 21:
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Shas party drove its high-pressure bargaining to a new
level of recklessness on Tuesday by giving 48 hours' notice of its
departure from Prime Minister Ehud Barak's governing coalition.
Shas' concerns have nothing to do with peacemaking or the
Palestinians. But if Shas, an Orthodox religious party, carries out
its resignation threat, Barak will lose the broad parliamentary
majority he needs to negotiate a final peace deal with the
Palestinians later this summer as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The issues dividing Shas from its government partners are
narrower than they were a few weeks ago when this crisis began.
Both sides need to find ways to bridge the remaining gaps and keep
Shas inside the Barak coalition.
</P>
<P>
   One of Shas' main demands concerns a network of radio stations
owned by its religious supporters. Currently those stations are
unlicensed and risk being shut down by the police. Shas wants
guarantees from Barak that they will be quickly accredited. The
government fears that making such a deal could create an
irresistible precedent allowing other unlicensed stations to evade
reasonable licensing requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' other main concern is insulating its private school system
from supervision by Barak's education minister, a strong
secularist. It has already gotten extra funding for its financially
struggling schools. Barak now proposes shifting authority over
those schools to the prime minister's office. Shas has not yet
responded to this offer.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' constituency, mainly working-class Jews whose families
came to Israel from other Middle Eastern countries, is a large and
important one. Only in recent years has it begun to be fairly
represented in the Israeli political system. By reaching agreement,
Barak and Shas party leaders can preserve a broadly inclusive
government as well as maintaining the delicate momentum of
peacemaking. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
