A0264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TEXAS-NYT &LR;      06-21 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TEXAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DUE PROCESS, TEXAS-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 21:
</P>
<P>
   Recent developments in the case of Gary Graham, a death row
inmate in Texas who is scheduled to die by lethal injection on
Thursday afternoon, reinforce qualms about his murder conviction _
and the duty of Gov. George W. Bush and the state pardons board to
prevent injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's conviction hinged primarily on the testimony of a
single witness, who testified she saw him from 30 to 40 feet away
through her car windshield. His defense lawyer failed to tell the
jury of the defective lineup procedure that may have guided her
identification of Graham, or of ballistics tests showing that the
gun Graham was carrying was not the murder weapon. Moreover, the
jury was never told of two other witnesses at the scene identified
in the police report, who say the assailant was not Graham.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days Graham's current lawyers have submitted
affidavits from three members of the jury to the Texas Board of
Pardons and Paroles, which is considering his application for a
full or conditional pardon, a 120-day reprieve to permit a hearing
or a commutation of the sentence. In these sworn statements the
jurors say that had they been presented with the additional
evidence, they would not have voted to find Graham guilty.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there is a strong likelihood the outcome would
have been different had Graham been afforded a fair trial. With the
clock ticking toward the execution date, the jurors' statements
have to weigh heavily on the consciences of Bush and the 18 members
of the pardons board. Together, they hold his life in their hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
