r s BC-BBA-LEBRETON-RANGERS-     06-21 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 5 WEEKS, TALE WILL BE TOLD ON THIS TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Minnesota Twins are back in town, but
let's knock off the jokes about small-market midgets and moving to
Charlotte, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   There are no gimmes for the Rangers. Not the Wal Mart-priced
Twins. Not the dysfunctional Orioles. Not even those mighty Tampa
Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   What once was found now appears lost. As they began an ominous
two-week stretch last night, the Rangers lead the American League
West only in losses and inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's early. But let me suggest that it's later than some
people care to think.
</P>
<P>
   After last night's 5-2 victory against the Twins, the Rangers
have 94 games to play. An eight-game sobriety test against the
division's two best teams, the Oakland Athletics and Seattle
Mariners, will be administered next week. By five weeks from
tonight, July 26, manager Johnny Oates' bunch will have played AL
West foes 17 more times.
</P>
<P>
   And that should tell us and general manager Doug Melvin all we
need to know about the '00 Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is different. His penchant is to see sunshine on a cloudy
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we've got the talent,'' the skipper said again last night.
``There's talent here. It's a matter of doing it consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Consistency. The C-word.
</P>
<P>
   A scrapbook of headlines from this puzzling Rangers season would
look like a ransom note. An awful April. A buoyant May. Who would
have thought that, at this point of the season, Oates' team would
have hit nearly as many double-play grounders (81) as home runs
(88)?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a magic secret button,'' Oates mused yesterday,
``we'd have pushed it weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, this club was reared with inconsistency's
bitter milk from the start. Radical change _ and excising a
two-time league MVP from the middle of your lineup certainly
constitutes radical change _ prompts a spike in team chemistry.
There were new and young faces, and both old and new arms.
</P>
<P>
   In poker terms, Melvin tried to fill an inside straight. It
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, does he draw again _ or bluff?
</P>
<P>
   By July 26, the GM should know. If the Rangers, having run their
gauntlet of AL West teams, aren't within an arm's length of the
division leaders, a change in landscaping will be in order.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland, who becomes a free agent at season's end,
figures to be the club's most tradable commodity. Yes, he has had a
maddeningly inconsistent season. But Wetteland's October
credentials alone should be enough to tease an Atlanta, a Boston, a
St. Louis, and maybe even the Dodgers, Indians or Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that first baseman-designated hitter David Segui
would also attract interest. Like Wetteland, Segui would be a free
agent at the end of the season. The guy is a big-league hitter, no
question _ but his presence in the lineup isn't helping Rafael
Palmeiro any, is it?
</P>
<P>
   By July 26, Melvin should also know what he needs to about the
enigmatic pitching twosome of Darren Oliver and Esteban Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty Oliver is ailing. Or, at least, his pitching suggests that
he must be.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver started 30 games for St. Louis last season and posted a
3.35 earned- run average in 13 starts after the All-Star break. The
Rangers gifted him with a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. But that's baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver probably needs to be shut down until his arm recovers
from whatever it is that continues to ail him. He and Loaiza have
been flickering beacons of inconsistency all season long.
</P>
<P>
   Trade bait? Pray tell, to whom? Where? When?
</P>
<P>
   Oates, meanwhile, is left to utter the C-word and wonder if this
odd mix of Rangers will ever show a steady pulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of it revolves around your pitching staff,'' Oates said.
``When they're consistent, you're going to play good baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates is baffled that his team is on the dire end of one of
baseball's most telling statistics _ runs scored vs. runs allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think we could be giving up 30 more runs than
we've scored,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 30 or so games, it's as much a badge of this team's
struggles as anything.
</P>
<P>
   There are no gimmes. The Rangers need to play out these five
weeks, and then plot for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, tomorrow looks a lot like 2001.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
