<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCINTILLATING, HIGH-SCORING FINALS OFFER HOPE FOR NBA FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the risk of descent into old fogeydom, I
remember when NBA teams, as a fairly regular event, made around
half their field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Jumpers were midrange, back-cuts to the hoop were frequent, and
players without the ball moved relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a flow that transcended defenses and whistles.
Which is not to say there weren't plenty of both. But the time
spent on offense was more about craftsmanship than circus.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere around the time of the Bad Boys' reign in Detroit in
1989-90 _ and the testosterone-flattering import of
sports-highlight shows _ things started going to hell.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on defensive brutality created twin Pistons
championships and an ugly trend. NBA coaches could show they
actually counted for something by devising defenses that could deal
more broken concrete than the Kingdome imploders.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't grim enough, the titles won by Houston in 1994
and '95 accelerated the decay. In the playoff absence of Michael
Jordan, the Rockets' strategy was largely about dumping the ball
into Hakeem Olajuwon and watching him decide between his Dream
Shake or a pass to a teammate rooted beyond the 3-point arc. It was
a league-wide hit, although largely a miss for offense-minded fans.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered around these developments were Chicago's six titles.
Splendid as was the achievement, no real trend emerged because the
extraordinary Jordan made imitation impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, his tandem with Scottie Pippen, for a while the
game's second-best player, gave the Bulls a pairing of midsized
players of versatility unprecedented in championship history.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the standard title recipe included a good big man
and a good point guard, with variations that might include a superb
forward (Julius Erving, Maurice Lucas, Tim Duncan) or a dominant
front line such as Boston's trio of Larry Bird, Kevin McHale and
Robert Parish.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the freakish Bulls, the emphasis continued to be on
defense and 3-point shooting. The results were so deadening that
the NBA in the late '90s set lows for scoring and shooting
percentage unseen since the Eisenhower years. Point totals in the
60s and 70s reintroduced a new generation of oblivious fans to the
former existences of franchises in Fort Wayne, Syracuse and St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But after spending a few weeks chasing the NBA tournament, it is
with some pleasure I report a trend:
</P>
<P>
   Hope.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying it's anything conclusive, but I bore witness to
three consecutive games in which both parties scored in triple
figures. My swoon was so severe I had to ask that sharp-cornered
furniture be removed from my hotel room, lest my faintness cause
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Games 4, 5 and 6 of the NBA Finals between the Los Angeles
Lakers and Indiana Pacers were mostly wonderful basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the Lakers tripped on their egos in the fifth game. It's
also true neither team will make basketball historians re-chisel
the ancient tablets, and Hack-a-Shaq and other sins of the
three-hour debacle of Game 2 can't be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, the games were reminiscent of the
stylistic successes of the 1980s, when the Lakers, Celtics and
76ers dominated with ball movement, alert passing, and above all,
quality shotmaking. As significantly, the Finals looked little like
the horrifying ball dispensed in recent seasons by the New York
Knicks and Miami Heat, who are to hoops what bazookas are to
woodcarving.
</P>
<P>
   Of themselves, the point totals are not ends, but barometers of
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's attack was a delight. All the starters are at least
scorers. Reggie Miller and Jalen Rose are splendid shooters. Miller
showed how even pencil-necked geeks can play a championship-level
game, with his relentless moves to get the ball and his cleverness
in getting open.
</P>
<P>
   In the final four games, the Pacers' accuracy from the field was
46, 50, 57 and 47 percent, despite Shaquille O'Neal's presence, and
they set a Finals record with 85.2 percent from the free-throw
line.
</P>
<P>
   A purist might lament the emphasis on the 3-pointer _ their 49
treys broke the record for a six-game Finals by 10 _ but the Pacers
are merely emphasizing a strength dictated by the rules, and not
deploying out of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers' offense seemed less remarkable, owing to its
tendency to stand and watch the large gentleman, it was much more
than a dunking machine.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's passing out of double-teams has improved markedly. Kobe
Bryant's eagerness to slash to the basket instead of dancing on the
perimeter was a throwback, albeit sometimes a throwaway, too.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Phil Jackson's much-discussed triangle offense has
proven to work without Jordan, and within a single season, it's
hard to know whether it is exportable to other teams. Mimicry is
best done when the target is overdrawn, not subtle.
</P>
<P>
   What can be said is that the NBA, with a different champion
three consecutive years, has this June witnessed a rekindling of
the kind of play that made its industry a hot item not so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   If what the Lakers and Pacers accomplished can be fanned into a
flame, hoops fans chilled by too many seasons of
stand-and-shoot-and-slug will warm up to an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at
</P>
<P>
   206-448-8135 or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
