<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-DERAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 60 ARE HURT IN SUBWAY DERAILMENT IN BROOKLYN
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At least 60 people were injured, three of them
critically, when a subway train derailed as it pulled out of a
station in downtown Brooklyn on Tuesday night, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth cars of the southbound B train slid off the
tracks as the train left the DeKalb Avenue station at 9:57 p.m.,
landing upright but hurling passengers up against each other and
the walls of the train, the authorities and passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   The derailment's cause was not immediately known, but Lawrence
G. Reuter, the New York City Transit president, said that the
derailment occurred as the train was passing over a switch and that
the investigation would focus on the switch.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said 10 people were taken to Brooklyn
Hospital Center or to Bellevue Hospital Center in Manhattan. One of
the critically injured passengers had suffered a heart attack, he
said, possibly caused in part by the 100-degree heat in the subway
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the station, at Flatbush and DeKalb Avenues, the scene
was one of controlled chaos on Tuesday night, with dozens of
emergency vehicles swarming the normally busy intersection and
about 30 passengers waiting on a triage line as the police barked
orders at them.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger, Tanya Acevedo, said that a few seconds after the
train left the DeKalb Avenue station, it jerked once, then five
seconds later jerked again with enough force to cause her to butt
heads with another passenger.
</P>
<P>
   She looked up to see the floor of the car carpeted with people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was total chaos,'' said Acevedo, who was nursing a
golfball-sized knot on her forehead. ``There were people yelling
`Oh my God.' They were crying, they were screaming, they were
praying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
