<HEADLINE>
FIRST-ROUND PICK IN AWE OF ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Joe Torres just received a $2.1 million
signing bonus, but the Anaheim Angels' first-round draft choice
looked like any other 17-year-old kid Tuesday when he walked on the
Edison Field diamond for the first time: starry-eyed, smiling and
humble.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, a left-handed pitcher from Gateway High in Kisssimmee,
Fla., met general manager Bill Stoneman, manager Mike Scioscia,
pitching coach Bud Black and catcher Bengie Molina, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angels have made my dream come true,'' said the 6-foot-3,
175-pound Torres, who was joined by his family. He didn't approach
any Angels during batting practice because ``I don't want to bother
them while they're doing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres will report Sunday to the Angels' Single-A club in Boise,
Idaho _ he'll be the only high school player to start his career
there this season _ and clearly big things are expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a high-ceiling, high-end, left-handed pitcher,'' said
director of scouting Donny Rowland, who saw Torres pitch four times
this season. ``He's the kind of player I think is profiled on a
championship club. He's got a fastball in the mid-90s and his
curveball is devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels now have signed 17 of their first 21 picks after
coming to terms Tuesday with second-round pick Jared Abruzzo, a
catcher from El Capitan High near San Diego. Nine of their first 12
picks were pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The only unsigned players in that group are Auburn right-handed
pitcher Chris Bootcheck (first round, 20th pick), Florida Atlantic
shortstop Tom Murphy (third round), Kansas right-handed reliever
Brandon O'Neal (sixth round) and Visalia Redwood High shortstop
Aaron Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland was most pleased about drafting and signing a pair of
Florida preps, catcher Michael Napoli (17th round) and right-handed
pitcher Brett Cimorelli (20th round), who he thought slipped
because many teams didn't think they were signable.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Kent Bottenfield, recovering from tendinitis in
his right shoulder, threw a simulated game and appears on track to
return from the disabled list Saturday, when he would start against
the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked great,'' Scioscia said. ``His pitches were sharp. He
was very strong. I hope he's ready to go this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other injured Angels starters, Ken Hill and Jason Dickson,
are continuing their road to recovery. Hill, out since May 10 with
a pulled rib-cage muscle, was scheduled to pitch for Triple-A
Edmonton Tuesday night and Dickson tonight.!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
