<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     06-21 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES DOWN METS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Hampton stood at his locker dressing silently,
while Armando Benitez, one stall away, explained over and over the
pitch he had thrown and the result of the pitch. Hampton did not
look up as Benitez expressed his apologies for the damage done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hampton had sat in the dugout less than an hour earlier,
watching as Benitez, the usually reliable New York Mets closer,
surrendered a leadoff home run in the top of the ninth inning to
pull a hard-earned victory away from him.
</P>
<P>
   The home run, by Philadelphia's Pat Burrell, tied the score at
2-2, spoiling seven innings of hard work by Hampton. At least
Hampton had made it that far after the elements conspired to ruin
his last two outings, but that did little to soothe the Mets'
frustration after Benitez gave the game away in the 10th and they
fell to the Phillies, 3-2, at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hanging slider,'' Benitez said of the home run pitch.
``He's a good hitter and he hit it. You can't do the job every
time. Sometimes you have to lose. I feel sorry for Mike. He threw a
real good game. I came in for one inning and I blew the game. I
feel real bad for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said Benitez had apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the guy was what, 16 appearances in a row without giving
up a run?'' Hampton said. ``You can't expect the guy not to give up
a run the rest of the year. He tried to make a pitch, probably left
it a little up, and the guy's got a lot of power and he hit the
ball out. He's out there trying to make good pitches and trying to
win. It's part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team game. I'm here for one reason, and that's to
help the team reach and win a World Series. We win as a team and
lose as a team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Hampton left with a 2-1 lead after seven innings, John
Franco pitched a perfect eighth and handed the ball to Benitez. But
the hard-throwing right-hander gave up a home run on a 1-2 pitch to
Burrell, ending Benitez's streak of 17 scoreless innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th, Benitez gave up a leadoff double to Doug Glanville.
After Benitez struck out Ron Gant and Scott Rolen, Mike Lieberthal
lined a hard single to center, scoring Glanville with the winning
run. The Mets went down meekly in the bottom of the inning, as Jeff
Brantley registered his ninth save.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous two starts, Hampton threw a total of just 79
pitches, battling the weather and an injury. Against the Yankees on
June 11, he pitched two and one-third innings before the game was
called because of rain. He started just three days later in
Chicago, but rain pelted Wrigley Field and he pitched just one
inning before the weather and a strained groin ended his day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the injury healed sufficiently for Hampton to take the
mound on Tuesday night, he toiled through seven innings, somehow
slipping around the holes he dug with control troubles to allow
just one run and four singles. He walked six, his highest total
since he issued six on May 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little out of sync the first three innings,'' Hampton
said. ``I started getting better as the game went on. I don't care
if I walk 50. If they score one run I can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza provided an early cushion for Hampton, driving an
0-1 fastball into the left-field bleachers for a two-run home run
off of Paul Byrd in the first inning, his 19th home run of the
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hampton had a rough first inning. He walked Gant and Rolen in
succession with one out, but got out of trouble by inducing
Lieberthal into a 5-4-3 double play. While he did not surrender a
hit over the first three innings, he struggled with his control,
walking five and throwing 51 pitches, 30 of them balls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies broke through in the bottom of the seventh. Kevin
Sefcik led off with a single that deflected off the glove of a
diving Robin Ventura at third base, and Alex Arias hit a ground
single just past second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo. Desi Relaford
sacrificed Sefcik to third, and he scored on Glanville's sacrifice
fly to right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
