<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      06-21 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BLANK REDSOX, 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Derek Jeter and Tino Martinez went out for lunch on
Tuesday afternoon, a chance for the New York Yankee teammates to
think about something other than the task that faced them in a few
hours: batting against Boston pitcher Pedro Martinez. They ordered
pizza and the pie served to them was custom-sliced: PEDRO, it
spelled.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Jeter earned the right to send his pizza back and
have these words added: Loses to the Yanks. Jeter, Bernie Williams
and Paul O'Neill slugged home runs against Martinez on Tuesday
night and Andy Pettitte shut out Boston into the eighth inning as
the Yankees beat the Red Sox, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner is the principal owner of a first-place team
once again. The Yankees (36-29) have taken the first two games of
this four-game series to move one and a half games ahead of the Red
Sox (35-31) in the American League East, and exactly one week after
he spoke ominously about his team at Yankee Stadium, Steinbrenner
cheerfully boarded an elevator on the third floor of Fenway Park on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did great,'' Steinbrenner said, words charging from his
mouth. ``Pettitte pitched a great game. Any time you beat that
guy'' _ Martinez _ ``you're doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had allowed only three home runs this season before
this game; he had not lost a decision to the Yankees since
September 1998. One of the goals against Martinez, Yankee Manager
Joe Torre said before Tuesday night's game, is to try to stay even
with the right-hander, to keep the game close and hope that you can
beat the pitchers who relieve him.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza lifted the Yankees' morale tremendously with his
performance here Monday night, when the Yankees crushed the Red
Sox, 22-1, and Pettitte's teammates could see early on Tuesday
night that he had the stuff and the focus to give them a chance to
win again.
</P>
<P>
   He was working with alacrity, nodding in agreement to the signs
quickly and pumping his two-seam fastballs for strikes, getting the
ball back and throwing it again. Pettitte said afterward that it
was as good as he had ever felt.
</P>
<P>
   A good thing, too, because Martinez was doing what he always
does. The Yankees began the game with just 15 hits in their last
112 at-bats against Martinez, with 51 strikeouts, and Martinez
retired the first nine hitters, six on strikeouts. The home plate
umpire, Larry Young, called out O'Neill on a low changeup to end
the first inning, and started the second inning by calling out
Williams on a fastball belly-button high. Torre yelled to Young
from the dugout, asking facetiously if the umpire was O.K.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte faltered in the third inning, walking Jeff Frye with a
runner on first and one out. Pettitte promised himself before the
game that he would not allow Nomar Garciaparra to beat him on an
inside fastball, but in this situation Pettitte whipped a cutter
and Garciaparra singled to left; self-loathing overcame Pettitte as
he ran to back up home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Shane Spencer charged Garciaparra's single,
thinking the ball was hit too softly for him to throw out Jose
Offerman at home plate, but he tried anyway, grabbing the bounder
quickly and firing, feeling as if he did not make the best possible
throw because he had gripped the ball deep in his palm.
</P>
<P>
   The throw reached catcher Jorge Posada on one bounce, awkwardly,
forcing Posada to draw both hands toward his chest. It appeared to
Pettitte that if Offerman had slid, he would have been safe easily.
</P>
<P>
   But Offerman went at the plate standing, preparing to separate
the ball from Posada, and he was out when Posada showed the ball to
the umpire. The Red Sox did not score in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch singled to lead off the next half-inning, the
Yankee fourth, before being picked off promptly with Jeter at the
plate. Before the game, Jeter had held a remote control in his
right hand, leaned forward and stared at a small TV screen, like a
kid absorbed by a cartoon. What Jeter was staring at, actually, was
videotape of Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The best approach against him, Jeter said before the game, is to
look for the fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guess with his other pitches, you got no chance,'' he
said. ``You can guess with the fastball and try to eliminate the
other pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a 1-and-1 count, Martinez threw a fastball. Jeter
swung and smashed the ball halfway up the screen that is built
above the monstrous left-field wall. It was only one run, but it
was a lead, and Pettitte agreed later that it bolstered his
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Williams decided before the game that the best way to hit
Martinez was to attack him early in the count, to try not to fall
behind in the count and fall at the mercy of his other pitches.
Williams, batting left-handed, led off the Yankee seventh and
whacked Martinez's first pitch the other way, into the screen,
close to where Jeter's ball had gone.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill homered the next inning, a golfed liner that barely
cleared the low wall of the Boston bullpen in right-center field.
It was the first time Martinez had allowed three homers in one game
since Sept. 24, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez left after eight innings, allowing one walk and
striking out nine, but as Pettitte shut out the Red Sox through the
seventh and into the eighth, the boos grew louder for the Red Sox,
who have mustered one run in 18 innings at home against the
once-slumping Yankees and have relinquished first place.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte departed with two out in the eighth, having yielded six
hits in a commanding effort, and Mariano Rivera got the final four
outs for his 16th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees shook hands in the middle of Fenway Park. If winning
back-to-back games in this town, including a victory against
Martinez, does not help the Yankees' confidence, Torre said
afterward, then nothing will. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
