<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS     06-21 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Season-ending surgery likely for Wagner
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
For nearly three months, Billy Wagner hasn't been, well, Billy
Wagner. On Tuesday, the Astros learned why.
</P>
<P>
   A magnetic resonance imaging exam revealed a partial tear of the
flexor tendon in Wagner's left elbow, and he likely will require
season-ending surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner will fly to Los Angeles later this week to seek a second
opinion from Dr. Lewis Yocum, an orthopedist with the Anaheim
Angels. If Wagner undergoes surgery, the expected rehabilitation
time is four months.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-throwing lefthander has been aware of a problem since
late last season, but he has continued to pitch this year while
hoping the elbow would improve. He informed Astros officials of his
predicament this past weekend in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt every time I pitched,'' said Wagner, who has blown
nine saves in 15 opportunities this season. ``All I knew was to go
out there and keep pitching, and sometime it would stop hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, and Wagner failed to find the form that led to his
recognition as one of the National League's top closers last
season. After posting a club-record 39 saves in 1999, Wagner is 2-4
with six saves and a 6.18 ERA this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who blew five consecutive saves earlier this season, was
removed from the closer's role on Friday. He suffered his ninth
blown save the next day when he walked four batters and failed to
record an out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew Billy wasn't Billy,'' general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said. ``The velocity seems to be there. We were all
searching for answers and mostly looking for mechanical reasons.
The fact is the hop and life just didn't seem to be there on his
fastball. Instead of guys swinging through pitches and fouling off
a lot of pitches, they were making pretty good contact. This would
appear to be the primary reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker stressed the injury is not career-threatening and that
no damage was found in the area of the medial collateral ligament,
which is commonly associated with Tommy John surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, 28, said he has been pitching with the injury since the
end of last season. Not wanting to risk further injury, he was
unavailable for the final game of the Astros' divisional playoff
series with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said rest during the offseason helped the elbow, but the
pain began to reappear early this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (team) doctors said to keep pitching, and it would get
better,'' Wagner said. ``It wasn't getting any better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for waiting so long before disclosing his condition, Wagner
said: ``I didn't want to make any excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker understood Wagner's reasoning for not informing the
club sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes guys feel like they are letting their teammates
down,'' Hunsicker said. ``If he would have come to us in March or
April, the results wouldn't have been any different. It's not like
he hurt himself further and could have avoided an operation if he
would have come to us sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   While his velocity remained in the high 90s, Wagner said the
most noticeable difference with his pitching involved location.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your livelihood is a fastball, of course you are
concerned,'' Wagner said. ``Next year I have to come back and
probably prove myself all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner will enter the final year of a three-year, $10.3 million
contract next season.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker said he will go with a closer-by-committee
in Wagner's absence. The Astros used a similar plan two years ago
when Wagner missed a month after being hit in the head by a line
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker will likely use Doug Henry and Jay Powell, who both have
experience as closers, in the role. After Tuesday night's loss to
the Dodgers, the Astros placed Wagner on the disabled list and
recalled reliever Jose Cabrera from Class AAA New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try and hold the fort,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, the Astros have suffered significant
injuries to three players. Third baseman Ken Caminiti underwent
surgery Monday to repair the tendon sheath in his right wrist, and
outfielder Richard Hidalgo will have an MRI today on his sprained
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when we thought we might be getting over the hump and
making a turn, we get knocked back down again,'' Hunsicker said.
``This is not going to be easy to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
