<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. OPTIMISTIC ABOUT HEARINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After a two-hour meeting in which the appeals of three
coaches and an on-field assistant were heard, Los Aneles Dodgers
officials emerged confident about a reduction or complete dismissal
of the suspensions _ in the cases of both the coaches and many of
the players.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 suspended players will have their appeals heard today,
but ground work was laid during Tuesday's appeals hearing for
coaches Glenn Hoffman, Rick Dempsey and John Shelby and bullpen
catcher Travis Barbary. The appeals were presented in front of Paul
Beeston, chief operating officer for the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were coming in, we were optimistic that there would be a
reduction because we were able to tell both Frank (Robinson,
baseball's vice president of on-field operations) and Paul our side
of the story,'' Dodgers senior vice president Derrick Hall said.
``I think because of that, now they're going to put some good
thought into it and make a decision based on that. And I think the
decision will be favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Today) is the players (hearing), but I think (the ruling will
be ) favorable toward everyone. Because of the appeals process,
we're able to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen players were suspended for 60 games and fined $57,000
for their roles in the May 16 altercation with fans at Wrigley
Field. The hardest hit _ and the focus of the appeals _ is catcher
Chad Kreuter, who was the first into the stands during the melee.
He was suspended eight games and fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case when Robinson handed down the suspensions May
24, baseball is expected to establish a schedule of when the
players will serve their suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner the better for us because there are going to be
implications with the roster,'' Hall said. ``Moves we make will
have strong implications on the roster. When looking at the
schedule, you have to worry about which guys are going to be
missing when. However, with no control of that, you just have to be
thankful that they're going to stagger the suspensions so at least
they're not all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Orza, associate general counsel for the players
association, will be at the meeting, as will a contingent of agents
and lawyers for both sides. Beeston and Robinson will be present.
</P>
<P>
   The players association hopes to conclude the hearing in one
session, but Dodgers officials said the matter is likely to move
into Thursday. It will be done in an informal group setting.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hoping Beeston announces his decision within 24
hours of the hearings' end, but because of the volume of
suspensions, that now seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Once a ruling is made, it's unlikely any grievances would be
filed, a players association official said.
</P>
<P>
   As for as the coaches' hearing, Dodgers managing general partner
and CEO Bob Daly, president and COO Bob Graziano, senior vice
president and general counsel Sam Fernandez and the suspended
parties each spoke. Fernandez handled the bulk of the discussions
from the Dodgers' side while Robinson gave his side.
</P>
<P>
   From procedure, which was described as informal, it turned into
a search of what a coach's role is in such an incident. The Dodgers
are saying the coaches were involved purely from a peacemaker
standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the tape and kind of went through what happened,''
Shelby said. ``It gave each person a chance, which was good. We got
to understand why we were fined, and I guess Frank's (reasons) for
suspending the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, Graziano and Malone were granted permission to be at the
players' appeal hearing, though they're not expected to speak.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley remains
day-to-day with a strained right oblique muscle. . . . Dodgers
right-hander Gregg Olson had another setback during a simulated
game Tuesday. He felt stiffness in the lower part of his right
biceps and had to stop after 17 pitches (he was scheduled to throw
20). Olson was hopeful to return by the All-Star break, but that
doesn't seem possible now, manager Davey Johnson said. . . .
Houston closer Billy Wagner's season is apparently over after he
was diagnosed with a partially torn flexor tendon in his left
elbow. However, before having surgery he will get a second opinion
from Angels team physician Dr. Lewis Yocum. . . . Dodgers right
fielder Shawn Green's RBI single in the fifth inning extended his
streak of reaching base via a hit or walk to 50 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
