<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     06-21 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH CALLS FOR BILLIONS TO FUND K-12 CLASSES  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. _ The price of school reform was racheted up
again Tuesday as Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush
promised to spend $2.3 billion on improving math and science
instruction in grades K-12.
</P>
<P>
   That comes on top of the $400 million for improved computer
instruction he pledged in a stop at Vancouver, Wash., on Monday and
any proposals he may make when he stops at an inner-city school
site in Los Angeles Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I propose to use federal taxpayer dollars to raise standards
and challenge the status quo,'' he told a room of teachers and
students at Cupertino's De Anza College Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   While the California economy is booming and voters seem
generally pleased with the way the state is running, public schools
are still a concern to many residents. That's one reason the Texas
governor has focused heavily on education, arguing that changes
need to be made in California and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Art Torres, the head of the state Democratic Party, disparaged
Bush's efforts as ``a photo op education plan.'' But Bush has
concentrated on education policy in Texas, and shows a passion when
discussing what education can mean to the country.
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason American students should be ranked far below
students in other industrialized countries when it comes to science
and math, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the world's leading economy and leader in technology
and innovation,'' he said. ``We are creating the jobs of the
future, but we are not preparing our children to fill them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the community college, Bush quizzed a panel of students and
educators about the need for improved math and science instruction
and highlighted his own plans to jump start those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to challenge the soft bigotry of low expectations,''
Bush said, citing his attempts to improve Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set high standards and we measure _ we measure a lot,'' he
said. ``We measure achievement not to punish people, but so we know
how we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's testing is part of a carrot-and-stick approach. If
testing shows that some schools are doing a good job, they can get
more funds to improve their efforts. But schools not meeting state
or national standards could find themselves losing their federal
education funding, which would then be turned over to the students
to let them pay for a better education elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan to improve math and science also contains rewards
and penalties. He would provide $1 billion to allow low-income
students who take college-level math and science classes in high
school to get an additional $1,000 for college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also would put together a $1 billion Math and Science
Partnership Fund to help states work with colleges to strengthen
technical education. He also would allow science and math teachers
who spend at least five years in a low-income school to have up to
$17,500 of their student loans forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, however, states getting the partnership money
would have to show that math and science achievement is improving.
And research universities receiving large amounts of federal grants
would be asked to work with their states to strengthen math and
science education.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that Bush focused on technical education during
a visit to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important economic issue we have in the Valley is a
well-trained workforce,'' said Ruben Barrales, president of Joint
Venture: Silicon Valley Network, a high-tech industry group. ``We
have to develop a home-grown workforce that brings in the African
American and Hispanic kids that are here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of people were at De Anza to hear Bush talk about
education Tuesday, a change from the hundreds who paid up to
$25,000 a couple to shake hands and schmooze with the GOP candidate
at fund-raising events Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast wasn't lost on the people on Bush's panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of educational problems could be solved if you're as
able to raise as much money for education as you have for the
Republican Party,'' said Barbara Illowsky, a math teacher at De
Anza.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the afternoon, Bush's wife, Laura, saw a different part
of the education mix as she toured a Menlo Park job training
center. Laura Bush, a former elementary school teacher, chatted
with students in a clerical training center and then stopped
briefly at a classroom where about 20 students were training for
guaranteed jobs with Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so terrific to see a great collaboration between
businesses that need people and people who need jobs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also stopped at the child development center, where she
tried to read a book to toddlers far more interested in the
television cameras that surrounded her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just to remind everyone here in the press that you
have to start reading to your babies when they're six months old,''
she said, laughing. ``Even if they aren't listening to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, who has avoided the limelight as Texas first lady,
also had a quick answer when asked if she was prepared for the
inevitable public scrutiny that comes with her husband's run for
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' she said as she followed Secret Service agents to her
car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
