<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS DELIVERS MUCH-NEEDED WIN FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Beating the Minnesota Twins should not be
considered progress for any American League team. After all, the
Twins are well on their way to their eighth consecutive losing
season.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're in last place and spinning out of control, any
victory against any team is worth a smile and a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, trying to get back into contention before their
season becomes irretrievably lost, began a potentially crucial
stretch of 15 out of 18 games at home with a 5-2 victory against
the Twins before 34,608 at The Ballpark in Arlington last night.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Kenny Rogers stopped the Twins on two runs and
five hits to get the victory, and John Wetteland, coming in with
runners at second and third, got the final three outs in the ninth
for his 17th save. They were supported by a 13-hit attack that
included at least one hit from each starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was a good start,'' left fielder Rusty Greer said.
``Kenny pitched well, and we threw some hits on the board. It's a
good start. If we build on that the next 14 games at home, we can
make up some ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't make up ground last night. The Oakland
Athletics defeated the Baltimore Orioles, leaving the Rangers eight
games out of first place. But getting back to .500 and out of last
place is the immediate goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well at home all year, so by no means do we think
all is lost,'' center fielder Gabe Kapler said. ``But we've dug
ourselves a little hole, so we have to dig ourselves out of it. We
just need to think about getting back to .500, then we can think
about catching the teams ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, after their disastrous 1-8 road trip, are four
games under .500. But yesterday's victory was their 11th in their
past 14 at The Ballpark, which gives them hope they can use the
upcoming stretch to get their ship righted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter, home or road, we're going to get it
righted,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``Right now, we've got to
focus on just one game. We can't worry about 15 of 18 or 13 of 16.
We need to worry about the next game and then, after two weeks,
we'll look back and see how we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Some good pitching would help immensely, and Rogers provided
that. He gave up four hits and two walks in the first four innings
but only one run. After his teammates staked him to a 4-1 lead in
the fourth against Twins starter and loser Mark Redman, Rogers
retired 13 consecutive hitters before allowing a walk and a double
to start the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we were in trouble in the fifth inning when he
got into a groove,'' Minnesota manager Tom Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, 6-5 with a 3.96 earned-run average, admitted he went
into the game hoping he would be the one who would get the Rangers
headed in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every starter, when he toes the rubber, wants to be
the one who pitches well enough to give his team a chance to win
and get things turned around,'' Rogers said. ``We need to play a
lot better. We played terrible on the road; nothing has gone right
for us. These next few weeks we have to play a lot better and get
into a groove. Nothing dramatic, like winning 10 in a row, but just
a lot more consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some more offense would also help, especially from the outfield,
and that may be forthcoming. Kapler went 2-for-4 with a homer to
give him a six-game hitting streak, and Greer went 2-for-5 for his
third consecutive multihit game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's time to worry about being eight games
out,'' Greer said. ``Obviously, we'd like to be closer. We'd like
to be in first place. But we dug ourselves into the hole, and we
have to dig ourselves out of it. Tonight was a good start.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
