<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-VOUCHERS-SCHOOL-SFCHR     06-21 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOUCHERS-SCHOOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO GIVE PARENTS VOUCHERS FOR PRIVATE SCHOOLING MOVES
TO  BALLOT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A initiative that would give parents $4,000 to
spend on their child's education qualified for the state's November
ballot day, the Secretary of State's office said.
</P>
<P>
   ``School Vouchers 2000'' would give parents money from the
state's education fund to pay for tuition at a private or religious
school. Families whose children go to public schools without
tuition would not receive the funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this initiative passes, schools will be accountable to
parents and grandparents and this accountability will improve
California's failing education system,'' said Silicon Valley
executive Tim Draper, who is sponsoring the initiative. ``It is
only fair that every child _ regardless of income _ have the chance
to receive a quality education.''
</P>
<P>
   The proponents submitted more than 823,000 signatures to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents _ including Gov. Gray Davis and teacher groups _
say the initiative will hurt public schools by draining resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to have to beat it,'' said Gary South, Davis'
political spokesman. The governor ``made it clear in the campaign
that he is not for vouchers. Particularly in the context of having
just gotten started in major improvements in accountability in the
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is expected to formally announce his opposition to the
initiative Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also argue the initiative would let schools receive
public money without being held accountable to state standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``By siphoning off scarce resources, this voucher initiative
will do nothing to improve our neighborhood public schools,'' said
Lavonne McBroom, president of the California State PTA. ``It
creates a new system of unregulated, taxpayer-funded voucher
schools that are not required to meet many of the state's new
educational standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper's group argues California schools are in such bad shape
they need a major overhaul, not just quick fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Another initiative that qualified for the November ballot this
week would stop allowing cities and counties to impose hidden
taxes, according to its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the California Chamber of Commerce, the initiative
seeks to close a loophole created by a 1997 California Supreme
Court decision that allows state and local governments to impose
``fees'' on businesses. Supporters say they are simply taxes by an
another name.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative would require the state's constitution to require
that fees be instituted like taxes, which must be passed by local
voters or the Legislature by a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``To protect taxpayer and consumer rights, voters must close a
damaging loophole in Proposition 13,'' said Larry McCarthy,
president of the California Taxpayers' Association. ``With this
initiative, voters have an opportunity to guarentee that they will
be part of the decision process determining which tax proposals are
necessary. Without this measure, California taxpayers could face
limitless new `fees' from state and local government, and there
will be no government accountability to trail the funds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
