<HEADER>
A0281 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ALCATRAZ--TOURS-SFCHR     06-21 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCATRAZ--TOURS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE ON THE ROCK: RIVALS CHALLENGE BLUE &AMP; GOLD FLEET
OVER  ACCESS TO ALCATRAZ  
 BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; The trip to Alcatraz has become such a hot ticket that tour
operators reserve space up to six months in advance, while summer
tourists looking for a same-day ticket at San Francisco's Pier 41
ticket booth are often out of luck.
<P>
   The tiny island has never been quite the same since the 1995
movie ``The Rock,'' starring Sean Connery and Nicholas Cage, made
it even more of an international tourist mecca.
</P>
<P>
   That has been good for Blue &AMP; Gold Fleet, which has a lock on
the Rock through an agreement with the National Park Service. Each
day, Blue &AMP; Gold has the exclusive right to ferry 4,200 visitors to
Alcatraz and sell the scarce tickets.
</P>
<P>
   While tourists love the trip, Blue &AMP; Gold is drawing fire for
the way it allocates tickets and deals with tour companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two small Fisherman's Wharf tour operators added new
charges to a lawsuit they filed in October that accuses Blue &AMP; Gold
of violating equal-access provisions of its park service contract
by giving more-favorable treatment to big tour companies.
</P>
<P>
   They also allege that Blue &AMP; Gold violated antitrust law by
threatening to cut off large tour operators' Alcatraz ticket
allotments unless they agreed to use Blue &AMP; Gold exclusively for
their other Bay cruise business.
</P>
<P>
   The ripples from this lawsuit are likely to grow. Red &AMP; White
Fleet believes Blue &AMP; Gold's alleged pressure tactics crippled its
own bay cruise business and is considering filing its own lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state attorney general's office is reviewing
the allegations. And the Park Service has asked Blue &AMP; Gold to
respond to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Blue &AMP; Gold, a unit of privately owned Pier 39, declined comment
on the charges filed in San Francisco Superior Court by Jeffrey
Sears' A American Tours and Elric Leano's San Francisco Magical
Mystery Tours. But attorney Ernest Reddick said, ``We believe this
is a nuisance lawsuit and are confident we will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue &AMP; Gold, which filed its cross-complaint in January, charged
that Sears' pedicab tours and Leano's walking tours were not
marketing Alcatraz tickets as part of a tour package but rather
were reselling them at prices well above their face value in
violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; High Stakes Fracas
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in this waterfront legal brawl are high. Even though
people did all they could to get off the Rock during its 29 years
as a maximum-security prison, now they are fighting to get on.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service limits visitors to 14 boats per day, 300
passengers per voyage, during summer. But daily demand is much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to Alcatraz with 40 Norwegian tourists, San
Francisco tour director Barbara White said she buys tickets as much
as six months in advance. Mark Kern, a massage machine salesman
from Anaheim (Orange County) paid a hotel concierge a $4.50
surcharge for two scarce last-minute tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can't get a ticket to Alcatraz, they want to jump
off the Golden Gate Bridge,'' joked Anthea McGoldrick, vice
president of marketing for Gray Line tours.
</P>
<P>
   Money Machine
</P>
<P>
   The attraction of the Rock has grown gradually since 1963, when
Alcatraz was shut down as a federal prison because of soaring
operating costs. Today, the 22-acre island is a federal cash cow.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 percent franchise fee that Blue &AMP; Gold pays the Park
Service on each ticket ($8.75 for adults) is expected to generate
$1.2 million in revenue this year. The $3.50 self-guided audio tour
used by about 80 percent of the 1.3 million annual visitors to
Alcatraz and a bookstore concession net about $2.2 million more for
the Golden Gate National Parks Association.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of its contract with the Park Service, Blue &AMP; Gold
must charge all customers the same price. But it can sell up to 130
out of 300 tickets per voyage to tour operators, who bundle them
with a bus or other tour and reportedly mark up the price of the
combined package as much as $20 above the component parts.
</P>
<P>
   Gray Line, for example, makes an additional $4.75 per ticket by
packaging the Alcatraz trip and $31 City Tour and charging $48.
Gray Line purchases 200 to 250 Alcatraz tickets a month in advance.
McGoldrick said the company could use 100 tickets more, but like
everyone else can't get them.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Gray Line uses whatever services its customers
want and that she was unaware of the lawsuit against Blue &AMP; Gold.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to the plaintiffs and depositions they
recently took from former Blue &AMP; Gold employees, tour companies
including Gray Line were pressured to purchase all their bay cruise
tickets from Blue &AMP; Gold rather than Red &AMP; White if they wanted to
keep their Alcatraz allotments.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant also allegedly placed similar ``illegal tying''
pressure on hotel concierges to buy city tours from Tower Tours
when Blue &AMP; Gold briefly owned that tour bus company.
</P>
<P>
   Sears and Leano also charge that Blue &AMP; Gold repeatedly gave
preferential treatment to their biggest wholesale customers,
including advance ticket allocations, the most-popular departure
times and, in the case of Tower Tours, exclusive permission to
return unsold tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorney Donald Jelinek of Berkeley said businesses
commonly give favorable treatment to their best and biggest
customers. But he said a Park Service contract requires Blue &AMP; Gold
to ``observe a strict impartiality as to rates and services in all
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the plaintiffs allege that Blue &AMP; Gold enforced
anti-solicitation provisions very selectively. While it allowed
Gray Line, Tower Tours and Eco Tours to sell tickets within 1,000
feet of Pier 41, the Alcatraz tour departure point, Blue &AMP; Gold
banned Sears' company from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just looking for a level playing field,'' said Sears,
who started Barbary Coast Pedicab in 1982, two years out of high
school. Over the years, he and his wife, Helena, went from doing
all the peddling to renting out a fleet of pedicabs to independent
contractors for $30 to $50 per shift. They also got into the
bicycle rental business.
</P>
<P>
   With the growing popularity of Alcatraz, Sears started A
American Tours (so named to get top billing in the classified ads)
and entered into a wholesale rate agreement with Blue &AMP; Gold in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Packaging pedicab tours with 50 or more Alcatraz tickets a day
became Sears' fastest-growing business. Then, a year ago, Sears
says Blue &AMP; Gold amended his contract adding provisions that A
American Tours could not sell tickets within 1,000 feet of the
pier.
</P>
<P>
   Sears refused to sign the non-solicitation clause because
Alcatraz tour signs on the back of his pedicabs generated a lot of
business. Now his tour business has evaporated and Sears said he is
already out more than $50,000 in legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Leano's Magical Mystery Tours, which offered a tour of Alcatraz
capped by a walking tour of North Beach and Chinatown, says it was
also singled out for unfair treatment by Blue &AMP; Gold and joined the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sears maintains his company ``did everything by the
book,'' several Fisherman's Wharf sources said Sears' independent
pedicab contractors frequently violated the law by buying Alcatraz
tickets at Blue &AMP; Gold's ticket booth days or weeks in advance and
then reselling them for big profits on the day of the sailing when
Blue &AMP; Gold was itself sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some pedicab drivers would buy up to 10 tickets at a time and
then scalp them,'' said Colin Jones, a former Alcatraz tour ticket
collector who said he was frequently offered $100 for a pair of
tickets on weekends but always said no. More Legal Clouds Loom
</P>
<P>
   Blue &AMP; Gold's legal battle may not end with Sears and Leano. Red
&AMP; White is trying to assess the damages from Blue &AMP; Gold's alleged
illegal tying arrangements. ``My business has been damaged
enormously,'' said Red &AMP; White owner Tom Escher. ``I've laid off
people and lost money.''
</P>
<P>
   Red &AMP; White knows a thing or two about the Alcatraz concession.
It used to own it when it was part of San Francisco's Crowley
Maritime Corp. Then, in 1997, Crowley decided to focus on
commercial hauling and sell Red &AMP; White's 11 tour boats, ferry
service, bay cruises, Alcatraz contract and a packaged bus tour
business to Blue &AMP; Gold.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a problem. Concerned about a monopoly on the Bay,
the California attorney general's office objected. As part of a
consent decree, Crowley relative Tom Escher acquired the Red &AMP;
White name, three of its ferryboats and its lease at Pier 431/2.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of most of the old Red &AMP; White fleet
nevertheless made Blue &AMP; Gold the Bay Area's largest provider of
ferry and water excursion services, with 13 vessels and annual
revenue of $27 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still interested in preserving competition on the bay,
California Deputy Attorney General John Donhoff said, ``We're
looking at the circumstances involved in the lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the National Park Service. Lawyers for Red &AMP; White and
Sears and Leano have advised Golden Gate National Recreation Area
General Superintendent Brian O'Neill that the Park Service has the
right to terminate Blue &AMP; Gold for material breach of contract.
O'Neill said he has asked Blue &AMP; Gold to respond to recent charges
but declined to comment on allegations. He also said that from his
vantage point, Blue &AMP; Gold has been ``an excellent operator.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Blue &AMP; Gold's 15-year contract expired at the end of
1998 and O'Neill is only allowed to grant three one-year extensions
before throwing the contract open to competitive bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service, which has granted two extensions, recently
began an 18-month water transportation planning study for the bay,
and O'Neill suggested it would make little sense to put a long-term
Alcatraz agreement out to bid until it is determined whether other
sites should be included in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   That could make the end of next year the earliest Blue &AMP; Gold's
hold on Alcatraz might be threatened. Unless, of course, legal
suits cause a sea change.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
