<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0282 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MP3--MUSIC-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3--MUSIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD INDUSTRY TOLD TO EJECT CDS FOR DOWNLOADABLE MUSIC 
 &HT;     BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; San Diego _ With Napster's wildfire popularity, the recording
industry has to learn to fight piracy by serving downloadable music
instead of lawsuits, MP3.com Inc. founder Michael Robertson said
Tuesday.
<P>
   In his keynote address to the 3rd annual MP3 Summit, Robertson
said record and Web music companies can head off the
revenue-sapping threat of free file-swapping programs like Napster
by becoming ``music service providers'' instead of just selling
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to fight piracy is not to wage a war-on-drugs''
campaign, Robertson said. ``It's about simply finding a way to
create a better drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by pioneering Web music portal MP3.com of San Diego
and other companies such as digital rights management firm
InterTrust Inc. of Santa Clara, the two-day event at the University
of California at San Diego is expected to draw nearly 2,000
technology and entertainment industry representatives from around
the world, about double the attendance from last year.
</P>
<P>
   The summit began as a way to promote MP3.com and using the MP3
file compression format to share and download music from the
Internet. But the summit is particularly significant this year
because of lawsuits involving Napster, an easy-to-use software
program made by a San Mateo startup of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry and several artists have sued to stop
Napster from allowing its 10 million registered users from swapping
free but illegal copies of top music hits.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com was also sued by the recording industry for copyright
infringement but has agreed to multimillion-dollar settlements with
two of the top five record labels and is negotiating similar
agreements with the remaining three.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is now positioning MP3.com as an ally to the recording
industry to help make sure everyone gets a slice of revenues from
downloadable music.
</P>
<P>
   To profit from downloadable music, record companies need to
discard the belief that the main source of their revenue is selling
a CD, Robertson said. The movie industry, for example, makes money
from one movie shown in different ways: theaters, home video sales
and cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Record and technology companies could deliver music, like power
companies distribute electricity, in forms that consumers could use
on the Internet, with portable handheld players and in wireless
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's all about CD sales,'' Robertson said. ``Tomorrow,
we believe that it will be about thinking of music as a service.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, who admitted the recording industry isn't rushing to
adopt his ideas, is also trying to push the phrase ``music service
providers,'' or MSPs, which he coined to describe all Internet
music companies in the same way ISP refers to Internet service
providers. This year's summit theme is ``The Year of the MSP.''
</P>
<P>
   Ric Dube, an analyst with the Internet research firm Webnoize,
said it's still ``the year of Napster'' but added that Napster's
grassroots success may spur the recording industry to follow
Robertson's ``MSP'' idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster sent a message to the major media companies that this
is not going away,'' Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   Rap star Ice-T said the controversy over Napster is generated by
lawyers, not artists like himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You going to worry about technology?'' Ice-T said. ``That's
stupid. Technology will always figure itself out. Whatever problem
there is, there's 15 guys in a building right now trying to figure
it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster is like radio,'' he added. ``If you put your record on
radio, people can tape it and hand it around. It's just not
widespread enough that it's going to cost you any record sales at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   An obscure trade show only three years ago, the MP3 Summit has
become one of the major events of the year for music technology
companies to meet and promote new products. The list of sponsors
and panel participants also includes Microsoft, Qualcomm and Texas
Instruments, as well as Bay Area companies like Emusic.com Inc. and
Napster Inc.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Cnet, for example, chose the summit to formally
launch its new Cnet Music Center, a Web resource for Internet users
to learn how to download, play and organize music. There are also
hints on how to better use programs like Napster.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Consumer Electronics of Indianapolis introduced five
portable MP3 players that will be on the market later this year
under the RCA Lyra brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the summit as one of the high points of the year in the
online music calendar, more so this year than ever before,'' said
Sara Perkins, spokeswoman for Rocket Network, a San Francisco firm
trying to make its mark with Internet recording studio technology.
``Every important player in the industry will be there and it is a
crucial networking opportunity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lattig, spokesman for San Francisco Net music company
Kick.com, said this year's summit ``could be a moment of truth for
MP3 technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If (MP3.com) can bridge the gap between the record companies
and technology companies, this could be a landmark event in moving
this industry where it needs to be,'' Lattig said. ``It could be a
moment of truth for MP3 technology.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
