<HEADLINE>
STANFORD GAMES WIN GLOBAL CONNECTIONS  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business plan competitions have become the rage on college
campuses as engineering and business school students vie for
venture capital, corporate recognition and academic degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University this week is hosting the equivalent of the
Olympic Games of entrepreneurial face-offs. The Global
Entrepreneurs Conference 2000, a four-day event that concludes
Wednesday, is the first worldwide business plan conference and
competition among the winning student business plans from 21
university teams representing 14 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the finalists in each of five categories listed by team
name, product or service and sponsor:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Most Innovative Product &LR; : Biomedical Modeling Co., patient
information (China's Tsing Hua University); T-RAM, semiconductor
memory (Stanford University); Personal Integrated Communication,
speech-recognition processing device (Germany's Munich Bavaria
Business Plan Competition).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Elegance of Business Strategy  &LR; (most compelling solution to a
market need): NyteFyre Systems, record-keeping and transcription
software (Purdue University); T-RAM (Stanford University);
M-Contact, mobile service (Korea Student Venture Business Center).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Positive Social Impact:  &LR; Eduisfun.com, education portal (Indian
Institute of Management Bangalore); Latinarte.com, online art
(Argentina team); Setagon Inc., medical delivery system (Darden
Business School, University of Virginia).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Global Market Potential &LR; : ThermaGen, pocket-size soda can that
will cool beverages in less than two minutes (France's Hautes
Etudes Commerciales); EyeGen, bio-markers (Massachusetts Institute
of Technology); Personal Integrated Communication (Germany's Munich
Bavaria Business Plan Competition).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Internet-Based Plan:  &LR; Apparel-Online, business-to-business
apparel exchange (Princeton University); Sydney Worldwide Pty.
Ltd., online city guides and portals for tourists to Asia and
Australia (Australia's University of Sydney).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some business plan contests, this one is not the idea of
venture capitalists interested in spotting new technology and
talent. Rather, it is the brainchild of Ted Acworth, head of
marketing for the Business Association of Stanford Engineering
Students and recent recipient of a doctorate in mechanical
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Acworth says the idea behind the global challenge is to give
Stanford's already well-developed entrepreneurial network a
worldwide reach. He and engineering school colleagues also wanted
to shift the focus of their event from winning prizes and doing
deals to learning and networking.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of business plan competitions are designed to funnel
good ideas to the firms that finance the contests,'' Acworth says.
By contrast, ``The global challenge is not just a money grab; it's
four days of conference and networking.''
</P>
<P>
   The event included a keynote address by well-known venture
capitalist John Doerr and eight 90-minute discussions on such key
issues as negotiating a term sheet, protecting intellectual
property, developing a marketing plan and building a management
team.
</P>
<P>
   Only yesterday, three days into the event, did the teams begin
making 45-minute pitches to 30 volunteer venture capital and
industry judges. Acworth maintains the main purpose of the judging
sessions was for the entrepreneurs to gain useful feedback rather
than win awards.
</P>
<P>
   But there are prizes for five of the teams:
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard put up $150,000 in consulting services, servers
and other hardware for the winner of the best Internet plan.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting contributed a total of $75,000 for four
other awards: groundbreaking product, elegance of business
strategy, positive social impact and global market potential.
</P>
<P>
   As at the Olympic Games, the Stanford global challenge is trying
to shift the glory to participation. As for Acworth, after the
contest he is heading for Alaska to spend the summer as a bush
pilot before biking back to the Bay Area and consulting with NASA
on calibrating space telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
