<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HARRY POTTER MAGIC COULD ENCHANT SCHOLASTIC'S TIMID STOCK  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Scholastic Inc. is printing 3.8 million copies of the fourth
installment in its wildly popular Harry Potter series. That's a
record first-run volume and it's soaking up a good chunk of the
nation's printing capacity. But that doesn't guarantee everyone who
wants the 752-page story about a teenage wizard will magically get
one.
<P>
   Believe it or not, New York's Scholastic, Harry Potter's U.S.
publisher, is being conservative _ or at least realistic _ in its
production schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fairly frugal in distributing (volumes) one, two
and three,'' says Scholastic Chief Financial Officer Kevin McEnery.
``We've been very careful with the distribution (of No. 4) and at
times have not blindly fulfilled the trade demands. We're trying
not to oversupply. Sometimes, logistically, that creates a little
bit of stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingram Book, a major wholesaler, is getting about 75 percent of
its initial order the first day, with the balance coming shortly
afterward, says President Jim Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic has reason to be cautious. The New York company
horrified investors when sales of its last megahit, the prodigious
Goosebumps series, did a vanishing act, leaving stacks of
paperbacks gathering cobwebs on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, its stock fell 40 percent in one day after the
company predicted a quarterly loss of 70 cents to 80 cents per
share, when Wall Street was expecting a 68 cent profit.
</P>
<P>
   The main culprit: a charge of 50 cents per share to cover
Goosebumps returns.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic stock (SCHL), which hit $77 in November 1996, sank to
$21 in April 1997. In March of that year, it was the lowest-rated
stock on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But Scholastic has never been a one-hit wonder. It has a long
list of popular kids' series including Clifford the Big Red Dog,
Babysitter's Club, Animorphis, I Spy, Captain Underpants, Dear
America and Pokemon. By building those brands, and cutting costs,
the company turned itself around.
</P>
<P>
   After earning next to nothing in fiscal 1997, Scholastic earned
$23.7 million ($1.88 per share) in 1998. It earned $36.8 million
($2.20) on $1.15 billion in revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate earnings of $3.20 per share for the year ended
in May and $3.68 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Given the turnaround, and the cacophony building toward the July
8 release of Harry Potter IV, it's odd that Scholastic stock, at
$61.94, is still below its all-time high and is trading at only 25
times trailing earnings, compared with 30 times for the S&AMP;P 500. In
late 1996, Scholastic traded at 50 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have long memories'' and many have not forgotten the
``Goosebumps incident,'' says analyst Peter Appert of Deutsche Banc
Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, Harry Potter is not another Goosebumps. ``Harry
Potter is classic children's literature as opposed to pulp fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rollout schedule is much more logical _ one a year, not
one a month. The hardcover becomes a softcover so there are
residual issues.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't even sold the second two (volumes) in softcover
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Goosebumps appealed mainly to preteen boys, Harry
Potter is a hit with boys, girls and many adults. The first three
books have sold 20.6 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   McEnery says Harry Potter accounts for about $100 million or 9
percent of total revenues. He wouldn't disclose profits, but
typically the publisher and retailer split the cover price 50-50.
The pseudonymous Harry Potter IV _ the real name is still under
wraps _ will retail for $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the initial printing of 3.8 million copies will satisfy
demand remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3, the ``Prisoner of Azkaban,'' sold 4.4 million copies. It
had an initial print run of 250,000 and was frequently out of
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic does not expect shortages this time around. ``We are
continuously monitoring our inventory levels and that of our
customers and we will be reprinting as necessary,'' spokeswoman
Judy Corman says.
</P>
<P>
   At Amazon.com, advance orders stood at 176,539 last night and
are growing by about 500 per hour, ``significantly up from a few
days ago,'' says Lynn Blake, general manager of Amazon books.
Amazon will start receiving books this week and Blake says she
``feels confident we'll receive the amount we requested.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller bookstores also expect to get their orders filled. ``No.
3 was out of stock pretty continuously for a few months last year.
But I think they've learned their lesson with No. 4,'' says Martha
Jackson of Book Passage in Corte Madera.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Wynne, co-owner of Cover to Cover in San Francisco, where
Harry Potter author J.K. Rowling appeared last fall, says the
initial printing is ``outrageously large, bigger than John Grisham.
If they were to run out, blood would flow in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Appert thinks the stock will get a short-term boost as
Harry Potter buzz builds. It's up almost $8 per share in the last
week. But, he says, investors should look beyond the Potter
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, you had (volumes) one, two and three all
contributing (to revenues) at once. But you will not sustain the
unit volume sales you had last year. There's little question that
Harry Potter revenues (overall) will be down this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-term gain, he says, will come from a ``significant
increase in operating margins over the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Management has said it expects to increase operating margins
from about 7 percent this year to about 10 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are also bullish about Scholastic's pending acquisition
of Grolier Inc. for $400 million. Grolier is about half the size of
Scholastic. It's the largest direct-mail marketer of books for kids
under age 5 and is a major publisher of online and print children's
reference products, sold primarily to libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic is the leading publisher of books for kids ages 6
through high school. It's also the largest operator of
book-ordering clubs and book fairs in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Sweeting, a senior vice president with Templeton Global
Advisors, sees all kinds of cross-selling opportunities. Scholastic
could sell its titles through Grolier's direct-marketing and
library channels, and Grolier could sell its reference works
through Scholastic's school channels.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting's firm started buying stock in Scholastic a few years
ago, betting on a turnaround. Once the stock rebounded, ``we
reduced our positions a bit, but we're quite comfortable with the
long-term prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   She considers Scholastic a classic case of ``growth at a
reasonable price.'' It is selling at 19.5 times estimated earnings,
and its long-term growth rate is 18.3. That gives it a PE-to-growth
ratio of 1.06, which is attractive to GARP investors.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic won't get any revenues from the movie version of
Harry Potter, scheduled for release in November 2001. But movie
hype may renew interest in the books, if everyone hasn't read them
by then.
</P>
<P>
   What's the worst that could happen? ``I have recurring
nightmares that on July 9 we'll read in the New York Times book
review that Harry Potter 4 is not so great after all,'' says
Appert.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
