<SLUG> BC-RESIDENCY-REQUIREMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT INVALIDATES RESIDENCY REQUIREMENT FOR
CONGRESSIONAL  CANDIDATES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal appeals court struck down Tuesday a
state law requiring candidates for the U.S. House of
Representatives to be California residents when they file for
candidacy, ruling in favor of a Nevada man who wanted to run for a
seat in Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. Constitution requires members of Congress to be
residents of the state they serve once they're elected, the U.S.
Court of Appeals in San Francisco said that the state cannot
require them to be living in the state when they file their
nomination papers.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires candidates to file for congressional seats
more than 83 days before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Bill Jones called the concept of someone from
out of state representing the people of California a ``nutty idea''
and vowed to appeal the ruling to the U.S. Supreme Court if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally reject with all due respect to the Ninth Circuit any
assumption that we are going to have state boundaries evaporate,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   While most states have similar residency requirements, San
Francisco lawyer Joseph Remcho, who represented Democrats in their
unsuccessful challenge of term limits for state lawmakers, said
that the decision is not expected to have much of a practical
impact on Congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could not imagine a ``serious candidate'' refusing to
move to the state where they're running for office unless they win
the election.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton and her husband bought a home last year in
Westchester County, north of New York City, because she needed a
New York address to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision was a victory for Michael Schaefer, a Nevada
resident who wanted to run in the special Congressional election in
April 1998 for the vacancy held by the late Sonny Bono.
</P>
<P>
   The registrar of voters for Riverside County refused to give him
the required papers because he was not registered to vote in the
state. Bono's widow Mary won the election, but Schaefer still
pursued his lawsuit, seeking a declaration of his rights to run for
a congressional seat in California.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's opinion, the three-judge panel said that even
though it was too late for Schaefer to run for Bono's seat, the
issue needed to be resolved for future candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In finding that the state residency requirement was
unconstitutional, the federal appeals court relied on a 1995 U.S.
Supreme Court ruling striking down state laws setting term limits
for members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The federal constitution explicitly sets out the qualifications
for members of Congress, wrote the judges, noting that the framers
of the constitution specifically rejected any requirement of
in-state residency before the election.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected the state's argument that it had the power to
set procedures for federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The California residency requirement has the likely effect of
handicapping the class of nonresident candidates who would
otherwise meet the requirements of the Qualifications Clause,''
wrote Judge Diarmuid O'Scannlain of Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer, who lives in North Las Vegas, said that eventually he
would like to sit in the U.S. House of Representative. For now, he
said, he is running for the local justice of the peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
