<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN--PROBE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OF CARDS BROUGHT DOWN BY INTEREST-RATE PITCH 
 &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
It came down to the simple act of refusing to tell consumers what
rate they would pay on transferred credit card balances.
<P>
   In their consumer fraud probe of credit card giant Providian
Financial, the San Francisco district attorney's office and federal
bank regulators found a range of practices they considered shady.
One of their top concerns was a sales pitch that promised savings
on transferred balances but failed to disclose interest rates, The
Chronicle has learned.
</P>
<P>
   A ban on that practice is a key part of a more-than $300 million
agreement to settle fraud charges that the law enforcement agencies
and San Francisco's Providian are likely to unveil in the next few
days, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, if approved, will be one of the largest
settlements reached in a consumer finance case, topping the $265
million retailer Sears Roebuck agreed to pay three years ago for
improperly dunning customers who had declared bankruptcy.
``Everybody is shocked by the size of the settlement,`` said Mark
Alpert, an analyst with the brokerage firm Deutsche Banc Alex.
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Tuesday, Providian confirmed it is near
an agreement with the district attorney's office and the Office of
the Comptroller of the Currency, the U.S. regulatory agency that
supervises the company's banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement would require the nation's sixth-largest issuer of
bank credit cards to pay a fine, reimburse victimized customers and
clean up certain business practices, the company noted. It said it
has already made many of the required changes.
</P>
<P>
   Providian didn't disclose the size of the settlement. But it
said it expects to take a charge against earnings of $1.12 to $1.17
a share to cover settlement costs, an amount analysts said was
consistent with the $300 million-plus figure. If a settlement is
reached, the company expects earnings per diluted share in the
second quarter of between 39 and 44 cents, about 66 percent below
Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   After initially jumping, the company's shares fell back as
investors digested the news, closing at $93.41, down 31 cents. The
stock dropped because the settlement is about 10 times larger than
had been expected and curbs on the company's business practices may
trim profit growth, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Providian that emerges from this settlement is going to be
a very different company,'' said Jefferies &AMP; Co. analyst Charlotte
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Providian said in its statement that settlement talks centered
on marketing and sales practices directed at the company's most
creditworthy customers. The company is best known for selling cards
to people with tarnished credit records.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to elaborate. But people familiar with the
case said the district attorney's and comptroller's offices
demanded that Providian halt its so-called Guaranteed Savings Rate
marketing pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That come-on promised to give customers who transferred balances
from other cards ``a rate that is guaranteed to save you money.''
Telemarketers were instructed not to tell customers what they would
be charged, but, if pressed, to say the rate would be 0.3 percent
better than the average they paid on other cards. Federal
regulations require lenders to clearly disclose rates and terms.
</P>
<P>
   Providian spokesman Alan Elias said the company stopped using
the pitch to solicit new customers several months ago and planned
to end the practice with existing clients later this year.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
