<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0287 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LEVIS--IMPROVES-SFCHR     06-21 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS--IMPROVES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FADING LEVI'S STARTS TO SHOW SIGNS OF LIFE 
 &HT;     BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Business is looking up for Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., the troubled San
Francisco jeansmaker whose sales have nose-dived in recent years.
<P>
   Although its performance remains well below par, Levi's, which
recently installed a new management team, has managed to stem its
sliding sales, fatten its profits, pay down debt and improve its
cash flow, according to financial results released Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Net income jumped 48 percent for the quarter to $45 million from
$30.4 million, the result of U.S. plant closings and other
cost-cutting measures. Levi's posted net income of $110.2 million
in the first half, compared with a loss of $206.8 million in the
comparable 1999 period.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the second quarter, which ended May 28, fell 6.4
percent to $1.15 billion, with currency changes accounting for one
percentage point of the decline. That compares with a drop of 15
percent in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Marineau, Levi's chief executive, said the company is on
track to post single-digit sales declines for the year instead of
the double-digit drop he expected when he came aboard in September.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Levi's sales plummeted to $5.1 billion from a peak of
$7.1 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope sales will be equal to a year ago as we end the year,
so we can stabilize the business or grow it modestly in 2001,''
said Marineau, a former PepsiCo executive who received a $3 million
signing bonus for joining Levi's.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to robust cash flows from operations, Levi's is paying
down its debt faster than anticipated. Debt stood at $2.3 billion
on May 28, down from $2.4 billion at the end of the fiscal first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of fiscal 1999, the company's indebtedness stood at
$2.7 billion, or more than half of its annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, sales of Levi's, Dockers and Slates clothing
declined 4.9 percent in North and South America for the quarter.
European sales fell 17.4 percent, with currency fluctuations
accounting for more than one-third of the European decline.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in Japan and the rest of Asia leaped 21.9 percent due to a
stronger dollar and improved economic conditions in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's is slowly improving its timely fulfillment of retailers'
orders, but ``we still have problems we need to fix'' in the supply
chain, Marineau said. A complete overhaul will take 18 to 30
months, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   For the crucial back-to-school season, which begins in August,
Marineau said he is confident that 95 percent of orders placed
before the season starts will be delivered complete and on time.
``That is a substantial improvement over where we were just a year
ago,'' he said, declining to disclose the earlier fulfillment rate.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, some retailers have been selling out of
Levi's because their order levels have been based on past demand
and didn't take into account recent fashion and marketing
initiatives, Marineau said.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's forecasters have begun working with retailers to develop
more realistic order levels, which will be in place for the
back-to-school season, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Levi's will roll out two advertising campaigns, one
featuring its pricey, futuristic-looking ``engineered jeans,''
which sell for $70 to $75, and one focusing on basic products,
including loose-fitting 569 jeans and a new line of Levi's
corduroys. The tag line will be ``Make them your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Engineered jeans have proven a big hit in Europe and Asia, where
they were introduced six months ago and already account for 8 to 10
percent of sales. The jeans are made from a dark, stretchy fabric
and are designed with twisted side seams and other features to make
them more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The rollout of engineered jeans has been slower in the United
States, in part because retailers were not convinced the
odd-looking pants would sell. But sales are strong in the 100 U.S.
specialty stores that carry them, and by August, distribution will
be expanded to 300 domestic stores.
</P>
<P>
   Although engineered jeans will never account for the bulk of
Levi's sales, ``they are allowing us to restore Levi's image and
the whole idea that (Levi's) is a hot brand,'' Marineau said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite significant brand erosion in the 1990s, Levi's is still
the first jean mentioned by American 15- to 29-year-olds when asked
to name a jeans brand. The company's market share has held steady
for the past year at about 15 percent after declining for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   One hopeful sign is a 20 percent increase in unit sales in the
United Kingdom, which Levi's is using as a test market for new
advertising, products and retail displays, Marineau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is that we're on the right track,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trading of Levi's corporate bonds also reflects a greater level
of confidence on Wall Street. Prices have also increased to more
than $83 from the $50s earlier this year. The bonds have a face
value of $100.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's stopped reporting detailed financial results after a 1996
buyout by the Haas family, which owns the company. Yesterday's
quarterly report is the second it has filed since registering its
bonds with the SEC in February, which triggered public disclosure
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
