<HEADER>
A0288 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-ENVIRONMENT-POLL-SFCH     06-21 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-POLL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ENVIRONMENT A BIG CONCERN FOR CALIFORNIANS, POLL SHOWS  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new poll finds that Californians are greatly
concerned about the environment and are willing to tolerate higher
housing and gasoline prices to protect the state's natural heritage
_ but they would rather not endure higher taxes to pay for cleanups
or land acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted by the Public Policy Institute of California
and the David and Lucile Packard Foundation, apparently is the most
comprehensive environmental survey ever conducted in the state.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people were questioned from various regions of
California. Latinos were broken out as a separate survey group,
reflecting the fact that they are California's fastest growing
ethnic group, said pollster Mark Baldassare, a senior fellow of the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   The sampling error for the survey is plus or minus 2 percent,
Baldassare said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the poll's key findings:
</P>
<P>
   -- Seventy percent of state residents see environmental problems
as a threat to their health and well-being, with 1 in 4 one in four
 &LR; characterizing the danger as ``very serious'' and almost half
considering the problem ``somewhat serious.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Half of all residents say state government efforts to protect
the environment are inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Air pollution tops the list of concerns, followed
respectively by runaway development, general pollution, water
pollution, traffic congestion and inadequate or unsafe water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   -- The majority of residents say they favor using public funds
to buy undeveloped land to slow growth, but become ambivalent when
given the choice of using surplus government revenues for tax cuts
or protecting open space.
</P>
<P>
   -- Latinos are more concerned about the environment than the
public at large.
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare said a strong economy and progress on other issues
such as crime and education may have shifted public focus to the
environment and may become a hot button issue in the upcoming
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is good and crime is down, and most people are
satisfied with progress on education,'' he said. ``(People) want to
hear from candidates on environmental issues, and the candidates
will have to address those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Californians are somewhat pessimistic about the environmental
future of the state _ especially so in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   By a 2-to-1 ratio, the largest of any region in the state, more
Bay Area respondents said their region will be a worse place to
live in 2010 than said it will be a better place to live _ 43
percent versus 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 36 percent predicted worse conditions, compared with
27 percent who said their region will be a better place to live in
2010. Only in the Central Valley did optimists edge out pessimists,
with 34 percent saying the region will be a better place and 31
percent saying it will be a worse place.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that Gov. Gray Davis ranked higher with
Californians on economic issues than environmental ones.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine percent of state residents approved of the way Davis
handled economic issues, while 29 percent disapproved and 22
percent had no opinion. But on environmental matters, only 36
percent approved of Davis' performance in office, while 28 percent
disapproved and 36 percent were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Most Californians feel current state efforts to halt
environmental decay are inadequate, said Baldassare. Fifty percent
of adults said state government is not doing enough to protect the
environment, compared with 37 percent who said ``just enough'' is
being done.
</P>
<P>
   While most Californians expressed concern about environmental
degradation, there were wide regional disparities of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, environmental concern was highest in the Bay
Area and lowest in the Central Valley. Los Angeles generally ranked
between the two in degree of concern.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 74 percent of Bay Area adult residents considered
traffic a big problem, while only 21 percent of Central Valley
residents were similarly concerned. Forty-seven percent of Los
Angeles residents put traffic in the ``big problem'' category.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven percent of Bay Area adults considered population
growth and development a ``big problem,'' compared to 17 percent of
Central Valley residents and 21 percent of Los Angelenos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is much more concerned about the environment in
general and is (particularly) concerned about growth,'' said
Baldassare. ``(Residents) are willing to limit development.''
</P>
<P>
   The one exception was air pollution. In the Bay Area, which
enjoys relatively good quality of breezy air, only 26 percent of
residents considered air pollution a big problem. In contrast, 40
percent of Los Angelenos consider air quality a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest surprises of the survey was the views of
Latinos, said Baldassare, who noted that many pundits thought
California's fastest growing ethnic group was generally
uninterested in environmental matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-one percent of Latino adults consider environmental
problems very serious, compared to 25 percent of adults in the
general public,'' said Baldassare. ``As the Latino population
grows, we can expect growing concern about environmental issues,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In protecting the environment, state residents are willing to
put their money where their mouths are _ to a degree.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine percent oppose development that threatens endangered
species, even if it results in more expensive housing. And 54
percent oppose offshore oil drilling in California, even if higher
gasoline prices are the result.
</P>
<P>
   And Californians would narrowly prefer using surplus government
revenues for a public land trust rather than receiving a tax cut,
with 49 percent supporting the trust, 44 percent favoring the tax
break and 7 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   But more than half _ 52 percent _ would vote against a
hypothetical local bond measure to buy undeveloped land to protect
it from development, even if it meant paying higher property taxes.
Forty-three percent would vote for the bond.
</P>
<P>
   (Complete poll results are available on the Public Policy
Institute of California's web site at  &UR; www.ppic.org. &LR; )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
