 SPONSORS FOR THAT SPECIAL DAY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Never underestimate the advertising world's
capacity to stoop to new depths.
</P>
<P>
   Ads printed on toilet paper, billboards on barges in the Bay,
billboard trucks that clog and blight the streets of San Francisco,
the hypnotic eye garbage of the Muni station saturation ads.
</P>
<P>
   And now (trumpet fanfare, please):
</P>
<P>
   Sponsor Your Wedding Inc. As crass as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I now pronounce you man and wife. You may kiss the bride &LR; 
 &UR; and chug this bottle of Colt 45 Malt Liquor, the brew that rings &LR; 
 &UR; your wedding bells! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For $1,000 to $1,750, the sponsor gets verbal acknowledgment at
the reception (``Thanks, Mom and Dad. And thanks, Roach Motel''),
sponsor name on invitation insertions, corporate logo on cups and
other memorabilia, a mailing list of all the guests, and the
knowledge that your sponsorship has cheapened a sacred ceremony!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oh, look at the lovely wedding cake, with The Chronicle &LR; 
 &UR; logo and the cute little tuxedo-clad figures of Scott Ostler and &LR; 
 &UR; Jon Carroll! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I would never sell my wedding to a sponsor. My funeral, sure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I know Scott would have wanted me to mention that he is &LR; 
 &UR; being buried with a can of Johnson's Lemon Pledge _ ``Ashes to &LR; 
 &UR; ashes, but no dust!'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RECENTLY SEEN sauntering into the same hotel room: Dennis
Richmond, anchor of Channel 2's top-rated news program, and Channel
5 general manager Jerry Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't using the bed, but strange bedfellows, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   What's up? Dennis' Channel 2 contract, for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN IT HIT 103 in the city last week, some kids in the south
part of town opened a fire hydrant. Fire fighters responded and
shut down the hydrant, but the kids fought back, throwing stuff.
Damage included a busted $1,000 computer inside the truck. The
truck left the scene under police escort.
</P>
<P>
   YOU PAID that damn parking ticket years ago, but now they're
sending you notices that you still owe the dough, plus a hefty late
fee?
</P>
<P>
   That's because the San Francisco Dept. of Parking &AMP; Traffic has
turned a huge stack of old tickets over to a new collection agency,
and some mistakes happen.
</P>
<P>
   Like to Sue Burgess, who recently had her car impounded for not
paying a 1968 parking ticket. It cost her $391 in assorted fees to
re-claim her ride, even though she says she has proof she paid the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Sue also says the ticket does not appear on her DMV record, so
she had no way of knowing that the DPT had not properly recorded
her payment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal: The DPT has instructed the collections agency
to honor legit proof of payment. The collections people have beefed
up their staff, so service should be improving.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Just because you got your car registration renewed doesn't
mean you don't have any outstanding tickets. Sometimes, for various
reasons, the DMV computer spits your ticket out and decides not to
put a hold on your renewal, even if the ticket is unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   But if you still have a beef about a ticket or about the
collection service, call DPT boss Fred Hamdun's office at (415)
554-9811. Fred assures me you will be treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE OTHER hand, Muni is looking good.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent Metro rider Cuffs Corbett gives thumbs-up to the new
honor system that allows riders to enter through a rear car or door
without showing a pass/transfer to the operator.
</P>
<P>
   Cars load more quickly, passengers are happier,
drivers/operators are happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nightmare is over,'' says Cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Can it be that easy? Why didn't they do this sooner?
</P>
<P>
   SHOUT OUT to We Three, the jazz trio celebrating the third
anniversary of its nightly gig at John's Grill on Ellis. Guitar
superstar Carl Lockett and the boys could be traveling the world,
but prefer to stay home, thrillin' da Grill.
</P>
<P>
   CONSIDER YOURSELF a grizzled native of San Francisco if you
remember who was the first person to drive the 49-Mile Scenic
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   It was Douglas (Wrong Way) Corrigan, who christened the Drive in
'38 by driving it backwards. I'm not sure if that means he drove
the car backwards, or drove the route from finish to start.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, if you have any cool memories of the Scenic Drive, or
attended the World Fair on Treasure Island ('39 and '40), or have
any comments on the 49-MSD, like favorite spots, call (415)
777-7132.
</P>
<P>
   GAVIN NEWSOM says it's a bum call by the Port Commission to turn
Pier 45 over to a firm that will create a virtual-San Francisco
fun-zone attraction with stuff like an earthquake ride and fake
fog.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Newsom and others favor a plan to build an
interactive environmental center.
</P>
<P>
   Citizen Steve Abney says if the commission winds up getting its
way, let's make the best of it by including such rides as a Parking
Space Race, a Looney Muni-go-'round and an Affordable Housing Hall
of Mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   LONG LINE at the bank, and a man whips out his cell phone and
leaves a message:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, beautiful, just wanted to hear your voice. Sorry I'm not
there, but I just wanted to say that last night was  &UR; wonderful, &LR; 
and I had an absolutely  &UR; great time  &LR; in bed. And I'm going to make
sure it happens again. Ciao.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same line, Don Stevens whispers to his SigOth, Nicole
Bilotti, that it's disgusting to have to listen to some jerk
talking to his babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be so sure,'' Nicole says. ``He's probably leaving the
message on his own answering machine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
