<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-SFCHR     06-21 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: SOCIAL SECURITY PLANS PAINT CONTRAST  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In just over a month, Social Security has gone from
the untouchable ``third rail'' of American politics to the main
vehicle for making every American a stockholder.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's proposal Tuesday to create new
government-subsidized private investment accounts as an add-on to
Social Security vividly demonstrates the rising political clout of
the new ``investor class,'' the nearly half of all households that
now own stock.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal follows a plan announced last month by his
Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, to allow people to
invest a portion of their Social Security payroll taxes in private
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   While the dueling plans make Social Security a defining issue of
the 2000 presidential campaign, they also starkly highlight the
differences between the two candidates, who approach the program
from opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's new ``Retirement Savings Plus'' accounts are aimed at
helping lower and middle-income workers _ the core Democratic
constituency _ build retirement savings outside of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore plan announced Tuesday would give up to $3 in
government subsidies for every $1 invested by an individual who
makes less than $15,000 annually and by couples earning $30,000 or
less. The subsidies would phase out for individuals earning $50,000
and couples earning $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's accounts would do nothing to reform Social Security
itself. The vice president has already announced that he plans to
deal with Social Security's impending insolvency by drawing on
expected future budget surpluses to shore up the program when the
Baby Boom generation begins to retire in just over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan, by contrast, would alter the program itself by
allowing workers to invest some portion _ many outside models
suggest 2 percentage points _ of the 12.4 percent payroll tax that
workers now pay into Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to give workers partial ownership of their Social
Security payroll taxes and to allow them to earn a potentially
higher return than the program's current level of 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, hopes to restructure Social Security by
replacing its government-backed promises to pay future benefits
with actual assets in private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore plan aims to increase savings among poor workers, many
of whom live paycheck to paycheck and depend entirely on Social
Security for their retirement. The problem of extremely low savings
among poor workers has long been a big policy concern because those
workers are likely to find themselves impoverished when they
retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any attempt to make savings more attractive to American
workers can only help,'' said William Arnone, director of employee
financial education at the big  &LR; accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young and a
member of the National Academy of Social Insurance. ``At the end of
the day, the only question that matters is ... `Can I afford not to
work?' And right now, most people are on track never to reach that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has criticized the Bush proposal as ``a risky scheme'' and
``stock-market roulette'' that threatens Social Security benefits.
But the idea of private retirement accounts has proven surprisingly
popular in the polls. Gore's new accounts  &LR; plan contains two
elements of the Bush platform that Gore has frequently criticized:
They would allow investment of government funds in the stock market
and would essentially amount to a large tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore contends that the new accounts, by running parallel to
Social Security, would enhance retirement security without posing
any risk to the program itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan is Social Security plus, not Social Security minus,''
Gore said Tuesday in Lexington, Ky. ``It's the best of both worlds,
not the worst of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an interview Tuesday with The Chronicle, called Gore's
proposal ``an interesting about-face'' on stock market investing
and praised what he called Gore's move ``toward my position ...
because it's the right thing to trust younger workers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago that the man was calling my plan to
allow younger workers to invest some of their payroll taxes in the
private sector `roulette,' as if the private markets were, you
know, a kind of huge gamble,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Gore accounts are a retooled and more expensive version
of a program President Clinton proposed last year as part of his
Social Security reform package. The accounts would provide very
 &LR; generous matching funds to low-income workers who choose to set
aside money for their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidies would be highly progressive, starting at the $3
government payment for every $1 saved for low-income workers, and
declining as people earn more money.
</P>
<P>
   Couples earning between $30,000 and $60,000 would get a
dollar-for-dollar government ``match.'' The subsidies would phase
out completely at individual incomes over $50,000, and couple
incomes over $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore adviser Alan Blinder, a Princeton University economist,
said the accounts were ``deliberately designed to be most
attractive to people at the bottom and in the middle of the income
distribution. For people at the top it's not attractive at all,
because they would receive no benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign estimates that the accounts would cost the
government $200 billion over 10 years, a fourfold increase over
Clinton's proposal that takes advantage of new projections of
burgeoning government budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Workers could also withdraw from the accounts penalty-free after
five years to pay for college, buy a new house or pay
``extraordinary'' medical expenses. The provision was added to make
the new accounts even more attractive to low-income workers who now
save little.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by far the biggest incentive for savings ever offered
to people of low incomes,'' Blinder said. ``A 300 percent match is
quite extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   But many policy analysts argued that the Gore retirement
accounts would create a large new entitlement program aimed
primarily at redistributing income to low and middle-income workers
while ignoring Social Security's future fiscal crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``To create a new entitlement at this juncture and not get any
mileage at all out of that by bringing Social Security into balance
I just find problematic,'' said Sylvester Siebert, a Social
Security expert and author of ``The Real Deal,'' a new book on the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weinberger, chief of staff of a 1994 presidential
commission on Social Security reform, praised Gore's focus on
retirement security but said the accounts divert attention from
Social Security's financing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does nothing to increase the return of the assets in Social
Security,'' Weinberger said, ``and it does nothing to make the
system more solvent.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberger also said low-income workers will still have to come
up with added savings to take advantage of the new accounts, which
may be difficult for many to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Gore's plan does is say to those people not earning a lot
of money, who are already paying more in payroll taxes than they do
in income taxes, to reach into their pockets and set aside money to
save,'' Weinberger said. Bush's plan, he said, allows poor workers
to invest money that they're already paying in payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even critics of Gore's plan to bail out Social
Security with future surpluses found some merit in the idea of
parallel private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Penner, a former director of the Congressional Budget
Office, said increasing savings is imperative, especially given the
host of ways that the government discourages the building of
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is reason to try to make everybody a capitalist,''
Penner said. ``I'm generally favorable toward any attempt to get
Americans to increase their retirement savings.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle columnist Debra Saunders contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
