</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PARDON-BOARD (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas board of pardons
and parole will vote this week on whether or not to give a reprieve
to convicted killer Gary Graham. A profile of the board, which is
unlike any other body in the country. They are all appointees of
Gov. George W. Bush and receive $80,000 a year. They never meet in
person but only talk on the phone. They are perhaps the governor's
biggest imprint on executions in Texas. By Sara Rimer. (ART ADV:
Photos [NYT18,19) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LUNG-CANCER-SCREENING (Undated) _ When word got out recently
that two radiology centers in Portland, Ore., were offering a new
screening test for the early detection of lung cancer, the response
was overwhelming. Smokers and former smokers jammed the centers'
phones, demanding the simple, painless test that can find lung
cancers so tiny that they can be snipped out and, doctors hope, the
patients cured. It is a scene that is being repeated throughout the
country as more and more radiologists begin advertising that they
can carry out the lung cancer screening test. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   VOCATION-SCHOOLS (New York) _ Vocational schools are struggling,
in a high-tech, white-collar era. The range of explanations for the
decline of the city's once vaunted trade schools is wide: budget
cuts and the sense that the schools had become dumping grounds for
students not smart enough to go to college; waning interest among
youngsters worried about making their way in a high-technology
economy; the difficulty of keeping teachers who, in a booming
marketplace, have no trouble finding high-paying work.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MOTHERS (Boston) _ At first, it seemed that it might be a
statistical blip. But no, public health officials said Tuesday, it
is a definite and striking trend: Massachusetts, they believe, has
become the first state where more babies are born to women over the
age of 30 than under it. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-CONDOS (Vail, Colo) _ The view from The Lodge at Lionshead
is to die for. Gore Creek babbles along noisily, just beyond
soaring pine trees that seem to reach halfway up the mountains in
the distance. ``You can even see the ski slopes,'' said Marilyn
Dyer, owner of Unit 1 and president of the Lodge homeowners
association, who splits the year between here and Denver. But not
all is as peaceful and serene as it appears outside the back
windows of Ms. Dyer's stylish 3-bedroom, 3-bath condominium. The
Lodge, which was built in 1978, is smack in the middle of a
proposed major development project that town officials argue is
critical for Vail's on-going economic stability. By Michael
Janofsky.
