<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER FINE OUTING BY COOPER WASTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When Kent Bottenfiled, Ken Hill and Jason
Dickson make their expected returns from the disabled list in the
next week or two, the Anaheim Angels will have to play a game of
musical chairs with their starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   When the music stops, they might have to hold a chair for Brian
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie right-hander from USC continued his bid for a
permanent spot in the rotation with another solid performance,
though he didn't have much to show for it after Kansas City scored
three runs in the top of the ninth to score an 8-6 victory over the
Angels before 16,711 Tuesday night at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive start in which Cooper turned over
a multiple-run lead to the bullpen, only to have Troy Percival blow
it. Last week at Tampa Bay, Cooper threw eight shutout innings
before the Devil Rays scored three times in the ninth against the
Angels closer.
</P>
<P>
   Percival gave up four consecutive hits on Tuesday night without
getting an out in the ninth. The Royals tied the score 6-6 on Mike
Sweeney's single _ his third RBI and fourth hit of the game _ and
took the lead on Joe Randa's single. Luis Ordaz drove in another
run with a two-out single off Mark Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped the Angels' three-game winning streak and
dropped them 5 games behind first-place Oakland in the AL West and
3 games behind second-place Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   All this was no fault of Cooper's.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed two runs in the first, then held the Royals to an
unearned run through the sixth. By that time, the Angels had
regained the lead on Tim Salmon's grand slam and a two-run shot by
Garret Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, through six starts, has given the Angels the type of
steady effort they have lacked in a season where nine pitchers have
already been on the disabled list and the healthy ones have been
inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   He is 2-2 despite the two blown leads, has a 3.85 ERA and hasn't
allowed more than four earned runs in any of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   His performance Tuesday night was typical of what the Angels
have received from him. After Sweeney's two-out RBI single staked
the Royals to a 3-0 lead in the third, Cooper retired 10 of the
next 13 Royals.
</P>
<P>
   He did it by inducing Kansas City, which had peppered the middle
of the infield with ground balls early, to keep the ball in the
air. The Royals hit 12 fly balls in all against Cooper, including
five that never left the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper left in the seventh, after his 115th pitch and
back-to-back singles by Johnny Damon and Jeff Reboulet started the
inning. Both runners would score against Shigetoshi Hasegawa, on
Carlos Beltran's sacrifice fly and Randa's single, closing the gap
to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals threatened against Hasegawa in the eighth, getting
runners to second and third with two out, but Reboulet grounded to
third baseman Troy Glaus, whose wild throw was flagged down by
first baseman Mo Vaughn, who tagged a sliding Reboulet.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, meanwhile, didn't do much with Crespi of Encino
graduate Jeff Suppan _ getting only four hits in six innings _ but
they made them count.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the third, Suppan walked Darin Erstad and Kevin
Stocker, then hit Vaughn on the left elbow with a 2-2 fastball to
load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   After raising his arms to home plate umpire Ron Kulpa to
complain about a 2-1 offspeed pitch to Salmon that was called a
ball, Suppan threw a fastball that Salmon blasted over the
left-field wall to give the Angels the lead, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson padded the lead to 6-3 in the sixth when he followed a
one-out, four-pitch walk to Salmon with a home run over the
right-field scoreboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
