<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0296 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     06-21 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIZCAINO TRADED TO YANKS; DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ By the time utility infielder Jose Vizcaino delivered
his go-ahead single in the top of the 10th inning, he was all but
on his way to the New York Yankees. Jim Leyritz, in turn, was set
to be the Los Angeles Dodgers' right-handed power off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The teams had the major points of a trade completed during the
eighth inning of the Dodgers' 10-inning 9-6 win over the Houston
Astros on Tuesday night, and the deal was announced afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But after Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw blew his sixth save in 18
chances, things took on an eeriness. Vizcaino was called on to
pinch-hit in the 10th with the go-ahead run at third and one out.
With the infield in, he grounded a ball off shortstop Tim Bogar's
glove that allowed Paul LoDuca to score. Gary Sheffield added a
three-run homer later in the inning. The Dodgers survived, but
Vizcaino didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a right-handed bat,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``With (Geronimo) Berroa going down, that's something we need
over here. Vizzy has done everything I've ever asked from him, and
it's only fitting that he got the game-winning hit. He'll help them
over in New York and we feel Leyritz will help us here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could catch him occasionally, but basically he's a threat
from the right side, he's an outstanding hitter. Those kind of
people that come off the bench late win you ballgames. It's
something we've been missing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Leyritz, the Dodgers get a proven veteran player who can
provide right-handed power in a pinch. He was hitting .231 (12 for
52) with a homer and four RBI with the Yankees, but he's been on
World Series winners, and the Dodgers like that.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also save a bunch of salary. Both players are in the
final year of contracts, but Vizcaino is making $3.5 million and
Leyritz $1 million. The Dodgers will pick up a slight portion of
Vizcaino's contract, but a final number is yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, 36, who played with Kevin Brown during the San Diego
Padres' run to the National League crown in 1998, won World Series
titles with the Yankees in 1996 and 1999. He can play catcher and
first base, but the Dodgers plan to use him mostly as a pinch
hitter. Leyritz is expected to join the team Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Leyritz) is the bat off the bench,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``Leyritz has championship experience. He's been
on a lot of championship clubs. He knows how to win. He's an
established veteran bat off the bench that can get you that big
hit, and he's an emergency catcher, a third catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers viewed Vizcaino as expendable because of the
development of Alex Cora at shortstop and the way Mark Grudzielanek
has made the transition to second base. He was used under only
extreme situations, though he had the game-winning hit in his last
Dodgers at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not having a good season, but I guess they need a second
baseman who can help out defensively,'' said Vizcaino, 32, who hit
.204 with four RBI in 40 games. ``I'll probably have a chance to
play over there. For sure, I think I'll get more playing time over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   To everyone, it was a crazy ending to a strange game. Brown
allowed four earned runs for the first time this season, Shaw had
trouble holding the lead in the ninth, but 30-year-old rookie Matt
Herges (4-0) came on with two on and none out with the game tied
5-5 and got out of it.
</P>
<P>
   After Vizcaino's RBI single, Sheffield continued his torrid
stretch with a three-run homer. It was his team-leading 21st homer.
He also leads the Dodgers with a .352 average and 61 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in New York before and it's going to be a good
experience,'' said Vizcaino, who signed a three-year, $9.5 million
free agent deal with the Dodgers before the 1998 season. ``I signed
here because I wanted to be close to home and I wanted to play
every day. I started playing every day, then I got hurt and things
didn't go my way. You have to keep working hard and when you get an
opportunity you have to do their job. Now, I have to prove I can
still play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
