<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS TALKING ABOUT TITLE, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KERRY MURRAY  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Just one day after the Los Angeles Lakers
celebrated their NBA championship in front of thousands of cheering
Southern California fans, the Sparks' Lisa Leslie told Los Angeles
fans they just might be getting one more banner to hang in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   And with a commanding 90-84 win over the three-time WNBA chmpion
Houston Comets at the Forum, that dream may not be so farfetched.
</P>
<P>
   Houston (9-2), which took only its second loss of the season,
remains atop the Western Division, but the Sparks proved that this
year's WNBA title is not a given.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes, Tina Thompson and Cynthia Cooper posted big
numbers for Houston, accounting for 62 of the Comets' 81 points,
but the Sparks manged to break Houston's six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we come out and give a concerted effort and don't beat
ourselves by giving up turnovers, we can play with anyone,'' said
Sparks coach Michael Cooper. ``Our team played great defense. We're
a very deep team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who has been hounding his team the past few weeks about
getting the ball in the net, finally got the showing he's been
looking for in the first 20 minutes of the game with successful
shooting from all ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Tamika Dixon's basket sparked a nine-point run that gave the
Sparks a 21-12 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That run was very important for us,'' Cooper said. ``After
that, our defense settled and started sticking its chest out .. it
gave us a little bit of room.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Houston struggled from the floor but did
manage to stay in the game since they were sent to the line so many
times _ Houston made 18 of their 23 free throws in the first half
and made another 10 of 14 in the final 20.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, who came up big with seven rebounds in the first half,
almost single handily put it to Houston in the final minutes,
scoring 11 points in a five-minute period to end the evening with
21 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
