<HEADER>
A0298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SUBWAY-DERAIL-1STL     06-21 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-DERAIL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
84 ARE HURT IN SUBWAY DERAILMENT IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eighty-four people were hurt, three of them
critically, when a subway train derailed as it pulled out of a
station in downtown Brooklyn on Tuesday night, hurling passengers
into one another and against the train's windows, causing many head
injuries, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   As the southbound B train left the DeKalb Avenue station at 9:57
p.m., the third car of the silver eight-car train slid off the
track, pulling the second car with it, said Al O'Leary, a spokesman
for New York City Transit. The cars landed upright, but with a
noise that passengers said sounded like an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was total chaos,'' said Tanya Acevedo, a passenger who was
nursing a golfball-sized knob on her forehead. ``There were people
yelling `Oh my God.' They were crying, they were screaming, they
were praying.''
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials said they expected service on several subway
lines to be disrupted at least through Wednesday morning rush hour
and reshuffled the routes of those trains.
</P>
<P>
   To clear the way for other trains, workers must lift three
40-ton cars back onto the track, an operation which takes two hours
per car under ideal conditions, O'Leary said. Damage to the tracks
themselves would cause further delay, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The DeKalb Avenue station is one of several main transit hubs in
downtown Brooklyn. The B train was traveling on tracks normally
used by the D train because there was a work train blocking the B's
tracks, transit officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The derailment occurred just a few carlengths out of the
station, where the track divides, O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two cars went to the left like they're supposed
to,'' he said, ``but the third car went into the dividing wall''
between the left and right tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The derailment's cause was not immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   Marina Gerkerova, 22, a school counselor from Bay Ridge,
Brooklyn, said the train started to jerk as it pulled out of the
station. Then there was a huge noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train was off the track,'' she said. ``I saw us next to an
N train and I thought we crashed into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed to be happening in slow motion , she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several people screaming,'' she said. ``A couple of
people were bleeding badly from their faces. When it happened I saw
smoke. The woman next to me grabbed my hand and we went flying into
the window.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman looked over at her. ``There was blood coming down her
face because she smashed in the window and broke it,'' Gerkerova
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that 10 people were taken to
Brooklyn Hospital Center or to Bellevue Hospital Center in
Manhattan. One critically injured passenger had suffered a heart
attack, he said, possibly caused in part by the 100-degree heat in
the subway tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People got shook up pretty badly,'' Giuliani said at the
scene. ``Heads were injured and they bounced back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the station, at Flatbush and DeKalb Avenues, the scene
was one of controlled chaos on Tuesday night, with dozens of
emergency vehicles swarming around the normally busy intersection
and about 30 passengers waiting on a triage line as the police
barked orders at them.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, emergency medical technicians commandeered a city bus
and turned it into a makeshift clinic, tying slings around injured
arms, wrapping knees in bandages, and applying ice packs. At 12:05
a.m., the bus carried 24 subway passengers the five blocks from the
DeKalb station to Brooklyn Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Charles, who was on her way home after work, said it felt
like someone had pulled the emergency brake. Passengers fell to the
floor and skidded toward the front of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   She said the conductor spoke over the loudspeaker, telling
passengers he had been injured, and to wait where they were for
paramedics to arrive. Those on the train remained calm, even though
the lights went out and the car doors had opened, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just waited,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo said that as the train pulled out of the station, she
was having a conversation with a friend about the band New Kids on
the Block. Seconds later the train jerked once, then again, the
second time with enough force to throw her headfirst into a fellow
passenger. She looked up to see the floor of the car carpeted with
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
