<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBOTT, RHODES, SASAKI HOLD RAYS AT BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Getting seven innings from a starting pitcher _ that's
music to Lou Piniella's ears.
</P>
<P>
   The man who gave him that Tuesday night, Paul Abbott, seems to
have found the right music for (ITAL) his (END ITAL) ears.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five starts, including a seven-inning effort in a
4-3 victory Tuesday over Tampa Bay at Safeco Field, Abbott has used
the same rotation of music on the day he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   First, Queensr &UR; gfumlaut &LR; yche, followed by a little acoustic
Bryan Adams, then Candlebox. You can see Abbott walking around the
Mariners' clubhouse before his starts, CD player in hand,
headphones duly attached, left and right. He's in his own world,
trying to get ready for battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to admit that I'm superstitious, but that's five games
in a row,'' Abbott said after his seven-inning, four-hit effort.
``Mostly it's positive music that gets me in a positive mood. It's
95 percent hard rock, with a little mellow Bryan Adams mixed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the formula, it seems to be working. In those five
games, Abbott is 3-1 with a 2.67 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, has been a major boost for a Mariners rotation
that has yet to coalesce because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbott gave us seven good innings on a night we really needed
it,'' Piniella said. ``Our bullpen was used up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game started, Piniella was hoping Abbott could give
him six or seven innings, because early exit by starter John Halama
on Monday had left the Mariners thin in the bullpen. There was no
way the manager wanted to use right-hander Frankie Rodriguez after
he had thrown three long innings. Lefty Rob Ramsay, who had thrown
two innings, wasn't much more likely to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott has had a habit of giving Piniella a lift when the
manager has the fewest resources on hand, and Tuesday night was no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   He threw a changeup so hard it looked like a fastball, and
Gerald Williams hit it so hard it looked like a home run. Which it
was, a two-run shot that brought Tampa Bay to within a run at 4-3
in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays didn't get another base runner off Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one bad pitch on the home run,'' Piniella admitted.
``But other than that, I'd say he pitched exceedingly well.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Arthur Rhodes, who pitched 11/3 innings of shutout relief
after Abbott's exit. Included was a ninth-inning matchup against
Fred McGriff, a veteran, left-handed slugger who has the most power
in the current Tampa Bay lineup.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff saw nothing but fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't working around him _ I was just trying to keep the
ball down and stay away from the homer,'' Rhodes said. ``But once
it got to 3-0, I threw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   McGriff struck out in what shortstop Alex Rodriguez called
``maybe the biggest at-bat of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was not over, however. Kazuhiro Sasaki took over at
that point to record his 11th save without much of the usual
Kaz-a-ma-tazz that accompanies Sasaki when he pitches at home.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki allowed a bloop single to John Flaherty before striking
out Bobby Smith. After pinch-runner Miguel Cairo had stolen second
and third, Sasaki walked Jose Guillen after getting two quick
strikes on him. That meant veteran Ozzie Guillen had a shot at
tying the game, but Sasaki induced a pop-up for the final out of a
game that was never a lock until Rodriguez squeezed the ball in his
glove.
</P>
<P>
   With Tampa Bay veteran Steve Trachsel pitching a solid game from
start to finish _ he threw a complete game and allowed just five
hits _ Seattle had to scrape and scratch for every run it got.
</P>
<P>
   The renaissance of first baseman John Olerud saw him hit two
more doubles _ he has six doubles in his past six games _ in
setting up the Mariners offense. Olerud scored twice, once on a Joe
Oliver single in the second and again in the third on a two-out
throwing error by Rays shortstop Felix Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olerud's made a little adjustment with his setup, and he's
driving the ball again,'' Piniella said. ``He's starting to come
on, and that's good to see, because we need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rest of the offense belonged to Rickey Henderson.
The left fielder came up with a two-out, bases-loaded single that
accounted for two runs in a three-run second inning after Oliver's
single had scored Olerud for an early 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trachsel's a veteran pitcher,'' Henderson said. ``We both know
how the game is played. I got to a point in the count where he had
to throw a fastball, and I hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple. But simply effective.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
