<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0399 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SYRIA-WEB-BOS &LR;      06-21 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SYRIA LEADER WANTS TO EASE INTERNET STRICTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ Down a deserted sidestreet, into an alley and up
three flights of stairs is ``Zoni Internet Service,'' which claims
to be Syria's only access to the Internet that is open to the
public and not controlled by the government.
</P>
<P>
   In this hidden corner of downtown, a fringe elite that can
afford the fees is going online despite tight Internet controls by
the authoritarian government. They are among the first here to pry
open a new door into the information age.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be arrested for this,'' said one surfer in his early
30s with an advanced degree in chemical engineering, who was
tapping into the Internet via the popular Yahoo portal.
</P>
<P>
   The Yahoo service is blocked at government-controlled sites.
Afterward, the surfer checked his e-mail on the Hotmail service,
the government stops at its sites. Internet sites with a
designation that includes the words ``Israel'' or ``sex'' and a
long list of other words are also blocked.
</P>
<P>
   The regime severely restricts information and limits freedom of
expression. Through control and fear, spies and secret police kept
President Hafez Assad in power for 30 years. But now as his son,
Bashar, moves to replace his father as president, Syria may be on
the edge of opening up to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At least, this is what the 34-year-old, London-educated Bashar
has said he intends to do, knowing just how far the country is
technologically behind its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   A younger generation of students, businessmen, and doctors are
all eager to open Internet access. People know the opportunities
that exist in the information age because they hear it from
relatives who have emigrated or they see it on satellite television
stations, which are also legally banned but the ban is not
enforced.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Syria has issued 7,000 tightly controlled ``points of
Internet connection,'' mostly to universities, research institutes,
industry and the tourism sector. Bashar's plan is to have as many
as 200,000 by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, Zoni says it is the only site that received a
license before many of the laws restricting Internet access were
put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, members of the ruling Baath Party fear the Internet
could become a tool used to stir opposition. Some said they worry
about the Internet's impact on a traditional culture. But the
biggest concern appears to be a culture of secrecy and tight
control of information.
</P>
<P>
   Zoni Internet Service opened just eight months ago. The manager
of the small, dingy room with six computers and a fan boasts that
it is the closest thing in Syria to an Internet cafe. But you won't
find any ``caffe latte'' here. It is not well-known outside a small
circle of foreigners and a few Syrians. That may be because Zoni is
a luxury for the rich: One hour on-line costs roughly the daily
salary of an average worker.
</P>
<P>
   The service is owned by Yamor Alzoni, whose father was a
military judge with connections to the ruling establishment that
has tolerated his license, Syria's only non-government controlled
access to the Internet available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Alzoni moved in the early 1990s to apply for a license for an
Internet ``access point'' and his family connections allowed him to
achieve the first, and only, one issued for public use by a private
company. All other access points allow only government-issued
e-mail and passwords to be used. It is illegal for a citizen not
registered by the government to use a desktop or laptop at home
with an Internet access phone number.
</P>
<P>
   At Zoni, a select few are exploring the edge of this government
control. They flock to annonymous Web surfing sites such as
``the-cloak.com'' and ``silentsurf.com'' to slip past
government-imposed firewalls, electronic eavesdropping, and blocks.
Some of the sites use encryption to hide the users' identity, and
the information being gathered.
</P>
<P>
   As the government moves almost daily to block these anonymous
surfing sites, the US-based providers provide an updated list of
new and anonymous sounding names to evade detection. These names
are scribbled daily on a whiteboard like specials on a menu, and
today the password is ``sahadifoods.com''.
</P>
<P>
   In one booth, the young Syrian chemical engineer was just
entering silentsurf.com to send an e-mail to a friend expressing a
political opinion that could land him in jail. He asked that his
name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   In the e-mail to a woman in America, he lashed out at what he
calls ``the sheep'' who have been expressing public sorrow for
Assad, whose iron-fisted rule left the nation politically paralyzed
and economically far behind. He clicked away on the computer
composing this e-mail:
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheep people say nothing, instead they go to his funeral
and they cry for him!!! I cry for another reason. I was dreaming of
that moment when a man can say ``No'' in his own, loud sound but
nothing will happen to him . . . . Now I am thinking I must leave
my country forever because it is a hopeless one.''
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughts are not heard in public or read in newspapers or
books. But others use the Internet not for political expression,
but for business.
</P>
<P>
   Raffi Kevorkian, 29, a jewelry designer, comes three or four
times a week to check the price of gold in the world markets. He
also studies designs of other jewelers who are online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too interested in political things,'' he said, adding
the wealth of his family allows him to go online but most of the
young people he knows in Syria have never been online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bashar has an open mind, a scientific person. He will do
many things with computers, technology and open up the economy.
This is what we hope for.''
</P>
<P>
   Imad Sakhal, 28, the manager of the site, said, ``People find a
way to use this tool. And it's going to come whether they want it
to or not. It's too big for them to try to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all members of the government are trying to stop it. The
Computer Society, a 10-member government board of professionals is
headed by Bashar Assad, is trying to hold the hand of the Baath
Party elite as Syria creeps forward into the information age.
</P>
<P>
   Saadalla Agha Kalaa, one board member, said the group was
founded in 1989 but only became active in 1994 with Bashar. Bashar
learned computer applications for ophthalmology when he was
studying in London. Board members who know Bashar said he is very
anxious to open up the Internet. He is constantly surfing the
Internet and is proud to say he is a ``Mac person,'' favoring Apple
computers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Syrian policy is reflected in a five-year plan. The
approach seems to cut against the whole idea of the Internet, which
opens doors to information and allows people to develop key skills
for technology, science, and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the slow apporach, Kalaa said, ``It is not a problem
of information, it is a problem of infrastructure. We simply do not
have the phone lines and the switches to open this to everyone. It
would completely shut down our communication system.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadik Azm, an analyst and philosopher at the University of
Damascus who has just returned from several years in the United
States, warned against regarding the Internet as Syria's savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opening up of Syria is not merely a question of the
Internet; this is reductive and unrealistic,'' he said. ``You could
still have the technology of the Internet, the dish, satellite TV
and maintain a more traditionally closed society. I think there are
more important decisions to make on the economy, and those lie
ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     06-21 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYSTEM OF CAPITAL PUNISHMENT DEEPLY FLAWED 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for
commentary on the U.S. Constitution His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The country is finally beginning to experience a backlash
against the blood lust of state executions.
</P>
