killed.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has already executed 22 inmates this year, nearly half the
total number of inmates executed in the nation during the same
period of time.
</P>
<P>
   An investigative two-part series of news stories by the Chicago
Tribune, published earlier this month, showed serious flaws in the
trials that led inmates to death row. The Tribune reporters
examined trial transcripts, legal briefs, appellate rulings, lawyer
disciplinary records and interviewed witnesses, lawyers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Tribune, in one-third of the capital crime
cases that were tried during the Bush administration, the
''defendant was represented at trial or on initial appeal by an
attorney who had been or was later disbarred, suspended or
otherwise sanctioned.''
</P>
<P>
   In a significant number of Texas cases, the prosecution
presented damaging testimony from a psychiatrist who predicted that
the defendant would commit future violence _ without ever
interviewing or examining the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune stories report that in many of the capital cases
during the Bush administration, trial outcomes were influenced by
experts whose credentials were worse than suspect: A forensic
scientist, who was temporarily released from a psychiatric ward, in
order to give testimony damaging to the defense; a psychiatrist,
who was nicknamed ``Dr. Death,'' and expelled from the American
Psychiatric Association; and a pathologist who has admitted faking
autopsies.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources have pointed to Texas lawyers who slept during
murder trials or who had been drinking, who had no trial experience
when appointed to defend a murder suspect, who never met with their
clients before trial, or who called no witnesses in defense of
their clients.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is so bad in Texas that the U.S. Supreme Court,
not known for coddling criminals or those on death row, vacated the
death sentence of Argentine national Victor H. Saldano because a
court-appointed psychologist had given racially prejudiced
testimony during the sentencing hearing. The psychologist testified
that Saldano was ``a continuing threat to society'' because
Hispanics are more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who argues that murder suspects in Texas get a fair trial
is either blind or ignorant of the facts. And Texas is the
execution capital of the nation _ it plans to execute 14 more
prisoners by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A recently published nine-year study conducted by Columbia Law
School Professor James S. Liebman of death penalty cases between
1973 and 1995 concludes that death penalty cases in the states
``are persistently and systematically fraught with serious error.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that ``during the 23-year study period, the
overall rate of prejudicial error in the American capital
punishment system was 68 percent.'' Those were errors that were
caught. Not all errors are.
</P>
<P>
   ``This much error, and the time needed to cure it,'' the report
states, ``renders unattainable the finality, retribution and
deterrence that are the reasons usually given for having a death
penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to the new questions raised by prosecutorial
misconduct or trial error in regard to death penalty cases,
Congress has initiated the ``Innocence Protection Act'' in both the
House (H.R. 4167) and in the Senate (S. 2690).
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation would allow inmates on death row to
request DNA testing on evidence from their case that is in the
government's possession. Many states put restrictions on DNA
testing. This bill would force states to keep biological evidence
and make DNA testing ``available to any person convicted in State
court.'' According to findings made by Congress, at least eight
individuals on death row have been exonerated by DNA testing, some
within days of being executed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill provides a mechanism to ensure competent legal
representation in capital cases in all the states. And the bill
would require that judges inform juries that life imprisonment
without the possibility of release is an option to the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   A judicial system that metes out death cannot be so flawed that
innocent people can and inevitably will be executed. That isn't
justice. It's retribution gone mad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
