<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parking scam is just good business
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A hearty round of congratulations is in order
for the enterprising Austin street people who pose as parking
attendants at parking lots and collect fees. Police say these folks
can make more than $100 a night.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty good money. Maybe I should buy myself a butler's
outfit and look into this.
</P>
<P>
   One place the transients try to collect parking fees is under
Interstate 35 between Sixth and Eighth streets, where parking is
supposed to be free. This idea is economically sound, because it
makes use of space that wasn't bringing in any funds. I look
forward to the day when an opportunistic crew of unauthorized
parking attendants in orange vests fills the Capitol lawn with SUVs
for the Pecan Street Festival.
</P>
<P>
   I say more power to these scam artists. It's encouraging to know
our transients have become inventive enough to branch out beyond
the banal collection of spare change.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say there aren't other fields of opportunity yet
untapped by street people that they should look into. How about the
position of impromptu elevator operator?
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows there are enough unmanned (unpersoned?) high-rise
elevators downtown that could use a guy to hold the doors open and
let people off on their floors, in exchange for tips.
</P>
<P>
   Shoot, if a guy came up with a spiffy doorman's suit with big
brass buttons and one of those little round hats, he could march
into 100 Congress Avenue, the Bank of America building or the Omni
Hotel and start working the tenants.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of activity is going on all over town, and I'm all for
it. Texans traditionally are reluctant to help the poor, so if the
poor can help themselves, why discourage them?
</P>
<P>
   The other day on East Sixth Street a free-lance window washer
walked up and asked if he could wash my car w or so later, the car
windows were clean, and the car wasn't up on blocks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I wasn't so sure about the self-proclaimed
auto body repairman who pulled up beside me in the parking lot of
the new Albertson's supermarket at Interstate 35 and Stassney Lane.
``Hey, mister, I'll fix your dents,'' the driver said, looking at
my car. ``What dents?'' I asked. I had just gotten my car out of
the body shop a few days earlier. ``Hey, man, I'm trying to raise
money for Mother's Day,'' the guy said. The trouble was, it was
Mother's Day. So when he offered to come to my house and fix my
alleged dents, I declined.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are unauthorized fields of opportunity that remain
open to the imaginative. How about tourism? A group of transients
could set up a booth at 11th Street and Congress Avenue with a
``Walking Tours'' sign and charge passers-by $20 a head for foot
tours of the Capitol, the grounds of the Governor's Mansion and
other points of interest. Just drag the tourists right on into the
Rotunda and show them around. Who better than a street person who
has tramped all over town to point out Austin's highlights?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
