A0423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX     06-21 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prayer ruling best way to keep government from taking sides
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same day that the Supreme Court reaffirmed the separation of
church and state, wire stories told of another deadly battle
between Christians and Muslims in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of killing between the warring religions in
Indonesia left at least 116 people dead, 292 homes burned and one
church destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   These deadly religious battles have been going on for more than
a year. An estimated 2,500 Christians and Muslims have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Christians, who are a distinct minority in Indonesia but a
majority where the fighting has occurred, have suffered the
greatest during the religious fighting.
</P>
<P>
   History overflows with examples of lethal religious intolerance,
a fact that did not escape this nation's founders.
</P>
<P>
   The first sentence in the First Amendment of the Bill of Rights
says, ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The ``establishment clause'' was meant to foster religious
tolerance by giving citizens the right to exercise individual
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   What the government cannot do is take sides in religious
matters. The government cannot favor one religion over another even
when one religion is dominant in terms of membership.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the Bill of Rights was to put restraints on
government while giving express rights to individual citizens. The
Bill of Rights protects individuals and minorities from the tyranny
of the majority, especially from oppressive state powers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas school prayer case decisively reaffirmed the founders'
beliefs embodied in the clause that says government has no business
sponsoring religion.
</P>
<P>
   By a 6-3 vote, the justices struck down an effort by Santa Fe
school officials to allow student prayers on the public address
system before football games.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe officials were sued by two anonymous families, one
Mormon and the other Catholic. These two religions are distinct
minorities in the town of 10,000 in western Galveston County.
</P>
<P>
   Before the courts instructed school officials to knock it off,
Santa Fe students were interrogated in an effort to ferret out the
families who brought the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Kennedy, a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
reported that the same week that a student prayed before a Friday
night Santa Fe High School Indians' football game, a group of
students surrounded Santa Fe eighth-grader Phil Nevelow and
chanted:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler missed one! No more Jews!
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler missed one! He should have gotten you!''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother told Kennedy that Santa Fe school officials
have done nothing all year about the slurs hurled at her son, the
only Jewish student in a town with only two Jewish families.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe, Nevelow told Kennedy, is not just divided, ``It's
fractured'' over the prayer case. ``Us, the Catholic families, the
Mormon families _ it's as if this is war and we're all on the other
side. Everybody else is against all of us. Nobody will even have a
logical discussion. You try to start a conversation, and people
just start shouting at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Santa Fe teens now face juvenile charges in connection
with a terroristic threat on a school bus to ``hang'' Nevelow,
``you dirty Jew.'' The Santa Fe superintendent reportedly called
the incident a ``teen-age prank.''
</P>
<P>
   While the government cannot force religious tolerance into the
hearts of individual Americans, it can promote religious
intolerance by taking sides in religious matters. That's the
constitutional principle reaffirmed by the Supreme Court in the
Santa Fe lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
