A0425 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE0622-CO     06-21 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nature's gardens sing call of the wild
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Blue sky, cool temperatures, mercifully low humidity
for a June day in Dixie. Indeed, it was a fine time for a walk in
the garden. Nature's garden. And so we ambled, dozens of us nature
lovers, just after the dedication of the Lady Bird Johnson
Wildflower Trail, at Callaway Gardens in Pine Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The trail, named for the legendary founder of the Lady Bird
Johnson Wildflower Center in Austin, Texas (of whose board I am a
member), begins near the Pioneer Log Cabin and gently winds its way
into the woods, offering close-up, in-action looks at shrubs,
trees, flowers, ferns, mosses and any other living thing you'd hope
to see during a woodland stroll. It is, to be sure, a trail of
nature, something that becomes more and more priceless as time and
clean air go by.
</P>
<P>
   Our walk was my latest reminder of efforts to green America,
efforts that should intensify with heightened concern over
ecological damage from hyper-development, and overburdened,
drought-ridden water supplies. Too, those efforts will be spurred
by the coming bulge of retirees demanding solace in unspoiled
places after a lifetime of slogging through polluteks close up.
</P>
<P>
   While each organization has its own focus, all have this in
common: They work to protect and preserve and promote nature's
beautiful, necessary bounty _ from the trust's riverside greenways,
to the botanical garden's all-around, inspiring cultivation, to the
history center's storytelling gardens. Through action and
instruction, each teaches the value of nature in harmony, its
contributions to our quality of life, such as trees' money-saving
cooling ability, herbs' medicinal value, shrubs' erosion control _
and, of course, the beauty of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Every walk through a garden reminds us of nature's gifts. So it
is with a walk through nature's gardens: the trails at Callaway,
those at the Botanical Garden, the History Center, along the
Chattahoochee River, those on our own land.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike traditional gardens more groomed, fed and weeded,
native-plant-rich trails, even while tended to keep them
accessible, sing that call of the wild, beckoning us to the
un-doneness of a trailful of hearty, drought-tolerant natives. What
eloquent persuasion. In many different ways, we're all trying to
get back to the garden. Tramping along a trail somewhere, anywhere,
discovering trillium, Christmas fern, jack-in-the-pulpit,
columbine, joe-pye weed, hearts-a-bustin', sweet shrub and indigo
takes us there. Back to the days when it was easier to find these
plants in gardens and woods. To the days when water was purer, air
cleaner and life simpler. No wonder, then, that the people I joined
on the Callaway trail got such complicated joy from simple
beauties, countless ones, including purple coneflower, Solomon's
seal, black-eyed Susan and mountain laurel.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder we took such delight in our seed-scattering ceremony,
imitating nature's summer and fall sowing (though our dirt was
tilled to improve seed-soil contact), anticipating a new crop of
wild things. No wonder; for a few precious minutes, we had found
ourselves in the right place. Wondrous.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
