A0426 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN22-COX     06-21 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gallin's decision one of care
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Perphaps the most puz- zling aspect of Dayton
school board member Mario Gallin's decision to send her son to
private school has been the muted response from parents.
</P>
<P>
   Gallin campaigned as a Dayton parent last November. Don't
parents feel betrayed, now that she is no longer one of them?
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton school board member knew there might be controversy.
Yet Ann Marie Gallin _ nicknamed Mario Andretti after plowing the
family car into the side of the house at 15 _ doesn't strike you as
the type who worries about winning popularity contests. ``I didn't
wrestle, 'Oh my gosh, are people going to yell at me?' I am first
and foremost responsible for this child.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallin hasn't received any calls from parents in the district,
but some have expressed public disappointment. ``If the schools
aren't good enough for her kids, why should we send ours to them?''
Bradie Brummett asked the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brummett, too, is pulling her son out of the district.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the heart of the matter. Dayton parents may be
disappointed _ but they've also been there. ``It looks bad, but
only you can decide what's best for your child,'' said my friend
Cris King, who has two children in the district.
</P>
<P>
   So, far, the harshest criticism has come not from parents, but
from teachers union President Joyce Fulwiler Shawhan, who called
the decision a ``slap in the face'' to teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Gallin maintains the move is not ``an anti-Dayton Public Schools
statement.'' It is a choice, she said, in the best interests of her
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't run to make things better for my child,'' she said.
``I wanted to make things better for the community's children.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallin came to parenthood late, and through unconventional
means. Four years ago, at 41, she married Thomas Ruddick, a
professor at Edison Community College in Piqua. Although she
decided against having children because of her age, ``we knew we
wanted to do something with children and with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, that took the form of volunteering to be a ``Big
Couple'' through Big Brothers/Big Sisters of Greater Dayton. They
were matched with a 10-year-old boy who, within several months,
came to live in their Walnut Hills home. They are legal guardians
for the boy, now 13.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his sixth-grade year, before entering middle
school, Gallin's son auditioned for Stivers School for the Arts.
When he was not accepted, she looked at other options. Gallin
became sold on Chamiande-Julienne because of its strong
extracurricular activities and community involvement program.
</P>
<P>
   Is she setting a bad example for parents who decide to ``stick
it out?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they think of it as 'sticking it out,' they're making the
wrong decision,'' Gallin said. ``We need to make Dayton Public
Schools a strong option for parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallin has vowed she will stay involved as a mentor or tutor in
Dayton Public Schools. But parents have reason to worry if her
decision will diminish one of her greatest strengths as a board
member: her ability to identify with parental frustration caused by
poor service from transportation and other boondoggles. Will
Gallin's sharp perspective on issues that affect parents fade when
she is no longer directly affected by such decisions? Gallin
doesn't think so: ``Parents have supported my decision in that I
believe in doing what's best for my child.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, at least, she will always be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
