<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-FILE     06-21 1615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent obituary for Mark Hughes, founder of the Herbalife
Corp., said an autopsy was planned. I didn't see a follow-up about
the results. Do you have any update?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Los Angeles County coroner's office determined that
Hughes died accidentally as the result of a lethal combination of
alcohol and an anti-depressant. Hughes, 44, was found dead on May
21 in his Malibu, Calif., mansion. The autopsy was performed
because of his relatively young age.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' blood-alcohol level at the time of death was found to be
0.21 percent, nearly three times the legally defined level of
intoxication, and he had an elevated level of the drug doxepin,
said Scott Carrier, spokesman for the coroner's office. Doxepin
sometimes is prescribed for anxiety-induced sleeplessness, and it
is thought that's why Hughes was using it. Neither the alcohol nor
the drug was present in sufficient quantity to have been the sole
cause of death, Carrier added.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication of foul play or intentional overdose. On
the day of his death, Hughes attended his grandmother's birthday
party, where he consumed alcohol, according to Herbalife.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Herbalife Web site, Hughes became interested in
nutrition at 18 when his mother, JoAnn Hughes, died of an
accidental overdose from prescription diet pills. Along with
Richard Marconi, a former colleague at Slender Now, Hughes started
the multimillion-dollar Herbalife empire in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Bagpipes often are played at funerals and other solemn
ceremonies involving police and firefighters. How did this
tradition begin?
</P>
<P>
   A: The practice of using bagpipes at the funerals of
firefighters and police officers began in the 19th century in
Northeast cities, particularly New York and Boston, where many of
the members came from the ranks of Irish and Scottish immigrants.
It apparently came from the use of bagpipes at funerals in the
Scottish military.
</P>
<P>
   In America, the playing of bagpipes spread from the Northeast to
cities everywhere and now is standard procedure, no matter the
ethnic descent of the police officer or firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've just learned that a friend in England has been awarded
an OBE, Officer of the Order of the British Empire, on Queen
Elizabeth's Birthday Honors List. Do you know how many people
received that honor this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: About 240. The list honors people in all walks of life _
politicians, civil servants, business people, doctors, teachers and
others _ for their contributions to their professions and to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   The honors, in descending order, are knighthood and its female
equivalent, dame; CBE (Commander of the Order of the British
Empire); OBE; and MBE (Member of the Order of the British Empire).
</P>
<P>
   Double Oscar-winning actor Michael Caine was awarded a
knighthood, heading a list of celebrities in the honors list that
included Sam Mendes, director of the Oscar-winning film ``American
Beauty'' (CBE); Harry Potter author Joanne K. Rowling (OBE);
thriller writer Dick Francis (CBE); pop singer Lulu Kennedy-Cairns,
whose professional name is simply Lulu (OBE); Tina Brown,
British-born editor of New York's Talk magazine (CBE); and fashion
designer Paul Smith (knighthood), whose clients include British
Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A high school teacher recently won $1 million on ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire'' by correctly answering this question: Which
of the following men doesn't have a chemical element named after
him? (A) Albert Einstein; (B) Isaac Newton; (C) Niels Bohr; (D)
Enrico Fermi. The answer was Newton. My question: What chemical
elements are named after the other three?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are einsteinium (chemical symbol Es, atomic number 99);
bohrium (symbol Bh, atomic number 107); and fermium (symbol Fm,
atomic number 100).
</P>
<P>
   All three are artificially created radioactive elements. Of the
109 recognized elements, 91 occur naturally on or in Earth, almost
all of them only in compounds, Scientists produced most of the
remaining 18, as well as three more not yet recognized by the
International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry, in particle
accelerators.
</P>
<P>
   Einsteinium was discovered in 1952 and was first produced in
laboratory experiments in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Production of bohrium was announced in 1976 by scientists at the
Joint Institute for Nuclear Research in Dubna, near Moscow. Until
1997, when the element was given its official name, bohrium
commonly was referred to simply as ``element 107.''
</P>
<P>
   Named for the Italian nuclear physicist who produced the first
controlled nuclear chain reaction, fermium was discovered in 1953
by a team of American scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After the Iridium satellite telecommunications system was
shut down, it was reported that the satellites might be sent back
into Earth's atmosphere to burn up. I never saw a follow-up. Do you
know the status?
</P>
<P>
   A: Motorola Inc., Iridium's biggest investor, said in late May
it was continuing to provide maintenance services for the bankrupt
global telephone and paging company's 66 low-Earth orbiting
satellite system ``for a limited time.'' Iridium, which announced
last August that it was seeking Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection,
terminated commercial service in March.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola says the satellites are Iridium-owned assets subject to
the oversight of the U.S. Bankruptcy Court of the Southern District
of New York, and ``a plan is in place to decommission the system''
once the deorbiting plan is finalized. Details will be announced
publicly at that time, Motorola told Q&AMP;A June12.
</P>
<P>
   For details and updates online, check
www.motorola.com/satellite/info/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In answering a recent question about manners, Q&AMP;A cited the
famous book ``Emily Post's Etiquette'' and mentioned that it was by
Peggy Post. Who is she?
</P>
<P>
   A: The newest member of the Post family to inherit Emily Post's
role, Peggy is married to Allen Post, Emily's great-grandson. Peggy
succeeded her mother-in-law, Elizabeth L. Post.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Washington, D.C., Peggy grew up in the Maryland suburbs
of Washington and in New Orleans. After graduating from Louisiana
State University, she worked for Chemical Bank and Merrill Lynch
Relocation Management.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, Peggy has represented the Emily Post Institute by
making personal appearances at bridal shows, and in September 1995
she took over the monthly etiquette column written for Good
Housekeeping. At the same time she began expanding her
participation in preparing the Emily Post books.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever became of Linda Kasabian, a member of the Charles
Manson ``family''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kasabian has virtually dropped out of sight since the
infamous August 1969 murder spree and subsequent trial of Manson
and his cult followers.
</P>
<P>
   She was granted immunity for testifying for the state that she
kept watch outside the California residence of actress Sharon Tate
during the murders of Tate and four others, then rode with Manson
the following night as he sought new victims at random, choosing
Leno and Rosemary LaBianca in their home near Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   At last report _ and that was in 1989 _ Kasabian was living in
the Milford, N.H., area, where she was raising four children.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lisa Stark has been a regular reporter on ABC Nightly News
for some time. Within the past two or three years, Betsy Stark also
has come aboard. Are they related?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Normandy beaches were named Omaha, Utah, Sword, Juno and
Gold. What do those names mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: They don't mean anything, in the sense that they were shaped
like Utah or a sword, or were the site of gold discoveries. They
simply were code names assigned by the Allies for clear
communications about target areas when the assault troops of the
combined Allied armies (American, British and Canadian) landed on
the Normandy coast June 6, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The French would have referred to the various stretches of the
Normandy coastline by their areas. What was code-named Sword would
have been the area stretching between Riva-Bella and St. Aubin, for
instance; Utah, between Isigny and Quineville.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently told us about the origin of 7Up. In a similar
vein, can you tell us how Dr Pepper got its name?
</P>
<P>
   A: A doctor was involved, but he didn't invent the drink _
which, as everyone knows, doesn't have a period in its name.
</P>
<P>
   According to the story it was invented in Waco, Texas, at
Morrison's Old Corner Drug Store. In 1885 _ the year before John
Stith Pemberton invented Coca-Cola _ Charles Alderton, a pharmacist
who worked at Morrison's, experimented on a soft drink, mixing
phosphorescent water, fruit juice, sugar and other ingredients. He
offered it to customers, one of whom jokingly called the concoction
``Dr. Pepper's drink,'' referring to Dr. Charles Pepper, the
disapproving father of a woman Morrison had been courting.
</P>
<P>
   When the drink became popular in Waco, beverage chemist Robert
Lazenby decided to participate in the development and marketing of
the new product. Lazenby agreed to go into partnership with the
owners of Morrison's drugstore to produce the beverage at his
Circle A Ginger Ale Co., also in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Alderton, meanwhile, disassociated himself from the enterprise,
opting instead to return to the pharmaceutical trade.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
