<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WRESTLING GRAPEVINE
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro wrestling might be taking a turn toward becoming safer.
</P>
<P>
   This week, World Wrestling Federation officials asked wrestlers
to cut back on finishing moves (DDTs, Tomestone Piledrivers and
Brainbusters) that could cause opponents to land on the top of
their head. The first wrestler affected was Perry Saturn, who will
lose the Brainbuster for a Flying Elbow Drop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the New Jersey Senate has begun hearings on ``extreme
wrestling'' legislation. The bill has already passed the New Jersey
State Assembly. This is not good news for Extreme Championship
Wrestling, which is based in Philadelphia and does a dozen shows in
New Jersey. The legislation would also affect smaller New
Jersey-based promotions, Jersey All-Pro Wrestling and Combat Zone
Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last Wednesday General Electric Co.'s NBC and the WWF
completed an agreement to jointly own and fund the spring pro
football league, the Xtreme Football League. In March, NBC agreed
to buy about $30 million in new shares of WWF Class A common stock,
giving it a stake of about 3 percent in the company and half
ownership of the XFL. The eight-team XFL is scheduled to start play
in February 2001. As part of the agreement, NBC has committed to
broadcast regional and national XFL games on Saturday nights in
prime time and the XFL championship game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some WWF money may be going to ECW. The WWF has offered
conditionalloans to ECW, but the WWF is not interested in owning
ECW, according to Internet reports.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tazz will return to the ring for the WWF in July. He suffered
a partially torn tricep. Meanwhile, Billy Gunn is still looking at
a September return from a torn rotator cuff. After working in
Memphis for the WWF for the past few months, Steven Regal will
return to the ring soon.
</P>
<P>
   _ After serving a 30 day suspension for allegedly assaulting a
member of the WCW production crew, Buff Bagwell was on last week's
Nitro and should begin a return to top-face status.
</P>
<P>
   _ Want to be as fit as Chyna? Soon you will have a chance as she
will release her own fitness videos.
</P>
<P>
   _ After finishing a program at the Gret American Bash, Sting and
Vampiro are both unhappy with the WCW. Sting's month-long hiatus
after last Sunday's match means a change of gimmicks, but Sting
wants to know why they want to change something that isn't broken.
Meanwhile, Vampiro wants to be paired with someone other than the
Demon for the next month. The Demon is a low-carder at best and
could drag Vampiro down from main-event status. Vampiro also was
unhappy about being asked to beat up a woman at the Thunder tapings
because his family has a history of spousal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   _ While many wrestlers are unhappy in the WCW, their newest
acquistion, Lance Storm, should debut before July. He should join
the New Bloods and align with Shane Douglas and Chris Candido as a
former ECW team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
