<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Has a final report been issued into the crash of the plane
carrying golfer Payne Stewart and several others?
</P>
<P>
   A: The crash investigation is continuing. Paul Schlamm of the
National Transportation Safetytold Q&AMP;A that a final report probably
won't be issued until sometime this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation into the Oct. 25, 1999, crash of the chartered
Learjet has centered on a loss of cabin pressure, the cause of
which remains undetermined. When the pilots were unable to correct
the situation, everyone aboard apparently succumbed to hypoxia, or
oxygen starvation.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft had taken off from Orlando and was supposed to go
to Dallas. But it flew, apparently on autopilot, until running out
of fuel and crashing in South Dakota. In addition to Stewart,
others killed in the crash were the pilot, Michael Kling; co-pilot
Stephanie Bellegarrigue; golf course architect Bruce Borland; and
Robert Fraley and Van Ardan, officials of a sports agency
representing Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Stan Drake, who used to draw the cartoon
strip ``Blondie''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Drake died on March 10, 1997, in Norwalk, Conn. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent question on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' asked:
``Where is the Sargasso Sea?'' The answer was the Atlantic Ocean.
How large is it, and what's the difference between a sea and an
ocean?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Sargasso Sea covers about 2 million square miles. It has
no land boundaries separating it from the rest of the open ocean,
making a precise determination of its size impossible. But
scientists say it's an oval-shaped area in the North Atlantic
roughly between the 20th and 40th parallels of north latitude and
between the 35th and 75th meridians west of Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   It's set apart from surrounding waters only by the presence of
seaweeds that float on its surface. The name Sargasso derives from
sargaco, Portuguese for seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   Seas are smaller bodies of water within oceans, such as the
Mediterranean and the Caribbean seas, part of the Atlantic; and the
Bering and South China seas, part of the Pacific. In some contexts,
the words are interchangeable: World Book Encyclopedia says an
ocean is ``the great body of water that covers more than 70 percent
of the Earth's surface. People also call it the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The American Film Institute recently released its list of the
100 best comedy movies of all time. Where can I find this list? Can
you print the top 10 ?
</P>
<P>
   A: A link to the complete list can be found online at
www.afionline.org/. The top 10, in descending order: ``Some Like It
Hot,'' ``Tootsie,'' ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``Annie Hall,'' ``Duck
Soup,'' ``Blazing Saddles,'' ``MASH,'' ``It Happened One Night,''
``The Graduate'' and ``Airplane!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is the oldest living offspring of an American president,
now that John Coolidge has died? And can you give us some
information about that person?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's John Sheldon Doud Eisenhower, who was born Aug. 3, 1922,
in Denver, to Dwight and Mamie Doud Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the U.S. Military Academy in 1944, he served in
the Army from 1944 until resigning in March 1963, one year short of
the 20-year minimum required for pension eligibility. As Colonel
Eisenhower later explained, ``Dad had done so well in the military.
I thought it best to try another profession.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined Doubleday as an editor and researcher until 1964, when
he took a position as executive vice president of the Freedoms
Foundation in Valley Forge, Pa. In 1965 he left that job to begin
full-time research for his book, ``The Bitter Woods,'' about Allied
operations in Europe in World War II. He served as U.S. ambassador
to Belgium from 1969 to 1971, then turned again to writing and
editing. His last book was ``So Far From God: The U.S. War With
Mexico, 1846-48,'' published by Random House.
</P>
<P>
   He generally avoids publicity, but made the news most recently
last November when he was in Washington for the renaming of the Old
Executive Office Building. Its new name: the Dwight D. Eisenhower
Executive Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who were the members of the U.S. delegation who went with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to Damascus, Syria, for the
June 13 funeral of Syrian President Hafez Assad?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department listed these names: Ryan Crocker, U.S.
ambassador to Syria; Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.); Dennis Ross, State
Department special Middle East adviser; Jesse Jackson, special
envoy to the secretary of state and President Clinton for the
promotion of democracy in Africa; Toni Verstandig, deputy assistant
secretary of state for Middle East affairs; Daniel Abraham,
chairman of the Center for Middle East Peace and Economic
Cooperation; and Dr. Issam Cheikh of the National Arab-American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is totally appropriate that we pay respects to a
historic figure and that we express our condolences to the people
of Syria,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac was the only Western leader to
attend the ceremony. Assad died June 10 of a heart attack after
years of declining health.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a way to get a videotape copy of a program shown on
C-SPAN? I want to give my grandchildren the excellent one shown
recently about the dedication of a D-Day museum in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, C-SPAN makes such programs available on videotape. To
order ``Opening of the D-Day Museum'' by charge to a credit card,
call 1-877-662-7726 or visit C-SPAN Archives' online video shopping
site, www.c-spanstore.com/157540.html. It costs $39.95 plus $7 for
shipping. Or send a check, made out to C-SPAN Archives, to: C-SPAN
Archives, P.O. Box 66809, Indianapolis, IN 46266-6809. Be sure to
put the D-Day program's ID number, 157540, on the check.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was in the Army from July 1, 1948, to April 21, 1957. Due
to several moves, I'm unable to locate my discharge papers. I need
them to seek benefits. Where can I get replacement documents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Assuming that your records weren't among those destroyed in a
disastrous 1973 fire at the National Personnel Records Center in
St. Louis, you can get duplicate discharge or separation papers by
writing: National Personnel Records Center, Military Personnel
Records, 9700 Page Blvd., St. Louis, MO 63132-5100. Specify that a
duplicate separation document or discharge is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Your full name should be typed or clearly printed. The request
also must contain your signature. Include branch of service,
service number or Social Security number, and exact or approximate
dates and years of service. Use Standard Form 180, ``Request
Pertaining to Military Records,'' available from VA offices or at
the VA forms Web site (www.va.gov/forms/default.asp).
</P>
<P>
   The VA says it isn't necessary to request a duplicate copy of
discharge or separation papers solely for the purpose of filing a
claim for VA benefits. If complete information about the veteran's
service is furnished on the application, VA will verify with the
National Personnel Records Center or the service department.
</P>
<P>
   More information can be obtained from any VA office, or call
1-800-827-1000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in knowing how a member of Congress has voted
over the years on certain issues. Is such information available on
the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Project Vote Smart has information on voting records of
any member of Congress. Go to www.vote-smart.org and, in the red
box, click on Issues. Under Categories, click on Voting Records. On
the U.S. map, click on the member's state and find your person.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that with the recent closing of the last Howard
Johnson's restaurant in Massachusetts, only 29 remain in the United
States. Can you list all the locations?
</P>
<P>
   A: There actually are 26 Howard Johnson's ``full'' restaurants
in the United States, said Barbara Leverone of Franchise Associates
in Weymouth, Mass. The restaurants are in Connecticut (Darien and
Waterbury); Delaware (Claymont and two locations in Wilmington);
Florida (Key Largo, Hollywood Beach and St. Petersburg Beach);
Maine (Bangor); Maryland (Millington); Massachusetts (Greenfield);
Michigan (Bay City); Missouri (Kirkwood); New Hampshire (Nashua);
New Jersey (Asbury Park); New York (Albany, Lake George, Lake
Placid and New York City); Pennsylvania (Pittsburgh, Pittston and
White Haven); Vermont (Springfield); and Virginia (Front Royal,
Harrisonburg and Lexington).
</P>
<P>
   There also are five Howard Johnson's ice cream shops: three in
Puerto Rico and one each in Florida and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
