<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TRAFFIC (San Francisco) _ Internet commerce, that sexy
new concept revolutionizing consumerism in the 21st century, is
causing a decidedly Old World problem in San Francisco: more
traffic headaches. The reality of increasing Internet commerce is
that most products bought online need to be delivered by the likes
of UPS, FedEx, Webvan or any number of delivery companies. But in
San Francisco, where the streets are narrow and crowded with cars,
the appearance of more delivery trucks _ often double-parked _ is
snarling traffic. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It's too bad that ``Gone in 60
Seconds'' is a movie about stealing cars. It would be a great title
for a workplace documentary. In this short-attention-span world, 60
seconds is all is takes for career opportunities _ and sometimes
careers _ to vanish. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTROLUX-DISCRMINATION (San Francisco) _ An Electrolux Corp.
manager, demoted by a boss who called him a ``dumb . . . Indian''
and told him he was too old, has been awarded $5.25 million for
race and age discrimination. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The restyled Toyota Corolla is the first
2001 model in the company's lineup to arrive at dealerships
nationwide. Among the new features of this compact sedan are better
fuel economy. Also: Porsche names its first sport-utility vehicle
after a pepper _ ``Cayenne.'' By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-STRAUSS (San Francisco) _ Recent belt-tightening at Levi
Strauss &AMP; Co. is starting to show results. The San Francisco-based
jeans maker reported Tuesday that net income had risen 48 percent
in the second quarter and that sales declines had slowed. By ALAN
T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   MONTIEL-RESIGNS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Steve Montiel never thought
he could change the world _ just the newsrooms of America. Twelve
years after assuming the helm of a journalism organization that
helped promote minority involvement in the country's newsrooms,
Montiel is stepping down as the head of the Robert C. Maynard
Institute for Journalism Education. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER-DR.-LAURA (Bolton Landing, N.Y.) _ Despite coming from
opposite ends of the political spectrum, it's not surprising that
bad boy Jerry Springer would back up the righteous Dr. Laura
Schlessinger. Schlessinger's anti-gay diatribes on radio have
prompted several companies to pull advertising from her upcoming TV
show. Who's not to say that Springer's raucous talk show could be
next for an advertising ban? By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BRENT-ROWAN (Undated) _ Guitarist Brent Rowan is one of
Nashville's most in-demand electric six-string gunslingers. He has
played on everyone who's anyone's records, including George Strait,
Shania Twain, Mark Chesnutt, Ronnie Milsap and Alabama, to name a
few. But in more than 20 years in the business, Rowan, 43, never
recorded an album of his own. Until now. By HECTOR SALDANA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The joy of travel is being threatened
just as more and more of us are eager and able to expand our
geographical horizons. To minimize the abundant hassles, research
every trip thoroughly, utilize time-proven companies, allow for
unexpected charges and unwanted surprises. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' column)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Caroline Krug's namesake winery in
France's Champagne region produces nothing but barrel-fermented
champagnes, and usually the most expensive on the market. Consider
the `88 vintage now available and you will know why. By MICHAEL
LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIC-FOODS (San Francisco) _ The city of San Francisco took
one small step toward one of the strongest stances in the nation
shunning bioengineered crops _ and one giant leap into a growing
furor. Three members of San Francisco's Commission on the
Environment on Tuesday agreed to push an ordinance that would,
among other things, favor hiring food vendors who use only organic
foods during city business or during events on city property. By
DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-SENIORS-TOUR (Undated) _ The Senior PGA Tour truly has been
a boon to the baby boom generation. What began in 1980 as two
exhibitions that enabled players to parade in carts has evolved
into a tour that is competitive, lucrative and unique. The Senior
PGA Tour is offering its players $54.1 million in prize money this
year, double the amount available in 1993. By RAUL DOMINGUEZ, JR.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
