<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-VETS-BAND0622-COX     06-21 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-BAND0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Therapy through music for Vietnam vets
 &HT;    By Rachel Kipp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ When Wayne Barker returned from serving in the
Vietnam War, he couldn't find a job. He would fill out applications
and proudly put down that he was a Vietnam veteran. But he says
that as soon as employers saw this information he wasn't hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally got a job when I quit putting down that I was a
vet,'' said Barker, 45. Barker attributes this to negative feelings
many people had toward the Vietnam War and those who fought in it.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to help other Vietnam veterans heal from similar
experiences, Barker formed the Vettz in 1985. Originally made up of
men who had all served in the Vietnam War, the band travels the
country playing for audiences made up of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like brothers helping brothers,'' Barker said. ``No
one else was doing it so we had to help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, the band's personnel has changed and now only lead
singer Barker, co-manager Tim Farrier of Kettering, and
percussionist (or ``concussionist,'' as he describes himself,)
Smoky LeBou of Huber Heights are Vietnam veterans. But the essence
of the band is still the same. The other members (drummer Marco
Miller, guitarist and vocalist Steve Linker, co-manager Keith
Wright, bassist and vocalist Terry Castle and guitarist and
vocalist Bob Neese) know what went on in Vietnam and have sympathy
for what their audiences _ and bandmates _ experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe through my grandfather serving in the (second) World
War, empathy comes easy,'' Linker said. ``It's such a brotherhood.
The only gift I can give is the music I play and my support. I
wasn't there but I still care.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the band gets together to practice at Farrier's house
whenever they can. The room is full of guitar cases, an old piano,
and various speakers and equipment. It is decorated with a poster
for the Vietnam War movie ``Full Metal Jacket `` and a sign of
support for men who were prisoners of war or are still missing in
action. Microphones let out squeaks and speakers are tested as the
men talk about some of the less-than-luxury hotels they have stayed
in and LeBou claims he can't make Friday's rehearsal because ``I
have nothing else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerts offer a mix of covers and originals. Barker compares
the Vettz repetoire to traveling through time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play music that most affected men while they were in
Vietnam,'' he said. ``We also play songs from today with messages
related back to Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   They usually close with a song Barker wrote called ``The Wall
.'' During the song the audience is invited to come up and speak
the names of friends and family who died during the war. This
``roll call'' can take hours. After that, the Vettz finish up with
something more upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's therapy through music,'' Linker said. ``A lot of people
don't understand. I don't, but I feel the energy and love and hurt
and pain all wrapped into one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The music releases all the (feelings) vets need to get out,''
Wright said. ``They promote the brotherhood so people don't feel
they are the only ones. If you have ever been to a vet reunion, you
see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Newest member Miller said that brotherhood extends to the band
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a show they put on and it was a very good show,''
Miller said. ``They're all so close and that's what makes the music
so good. I'm looking forward to a future with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vettz will get up early to play at 6 a.m. Friday for the
arrival of the Vietnam Memorial Moving Wall, a replica of the
memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Linker remembers visiting the full-size Vietnam Veterans
Memorial in Washington. He was walking with Farrier when a young
girl came up to them with a letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked Tim if he was a veteran and handed him a letter,''
Linker said. ``Inside was a letter thanking him for his service. I
got choked up. You don't have to be a vet to shed a tear.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
