<HEADER>
A0456 &Cx1f; tab-z
u d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV12-     06-21 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV12-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV12  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: SALMON WITH TARRAGON AND PEPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, July 12, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the old days, when classical French cuisine was the
touchstone for the finest cooking in this part of the world, rich
sauces often accompanied rich meats and fish so it was not uncommon
to have salmon served with hollandaise. But modern palates find
that opposites are even more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In other words something acid to provide a sharp contrast with
the richness of the fish. If a bit of sweetness is also factored in
there is a lovely balance of flavors. Balsamic vinegar and orange
juice are both sweet and acid. Sauteed onions add another sweet
note. For textural contrast with the fish, there are Bell peppers.
</P>
<P>
   A dish of noodles that are seasoned with sesame, soy and hot
pepper flavors provide their own distinctive contrast to the salmon
dish. You may want to adjust the amount of chili paste, depending
on how hot you like your food. This dish, too, provides its own
textural contrasts with the very crunchy sugar snap peas and the
soft noodles. If you like that crunch don't overcook those peas!
And if you cannot find sugar snaps you can use snow peas.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON WITH TARRAGON AND PEPPERS
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces salmon fillet
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole onion or 7 ounces chopped, ready-cut (1 2/3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces each red pepper, yellow pepper and green pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine orange juice and vinegar in a bowl and add salmon,
turning to coat. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chop whole onion. Heat nonstick pan large enough to hold all
the ingredients until it is hot. Reduce heat to medium-high and add
oil. Stir in onion and cook until it begins to soften and brown.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile wash, trim, seed and coarsely chop peppers; add to
onion as it cooks.
</P>
<P>
   4. Mince garlic; add and saute 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   5. Place salmon under the vegetables in the pan along with
marinade. Reduce heat to medium; cover and cook fish according to
Canadian rule: measure at thickest part and cook 8 minutes to the
inch. Season with salt and pepper and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   COLD SESAME NOODLES
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh Chinese or Italian noodles
</P>
<P>
   1/8 pound sugar snap peas
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tahini or sesame paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup no-salt-added chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons Chinese rice wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chili paste with garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon reduced-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring water to boil for noodles and sugar snap peas.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash the peas and trim off ends and cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wash and trim the green onions and thinly slice crosswise
white and green part.
</P>
<P>
   4. Either use food processor or a whisk and thoroughly blend the
sesame oil, tahini, stock, rice wine, chili paste and soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   5. Cook the noodles according to package directions. Three
minutes before noodles are cooked, add the sugar snap peas and cook
until tender. Drain the noodles and peas. Mix with the tahini
dressing and sprinkle with green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare noodles through step 1.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare salmon through step 2.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with noodles through step 2.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with salmon through step 5.
</P>
<P>
   Finish noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Finish salmon.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   No salt added chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Reduced sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces salmon fillet
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole onion or 7 ounces chopped ready-cut
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces each red, yellow an green pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh Chinese or Italian noodles
</P>
<P>
   1/8 pound sugar snap peas
</P>
<P>
   Bunch green onion (2)
</P>
<P>
   Jar of tahini or sesame seed paste
</P>
<P>
   Chinese rice wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   Jar chili paste with garlic
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 920 calories, 24 grams total
fat, 4 grams saturated fat, 90 milligrams cholesterol, 580
milligrams sodium, 55 grams protein, 120 grams carbohydrate, 8.5
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on
20MINUTE-MENUS and other features. &QL;
</P>
