<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0457 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-LAKER-RIOTS-CO     06-21 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-LAKER-RIOTS-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOTERS SMILE FOR THE CAMERAS _ AND GET ARRESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, June 22, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That was quite a parade of potential arrestees who rioted
outside the Staples Center after the Los Angeles Lakers won the NBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't be too hard to identify these clowns, especially when
you can stop, rewind, freeze-frame and even zoom in on their mugs.
</P>
<P>
   There was the guy in the navy pants and checkered shirt who used
something like a tire iron to smash in the right front window of
Los Angeles Police Dept. Patrol No. 666.
</P>
<P>
   The two men who threw traffic barricades onto the hood of that
same car. Another mope who was proudly wearing his Kobe Bryant
souvenir jersey as he swung a jacket filled with something like
rocks and pounded a police windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and let's not forget another Kobe fan who was wearing a No.
8 road jersey as he ran up to a burning vehicle with a large chunk
of a tree to fan the flames. Excellent kindling!
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the shirtless yahoos rocking the TV station van,
the goofs setting bonfires and the rock-tossing idiots who
occasionally halted their rampage long enough to jump for joy as
the cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, make sure you smile, dimwits, because you're on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   By now you'd think that looters, rioters, wilders, packs of
breast-grabbing molesters and other jokers who engage in
spontaneous, public displays of criminal behavior would have
figured out that cameras are loaded with film or videotape _ and
that nice clean images are captured on these wondrous inventions,
which means they can be caught in the act of committing crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But nope. I guess if you're so mindless that you'll attack a
limousine, manhandle women, loot stores or set bonfires in the heat
of a pack-mentality moment, you're also too stupid to realize that
all those cameras pointing in your direction could lead to your
arrest and conviction.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Los Angeles investigators will be sifting through
professional and amateur videotape of Monday night's distuburances,
even as TV stations continue to broadcast the footage and viewers
have the chance to say, ``Wait a minute, I know that idiot ...''
</P>
<P>
   And no doubt it'll lead to arrests and convictions.
</P>
<P>
   That's what's been happening over the last several days in New
York City, where police continue to arrest men who allegedly
participated in a series of assaults against women in Central Park
after the National Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lonnie Hopson became the 17th arrest in the case when
he was apprehended at his Queens home and was charged with one
count of first-degree sexual abuse and one count of first-degree
riot. A police spokesman told the New York Times that Hopson was
identified by an anonymous caller who recognized him from a
broadcast of an amateur videotape of the assaults. Among the
identifying characteristics: The football jersey with the No. 20,
the hair braided in wide cornrows and the fat gold chain around
Hopson's neck.
</P>
<P>
   Timely tip for wilders: Dress down!
</P>
<P>
   Then again, don't. The better to ID you and nail you.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do we have video of the L.A. and New York
troublemakers, we have Web site photos as well. By Tuesday morning,
a number of sites on the Internet were burning with color photos of
several of the morons who were wreaking havoc outside the Staples
Center just a few hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of years, video images and digital photos
have been used as evidence-gathering tools in a number of other
incidents, including assaults and arson at Woodstock '99; rioting
at the University of Colorado at Boulder in October of 1999; and
crimes that occurred at the Million Youth March in New York in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   When Michigan State students got out of a control in East
Lansing in March of 1999, police used videotape and photos to go
after students who participated in illegal activities, even the
seemingly harmless offense of flashing. A 19-year-old woman was
sentenced to 10 days in jail for lifting up her shirt and inciting
a crowd _ and she also suffered the humiliation of finding a photo
of her topless self, purloined from the Internet, taped to her dorm
room door by a malicious prankster.
</P>
<P>
   And a guy who danced around with pants around his ankles during
those MSU riots received 21 days in jail. Guess somebody recognized
his assets as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a weekend parade or a basketball championship or a
music festival (or a Cubs/Dodgers game for that matter), few people
head to the event thinking, ``I think I'll do a little rioting
tonight!'' They don't throw ``Scream'' masks or
mustache-and-glasses disguises in their backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   It just ... happens. They get swept up in the moment and put
their little brains on hold.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, they probably wish they could forget what
they've done. But the camera always remembers.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'')
</P>
