<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S DANCE, TIGER'S TALENT, HILLARY'S MUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON: The first lady is on the attack in her campaign
for the U.S. Senate in New York, ripping opponent Rep. Rick Lazio
as an enemy of ``women, children and families.'' Lazio has
denounced Clinton's criticism as ``mudslinging.''
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that Clinton has decided to go negative, since
she spent nearly eight years whining about ``the politics of
personal destruction.'' If it's good enough for her enemies,
apparently, it's good enough for her.
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution: With the independent counsel's report on the
first lady's role in the Travelgate scandal likely to be made
public before Election Day, she might find some of that mud flying
right back in her face.
</P>
<P>
   PAT BUCHANAN: The ex-columnist, ex-commentator, ex-Republican
caused an uproar at the Reform Party state convention in Texas when
his supporters hijacked the party's party from supporters of
founder Ross Perot. The Perotistas are complaining that Buchanan is
conducting a hostile takeover of the party rather than merely
seeking its presidential nomination _ and their complaints seem to
be well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Once Buchanan completes the takeover, will he
have anything that's worth having?
</P>
<P>
   ROSS PEROT: Which raises another question: Does Buchanan
actually believe that Perot will let him get away with this?
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: The guy is amazing, isn't he? In what seemed like a
matter of hours, the vice president dumped his campaign manager,
dumped his opposition to tax cuts and dumped his claim that
partially privatizing Social Security is a risky scheme. He ought
to be campaigning in a dump truck.
</P>
<P>
   All these switcheroos were part of Gore's latest attempt to
reinvent himself and create the illusion that he has something to
offer in the 2000 presidential race _ something other than timeworn
liberal bromides and tedious Clinton-Gore scare tactics from past
campaigns. It's easy for Gore to change directions, of course,
because he believes in nothing except the latest poll results.
</P>
<P>
   Gore obviously noticed that most of the polls show him trailing
Republican nominee-to-be George W. Bush in overall voter
preference, and trailing or losing ground among important voter
groups needed to construct an electoral majority. Bush has
virtually erased the Democrats' long-standing and crucial ``gender
gap,'' for example _ and that's extremely bad news for a Democratic
presidential candidate who desperately needs the votes of women to
prevail in November.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: While Gore tries this, then tries that, then
tries this again in a panic-stricken attempt to keep his campaign
afloat, Bush methodically goes about the business of laying out his
policy proposals and articulating his vision for the nation's
future. Bush's ideas are so appealing that Gore can't resist the
urge to steal them, although Gore's watered-down versions of Bush's
excellent proposals are pale imitations of the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Bush clearly has Gore on the run _ and there's no
reason in the world to believe that the situation will change. The
pundits have been predicting a too-close-to-call election, but the
contest could be shaping up as something else entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, Bush is gearing up to run away with it.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS: Some people apparently don't understand what all
the fuss is about. Here's the deal: Tiger belongs to one of the
world's most exclusive aristocracies: athletes who transcend not
only the game they play but the world of sport.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan. Muhammad Ali. Maybe Babe Ruth, once upon a time.
For a fleeting moment, perhaps, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, part of it is because Woods is a black man dominating a
sport that until about 10 minutes ago was the private property of
wealthy white guys. But it's mostly about the stuff that superstars
are made of: talent, charisma, dedication and a relentless
commitment to excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Even his opponents are awe-struck. The fuss is deserved.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
