<HEADER>
A0487 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-SPRINGER-DR.-LAURA-HN     06-21 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGER-DR.-LAURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `DR. LAURA' GETS SUPPORT FROM A TV BAD BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. _ You can't say Jerry Springer
enthusiastically leapt to the defense of Dr. Laura Schlessinger.
When asked, he just sort of flinched and did what he had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't personally like her views ... but she has every right
to be on the air,'' Springer said Tuesday. ``If we start any form
of censorship because we don't like (someone's) views ... then we
are all in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite coming from opposite ends of the political spectrum,
it's not surprising that bad boy Springer would back up the
righteous Dr. Laura, the radio physiologist-playing-psychologist
who is coming to syndicated television this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger's anti-gay diatribes (actually only a small part of
her show) have sparked a backlash in the gay community, which has
targeted the show by pressuring its potential advertisers. Several,
such as Procter &AMP; Gamble, have already backed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we see other advertisers announce that they will not pursue
sponsorship of the show, we praise them for their commitment to
fairness and to inclusive rather than divisive television
programming,'' Joan M. Garry, executive director of the Gay &AMP;
Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Springer, interviewed Tuesday before he moderated a panel
discussion on judge shows as part of 39th Executive Conference of
the New York State Broadcasters Association, has to back up
Schlessinger. If such an assault on advertisers is successful,
who's not to say that Springer's raucous talk show _ entering its
10th season _ could be next?
</P>
<P>
   ``Abhorrent views fall by their own weight,'' Springer said,
``not because we silence them.''
</P>
<P>
   But is there a line? Is it OK to air anti-gay television? Then
what about anti-black shows, or talkfests which target Jews? No?
Then what about the free exchange of ideas?
</P>
<P>
   Schlessinger would have had a perfect opportunity to discuss
this, at next month's gathering of television critics in
California.
</P>
<P>
   But she is not on the schedule, apparently ducking the event. So
much for personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   YOU BE THE JUDGE
</P>
<P>
   James Curtis, one of several jurists getting new judge shows for
the fall, was somewhat handcuffed by the question: How are you
going to make your show different from all the others?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Springer helped him out: ``Did you ever think about
throwing a bench?''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, whose ``Curtis Court'' begins this fall, and Greg Mathis
of ``Judge Mathis Court'' were part of a panel Tuesday that
examined the phenomenon of judge shows.
</P>
<P>
   The panel examined several reasons for the rise in popularity.
(``Judge Judy'' leads the pack as the third-highest-rated
syndicated show, behind ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy!'')
Springer, drawing from his own experience and that of talk radio,
posited that ``the audience has become the entertainer. We are just
watching ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis countered that ``the game show element'' plays a role:
Viewers want to guess the outcome before the verdict is handed
down. But it was newcomer Curtis who gave perhaps the best answer:
People had been amusing themselves at stockades, executions and
trials long before broadcasting even existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Court was the first entertainment,'' he said, exaggerating
only slightly. ``I think it's simply coming full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
