<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0496 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EVEN MULTIVINTAGE KRUG WORTH THE PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL LONSFORD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caroline Krug's namesake winery in France's Champagne region
produces nothing but barrel-fermented champagnes, and usually the
most expensive on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The nonvintage _ oops, according to Krug, that's
``multivintage'' Grande Cuve costs as much as most other tete de
cuve vintage champagnes, and Krug's vintage champagnes are even
more expensive _ in the $150-$175 a bottle bracket - and are
characterized by a wonderful toasty quality.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heady stuff, both stylistically and financially.
</P>
<P>
   Krug was in town recently to launch the new vintage of her
champagne, and therein lies the story. Because the new vintage is
actually older than the one in current release. How's that again?
</P>
<P>
   Normally I wouldn't give so much space to a single wine,
especially one so expensive as to be beyond the financial reach of
all but a handful of wine drinkers, but the Krug story is an
interesting one. How did the French firm with the German name get
to be the ne plus ultra of bubblies?
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Krug, an ambitious, restless German, emigrated to France
in the 1830s and by 1843 was running his own champagne firm.
Champagne Krug has passed down through family hands, and although
now owned by the giant LVMH conglomerate (Louis Vuitton,
Moet-Hennessey, Christian Dior, Givenchy, Fred Joaillier, Zenith,
Veuve-Clicquot, etc.), Krug is still run by Henri Krug, as
president and winemaker, and Remi Krug, as managing director in
charge of sales and worldwide promotions. Caroline Krug, 34, is Rmi
Krug's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Krug, because of its relative small production and extremely
high prices, is unknown to many champagne drinkers. Yet it usually
sits at the head of the table in the minds of those who have tasted
it. What sets Krug apart?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Krug ferments its wine the old-fashioned way, in
oak barrels, rather than in stainless steel tanks. That these are
usually older, fairly neutral barrels is not the point. It is
expensive and time-consuming, and a fine example of attention to
tradition and detail.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that sets Krug apart is its reliance on a fair
percentage of a black grape called pinot meunier in the blends.
Many champagne-makers rely exclusively on chardonnay, a white
grape, and pinot noir, a black grape, for their wines, and some of
those are terrific champagnes. But even some other firms who also
use pinot meunier look upon it as a poor relation, one not to be
proud of. Krug harbors no such notions. Pinot meunier is critical
to Krug.
</P>
<P>
   (An interesting historical aside: One of the great Krug vintages
was the 1915, and its blend was unique. This was during the darkest
days of World War I, and conflict raged across Europe. Joseph Krug
II, who had been making the Krug wines for several years, was taken
prisoner by the Germans. So that year his wife Jeanne took over the
winemaker reins, and made the vintage wine _ but all from pinot
noir and pinot meunier, the black grapes. Because of the war, Krug
could not obtain any chardonnay from the Cote des Blancs. And the
1915 Krug became a classic.)
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: Champagne companies' bread-and-butter wines
are their nonvintage bruts. These make up the vast majority of
their production.
</P>
<P>
   And Krug is no exception. Its Grande Cuve makes up about 80
percent of its production.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas other firms cherry-pick their lots of wines and
select first the best ones for possible vintage-dating - and then
later blend their nonvintage bruts - Krug makes up its
``multivintage'' Grande Cuve first.
</P>
<P>
   The Grande Cuve (it's around $100 a bottle) is a melange of as
many as 40-plus lots from as many as seven or eight vintages, all
blended to retain the Krug toasty, complex character. The result:
Krug's Grande Cuve is usually the quality (and price) of other
firms' best vintage champagnes.
</P>
<P>
   Krug also has a vast inventory of unreleased wines, meaning that
while it's costly to hold back a wine like the 1988 vintage and
release it later, Krug can _ and does.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: It is at each champagne firm's discretion
whether to release a vintage wine, especially their top-of-the-line
champagne, and some do _ almost every year. Not Krug. But the 1980s
(and 1990) were kind to Krug. The 1985 was considered an all-time
classic at Krug. And in 1997, Krug unveiled its 1989 vintage and it
was _ and is _ a big, toasty, very full-bodied champagne. Consumers
_ those who can afford it _ love the stuff. The 1990 vintage
promises to be even better, Caroline Krug says.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1988 harvest produced leaner wines of higher acidity,
and these wines needed more time to develop. ``It's a more subtle
vintage,'' Caroline Krug said. When I talked with her in 1997, she
said it would be at least a year and a half before the '88 came
out. It was almost three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we tasted the '88 three years ago, Henri thought it was
still shy.
</P>
<P>
   There was no pressure to release it until it was ready; we don't
have to follow the chronological rule.''
</P>
<P>
   But brothers and sisters, the wait was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   I asked her about the reception of the steely-but-toasty,
bracing '88 by those who have tasted the voluptuous '89, and she
said, predictably, that while some prefer one vintage (style),
others prefer the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I like the '88,'' she said. ``It's a vintage that
plays with you; it doesn't show you everything at once.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm enamored of wines with high acidity, and I found the 1988
Krug Champagne (Five Stars) marvelously complex. It displayed the
trademark buttered-toast character of Krug (from the barrel
fermentation), but also an almost lime-citrus quality and rapier
acidity. It is just now _ at 12 years of age _ beginning to come
together. And this wine belies the notion that champagnes cannot
age. This one should outlive the '89 and even the '85. If you have
a special occasion to mark the year 1988, whether a birthday,
anniversary, whatever, the 1988 Krug (and to be fair, perhaps the
1988 Dom Perignon, as well) should prove worthy of your
consideration. ``It's a vintage that will last for years,'' Krug
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly I think more consumers will prefer the '89, and that's
just fine. (Krug is handled here by Republic Beverage.)As for me,
``Waiter, I'll have another glass of the '88 Krug, please, and
thank you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
