<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-21 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HASSLES CAN CRIMP THE JOYS OF TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ I usually try to remain upbeat in this space because
... well, because leisure travel is supposed to be upbeat. Fun. A
relaxing escape from the pressures and time constraints and other
negatives of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   A happy face, that's what I aim to wear.
</P>
<P>
   But today, I'm miffed.
</P>
<P>
   I'm miffed because I sense, from my correspondence and from what
I read and hear in news reports, that the joy of travel - the very
essence of travel - is being threatened just as more and more of us
are eager and able to expand our geographical horizons.
</P>
<P>
   I'm miffed that United Airlines confined almost 200 people
inside one airplane for 8 1/2 hours at Chicago's O'Hare Airport,
waiting for clearance to take off to the East Coast, where weather
was playing havoc with routings and landings.
</P>
<P>
   Other aircraft that day made prisoners of passengers for five
and six hours. And this isn't a first.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care where the blame lies _ the airline, airport
designers who don't create enough gates, controllers,
meteorologists, the Federal Aviation Administration _ this is
unforgivable. We have a serious problem with air rage in today's
skies; is this any way to confront it?
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, passenger complaints to the
Department of Transportation about major air carriers increased 89
percent _ mirroring 1999 trends. Is anybody listening? The peak
travel season has just begun. There has to be a better way.
</P>
<P>
   How sad, too, to learn of kids inconvenienced or stranded during
much-anticipated end-of-the-school-year vacation trips because tour
promoters fail to live up to promises. These disappointments occur
too often.
</P>
<P>
   I'm miffed at the World Cruise Co. for shutting down 41 days
into its second 114-day around-the-world itinerary, requiring
passengers and crew to find ways home from Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   We wrote about the World Cruise Co. last year. So did other
travel media nationwide. It seemed such a promising idea - an
opportunity to sail from continent to continent for only about $100
per day, a fraction of the cost other lines charge for global
itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   What is it I frequently tell readers? ``If an offer sounds too
good to be true, it usually is.'' Maybe I should have seen this
coming. The Toronto-based promoters have a good track record with
Marine Expeditions, a companion company. But even as they scramble
to appease passengers inconvenienced by the abrupt ending of their
dream world cruise, these same people are now touting yet another
new endeavor: cruises to Cuba (from the Bahamas) beginning this
fall. My suggestion is to study that offer long and hard before
biting.
</P>
<P>
   The early misfortunes of Premier Cruise Lines' Houston-based Big
Red Boat III also are discomforting.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with air conditioning on the inaugural sailing were bad
enough. Then, a collision with a tugboat at the end of voyage No. 2
rendered Big Red Boat III idle and certainly isn't helping this new
family-oriented venture get off the ground - or rather, into the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   After all, how many consecutive weeks can a company afford to
keep issuing refunds and/or doling out certificates for free future
cruises?
</P>
<P>
   On a broader spectrum, I'm miffed that travelers too often
aren't told the truth about how much vacations really cost. Taxes,
fees and service charges are destroying budgets at hotels, car
rental counters, in airports and on some cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   Syd Kearney, my associate, tells about checking out of a hotel
in New Orleans a few weeks ago: ``A woman had emptied all of the
contents of her purse onto the counter and was crying and saying,
`I brought enough money to cover what you told me the room would
cost. And now you add all these other things to the bill. Why can't
you just be honest?' ''Why indeed. Look at advertisements whose
bold print reads, ``Cars $29.95 per day'' or ``Weekend special room
rate $79'' or ``Air fare sale $99 each way.'' Any chance that's
what your actual bill will total? Not after all the extra charges
are applied.
</P>
<P>
   Message to service providers: Add 25 percent, 30 percent or more
to the tariff, if you must. We know much of it is beyond your
control. Just tell us in advance so the shock won't spoil our
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Little things are bothersome, too. Or maybe they aren't so
little.
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker, in need of a passport on short notice, tested _ at
my suggestion _ the Houston Regional Passport Office's ``new and
improved'' expedited appointment system and called me on a cell
phone from the federal building to report, ``You should see this
scene. The lines are snaking out of the office and down the
hallway. Everyone here seems to have a 2:30 appointment, and there
are only two windows open. And there is no communication, nobody to
tell you what line to stand in or what the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   At least there was a line. After making several driving trips
over the past two months, I'm aghast at the number of highway rest
stops _ especially in Texas _ closed for construction. Are we just
supposed to close down our bladders, too?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'm miffed at myself for being so miffed. No, I didn't
get up on the wrong side of the bed; it's just that I want all of
us to enjoy our vacations, especially when we invest hard-earned
money and cherish the little time we have away from home for family
and new adventures.
</P>
<P>
   There are lessons each of us can learn: Research every trip
thoroughly, utilize time-proven companies, allow for unexpected
charges and unwanted surprises.
</P>
<P>
   But we also have a right to expect some degree of competence,
consistency and caring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
