<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-21 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT CHOICE BY SUPREME COURT ON PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that we cannot solemnize public high
school football games with pregame prayers. The court ruled, 6-3,
that the Santa Fe Independent School District, near Galveston,
Texas, was wrong to let students deliver prayers before the
kickoff. In one such prayer last season, Santa Fe High School
student Marian Ward, wearing her band uniform, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have chosen to solemnize this game. And if you want to
participate, bow your heads and give thanks to the Lord. Lord,
thank you for this evening. Thank you for all the prayers that were
lifted up this week for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that you watch over each and every person here tonight,
especially those involved in the game. Just be with the fans. And
just be with each and every one of us as we go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jesus' name I pray. Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   The court being the court, it struck down such prayers with an
insomnia-curing solemnity that left no room to blitz and sack the
absurdities. Writing for the majority, Justice John Paul Stevens,
said, ``School sponsorship of a religious message is impermissible
because it sends the ancillary message to members of the audience
who are nonadherents that they are outsiders, not full members of
the political community, and an accompanying message to adherents
that they are insiders, favored members of the political community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delivery of such a message _ over the school's public
address system by a speaker representing the student body, under
the supervision of school faculty and pursuant to a school policy
that explicitly and implicitly encourages public prayer _ is not
properly characterized as private speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough of the 50-cent words. The court made the right choice in
the five-year-old suit brought by a Mormon family and a Catholic
family who were offended by the prayers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the whole story. What the court could not say in its
solemn trashing of solemnizing is what a seddity sacrilege pregame
prayers are.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press photo that ran in the nation's newspapers
this week of Ward praying from the public address booth as the fans
bowed their heads in the stands, had me thinking that Jesse Ventura
might actually have a point.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, the wrestling crackpot who managed to become governor
of Minnesota, offended much of the nation when he said, ``organized
religion is a sham and a crutch for weak-minded people who need
strength in numbers. It tells people to go out and stick their
noses in other people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   I believe in God, Jesus is up there as a role model and I like
football. But anyone who confuses the holy trinity of father, son,
and holy ghost with the gridiron trinity of mayhem, manhandling and
maiming has an odd set of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   No prayer, no assembly of bowed heads, no show of reverence can
gloss over the obvious. All these students, parents, teachers,and
community leaders are in the stadium is to see their team crush the
other team. The Bible may talk about David slaying Goliath, but
please, you cannot find a single person in a typical stadium who
wants to be David at kickoff time.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Book may want us to be good Samaritans, but in
football, gracious gestures of assistance from opponents only
happen after the opponent is sufficiently secure that you are
either: A. Flat on your back, after a 10-yard-loss; B. You have had
the wind knocked out of you; C. You have a concussion; or D. You
are being wheeled off the field with torn knee cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Paul in his letter to the Ephesians, said, ``Put on the whole
armor of God, so that you may be able to stand against the wiles of
the devil. For our struggle is not against enemies of blood and
flesh, but against rulers, against the authorities, against the
cosmic powers of this present evil age.''
</P>
<P>
   That would not seem to be quite the interest of college scouts
who scour the high school flesh under the armor of shoulder pads.
They are not there to pray. They are not there to find not players
who buck evil authority. They are looking for running backs with
the wiles of Tasmanian devils and behemoth linemen who pound their
opponents into a bloody pulp.
</P>
<P>
   With 24 hours in a day and seven days in a week to pray, it is
interesting to see people try to turn football stadiums into
churches. Perhaps the need to crudely overwhelm a stadium with a
prevailing religion befits the American team sport most crudely
dependent on overwhelming opponents with brute strength.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the prayers are also a cover for the obvious. You have
to admit, even if you are a football fan, that it is a stupid game.
No parent in the abstract would tell his or her son, ``Say, Johnny,
go to the corner and get your chest caved in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet tens of thousands of parents do it every fall in America.
Our children are out there on the field in the American trinity of
mayhem, manhandling, and maiming. The folks in the stands pray,
probably because it ain't Jesus and the heavens who will be lifting
up their son on the next play. It will be that 6-2, 250-pound nose
tackle, straight from hell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-21 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 TOULOUSE, France: ... 15 to 25 years?''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the high stakes involved, both companies are willing to
pull out all the stops in a sales campaign, even for small
customers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most influential airlines in Asia, if not the world,
is Singapore Airlines. Last year, Boeing scored a major coup when
it persuaded the airline to swap its A340-300 fleet with 777s. The
airline agreed to buy the Boeing planes if Boeing took 15
A340-300s. Furious, Airbus said it would not service the planes if
they were resold by Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tremendous validation of our product,'' said
Dickenson, who at the time headed Boeing's Asian sales unit.
``Singapore Airlines is run by very shrewd and capable business
people who have the unique ability to look around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is now trying to persuade Singapore to replace
longer-range A340-500s that are on order with a new, long-range
version of the 777 that Boeing unveiled this year. Singapore
Airlines has also expressed an interest in the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus struck back with its El Al deal. Leahy, senior vice
president of Airbus, targeted El Al even after the airline crushed
the hopes of Airbus a few years ago when it decided to stick with
Boeing rather than buy the A320.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came back two years later and said they were looking at
widebody aircraft, and we were told by the government and the
airline that they would make this purely business. I said, `What
the hell, I'm a glutton for punishment,' '' Leahy recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy and a sales team flew an A330 to Israel _ a bold,
expensive proposition for a relatively small sale of about $400
million _ and showed the plane off.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, El Al's board voted unanimously to split the
order by buying the 777 as well as some medium-range A330s. The
deal was considered so pivotal that US Secretary of State Albright
lobbied the Israeli government to cancel the Airbus order and
threatened future US aid to Israel. In December, Israel froze the
contract, pending a review, which is still on-going.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said he is confident Israel will buy the planes, but even
if it does not, ``They got to know our product and found it a good
fit for El Al _ that in itself is a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   But he blasted the United States for what Airbus perceives as
diplomatic interference run by high-ranking US officials on behalf
of Boeing. ``I'm an American, I'm proud of being American, but it
is disappointing to see this administration says, `Free trade, but
only if we win.' To threaten Israel and say there could be a
problem with aid borders on hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, Boeing's Dickenson counters, is the master at pulling
political strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Japanese leaders make an aircraft decision, the
ambassadors from France, the UK, and Germany, and sometimes Spain,
call upon them and attempt to put pressure on them by talking about
bilateral issues. We'll just leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, an industry analyst at JSA Research in Newport,
says the companies have very different strategies. ``The strategy
of Airbus is to gain market share and provide gobs of employment to
their benefactors, i.e. the governments of Europe. Boeing is quite
different. It is oriented to optimizing profit growth over the long
term. They are two very different ways of operating, and there is
just not a profit motive of any consequence at Airbus.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is composed of Aerospatiale Matra Airbus of France and
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace of Germany, with 37.9 percent share each,
BAE Systems of Britain, with 20 percent, and CASA of Spain with 4.2
percent. Its subsidies have irked Boeing, but officials in Toulouse
say the company has paid back all recent government loans.
</P>
<P>
   The officials added that Boeing reaps research and development
benefits for its commercial aircraft from its military contracts,
which Airbus contends is another kind of subsidy. Boeing's
Commercial Airplane Group brought in well more than half of the
company's $58 billion in revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had the US government shelve the dispute over subsidies
in the early 1990s and a tenuous compromise was worked out. But
there is concern in Seattle and Washington over a new round of
subsidies for Airbus to develop the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the US trade representative, has stated her
concern about such subsidies and the matter is being scrutinized,
said an official from the US trade office.
</P>
<P>
   One big plus for Boeing out of Washington was last month's vote
to approve permanent normal trade relations with China. It is no
accident that Airbus and Boeing have invested millions in
facilities in China. The country represents the largest market for
new aircraft in the next 20 years, and Asia in general, according
to Boeing's long-range outlook, will see air travel needs grow at
nearly 7 percent, while the rest of the world will be under 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is a huge market for us,'' said Dickenson. ``If
relations between the US and China do not go well, we will not sell
airplanes there.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences, analysts say, the products that
Airbus and Boeing produce are very similar and very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The later generation 737s may not have all the bells and
whistles that the A320 series does, but they are cheaper,'' said
Nisbet.
</P>
<P>
   Massive production problems at Boeing in recent years damaged
the company and some orders went to Airbus as a result, Nisbet
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing is overhauling and becoming more efficient _ they
should be 10 to 15 percent cheaper, but they lost some of that
edge. Their planes are designed to be more efficient, have lower
operating costs while still being competitive in performance. That
is why Boeing has sold so many airplanes over the years. But Airbus
was the first with fly by wire and innovation of that sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as far as sitting in an airplane as a passenger, there is
very little difference in comfort, and if you are not an airplane
buff, you would not know which one you are in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
