<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR FAULTS PAPACY FOR REFUSING TO ADMIT ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garry Wills embraces his Roman Catholic faith but is not
enamored of church fathers in the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The church hierarchy, Wills says, has resorted to ``structures
of deceit'' to hold fast to teachings on issues ranging from the
ordination of women to the church's role in the Holocaust, that
vast numbers of lay people as well as priests and nuns do not
accept.
</P>
<P>
   The papacy in particular, in Wills's view, has been
characterized by an unwillingness to admit it could make mistakes
or bring harm to others, an intransigence that has alienated
Catholics and non-Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever topic you want to talk about _ sex, Jews, women _ it
comes down the same problem,'' said Wills, a Northwestern
University professor who lays out his arguments in his latest book,
``Papal Sin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vatican has always sought to advance the claim that church
rulers have always been right and have never erred,'' Wills, the
Pulitzer Prize-winning author of ``Lincoln at Gettysburg,'' said in
a recent interview. ``If you start having to defend that
proposition you find yourself having to distort and suppress
information and call up false arguments from tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   While other authors have taken issue with the Vatican's stance
on individual controversial issues, Wills focuses on what he says
are systemic and entrenched attitudes and behaviors that have
caused church fathers to commit ``quiet sins of intellectual
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis believes it is this headstrong leadership style that has
contributed to the decline in the number of priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arguments for much of what passes as current church
doctrine are so intellectually contemptible that mere self-respect
forbids a man to voice them as his own,'' Wills writes. ``The very
fact that the intellectual level of the church has been raised
makes it harder for a priest to swallow the scriptural
fundamentalism reverted to by Rome when it claims that priests must
be celibate or that women cannot be priests.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Wills believes many aspiring priests are unwilling
to put themselves in a position where they would have to defend
what Wills says are dishonest teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Wills says his book is not an attack on the papacy but on the
the way the papacy has defined its role. ``My own heroes, it will
become clear, are the many truth tellers in Catholic ranks,
preeminently Saint Augustine, Cardinal Newman, Lord Acton and Pope
John XXIII,'' Wills writes. ``The truth, we are told, will make us
free. It is time to free Catholics . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He provides a scathing critique of ``We Remember,'' the
Vatican's long-anticipated document on the Holocaust issued in
March 1998. Wills writes that the document is a tortured attempt by
the authors to exonerate the church from any direct culpability or
from having promoted teachings that may have fostered a climate of
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   While Pope John Paul II lauded the document for calling ``memory
to play its necessary part in the process of shaping the future,''
Wills says the pontiff never mentions the bishops and priests who
were supportive of the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may (or may not) have been extenuating circumstances for
some of these collaborators. But to pretend _ nay, to assert _ that
they did not exist is to remove ``We Remember'' from any serious
consideration as an honest confrontation with a complicated
history.'' Its `memory,' far from being useful to the cause of true
understanding that would prevent another Holocaust, is useful only
to the fiction that the Vatican wants to maintain about itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Wills is equally harsh in his assessment of the church's
argument that women cannot be priests because Jesus only chose men
as his apostles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the twelve apostles were married, and the church
authorities decided they could change that _ in fact, John Paul
says that the church cannot go back to the original situation on
this point,'' Wills writes. ``Saint Peter had a wife, but no modern
priest or Pope can. Are we to say that all priests must be
converted Jews? The twelve were. Are they all to speak Aramaic? For
that matter, if we are to make the gospel situation binding now, we
should observe that the apostles were not priests themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his sober evaluation of the church's upper echelons,
Wills says the Catholic spirit is thriving wherever people,
motivated by their faith, are working on social justice issues,
whether it be fighing the death penalty or helping the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campus churches I know have young people readier than I
and my friends were at their age to work on soup lines, to minister
to the inner cities,'' he writes. ``The Spirit is in them. He needs
no license from the Vatican . . .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BRIEFS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --A historic Attleboro building used as a retreat for Catholic
priests but destroyed in a fatal fire last fall will not be
rebuilt, the La Salette Missionaries have decided.
</P>
<P>
   The missionaries, who are trying to raise $4.5 million to
construct a new shrine church, decided that even with insurance
they could not afford the $11 million needed to reconstruct the
stone building. The building, known as ``the castle,'' was
constructed in 1902 as a sanitarium and was later used as a
seminary and as provincial headquarters for the missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   The building was destroyed in a fire last November, and a
visiting priest was killed. The fire apparently started when the
priest fell asleep while smoking a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   The Missionaries of La Salette are a Roman Catholic community of
priests and brothers who take their name from a town in the French
alps where an apparition of Mary is said to have appeared to two
shepherds in 1846.
</P>
</TEXT>
