<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PTBOAT-CONTROVERSY-1stLdWritethru-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORPEDO BOAT'S RESTORERS FIGHT TO KEEP CRAFT IN WATER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Fixes name of Toots Shor's restaurant) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEABROOK, Texas _ PT-309, the last still-seaworthy U.S. torpedo
boat to see action in World War II, bobs in its borrowed slip at
the Lakewood Yacht Club like an anxious sailor ready for shore
leave.
</P>
<P>
   But where it goes is a question that has created a contentious
debate between the volunteers who made it shipshape, and the Texas
Parks and Wildlife Department, which owns it.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-foot, 50-ton patrol torpedo boat that saw action in the
Mediterranean Sea is considered the centerpiece for a new exhibit
at the Admiral Nimitz Museum in Fredericksburg, 250 miles away from
the salt air and seawater of the Texas Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers who spent the past six years peeling away decades of
neglect from the boat's rotted wooden hull believe that all their
work will be ruined if the state dry-docks the 309 in the Texas
Hill Country. They are pleading with the Nimitz Museum and the
Parks and Wildlife Department to reconsider the plans and allow the
torpedo boat to remain in the brackish waters of Galveston Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They honestly don't know what we're doing down here,'' said
Tim Kelley, an energy company systems scheduler, and the elected
``commanding officer'' of PT-309. ``They think we want to take it
away from them. We don't. We want to remain connected to the Nimitz
Museum, but all the master boatbuilders we've talked to say that
taking this boat out of the water will destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it will be devastated by dry rot within three to five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dolman, a historian for Parks and Wildlife, said there is
no definitive proof for that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest maintenance headache is when you have water, and
then dry cycles,'' Dolman said. ``It's better for it to be
continuously wet, or continuously dry. Not go back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is more at issue than just the drying of the PT boat's
fragile wooden hull. The volunteers have worked hard for the past
few years, painstakingly refurbishing the boat fore and aft, and in
the process they became familiar with its WWII crews and its
wartime history.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 39-member volunteer crew feels a part of the boat.
They have what the Nimitz Museum curator of exhibits and programs,
Helen McDonald, calls ``sweat equity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They poured their heart and tears into that boat. I understand
that,'' McDonald said. ``We're anxious for them to be a part of our
program here.''
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers are not so magnanimous toward the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fuller, a former Navy pilot who has volunteered hundreds of
hours and thousands of dollars of his own money toward restoration
of PT-309, said the Nimitz abandoned the PT boat while all the work
was going on, and only now that the work is nearly finished is the
museum ready to take control.
</P>
<P>
   The 309 was purchased six years ago in New York by the Admiral
Nimitz Foundation, a Texas-based museum support group. The
foundation gave the boat to the Parks and Wildlife Department,
which oversees the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 2 1/2 years, they stopped supporting it
completely,'' Fuller said of the foundation. ``I've had four
conversations with the foundation, pleading for financial
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said the Nimitz foundation paid $80,000 for PT-309, and
another $70,000 to transport it to Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, the 309's commander, estimates that it has taken more
than $750,000 in work hours, donated services and supplies to
refurbish the boat. The torpedo boat is resting in a $500-a-month
slip at the Lakewood Yacht Club, paid for by a donor.
</P>
<P>
   The crew has occasionally opened the boat to tours at nearby
Kemah, and the result has been promising, Fuller said. ``The city
of Kemah has allocated $55,000 to build a secure slip right under
the Kemah bridge on the boardwalk,'' Fuller said. ``They have 5.1
million visitors a year on that boardwalk and even if we get 1 or 2
percent of those people to pay for a tour of the boat, it will
offer a revenue stream for the boat, and for the Nimitz Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation if the museum lets us keep the boat
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer crew members say they are willing to staff the boat at
Kemah and other locations and provide visitors with a complete
history of PT-309, which has a war record of 20 missions under
fire, including the sinking of five enemy vessels and the capture
of an Italian torpedo boat and its crew.
</P>
<P>
   The 309's first commander, Lt. Wayne Barber, had a chance
meeting with Frank Sinatra at Toots Shor's restaurant, and the two
decided to christen the boat ``Oh Frankie,'' a name it still
carries on its hull.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the boat was decommissioned and sold as surplus
for $3,500. It was purchased by a fishing company and pressed into
service off Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saltwater she plied through daily preserved her precious
mahogany hull for more than 50 years,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nimitz Foundation bought the boat in 1994. It was
transported to Galveston, then to San Jacinto Battleground State
Park where it was dry-docked alongside the Battleship Texas for
hull restoration. It was then moved to Clear Lake where the engines
have been installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see how they could become attached to it,'' Parks and
Wildlife's Dolman said, acknowledging the acrimony that has
erupted. ``But our intent has not changed. It is to be on permanent
display in Fredericksburg. We've got a museum that focuses on World
War II, and we are planning to use the PT boat to tell an important
part of that story.''
</P>
<P>
   PT-309's wartime executive officer, William F. ``Bill''
Pleasants, counters: ``To all who served in World War II, it would
be like sending a living memorial to her grave. All the thousands
of dollars and work by volunteers will be wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolman said he will meet with the PT-309 volunteers soon to
discuss the problems, but he warns that the foundation has raised a
million dollars to display the PT boat in Fredericksburg, and
``some of that money is conditional.'' If it isn't used for that
purpose, it has to be returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of stuck between a rock and a hard place,'' he
said. ``But we'll continue to look for some wiggle room.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
