<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-21 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISMANTLING THE DOCTRINE OF THE INFALLIBLE POPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Latin phrase ``ad hominem'' does not begin to describe the
amount of guff and grief that Garry Wills is facing because of his
new book, ``Papal Sin: Structures of Deceit.'' The phrase means
``to the man'' and its argument is really no argument, but a demand
that neither he nor anyone else should question papal authority.
</P>
<P>
   Wills does, with crisp and coherent argument, but his critics
are sure he's wrong before they've read the book. They thus prove
his point and that of other men of faith who believed that popes
were human.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no worse heresy than that the office sanctifies the
holder of it,'' the British Catholic historian, Lord Acton, wrote
in 1887. Wills cites Acton, Cardinal Newman, St. Augustine, and
others in illuminating how modern popes have managed to weaken the
rock on which St. Peter built the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   His chapter titles show the candor he brings to his task:
``Excluded Women,'' ``The Pope's Eunuchs,'' and ``A Gay
Priesthood.'' This latter chapter does not dwell on lurid
headlines, but argues that scandal may eventually lead the church
out of some doctrinal dilemmas: ``The admission of married men and
women to the priesthood _ which is bound to come anyway _ may well
come for the wrong reason, not because women and the community
deserve this, but because of panic at the perception that the
priesthood is becoming predominantly gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Wills is one of America's leading intellectuals, who has shone
new light on the Declaration of Independence, the Gettysburg
Address, and various political figures, including John Wayne. He is
also a former altar boy and a former seminarian, but he is not an
apostate. Anyone who challenges his devoutness would be sadly
mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite metaphors for less-than-devout Catholics are
passive-aggressive: lapsed, lax, fallen away, back-slider. (I
prefer the formulation of Wills's fellow intellectual, John Gregory
Dunne: ``It says RC on my dogtags.'') While critics can challenge
his piety, Wills offers a vigorous, active faith that uses logic to
dismantle the relatively recent doctrine of papal infallibility. In
the 20th century, while the world slowly embraced democracy, the
Vatican reinforced absolute papal authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humanae Vitae,'' banning birth control, was issued by Pope
Paul VI in 1968. Wills call it ``the most disastrous papal document
of the century'' and also one of the most ignored, as Italy's low
birth rate suggests. But, Wills writes, the encyclical ``is not
really about sex. It is about authority. Paul decided the issue on
that ground alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Popes are politicians, a notion that sounds heretical, but
isn't. Pope John Paul II has pursued a Sun Belt strategy by
courting Africa, Asia, and Latin America and probably not minding
if Europe and North America drift away. His papacy may end soon,
and perhaps his successor will be someone like Pope John XXIII, who
opened the windows and fumigated the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The people are the church, not the pope. That is the bold theme
of ``Papal Sin,'' echoing earlier critics of durable and loving
faith. Lord Acton was skeptical of power. After the First Vatican
Council had approved the doctrine of the infallibility of the pope,
he wrote to Mandell Creighton, commenting on the latter's history
of the papacy:
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot accept your canon that we are to judge pope and king
unlike other men, with a favorable presumption that they did no
wrong. If there is any presumption it is the other way, against
holders of power, increasing as the power increases. Historic
responsibility has to make up for the want of legal responsibility.
Power tends to corrupt and absolute power corrupts absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Garry Wills, along with other doubters, will inhabit
purgatory for an eon or two. But when he gets there, he'll be in
good company. The place could be crowded with popes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
