1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0533 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-BONE-COLLECTOR-DISCOV     06-21 1586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONE-COLLECTOR-DISCOVER-$ADV13-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANCING THE BONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., June 13, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is included.) 
 By JACK McCLINTOCK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Belted into the seat of a Toyota Land Cruiser piloted by a
friend, 78-year-old Joan Wiffen heads for the outback on a sunny
morning. She hangs on tight as she bounces through the heavily
forested New Zealand countryside. Then, out of the car, she grabs a
walking stick and tramps through shady glades.
 &HT;    Finally she stops at the edge of rushing Mangahouanga Stream and
tentatively dips in a sneaker-shod foot. ``You have to be very
strong or totally insane to keep coming back here for 27 years.''
 &HT;    Wiffen keeps coming back because the place is full of fossils.
She fell in love with them three decades ago and has been hunting
them here ever since.
 &HT;    Wiffen never attended a university or got a single research
grant. However, professional paleontologists call this amateur
``the dragon lady'' for her work excavating the fossils of four
previously unknown sea monsters, including a voracious lizardlike
mosasaur bigger than a killer whale and as fierce as Tyrannosaurus
rex.
 &HT;    But Wiffen's contribution to the understanding of prehistory
goes well beyond unearthing frightening predators. She was the
first person to find dinosaur fossils in New Zealand. Before her
work, paleontologists thought New Zealand was one of the least
likely places for dinosaurs to have lived.
 &HT;    Wiffen never thought she'd become famous. She grew up on farms
in a conventional family and expected to become a housewife. She
did.
 &HT;    Her late husband Pont, an electronics technician who died in
1992, worked at radio stations. They lived in the country, and
Wiffen cooked, cleaned and looked after the sheep, the goats and
the two children, Christopher and Judith.
 &HT;    ``I only heard about dinosaurs when I started buying books for
my own kids,'' she says.
 &HT;    The family hobby was rock collecting. The Wiffens belonged to
rock and mineral clubs, attended night classes in geology and for
seven months in the late 1960s drove all over Australia collecting
opals, topazes, sapphires and garnets and turning them into
jewelry.
 &HT;    Then one day she bought a trilobite fossil at a roadside shop
for 50 cents. Something about the fact that this weird-looking
creature had been alive millions of years before resonated in her:
``I was hooked,'' she says.
 &HT;    She wanted to know what these creatures were, where they lived,
how they came to be and what their lives were like. With her family
in tow, she tramped all over New Zealand, collecting fossil shells
from Motunau, ammonites from Kawhia, belemnites from Port Waikato.
 &HT;    And she read. There were no universities or natural-history
museums in Hawke's Bay _ where her family lived _ so she haunted
libraries and mail-ordered textbooks and articles from journals.
She read everything from basic encyclopedias to specialized texts.
 &HT;    ``The cretaceous reptiles just caught her attention,'' says
paleontologist Gorden Bell of the U.S. National Park Service. ``She
knew there wasn't a lot of information, and she may have realized
the contribution she could make.''
 &HT;    Slowly, Wiffen became convinced dinosaurs could have lived in
New Zealand. There was fossil evidence of forests existing during
the Jurassic period _ 190 million to 135 million years ago _ and a
record of marine reptiles extending nearly that far back.
 &HT;    Snakes and marsupials hadn't evolved at the time New Zealand
split off from Gondwana _ the southern supercontinent that about 85
million years ago divided into South America, Africa and Australia
_ so those species aren't native to the two islands.
 &HT;    But dinosaurs had existed for some 150 million years at the time
of the split, so why hadn't their remains been found in New
Zealand?
 &HT;    The conventional wisdom was that dinosaurs never migrated to
Wiffen's part of Gondwana before the split, or that the climate had
turned too cold for them to survive.
 &HT;    Wiffen didn't buy it. ``I didn't know a huge amount _ nobody did
at that time in New Zealand _ but I couldn't see any reason why
they couldn't be there.''
 &HT;    So she decided to keep looking.
 &HT;    The search was expensive, so the Wiffens began seeking fossil
sites close to Hawke's Bay. Her big break came in 1972, when she
found an old geological map in the back of a village toy shop. The
map was based on oil exploring, and in a legend down one side, she
read: ``Reptilian bones in beds of brackish water in the Te Hoe
Valley.''
 &HT;    Six months later Wiffen found the site, a remote stream 70 miles
inland and 1,500 feet above sea level. The area had been an estuary
in the Late Cretaceous period. Now fossils were literally bursting
out of the rocks: fish teeth, fish scales and vertebrae, shark
teeth, shells and turtle parts. But no dinosaurs.
 &HT;    Wiffen's whole family became involved in her fossil search and
was joined by a widening circle of friends recruited as much for
brawn as dedication. Wiffen let them feel important, and they were,
but she was the one who learned the names of the bones, understood
how a marine reptile's limbs differed from those of a land reptile
and studied how to get fossils out of rocks.
 &HT;    Her gang prospected up and down Mangahouanga Stream. Sometimes
the crew blew apart the bigger rocks with dynamite, a practice
Wiffen now regards as excessive. But one such explosion in 1974
produced a major discovery _ her first mosasaur specimen.
 &HT;    Four years later she started the process of extracting the bones
from the sandstone surrounding them. For two years, Wiffen toiled
in her garage workshop, sawing at sandstone to reveal more bone,
soaking the bone in an acid bath to eat away more rock, and then
coating the exposed bone with protective resin. Then she repeated
the process until the bone was fully revealed.
 &HT;    In 1980 her long labor was rewarded with the skeleton of what
turned out to be a new genus and species of mosasaur, a massive
carnivorous marine reptile that grew to be as long as 45 feet. The
creatures had powerful sinuous bodies, broad, webbed paddles for
limbs, and long, conical, tooth-filled heads like those of
alligators.
 &HT;    Had she found nothing more than this single creature, her place
in history would be secure, Bell says. But the new genus represents
a specific, separate, unknown lineage of mosasaur and sheds light
on the development of marine reptiles in general. Before long
Wiffen had discovered three more.
 &HT;    But she wasn't just digging up sea creatures. Without knowing
it, she had also found dinosaurs. One day in 1975, Pont found a
piece of petrified wood sticking out of a football-sized
concretion. He broke the rock open with his hammer, saw nothing
interesting and turned it over to his wife. When she inspected it,
fragments of a fossil caught her eye.
 &HT;    ``I thought it was a vertebra, but I didn't know,'' she says.
``I just knew that it was different.'' She couldn't identify it
precisely, and it joined her other unidentified fossils in a locked
cabinet.
 &HT;    In 1979, she and Pont took a holiday in Brisbane and stopped at
the Queensland Museum. There she met Ralph Molnar, an American
paleontologist working as the senior curator of vertebrate fossils.
She noticed some fossil bones on his desk that looked familiar.
 &HT;    ``I have a vertebra like that at home,'' Wiffen said,
remembering the one she'd found back in 1975. ``What is it?''
 &HT;    A dinosaur bone, he said.
 &HT;    Back in Hawke's Bay, Wiffen made casts and photos of her find
and sent them off to Molnar. He phoned two weeks later. ``You've
got yourself a dinosaur.''
 &HT;    ``It was the first dinosaur found in New Zealand,'' Molnar says
today. It belonged to a theropod _ a carnivorous, large-headed
creature resembling a smaller T rex. The bone proved Wiffen's
central point _ that dinosaurs had roamed New Zealand.
 &HT;    Today nobody disputes Wiffen's conclusions. ``She put New
Zealand on the map with respect to Mesozoic reptile discoveries,''
says John Long, curator of vertebrate paleontology at the Western
Australian Museum in Perth and the author of ``Dinosaurs of
Australia and New Zealand.''
 &HT;    The more Wiffen has learned, the more she sees how even the
tiniest finds improve our understanding of an ancient world.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Jack McClintock is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on DISCOVER
NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
