<HEADER>
A0536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     06-21 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL'S NAME LARGEST IN LAKER TITLE CREDITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers are a Hollywood team with
Hollywood themes, which makes it difficult to take them seriously.
It's not always clear what mode they are in: Is it animation or
based on a true story? So when someone tells you that the Lakers
have a player who is just as dominant as any center in pro
basketball history, you brace yourself for the well-timed punch
line.
</P>
<P>
   But there is none.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal stands 7 feet 1 inch and weighs 315 pounds. He
is 28 years old. He compares himself to influential figures such as
Superman and Aristotle. He plays before fans who remember watching
Wilt Chamberlain and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar (he wouldn't have been
able to stop them, but they wouldn't have stopped him, either). He
plays before fans who remember watching Bill Russell take title
after title from the Lakers (he wouldn't have been able to stop the
220-pound Celtic, but Russell wouldn't have stopped him, either).
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal won his first NBA championship Monday night, and did it
in front of another Hall of Fame center, Bill Walton. Like the
others, Walton wouldn't have stopped O'Neal. Hakeem Olajuwon used
to post up so elegantly that you swore there was a secret ballet
being staged in his sneakers . . . Moses Malone had a biblical name
and brought a construction worker's mentality to his game . . .
Patrick Ewing . . . Robert Parish . . . George Mikan . . . David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Scan all the names in the NBA's Big &AMP; Tall register and match
them with O'Neal's. Nothing changes. He doesn't dwarf them nor is
he dwarfed. He is a great player, a Hall of Fame player, and he
held that status long before he averaged 38 points and 16.7
rebounds in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year before the Orlando Magic drafted O'Neal, the team won
21 games. In his rookie season, 1992-93, the team won 41 games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of Hollywood in O'Neal's Lakers. Mel Gibson and
Brad Pitt cheered for them during Monday's game and Vivica A. Fox
talked with them afterward. Their owner, Dr. Jerry Buss, calls
himself an entertainer. Their coach, Phil Jackson, produced his own
version of ``Love And Basketball'' when his wife, June, asked him
to choose between her and the sport. He chose the sport. Recently,
he has also chosen to spend a lot of time with Buss's daughter,
Jeanie. (That, friends, is what you call a triangle offense.)
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and their fans know about dysfunction, too. Shortly
after the clinching, 116-111 win over Indiana, some fans began
setting cars on fire outside Staples Center. Before that, the
hottest story was Mrs. Glen Rice claiming that Jackson was using
her husband as a high-paid hostage in order to get management's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal doesn't fit into that surreal film category. The man is a
straight-up documentary. He is so strong that he sometimes
resembles the red-caped superhero whose logo is branded into his
biceps. One of the funniest scenes from the Finals occurred in Game
5 when Travis Best tried to foul O'Neal flagrantly. The
5-foot-11-inch guard apparently wanted to take O'Neal down. But he
flopped to the court instead. O'Neal looked over the fallen fouler
as if to say, ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar averaged 24.6 points, 11.2 rebounds, and 3.6
assists in his career. Before this season, in which he averaged
29.7 points, 13.6 rebounds, and 3.8 assists, O'Neal's career
numbers were 27.1, 12.2, and 2.5.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal cried after the Lakers won their first title since
1987-88. He was a big man, crying in his mother's arms. He said he
has held his emotions in for a long time, and he is tired of
hearing his critics say what he can't do. He is correct in
defending himself. There are areas in which he is certainly
medicore _ like rapping. But the rap about other areas of his game
are unfair.
</P>
<P>
   No one, absolutely no one, in the NBA can guard him. The game
has changed dramatically, so you won't see O'Neal score 100 points
as Chamberlain did in 1962. He could probably average 50 a night,
even with his poor free throw shooting, but the Lakers wouldn't win
as much. You could put him on the worst team in the NBA right now
and that team would become capable of winning a title. Yes, even
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Lakers executive Jerry West remodeled his team in the
summer of 1996 so O'Neal could join it. Now the Lakers can say they
have won titles in seasons that began in the 1970s, '80s and '90s.
Their former rivals, the Celtics, stopped competing for
championships in the Arsenio Hall era.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russell's career free throw percentage: 56.1.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's: 53.6.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's: 51.1.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's: 76.9 (but he did have small hands).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize, until they play with him, how much he
makes you better, how much easier the game is when he is on the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox said that after O'Neal's 41-point, 12-rebound
performance in Game 6. Fox played 14 minutes in that game and made
one shot. But the shot was O'Neal-inspired and significant. Fox was
being guarded by Reggie Miller, who was trying to decide between
playing closer to Fox or cheating back on O'Neal. Fox faked a pass
to O'Neal. Miller moved back slightly. Just as Miller made the
wrong decision, Fox released a shot beyond the 3-point arc and made
it. The Lakers had a 94-90 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fox knows how easy it is to play with O'Neal because it is
proven that other players disappear when the Big IPO _ he calls
himself that, too _ is not on their side.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Magic went to the finals in 1995. That season, perimeter
shooter Dennis Scott made 44 percent of his shots. With no O'Neal
in the 1996-97 season, Scott made 39 percent of his shots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Indiana coach Larry Bird sat in his temporary
coach's office for more than an hour. He was miserable. Earlier, he
had said of O'Neal: ``He's the most dominating player in our
league. He's just so dominating that they have an opportunity here
to do something great for a number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point the great actor, Jack Nicholson, talked with Bird.
But what was there to say? O'Neal is an atypical Hollywood story.
When you watch him, you expect the credits to roll and reveal the
following:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The previous documentary was produced and directed by Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
