<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SUMMER HITS, TEAM IS BEACHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What now, Boston? Pedro Martinez has succumbed to the
fate that has met so many Red Sox hurlers before him. He was beaten
by the New York Yankees in a game that was badly needed for morale.
The Yankees reached him for three homers in a 3-0 victory over the
staggering Sox.
</P>
<P>
   And so the SS Jimy appears headed into another one of those
Perfect Storms that have splintered Sox boats so many times. Nitwit
sports radio ought to be fun around here today. How do you spell
P-A-N-I-C?
</P>
<P>
   Memo from Red Sox management: Any Sox fan hurt jumping off the
bandwagon must get team approval before surgery or risk having
their contract voided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't panic,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``It's not the
right thing to do in my mind. That's what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   As June games go, this was one the fans felt they had to have.
The Sox were reeling. They'd just given up 22 runs in the worst
Fenway beating in club history. Wounded players were stacked like
cordwood in the trainer's room. The Blue Jays were breathing down
their necks, threatening to drop Boston into third place.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox Nation was nervous. Monday's 22-1 beating ignited
flashbacks of the Boston Massacre of '78. The ghoulish presence of
Don Zimmer in the Yankee dugout wasn't helping any. In a cruel
quirk of the calendar, the dreaded fall was coming on the cusp of
summer and Boston fans were rightfully scared.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro would make everything right, they figured. Pedro would put
the planets back in line. Pedro would slay the hated Yankee dragon
and restore pride and confidence to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out six consecutive Yankees in the early innings
Tuesday night. He gave up only five hits and one walk while fanning
nine. He threw 118 pitches, 76 for strikes. But not even the magic
of Pedro is enough to overcome a salami-bat offense, Wendell ``Send
'Em In'' Kim, two more infield errors, and that old Yankee
dominance that has haunted us for so many months, years, decades,
and centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams, and Paul O'Neill hit solo homers
off Pedro, and Boss Steinbrenner laughed from his club box as the
Yankees conquered the Red Sox before another packed house at
ancient Fenway. It's now an aggregate 25-1 over two days with Pete
(2-6) Schourek and Brother Ramon (6.08 ERA) lined up against the
world champs for the next two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only tell (the fans) to be patient,'' said Pedro, who
saw his ERA skyrocket past Bob Gibson to 1.18. ``We're gonna snap
out of it and hopefully do better. We have plenty of time, we have
plenty of talent and plenty of people willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but the Townies have lost 13 of 19, Pedro has dropped two
straight to the Yanks, and Boston may need Bobby Sprowl and Oil Can
Boyd on the hill at SkyDome this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end of the world,'' said Trot Nixon, looking like
his dog just died. ``But these games against the Yankees are a
little more magnified than others. For me, possibly I'm trying too
hard. Little things in this game can mess with your mind, and with
some of us, it might be messing with our minds out there. But
everybody in the clubhouse cares and cares a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it's depressing when Pedro is unable to pull the Sox
from the abyss, but how much can one man do? In six of Pedro's 13
starts, his teammates have not scored a run in the first five
innings. It's hard to win without any runs. Anybody wish John
Valentin were still around? Wilton Veras clearly is not ready to be
an everyday player in the majors. He's a nice prospect who never
hits the ball hard and looks increasingly skittish in the field.
And now Nomar has bungled two balls in two nights. Yeesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a team,'' Pedro reminded the panic-striken media
throng. ``We go down together and stand together. We're all
struggling, but it's just a bump in the road. We have to keep
playing and find our way out.''
</P>
<P>
   He bristled when it was suggested that the Sox might be
pressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question that doesn't belong in here,'' said the ace.
``We all lose and win. That's not pressing, not with me and my
teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   The mark of these Red Sox under Williams has been that they
don't get too high or too low. They have the correct mentality for
a 162-game hardball marathon. But that approach is being tested now
as never before. They have the look of a rusty 1987 Toyota chugging
uphill just before the wheels come off. These Sox need help, and
it's past time for Boy Wonder Dan Duquette (still harder to find
than Whitey Bulger) to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like these kids, they can play,'' said ultimate company man
Williams. ``I can only talk about the players that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro added, ``Whatever help this team can get, I would like to
be here, but I think this team is good enough to win, personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful. The light from Pedro's star is truly blinding, but it
cannot illuminate an entire franchise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
