<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-OSLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSLO'S MODERN ART LOOKS BEYOND `THE SCREAM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO _ Before heading off to Norway, I asked some local curators
about the contemporary art scene there. They offered to tell me
about Stockholm and Helsinki, about the wonderful new museums in
those cities by Rafael Moneo (Stockholm) and Stephen Holl
(Helsinki.) Those I'd already seen.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Oslo? What happened there after the only
Norwegian artist most of us have heard of, Edvard Munch, of ``The
Scream'' fame? The only contemporary Norwegian artist anyone seemed
aware of was Odd Nerdrum, and primarily because his posh New York
gallery, Forum, regularly places full-page ads for his
Son-of-Old-Master canvases in glossy American art magazines. I saw
a couple of Nerdrums in Oslo's Astrup Fearnley Museum, and odd they
were indeed, unsettling updates of Rembrandt and Caravaggio, the
masters he's mastered. He makes paintings of subjects like ``Woman
Killing Injured Man'' and ``Man with a Woman's Head.'' He's a
flamboyant and controversial figure. To me, his art is creepy and
contrived.
</P>
<P>
   Nerdrum ``is a very public and active figure in Norway,
important in creating interest in art,'' says Per Bjarne Boym, the
director of Oslo's National Museum of Contemporary Art. Boym
expresses his own opinion of Nerdrum through a roundabout route.
``I took the initiative to do a Smithson show here,'' he says,
referring to the American ``Earthworks'' artist Robert Smithson,
most famous for his ``Spiral Jetty'' in Utah's Great Salt Lake.
``It's a different perspective from Nerdrum.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum Boym leads and the Astrup Fearnley Museum of Modern
Art are just around the corner from each other, in one of Oslo's
oldest areas, near the harbor and castle and the quarter of the
city built by King Christian IV in 1624 after a devastating fire
destroyed much of the rest. The two museums have related goals:
Both attempt to integrate contemporary Norwegian art into the
international scene. There's also a current attempt to integrate
Norway into the rest of Scandinavia, through that increasingly
common tactic, the biennale. Cities from Istanbul to Johannesburg
to Havana now have them; Norway's, the ``Momentum Festival of
Contemporary Art,'' restricts itself to Nordic artists. On view
through July 2 this year, ``Momentum'' is being held in the
lakeside town of Moss, a 45-minute train ride from Oslo. (It opened
after I'd already left the country, alas, so I didn't get a look at
it.)
</P>
<P>
   I did, though, get a good look at the 10-year-old National
Museum of Contemporary Art, which is funded by the government, and
at the 7-year-old Astrup Fearnley, which is privately funded by
family foundations established by shipowners Thomas Fearnley and
Nils Astrup, both also descendants of the 19th century Norwegian
landscape painter Thomas Fearnley. The museum, housed within the
sleek modern office building owned by the Astrup Fearnley company,
is vaguely ship-like in design, alluding both to family business
and Viking heritage, with an elevated walkway and prow effect and
enviably handsome galleries of various shapes and sizes. They house
both permanent installations from the considerable collections and
temporary shows.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Contemporary Museum, it split off from the National
Gallery a decade ago, moving into the erstwhile Bank of Norway
building, a stately Art Nouveau structure. Boym, who says ``there's
a very strong situation in Norwegian contemporary art at present,''
wants to move out _ to a new, purpose-built facility behind the
existing National Gallery, so the two collections can be reunited,
each putting the other in context. Besides, says Boym, sounding
like museum directors the world over, the current building is far
too small to show much of what his museum owns. The target date for
the opening of the new one is 2005, pending parliamentary approval
in this fall's session.
</P>
<P>
   The Contemporary Museum's collections, which now number 4,500
works, used to be entirely Norwegian. Now, almost 15 percent of the
objects are by foreigners. Boym has recently acquired a work by US
video sculptor Bill Viola, and the museum owns a spectacular video
by Yugoslavian-born Marina Abramovic, a tower of five monitors, all
showing human hands scrubbing away at a skeleton, as if it could
never be clean enough. Under the Contemporary Museum's auspices,
Jenny Holzer projections have also appeared on the ski jump built
for the Lillehammer Olympics and on Oslo's City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The temporary show I caught at Astrup Fearnley was by the
eminent Norwegian photographer Tom Sandberg, whose large, blurry,
black and white photographs of shadows observed through a veil of
raindrops, or the backs of babies' heads, are fragile and
apparition-like _ especially those that are unframed and tacked
directly on the wall, as if they'd grown right out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The impressive mix at Astrup Fearnley also includes major works
by such international stars as Gerhard Richter, Damien Hirst, and
Anselm Kiefer. Richter's glorious triptych ``River'' surrounds you,
like Monet's last paintings. Hirst, the Bad Boy of British
sculpture, is represented by ``Mother and Child Divided,'' one of
his finest works, a cow and calf, each sliced down the center, each
half floating in formaldehyde in a glass vitrine. Even sadder than
the division of the individual animals is the separation of mother
and child. You have to squeeze yourself between the halves of this
piece, but it's worth the effort, so rich and varied are the
exposed innards. Hirst comes in for a lot of ridicule and protest;
in this piece, he's a poet of the macabre.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer, too, is a poet, one of the towering figures of
contemporary art. His ``The High Priestess'' is permanently
installed in a sanctuary-like space in the depths of the museum. A
vast steel bookcase, it is filled with 126 gigantic lead books,
wrinkled and crumpled, spitting out forbidding wire frizzes,
seeming to contain _ and guard _ the secrets of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have mixed feelings on seeing the same two dozen
internationally celebrated artists in every contemporary museum on
every continent I visit, although, for me, Kiefer is almost always
worth traveling any distance. But the international contemporary
museum experience often boils down to which museum boasts the best
Frank Stellas, and which best displays them. It's a contest of
quality, quantity, and setting.
</P>
<P>
   So it's wonderful to ``click'' with an artist I'd never heard
of, which is what happened to me at the ``Terje Bergstad: Images _
Signs'' show recently at Oslo's Contemporary Museum. Bergstad, now
61, is virtually unknown outside Norway, and exhibits rarely,
largely because his life has been spent in and out of hospitals
with what Boym calls ``mental and physical illness that has
debilitated him through the drugs he has to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone, especially any foreigner, will see Munch in Bergstad:
Both are suffering souls finding solace in nature. But Bergstad
seems to me an authentic voice, although his Oslo retrospective,
covering work from the 1960s to the present, met with mixed
critical reaction, partly because of its somber Munch-ishness.
</P>
<P>
   Bergstad works primarily on paper, which gives his art
fragility, and with the most basic materials. Darkness is his
hallmark, and some works are so smudgy that you can barely tell a
nude from a landscape. His series of ``Cathedrals'' has more in
common with the dark, rugged outlines of Rouault than with the
cathedrals of Monet. Some of Bergstad's cathedrals sag, as if about
to collapse. A couple of them are on blackened, coarse, wrinkled
burlap, as if drowned by dirt and soot.
</P>
<P>
   Like Munch, Bergstad is obsessed with deathbed and sickroom
scenes, which light cannot penetrate even through there are large
windows in the rooms. He's made a series of highly intuitive
drawings, on scraps of paper, of patients waiting in doctors'
offices. He's also obsessed with the forests of Telemark,
traditional home of trolls, and draws and paints its cottages,
farms, and lakes with thick, jagged lines. During his hospital
stays, he listened to radio reports of atrocities historic and
modern, at Terezin and Soweto, and made series on those themes, the
imagery askew, the faces disembodied, sometimes drawn on brown
paper that looks like grocery store bags.
</P>
<P>
   Bergstad had a single US show, in a New York gallery in 1967,
when he was exhibited as ``promising.'' The promise was fulfilled;
the career was not. Next February, the McMullen Museum of Art at
Boston College will mount a Munch show. It would be wonderful if
some other area institution would seize the opportunity to restage
the Bergstad show at the same time: There's already a handsome
catalog translated into English.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
