<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S WELL ON HIS WAY TO BEING ABLE TO RETIRE AT 55 OR 60 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I am single and intend to work until I am 60. I have other
savings for emergencies and to purchase of a home. My 401(k) will
be my only retirement savings. Will I have enough to retire at 60?
What about at 55? Should I reallocate my 401(k) investments? What
would be the advantage of a Roth IRA as an alternative to funding
my 401(k) to the same extent?
</P>
<P>
   M.O., Weymouth, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You would probably be in good shape to retire at 55, and
certainly at 60. The numbers can be a little elusive, since I am
simply plotting out the growth of your 401(k) with the current
balance and contributions. In reality, if you continue your
retirement savings as a percentage of earnings, the expected
accumulation would rise as your earnings rise, and over 30 or 35
years that would make a very big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here's the math based on current contributions. If you
earned average 10 percent investment returns, you would have
$1,999,008 at age 55 and $3,342,214 at age 60. Those numbers sound
nice, but here's the shocker: You are now living on $48,400 a year
_ your income less your retirement savings. If inflation runs at
3.5 percent a year for 30 years, you will need $135,848 to buy what
$48,400 buys today; after 35 years, the figure would rise to
$161,345.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulation at age 55 would provide an income stream
sufficient to maintain your lifestyle, but there would not be
enough left over to provide capital growth to protect you against
the inflation of your retirement years.
</P>
<P>
   So why did I say you probably could retire comfortably at 55?
Because as your income rises, so would your contributions. These
additions should generate sufficient additional accumulation to put
you in a much brighter situation than the one spelled out above.
</P>
<P>
   Your 401(k) allocations are OK, but not much more. I find no
record of a Fidelity Enhanced Index fund, and am guessing that what
you hold is the Fidelity Spartan Total Market Index fund, which has
about 2,300 stocks _ basically the Standard and Poor's 500 plus a
sampling from the smaller-cap universe.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that since index funds are market-cap weighted,
the broader market index funds remain almost thoroughly dominated
by the large-cap domestic funds. For that reason, I'd suggest you
drop the total market index offering and seek out direct
participation in different market sectors. Among the available
offerings you listed, I would suggest 15 percent positions in each
of the Putnam Small Cap and International offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as you can see, your expected accumulation in the
401(k) will be substantial, so you won't be in a position to face
significantly reduced taxes in retirement. So there is only one
situation in which the Roth IRA would not be a good idea, which is
if a reduction in your 401(k) contributions would cause a reduction
in your employer match. If you can reduce your contributions to the
401(k) by $2,000 a year without affecting the employer match, I
suggest you do open Roth IRA accounts, beginning with a holding
such as Vanguard Health Care fund, and then in the following year
using Fidelity Select Technology fund, thereafter alternating your
investments between the two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Almost 11 years ago, I bought 40 shares of Harley-Davidson at
$25 a share. Through subsequent purchases, five stock splits, and
reinvestment of dividends, the position has grown to 4,228 shares.
My dilemma is what to do with the investment. I do not need the
money. Should I sell some shares and diversify? What do I do with
the capital gains? Selling would be difficult, since I have become
fond of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Sun Lakes, Ariz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can understand why you hesitate to sell. I calculate that
your base cost for your initial purchase of 40 shares comes out to
$2.23, after adjusting for the five two-for-one stock splits.
</P>
<P>
   Since I can't estimate your overall base cost without knowing
the full sequence of subsequent purchases and reinvestments, I
can't estimate your capital gains exposure, but when you look at a
14-year chart for the stock, the path is dominantly upward, with a
few dips showing fairly quick recoveries. The result, of course, if
that you would face substantial capital gains taxes upon any sale.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have a clear idea of your overall portfolio, but from
what you have written it seems likely the HDI position represents a
very substantial percentage. If that's the case, it seems to me a
good idea to diversify. One thing you may be able to do is isolate
some purchases that have not seen terrific growth levels.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you bought shares in early 1999, you might have
a few purchases that were made in the low $30s. As this is written,
the stock has a $35.69 per share market value, down from a 52-week
high of $46.63 achieved at a spike in the stock in mid-April. If
you were to sell some shares with a fairly high base cost, your tax
burden would not be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   But it is important that when you isolate those shares with the
highest base cost, you specify to your broker in writing when you
make your sale order what specific shares you are selling,
identifying them either with a certificate number or the precise
date of purchase. If you do not make such a specification, the IRS
follows the FIFO rule _ the first shares that went into your
portfolio will be deemed the first out, and thus you will be back
to those shares with the $2.23 base cost.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing you can do to diversify is to discontinue your
participation in the dividend reinvestment plan. I know it's not a
lot of money, with the current 0.2 percent yield working out to
only $422 a year, but if you were to sell some of the more
expensive shares and put the proceeds into a broadly diversified
mutual fund, the Harley dividends would provide a steady, if slow,
rate of additions to the diversified account.
</P>
<P>
   As for holding onto a large percentage of the stock, it doesn't
seem too terrible on the surface. Growth prospects for Harley are
strong, with projected earnings of $1.06 per share for this year
comparing nicely to the 86 cents earned in 1999. In the current
market, such a growth rate seems to me to justify its
price-to-earnings ratio of 38.5, compared to a 32.5 PE for the
Standard and Poor's Index.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the key words in that last sentence are ``in the
current market,'' and an old bear such as myself is pretty spooked
by a market with a 32.5 PE for the broad large-cap index. For that
reason, I would get as close as you can without serious tax
consequences to getting the HDI position reduced by about half.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I enclose a list of my 401(k) plan allocations and the
alternatives available. Should I make any changes?
</P>
<P>
   J.G., Quincy, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would suggest a few. Except for the Overseas fund, your
holdings are in large-cap US stocks. I would reduce the positions
in Blue Chip Growth and Magellan by 5 percent each, putting that 10
percent in Fidelity OTC, a fund with a mid-cap growth-oriented
portfolio. The fund typically invests in a fairly risky portfolio _
61 percent in technology stocks, according to the latest
Morningstar Mutual Funds report _ but since your time frame is so
long, you should be willing to face that risk.
</P>
<P>
   The other change I would suggest is with the Fidelity Freedom
2020 holding. The various Freedom funds simply invest in other
Fidelity funds, with the portfolio makeup targeted to the date in
the fund's name. The shorter the target date, the more the fund
moves to conservative, yield-oriented holdings. The longer the
target date, the more aggressive the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Since you anticipate retiring in 2030, it seems Fidelity Freedom
2030 would be a better choice than Freedom 2020. What's the
difference? Not a great deal. Each spreads its assets among 16
Fidelity funds, but Freedom 2020's fixed-income holdings make up 22
percent of the portfolio, while the Freedom 2030 fund has only 15.5
percent on the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   But the heavier stock position of the 2030 fund can spell a
noticeable difference in results. Last year, Fidelity Freedom 2020
produced a 25.3 percent gain, while Freedom 2030 had a 28.5 percent
total return. Over 30 years, differences such as that will really
add up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
