<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-A3XX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OUTSIZED DEBATE OVER THE A3XX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Airbus and Boeing have competitive planes from 100
seats to more than 350 seats, but Boeing is alone in the 400-plus
seat market with the 30-year-old 747.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's monopoly in this jumbo jet market has more than
irritated Airbus executives in Toulouse, France. Consortium
officials say privately that they need to build its A3XX if only to
prevent Boeing from maintaining a vise grip on that market.
</P>
<P>
   Some Airbus officials say that with no competition at the high
end, Boeing can use profits from the 747 to lower the cost on
airplanes where the two companies do compete _ a charge Boeing
officials say is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus and Boeing agree there is a market for such a large plane
_ and Boeing chairman Phil Condit is actively pushing a stretched
version of the 747-400, known as the 747X _ but they disagree on
how large a market there is. Boeing says there is a need for about
365 planes that seat more than 500; Airbus says it is more than
1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is unwilling to spend billions on developing a new
airplane for such a small market. Airbus officials say development
costs of the A3XX will be at least $12 billion, but they think the
cost is worth it. Their planes would sell for more than $200
million each and have a lower operating cost than the 747-400.
</P>
<P>
   Emirates Airlines and Singapore Airlines have said they would
buy the airplane, but Airbus last month indefinitely postponed a
board meeting to possibly decide whether to proceed with the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus officials have said that Cathay Pacific, Virgin Atlantic,
Air France, and FedEx are interested in the plane as well.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, however, believes that the future of air traffic will
involve much more point-to-point traffic with smaller aircraft
seating 200-300 people. They point to the North Atlantic as an
example of what will happen in the Pacific. Indeed, United Airlines
has said that if it merges with US Airways, it will begin nonstop
Asian service from several eastern cities, including Boston. It is
that type of routing, Boeing officials say, that lessens the need
for a 600-seat jet.
</P>
<P>
   The 747 was built in the late 1960s, when the industry was
highly regulated. Airlines were told where they could fly, how
frequently they could fly, and what they could charge. The only way
to increase profit was to increase the number of seats, hence the
need for the 747.
</P>
<P>
   But with deregulation, routes that were unthinkable a short time
ago became commonplace. For example, in 1987 there was one daily
flight from Chicago's O'Hare Airport to Europe. Today, according to
Boeing, there are 21.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and many Boeing officials fear a plane the size of
the A3XX would result in a downturn in the airline industry. They
reason that in order to fill the seats, the airlines would lower
costs, which would reduce yields across the board. As a result,
with lower profits airlines would be less inclined to buy
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, filling the 747 can prove to be a challenge. Boeing has
sold more than 1,200 in the last 30 years. Tower Air, which ranks
19th on the list of airlines with the most 747s, filed for
bankruptcy protection earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 747 is a marvelous airplane, but it is the quickest way to
go broke if you don't fill it up,'' said Joseph W. Ozimek, Boeing's
Commercial Airplane Group director of product marketing, in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus senior vice president John Leahy stopped an interview in
Toulouse to take a private call from FedEx chairman and chief
executive Frederick W. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, Leahy called the reporter back into his
office and said with a smile, ``It's fair to say the A3XX came up
in that conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said that Airbus ``has 60 percent of the market where we
do compete and once we get the A3XX on line it will become very
obvious _ Airbus will have better than half the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to make sure we are not equal, but I think it will
stabilize and we and Boeing will drift back and forth. It is a
duopoly. Airlines like that and it will be stable.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Leahy think of Boeing's concern that there is not
enough demand for such a large plane to invest billions in research
and development?
</P>
<P>
   ``I genuinely appreciate the fact that they put their little
hostilities toward Airbus behind them and are now trying
desperately to save us from ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
