<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-ART-2TA     06-21 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING, AIRBUS BATTLE TO RULE THE SKIES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TOULOUSE, France _ It began almost as a patriotic last stand:
European countries banding together to create a consortium to crack
America's complete dominance in commercial aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Airbus Industrie created the world's first
twin-aisle, twin-engine airplane, the A300 Airbus. Since then, the
company has been an innovator in the use of computers to design and
manufacture airplanes. Bankrolled by European governments, Airbus
was the first to introduce fly-by-wire controls _ where electrical
signals convey the control commands from the pilot to wing flaps,
rather than mechanical devices _ saving on maintenance costs and
reducing the weight of airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it seems, the Boeing Co., which rode the 707, 727,
737, and 747 to supremacy in manufacturing commercial jet
airplanes, is in the middle of a 15-round battle to maintain its
crown, and the last few rounds have been going to challenger
Airbus. The European manufacturer landed a punishing blow last
year: For the first time, it took the majority of orders for new
aircraft _ a $50 billion market _ away from Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in market share from 19 percent in 1995 to 55 percent
last year reflects a stunning success. And Airbus has grabbed more
than market share; it has captured Boeing's attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based aerospace giant is now using computers to
design its planes and fly-by-wire technology. And it is creating
other services (such as pilot training, a rapid high-technology
distribution system for spare parts, and after-market engineering)
and even new airplane models (two new long-range 777s and a
stretched 767).
</P>
<P>
   Because Boeing is so important to the US economy _ it is the
nation's leading exporter _ some sales competitions have been
accompanied by intense diplomatic pressures. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright lobbied Israel to reconsider purchasing Airbus
aircraft for the first time for its national airline, El Al, even
though the country also said it would buy Boeing. Just having some
Airbus aircraft at El Al, which had been all-Boeing, was a symbolic
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The competition has also resulted in ill will as obvious as the
roar of a jet engine. Officials from both companies are often heard
deriding the talent and product of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been battling Airbus for almost as long as they have
been in business, and make no mistake, they are formidable
competition,'' said Larry Dickenson, who began his career with
McDonnell Douglas, came to Boeing in 1986, and was promoted this
year to senior vice president of sales and marketing in Boeing's
commercial airplane group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have come a long way. Are they on a par with Boeing?
No,'' he said, punctuating his answer with a defiant snort.
</P>
<P>
   Some airline executives disagree. Airbus has won several
converts because their airplanes share the same cockpit design,
which reduces training and maintenance costs. Swissair officials
said the ability to have pilots certified to fly both single-aisle
and widebody aircraft will save the airline as much as 20 percent
of its flight-crew costs. Furthermore, Airbus's single-aisle family
of aircraft _ the A318, A319, A320 and A321 _ have a fuselage that
is several inches wider than Boeing's venerable 737 and the 757,
which some analysts say makes the Airbus planes more comfortable
for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue, the well-financed, low-cost start-up operating out of
New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport, chose the A320
over Boeing 737 aircraft and has firm orders for 40 of the
airplanes and options for another 43. That decision surprised many,
including JetBlue founder and chief executive David Neeleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an all-Boeing team. . . but when it came down to it,
the A320 was superior,'' Neeleman said in a recent interview. ``Our
business plan was to use 737s, but every airline that we talked to
that was operating the two side-by-side all basically said they
would not consider buying another 737.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus's success last year came predominantly in the
single-aisle market _ 408 of its 476 orders were for the A320
family. Of Boeing's 391 orders, 95 were wide-bodies, which are more
expensive. The company sold 35 747-400s, 37 767s, and 23 777s.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other airlines, such as Midway and Aloha, that
chose the 737 over the A320. And Delta flies only Boeing airplanes
and the new 737s will compete head-on with the A320s on the
Boston-New York-Washington shuttle this year.
</P>
<P>
   With its recent success in the single-aisle market, Airbus seems
poised to risk at least $12 billion _ much of it coming from
European governments _ to build the A3XX, a superjumbo with 550 to
650 seats. The A3XX would compete directly with Boeing's last
stronghold, the 747, which is the only plane with more than 400
seats. While Boeing insists there is only a small market for such
enormous planes, it is spending more than $1 billion to stretch the
747 so it can hold 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Because Airbus is not publicly traded (the company is moving to
become a publicly held corporation), it is impossible to
financially compare the two companies or determine to what extent
government loans to Airbus have gone unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   What is obvious, however, is the ill will between the two
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In Toulouse, the city in southwestern France that is home to
Airbus headquarters, Boeing products are derided as old-fashioned,
outdated and costly; executives of the American company are viewed
as arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   At Boeing headquarters, Airbus airplanes are dismissed as old
(the fuselage design has not changed), uncomfortable, and costly.
Boeing executives view Airbus Industrie as a company propped up by
subsidies and run by executives who try to jam products into a
reluctant market rather than respond to market needs, and who will
raise phony safety issues in an effort to gain market share.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives become almost apoplectic when talking about a
recent Airbus ad for the A340, which has four engines and competes
with the twin-engine 777. Over a photograph of a wind-whipped
menacing sea and an A340 in the upper-right corner, the copy reads:
``If you're over the middle of the Pacific, you want to be in the
middle of four engines.'' And in smaller type, ``It's always
reassuring to have the redundancy option of four engines rather
than two. Especially when you're a long, long, long way from
home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a bogus controversy,'' said Ishanne Mounir, a regional
marketing director for Boeing, who points out that four-engine
aircraft, like the A340 and 747, have a much higher turnback rate
because of engine problems than the twin-engine 777 and the
twin-engine 767.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus spokeswoman Mary Anne Greczyn said the ad _ which is no
longer running _ was not intended to question safety but rather to
point out the cost efficiency of a four-engine airplane, which does
not have to conform to routing known as ETOPS. Such routes require
two-engine planes to always be within three hours of a suitable
airport.
</P>
<P>
   It is an argument Boeing officials don't buy, because the
curvature of the Earth makes most ETOPS routes similar to
four-engine routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are people in France who believe in the Flat
Earth Society, but I don't know why they would do this unless they
were trying to sell airplanes by fear,'' said Joseph W. Ozimek,
director of product marketing, in a recent interview in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials note that their planes _ even fly-by-wire 777
aircraft _ give pilots more control than Airbus aircraft, which
limit the amount of pitch and roll no matter how hard a pilot turns
or dives an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the differences in the jets are subtle. As a result,
sales campaigns to airlines are carefully planned and orchestrated
with analysts, financial planners, engineers, pilots, and sales
executives contributing to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not like a discretionary income purchase where you walk
in and kick the tires and drive out of the showroom with a new
plane,'' said John Leahy, the hard-charging American who heads
Airbus sales efforts. ``These campaigns take a year, two years. If
I brought something over here from America, it is the team
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing's Dickenson says the support system that comes with
an airplane acquisition is critical. ``At the end of the day, this
is a people business. Buying an airplane is like getting married,
it is a question of whom do you want to deal with for the next 15
to 25 years?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
