<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $1,300 JACKET? DAMN RIGHT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   See the movie. Buy his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   During the filming of ``Shaft,'' which grossed more than $21
million over the weekend, Samuel L. Jackson had 65 costume changes.
</P>
<P>
   Although a range of designers contributed to the movie's
wardrobe, Giorgio Armani created the signature sartorial look,
dressing detective Shaft in a black three-quarter-length leather
jacket, a high mock-neck wool sweater, wool pants, and lace-up
leather boots.
</P>
<P>
   Armani's so-called ``Shaft jacket'' has raw-cut edges and
unfinished seams. It is in stock at some Emporio Armani stores for
$1,298. The Boston outlet carries only the women's version of this.
However, a different men's overcoat and leather pants for about
$600 each will be coming soon. Can you dig it?
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, wardrobe reflects the inner changes of the title
character. Shaft is also seen in a longer black leather jacket
designed by Versace (tagged in a Newbury Street store for $1,814),
which is worn over a Gianfranco Ferre gray wool knit turtleneck
subtly striped with black, along with wool gabardine flat-front
pants by Armani and Kenzo boots. This is Shaft's ``classic'' look.
</P>
<P>
   During his underground phase, Shaft's style turns more street
casual, and he wears dark, mysterious colors that befit his mood.
But the look is still high fashion, from the top of his bald pate _
capped in a knit number by Missoni _ right down to his Miu Miu
ridge-soled olive police shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Shaft emerging later in the movie is dressed in
suedes, as if to say the character is softer, more approachable.
</P>
<P>
   An Emporio Armani spokeswoman said skullcaps and mock necks
would be available soon, along with a post-Monica velvet beret
($98), similar to the one Vanessa Williams wears in the flick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perspiration inspiration
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the thought of spending $1,298 on a Shaft jacket is enough to
make you sweat, relax.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new wrinkle in the use of Botox, otherwise used to
diminish lines around the eyes and forehead.
</P>
<P>
   For about $1,000, dermatologists can inject both flanks with the
toxin, produced by the same bacteria that, if ingested in large
amounts, causes bacillism.
</P>
<P>
   The result: No sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It interferes with the transmission of the signal between
certain nerves and certain . . . muscles or sweat glands,'' says
dermatologist Rachel Herschenfeld. ``When the nerves can't send the
signal, the muscle can't contract or the sweat gland won't produce
sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatment can also help patients with severely sweaty palms
or foreheads. Those procedures cost less because a smaller amount
of Botox is used.
</P>
<P>
   However, the injections, which last a few months, aren't
recommended for the occasional sufferer and are not covered by
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be very useful for people who have a problem,''
Herschenfeld said. ``It's amazing. It's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looks for the leg
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those cringing at the thought would surely rule out liposuction.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do when looking jiggly in that clingy sundress is
not an option and pantyhose simply cannot be worn with sandals?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of cutting the feet off your nylons, and having them
roll up to your knees, buy footless stockings, which have become
popular with the open-toe shoe trend. They often come in two
lengths: Midthigh and just-below the knee.
</P>
<P>
   When the summer is over, switch to fishnets, the leg covering a
la mode, especially in nude colors.
</P>
<P>
   Italian women _ even the most business-minded and matronly among
them _ have been loyal to fishnets for the better part of a decade
because they offer just enough covering with texture.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion, which has finally migrated to this country, is
being pushed as a serious alternative hosiery, not as a vampy
nightclub accessory. Although that works, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unleash your pride
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Friday is Take Your Dog to Work Day. But if your boss
balks at the idea, you can pin a likeness of the pooch on your
blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin Pearl on Newbury Street has a new line of hand-painted
French enamel dog _ and cat _ pins. Prices range from $75 to $100.
Breeds range from pugs to Labradors. They also sell stands to
display the pins as works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Five percent of the retail price goes toward the American
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
