<HEADLINE>
PARTIES DIVIDE WHEN POLITICS, MARKETS MEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We usually write about markets and leave the subject of politics
to our colleagues in other parts of the paper.
</P>
<P>
   But we've been struck this year by how frequently markets and
politics are colliding. On a wide range of issues _ Social
Security, Medicare, the budget surplus, Microsoft _ the central
question is: How much faith do you have in markets and how much
faith do you have in the government?
</P>
<P>
   On all these issues and even a few others, Al Gore and the
Democrats find themselves in a different place along the spectrum
than George W. Bush and the Republicans. ``The Democrats generally
believe a little more government is better, and the Republicans
generally prefer to leave a little more to the market,'' said Mark
Zandi, chief economist at RFA Dismal Sciences, Pennsylvania
forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between the two parties is not as large it once was. A
decade of prosperity and a booming stock market have pushed the
Democrats to embrace free-market capitalism in a way they never
would have in the past. Last week 65 Democrats in the House of
Representatives even voted to abolish the federal estate tax, an
act of heresy that must have had Tip O'Neill rolling over in his
grave.
</P>
<P>
   But if the gap between the parties is smaller, it is still
critical. ``To me the differences come through loud and clear,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist at Primark Decision Economics in
Waltham. ``The question is: what role or how big a role will the
federal government play in our lives and in our economy?''
</P>
<P>
   Take Social Security. Bush has proposed letting individuals
invest a portion of their Social Security contribution in stocks or
bonds. Gore wants to leave the program alone, arguing that Social
Security recepients should not be subject to the vagaries of the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore is hedging his bets. This week he unveiled a
supplemental retirement plan that would let Americans _ you guessed
it _ invest a portion of their savings in the stock market. Bush
promptly accused Gore of being a copycat and hypocrite. ``It raises
a question of what Al Gore believes in,'' said a Bush spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the end the two plans are different. Bush is willing to
trust the market to improve Social Security. Gore wants Social
Security to remain a government guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   On Medicare, both parties are in favor of adding a drug benefit
to the health insurance plan for seniors. The Republicans, as the
New York Times put it, ``want more choices and options for
beneficiaries, a larger role for private insurance companies, and a
smaller role and lower costs for the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats fear that too great a reliance on the market will
leave seniors at the mercy of insurance companies that only want to
cover the healthy. The Republicans fear that too great a reliance
on government will lead to price controls on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to use the surplus to pay down debt, beef up Social
Security and Medicare and provide a modest tax cut. Bush wants a
bigger tax cut on the theory that surplus money left in Washington
will wind up being spent on bigger government.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has yet to surface as a campaign issue but it could.
``The Microsoft case represents a watershed event in antitrust
policy,'' said Mark Zandi. By pursuing the breakup of a company
because it stifles innovation, rather than because it pushes up
prices, the Clinton administration has taken antitrust to a new and
more aggressive level, according to Zandi.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hasn't said much about the case, but it is not too hard to
imagine him suggesting that he'd prefer to let the market rather
than government decide Microsoft's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline is another issue with the potential to pop up on the
campaign trail. Nationally gas prices are over $1.60 a gallon; in
some places in the Midwest they are over $2 a gallon. Energy
specialists blame some of the price hikes in the Midwest on new
federal environmental regulations that have created tight supplies
in certain markets.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too much of a stretch to picture Bush blaming the problem
on the ``big government solutions'' of the Clinton-Gore
administration?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes government regulation,'' conceded Robert Reich, a
former member of the Clinton administration, now a professor at
Brandeis. But Reich says there is still a constituency for
government programs ``that don't leave people vulnerable to the
random ups and downs of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Will that kind of philosophy prevail in November? Or are voters
ready to put their trust in the markets and George W. Bush? Stay
tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
