<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHICKENRUN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHICKEN RUN' CREATORS HAVE ANIMATED TIME JUST FOWLING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Growing up in Great Britain in the '70s, Peter Lord
and Nick Park didn't have to look far for comic inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we are the Monty Python kids,'' says Park, who joined
Lord to co-direct the upcoming claymation comedy ``Chicken Run,''
which is voiced by Mel Gibson and could be this summer's `Toy
Story.`
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Lord imitated the work of Python trouper Terry
Gilliam, who assembled the bizarre artwork on the group's zany
television show. Lord eventually became a cell animator, which he
found slow, painful and ``not very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he discovered the joys of claymation, ultimately
creating a British version of Gumby called Morph. That impressed
his future partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always secretly dreamt of creating characters that would
become household names,'' Park says. ``When I first met Pete, he
had a badge on his lapel off his TV character Morph...I just
thought, `How cool is that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, the two teamed up to produce ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit,''
an Oscar-winning series of stop-action animated shorts known for
fluid action sequences and dry wit.
</P>
<P>
   That same British humor permeates ``Chicken Run,'' a
feature-length claymation film that remakes ``The Great Escape,''
casting chickens as the prisoners. In the film, which opens Friday,
the birds must break out of an egg farm before they're turned into
pot pies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a British sensibility,'' Park says, ``playing on
the minimal and the deadpan and the mundane.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lord and Park are top animators, ``Chicken Run''
presented some unique challenges.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the fat, round bodies that prevent chickens from flying
_ a major point of the story _ also makes them difficult to
re-create as puppets.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy clay bodies wouldn't stand up for long on spindly chicken
legs, so the animators came up with a compromise. The chickens'
heads and the wings were made of a claylike substance called
Plasticine, but the bodies were actually latex stretched over
silicone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have some kind of skeletal structure inside the
chicken as well, to keep up their weight,'' Park says. ``So you
have this kind of ``RoboCop`-style armature ... the animator has to
grab hold of the puppet and force it or tweak it.''
</P>
<P>
   Every chicken was created in two scales. About 300 larger ``A
scale'' models were used when the chickens were interacting with
each other, while 130 smaller, ``B scale'' models were employed
when they were dealing with Mr. and Mrs. Tweedy, the humans who run
the chicken farm.
</P>
<P>
   The puppets were produced using a special brand of Plasticine,
concocted by Aardman, a model animation studio co-founded by Lord
and David Sproxton in 1972. The color of each bird was selected and
blended in a converted chewing-gum machine in the studio. The
molded feathers were hand-painted in a painstaking process that
took up to a day for each chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The scarves and necklaces worn by the chickens serve a dual
purpose: giving each bird an individual personality and hiding the
seams of their detachable heads. Filmmakers also created about 60
interchangeable beaks, which were used to express different vowels
or consonants and allowed the chickens to look like they are
actually speaking.
</P>
<P>
   The attention to detail is incredible: The knitting carried by
one chicken was created with cocktail toothpicks and thread, while
Mrs. Tweedy's cardigan was knitted by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive is the Aardman style of animation, which
requires repositioning the chickens up to 24 times per second of
film. Even when 28 sets were operating simultaneously, the goal was
to produce about 10 seconds of film per day.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the fluid motion that has made Aardman famous,
animators used both video and digital cameras, constantly checking
for continuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was up to Nick and me, the whole film would have been a
horrendous tangle,'' Lord says. ``We employed dozens of people to
sort it all out. Each of us had a continuity person at our shoulder
always saying to us, `You can't put that chicken there.'''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the technique is showcased in a dance sequence _
dubbed ``Flip, Flop and Fly'' by the filmmakers _ that has multiple
characters moving at different speeds on different levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We relied on the fantastic energy of our animators,'' Lord
says, noting that he asked them to do things that he would have
never done as an animator.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock running down on the movie, Park adds, they
decided to do close-ups, which they thought might be easier to
animate. But the economical move didn't pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even on close-ups, there were always at least sort of 12
chickens in the background that all had to be expressing themselves
and moving in some way or another,'' Park says.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the filmmakers feel like they produced something
that crosses boundaries between realism and cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're operating in a twilight world,'' Park says. ``You've got
the gritty reality of live action ... but we can be cartoony
because it's clay. It's a strangely real but magical kind of
illusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
