<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-INTERNET-TRAFFIC-HNS &LR;      06-21 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TRAFFIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW ECONOMY, OLD FOE: SOME DRIVERS BLAME GRIDLOCK ON
E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: Filed in ``l'' and ``f'' category; note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RYAN KIM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internet commerce, that sexy new concept
revolutionizing consumerism in the 21st century, is causing a
decidedly Old World problem in San Francisco: more traffic
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of increasing Internet commerce is that most
products bought on line need to be delivered by the likes of UPS,
FedEx, Webvan or any number of courier services. But in San
Francisco, where the streets are narrow and crowded with cars, the
appearance of more delivery trucks _ often double-parked _ is
causing traffic snarls that are sure to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   It has made an already congested city even more gridlocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing the trucks that double-park,'' said Ashley Ryles,
38, who commutes to the city from Danville. ``When you come down
Fifth or Fremont (streets), the whole right lane can be taken with
delivery trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Delivery companies defend their work, saying they are helping
traffic, not hindering it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking people off the road who would be going to the
grocery store,'' said Amy Nobile, a spokeswoman for Webvan, a
door-to-door grocery deliver service. ``It can be seen as a
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the drivers, although sometimes double-parked, are
usually very quick and do not spend unnecessary time while parking.
Nobile said that if consumers weren't using Webvan, many of them
would be on the streets, double-parking while doing errands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say they'd be double-parking all of Saturday if it
weren't for Webvan,'' Nobile said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all drivers buy her logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't consider them taking more traffic off the street,''
said Pete Haffner, 22, of Glen Park. ``Those trucks take up more
room than cars, and people usually find a parking spot during a
grocery run.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, San Francisco, the city with the second-highest
density in the nation, always has had to deal with delivery trucks
that double-park. The city has a shortage of curb-side parking, and
more commuters keep driving to work as part of a technology-fueled
hiring boom.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers say the situation has gotten worse in the
past couple years because of increased e-commerce deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers seem to suggest they are right. According to
Forrester Research Inc., a Cambridge, Mass.-based technology
research company, $20.2 billion was spent over the Internet last
year, and $38.7 billion is expected to change hands on the Web this
year. By 2004, $184.5 billion is expected to be spent on line,
according to Forrester.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a small percentage of the products that can be
downloaded onto a computer, the bulk needs to be delivered, said
Chris Kelley, an analyst with Forrester.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more experienced consumers get with purchasing on line,
the more they will purchase, and the larger their purchases will
be,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said that if the crush of delivery trucks became too much
for some urban areas, delivery companies might opt to extend their
hours or might consider having customers pick up their products at
a depot for a reduced price.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see more creative ways to get products to the
consumer,'' Kelley said. ``But you'll see some increased traffic
along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hamdun, San Francisco's acting director of parking and
traffic, agreed the rise in on-line retail has made traffic worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person's convenience is another person's inconvenience,''
Hamdun said. ``With the expansion of e-commerce, it just makes it
that much more important for our department to come up with
solutions for double-parking.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his department, which tickets double-parked delivery
trucks, was looking at other measures to ease the flow of traffic.
In July, the department will begin doubling fines for
double-parking on 15 key transit lines. Within 60 days, parking
officials also will be testing extended truck loading zones that
will accommodate larger trucks that can't fit into existing loading
zones.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the road, the department is considering plans to
restrict downtown deliveries, either during certain hours or on
specific thoroughfares. Such a program, which would involve the
cooperation of businesses and the delivery companies, would not get
under way for some time, Hamdun said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department recognizes that the streets have been a little
more congested lately, and we're trying to do something about it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Currently, UPS is the biggest deliverer of Internet goods with a
commanding 55 percent share of the market. The U.S. Postal Service
follows with 32 percent, and FedEx is third with 10 percent of
e-commerce deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   UPS spokeswoman Angela McMahon said the company delivers about
13 million packages per day, 1.5 million more than two years ago.
She said much of that increase has come from Internet purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's generally understood that UPS has benefited from the
growth in e-commerce,'' McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   She said there was not much the company could do about traffic
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a delivery company, we just deliver packages,'' McMahon
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some commuters still blame delivery truck drivers for not
trying harder to lessen the congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there's a parking space two or three spots down,
(delivery truck drivers) won't park there,'' said Smita Gupta, 33,
a Palo Alto architect who works in San Francisco. ``They just stop
right in front and double-park.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon, however, said UPS did not encourage double-parking by
its drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In finding places to park, UPS's policy is to avoid
double-parking whenever possible, and in some cases we have
adjusted delivery schedules when loading zones were more
available,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the crunch on the street is likely to get worse as
more people flock to on-line buying. That is, unless technology can
produce a solution, said 48-year-old Dave Byers of Concord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to be able to download groceries by modem,'' he
said, ``and then we're all set.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
