<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASYLUM-MILOSEVIC-OPED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICTATORS DON'T DESERVE SAFE HAVENS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The fate of Slobodan Milosevic remains a conundrum for all, not
least for the Yugoslav president himself. He has successfully clung
to power for more than a decade _ despite repeated predictions of
his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition is so chaotically divided that Milosevic's hold
on power is shaken but scarcely stirred.
</P>
<P>
   The West, eager to find an incentive for Milosevic to give up
the reins, now seems ready to cut a deal whereby the Serb leader
would find asylum outside Yugoslavia _ in Russia, say, or Greece.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of precedents for such a comfortable
retirement. From Idi Amin, in Uganda, to the Haitian dictator Baby
Doc Duvalier, the tradition has long been that a departing dictator
finds luxury elsewhere _ in Baby Doc's case, in the south of
France.
</P>
<P>
   Another argument in favor of allowing Milosevic an easy way out
is that he could get especially nasty if he knew his back was
firmly against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic believes that any future democratic government in
Belgrade would deliver him up to the war crimes tribunal at The
Hague, there can be no advantage for him in a handover of power.
Instead, he might turn his gun on himself (both his parents
committed suicide).
</P>
<P>
   Or _ an outcome that many Serbs now expect _ he might stoke one
final apocalypse before going down in a Ceausescu-style hail of
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted assassination this week of Vuk Draskovic, Serbia's
main opposition leader, serves as a reminder that political
violence is never far away.
</P>
<P>
   The discreet offer of a safe haven seems attractive _ and more
defensible than the French luxury that was enjoyed by Duvalier. It
would offer Milosevic an incentive to give up power peacefully, a
considerable prize.
</P>
<P>
   Such an outcome would, however, create a raft of new problems.
It would create new bitterness in Serbia, where the current
animosity toward the West for its harsh treatment of Serbia could
give way to even greater bitterness if, when Milosevic goes, the
West turns soft on the chief author of Serbia's misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, too, such a deal would undermine the principle that
has been established in recent years _ that, following the
establishment of the International Criminal Court, dictators can
expect no mercy when they are brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   That knowledge must be a disincentive to future dictators. To
break the principle for Milosevic's sake would make a mockery of
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Milosevic to justice will be enormously difficult.
Permitting a peaceful retirement would be easy _ but wrong. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 425-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
