 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTN. EDITORS: NOTE TWO HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 400
WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,100.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By STEVE BOGGAN  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It evoked images of the cattle trucks in which so
many Jews died while being transported to concentration camps
during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty people, 56 men and four women, crammed into the back of a
truck, clawing at the walls, fighting for air. And when the doors
were finally opened at Dover's Eastern Docks in the darkness of
Monday morning, all but two were dead.
</P>
<P>
   As Jack Straw, Britain's home secretary, vowed to stamp out the
``evil'' trade in people-smuggling, the full horror of the victims'
journey from Zeebrugge on Sunday began to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Details emerged from hospital sources of a brief conversation
the survivors, both men, had had with an interpreter. Under police
guard at an undisclosed Kent hospital and still traumatized by
their ordeal, they described the moments of panic as their air
began to run out.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital source said: ``They were all clawing at the inside
of the back door. They said it was very dark inside the trailer so
they were tripping over dead bodies as they tried to make their way
to the doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they banged on the doors and shouted at the top of
their voices, but eventually they had to give up through weakness.
They had no idea how many of the people with them had died until
they got to the hospital this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the survivors and the Dutch driver of the vehicle know how
long they had been packed into the tiny space on one of the hottest
days of the year. It is likely the survivors would also have died
had it not been for the driver's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Although the driver was under arrest Monday night, it is
understood detectives are not automatically assuming he knew what,
besides tomatoes, he was carrying. ``It could have been loaded
before he arrived to pick it up,'' said one officer. ``We simply
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   As post-mortem examinations began, it was reported that the
driver had paid for his passage from Zeebrugge aboard the P&AMP;O
European Pathway in cash. Most companies have billing accounts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 125 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 350) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It is understood that at the P&AMP;O Stena Line office in Zeebrugge
the driver gave the owner's name as Van Der Spek Transporten at an
address in Terbregtseweg, Rotterdam but could not provide some of
the details of the truck. He said the company would provide them
later.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;O Stena Line said it had not dealt with a company by that name
before and had no company account. These combined factors are
thought to have been enough to arouse the suspicions of Customs at
Dover.
</P>
<P>
   The driver took the 7:30 p.m. sailing from Zeebrugge, arriving
in Dover around midnight. Customs and Excise officers say the truck
passed through immigration but was stopped by a team of four
officers because it fitted ``a certain profile.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   An average of 4,000 trucks pass through the port of Dover each
day and only 4 percent are stopped by Customs. Although they
refused to discuss the specific profiling criteria used to check
suspected vehicles it is thought the method of payment rang the
most alarm bells.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-meter (60-foot) Dutch-registered Mercedes truck, bearing
the name Van Der Spek on the side, was diverted into customs
inspection bay nine. The back doors were sealed and airtight but
inspectors opened them to conduct a search.
</P>
<P>
   What they found has left them in shock. Nigel Knott, a Customs
spokesman, said: ``It was a refrigerated lorry but the
refrigeration was not in operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were pallets of tomatoes inside. At first two of the
officers went inside, then they were joined by the other two.
Nothing could have prepared them for what they found.''
</P>
<P>
   They discovered piles of bodies hidden among the cargo. And then
began the grim task of checking for survivors. The customs officers
called for ambulances but vital signs were found in only two men.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital source said: ``One of the men said it was like an
angel had been sent from heaven when the back door of the lorry
trailer was finally opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time they were brought here they were both extremely
dehydrated and very weak. We managed to patch them up pretty
quickly by giving them lots of fluids but I think the psychological
torment will stay with them for the rest of their lives.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 275 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The customs officers who made the find were told to stay off
work Monday and have been offered counselling. An international
search is under way to try to identify the victims, their country
of origin and the people behind their deaths. The police would say
only that they were Oriental, although it is understood that a
Chinese interpreter has been used.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the number of people involved, police believe a big
organized operation may be behind the trafficking operation. In
some cases, criminal gangs are known to charge foreigners up to
$48,000 to get them into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pugash, a Kent police spokesman said: ``Movements of such
numbers of people don't happen by accident so we have to assume an
organized criminal element is involved. We have had incidents
before where lorries have been stopped carrying more than 10
illegal immigrants, but they survived, there has never been
anything on this scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the survivors, who were later moved to an
undisclosed police station, were under armed guard, he replied:
``We are taking all the precautions you would expect us to, their
physical injuries are not bad, but they have been through a very
traumatic time so we are taking medical advice on when we can talk
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Forensic science specialists were examining the truck and the
freight area and appeared to take away a number of the pallets
behind which the human cargo was hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Two pathologists were conducting the examinations but results on
all 58 victims are likely to take a few days to complete. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,100) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In Dover itself sadness over the deaths was in short supply.
Many people feel besieged by the influx of illegal immigrants and
asylum-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   One driver, who asked not to be named, said: ``Good riddance.
It's 58 less for us to support. We're sick of it round here. My
poll tax has gone up by (pounds sterling)3 ($5.00) a month to
support these people.''
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
