<SLUG> BC-ELECTROLUX-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE AWARDS $5.25M TO IN RACE, AGE BIAS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An Electrolux Corp. manager, demoted by a boss
who called him a ``dumb . . . Indian'' and told him he was too old,
has been awarded $5.25 million for race and age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge William Orrick said the vacuum cleaner
company shrugged off the complaint by William L. McAlvain, manager
of its Santa Rosa branch, as well as allegations of discrimination
from many other employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electrolux's near-complete failure to investigate
discrimination complaints in general is appalling,'' Orrick wrote
in a ruling filed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McAlvain, an American Indian, was 53 when he was hired as a
manager trainee in 1989. He was soon promoted to manager of a
series of branches selling Electrolux products and compiled a
respectable record, generally equaling or exceeding sales of other
managers at those branches, Orrick said.
</P>
<P>
   He also received numerous company awards, including a $10,000
award for sales by newly hired employees on his staff in 1994, his
last full year with Electrolux. His branch was 15th highest in such
sales out of about 500 in the nation, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   After he finished relocating a branch office from Redding to
Santa Rosa, however, McAlvain was told by his supervisor in January
1995 that the area vice president, Allen Lawson, wanted him
replaced by a younger man. McAlvain, then 58, called Lawson, who
swore at him, called him a ``dumb ... Indian,'' and told him,
``You're too goddamn old. You can't cut it anymore,'' according to
testimony quoted by Orrick.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson repeated his slurs in several subsequent phone calls,
Orrick said. McAlvain complained to Gary Griffin, the company's
vice president of sales, who told him he didn't care what Lawson
did as long as he was productive. Griffin actually had not even
talked to Lawson, and did not refer McAlvain's complaint to anyone
else in the company, in violation of Electrolux's stated
discrimination policy, Orrick said.
</P>
<P>
   A day or two later, McAlvain found his office locked when he
reported for work. He found another job about three weeks later but
was still suffering from depression and humiliation when the case
went to trial this April, Orrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson was later fired for verbally abusing employees. He and
other Electrolux supervisors said McAlvain was demoted for poor
performance, statements that Orrick described as transparently
false.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the rare case where there is direct evidence of
unlawful discrimination,'' said the judge, who presided over the
non-jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   He said McAlvain had not shown any financial loss, but was
entitled to $250,000 for emotional distress and $5 million in
punitive damages. That may be enough to get the company's
attention, said McAlvain's lawyer, Karl I. Mullen, who has filed
several discrimination suits on behalf of Electrolux employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem they've had for a long time,'' Mullen said.
``They've done nothing to try to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin L. Keith, lawyer for the Virginia-based company, was away
from his and unavailable for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
