<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   Part 5 of 5 Parts
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN _ Analysts say that Michigan usually leans slightly
toward the Democrats in presidential elections but nobody's sure
what to expect this year. Both Democrats and Republicans are
licking their wounds and trying to mend fences. The UAW _ with more
than 400,000 active and retired members _ would like to shove
Democrat Al Gore, who's supposed to be labor's candidate, right up
the tailpipe of the nearest Chevrolet, Plymouth or Ford. It's hard
to tell which issue has made the UAW more angry _ Gore's support
for granting China normal trade status or his rants against the
internal combustion engine. Republicans, meanwhile, are trying to
get back together after Sen. John McCain creamed Gov. George W.
Bush in the Republican primary. The healing was moving smoothly
until McCain backers claimed they got the shaft when it came to
picking delegates to the Republican National Convention. McCain got
so angry that he said he wouldn't return to the state. For the time
being _ and the dust still is settling _ Bush seems more solid with
his Republican base in western Michigan than Gore is with labor and
African-Americans in Detroit. ``Reagan Democrats'' in the Detroit
suburbs _ who voted for Ronald Reagan and then switched back to
Bill Clinton _ likely will have the last word and they're still
deciding. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News). 60.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGANBAR _ This booming, suburban Detroit county is home to
thousands of the ``Reagan Democrats'' who switched parties to put
Ronald Reagan in the White House. Many, but not all, returned to
their roots to help Democrat Bill Clinton win two terms as
president. This year the county also became a hotbed of ``McCain
Republicans,'' the potpouri of voters who gave George W. Bush a
surprise tumble in Michigan's Republican presidential primary. Both
parties are courting these all swing voters. Meanwhile, the county
is awash in scandals of its own. Among other things, the Democratic
sheriff, in office for 24 years, was convicted of rape. We talk
with auto workers, senior citizens, college students, educators and
others from the county. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
