<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Blue sky, cool temperatures, mercifully low
humidity for a June day in Dixie. Indeed, it was a fine time for a
walk in the garden. Nature's garden. And so we ambled, dozens of us
nature lovers, just after the dedication of the Lady Bird Johnson
Nature Trail, at Callaway Gardens in Pine Mountain. The walk was
the latest efforts to green America, efforts that should intensify
with heightened concern over ecological damage from
hyper-development, and overburdened, drought-ridden water
supplies.(May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WINDOW-BOX _ Some ideas never grow old. Take the window box. If
you want to give your house a little personality _ both from
indoors and out _ these container gardens make a statement that
says, ``Welcome.'' If you're a townhouse or high-rise dweller tight
on space, they offer a solution to your gardening frustrations. And
if the outdoor watering bans forces you to curtail yard work, they
can be an even more practical option. Three local experts give
``recipes'' for two types of boxes -- one for shade, the other for
sun. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WINDOW-SIDE _ Like all container gardens, window boxes can be
planted from scratch each spring and fall or, like a wardrobe,
updated with a few changes. One gardening expert provides a
step-by-step guide to building your own windowbox. Plenty of plant
suggestions.(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-PLANTS _ With the recently imposed water restrictions in
many parts of Georgia, it's a good time to discuss perennials that
tolerate dry shade. Regardless of the site (sun or shade) the key
ingredients to ensure that your plants thrive are the right soil
and choosing the right plant for your site. Story provides tips for
both. (Glasener, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for
use by NYTNS clients.)
</P>
