<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0625 &Cx1f; taf-z
* s 7 &LR;      06-21 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-NATIVE-$ADV25-NYT8 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7  
 A TRUE COUNTRY MUSIC FAN HAS SOUTHERN ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
(Editors: Also see COUNTRY-MUSIC-CONVERT) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several months, I've been dating a girl who lives in Baton
Rouge, La. Not only is she the first Southern girl I've dated, but
she does something I've never seen before. Whenever we're in her
car, she reaches for the radio, hits a button for one of the
country stations on preset and starts singing along. Now, I've
lived in a lot of cities _ Chicago, New York, Los Angeles,
Nashville, Seattle _ and met a lot of people. But this is the first
time I've spent time with anybody who sings along with
country-music radio. Even in Nashville, where the people who
manufacture the music live, rock 'n' roll, rap or alternative
country reigns in cars. Country radio listening, in general, is
strictly business.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like many of my friends, I love country music. We
listen to Willie Nelson, Merle &UR; 9 &LR;  Haggard, Hank Williams, George
Jones, Johnny Cash, Loretta &UR; 10 &LR;  Lynn and all the great lesser-known
Texans like Townes &UR; 11 &LR;  Van Zandt &UR; 12 &LR;  and Jimmie &UR; 13 &LR;  Dale
Gilmore &UR; 14 &LR; . But we're city folk and musical intelligentsia. This
is music we like, not music we live or grow up to. It's definitely
not the country my Baton Rouge girl listens to. Sure, she likes
most of the above _ she was even named after a Waylon &UR; 15 &LR;  Jennings
song. But that's her parents' music. Country to her is Jo &UR; 16 &LR; 
Dee &UR; 17 &LR;  Messina &UR; 18 &LR; , Tracy Lawrence, Faith Hill (but not pop songs
like ``This Kiss''), Diamond Rio, Steve Wariner &UR; 19 &LR; , and that one
song by Shedaisy &UR; 20 &LR;  about a girl breaking up with her boyfriend
and taking the cat but leaving the litter. When she's in the mood
for more classic country, she listens to the Judds, George Strait,
Pam Tillis &UR; 21 &LR; , early Reba &UR; 22 &LR;  McIntyre &UR; 23C &LR;  and that Nitty &UR; 24 &LR; 
Gritty Dirt Band song about fishing in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging out with her, I've come to realize that, although at the
very least 60 million records are sold each year by such
contemporary country acts, not one person I know in any position of
cultural authority whatsoever can truly say they like the genre. So
what's the problem? The genre or us?
</P>
<P>
   Let's start by taking a look at us. To simplify things, we like
music that we can relate to. This may be music that triggers a
connection with our past _ reminding us of, say, the Beatles songs
that we grew up with. It may simply be music that we've been
socialized to like by friends and colleagues. Or it may be music
that offers an escapist fantasy _ from the thug posturing of
gangsta &UR; 25 &LR;  rap to the hard drinking, hard living and heartbreaking
of classic country. But there is no cultural reinforcement in
Northern cities for listening to contemporary country pop. Our
friends don't listen to it, we didn't grow up on it and there isn't
a radio station in Manhattan that plays it. Overall, it seems like
canned, manufactured cliche &UR; 26 &LR; . We may be able to enjoy
Britney &UR; 27 &LR;  Spears singing ``I'm not that innocent'' as a guilty
pop pleasure, but when it comes to Shedaisy &UR; 20 &LR;  and its cat litter
we shut our ears.
</P>
<P>
   My epiphany came when my girlfriend bought me a Steve
Wariner &UR; 19 &LR;  CD. ``Listen to `Small-Town Girl,''' she insisted. It
was probably one of the cheesiest songs anyone's ever asked me to
listen to. The singing was over-sentimental and the music, full of
synthesizer stabs, was trite. But then there were the lyrics, about
a man who married a country girl and brought her back to a
skyscraper apartment in the city, where she has hot coffee waiting
and country radio playing every night after he comes home from a
hard day at work. ``There ain't &UR; 28 &LR;  nothing like the love of a
small-town girl,'' ran the chorus. They were the most hackneyed
lyrics in the world, but I loved them. Because I understood that
the song was her, singing to me.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I was able to connect the song with my life and the
things I cared about, and it opened up a door to the music. Though
country has a large audience in the north, it's important because
it remains a regional music, affirming the identity of those who
live in a country within a country: the South, home to a race of
very proud people often made to feel like second-class citizens
culturally. It is a very different place from the North. In the
South, they walk around every day with the identity of Southerner.
In the North, we're simply Americans; we don't realize we're
Northerners until we're in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as evidence of a changing South, most pop country is
about middle-class small-town life, or town-and-country, as Pat
Quigley &UR; 29 &LR; , the president of Capitol Records, likes to call it.
When the music comes across as more backwater and rural, it is
usually with the intention of further distinguishing itself from
the entertainment of the city. For example, Tim McGraw &UR; C &LR;  sings:
``You can have a lot of fun in a New York minute/ But there are
some things you can't do within those city limits/ There ain't &UR; 28 &LR; 
no closing time, ain't &UR; 28 &LR;  no cover charge/ Just country boys and
girls getting down on the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of criticisms we often apply to contemporary country is
as much a cliche &UR; 26 &LR;  as the music is accused of being. Detractors
say it's slick, soulless and manufactured. There is no twang, no
weepy steel guitar, no connection to legends like Hank Williams.
Whose standards are we judging it by? We don't expect rockers to
keep playing ``Rock Around the Clock'' and ``Blue Suede Shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   I certainly don't want to defend the music, but I do want to
make the point that many people don't understand it. We want our
hicks to remain hicks. But the hick musical savant is largely a
myth: many of the aw-shucks &UR; 30 &LR;  performers on the Grand Ole &UR; 31 &LR; 
Opry &UR; 32 &LR;  show 60 or 70 years ago were well-educated entertainers
playing a vaudevillian part. Today, country has evolved into an
industry that in many ways is much more sophisticated than rock,
rap, even most pop. It exists in a small, centralized and very
complex world. When record labels restructure and consolidate,
there is massive bloodshed at the rock and pop labels while the
country divisions are generally left alone. The simple reason is
that most New York and Los Angeles executives don't understand that
world. It doesn't work the same way. It's not based on talent
scouts signing artists to labels. There are other components that,
while they exist in the pop world, are the lifeblood of country:
songwriters, publishers and studio musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Great country hits are generally not written by a singer; they
are shopped for and bought in the closest parallel modern music has
to Tin Pan Alley. Listen to country radio and pay close attention
to the lyrics. They are meticulously written and thought out.
Vagueness will not do here: only clearly stated sentiments
calculated to appeal to the broadest swath of the American public.
(The most blatant example: the Chely &UR; 33 &LR;  Wright chorus ``I'm a
single white female looking for a man like you.'')
</P>
<P>
   I suppose in the Big City we think we're too smart to fall for
this. We have a snobbish attitude toward pop country, which in many
ways is the same attitude we have toward the South. When I moved to
Nashville for a short time, most of my New York friends turned up
their noses on hearing the news and laughed: ``What are you going
to do there?'' The answer: ``Well, think of it as spending a year
abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling around Tennessee, I entered a world with its own
regional cuisine and its own music. I came back with the
realization that we can never really appreciate country in the same
way country folks do. At best, we can appreciate it the way we
listen to the Buena &UR; 34 &LR;  Vista Social Club: admire it from a
distance, enjoying its intrinsic value but oblivious to its context
and relationship with quotidian life.
</P>
<P>
   If you disagree, go buy an album by the best-selling group
Montgomery Gentry. It's called ``Tattoos and Scars,'' and has been
on the country charts for over 60 weeks. On the cover you'll see
two hairy, beefy, mullet-topped good ole &UR; 31 &LR;  Kentucky boys who like
to wear leather overcoats with black cowboy hats. Inside, you'll
hear some strange attempt to package slick Nashville pop with
bad-boy Southern rock.You'll listen to it once, then set it aside,
shaking your head and saying, ``This is not for me.'' That's not
musical elitism: I don't like it either. It wasn't made for you or
me. It was made for people who don't like us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-CONVERT     06-21 1989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-CONVERT-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOUTHERN THROB IN A NORTHERN HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 (Editors: Also see COUNTRY-MUSIC-NATIVE)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   I'm not entirely sure how I became
a hick. I don't flatter myself by claiming to be anything close to
the genuine item. I grew up on Long Island (OK, Great Neck),
listening to the Beatles and Stones like everyone else. I'm not
unfamiliar with classical music; I know my way around Miles Davis
and John Coltrane, Sonny Rollins and Thelonious Monk.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But as my increasingly embarrassed children can attest, when it
comes to music these days, I'm alarmingly close to all country all
the time. So as I do the usual suburban dad things, with Steve
Earle or the Dixie Chicks, George Jones or Emmylou Harris, pedal
steel and dobro and creaky Appalachian harmonies being drowned out
by the THUMP-THUMP-THUMP of the hip-hop or dance music coming from
the Jeep Cherokee stopped at the same light, it's hard not to
wonder what's wrong with this picture. I may be a faux hick, but
I'm a committed one, and even I can't entirely explain how things
worked out this way.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the first person I ever met who listened to country
music. It was my boss at my first newspaper job in Ypsilanti, Mich.
Ypsi, like Bakersfield, Calif., was a mangy Southern kingdom in
exile, full of expatriates working at the Ford and GM plants and
dimly lit, famously rowdy bars full of beefy, gimlet-eyed guys
named Sonny, Lester and Earl. Finding out my boss listened to
country music was like finding out about some really embarrassing
aspect of his sex life. I tried to put it out of my mind, but I
couldn't. I'd see him walking around the newsroom and look at him
as if he were some geek with three heads.
</P>
<P>
   If I'd thought about the music, instead of the cultural cliches,
it wouldn't have seemed so odd. After all, before the Beatles
changed the world, the first music I really got excited about was
the sound-alike folk music of the 1960s, the Kingston Trio, the
Limeliters, the Brothers Four, the Mitchell Trio. They were all
preternaturally clean-cut, homogenized creatures of the interregnum
between the '50s and the '60s who took the rough edges, twang and
grit _ everything that made it matter _ out of acoustic Southern
music and sold it for mass consumption. When the Beatles sang ``Act
Naturally'' or the Stones sang ``Wild Horses,'' it sounded fine to
me, even if I would have gagged at the thought of listening to Buck
Owens. The group from that time that most resonated with me, and
still does, was the Byrds, built around the ex-folkies Roger
McGuinn, David Crosby and Gene Clark and the ex-bluegrass mandolin
player Chris Hillman.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the group's mix of rock and folk veered off
naturally into hard-core country and bluegrass like Porter
Wagoner's ``Satisfied Mind,'' which popped up incongruously on the
group's ``Turn, Turn, Turn'' album. The Byrds looked and seemed too
cool to be carrying the hick gene, so, if anything, their forays
into country seemed like a knowing, hip affectation, a cool '60s
goof on the inhabitants of the lower orders. Still, there was
something there that spoke to richer worlds than the teen-age
posturing of rock 'n' roll in the rootsy jangle of McGuinn's
12-string, the ragged edges of the harmonies, the exhilarating
bluegrass flourishes of Hillman's ``Time Between'' and ``Girl With
No Name'' or the hilarious pop-country hybrid of `` Spaceman.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, somewhere along the line, I sort of got it. Like a lot of
'60s types, the first real country music I listened to was the
Byrds' ``Sweetheart of the Rodeo,'' a brilliant exercise in
commercial suicide in which Gram Parsons took the twang from the
fringes to the heart of the group's music. It included hard country
classics like the Louvin Brothers' ``Christian Life,'' the
country/soul of William Bell's ``You Don't Your Water'' and
memorable originals like Parsons' ``Hickory Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, it sounds every bit as soulful and
compelling as it did then. Parsons later went on to do inspired and
original cosmic cowboy turns with the Flying Burrito Brothers and
on his own, burn himself out and become the first alt.country
martyr when he died in 1973 at the age of 26.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Byrds and Parsons did was to meld the restless
energies and alienation of the '60s generation with the unaffected,
quintessentially American longing and alienation of country. It was
grown-up in a way rock could never be, rebellious in a way
Nashville never wanted to be and true to something both ancient and
contemporary in the American experience. Though I didn't think of
it that way at the time, it was both musically and spiritually a
bridge from the self-indulgent elitism of the 60s to the real world
and a reminder of how fine the line was between the approved lefty
music and politics of Woody Guthrie and the scorned righty music
and politics of Merle Haggard.
</P>
<P>
   I moved to Texas in the mid-70s, picking up a stiff dose of the
woozy progressive country of Jerry Jeff Walker and Ray Wylie
Hubbard, the rockabilly of Joe Ely and the prairie heartache of
Willie Nelson, and then to Atlanta, where learning a little about
Nashville seemed a part of my job, covering the South for The New
York Times. It was the time of country's biggest commercial
breakthrough, with Garth Brooks selling more records than anyone in
America. For a while Nashville seemed to capture, for better or
worse, the moment _ the Reagan-Bush-era triumph of heartland
culture over coastal culture _ much as Motown captured its moment
in the 1960s. Working on a book about how much the country had been
influenced by the South, I hung out in Nashville for a week or so
and then drove across Mississippi, from the casinos of the Delta to
the casinos of the Gulf Coast, living mostly on bottled water and
Sun chips.
</P>
<P>
   My background music was the country smorgasbord I'd picked up in
Nashville _ the pop-country of Faith Hill before she went all pop
and became Shania Twain's rival for Country Super Babe; the
honky-tonk of David Ball; a rockabilly album no one else seems to
have heard by James House; the plaintive, literate Appalachian folk
of Iris DeMent; a terrific Merle Haggard tribute album, and my
favorite at the time, the cranky, Okie country rock of the
Tractors. A lot of it was wretched, like Tim McGraw, Clay Walker,
John Michael Montgomery and the prefabricated Nashville hunks in
hats on the radio, the 90s version of the sound-alike folk acts of
the 60s. But it almost didn't matter. I drove along Highway 61 in
the 100-degree heat, throwing the empty water bottles in the back
seat of my rental car, wondering if I'd ever have so much fun
again. After that, for the first time in my life, I reflexively
searched for the country station on the radio and headed straight
for the country section of the record store. I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   For a while I thought of my listening habits as a transitory
eccentricity I'd soon outgrow. I thought it would end when I
finished my book, and then when I moved back to New York a few
years later. But for now, it feels like a part of the post-genetic
code you pick up as you live your life. Every now and then the
frequency fades out, like a too-distant radio signal, the twang
just grates, and I listen mostly to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But then, invariably, the signal locks back in, and I'm back to
the off-the-reservation alternative country, whatever that is, of
Steve Earle, Buddy Miller or Robbie Fulks or grand masters like
George Jones. It's pretty eclectic fare, not the mass-produced
Nashville of the radio, but one part Byrds and the Band, one part
Hank Williams and Merle Haggard _ pretty much the tastes of someone
who came to country through Gram Parsons, not Loretta Lynn. It's a
suspect pedigree, but it's all I've got.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to see my immersion in twang as a waste of limited
mental disc capacity. Here I find myself periodically forgetting
familiar phone numbers and the names of people I work with, and my
head is full of useless knowledge about which obscure CDs Gurf
Morlux played guitar on. But maybe I shouldn't be surprised.
There's not much out there for grownups to listen to. Hip-hop?
Hyper-emoting tabloid divas? Horrible thrashing post-Nirvana
teen-age rock? Yuck. I guess we all get to choose our turf in the
new Balkanized music market, and the alt.country diaspora is mine.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably generic and personal reasons for my
predilection toward twang. Country has traditionally been music for
middle-aged adults with grown-up bruises and scars. When Pete
Townshend sang, ``Hope I die before I get old,'' he was mouthing
the primal trope of music meant to be of, by and for kids. It no
longer strikes me _ and I assume him _ as such a swell idea. When
George Jones sings, ``I've had choices/ Since the day that I was
born/ There were voices that told me right from wrong/ If I had
listened, I wouldn't be here today/ living and dying with the
choices I made,'' it rings true. I guess I could listen to Stephen
Sondheim, who writes pretty smart songs about adults, too, but for
now I'll stick with George Jones.
</P>
<P>
   One of the triumphs of the contemporary
roots/alternative-country music is to mix the frazzled, dog-eared
wisdom of country with an edgy, Keroucian energy that has made this
stuff vaguely _ sigh _ hip. After all, Steve Earle, the godfather
of neo-twang, was featured along with the literateurs at the New
Yorker's celebration of its 75th anniversary last month. Even the
name of his new album, ``Transcendental Blues,'' bespeaks a
sensibility a tad less rustic than, say, Ernest Tubb or Lefty
Frizzell.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, back here in the land of the enlightened, I guess I
miss my time in the South. I think sometimes of an article the
Texas writer Larry L. King wrote in a 1975 special issue of The
Atlantic Monthly devoted entirely to the state. He reminisced about
the mythic Texas of his youth, and he paid homage to an unspoiled
stretch of desolate West Texas highway. Driving there, he wrote, he
found himself in a mental time warp, back in Old Texas ``under a
high sky where all things are again possible and the wind blows
free.'' He wrote of putting the heavy spurs to his trusty Hertz or
Avis steed, and flying lickety-split down the road, ``scattering
roadside gravel like bursts of buckshot.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds a lot like my highway satori in Mississippi. I spent
much of my life wandering out to places like Wink, Alpine and
Marfa, Texas, but now I'm one of the drones on the train platform,
catching the 7:48 each morning from Chappaqua. Ferrying the kids
around over the weekend or before school, I no longer even control
the music in the car. My daughter, who for a time I brainwashed
into thinking that rock 'n' roll was Mary Chapin Carpenter singing
``I Feel Lucky,'' is still ecumenical enough to appreciate the
Dixie Chicks but now insists on the radio station Z-100, which
means I hear Britney Spears and 'N Sync more than I hear Steve
Earle. My son wants to listen to Imus in the morning, and if we're
taking one of his friends along somewhere he issues a stern warning
about not embarrassing him by playing any of ``that stuff'' in
public. My wife's from the South, but she's anti-twang, too. Even
if suburban dads escaped to the neighborhood bar at night, I doubt
there's one anywhere nearby with Patsy Cline or Ray Price, Vince
Gill or George Strait on the jukebox, so that's no option either.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a little lonely up here, but I do my best. Scattering
roadside gravel like buckshot isn't quite my thing. But when I'm
alone in my trusty old Volvo, tooling around the dusty byways of
Westchester County from the A&AMP;P to the BJ's, from the Home Depot to
the Old Navy, I crank up my twang, imagine myself under a high sky
where all things are possible and go flying lickety-split down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
