<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0629 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-NATIVE-     06-21 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-NATIVE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRUE COUNTRY MUSIC FAN HAS SOUTHERN ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
(Editors: Also see COUNTRY-MUSIC-CONVERT) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several months, I've been dating a girl who lives in Baton
Rouge, La. Not only is she the first Southern girl I've dated, but
she does something I've never seen before. Whenever we're in her
car, she reaches for the radio, hits a button for one of the
country stations on preset and starts singing along. Now, I've
lived in a lot of cities _ Chicago, New York, Los Angeles,
Nashville, Seattle _ and met a lot of people. But this is the first
time I've spent time with anybody who sings along with
country-music radio. Even in Nashville, where the people who
manufacture the music live, rock 'n' roll, rap or alternative
country reigns in cars. Country radio listening, in general, is
strictly business.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like many of my friends, I love country music. We
listen to Willie Nelson, Merle Haggard, Hank Williams, George
Jones, Johnny Cash, Loretta Lynn and all the great lesser-known
Texans like Townes Van Zandt and Jimmie Dale Gilmore. But we're
city folk and musical intelligentsia. This is music we like, not
music we live or grow up to. It's definitely not the country my
Baton Rouge girl listens to. Sure, she likes most of the above _
she was even named after a Waylon Jennings song. But that's her
parents' music. Country to her is Jo Dee Messina, Tracy Lawrence,
Faith Hill (but not pop songs like ``This Kiss''), Diamond Rio,
Steve Wariner, and that one song by Shedaisy about a girl breaking
up with her boyfriend and taking the cat but leaving the litter.
When she's in the mood for more classic country, she listens to the
Judds, George Strait, Pam Tillis, early Reba McIntyre and that
Nitty Gritty Dirt Band song about fishing in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging out with her, I've come to realize that, although at the
very least 60 million records are sold each year by such
contemporary country acts, not one person I know in any position of
cultural authority whatsoever can truly say they like the genre. So
what's the problem? The genre or us?
</P>
<P>
   Let's start by taking a look at us. To simplify things, we like
music that we can relate to. This may be music that triggers a
connection with our past _ reminding us of, say, the Beatles songs
that we grew up with. It may simply be music that we've been
socialized to like by friends and colleagues. Or it may be music
that offers an escapist fantasy _ from the thug posturing of
gangsta rap to the hard drinking, hard living and heartbreaking of
classic country. But there is no cultural reinforcement in Northern
cities for listening to contemporary country pop. Our friends don't
listen to it, we didn't grow up on it and there isn't a radio
station in Manhattan that plays it. Overall, it seems like canned,
manufactured cliche. We may be able to enjoy Britney Spears singing
``I'm not that innocent'' as a guilty pop pleasure, but when it
comes to Shedaisy and its cat litter we shut our ears.
</P>
<P>
   My epiphany came when my girlfriend bought me a Steve Wariner
CD. ``Listen to `Small-Town Girl,''' she insisted. It was probably
one of the cheesiest songs anyone's ever asked me to listen to. The
singing was over-sentimental and the music, full of synthesizer
stabs, was trite. But then there were the lyrics, about a man who
married a country girl and brought her back to a skyscraper
apartment in the city, where she has hot coffee waiting and country
radio playing every night after he comes home from a hard day at
work. ``There ain't nothing like the love of a small-town girl,''
ran the chorus. They were the most hackneyed lyrics in the world,
but I loved them. Because I understood that the song was her,
singing to me.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I was able to connect the song with my life and the
things I cared about, and it opened up a door to the music. Though
country has a large audience in the north, it's important because
it remains a regional music, affirming the identity of those who
live in a country within a country: the South, home to a race of
very proud people often made to feel like second-class citizens
culturally. It is a very different place from the North. In the
South, they walk around every day with the identity of Southerner.
In the North, we're simply Americans; we don't realize we're
Northerners until we're in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as evidence of a changing South, most pop country is
about middle-class small-town life, or town-and-country, as Pat
Quigley, the president of Capitol Records, likes to call it. When
the music comes across as more backwater and rural, it is usually
with the intention of further distinguishing itself from the
entertainment of the city. For example, Tim McGraw sings: ``You can
have a lot of fun in a New York minute/ But there are some things
you can't do within those city limits/ There ain't no closing time,
ain't no cover charge/ Just country boys and girls getting down on
the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of criticisms we often apply to contemporary country is
as much a cliche as the music is accused of being. Detractors say
it's slick, soulless and manufactured. There is no twang, no weepy
steel guitar, no connection to legends like Hank Williams. Whose
standards are we judging it by? We don't expect rockers to keep
playing ``Rock Around the Clock'' and ``Blue Suede Shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   I certainly don't want to defend the music, but I do want to
make the point that many people don't understand it. We want our
hicks to remain hicks. But the hick musical savant is largely a
myth: many of the aw-shucks performers on the Grand Ole Opry show
60 or 70 years ago were well-educated entertainers playing a
vaudevillian part. Today, country has evolved into an industry that
in many ways is much more sophisticated than rock, rap, even most
pop. It exists in a small, centralized and very complex world. When
record labels restructure and consolidate, there is massive
bloodshed at the rock and pop labels while the country divisions
are generally left alone. The simple reason is that most New York
and Los Angeles executives don't understand that world. It doesn't
work the same way. It's not based on talent scouts signing artists
to labels. There are other components that, while they exist in the
pop world, are the lifeblood of country: songwriters, publishers
and studio musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Great country hits are generally not written by a singer; they
are shopped for and bought in the closest parallel modern music has
to Tin Pan Alley. Listen to country radio and pay close attention
to the lyrics. They are meticulously written and thought out.
Vagueness will not do here: only clearly stated sentiments
calculated to appeal to the broadest swath of the American public.
(The most blatant example: the Chely Wright chorus ``I'm a single
white female looking for a man like you.'')
</P>
<P>
   I suppose in the Big City we think we're too smart to fall for
this. We have a snobbish attitude toward pop country, which in many
ways is the same attitude we have toward the South. When I moved to
Nashville for a short time, most of my New York friends turned up
their noses on hearing the news and laughed: ``What are you going
to do there?'' The answer: ``Well, think of it as spending a year
abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling around Tennessee, I entered a world with its own
regional cuisine and its own music. I came back with the
realization that we can never really appreciate country in the same
way country folks do. At best, we can appreciate it the way we
listen to the Buena Vista Social Club: admire it from a distance,
enjoying its intrinsic value but oblivious to its context and
relationship with quotidian life.
</P>
<P>
   If you disagree, go buy an album by the best-selling group
Montgomery Gentry. It's called ``Tattoos and Scars,'' and has been
on the country charts for over 60 weeks. On the cover you'll see
two hairy, beefy, mullet-topped good ole Kentucky boys who like to
wear leather overcoats with black cowboy hats. Inside, you'll hear
some strange attempt to package slick Nashville pop with bad-boy
Southern rock.You'll listen to it once, then set it aside, shaking
your head and saying, ``This is not for me.'' That's not musical
elitism: I don't like it either. It wasn't made for you or me. It
was made for people who don't like us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
