<SLUG> BC-WINDOW-BOX22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Six recipes for winning window boxes
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some ideas never grow old.
</P>
<P>
   Take the window box.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to give your house a little personality _ both from
indoors and out _ these container gardens make a statement that
says, ``Welcome.'' If you're a townhouse or high-rise dweller tight
on space, they offer a solution to your gardening frustrations. And
if outdoor watering bans have forced you to curtail yard work, they
can be an even more practical option.
</P>
<P>
   Save money by designing your window box with a mix of evergreens
and annuals. By including a foundation of ivy, a small boxwood or
other shrubs, you'll need only to swap out the annuals from season
to season for a new punch of color.
</P>
<P>
   That's important, because window box materials can be expensive.
You can go as simple as a homemade wooden box, for less than $10,
or as high end as metal hayracks, which sell for $50 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting a box, decide where it will go _ in sun or
shade. That will help narrow your plant selections.
</P>
<P>
   Planning is important, but don't forget to be spontaneous. Have
a little fun with your box.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate, Home &AMP; Garden asked three Atlanta-area gardening
experts _ David Ellis, Marcia Weber and Harriet Kirkpatrick _ to
cook up two window boxes each, one for sun and one for shade. Their
``kitchen'' was Habersham Gardens, an Atlanta garden center, where
they had access to a candy shop of ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Check out their recipes on these pages. Give them a try _
keeping in mind, of course, that some of the best cooks never use a
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE 1: SUN _ BY DAVID ELLIS
</P>
<P>
   Red Sentinel hibiscus
</P>
<P>
   Pink bachelor's button
</P>
<P>
   Cuphea
</P>
<P>
   Homestead verbena
</P>
<P>
   Snow Nymph salvia
</P>
<P>
   Gomphrena
</P>
<P>
   Black Heart sweet potato vine
</P>
<P>
   Variegated ivy
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE 2: SUN _ BY HARRIET KIRKPATRICK
</P>
<P>
   Ivy
</P>
<P>
   Boston fern
</P>
<P>
   Chartreuse coleus
</P>
<P>
   Dusty miller
</P>
<P>
   Mondo grass
</P>
<P>
   Pink New Guinea impatiens
</P>
<P>
   Scaevola
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE 3: SUN _ BY MARCIA WEBER
</P>
<P>
   (this box shown on cover)
</P>
<P>
   Lady in Red salvia
</P>
<P>
   Veronica trehanii
</P>
<P>
   Arctic Summer verbascum
</P>
<P>
   Black Heart sweet potato vine
</P>
<P>
   A ceramic obelisk
</P>
