<HEADER>
A0634 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ARCHITECTURE-GLOBAL-$     06-21 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-GLOBAL-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL FANTASIES: WHEN THE EMPIRE HAS NO CLOTHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nous champions le bikini mais pas la nudite!'' So I recall
hearing a Club Med staff member bark at me in the summer of 1966 as
I lay sunning on a white sand beach on the Tunisian island of
Djerba. An Ella Fitzgerald tape was playing in the background. I
was the only American staying at a camp full of young French.
Naturally, my fellow holiday makers wanted to berate me about
Vietnam. I just wanted somebody to rub oil on my back.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered seeing French Indo-China on old maps. But I knew
nothing about that region's history, and very little about European
colonialism, for that matter, apart from its role in my country's
formation. Not until much later could I connect the dots between a
war against the Commies in a faraway jungle and Club Med's
delightful fantasy of primitive life on a South Pacific island.
Now, after reading Patricia A. Morton's new book, ``Hybrid
Modernities'' (MIT Press), I can see that Club Med's fake grass
huts were part of the greater global village, not an escape from
it.
</P>
<P>
   Morton, an architecture historian at the University of
California, Riverside, takes as her subject the International
Colonial Exposition held in Paris in 1931. The event was sponsored
by the French government and staged in the capital's poor, eastern
quarter. It was conceived as a celebration of the colonial system
and therefore a justification for it. Though primarily devoted to
French colonies, the exposition also included sections on
territories ruled by the Netherlands, Belgium, the United States,
Portugal, Germany, Denmark and Italy. Pavilions for individual
colonies were executed in indigenous architectural styles. Native
colonials were imported to perform music and dance, to demonstrate
craft techniques and to provide living simulations of local color.
These displays were juxtaposed with official French pavilions
designed in the classically derived Art Deco style.
</P>
<P>
   The fair's organizers touted the authenticity of the
reconstructed native architecture. A previous expo, held in 1890 at
the foot of the new Eiffel Tower, had also included pavilions on
the French colonies, but these had been designed as imaginary
pastiches of exotic styles. In 1931, the organizers invoked the
authority of accuracy _ of science, that is to say, thus intimating
that what visitors saw was objectively true. Extending this hint to
the expo's overall design, a visitor might conclude that the
cultural superiority of France to its colonies was self-evident.
The layout conveyed in spatial terms that European civilization
occupied an advanced position to which other peoples could, as yet,
only aspire.
</P>
<P>
   Morton defies the caricature of the post-modern cultural critic.
At no point does she deny the objectivity of science or the
positive uses to which it has been put. Her target is the
transformation of science into unscientific myth. Like
``Orientalism,'' Edward Said's blast against Western ways of
looking at Eastern ways of life, Morton's book unmasks the
attitudes behind common Occidental rituals. Reversing the
anthropological lens, she scrutinizes the Western habit of
scrutinizing others. At the Colonial Exposition, this habit was
given a habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Morton studies in detail how the fair's ostensibly authentic
pavilions actually deformed the originals on which they were based.
The Cambodian pavilion, for example, was a Westernized version of
the Angkor Wat, reconfigured in an axial Beaux Arts composition.
Inside, there were galleries arranged in the traditional enfillade
of the classical Western museum. These were filled with display
cabinets for ethnological artifacts. (The actual Angkor Wat has no
inside.) Outside, instead of indigenous jungle foliage, the temple
sat in a terrace paved with modern glass blocks: a skylight for the
galleries underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, despite the accuracy of its reproduced sculptures, the
temple was a deformed membrane separating the inner and outer
halves of a thoroughly Parisian space. An Enlightenment virtue
(exactitude) was used to lend credibility to a shameful cause
(colonial exploitation). This is what Morton means by hybrid
modernities. The intention of the expo was to emphasize the
separation _ the difference _ between France and its colonies. The
result was the reverse: a display of '30s decorative motifs. It
placed three-dimensional panels of exotic styles in an art moderne
frame. The claims of accuracy, authenticity and objectivity
diverted attention from the warped perspective of the whole.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight is 20/20. But the 1931 Expo was criticized in its own
time for the same reasons Morton identifies. French Communists
thought it glorified the exploitation of workers overseas. The
Surrealists saw it as a perfect example of the way modern
civilization flattens the sacred dimension of everyday life. Morton
devotes nearly a chapter to a counter-exposition organized by the
Surrealists to coincide with the state event.
</P>
<P>
   This production was staged in the empty Constructivist building
designed by Melnikov for the Soviet Union for the 1925 Paris
Exposition des Arts Decoratifs (the fair from which the term Art
Deco was derived). To contradict the idea that the West represents
rationality, the Surrealists drew on the twin poles of their
thought: the Freudian subconscious and the Marxian belief in social
emancipation.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural exhibitions were directed by Louis Aragon. They
included African, Oceanic and American tribal artifacts that had
been collected by Tristan Tzara, Andre Breton and Aragon himself.
Wall placards bore inscriptions from Karl Marx. Roman Catholic
figurines and ladies' hats from Parisian designers were displayed
as symbolic equivalents to tribal fetishes.
</P>
<P>
   This chapter raises Morton's book above the level of a diatribe
against colonial abominations. Instead, it becomes a tribute to
Surrealist tradition. As is more widely understood today than at
any time since the 1940s, the Surrealists regarded their paintings
and writings not as aesthetic objects but as catalysts for cultural
change. Thus the ``counter-expo,'' while containing no Surrealist
paintings, was an ideal Surrealist work: temporary, collective,
dialectical, fusing political and psychological realms.
</P>
<P>
   As Morton points out, the organizers of the official expo might
have included European work that was influenced by exposure to
tribal artifacts. After all, it was in 1914 that Picasso first
depicted African masks in his work. By 1931, Josephine Baker had
been the toast of Paris for six years, fashion and interior design
depicted primitivist themes and a romantic mythology of colonial
life was already well established. Dashing aviators, the French
Foreign Legion, Jean Gabin, travel posters, slippers in the sand:
these images were already integral to the French imagination.
</P>
<P>
   They were not, however, to be seen at the Colonial Exposition,
because the purpose of the event was to affirm the segregation of
France from its colonies, not to reveal that the two had already
begun to interbreed. Despite the intention, the expo produced the
opposite effect. From an anthropological and even an aesthetic
point of view, the expo demonstrated cross-fertilization. Behold
the Angkor Wat with glass block tiles. Thirty-five years later, in
post-colonial times, the expo has morphed into Club Med, with
sarong-draped youths, drinking Cokes purchased with plastic beads,
railing against American imperialism on a North African beach.
</P>
<P>
   Morton sees the expo as a microcosm of Greater France. She
writes, ``The Exposition occupied a `middle region' of experience
where the norms, rules, and systems of French colonialism both
emerged and broke down, unsustainable because of their internal
contradictions.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the expo could be faulted not simply because
colonialism was immoral, but because it was absurd. This was the
lesson of the Surrealist show as well. If it was absurd to exhibit
Paris fashions in an anthropological setting, it was no less
ridiculous to promenade religious artifacts in an ethnographic
setting. The Surrealist objective was to show that the official
expo was itself Surrealistic. Their outlook, a natural response to
the internal contradictions of modernity, remains a useful approach
for exposing the inner conflicts of our day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   New York, 2000. Low crime, high times. Last March, police
officers issued 220 summonses to owners of small shops in lower
Manhattan. The Chinese merchants were charged, among other things,
with violating a set of design restrictions issued in 1975 by the
New York City Department of City Planning. This program, called
Little Italy Risorgimento, focused on the design of storefronts
along Mulberry and other streets in Little Italy. It was a
precursor of what would later be called contextual zoning,
legislation intended to preserve the existing character of New York
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delights of the San Gennaro Festival should be the rule,''
stated a document outlining the design regulations for the new
Little Italy special district.
</P>
<P>
   I shuddered when I read that sentence 25 years ago. At the time,
New York was just awakening to the full horror of the festival
marketplace going up at South Street Seaport. But at least that
maritime theme park was quarantined. Now the pestilence had broken
out on a real city street. Since then, there has arisen an entire
industry for branding streets with mix-and-match colors, lighting,
signage, street furniture and other techniques adapted from
suburban malls.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Little Italy was not just a matter of taste. As
in Paris, it was a question of internal contradiction. Though the
new zoning was promoted in the name of diversity, it actually
reflected a desire for sameness. A seasonal festival should become
The Rule. Only approved colors could stand for The Character of
Little Italy. Illuminated arches overhead should unify the street.
The contradiction became more evident with the police crackdown on
the Chinese merchants. Not only had they failed to represent the
approved ethnicity. They also dared to show that diversity exists
even among themselves. Since context is a matter of time as well as
place, the police were destroying the very tissue the design
guidelines were supposed to protect.
</P>
<P>
   We could see this as Italo Calvino might: Marco Polo imagining
the legendary cities of Cathay while remaining behind in Venice.
After all, it's not very useful to appraise contextual zoning on
purely aesthetic grounds. Once you accept that city streets should
be branded, it doesn't make much difference which colors are
chosen. Blue, green or orange, the twinkling lights, storefronts or
banners will look the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Surrealist critique remains as available as the formalist
one. It is perhaps the most useful method we have for revealing the
values at work in environments constructed in the name of
civilization: a Tahitian village in Tunisia, a Cambodian temple in
Paris, or a freeze-dried street festival at our feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
