<HEADER>
A0637 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-SENIOR-TOUR-HNS &LR;      06-21 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR-TOUR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AFTER 20 YEARS, SENIOR TOUR IS VIBRANT AND LUCRATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAUL DOMINGUEZ Jr.  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senior PGA Tour truly has been a boon to the baby boom
generation.
</P>
<P>
   What began in 1980 as two exhibitions that enabled players to
parade in carts has evolved into a tour that is competitive,
lucrative and unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior PGA Tour is offering its players $54.1 million in
prize money this year, double the amount available in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With so much money at stake, the days when Sam Snead and Billy
Casper could stage a competition that put the ``friend'' in
friendly rivalry are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Now PGA Tour legends such as Tom Watson, Hale Irwin and Tom Kite
must work hard to keep pace with players like Dana Quigley, Allen
Doyle and Walter Hall, who had little to no professional careers
before joining the Senior PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The players still are friendly to each other, but even Chi Chi
Rodriguez says, ``it's a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven players have earned more than $4 million on the
tour, and at least 10 more players should join that list by the
close of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin is the leading money winner, having earned $10.7 million
in six seasons compared to the $5.9 million he picked up in 14
years on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turned into a highly, highly competitive tour,'' Raymond
Floyd said. ``When it started, it was more of an exhibition to
bring some of the older guys out, have some camaraderie and service
corporate America somewhat. None of us imagined how popular it
would be received with corporate America and with television.''
</P>
<P>
   All Senior PGA Tour events will be broadcast on cable or network
television next year for the first time ever. The average purse in
the 36 full-field events is $1.3 million, the total amount awarded
for the 11 tournaments in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC Championship, which concluded Sunday at The Dominion in
San Antonio with Doug Tewell claiming a one-stroke victory, awarded
$1.1 million, and the purse is expected to increase another
$300,000 to $400,000 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not playing for all this money and giving all this
money to charity _ last year, $11 million _ just by accident,''
said Hal Seward, Senior PGA Tour vice president of tournament
business affairs. ``It's because it's a good product, people like
to come out and watch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it as successful as the PGA Tour? No, but it doesn't have
to be and it's not supposed to be. It's found its niche and it's
successful and it continues to grow every year.''
</P>
<P>
   While the growth has been lucrative, it also has come at a
price.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior PGA Tour started innocently in 1980 with two events
and became a full-fledged league in 1984 for players who are at
least 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Senior PGA Tour staples such as Casper and Gay Brewer seldom
play because they have dropped so far down the all-time money list.
They only participate when dozens of players elect not to play in
an event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the camaraderie we used to have and the fun we used to
have,'' Rodriguez said. ``The regular tour is the same way, it's
all a business. The guys who used to play this tour when I started
were ex-caddies. Now they are all bean counters; they come out of
college. I miss Casper, (Gene) Littler, Gay Brewer _ that laugh
that (Brewer) had _ I miss Arnie (Palmer).''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is players such as Hall and Doyle who are instilling
dreams in everyday golfers, generating greater interest and raising
the talent level on the Senior PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that I like are the guys that have a second
opportunity,'' Floyd said. ``The guys that were not very good
players or did not have much of a career on the regular tour or
might have been a club pro or in some cases worked in other fields
or were amateurs. That's an embellishment to this tour when you see
people like that that come here and are very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The influx of PGA Tour members who are turning 50 in addition to
players from other fields allows the Senior PGA Tour to regenerate
every few years.
</P>
<P>
   The money title has gone from Don January to Trevino to Jim
Colbert to Irwin to Bruce Fleisher over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the senior tour has gone through a natural evolution
that would happen to any organization,'' Seward said. ``I think it
has been a good evolution. Now it is a balance of being able to see
your heroes that you may have grown up with still compete at a high
level, but it's also a business and it's competition.''
</P>
<P>
   While many fans attend events to see favorites such as Trevino,
Rodriguez and Gary Player, it is the competition that is attracting
PGA Tour stalwarts like Floyd, Kite, Watson and Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a very competitive,'' Floyd said. ``Guys work
out, they work hard, they eat properly and they're practicing. When
the first guys started this tour, that was not the way it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evolved into a highly competitive tour and I think, as a
result of that, the bar has been raised and that's why we're seeing
the winning scores out here are so low. I think the field staff is
starting to recognize that and they are starting to set these golf
courses a little bit more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four scoring records set by a field were set in the
past four years. The lowest scoring average for a field was set in
the '97 Emerald Coast Classic (69.442).
</P>
<P>
   Because its members are getting better and the field deeper with
talent, Floyd said the Senior PGA Tour must prep its courses with
thicker rough and extend the course's length. The only other way to
toughen the 54-hole events is to expand them to 72 holes, which
most say won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too successful with the two pro-ams,'' Floyd said. ``I
think if we pull one of those pro-ams away from corporate America,
it might not be as successful. It's not broke, so let's don't go
try and fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   While legends in other sports are limited to old-timers' games
and autograph signings, their peers in golf are competing for
millions.
</P>
<P>
   Although his business ventures limit his schedule now, Palmer
has been playing professionally since 1954. Player has competed
since 1953, and Jack Nicklaus since 1961. Their contemporaries in
other sports _ Johnny Unitas, Stan Musial, Bill Russell _ have long
since retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandfathers and fathers can bring their boys and their sons
and daughters out here for Father's Day and let them see one of the
great personalities in golf,'' Seward said. ``They get to
understand what the guy does versus taking them to see a Hall of
Fame athlete in another sport who hasn't played in 30 years and try
to explain to the kid how great this guy was and what he used to
do. I think that's unique.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Raul Dominguez Jr. can be reached by e-mail at
rdominguez(at)express-news.net)
</P>
