<HEADER>
A0648 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-BLACK-POLITICAL-ANALY     06-21 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-POLITICAL-ANALYSTS-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLEASHING NEW POLITICAL VOICES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By KEVIN MERIDA  
 &HT;    You rarely see them quoted in news stories. Their advice is not
sought by candidates running for state or national office. For the
most part, they research and publish in obscurity. Thus, we hardly
hear from some of the most brilliant political minds in the country
and their work is not widely disseminated. They are the nation's
Black political scientists, with expertise ranging from American
government to the politics of hip-hop.
 &HT;    ``At least give us a say,'' says Robert T. Starks, a political
scientist at Northeastern Illinois University in Chicago.
 &HT;    Michael Preston, an expert on urban and racial politics at the
University of Southern California, agrees. ``If Jesse Jackson is
running, everybody wants to talk to you. If Bush and McCain are
running, nobody wants to talk to you,'' he says.
 &HT;    Linda Faye Williams, associate professor of government and
politics at the University of Maryland, put it this way. ``Many
journalists don't know any Black experts, period. So, what you
really see are the same old people quoted over and over.''
 &HT;    There also is a pecking order in academia that limits the
exposure of many Black scholars.
 &HT;    ``Unless you're at one of those Ivy League schools and you're
Comel West or Skip Gates, you're likely to be overlooked,''
Williams says.
 &HT;    The insights of the country's Black political intelligentsia
were on full display in Washington recently at the National
Conference of Black Political Scientists' annual meeting. They
discussed the growth of Black nationalists as a political force,
judicial politics, race and the digital revolution. The group is an
outgrowth of a 1969 meeting in Baton Rouge, La., where 35 Black
political scientists met to share problems they faced in their
work. They later agreed that Blacks needed their own organization.
In May 1970, they held their first meeting.
 &HT;    Joseph McCormick, a political scientist at Howard University and
an expert on Black public opinion research, says we are now on the
fifth generation of Black political scientists. They first taught
at Black colleges in the late 1940s and early '50s. Some of the
pioneers are still sharing their knowledge: Twiley Barker, an
expert in judicial politics at Howard, and Jewel Prestage, a
political science professor at Prairie View, and one of the first
Black women to earn a doctorate in political science.
 &HT;    McCormick views the development of the conference in the context
of the two periods in which Black organizations sprouted. The first
period, 1905-12, produced such groups as the NAACP, the National
Bar Association and Black fraternities.
 &HT;    ``Black people were responding to segregation,'' McCormick says.
 &HT;    In some cases, they were trying to combat the forces of White
supremacy. In others, they were responding to being excluded by
White professionals.
 &HT;    The second period, the '60s and early '70s, produced groups
whose missions were rooted in the Civil Rights Movement and the
Black Power struggle. ``We took the position that we needed to
speak in a more authentic voice, define issues for ourselves.''
Some Black professional groups _ sociologists, economists, to name
a few _ operated within the mainstream groups. Black political
scientists chose to break away.
 &HT;    It is more than ironic that almost all of the Black groups have
``national'' in their names.
 &HT;    ``They didn't get American because all of the White folks
monopolized that,'' McCormick points out, referring to such
examples as the American Historical Association and the American
Political Science Association.
 &HT;    In the millennium's first political season, it is long past time
for Black political scientists to get their due. The media should
focus on Nick Nelson, an expert on Black mayors at Ohio State,
Sarita McCoy, who has worked on the Black gender gap at the
University of Chicago and F. Carl Walton, chairman of the
conference's program on electoral and legislative politics.
 &HT;    This year the organization decided to compile a directory of
Black political scientists, including their areas of specialty and
contact numbers for U.S. media outlets.
 &HT;    Then, instead of seeing the same old tired mugs on the political
talk shows, and the same old predictable comments in news articles,
we might finally be treated to some fresh faces and some new
voices.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Kevin Merida is a contributing columnist for Emerge magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 EMERGE magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NEW
AMERICA NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
