<HEADER>
A0674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-R-AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      06-21 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-R-AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, June 22.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACE SERIES &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PLANTATION (NATCHITOCHES, La.) _ At the south edge of the
old plantation, eight simple cabins stood in a field of clover.
Generations of whitewash were peeling in ugly patches from the
mud-brick walls. All but one front porch had rotted away, and there
were gaping holes where doors and windows used to be. Obscured by
rows of live oaks, the cabins had been forgotten by many and
ignored by most. There was almost nothing left _ except the stories
of the slaves who once lived in them. By Ginger Thompson. (6500
words, with an abridged version of about half that length.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT901-908.
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth article in a series, How Race Is Lived in
America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Seoul, South Korea) _ The euphoria of last week's
summit meeting is wearing off to reveal the hard road ahead. In the
North, Kim Jong Il has urged North Koreans to hew to communism and
self-reliance, saying that market openings would be disastrous for
country. In the South, the political opposition has jumped on Kim
Dae-jung, saying he got nothing and was taken in by a Kim Jong Il.
By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-ACID (Gosarigaon, Bangladesh) _ Acid is thrown is the
faces of nearly 200 women a year in Bangladesh. Most often, the
culprit is a spurned suitor. No one is sure why this crime occurs
here at such a high pace, for this nation on the Indian
subcontinent is not so different from many others in its poverty or
its culture or its treatment of women. By Barry Bearak. (With photo
and map.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Metullah, Israel) _ In the vacuum at the
Israel-Lebanon border, Hezbollah patrols its side of the fence with
slingshots. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WAR-CRIMES (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The chief prosecutor
of the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia,
Carla del Ponte, said Wednesday that Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president, may face more charges and that some members of
the Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army are being investigated for
suspected war crimes. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DRUGS (Washington) _ The House Ways and Means Committee
takes up legislation to add drug benefits to Medicare; it is
expected to approve a Republican proposal on a party-line vote
after a lengthy session and impassioned debate. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-SECURITY (Washington) _ The recovered Los Alamos hard
drives are authentic and there is no evidence of espionage,
Richardson says in his first congressional testimony on the
security failure at the nuclear weapons lab. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-WWII-VETS (Washington)_ A score of Japanese-American
veterans of WWII take part in wreath-laying at Tomb of Unknowns
before going to W.House to get Medals of Honor they were long
denied because of prejudice. Interviews with two vets. By David
Stout.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,4.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CRIME (Washington) _ More than half of guns used in crimes
were illegally obtained, according to a new study by Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline to kum) _ George W. Bush's campaign day. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHILD-KILLERS (Miami) _ Why would a child kill? Because he
IS a child and doesn't consider the consequences of his actions,
says the mother of 13-year-old Nathaniel Brazill, accused of
shooting his teacher to death. The state of Florida has no middle
ground in such cases: A child like Nathaniel, accused of a felony,
is tried as an adult. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRAYER-REACT (Plano, Ill.) _ In the aftermath of the
Supreme Court decision on prayer, we talk with people in Plano,
Ill. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-GENOME (Undated) _ After months of fitful negotiation
that flamed out in an angry exchange in February _ and only days
away from reaching a decisive point in the historic project _ the
two sides racing to complete the sequence of the human genome are
expected to announce a truce. Although it is too late for
collaboration and a pooling of scientific efforts, the truce will
be an agreement for the competitors to publish their genome
findings in the same issue of a scientific journal, though in
separate articles. By Nicholas Wade. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-TEXTING (Manila) _ Texting, the exchange of short
typed messages over a cell phone, is possible on most digital
networks but relatively few people take advantage of it. That is
hardly the case in the Philippines, however. Here, where most
people still do not have a telephone, it is so popular that it has
spawned a subculture, with its own vocabulary, etiquette and
tactical uses. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-OIL (Vienna) _ OPEC ministers are expected to announce that
they will raise their oil production ceiling when they meet
Wednesday. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-SPRINT (Undated) _ Folo on reports that the proposed
merger of WorldCom Inc. and Sprint is facing opposition in both the
European Union and the United States. The European Commission said
it was too early to speculate on whether it would block the deal,
but it may well preparing for hard bargaining as it did in the
Boeing-McDonnell Douglas application.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-INSURANCE (Undated) _ One of the country's biggest life
insurers, American General, said it was paying $175 million to
settle claims that until as recently as early this year black
customers were charged more for coverage than were white customers.
The money is to cover fines imposed by state regulators and to
resolve a class action suit. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Undated) _ The World Wide Web Consortium and
businesses including Citigroup, IBM, Microsoft, NCR, NEC, Nokia
demonstrate the Platform for Privacy Preferences (P3P), a standard
that makes it possible for Web users' browsers to reject or accept
Web sites based on an automated privacy guard. Other companies and
consumers' groups have already criticized the plan. By Jeri
Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-WORK-CONDITIONS (Geneva) _ Spain is the most generous of
the developed nations in providing unemployment insurance to
workers, while New Zealand is the least generous, the International
Labor Organization says in an annual report assessing world labor
conditions. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column. By Alan B.
Krueger.
</P>
