<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MONTIEL-RESIGNS-HNS &LR;      06-21 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTIEL-RESIGNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEAD OF MAYNARD INSTITUTE TO LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Steve Montiel never thought he could change
the world, just the newsrooms of America.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years after taking over a journalism organization that
helped promote minority involvement in newsrooms, Montiel is
stepping down as the head of the Robert C. Maynard Institute for
Journalism Education.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel, 52, said he would remain as president and chief
executive officer of the Oakland-based institute until Sept. 5. The
institute provides training and services to promote diversity in
news media content, staffing and business operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to dig deeper into a project or two in a way that I am
not able to while leading an organization,'' said Montiel, who will
continue to serve on the board of the institute. ``I'm very
interested in journalistic storytelling that helps us see ourselves
and our communities whole.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the ultimate goal of the institute's founders _ among
them the late Robert C. Maynard, former publisher of the Oakland
Tribune _ when they revived a summer journalism boot camp for
minority journalists in 1976 that had ended at Columbia University
two years before.
</P>
<P>
   Relocated to the Graduate School of Journalism at the University
of California at Berkeley, the program trained minorities in the
summer and sent them to newspapers across the country as reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1976 and 1989, the institute trained more than 200
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 journalists also have graduated from the institute's
editing program during its 20 years at the University of Arizona.
The program recently relocated to UC-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   And another 300 news professionals have participated in the
institute's five-week Management Training Center program at
Northwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   In all, more than 2,000 journalists and news executives have
been involved in Maynard Institute programs.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel was a young Associated Press reporter when he applied to
become city editor for the institute's first class of reporters in
1976 in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   A Vietnam War correspondent for Pacific Stars and Stripes, the
native of Tucson, Ariz., became a founding member of the institute,
which incorporated a year later.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first members of the California Chicano News Media
Association, Montiel's work with the institute reshaped his
thinking about diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were already thinking and talking about the impact the
reporters coming through the summer program could have in the next
century,'' he said. ``Boy, it was a life-changing experience for me
to be around people who thought that big.''
</P>
<P>
   That optimism wasn't misplaced, Montiel said, citing graduates
who have had an impact in the news business.
</P>
<P>
   At least two alumni of Maynard programs are publishers of
newspapers _ Dorothy Bland, publisher of the Coloradoan in Fort
Collins, Colo., and Alexis Scott, publisher of the Atlanta Daily
World.
</P>
<P>
   Others are executives: Carolina Garcia, managing editor of the
San Antonio Express-News; Milton Coleman, deputy managing editor at
the Washington Post; and Evelyn Hsu, associate director of the
American Press Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Hsu, a former reporter for the San Francisco Chronicle and the
Washington Post, is also directing the Poynter Institute's new high
school journalism program. She credited the institute's founders
for her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like having really brilliant and inspiring
people believe in you,'' said Hsu, a Maynard Institute board
member. ``It paves the way for your accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Other graduates continue to report, including Mireya Navarro, a
reporter and former Miami bureau chief for the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe my career to the institute,'' said Navarro, a former San
Francisco Examiner reporter. ``They got me fresh out of college and
gave me these incredible standards, and I'm grateful for that. It
also provided us with this wonderful network of people who shared
that boot camp experience. We still run into each other. It really
feels like family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0622-C     06-21 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: A SHOPPING SPREE THROUGH KOSOVO'S NOT-SO-BLACK MARKET
ECONOMY
 &HT;    With Photo mug of Coker.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ What had started as a bad day turned even
worse when the shaggy-haired man pointed one nicotine-stained hand
at my face, held my crisp American dollar bill in the other and
shouted ``Counterfeit!''
</P>
<P>
   I had stepped inside Paris Boutique, a small shop off Mother
Teresa Street, the main drag in Kosovo's capital, to buy a new
dress and other clothes after concluding my luggage was lost, not
merely ``delayed,'' as the airline insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a pair of pants to supplement the clothes I was wearing
_ the only ones I had for my two-week reporting trip _ was a trial
in itself. But exchanging my dollars for German Deutsch marks, the
preferred currency in Kosovo, turned into an inquisition lacking
only hooded judges.
</P>
<P>
   Shaking my $100 bill twice and then rubbing Benjamin Franklin's
face on the inside of his wrist, like a perfume insert from a
fashion magazine, the money-changer insisted that traces of paint
had rubbed off, proving I was a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Counterfeit! It's counterfeit!'' he shrieked until I poured
out my story of how my luggage had been lost between Moscow and
Macedonia. The saleswomen, who had warmed to me after discovering I
was a dyed-in-the-wool American, scolded him for his rudeness
toward a citizen of the country that played a major role in NATO's
defeat of the Serb military last year.
</P>
<P>
   His face suddenly softening, the money-changer offered me a
generous exchange rate if I'd mail a letter to basketball great
Michael Jordan for him. ``He's my hero,'' the paunchy man said.
``He's the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   My encounter with the currency specialist-cum-Chicago Bulls fan
was merely the beginning of my tour through Kosovo's gray economy.
Thanks to lost baggage, I learned how honest citizens eat, clothe
themselves and eke out a living after two years of war with the
Serb army had unraveled their lives. I also learned how slowly
traditional gender relations change in this nominally Muslim
country.
</P>
<P>
   These Kosovars are not part of the prostitution or drug rings
that thrive in this Connecticut-sized province set between Albania
and Serbia, arguably Europe's most criminalized societies. Still,
necessity forces them every day to take advantage of Kosovo's black
market to ease life in a war-battered region where electricity runs
part of the time and food supplies depend on the season.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 70 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people are
unemployed, pushing a large number to the edge of poverty. The
United Nations is the largest employer, and officials admit it will
be years before investment generates new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen take advantage of the porous U.N. administration to
smuggle in vegetables from Italy, construction materials from
Turkey and shoes from Spain without paying duties and to resell
them without paying taxes _ crimes that technically make almost all
consumer goods part of the black market.
</P>
<P>
   A whiff of illegality hangs over downtown Pristina, from the
bootleg Marlboros hawked by 10-year-old boys for US$1.50 to the
pirated Jennifer Lopez and Dr. Dre CDs sold for US$2 on almost
every corner _ including on the sidewalk in front of the U.N.
police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But, law-enforcement officers are too overworked to crack down
on petty economic crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you bust a kid earning pennies to take home to his
family?'' said Bruce Lloy, spokesman for the U.N. police force in
Kosovo. ``We're better off focusing our resources on the serious
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   For me and for most people in Kosovo, the underworld of
drug-trafficking and other heavy-duty crime _ the ``serious stuff''
_ swirls out of sight. Night after night, I'd walk alone from
Pristina's Internet cafe to a bar then home after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   My translator's family thought my schedule was a bit crazy _ a
reaction that revealed more their views about what woman should do
after dark than their fear of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Long-standing cultural values have melted a bit, however. Shops
brim with the latest American fashions, including pink hot pants,
high wedge-shaped black heels and snug halter tops. Not at all what
I thought women in a Muslim country would wear.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, my original fears that I wouldn't find any clothes for
sale in Kosovo _ ``Who goes shopping in a war zone?'' I thought _
quickly turned to fears that I wouldn't find anything suitable for
reporting, only street walking.
</P>
<P>
   But two days and five or six stores later, just in time for my
interview with the head of Kosovo's largest political party, I
finally found the right item _ a sleeveless, bright blue printed
cotton dress long enough to be modest in an interview yet hip
enough to wear to a restaurant. All for 42 German marks, or $21
U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to look good is to feel good,'' Alma, a 22-year-old
saleswoman dressed in khaki cargo pants and a black polyester tank
top, told me as I handed over my cash. ``You've got to go out,
laugh with friends, or else life just becomes work, cooking and
sitting in an old apartment where you don't have electricity half
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Having already spent a week's worth of evenings typing notes and
washing my grimy clothes by hand under candlelight, I knew exactly
how she felt.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
