u i BC-RUSSIA-SPY-0622-COX     06-21 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SPY-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALLEGED U.S. SPY JAILED IN RUSSIA RAISES COLD WAR FEARS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The wife of an alleged American spy pleaded with
Russian officials Wednesday to free her jailed husband in a case
reminiscent of superpower relations during the Cold War's iciest
years.
</P>
<P>
   A shroud of official silence surrounds what Moscow-based
diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, have called a highly
unusual case that comes at politically sensitive time in
U.S.-Russia relations.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Cheryl Pope visited her husband, Edmond Pope, a
retired U.S. Naval intelligence officer, for the first time since
his arrest here on April 3. Trembling and struggling to hold back
tears, she insisted that her husband, now a businessman, was
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to see him yesterday and we embraced. The first
thing he said to me was 'I'm innocent,' and I said, 'I know you
are,''' she said. ``I would just like to ask (Russian President
Vladimir) Putin to please look at my husband as an individual, and
to see there's a mistake being made here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pope said she knew little about her husband's business in
Russia or the charges against him. She said her brief conversation
with him in the waiting room at Lefortovo prison, a Soviet-era jail
used by the KGB to hold political prisoners, concentrated on family
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told each other we loved each other very much, and that we
would stay a strong family,'' Cheryl Pope said, adding that she
told him that their infant grandson had taken his first steps.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has yet to release a detailed explanation
of the charges against Pope. The Federal Security Service, the
successor agency to the KGB and the organization Putin ran last
year before running for president, has simply said the American is
charged with stealing ``state secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether President Bill Clinton raised the Pope
case during his visit to Moscow earlier this month. Clinton's
meetings were largely devoted to defense issues, especially
Russia's concern over U.S. plans to developing a controversial
national missile defense (NMD) that could alter the 1972
Anti-ballistic Missile treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Pope, a veteran traveler to Russia, runs CERF Technologies
International, a consulting firm based in State College, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Before his arrest, he was working in Moscow with a weapons
company called Russian Technologies to help market Russian torpedo
technology to international buyers, according to copies of business
plans and correspondence between Pope and the company made
available to Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The technology has been described by defense analysts as
unclassified and already for sale on the world arms markets.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats in Moscow said the Pope case deviates from the usual
practice in alleged espionage incidents in Russia. Usually, a
suspected spy is deported immediately, not jailed for long periods
of time, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian defense analyst Vladimir Rudenko said Pope's arrest
could be a by-product in a long-running battle between Russian
weapons companies, a murky world run by former Soviet military
figures and KGB agents that brings in billions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's election as president in March has resulted in a
reshuffle of figures throughout the government as well as the
weapons sector. Russian Technologies became a casualty of the
jockey for power, and was disbanded in April, Rudenko said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have mistakenly landed in the middle of something
over his head,'' Rudenko said of Pope.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., was denied access to Pope during a
visit to Moscow one week ago. Like Pope's wife, Weldon claims the
former naval officer was not a spy but merely a businessman who
openly bought technology and sought joint ventures with Russian
firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CIA has assured me that he is not one of theirs,'' Weldon
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.house.gov/curtweldon
</P>
<P>
   www.house.gov/johnpeterson
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
