<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVI-STRAUSS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEVI STRAUSS REPORTS BETTER PERFORMANCE IN 2ND QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. says that net income rose 48
percent in the second quarter and that sales declines slowed in the
same period, indicating that recent belt-tightening at the jeans
maker is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with where we are in our business
turnaround,'' said Philip Marineau, the company's president and
chief executive. ``We are doing what we said we would do to
stabilize the business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of our sales decline has slowed, gross margins are
up, our net income is rising and we are decreasing our debt,'' he
said. ``In addition, we have maintained strict and effective cost
controls.``
</P>
<P>
   Net income in the quarter ended May 28 rose to $45 million from
$30.4 million a year earlier, while sales declined 6 percent to
$1.15 billion from $1.23 billion in the year-ago period, an
improvement from the 15 percent decline in net sales reported for
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Product innovation and marketing initiatives contributed to the
improved sales trend, the privately held company said.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter gross margin, which reflects the profitability of
sales, rose to 42.4 percent compared with 40 percent in the second
quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals such as Tommy Hilfiger Corp. and Calvin Klein Inc. have
been taking sales from Levi Strauss in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   That forced the company to restructure its operations over the
past 12 months, a move that included significant job cuts at its
headquarters in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts saw the second quarter figures as a sign that business
was turning around at Levi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales declines are decreasing, and they are managing their
inventories with discipline, and that is having an impact on gross
margins,'' said analyst Todd Slater of Lazard Freres &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Total debt stood at $2.3 billion at quarter's end, down from
$2.67 billion six months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The action that we've taken to improve profitability has
worked,'' said Bill Chiasson, the company's chief financial
officer. ``At the same time, I don't want people to think we're all
the way back. We expect to see improvement every season. It may
take a year, maybe a year and a half, to get where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiasson said new products are helping the company attract young
buyers. Those products include a line of freight jeans, corduroys
and hip-huggers. Many of those products were introduced first in
Asia and Europe, where they are selling strongly, said Chiasson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to create a buzz in the marketplace,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
