<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-RUSSIA-SPY-0622-COX     06-21 0206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SPY-0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALLEGED U.S. SPY JAILED IN RUSSIA RAISES COLD WAR FEARS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The wife of an alleged American now a businessman, was
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to see him yesterday and we embraced. The first
thing he said to me was 'I'm innocent,' and I said, 'I know you
are,''' she said. ``I would just like to ask (Russian President
Vladimir) Putin to please look at my husband as an individual, and
to see there's a mistake being made here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Pope said she knew little about her husband's business in
Russia or the charges against him. She said her brief conversation
with him in the waiting room at Lefortovo prison, a Soviet-era jail
used by the KGB to hold political prisoners, concentrated on family
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told each other we loved each other very much, and that we
would stay a strong family,'' Cheryl Pope said, adding that she
told him that their infant grandson had taken his first steps.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has yet to release a detailed explanation
of the charges against Pope. The Federal Security Service, the
successor agency to the KGB and the organi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
