<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TRACKING-COWS-NYT     06-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRACKING-COWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GPS COLLARS: A NEW WAY TO TELL WHEN THE COWS COME HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to capture the cowboy mystique, wealthy executives
from high-tech companies are grabbing up land in the Texas Hill
Country between San Antonio and Austin and stocking it with cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People buy plots on subdivided ranches, and where they should
have two cows they'll have 20, plus two horses, three or four sheep
and some chickens,'' said Dr. Lew Hunnicut, an assistant professor
of range and animal science at Southwest Texas State University in
San Marcos. ``It takes a minimum of 25 to 30 acres to support a cow
in Texas Hill Country.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicut is using global positioning system technology and
digitized mapping in a study designed to find out exactly where
cows will graze.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred acres of ranch land doesn't mean 200 acres of
grazable land, he explained. The brush a rancher sees on the range
may hide rocky ground or rich clay-based soil that is fine for
grazing. So clearing the brush over rocky ground doesn't make sense
because cattle won't walk over it to feed on prairie grasses.
</P>
<P>
   By analyzing grazing patterns, Hunnicut hopes to offer new
ranchers information on where to clear their land for cattle and
what to leave as habitat for wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   He and Dr. Bob Lyons, a range extension specialist at Texas A&AMP;M
University, have begun a research program that uses GPS-equipped
collars developed to track wild animals to pinpoint exactly where
on a 4,200-acre research ranch cattle are eating, chewing their cud
or resting.
</P>
<P>
   The GPS unit records longitude and latitude every 15 minutes.
The points of data showing a cow's position are downloaded and
overlaid onto two types of maps to interpret where the cows are
grazing. One is a map illustrating soil types, and the other, using
infared images taken from 20,000 feet, shows which part of the test
ranch has thick vegetation and which is rocky.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Hunnicut hopes to use maps like those generated in
the study as an education tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to convince someone not to use 40 percent of their
ranch for grazing,'' he said. ``A lot of Hill Country isn't good
for cows because of the rock and brush. The maps can help ranchers
visualize the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The GPS collars, which weigh about a pound, are made by Lotek
Wireless of Newmarket, Ontario. They are very rugged, designed for
use with wild animals like elephants, wildebeest, wolves, reindeer,
bears and mountain lions, said Leszek Meczarski, the product
manager for GPS items at Lotek.
</P>
<P>
   The units are waterproof and can withstand the shock of running
animals and being banged against rocks or trees, he said. The GPS
devices are one-size-fits-all, and they are fitted onto the various
animals using customized collars. Lotek even makes tiny GPS units
that are imbedded in fresh-water and saltwater fish for marine
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Each GPS collar in the cattle study, which costs about $5,000,
must be removed weekly to recharge the batteries and download the
data via a cable to a computer. The collars made for tracking wild
animals typically have a one-year battery life and a transmitter
for sending data to an overflying aircraft. They cost about $2,000
more. They also have a release mechanism that can be triggered with
a radio signal so the animals do not have to be captured to
retrieve their collars.
</P>
<P>
   The cow collar is a vast improvement over the traditional tool
for data collection in agricultural studies: graduate students.
``We could have used grad students to walk around and follow the
cows,'' Hunnicut said. The problem is that when cows see one of the
white pickup trucks from the school, they walk toward it hoping for
a treat (hay or food pellets with corn), thus changing their
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the collars, we can plot their movement without human
intervention,'' Hunnicut said.
</P>
<P>
   The study uses four collars, rotated among the cows so that the
grazing choices of the entire herd are reflected in the data.
Still, a graduate student leaves the pickup truck behind and goes
out on horseback twice a day to see if the collared cow is with the
herd or off by herself and to take notes on behavior to validate
the GPS data.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicut meets with cattle owners, environmentalists and new
landowners as part of the university's agricultural extension
program. Some of these newer ranchers eagerly attend so-called
master naturalist classes to learn how to care for their land, but
others will need convincing with cow grazing maps, spreadsheets and
charts.
</P>
<P>
   The cattle study study may help boutique ranchers, but Texas'
traditional ranchers already know what their cattle are doing and
where they will eat.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Kiker, an eighth-generation rancher in the Beaumont area
of southeast Texas, can rattle off the protein and nutritional
content of rice and grasses he plants in his pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Kiker, who interrupted his soybean planting and set his tractor
on idle to answer questions in a short interview by cell phone,
agreed with Hunnicut that the soil is the key: ``When you find a
spot that grows good grass you know it. I know where the cows eat
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
