<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN NEVER HAVE ENOUGH COOKIES IN A JAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scrolling the food wires the other day, I came across the
counterpart to this column that runs in The Miami Herald.
Coincidentally, the column I saw was about ``cookies in a jar'' _ a
subject we covered a couple of weeks back. The recipes, though,
were not the ones we had run. So, here are some bonus recipes from
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   RAISIN OATMEAL BARS IN A JAR
</P>
<P>
   Yields 16
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup old-fashioned rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed dark brown sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cups buttermilk baking mix (such as Bisquick), divided
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Have a sterilized, dry, quart-size, wide-mouth canning jar
ready. Pour the oats in the bottom. Add the raisins in a layer. Add
1/2 cup of the brown sugar. Add 1 cup of the baking mix. Sprinkle
the cinnamon on top. Add the remaining 1/2 cup brown sugar in a
layer. Top with the remaining baking mix. If there is space left,
add more raisins, or, if desired, use chocolate or butterscotch
chips. Close jar with clean, sterilized lid. Put this recipe on a
gift card:
</P>
<P>
   To make bars:
</P>
<P>
   Empty this jar of goodies into a bowl. Stir in 1 stick of melted
butter or margarine, 1 egg and 1 teaspoon of vanilla. Coat an
8-inch baking pan generously with cooking spray. Press mixture into
the pan and bake 20 to 22 minutes at 350 degrees, or until light
golden brown. Cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per square: 135 calories, 2 grams fat, 28
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 180 milligrams
sodium, 14 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HOT HOMEMADE COOKIE MIX IN A JAR
</P>
<P>
   Yields 30
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crisp rice cereal (such as Rice Krispies)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup quick oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Layer ingredients in order given in a large Mason jar. (Mix the
flour with the baking powder first.) Press ingredients down with a
fork a little at a time. Attach a decorative tag with the following
directions:
</P>
<P>
   Empty cookie mix into large bowl. Use your hands to blend
thoroughly. Add 1 stick of very soft butter or margarine (but not
diet margarine), plus 1 egg and 1 teaspoon vanilla. Mix well, using
your hands. (You can't use an electric mixer or the chips will be
smashed.) Shape into walnut-size balls. Place 2 inches apart on
baking sheets coated with vegetable oil spray. Bake at 350 degrees
for 13 to 15 minutes, until edges are lightly brown. Cool 5 minutes
on baking sheet. Remove to racks to finish cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cookie: 111 calories, 5 grams fat, 17
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 15 milligrams cholesterol, 55
milligrams sodium, 36 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Delores McFadden would like a recipe for German potato salad
that she clipped from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram several years
ago. I searched our electronic library but couldn't find that
recipe. The recipe Delores remembers included frozen hash brown
potatoes and sour cream and was topped off with small link
sausages.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
