<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BOTTLEDMARINADE-TEX     06-21 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTTLEDMARINADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BOTTLED MARINADES, SIMPLY ADD MEAT, CHICKEN OR FISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget rubbing and brushing. It appears the hottest thing this
summer is soaking.
</P>
<P>
   And no, we don't mean a pedicure for your sandal-destined
tootsies.
</P>
<P>
   It's marinades _ seemingly an army of them _ marching across
grocery store shelves. Lawry's, KC Masterpiece, Paul Prudhomme and
Stubb's all have products to coat and tenderize food. Even
companies not known for barbecue or spices have entered the arena.
A.1. Steak Sauce and French's also have products in the category.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of factors'' driving the trend, says John
Barrows, director of communication for Nabisco, A.1.'s corporate
parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer want convenience, so we're giving them a marinade in
a ready-to-use format. It takes some of the guesswork out of making
their own,'' Barrows says.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our own part at A.1., we recognized that half of all
steaks consumed are marinated, but there was no marinade designed
especially for steaks on the market. Most are designed for poultry
and white meat. So it was natural for the No. 1 condiment in steak
to grow in the marinade direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco's research also revealed that consumers often reach for
a bottle of Italian salad dressing to douse their meat. So A.1. is
available in an Italian herb variety as well as a hickory flavor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using more acid in the formula, A.1. has
seriously punched up the herb content of its marinade _ the bottle
is almost green with seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers who make their own steak marinades use a hefty
splash of Worcestershire sauce. Because French's produces
Worcestershire sauce, the company went in a different direction
with its Grill &AMP; Glaze line designed for chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Bender, spokesperson for French's Grill &AMP; Glaze, says a
lot of what drove the formulation was chicken consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken consumption has jumped from 60-some pounds per person
a year to about 80 pounds per person a year,'' Bender says. ``None
of the marinades on the market were geared specifically to chicken.
We used a plastic squeeze bottle for convenience and because it's
familiar to consumers because of our mustard.''
</P>
<P>
   French's has pumped up its convenience factor by giving
consumers the option of not marinating, but simply brushing the
product onto chicken. Or, if the cook has an extra 20 minutes,
using Grill &AMP; Glaze for marinating and basting.
</P>
<P>
   Lawry's, known for years for its Seasoned Salt and dry flavoring
pouch mixes, was the first big boy to produce bottled marinades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted something that could flavor a lot of things, not
just proteins, which we had covered,'' says Vicki Gagliano,
consumer test-kitchen manager for Lawry's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use fruit juices in our marinades, which gives big, bold,
robust flavors without being heavy like barbecue sauces. And
because there's no fat, that appeals to people, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use our marinades on vegetables, say one of those big
portobello mushrooms, and eat it like a burger. That appeals to a
lot of the younger people who are steering away from meat.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottled marinade category is so new, despite the plethora of
products, that even the industry association, the Association for
Dressings and Sauces, doesn't have tracking numbers. However, the
latest A.C. Nielsen tracking numbers, according to Lawry's, show
that the marinade category has grown 98 percent over last year's
same-period sales.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the varieties you'll find in area stores and what each
goes best on.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: KC Masterpiece, a big name in barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   Varieties: Honey Teriyaki, Original BBQ
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Meat, seafood, chicken
</P>
<P>
   Price: $2.89 for 16 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Very thick marinades seem almost to ``enrobe''
the food instead of seeping into it. We find the BBQ flavor
redundant _ why not use barbecue sauce?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: Chef Paul Prudhomme, a big name in Cajun food
</P>
<P>
   Variety: Southwest Chipotle Marinade
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Meat, seafood, chicken
</P>
<P>
   Price: $1.99 for 12 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Nice and hot; good thin consistency; a little
goes a long way; best on ``big'' food like beef, lamb and pork
chops.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: Stubb's, an Austin barbecue legend
</P>
<P>
   Variety: Pork Marinade
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Chops, tenderloin, kebabs
</P>
<P>
   Price: $1.99 for 12 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Nice sweet-and-sour flavor replete with chile
flakes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: World Harbors Acadia, a Maine company
</P>
<P>
   Variety: Lemon Pepper &AMP; Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Seafood and fish
</P>
<P>
   Price: $1.99 for 18 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Pretty wimpy and skimpy on herbs and spices.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: Allegro, a Creole foods specialist
</P>
<P>
   Varieties: Hot &AMP; Spicy Marinade
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Shrimp, fish kebabs, chicken
</P>
<P>
   Price: $1.99 for 12.7 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Distinct flavor that speaks of the South
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: Lawry's, a longtime name in dry-seasoning blends and at
steak restaurants
</P>
<P>
   Varieties: 30 Minute Marinades range from Teriyaki to
Mediterranean to Tequila Lime
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Chicken, meat, fish
</P>
<P>
   Price: $2.99 for 12 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: This was one of the first mass-marketed bottled
marinades. We liked it when it was introduced a couple of years
ago, and we still like it. This year's new citrus flavors are kicky
on seafood _ try the Tequila Lime on shrimp for a barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: French's
</P>
<P>
   Varieties: Grill &AMP; Glaze in Teriyaki and Honey Mustard
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Price: $1.89 for 15 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: On chicken, it's great. Plus the glaze effect
makes it attractive to children.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: A.1.
</P>
<P>
   Varieties: Italian and Hickory
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Steak
</P>
<P>
   Price: $2.99 for 12 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Chock-full of herbs, this is a nice addition to
the weekday steak.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brand: Consorzio
</P>
<P>
   Varieties: Tropical Grill and other new-age flavors
</P>
<P>
   Recommended for: Mild fish and seafood
</P>
<P>
   Price: $2.99 for 12 ounces
</P>
<P>
   What we thought: Good flavor, and the squeeze bottle is a good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
