<HEADER>
A0758 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     06-21 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE TO PEEK INTO LOST LUGGAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time I was waiting for my luggage at the airport, I saw
a cracked leather valise stuffed so full that it might have
actually encased a live pig. The frenzied way someone had wrapped
twine around the bulging case suggested a disturbing record of
attempted escapes.
</P>
<P>
   But then, as the valise traveled around the baggage carousel, I
changed my mind. It must have contained something more valuable:
Otherwise why bother with those additional strips of electrical
tape across the locks? After all the other suitcases had been
claimed, I decided that it must have belonged to a smuggler
apprehended at the gate before he could reclaim his uncut diamonds.
Or ivory tusks. Or unpasteurized French cheese.
</P>
<P>
   I am fascinated by the mystery of other people's luggage,
especially their unclaimed luggage. The glamour tends to fade if
the owner shows up and turns out to be the same man who sat a row
ahead in economy and begged the flight attendant for extra salted
nuts. But luggage that is never reunited with its owner always
contains the thrill of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   So when I learned last week about an online shopping site called
Unclaimedbaggage.com, where you can actually buy the contents of
unclaimed suitcases, there was no way I could resist
(www.unclaimedbaggage.com). This was something far more tantalizing
than the usual discards at a garage sale or thrift store. Here was
a rare legal opportunity to riffle through personal items that
still had value to their owners at the time they were separated by
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an archaeological dig in the sense that you see a
cross-section of the culture when you open up suitcases: the kinds
of clothes people are wearing, the books they're reading, the
keepsakes they bought on vacation,'' said Bryan Owens, the owner of
the Unclaimed Baggage Center, which operates both the Web site and
a block-long retail store in the Appalachian foothills of
Scottsboro, Ala. `We've been doing this for 30 years, and we have
long-term, exclusive contracts with many of the major carriers.
It's anything you could imagine, although certain things we don't
sell. We have an agreement with the FDA to destroy prescription
drugs, for instance.''
</P>
<P>
   Recovering from my disappointment over the prescription drugs, I
went to the site's Click on the Suitcase feature to learn about
some of the more unusual items that Unclaimed Baggage has collected
over the years. The list included two that had once concealed rolls
of money: a Barbie doll (luckily the buyer's daughter pulled off
the head by accident, revealing $500 inside the torso) and a
``perfectly ordinary soap on a rope'' that had been hollowed out. I
was ready to buy. Judging from the home page, which announced
``lost treasures from around the world,'' Owens is familiar with
the psychology of shoppers like me. The site asked: ``What do you
imagine a wealthy retired couple might have packed to go to Hawaii?
An expensive camera?'' What would the finely tailored corporate
executive flying back from Moscow have had in his suitcases? An
elegant cashmere top coat? Gold cuff links?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes, I thought. That's exactly what I would expect!
Forgetting for the moment that most suitcases are more likely to
harbor items that fall into less savory categories _ like hair
care, underwear and tweezers _ I eagerly clicked on Let's Shop. I
arrived at 40 categories of merchandise, from Cigars to Jewelry to
Women's Closet, in which a total of 344 different items were
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody's used cigars? That brought me up short for the same
reasons that are causing goose bumps on your arms right now.
</P>
<P>
   But when I examined the nine items for sale in that category,
they didn't look used at all. In fact, they were all new: an
unopened five-pack of Muriel Air Tip regulars for $1, a new
portable pouch called the Humi to keep cigars fresh for $3, a
package of pipe filters for $1.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Owens, he acknowledged that most of the items
online were new and in fact came from unclaimed shipments of cargo,
things like unworn bedroom slippers, brand-new baby bottles and
unused film that had been lost in transit. Nothing from that finely
tailored corporate executive after all, no suits in the women's
closet section and certainly no used Barbies or rope soaps.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he thought that it would be unfair to sell online
shoppers many used items because it was difficult to examine them
closely enough online to determine if they met standards of
cleanliness. The FAQ section on the site did pose the pertinent
question ``Is it clean?'' (Answer: the store launders or dry-cleans
all applicable articles of clothing.) So while the Internet site
does sell some mysteries _ like the 40.95-carat emerald offered for
$14,750, which would easily enable you to meet the $25 minimum for
Internet purchases _ most of the online offerings betrayed no hint
of their owner's personality.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I decided that the online site was not really a
place to shop, but more like one of those mystery bags with a
question mark stamped on it that you used to get from a vending
machine after you paid 50 cents to take a chance on finding
treasure. It was a lot of fun, though, to click on the Peek in the
Bag feature and see the receipt from a recent purchase: ``Kenneth
Cole women's shoes $59.40, novelty birthday candles $1, lefty
scissors three at 25 cents each.''
</P>
<P>
   No pigs, though.
</P>
</TEXT>
