u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-400&AMP;AD     06-21 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKS, NOT BULLETS, NOW FLY ACROSS THE ISRAEL-LEBANON BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   METULLA, Israel _ Armed with a slingshot, a walkie-talkie and a
pistol tucked into his pants, a Hezbollah guerrilla across the
fence in Lebanon let another stone fly Wednesday toward a
mesh-covered Israeli army post on the outskirts of this northern
border community.
</P>
<P>
   What had once been a frontier lookout point for Israeli visitors
was closed off with coils of barbed wire. The ground was strewn
with rubble heaved in recent weeks from the Lebanese side, where
burnt out buildings and barriers in an abandoned Israeli base were
covered with with anti-Israeli graffiti and posters for Hezbollah,
or the Party of God.
</P>
<P>
   Rocks regularly sail over the fence these days at Israeli
farmers from Metulla who work in apple orchards that stretch to the
border. Vehicles have been hit and irrigation systems smashed,
disrupting work in recent weeks, although no one has been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers patrolling the border are under strict orders
not to fire unless they are fired upon, and it has been only
stones, not bullets, that have crossed the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a month after Israel withdrew its troops from southern
Lebanon, the frontier between the countries remains free of gunfire
but unsettled. The line of Israeli withdrawal, certified by the
United Nations but disputed in some points by Lebanon, is still
being checked by U.N. teams. In the meantime, Hezbollah guerrillas,
not Lebanese or U.N. soldiers, face the Israelis along the
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all our land is not liberated we will continue fighting,
and we want our prisoners released,'' one warned near the border
fence Wednesday, echoing the pledge of his movement's leader, Sheik
Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who is visiting the Middle
East, was in Israel Wednesday to try to iron out the reported
violations of the withdrawal line, and after meeting him, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said he expected the matter to be settled in 24
to 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who met Nasrallah in Lebanon on Tuesday, noted the
``restraint, responsibility and discipline'' of Hezbollah, which
has not fired across the border since the Israeli withdrawal, and
he asserted that U.N. peacekeepers would be posted on the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will move the troops to the border,'' he said, adding that
Lebanese officials had indicated to him that they, too, would soon
send their troops to southern Lebanon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the meantime, life in Metulla is ``anything but routine,''
said Herzl Boker, the local council's security officer. Farmers
take roundabout routes to their orchards and work in the early
morning to avoid the stone-throwing, but are often are forced to
leave, he said. Recently, he added, the army discovered an
attempted entry through the fence, but the intruders fled back to
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one to talk to right now on the other side,'' Boker
said. ``The minute the Lebanese army and the United Nations arrive
and take control, it will be possible to stop the vandalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Avi Rauner, who has apple and pear orchards near the border
fence, said he had cut back his work there to avoid the daily
shower of stones. Yet compared to the warfare that used to rage
across the border between Hezbollah and the Israeli army, ``the
situation is quiet,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected that when the army left Lebanon, Hezbollah would
take over and that mobs would loot what was left behind,'' he said.
``But in a few weeks, U.N. and Lebanese forces will come. This is
only temporary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
