<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0761 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SIDEKICK-TV-$ADV25-2T     06-21 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDEKICK-TV-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHTER LEAVES, AND SIDEKICKERY GOES WITH HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By JAMES BARRON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is the day after his last appearance on ``Late
Night With Conan O'Brien'' _ a day that a more predictable type
might describe as ``the first day of the rest of my life.'' Nothing
so shopworn comes from Andy Richter. He takes stock in his own way,
doing a kind of ``In the Year 2000'' routine about where he is and
where he is going (but without the flashlight under his chin or the
squeaky falsetto refrain).
</P>
<P>
   ``For Conan,'' he says in the vaguely Midwestern voice that
launched a thousand ad-libs in the night, ``the show was a dream
come true. I was more of a hired gun. I was never going to be it.
I've done this every day in front of a live audience for seven
years. Now I'd like to go off into the woods with a camera, fake
beards, armor, Roman centurions and Elizabethan hoop skirts, talk
in accents, do 20 takes, edit it for a week and watch it without a
laugh track.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of postmidnight shenanigans, Richter has given
up his place as the trusty No. 2 on ``Late Night'' to go it alone
and concentrate on his acting career. But breaking out of the
``Late Night'' orbit has not lofted him beyond supporting-player
status _ not yet, anyway. In his first post-``Late Night'' role, he
is once again playing somebody's buddy: Richard Gere's hunting
companion in the Robert Altman film ``Dr. T. and the Women''
(which, for the record, has no fake beards, armor, Roman centurions
or Elizabethan hoop skirts). He will also appear, again in a
supporting role, in a new movie starring Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Richter has been gone only a few weeks, but already couch
potatoes miss him. He was the last of the old-fashioned sidekicks,
and for now, anyway, there are no plans to replace him on ``Late
Night.'' And virtually no other show has a guy in a suit whose main
responsibilities are to serve as the host's Greek chorus and to
slide over when the guests start arriving. His fans say he
single-handedly redefined what was once a television staple: the
role of the sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bob had Howdy Doody, after all, and Dave Garroway had a
chimpanzee. As television's evolution continued, the sidekicks
became human. Groucho Marx had George Fenneman on the quiz show
``You Bet Your Life.'' Late at night, Jack Paar had Hugh Downs in
the 1950s, Joey Bishop had Regis Philbin in the 1960s, and Johnny
Carson, of course, had the grand master of second bananas, Ed
McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed McMahon made Tonto look like a three-dimensional
character,'' said Robert J. Thompson, professor of film and
television at Syracuse University. ``He was there to reflect the
glory of Johnny. You get into this ironic age, where Letterman and
Conan are so self-conscious of these kinds of formats, and the
sidekick takes on a very different air.''
</P>
<P>
   Letterman chose not to have a sidekick in the traditional sense.
He banters with his bandleader, Paul Shaffer, but Shaffer is more
of a foil than a sidekick. O'Brien has a bandleader, too _ Max
Weinberg, who is perhaps better known as Bruce Springsteen's
drummer. But it was left to Richter to reinterpret the sidekick's
place, doing the Ed McMahon job while simultaneously making fun of
it.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a kind of comedic Siamese twinning, a dialogue
between near-equals rather than the relationship of omnipotent host
and fawning subordinate that Carson and McMahon perfected (though
it must be noted that Richter always lost the staring contests with
O'Brien). ``It was so much less planned than anyone knows,''
Richter said. ``Our rhythms were good together. We'd been doing
bits around the office, just impromptu bits'' before the program
went on the air. From their off-camera improvisation, Richter
understood how they could work together: ``He's trilling, I'm the
bass note.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sidekick was not a role he had been looking for _ he had
joined the program expecting to do comedy sketches, not sit at the
right hand of O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they started out, nobody knew what to do with this guy
Andy,'' Thompson said. ``He wasn't your typical sidekick. He was
heavier back then, and Conan was like mainstream entertainment's
sidekick already _ never been on a show, been to Harvard, came out
of left field, the kind you always expect to work as a supporting
character but not be the guy in and of himself. Andy seemed to be
coming from the planet Pluto for a while. It took a long time for
people to get used to him. In the core demographic for Conan, which
is college students, the anti-Andy sentiment was very, very strong
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, some NBC executives were also anti-Andy in the
program's rocky first couple of seasons, though Richter credits
O'Brien and the show's producers with not telling him that his
perch next to O'Brien was precarious. Good thing, too. ``It was
asthough Andy was inventing himself as he went along,'' Thompson
said, ``and by the time he left, he was one of the big appeals.
Many college students were more likely to send a fan letter to Andy
than to Conan.'' No less an authority on hipness than Janeane
Garofalo told Entertainment Weekly magazine last month that ``his
appeal is off the charts.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin, too, sounded like a true fan. ``He may be the last
official sidekick,'' he said of Richter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The role has changed considerably since I did that,'' Philbin
said. ``Now they're more a part of the show than just a prompter.
In those days, you were there to make the host look good and that
was the job, take it or leave it. I would come out in the opening
segment and prompt Joey Bishop with my own observations about
things, knowing that he would have a punch line. He was a great
counterpuncher and that was what he wanted me to do, and I did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter, Philbin said, ``had more to do than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most important element of Richter's job description was
the same _ and it was paramount for McMahon as well. ``I understood
that my job was to support Johnny Carson,'' he wrote in his
autobiography, ``For Laughing Out Loud'' (Warner, 1998). ``I didn't
tell the jokes, I set up the jokes. I didn't get the laughs, I
helped him get the laughs. Johnny and I never discussed this; we
didn't have to. We were smart enough to see how well our
relationship worked.'' McMahon said he had to undergo on-the-air
behavior modification to preserve that relationship. ``At times I
had to consciously stop myself from responding to something he
said,'' McMahon wrote. Before he went on the air with Carson, ``I'd
always had my own shows, I'd always been free to say whatever
popped into my mind. But after a few weeks I had slipped quite
comfortably into the role of straight man, his second banana.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Downs had played a similar role when Jack Paar was the host
on ``Tonight,'' but like Richter on ``Late Night,'' he found
himself caught up in a relationship that was evolving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started as an announcer's job,'' Downs said. ``I started
out just saying, `Here's Jack Paar.' In fact, I think at first I
was only heard. Then I think they put a camera on me turning it
over to him. Then he took to calling me over to the desk. Then the
format was established: when he brought the first guest out, I'd
move over to the sofa. He felt insecure and wanted me there by him
and would ask me questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Downs had another responsibility besides making the host feel
comfortable, one that was never in Richter's portfolio: in his day,
announcers did the commercials, live. There were no breaks while
the commercials rolled, leaving the band to perform for the studio
audience and the host to light up a cigar, as Letterman often did
before his heart surgery. Unintentionally, the commercials often
became funnier than anyone had bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, I was standing, waiting to do this commercial,'' Downs
said. ``I was going to demonstrate this can opener. I had a number
of tin cans. Katharine Murray was on. Paar complimented her. Paar
said to her, she had a good figure. She said, `Destiny has shaped
my end.' Paar threw it to me and I went into the commercial, which
began, `No matter what size or shape can you have, the Reliance can
opener can handle it.' I got about that far and I was finished.
</P>
<P>
   As for Richter, having reinvented the sidekick's role and stayed
with ``Late Night'' until it established itself as popular and
profitable, why step aside?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any real plan as to how long I would be on the
show,'' Richter said. ``If you'd asked when we started, I would
probably have said, `I can see about seven years,' and that's
exactly what we've done. It's not just the form. There are other
things _ it became a cumulative effect: I became tired of doing a
show every day. There's this pressure where you never feel you've
done any one item justice because there's this
slap-it-together-and-get-it-out-the-door feeling to the work.
That's the way it was: Did we say all the lines right? Did the
camera get the shot of the parrot? Yeah? OK, we're done, on to the
next thing. Could we do it any better? It's pretty slapdash when
you're working so hard and putting out so much.''
</P>
<P>
   So why not simply take a sabbatical? ``Yeah,'' Richter sighed.
``People have said to me, `Why don't you take leaves of absence
like Max Weinberg does?' Springsteen's tour is pretty reliable in
terms of the dates and when it's going to happen. But if you get
hired for a movie and they say, `We need you for two weeks,' that
can stretch to five weeks just with the natural flow of shooting
the film. I can't say I'm going to be gone next month and when the
month's ending, say: `They're going to need me another week and a
half. The show you were writing for two guys, you've got to scrap
that.' It would make the writers write two different shows. I
couldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
