<HEADER>
A0763 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BACH-MUSIC-$ADV25-NYT     06-21 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-MUSIC-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTTING THE BACH CHOIR DOWN TO SIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On this 250th anniversary of the death of Bach or in any other
year, there can be few musicological questions more pressing than
that of how the composer's music sounded when it was being
performed for the first time, week after week, under his direction
in St. Thomas' Church in Leipzig, Germany. Light is now being shed
on this subject by one of the leading practitioners of early music,
the English conductor Andrew Parrott, in performances, recordings
and a book, ``The Essential Bach Choir'' (University of Rochester
Press).
</P>
<P>
   Parrott takes up the story from the American scholar Joshua
Rifkin, who, nearly 20 years ago, caused a stir in the world of
early music by suggesting that Bach's B minor Mass, ``St. Matthew
Passion'' and cantatas were not the choral masterpieces everybody
had always taken them to be. They were still masterpieces, for
sure. What Rifkin was doubting was that they were intended to be
choral music as listeners then knew it.
</P>
<P>
   In Rifkin's view, what Bach meant by ``chorus'' was not a throng
of enthusiastic singers but rather a set of soloists. Since Bach's
choral movements generally have four vocal parts _ soprano, alto,
tenor and bass _ just four singers would be required to perform
them. In works that have two choirs, the number would be eight.
</P>
<P>
   This notion that the ``St. Matthew Passion,'' for instance,
might be sung by just eight singers was revolutionary when Rifkin
broached it at a conference in Boston in 1981, and the controversy
has rumbled on. Parrott, in his book, is out to end it. He includes
Rifkin's paper _ which, astonishingly, has never been published
complete before _ and adds the evidence of his own exhaustive
research to present a strong and fascinating case.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott's argument rests principally on the primary evidence:
the performance materials surviving from Bach's musical household,
produced by the composer's numerous offspring and equally numerous
apprentices. These young people had to copy, from Bach's score, the
parts that the instrumentalists and singers would need to read as
they played and sang. And it turns out that in virtually every
case, only one part exists for each line in a choir.
</P>
<P>
   If one wants to imagine that more than four singers were
involved _ or eight in works for double choir _ then one has to see
these singers as clustered together, perhaps three of them reading
from one part. This setup is unlikely, according to Parrott,
because the parts that Bach's children and assistants wrote out do
not consistently indicate changes from choral sections to solos, in
which the presumed second and third singers would have had to stop
singing. One might add that the parts, several of which are
reproduced in Parrott's book, appear too casual, fine and detailed
to have been read by more than one person.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting evidence includes pictorial representations of
musical performance from Bach's time, none of them showing singers
(or instrumentalists, for that matter) sharing copies. Parrott also
cites references to choral singing in various documents, most of
which suggest that choirs in Baroque Germany generally had one
singer for each part or, at most, two.
</P>
<P>
   But the most crucial document of all is one that comes to us
from the hand of Bach himself, the memorandum he lodged with the
Leipzig Town Council in 1730: what he called a ``brief yet highly
necessary outline of a properly constituted church musical
establishment, with some sober reflections on the decline of the
same.'' This, too, Parrott incorporates in his book complete, in
the original German and in translation.
</P>
<P>
   As director of music at St. Thomas' School, Bach was responsible
for the choirs of four Leipzig churches, and three of those choirs
had to be musically proficient, the fourth singing only chorales.
Each choir, he stipulates, ``must have at least three sopranos,
three altos, three tenors and as many basses.'' Four would be
better. But as he immediately explains, this was to provide for
illness: a common occurrence, ``as the prescriptions written by the
school doctor for the apothecary must show.''
</P>
<P>
   Bach was thus asking the city to provide for choirs of 12
singers (16 in his dreams), but only so that, barring epidemics,
there would always be enough to perform works with eight vocal
parts. What is not clear _ since Bach was writing for the
councilors of Leipzig, not for musicians nearly 300 years later _
is whether he would have expected all 12 singers to perform a piece
with four parts (the standard for the Sunday cantatas) at times
when the apothecary was not so busy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as he miserably concludes, he did not have that luxury.
In 1730, when he was writing, only 17 singers under his
jurisdiction were musically able, so the school could hardly have
done more than send a choir of four to each of the three churches
where elaborate music was performed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no reason for professional musicians now to
be constrained by the deteriorated conditions of musical Leipzig in
1730, and Parrott risks putting the music on a fast to imitate what
Bach considered starvation. The evidence of the parts and of other
contemporary documents, written and pictorial, is not entirely
conclusive: the pictures are too few; the documents (like Bach's
statement) had their own purposes. And it seems plausible that if
Bach had had what he wanted _ choirs of 12 or even 16 _ he would
have wanted everybody to sing, even in a four-part composition.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the important support for musical choices must come
not from the archives but from the sound. And the sound of
Parrott's performances _ here recently with the New York Collegium,
and on a Sony Classical CD with his own Taverner Consort and
Players in the ``Trauer-Ode'' and two motets _ is compelling proof
that his ideas work.
</P>
<P>
   Choirs of soloists balance and blend beautifully with a
period-style chamber orchestra. They sound well, even in a
relatively large church. Phrasing and texture can be lighter, the
effect, as Eric Van Tassel puts it in his liner notes for the
recording, ``more personal and, in a way, more human.''
</P>
<P>
   And at one point in the ``Trauer-Ode,'' as recorded here, the
advantage of the four-person choir becomes startling. The tenor
sings a short recitative, then he alone _ not clumped into a
faceless group _ leads his companions into the ensuing chorus. More
than all the arguments, the moment makes the case.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate that Parrott, in his book, should appeal not
to such musical value but instead to a merely reproductive
correctness, writing that his is ``the mode of performance which
... best reflects Bach's own practice.'' For one thing, if that
were to be the criterion, then Bach choirs would have to be all
male.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his reforming zeal is understandable. If, as he points
out, the great quartets of Haydn and Beethoven had always been
performed by string orchestras, performances by just four players
would be revelatory. So is his gentle, touching and musicianly
Bach.
</P>
<P>
   This is, to be sure, not the only way. Other conductors will go
on using choirs on the scale Bach might have hoped for, rather than
of the size he had. Most important of all, choirs of schools,
churches and amateur societies, through which most of us came to
feel the glory of Bach for the first time, will go on performing
the ``St. Matthew Passion'' with crowds of singers, the more the
merrier.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott, though, is vindicating a real alternative.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
