<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PART OF RUSSIA PROSPERS WITH NEW FREEDOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 25)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The late Nikita Khrushchev was shrewd
and bombastic, but he was not prescient about which type of
government would triumph in the lengthy communism-vs.-capitalism
conflict known as the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Khrushchev bluntly told the capitalist nations:
``Whether you like it or not, history is on our side. We will bury
you.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years thereafter, that declaration represented the
Soviet Union's goal in its ideological and political dispute with
the United States and its democratic partners. In 1962 Khrushchev
tried and failed to place nuclear missiles in Cuba as a threat to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   History was not on the side of the communists. They did not bury
us. Instead, communism _ with help from America and its allies _
buried itself.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to this majestic city, founded by Peter the Great in
1703 as his window on the West, confirms that at least part of
Russia is prospering in the wake of dramatic changes initiated more
than a decade ago by Mikhail Gorbachev and continued by Boris
Yeltsin. Many of the barriers that once inhibited freedom of
movement and choice have been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders no longer are foisted on the people by a
ruling oligarchy. They are elected by the people.
</P>
<P>
   Ships fill St. Petersburg's harbor. Tourists jam the Hermitage,
with its magnificent art collection running the gamut from
Rembrandt to Picasso. Visitors from the West fill the city's ballet
theater, restaurants and boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity of wealth seen on a visit to the enormous, elegant
palaces that once housed high-living Russian czars tends to explain
why Russia, with millions of poor people, was ripe for revolution
in 1917 when the Bolsheviks took over.
</P>
<P>
   What is not well explained is why the revolutionaries felt it
necessary to kill Czar Nicholas II and his family that year and
place tight controls on freedoms that were enjoyed in other
nations.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Petersburg, only memories remain of the terrible German
siege of 900 days during World War II when the city was called
Leningrad after V.I. Lenin, the father of the Soviet Union and the
fanatical leader of the communist movement. The siege, which ran
from 1941 to 1944, failed when the frigid Russian winter and the
Red Army finally proved too much for the invading Germans. But it
is commemorated in a park where 900 trees have been planted.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings that were destroyed during that tragic period have
been rebuilt, and St. Petersburg abounds in architectural gems.
Russia, which continues to have many problems, is making strides
that were not possible in the days of absolute communist control.
</P>
<P>
   What we see in Russia and its neighbors that border the English
Channel, the North Sea and the Baltic Sea is that change is an
indispensable part of life. Nothing lasts forever.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Le Havre, France's second largest port, was
decimated by German and allied bombs during World War II. Local
citizens recall that only one building was left standing and that
80,000 people were homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Le Havre is a vigorous port city that shows no signs of
the disaster that befell it more than a half century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some distance down the Normandy coastline from Le Havre,
visitors return to the beaches where the allies invaded France in
June, 1944. It was there that the blood of heroes left its
indelible mark on history. It was there that the mighty military
offensive that ended with the defeat of Adolf Hitler's Germany
began.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors still marvel at Western Europe's dramatic rebirth in
the wake of history's most devastating war. The rejuvenation began
with the U.S. Marshall Plan in the late 1940s. At that time,
America announced its readiness to provide substantial financial
aid to the countries suffering great destruction if they would
determine their needs and work together. They did exactly that and
the results were spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   The United States offered to include its wartime ally, the
Soviet Union, in the Marshall Plan, but dictator Josef Stalin
rejected the offer and persuaded Soviet satellites to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   That was a colossal mistake. Had the Soviet Union participated,
the world would have been a very different place.
</P>
<P>
   Russia now is striving to catch up with America and her allies,
but despite its dramatic improvement in recent years, it has a long
way to go.
</P>
<P>
   The strides that now are so evident in St. Petersburg could have
been taken decades ago. That is a part of history that Khrushchev
failed to understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
