<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PERRY0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TBy Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lt. Gov. Rick Perry and Attorney General John
Cornyn rallied Wednesday to defend the state's ``honor'' and the
death penalty sentence for convicted murderer Gary Graham, who is
scheduled to be executed today for a 1981 Houston murder he says he
did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   Their joint press conference at the Capitol was a response to
calls from high-profile celebrities such as the Rev. Jesse Jackson
and Bianca Jagger of Amnesty International to postpone Graham's
execution, as well as mounting national criticism of the state's
use of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Texas is being showcased by some for political
reasons as not such a fine place,'' Perry complained. ``I will
continue to stand up for this state. I will continue to defend
Texas' honor in every way that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and Cornyn were joined by state Rep. Terry Keel, R-Austin,
a former Travis County sheriff, and former state Rep. Allen
Hightower, a Democrat who spent 12 years as chairman of the House
Corrections Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, like Perry, said he was not speaking up on behalf of
Gov. George W. Bush, whose presidential campaign has attracted new
and often critical attention to the state's use of the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally felt it was important for us to be able to
explain, again, what type of super due process that criminal
defendants are entitled to and in fact receive _ and in fact Mr.
Graham has received _ in reviewing their cases,'' Cornyn said of
Texas death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn criticized the ``confusion'' and ``disinformation'' that
he said were ``based on political agendas by people outside of the
state to make it look like the Texas system is not fair. The Texas
criminal justice system is fair _ and Mr. Graham did get a fair
trial and has gotten fair review'' by courts of appeal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general also defended the state's efforts to uphold
the conviction of Calvin Burdine, who has complained that his
lawyer slept through long stretches of the 1984 Harris County trial
that ended with him convicted and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not condone lawyers sleeping through trial, we do not
condone it,'' Cornyn said, explaining his office's defense of the
conviction of Calvin Burdine. But the state's position is that the
defendant has the burden to show that a new trial might result in a
different verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
