<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-GENOME (Undated) _ After months of fitful negotiation
that seemed to flame out in a final angry exchange in February, the
two sides racing to sequence the DNA of human cells have contrived
a last-minute truce. The first element of the suddenly resurrected
pact will be a joint announcement next week of the effective
completion of the genome. Although it is too late for collaboration
and a pooling of DNA sequencing efforts, the truce will include
agreement for the competitors to publish their genome findings in
the same issue of a scientific journal, though in separate
articles. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-WATER (Washington) _ The Mars Global Surveyor has
radioed data to Earth suggesting there is surface water on the Red
Planet, which could boost the possibility of finding evidence of
life, experts say. (Summary from wires) By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MACBETH-THEATER-REVIEW (New Haven, Conn.) _ Ben Brantley reviews
the Royal Shakespeare Company's new production of ``Macbeth,''
which runs through Sunday at the Long Wharf Theater here.
</P>
</TEXT>
