<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LASTIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHBISHOP ALAN DE LASTIC, 70, CHRISTIAN LEADER IN INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   India's most prominent Christian leader, Alan de Lastic, the
Roman Catholic archbishop of Delhi, was killed Tuesday night in a
car crash in Poland, where he had been been praying at Krakow's
shrine to the Black Madonna following a working visit to Rome. He
was 70.
</P>
<P>
   De Lastic's death deals a blow not only to India's Christian
minority, now under attack by Hindu militants, but also to Indian
human rights organizations of all faiths. An outspoken defender of
Christian rights in a Hindu-majority nation, he was president of
the Catholic Bishops Conference of India, a position that lent
weight to his human rights activities at a time when Indian
churches are being destroyed by mobs and priests and nuns have been
murdered in several Indian states.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop was the founder of the United Christian Forum for
Human Rights. On Wednesday, the forum's convenor, John Dayal, said
in a telephone interview from New Delhi that de Lastic was ``the
voice of the Christian community and a natural leader of the entire
human rights movement in India.''
</P>
<P>
   In April in New York, Indians in the United States presented to
the archbishop and Dayal, a writer, the first Graham Staines
International Award for Human Rights and Communal Harmony, named
for an Australian missionary doctor who was burned to death in his
car with his two young sons last year in the eastern Indian state
of Orissa. A Hindu militant has been charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Christians account for only 2.5 percent of India's 1 billion
people, but have played a leading part in providing health and
education services that many other Indians consider superior to
those supplied by the government. Christianity, which was first
brought to India from the Middle East in the 1st century and was
later bolstered by Western missionaries who often converted
disadvantaged Hindu outcastes, has long been an integral part of
Indian life.
</P>
<P>
   Religion, however, has always been close to the surface of
politics in India, a constitutionally secular nation _ most often
where Muslims are concerned. In recent years, with a Hindu
nationalist-led government in power in New Delhi, militant Hindu
organizations that had been focusing mainly on Muslim targets also
began a campaign against Christin conversions by Indian priests,
and have introduced ``re-conversion'' ceremonies carried out with
varying degrees of intimidation, Indian Christians say.
</P>
<P>
   De Lastic had lately been discussing the new problems faced by
Christians with Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, a moderate
leader among Hindu politicians. Wednesday in New Delhi, after he
heard of the archbishop's death, Vajpayee called a meeting of
Christian church leaders The prime minister called de Lastic ``a
man of God who had dedicated his life to the service of
humankind.''
</P>
<P>
   De Lastic's readiness to publicly protest attacks by Hindus
wherever they occurred drew some criticism from non-Catholic
Christian groups in India.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangalore, professor K.E. Eapen, a lay leader of the Mar
Thoma church, India's oldest Christian community, said in a
telephone interview Wednesday that many members of his church were
concerned that the archbishop's strident defense of Christian
conversions may have played into the hands of Hindu militants. When
Pope John Paul II visited India last November, he added fuel to the
controversy by also advocating conversions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0622-COX     06-21 1784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Oil on the political fire
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OIL ON THE POLITICAL FIRE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush voiced support today for the Federal Trade
Commission's probe of soaring gasoline prices, but he put most of
the blame on the White House's failure to convince foreign crude
producers to ``open the spigots.'' In Los Angeles, Bush said, ``I
do think it's fair to have the FTC investigate,'' adding that the
results would be ``healthy.'' Bush didn't accuse the Clinton
administration or Al Gore of demagoguing the issue by launching the
probe, but the former Texas oilman did insist that it's the
administration's job to pressure the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Nations to increase oil output.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO YOU CALL A NON-ENDORSING ENDORSEMENT?
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring his brawny union's disenchantment with Al Gore,
Teamsters chief James P. Hoffa will join Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader in Los Angeles on Thursday to make a ``special
statement ... concerning the 2000 presidential election.'' A
Teamsters spokesman said Hoffa doesn't plan at that time to endorse
Nader. The United Auto Workers has hinted it also may support Nader
for his opposition to ``corporate globalization.'' The Teamsters
and UAW pointedly abstained last October when the AFL-CIO voted to
give Gore an early endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   THE TRUTH, TEXAS-TOAST STYLE
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has issued a warning to George W. Bush: ``The Texas
Truth Squad is coming.'' The group of workers from Texas will
appear at labor-sponsored meetings around the country to try to
sully the governor's reputation by talking about problems in Texas
that include education, health care and the treatment of farm
workers. The union leaflet says the truth squad will note that
Texas ranks the lowest among all states in the percentage of people
who have health insurance and near the bottom in College Board
scores. The first event is to be held in Philadelphia on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   PLOWING FERTILE GROUND
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore went to Iowa today and proposed exempting more family
farms and small businesses from estate taxes. While attempting to
carve out his own piece of a Republican campaign issue, Democrats
warn that eliminating the tax would blow a hole in the budget and
mainly benefit the rich. Instead, Gore proposed increasing the
exemption for small businesses and farmers _ currently up to $2.6
million _ to $5 million, meaning, he said, that 90 percent of the
nation's farmers would not owe estate taxes. Gore: ``Some on
Capitol Hill believe we should completely repeal the estate tax and
give a massive tax break to the wealthiest Americans. They want to
give away the store to those who already own the shopping center.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS AND QUAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Political protesters are saying they won't foment a repeat of
violence that erupted after the Los Angeles Lakers won the NBA
title the other night, but they fear police may use the riot as a
pretext to bully them away from the Democratic convention. Shawn
McDougal of the American Friends Service Committee, a Quaker social
service movement, and other planners promise boisterous and
disruptive rallies, but maintain their groups won't try to hurt
anyone or destroy property. And the LAPD insists it won't impede
the protests as long as the activists remain peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-BUDGET CAMPAIGN COVERAGE . . .
</P>
<P>
   ABC News, citing cost concerns, has pulled out of a pool
arrangement where three networks had shared camera coverage of
George W. Bush and Al Gore. ABC had joined with CBS and Fox News
Channel to share camera coverage of the campaign. But with interest
in the candidates at an ebb now and relatively few public
appearances, ABC found it wasn't worth the expense, said
spokeswoman Su-Lin Nichols. ABC is using its own cameras to cover
some events and relying on affiliates for others, she said. The
network currently has just one producer, without a correspondent or
camera crew, traveling full-time with each candidate. CBS and NBC
have yet to announce their plans, but are expected to scale back,
also.
</P>
<P>
   . . . WITH A WAY TO STAY IN THE GAME . . .
</P>
<P>
   ABC has invited Al Gore and George W. Bush to participate in a
one-on-one televised conversation shortly after Labor Day. The
network said it wanted as little participation as possible from a
moderator so the event doesn't look like a formal debate. So far,
the two candidates have agreed only to three fall debates sponsored
by the Commission on Presidential Debates. But, ``if you can have
them talk to each other directly, it will become less adversarial
and less debate-like,'' said ABC News president David Westin.
Campaigns keep such tight control on all aspects of personal
appearances that Westin's idea might be a tough sell, said ABC
anchor Peter Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND STILL KEEP MONDAY NIGHT SAFE FOR FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   ABC, in its dialing down of convention coverage in prime time,
doesn't plan to pre-empt two preseason NFL games. The network says
it will go ahead with the San Francisco 49ers-New England Patriots
on the Republicans' opening night, July 31, and Los Angeles
Rams-Tennessee Titans on the Democrats' opening night, July 14. But
news division chief David Westin says they'll provide coverage
during halftime. What's that come to, 10 minutes worth?
</P>
<P>
   BUT YOU KNOW HOW CREATIVE ACCOUNTING CAN BE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush broke through the $90 million fund-raising mark
last month. Bush, reported having $7.1 million in his campaign
account at the end of May, has raised $650,000 so far this month,
and has another fund-raiser Friday in Alabama. Al Gore reported a
bank balance of $8.3 million, and expects an additional $1.3
million in federal matching funds. After the national conventions,
each candidate will receive $67.6 million in federal funds for the
general election and cannot raise any more money except to cover
legal and accounting costs.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIST CHALLENGING BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   John Hagelin, the quantum physicist who founded the Natural Law
Party, is challenging Pat Buchanan for the Reform Party's
presidential nomination and the right to spend the party's $12.6
million in federal campaign money. In addition to running as the
Natural Law nominee, Hagelin said he's qualified to have his name
placed on Reform Party's mail ballot. Ever since Buchanan left the
Republican Party last year, he has been taking over the Reform
Party, winning the biggest share of delegates. But a two-thirds
majority at the national convention can overturn the mail-in voting
results.
</P>
<P>
   ZEROING IN ON MINORITIES . . .
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials announced the start of a radio and TV
ad campaign intended to appeal specifically to African-American and
Hispanic voters. Al Gore's health care proposals, including a
patients' bill of rights plan, are the focus of ads intended for
African-Americans. The ads for Hispanic voters, with Gore speaking
Spanish, touch on education and preserving Social Security. The
African-American spots will be broadcast in 17 states, while the
ads for Hispanics will air only in Florida, Illinois, New Mexico
and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND SHOWING UP AT CONVENTIONS
</P>
<P>
   With the bruising battle for Hispanic voters heating up, Al Gore
and George W. Bush both are scheduled to address Hispanics at
national conventions over the next two weeks: the League of United
Latin American Citizens, in Washington, next week, and the National
Council of La Raza, in San Diego, over the July 4th holiday.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH ISSUE OVERSHADOWS EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Controversy over Texas' death penalty stalked George W. Bush as
he tried to court California voters with a plan to spend $2.3
billion in federal money to boost students' math and science
scores. In Cupertino, Bush refused to take a question about Gary
Graham, the Texas convict scheduled for lethal injection Thursday,
then skipped a planned news conference. Under Texas' weak-governor
system, Bush has no power to spare Graham's life unless the state
Board of Pardons and Paroles recommends it. But in Los Angeles
today, he defended his state's legal system as ``fair and just''
and said there's no need for a moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD THING HE LIKES TO TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore broke off his much-interrupted ``prosperity tour'' in
Kentucky to hasten back to Washington for a Senate vote on hate
crimes, but his potential tie-breaking vote as president of the
Senate wasn't needed. The legislation to expand the hate-crimes law
passed 57-42. It was the fifth time this year that Gore seized upon
close calls in the Senate to underscore his position on key issues
that divide him with George W. Bush. And it was the fifth time his
vote wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOYS OF SUMMIT
</P>
<P>
   Whether by grace or by happenstance, the two contenders for
retiring Sen. Frank Lautenberg's seat are practically neighbors on
the crest of the Watchung Mountains in central New Jersey, and both
are regarded as local boys. Jon Corzine, the multimillionaire bond
trader and liberal Democrat, lives in the rich north side of
Summit, while Rep. Bob Franks, the journeyman moderate who founded
the Summit High School Young Republicans while he was in school,
now has a home in a kind of suburb of a suburb at Berkeley Heights,
the next town over. Their proximity is both a source of local pride
and a lesson in the evolving politics of New Jersey, a state that
grows more suburban by the year and whose politics seem to be
following the people out of old urban traditions into something
new.
</P>
<P>
   THE CASE AGAINST A DEMOCRATIC SENATOR
</P>
<P>
   As Al Gore scrutinizes at least six senators as possible running
mates, the Democratic Party is facing a quandary, because picking a
senator could undermine efforts to regain control of the Senate.
All six of the most frequently mentioned Senate prospects _ John
Kerry of Massachusetts, Bob Graham of Florida, Richard Durbin of
Illinois, Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Dianne Feinstein of
California and Evan Bayh of Indiana _ hold seats that probably
would be filled by a Republican, either through appointment or a
later special election. ``There would have to be an incredibly
compelling reason to pick one particular senator to punt away a
Senate seat,'' said Charles Cook, editor of the Cook Political
Report and an authority on Senate races.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
