<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dell Planning to Offer Digital Audio Receiver
</P>
<P>
   Making its first foray into consumer electronics _ but still
tethered to the personal computer _ the Dell Computer Corp. said
Wednesday that it was preparing to introduce a PC-based digital
audio receiver that would allow MP3 and WMA music files stored on a
personal computer to be played through a home stereo system or in
any room of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The new Dell receiver, which is expected to go on sale at
www.gigabuys.com in August for $249 (or $199 when bought with a
Dell Dimension computer), is a small, radio-style box that uses an
HPNA (Home Phoneline Networking Alliance) version 2.0 or Ethernet
network to tap into the digital music files stored on a personal
computer. An HPNA 2.0 network card for the PC costs between $50 and
$70, depending on the manufacturer. It allows the digital audio
receiver to pull MP3 songs and playlists, managed by either Music
Match or Real Audio software, into the receiver through a home's
existing phone jacks. The receiver itself can be plugged into the
home stereo's RCA jack to fill the house with music, or it can be
set up with an optional $99 set of Acoustic Research speakers to
bring the PC music to any room where music is wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's new audio appliance shares the same basic design as S3
Inc.'s Rio Digital Audio Receiver, which was demonstrated last
month, but unlike the Rio, the Dell has a retro-style radio control
panel. The Rio music appliance will be sold in consumer electronics
and computer retail stores later this summer for $299.95, which
includes the receiver, an HPNA 2.0 network card, two phone cords
and an RCA cable.
</P>
<P>
   Babel Expansion
</P>
<P>
   Babel Fish, the popular computer-based translator owned by
AltaVista, is expanding the number of languages it offers. In
addition to the original five language pairs (all of which include
English), users of Babel Fish (babelfish.altavista.com) can now
translate Russian to English, French to German and German to
French. Babel Fish has added World Keyboard, which can write with
the native characters of six languages, including Cyrillic letters.
</P>
<P>
   A Site Offers to Send E-Mail With Complaints or Praise
</P>
<P>
   Wiley Brooks was frustrated when he wanted to complain to a
restaurant chain by e-mail about an undercooked hamburger. ``It
wasn't easy to get a valid e-mail address,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of that frustration has come TellThemNow.com
(www.tellthemnow.com), a Web site that Brooks said would make it
easier to send electronic complaints or compliments to corporate
leaders, politicians, journalists and celebrities. TellThemNow.com
is similar to some other Web sites, like the recently opened
eComplaints (www.ecomplaints.com).
</P>
<P>
   Brooks hopes that his service will increase the odds that the
e-mail messages will actually be read. At the heart of the service
is a directory of about 600,000 e-mail addresses. Nine employees
compiled the list by scanning Web sites with special software, by
purchasing directories and by using, as Brooks put it, ``the
old-fashioned way: making phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Addresses can be found by using either the site's search engine
or directories organized by category.
</P>
<P>
   Once a user finds an address, he or she can compose a message on
a form at the site. Before sending off the note, the user must
assign it to one of five categories, from ``highly positive'' to
``highly negative.''
</P>
<P>
   TellThemNow holds all the messages until late in the evening,
when the day's messages for each recipient are bundled. The site
adds a breakdown _ by percentage and number _ of the tone of the
messages in the package, based on the users' self-assigned
rankings. The bulk packaging, and an attached mini-opinion poll,
give messages ``a little more voice'' than if they had arrived
singly, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   During the first month and a half of the site's operation,
Brooks said, politicians have tended to receive an even number of
positive and negative messages.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, about 70 percent of celebrity messages are ``very
positive,'' leading Brooks to speculate that they are fan mail. He
added that the company did not examine the contents of any message.
</P>
<P>
   But what are the odds that Britney Spears will actually read
your e-mail note if it is sent through TellThemNow?
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' makes a modest claim: ``For the most part, it would be
about the same as if you sent a snail-mail letter and you have the
actual, correct address.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Quite as High as an Elephant's Eye
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that on a hot July day in a Midwestern
cornfield, you can hear the corn growing. Whether or not that is
true, Web surfers can watch corn as it grows on an Iowa farm.
</P>
<P>
   CornCam presents fresh images every 15 minutes from a cornfield
near Prairieburg, Iowa (www.IowaFarmer.com/corncam/corn.html).
Viewers can check regularly to see how much the crop has grown
since it was planted in late April. (It is not quite as high as an
elephant's eye.)
</P>
<P>
   The site includes information about the field (it was planted on
April 30 without tilling, a method that conserves soil) and links
to many other corn sites, including one dedicated to the Corn
Palace in Mitchell, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   CornCam is operated by Iowa Farmer Today, a weekly newspaper,
which is seeking sponsors for a SoyBeanCam.
</P>
<P>
   No word on whether a PaintDryCam is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
