<HEADLINE>
YOU, TOO, CAN ROCK ON AT SEATTLE'S NEW HANDS-ON MUSIC MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Fricke doesn't want people to be awed when they walk into
Experience Music Project (EMP), the massive new celebration of rock
'n' roll opening in Seattle this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the building itself is amazing: A fluid, brightly colored,
curving space that suggests smashed electric guitars, designed by
Frank Gehry, renowned for the Guggenheim Museum in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there are thousands of artifacts, from a suit worn by
Notorious B.I.G. to Eric Clapton's famous ``Brownie'' guitar to the
world's largest collection of Jimi Hendrix memorabilia, all brought
to you via Microsoft co-founder, multibillionaire Hendrix fanatic
and amateur guitarist Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   But Fricke, one of EMP's senior curators, says he's not going
for jaw-dropping glitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anyone to think, `I could never do that.''' he
says. ``We're celebrating creativity in American popular music, and
the whole idea is creating a place to celebrate music and the
people who make it and all that surrounds it. We hope the response
will be, `That's amazing _ I want to go buy a guitar and learn to
play.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is because the Experience Music Project is far more
interactive than Cleveland's Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. Opening to
the public Friday with a weekend orgy of music that includes shows
by Metallica, Dr. Dre, Patti Smith, Alanis Morissette and James
Brown, EMP is all about taking the history of American pop music
out from behind the glass and thrusting it into the hands of its
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Paul Allen is behind this and he comes from a
technology background, we were pushed to include true interactive
technology from the ground up, with everything we were doing,''
Fricke says.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be given a hand-held computer and headphones,
which will provide information during a museum tour and give access
to custom audio clips at different stops.
</P>
<P>
   If you stop at the ``Is This the First Rock 'n' Roll Record?''
exhibit, for example, you can punch in a video of R&AMP;B legend Big
Jay McNeely talking about his music and playing a song. If you are
interested in a particular piece in this exhibit, such as his
saxophone, you can punch in a number and see McNeely talking about
the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of EMP's interactive mission is the Sound Lab. In
the Jam-O-Drum area, visitors can beat rhythms on a giant drum head
with psychedelic graphics lighting up the room. On Stage re-creates
the feeling of being onstage at a rock concert; visitors can play
guitar, bass, drums and keyboards, sing with the help of a
TelePrompTer and be cheered on by a virtual audience.
</P>
<P>
   There also are the Music Instrument Platforms, which are set up
with guitar, bass, drums and keyboards. A novice musician can, in a
few minutes, learn to play, for example, ``Louie Louie.'' More
proficient players can learn more difficult songs. If you go with
friends, all of you can play along _ with help along the way. There
are three rooms set aside just for improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for hip-hop fans _ visitors can be shown how to
scratch on turntables. And guests can go back home and take
interactive guitar instruction online via www.emplive.com: Every
weekday a famous guitar lick is posted, with instructions about how
to play it.
</P>
<P>
   On Mondays, visitors can participate in a live guitar lesson
using the licks from the previous week. The Web site also features
a peek at three of the museum's exhibit areas (Northwest Passage,
Guitar Gallery and Jimi Hendrix) and access to museum archives.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits at Experience Music Project are different from the
Rock Hall. In Cleveland, says Fricke, exhibits are based on
personalities, often people inducted into the hall. In Seattle,
they are based on ``a story line and building around it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is This the First Rock 'n' Roll Record?'' area, he says, is
based on the years 1938-1956, when blues, country, gospel and R&AMP;B
came together to make protean rock. One item is an upright bass
used by Fred Maddox of the Maddox Brothers and Rose, who merged
hillbilly and boogie in the late '40s and early '50s; Fred's
slapping style on the bass was a direct antecedent of Bill Black's
bass style on early Elvis records. Which is why Fricke tracked down
the bass.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not to say that EMP is in competition with the Rock
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all anxious to have a spirit of partnership,''
says Bob Santelli, who is leaving the Rock Hall to become EMP's
deputy director of public programs. ``I think both institutions
take different paths to get to the same destination. The Hall
preserves and celebrates the history of the music, and EMP is there
to celebrate the creativity that goes into the music.''
</P>
<P>
   They will be trading artifacts back and forth; both will send
people on a travel program to various places around the country
where musical history was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we know each other's missions,'' Santelli says.
``People make pilgrimages to the Rock Hall _ I want that to happen
at EMP, because what you can experience there is like nothing else
happening in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Experience Music Project
</P>
<P>
   Summer hours (Memorial Day through Labor Day) are 9 a.m.-11 p.m.
Winter hours (the rest of the year) are 10 a.m.-6 p.m.
Sunday-Thursday and 10 a.m.-11 p.m. Friday and Saturday at Fifth
and Harrison in downtown Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $19.95 for adults 18 to 64; $15.95 for seniors 65 and
older with an ID, students 13 to 17 with an ID and members of the
military with an ID; $14.95 for children 7-12; and free for
children 6 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (206) 770-2700 or www.emplive.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
