<SLUG> BC-NEWMONT-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWMONT MINING TO ACQUIRE BATTLE MOUNTAIN GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH RUBENSTEIN   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newmont Mining (NEM:NYSE) announced Wednesday that it will
acquire Battle Mountain Gold (BMG:NYSE), consolidating both
companies' strategic land positions in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Newmont will exchange 0.105 share for each of Battle Mountain's
230 million shares in a deal the companies expect to be completed
this fall. The companies predicted that the merger will generate
savings of about $30 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Newmont, based in Denver, plans to develop and drill on Battle
Mountain's land in Phoenix, located within 30 miles of Newmont's
Lone Tree complex in Nevada. The property had year-end reserves of
5.7 million ounces of gold and 430 million pounds of copper
--reserves Newmont believes, along with the reserves at Battle
Mountain's adjacent holdings, could increase significantly. Newmont
will also acquire property in Canada, Bolivia and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a thorough review of the Phoenix project, which is the
prime attraction for us, we concur with Battle Mountain Gold's
management that it is one of the best undeveloped gold properties
in North America,'' Ronald C. Cambre, Newmont's chairman and chief
executive officer, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Newmont expects to save $25 million to $30 million by using in
Phoenix surplus mining equipment from the Mesquite mine in
California and Mule Canyon in Nevada, where deposits are being
mined out. It plans to eliminate smelting costs, reduce
transportation charges and increase recovery rates for gold and
copper by processing gold and copper concentrate from Phoonix
through its Lone Tree autoclave.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Houston, Battle Mountain was formed as a spinoff of
Pennzoil in 1985 and merged with Hemlo Gold Mines in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
