<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIST OF `SURVIVOR' WANNABES TOSSED BUT NOT FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a show like ``Survivor'' succeeds on a mainstream network,
the copycats descend like moths to a bright idea. Remember all the
game shows that surfaced and quickly withered after ``Who Wants To
Be a Millionaire'' proved that Americans would watch a prime-time
game show?
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of ``Survivor,'' there'll be plenty more voyeuristic
``reality'' programming, which, if anything, proves MTV knew what
it was doing by putting ``The Real World'' and ``Road Rules'' on
about 30 times a day.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the sincerely flattering imitation will make it
to air. Strange as it seems, programming executives are a choosy
lot, and from a Dumpster beneath a burned-out streetlight in
Burbank come these recently discarded plans to combat _ with
similar-sounding knock-offs _ the unexpected success of CBS's
summertime hit. Appearing after each working title is the show's
premise and the apparent reason the idea was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serve Ivar's.'' Premise: Sixteen patrons, marooned inside a
Seattle seafood restaurant, are forced to eat fried clams for three
months. Reason rejected: Risk of repeated exposure to tartar sauce
has never been completely studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subscriber.'' Premise: Sixteen women must sign up for a year
of O, the Oprah Magazine, and count the total number of references
to Ms. Winfrey. Reason rejected: Nobody can count that high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imbiber.'' Premise: Sixteen people living on a traffic island
in St. Louis must drink a six-pack a day without going to the
bathroom. Champion holder of water wins a kidney transplant or cash
equivalent. Reason rejected: Fluctuating price of kidneys on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godiva.'' Premise: Sixteen partially naked women race 16
completely naked horses on a South Seas beach. Winner gets a
lifetime assortment of pricey chocolates. Reason rejected:
Chocolate activists protest mistreatment of bon-bons in tropical
heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contriver.'' Premise: Sixteen writers are locked in a room and
forced to come up with fresh, new ideas for a TV sitcom. First to
suggest Betty White as the wacky neighbor becomes network
president. Reason rejected: No current openings at the networks.
(Concept could be revived for midseason schedule, though.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Fiber.'' Premise: Sixteen contestants in a Winnebago test
the All Raisin Bran Diet for 16 weeks. Reason rejected: Government
scientists fear lethal gas buildup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low Fiver.'' Premise: Sixteen executives, stuck in a board
room with nothing but a Power Point presentation on sexual
harassment, must refrain from high-fiving their colleagues when the
moderator tells sexist jokes. Reason rejected: Moderator gets
better-paying job as host of ``The Man Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saab/Volvo.'' Premise: Sixteen people spend a winter rotating
the tires of well-to-do Swedes. Fastest tire changer wins a trip to
Norway. Reason rejected: Swedes change their own tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revive Her.'' Premise: Sixteen college boys spend spring break
in Hawaii practicing CPR on former ``Baywatch'' babes. Reason
rejected: Too many contestants injured during chest-compression
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``MacGyver.'' Premise: Government agent must rescue 16 Americans
from an island prison using nothing but a toothpick, a used teabag
and some dental floss. Reason rejected: Too implausible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
