<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-KDLANG22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lang's latest frolicks with groovy melodies
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pasty-skinned Canadian K.D. Lang is the last person you would
expect to be frolicking in the sunny sun of Southern California.
But on this new CD, she has raised the Venetian blinds, tacked up
some flower power posters on the wall and tossed the gloom and
melancholy of her recent works out the picture window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Invincible Summer'' finds Lang in the role of a love-struck,
junior high ingenue, circa 1967. These 11 tunes are lifted straight
from the groovy, innocent days when Burt Bacharach, the Turtles and
the Mamas &AMP; Papas defined the sounds of summer _ breezy melodies,
Herb Alpert horns, bah-bah-bah background vocals, Jimmy Webb
strings. Like Shelby Lynne, who recently resurrected the Memphis
soul sounds of that often-dismissed era, Lang has mined the best
elements of the early days of hippie pop/rock, before the harder
edges of FM radio strip-mined the legitimacy out of jukebox music.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the arrangements draw from the kind of sweetly
innocent, piano/horn melodies that sent America seeking the way to
San Jose, Lang infuses the material with contemporary touches, such
as dribblings of techno keyboard beeps and harmonies that stray
beyond the three chords of most let's-grow-bangs music. On tracks
such as ``When We Collide,'' she dips into the orchestral
experimentation of the Beatles at their most excessive ``Day in the
Life'' studio explorations. ``Only Love'' is an electronic version
of the James Bond theme, ``You Only Live Twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely, Lang sounds like the mood singer of her ``Constant
Craving'' era, weaving hypnotic vocals over the period music like
someone aimlessly drifting on a bright, plastic pool float. It's
fresh in a remotely nostalgic kind of way, entrenching Lang in her
mid-career as Sade for the hip.
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   `Invincible Summer'
</P>
<P>
   K.D. Lang. Warner Bros. 11 tracks. Our critic's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on K.D. Lang: www.kdlang.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
