<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL22-COX     06-21 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courage brings exciting cinema out of closet
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Gay Pride Week in Atlanta, making it a good time to reflect
on how far gay and lesbian cinema has come. These days, some of the
most exciting work in movies has a gay/lesbian theme; some of the
most honored work, too. Gender issues were central to Hilary
Swank's Oscar-winning portrayal in ``Boys Don't Cry.'' In fact, gay
or lesbian characters have become so, well, ``safe'' that they can
be the center of a TV sitcom (``Will &AMP; Grace''). But it wasn't
always that way. Here are a few titles _ some dated, some not _
made back when it took some guts to be out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Parting Glances'' (1986): Slight but oh-so-right. Filmmaker
Bill Sherwood takes his characters' sexual orientation as a given,
something you didn't see much of in the mid-'80s. The film's
cute-couple-in-Manhattan opening could kick off a dozen romantic
comedies. The difference is that this cute couple is Robert (John
Bolger) and Michael (Richard Ganoung). The picture centers on
Robert's last night in town; he's about to take a job overseas and
leave Michael, his live-in lover of six years. Most of their last
24 hours together are spent at a farewell party that has down cold
one corner of the gay scene at that time _ from the cover-up
marriages to an aging queen's come-on. This was, alas, Sherwood's
only movie; he died of AIDS in 1990. But he had an eye for talent.
The picture's most blazing presence is a young Steve Buscemi, as an
AIDS patient whose body may be breaking down, but whose mind is
still sharp, rude and very funny.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Prick Up Your Ears'' (1987): An enthralling bio-pic of the
naughty-boy wonder, playwright Joe Orton, whose thumb-nosing farces
(``Loot,'' among others) made him the toast of swinging London. He
was murdered in 1967 by his longtime lover, Kenneth Halliwell, who
then committed suicide. Based on John Lahr's biography of the same
name, Stephen Frears' film jumps around chronologically, with a
postmortem framework provided by Lahr's (Wallace Shawn) efforts to
figure out this lord of misrule. Orton truly believed that a day
without sex with a total stranger was like a day without ... well,
you get the idea. The movie is somewhat flawed as psychodrama, but
it's a tremendous actor's showcase. And no wonder. Gary Oldman
plays Orton with charisma to burn and Alfred Molina is poor,
unhappy Halliwell.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Boys in the Band'' (1970): Viewed today, this is either
campy or appalling (or maybe both), depending on your mood. But
remember that when it was released 30 years ago, it was the first
major Hollywood film entirely out front (so to speak) about
homosexuality. Based on a play by Matt Crowley and directed by
William Friedkin (yes, ``The Exorcist'' guy), the movie takes place
at a birthday party given by Kenneth Nelson (who once starred in
``The Fantastiks''). There's plenty of swishy behavior and bitchy,
back-biting humor, but at heart the film is a rather touchingly
dated ``we're just like you!'' plea for tolerance. Again, it looks
like a period piece now, as embarrassing in some ways as
African-American stereotypes from pre-'60s Hollywood. But in 1970,
it took courage to get it made.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Celluloid Closet'' (1995): A not-to-be missed outing in
every sense of the word. Narrated by Lily Tomlin, this amusing and
illuminating documentary examines images of lesbians and gays in
movies for the past 100 years. Based on Vito Russo's book, it's
pretty much essential viewing _ an amazing prism through which to
view both cinema and society.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on this topic:
www.time.com/time/magazine/1998
</P>
<P>
   /dom/980824/thearts.cinema.objects18.html
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
