<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-TOPSY-TURVY22-C     06-21 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-TOPSY-TURVY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The rejuvenation of Gilbert and Sullivan
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A love of the theater can help you appreciate Mike Leigh's
meticulously detailed valentine to 19th-century performers. At
first glance, the film seems to be a startling departure from
Leigh's usual kitchen-sink realism (``Naked,'' ``Secrets &AMP; Lies'').
But it's not really. Despite the period costumes and Victorian
furniture, the writer-director is continuing to do what he does
best: document everyday moments and present a detailed slice of
life.
</P>
<P>
   This slice just happens to be set 100 years ago, populated with
historical characters instead of fictional: librettist-director
William Gilbert (Jim Broadbent) and composer Arthur Sullivan (Allan
Corduner). Covering only a tiny portion of their career,
``Topsy-Turvy'' focuses on the rejuvenation of the men's
partnership when Gilbert, inspired by a Japanese expo, comes up
with the idea for ``The Mikado.''
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, Leigh shows us that the blissful upside-down worlds
Gilbert and Sullivan created were a place that everyone _ including
the artists involved _ could escape to as a way to forget the
everyday disappointments of real life. Timothy Spall's character
sums up the movie's theme succinctly with three words: ``laughter,
tears, curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   `Topsy-Turvy'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a fan site on Gilbert and Sullivan:
www.home.onet.co.uk/(tilde)cbrowne/
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Anna and the King'' (PG-13) _ Maybe we didn't need another
version, but this one is handsome and engaging. Jodie Foster and
Chow Yun-Fat star in this lavish, songless costume drama that holds
its own against the beloved 1956 musical ``The King and I.'' It's a
mix of old-fashioned moviemaking doused with contemporary political
correctness. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Edge of Seventeen'' (unrated) _ Not much cutting edge here,
but this teen saga about coming out and coming of age in 1984
small-town Ohio has a refreshingly unforced tone and a really
appealing young lead (Chris Stafford, who, depending on the angle,
recalls either a young Jim Carrey or a young Tom Cruise). What
works best here _ along with some sly time-capsule touches _ is the
way Stafford doesn't just discover a new sense of sexual
orientation, he discovers a new sense of himself as a whole. Grade:
B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sweet and Lowdown'' (R) _ This jazzy little doodle of a
mockumentary is middling Woody Allen and, as such, mildly likable
once you get past the insistent whiff of self-justification. Sean
Penn is superb as a legendary (and fictional) jazz guitarist in the
1930s who's an angel with a guitar in his hands and a louse the
rest of the time. He takes up with a waifish mute (Samantha Morton)
_ she's sweet; he's lowdown _ but his selfishness, womanizing and
drinking work against them. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Liberty Heights'' (R) _ Like warmed-over chicken soup. Barry
Levinson's memory movie about coming of age in a Jewish
neighborhood in '50s Baltimore is generally well-acted and
sometimes evocative. But his anecdotal reminiscences concerning the
Kurtman brothers _ sensitive Adrien Brody and irrepressible Ben
Foster _ don't convey much that's fresh or surprising. Joe Mantegna
brings an unexpected dignity and a nuanced self-knowledge to the
role of the boys' numbers-running dad. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bicentennial Man'' (PG) _ Huggy-feely Robin Williams plays
the android Andrews, a metallic butler who slowly develops human
traits (creativity, curiosity and a hint of emotion). But the
people around him age, wither, die. Overlong, ``Man'' moves swiftly
for its first 90 minutes, but it slows down to become a
disappointingly conventional love story that isn't really
persuasive. The movie has a heart, but a flagging pulse. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo'' (R) _ It's choppy and cheap
looking, and it has dead spots like the Sahara, but it also has a
surprising number of genuinely funny bits, most of them slapsticky
and gleefully rude. Rob Schneider plays Deuce, a fish tender who
moonlights as a ``manwhore,'' and, although he has never been funny
for more than three minutes at any previous time in his career, he
sustains a level of genial, tasteless humor. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Chris Hewitt, Knight Ridder
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gun Shy'' (R) _ Stressed-out undercover drug cop Liam Neeson
matches ulcers with stressed-out junior mafioso Oliver Platt in a
deeply funky New York comedy about murder, stomach disorders and
male anxiety. It's scattershot, but it scores a few surprising
satirical bull's-eyes. Love interest Sandra Bullock's screen time
is unwisely minimized by producer Sandra Bullock. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Campbell, Newhouse News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
