<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrity chefs come out of kitchen
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, their names were known only to restaurateurs, food critics
and an esoteric circle of gourmets and foodies as they worked their
magic behind the scenes. Now, scores of celebrity chefs have come
out of the kitchen _ emerging with publicists, agents, entourages,
fan clubs, product endorsements and listings in Forbes magazine _
to garner their share of wealth, fame and public adulation in the
rarefied atmosphere occupied by sports heroes, movie stars and
entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   What has been called the food renaissance that began in the
1990s has propelled the once invisible chef to a high-visibility,
high-stature role of entertainer, artist and magician, who creates
drama, spectacle, excitement and pleasure for masses of people who
just can't seem to get enough.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought, less than a decade ago, that there would
be a 24-hour-a-day television channel devoted to food that reaches
more than 45 million homes and continues to grow?
</P>
<P>
   The aura and excitement generated by this new breed of chef seem
to be spreading as people enroll in culinary schools in
unprecedented numbers. In 1992 the New York Restaurant School had
400 students; four years later, enrollment had reached 1,000. When
the Culinary Institute of America, headquartered in Hyde Park,
N.Y., opened its Greystone campus in California in 1995, the
maximum enrollment of 2,000 was reached almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   And not all these fledgling chefs are kids, either. Many are
leaving longtime careers to follow their heart's desire into the
kitchen. Of the students enrolled at Manhattan's French Culinary
Institute in 1996, 85 percent were career-changers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these new chefs won't all become famous, but there
are plenty of jobs out there for them, celebrity or not. The Bureau
of Labor Statistics reports that jobs for skilled cooks rose from
408,000 in 1983 to 727,000 in 1996, and the category is expected to
increase by 14.6 percent in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what Julia Child started in the early 1960s, when she
appeared on public television and became the first chef to become a
household word, has now become ``chef hysteria,'' says Leonard
Pickell, who heads the James Beard Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the celebrity chef heap, without question, is
Emeril Lagasse. When the Food Network superstar visited Chicago
last year, one newspaper compared the excitement to that inspired
by a papal visit. The Food Network reports that it gets more than
150,000 requests every week for the 1,500 seats to see this earthy
and engaging native of Fall River, Mass., ``kick it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are scores of other celebrity chefs who have captured
our imagination. Old favorites such as Graham Kerr, the ``Galloping
Gourmet'' (who is still galloping), Jacques Pepin, Justin Wilson
and, of course, Julia Child still hold a place in our hearts. Add
to these old-timers names like Curtis Aikens, an Atlanta native who
has gained national fame as a health food expert, consumer food
advocate, cookbook author and host of the popular Food Network show
``Pick of the Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Hot Off the Grill With Bobby Flay,'' a master of
Southwestern cuisine who developed a cult following in New York
food circles after he opened his now-celebrated Mesa Grill there
and The New York Times gushed that it ``surpasses anything of its
kind elsewhere in New York.'' And there's Mario Batali (``Molto
Mario''), Alton Brown (``Good Eats''), Sissy Biggers (``Ready . . .
Set . . . Cook!''), Jacqui Malouf (``Hot Off the Grill''), Sara
Moulton (``Cooking Live''), Tyler Florence (``Food 911'') and a
host of others, each with impressive resumes and adoring and
dedicated fans.
</P>
<P>
   So who's your favorite?
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with these new celebrities, food television and the
food renaissance in general, check out these Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At the epicenter is the Food Network on cable television and
the corresponding Food TV site at www.foodtv.com.
</P>
<P>
   While many TV stations and programs have companion Web sites, it
would be hard to find any that do it better. Updated daily, this
site, which reports 2 million unique visitors a month, has all the
bells and whistles of a top-notch culinary Web site, even without
its TV twin. It offers loads of background information on your
favorite chef or show, interesting articles, ideas, tips, forums,
Q&AMP;As and places where you can e-mail chefs directly. If you missed
a recipe on your favorite cooking show, daily recipes are easily
accessible. If you don't have the Food Network on your television,
the Web site is equally satisfying _ in a virtual sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If 24 hours of cooking shows on the Food Network aren't
enough, the truly hooked can check out Kitchen Link's listing of TV
and radio cooking shows _ a mind-boggling list with links to what
looks like every cooking show in North America. From the biggies on
the networks and cable to cooking segments on local TV and radio,
it's all there, with schedules, links and recipes. See
www.kitchenlink.com/cgi
</P>
<P>
   /publicframes?page &QC; tv
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the off chance that what you're looking for isn't on that
list, or you just want to surf, see About.coms Television Food at
homecooking.about.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /homecooking/library/sub
</P>
<P>
   /msub22.htm?rnk &QC; r8&AMP;terms
</P>
<P>
   &QC; celebrity+chefs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a more in-depth look at the world of famous and
not-so-famous chefs, restaurants and the food business, see
StarChefs at www
</P>
<P>
   .starchefs.com. Along with profiles of chefs and cookbook
authors, there's food industry news, information on culinary
schools and even a list of cooking jobs around the country. There
are lots of good articles about food trends, recipes by top-notch
chefs and all you need to stay on top of the food renatm) will link
you to the Web sites of such familiar TV food personalities as
Graham Kerr, Nathalie Dupree and Mr. Food.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you're interested in what just plain old celebrities are
cooking for dinner, TV Guide has compiled a fun and interesting
site (www
</P>
<P>
   .tvguidelive.com/celebchef/index
</P>
<P>
   .html) giving the favorite recipes of the stars. Click on Star
Name for an alphabetical list of TV personalities and their
favorite eats, from Dan Aykroyd's bread pudding to Alex Trebek's
tourtier (a French Canadian stew).
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Black-Eyed Pea Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Soaking time: 8-24 hours Preparation time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, courtesy of Curtis Aikens, makes a refreshing and
degrees. Spray a 13-by-9-inch baking pan with nonstick baking spray
and set aside. In the large bowl of an electric mixer, beat the
shortening, gradually adding the sugar. Continue beating until
fluffy. Add the eggs, one at a time, beating well after each
addition. In a small bowl, sift together the flour, salt and cocoa
powder. Add this mixture to the bowl alternately with the milk,
beginning and ending with the dry ingredients. Fold in the vanilla
and pecans. Pour the batter into the prepared pan, place in the
oven and bake for 40 to 45 minutes or until a tester inserted into
the middle of the cake comes out clean. Place marshmallows on top
of hot cake and allow to melt before icing cake.
</P>
<P>
   For the icing: In a medium mixing bowl, beat together the
margarine, vanilla, evaporated milk, cocoa powder, confectioners'
sugar and pecans. Pour over cake and let stand one hour before
cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 660 calories, 6 grams protein, 36 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 83 grams carbohydrates, 83
milligrams cholesterol, 235 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   Lydia P. Miller of Decatur, Ga., is searching for a peach
frosting for a peach poundcake.
</P>
