<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former railroad town picks up steam again
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLINGBROKE, Ga. _ This tiny town is on a byway _ U.S. 41 _ but
maybe it should be called a buy-way.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly a little railroad and farming community in Monroe
County, about 70 miles from downtown Atlanta, Bolingbroke has
morphed into an antique lover's destination.
</P>
<P>
   While it doesn't have an abundance of gift and antique stores,
it has enough to keep shoppers content and happy. Four stores are
chock-full of goodies ranging from old syrup buckets ($20) to a
vintage hat stand ($60) to an early 19th-century English mahogany
secretary ($11,200). The fifth, Bolingbroke Country Gardens, sells
plants and garden accessories as well as offering nursery and
landscape services. All are within walking distance or a short ride
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the whole scenario,'' said Esmeralda Wells of Roswell,
Ga., strolling through the 5-year-old shop Galligans of Bolingbroke
on a recent Thursday morning. ``The scene takes you back in time.
Fortunately, the town has retained its character with these
charming shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Shop owner Mary Stewart Galligan dabbles in a bit of everything,
from antique china and pine furniture to new sterling silver
jewelry and charms. ``I carry so much variety because customers buy
everything and anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bolingbroke was established in 1824 as Stallings Store; it
changed its name to Prattsville in 1844. Six years later, the town
became Colaparchee. The current moniker was bestowed by Central
Georgia Railroad President William M. Wadley in 1866, to honor
Englishman and author Lord Bolingbroke, whom he admired.
</P>
<P>
   Wadley was the great-grandfather of Beverly Mickle, who
currently owns the only restaurant in town, Sweet Sue's Tea Room
and Soda Fountain. ``My wife's great-grandfather was responsible
for rebuilding the railroads in the South,'' said Jim Mickle, the
unofficial mayor of Bolingbroke. ``That's how our town came about,
and thrived. There were lots of businesses here until 1935, when a
steam engine exploded and killed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, an antique shop opened. Others followed, and a
community developed. While shops have come and gone, the current
crop has been around long enough to see business grow. And
Bolingbroke's location, with its easy access to I-75, makes it
attractive to shoppers from Atlanta, Macon, Forsyth, Perry and
South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The most established store is the 10-year-old Antiques at
Bolingbroke, housed in a charming 1874 cottage, plus two
warehouses. Owners Jerry and Elaine Schmitt specialize in late
18th-century, 19th-century and early 20th-century American and
English furniture. Not many places offer you fresh-squeezed
lemonade while you hunt for that perfect armoire or dining room
table. Elaine says her customers are from all over the country, and
she regularly ships furniture to New York and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's of Bolingbroke is an unusual business that features
gifts, antiques and decorative accessories. Fifteen people banded
together three years ago to buy an eclectic mix of merchandise.
They rent space in a rambling 1920s house owned by Mickle and
display their specialties _ children's clothing, home accessories,
rugs, artwork, jewelry and new and antique furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all work together to run the shop,'' said Phillipa
Shoffner. ``Each person works two days a month helping customers.
Someone waters the plants; someone else does the advertising; yet
another person does the book work. ``And it's amazing that with 15
people we never have arguments!''
</P>
<P>
   For art lovers, a must stop is 4 1/2-year-old Stofko-Dixon Line
Fine Art Gallery &AMP; Studio, where owner and artist Ernestine
Stofko-Dixon holds classes for all ages. She also represents about
35 area artists, selling their works, which range from acrylic on
canvas landscapes to wood bowls to pottery. One such artist is
Trudi McKinley of Alpharetta, who specializes in painted garden
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask how many residents live in this cute little village,
you'll get the answer ``300 residents and one sorehead.'' And who
is the sorehead?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the shoe fits, wear it,'' says Jim Mickle with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-75 south to I-475 (Exit 177). Take Exit
15 (the first exit) and turn right at the end of the ramp onto U.S.
41. Bolingbroke is about half a mile.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Business hours vary. Call ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Ample free parking in front of or behind the shops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Restrooms are located in Sweet Sue's Tea Room &AMP;
Soda Fountain or in individual stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Not all stores are wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Forsyth-Monroe County Chamber of Commerce.
1-888-642-4628.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Sue's Tea Room &AMP; Soda Fountain. Step back into the past at
this eatery _ formerly a feed store and general store _ that dishes
up plenty of nostalgia for lunch and afternoon tea. It also boasts
a 1920s soda fountain that still dispenses old-fash-
</P>
<P>
   ioned phosphates: a Green River, a Zombie or a Pink Lady (each
$1.25) and what one fan calls ``the best chocolate soda in
Georgia'' ($1.95). For more substantial fare on a hot day, nothing
beats the Tea Sandwich Plate ($4.95) _ petite chicken salad and
cream cheese sandwiches with cheese wafers and creamy frozen fruit
salad, just like Rich's Magnolia Room used to serve. Other choices:
the quiche, small garden salad and fresh fruit ($5.95) or a
homemade pimento cheese sandwich ($2.95). And the dessert of
choice? A cream puff filled with vanilla ice cream topped with
praline sauce ($2.95). Owner Sue Mickle named her 4 1/2-year-old
tearoom after her aunt Sue Wadley, ``a special person in my life.''
To give it a nostalgic feel, she has decorated the restaurant with
her aunt's keepsakes and pictures. 11 a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays-
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays. 6025 U.S. 41 South. 912-994-0031.
</P>
<P>
   While browsing around Bolingbroke, we found . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Acrylic on canvas of potted geraniums and pansies painted by
Ernestine Stofko-Dixon ($375). Stofko-Dixon Line Fine Art Gallery &AMP;
Studio. 6025 U.S. 41 South. 912-994-2303.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Child's stool hand-painted by Hilda Tidwell ($49).
Stofko-Dixon Line Fine Art Gallery &AMP; Studio. 6025 U.S. 41 South.
912-994-2303.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vintage galvanized steel syrup bucket used for flowers ($20).
Henry's of Bolingbroke, 6009 U.S. 41 South. 912-992-9878.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hand-smocked little boy's romper suit by Sir John ($44.95).
Henry's of Bolingbroke, 6009 U.S. 41 South. 912-992-9878.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden accessory featuring a hand-painted American flag on tin
($40). Galligans of Bolingbroke, 6001 U.S. 41 South. 912-994-8490.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hanging basket of salmon-colored impatiens ($10). Bolingbroke
Country Gardens, 6109 U.S. 41 South. 912-994-8100.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Three etched seltzer bottles, circa 1900 ($52-$55). Antiques
at Bolingbroke, 8083 Rivoli Road. 912-994-9353.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A 1920s rocker with cane back and seat ($90). Antiques at
Bolingbroke, 8083 Rivoli Road. 912-994-9353.
</P>
<P>
   Shop talk
</P>
<P>
   Shops in Bolingbroke:
</P>
<P>
   Antiques at Bolingbroke, 8083 Rivoli Road. 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Bolingbroke Country Gardens, 6109 U.S. 41 South. 10 a.m.-6 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Galligans of Bolingbroke, 6001 U.S. 41 South. 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's of Bolingbroke, 6009 U.S. 41 South. 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Stofko-Dixon Line Fine Art Gallery &AMP; Studio, 6025 U.S. 41 South.
Gallery,10 a.m.-4 p.m. Saturdays and by appointment. Studio, 10
a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
