<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been looking everywhere for Kenneth Jay Lane jewelry.
It came into prominence when Barbara Bush was first lady. I ordered
some pieces and was very satisfied. I tried to reorder, but I can
no longer find anyone selling the jewelry line.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jean Warren, Dunwoody, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Former first lady Barbara Bush is a big fan of Kenneth Jay
Lane pearls, which she wear as a three-strand choker with daytime
silks as well as evening satins. But Lane jewelry is much more than
just pearls. The New York designer started his business in the '60s
with a pair of sparkly earrings. Some of his designs, shown here,
include a starfish pin ($110) and a colorful ``pebble'' necklace
($155). He's also known for art deco-inspired pins and ``bug''
earrings. Fans include Jackie Collins, Nancy Reagan and Raquel
Welch. His collection is available exclusively at Beth Ann, an
image and accessory boutique at 47 Irby Ave. (404-233-4424).
</P>
<P>
   ``His jewelry is not serious,'' says shop owner Beth Ann
Taratoot. ``Many women wear some of their real jewelry with Kenneth
Jay Lane pieces for an eclectic mix. And women of all ages can wear
his earrings and pins.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: After reading about the possible absorption of harsh
hair-coloring chemicals into the bloodstream during pregnancy, I
heard about Avigal, an all-natural, plant-based henna. I would like
to know where I can find it or which salon uses this henna.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alisa Crovetti, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: For millennia, women have used henna to color or highlight
their hair. Avigal henna, an all-natural hair color, is derived
from the leaves of the plant Lawsonia inermis, found in Saudi
Arabia, Iran, India, Egypt and Morocco. It comes in three shades _
red, black and colorless or natural. And it's the combination of
these three that creates the shades of Avigal henna, ranging from
hazel and champagne to cognac, copper, auburn and burgundy. Each
shade _ there are 12 in all, plus natural _ will look slightly
different on each individual. Currently no one in Atlanta sells
Avigal henna, but you can order it at 1-800-722-1011. Prices range
from a 4.5-ounce package at $9 to a 32.5-ounce bag for $35.
</P>
<P>
   Henna can be used on any type of hair _ virgin, tinted,
bleached, permed or streaked, says Avigal founder Ilana Harkavi.
She adds, ``It also conditions hair abused by chemicals, adds body
and texture and helps to strengthen hair.''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
