<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUKE-SECURITY-NYT &LR;      06-21 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY REASSURES SENATORS ON MISSING HARD DRIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson went to Capitol
Hill on Wednesday to reassure skeptical lawmakers about security in
nuclear laboratories, telling them there was ``no evidence of
espionage'' in the recent disappearance and subsequent recovery of
two sensitive computer hard drives at the Los Alamos laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary doubtless knew that bitter criticism awaited him
in the hearing room, so he was not surprised when he got it, from
senators of both parties at a session of the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight, Mr. Secretary, was yours, and I believe you've
lost,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who heads the Senate
Intelligence Committee and sat in on Wednesday's Armed Services
Committee hearing. ``I believe you've lost what credibility you
have left on Capitol Hill, and I think it's time for you to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson gamely insisted he was trying to improve security
consciousness at the laboratories, putting into effect procedures
that are compatible with secrecy as well as science, and that in
many ways he was succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI is still looking at the two hard drives found last
Friday at the Los Alamos National Lab,'' Richardson testified.
``I've been speaking with FBI Director Louis Freeh throughout,
spoke with him this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary said the two drives found behind a copying machine
had been determined by the FBI to be genuine _ a question that had
not been widely raised _ and that ``there is no evidence of
espionage, nor is there evidence that the drives ever left the Los
Alamos X Division.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos officials announced a week ago Monday that the hard
drives containing nuclear data were missing, then announced on
Friday that they had been found behind the copier. The hard drives
were used to store weapons data needed by an emergency team that
responds to nuclear accidents and nuclear-related threats. The
drives contained design data about weapons from China, France,
Russia and the United States that could be used to disarm weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After their discovery on Friday, the drives were flown to
Washington for analysis to determine whether they had been tampered
with. Richardson's testimony indicated that, initially at least, no
such evidence had been found.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary said the drives were still being studied for
fingerprints. He speculated that their mishandling might have been
the result of carelessness, and that a lab employee might have been
too frightened to acknowledge what was indisputably a grave
security lapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no excuses,'' Richardson said. ``It's unacceptable,
incomprehensible to me what happened. I will not rest until I know
what happened, when, where, why and by whom.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode of the missing and suddenly-rediscovered hard drives
is the latest in a string of embarrassing security lapses
associated with the laboratories, a fact that senators brought out
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one more potentially catastrophic security
failure which has become an all-too-familiar pattern,'' said Sen.
John Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
