<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FT-STLOUIS-DIG0622-CO     06-21 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FT-STLOUIS-DIG0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    X marks the spot
 &HT;    By Kevin Robbins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, Texas _ The dirt near the water is dark and sticky and
thick with clues just a few inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists rake the ground for ceramics, weapons, the bones
of soldiers buried before Texas was Texas. Nothing slips their
attention. Everything fetched from the clay of this old cattle
ranch is cleaned, dried, tagged and bagged in the hope that before
long, what is left of the first European colony in the state will
be dug from the banks of Garcitas Creek and preserved to explain
the rise and tragic fall of Fort St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The fort was founded by the French explorer Rene Robert
Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle. He and about 180 colonists built Fort
St. Louis in 1685. Three years later, the settlement was gone.
Disease, abandonment and a surprise winter ambush by Karankawa
Indians claimed the brief but significant life of Fort St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers with the Texas Historical Commission have been
interested in the site for decades but especially since 1996, when
the fort's location was confirmed. That year, a ranch foreman swept
a metal detector over a mound and found eight iron cannons from
France, laid together like matchsticks above the brackish Garcitas,
four miles upstream of Lavaca Bay and 20 miles from the Gulf of
Mexico that carried the colonists to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists began excavating for artifacts this January. More
than 16,000 have been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other site like Fort St. Louis in Texas,'' said
Michael Davis, an archaeologist and director of special projects
with the historical commission who compared the historical
significance of the site to that of Jamestown in Virginia and
Plymouth in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed over the years. The land today resembles the
land three centuries ago. Mesquites grow near bluebonnets, which
sprout near mushrooms on a warm, soggy morning. Diamondback
rattlesnakes live here (the archaeologists have seen at least
seven). So do feral hogs and alligators.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen archaeologists have been at work at the fort site,
which occupies about 30 acres on the Coastal Bend. They've found a
range of artifacts, from half a pair of wooden dice to inchlong,
evil-warding bronze ficas that dangled from horse bridles to many
thousands of glazed, ceramic shards from certain regions of France.
Musket balls, arrow points, earrings and a French coin also have
been taken from the dense soil known as clay gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me goose bumps,'' field archaeologist Robyn Pry said.
</P>
<P>
   With each artifact the archaeologists find, the fort becomes
more whole and complete, and within a few years the artifacts taken
from the ground will be sent to museums across Texas. Then Texans
can see what was left behind by the doomed French explorers and
their leader, La Salle.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for his travels through the Great Lakes, finding the
Mississippi River and laying claim to territory known later as the
Louisiana Purchase, La Salle sailed from France to the New World in
1684. He hoped to arrive at the mouth of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   He misjudged badly. The La Salle expedition ended up in
Matagorda Bay, hundreds of miles west of what became New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Two of La Salle's four vessels _ La Belle, L'Aimable, Le Joly
and St. Francois _ eventually sank. The project to raise La Belle
from the bay ended in 1997. The ship now is being reconstructed, a
process that will take years. The wreckage of L'Aimable was never
found.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two other ships, St. Francois was lost to pirates en
route in the Caribbean. And the Joly later sailed back to France
with disgruntled settlers aboard.
</P>
<P>
   La Salle's expedition party settled on the first high point in
Garcitas Creek, but problems in the settlement forced him and some
of his men to seek help from the nearest French settlement in
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next influenced the future of the New World.
</P>
<P>
   In 1687, on the way to Illinois to find help for the troubled
fort, La Salle's companions killed him and dumped his body in the
East Texas brush.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, smallpox was creeping through Fort St. Louis, killing
colonists. Then, less than a year after La Salle's death, the fort
was raided by the Karankawas. Only the children were spared.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish explorers found the fort in 1689, and they built a
presidio, or military post, on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was considered Spanish country, and the French jumped
in,'' said historian William Foster of nearby Cuero, who is not
associated with the archaeological project. ``It was a very
aggressive move by France and a very large move.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers involved in the Fort St. Louis recovery consider the
daring French colonization in Texas a defining moment in Spanish
interest in the New World. Spain was interested in protecting its
silver mines in northern Mexico, so when the French arrived, the
Spanish moved more quickly to establish their own presence in
Texas. The French forced Spain to take Texas more seriously,
historians say, and Spain did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we have the Spanish background right now,'' said
Jim Bruseth, the director of the historical commission's
archaeological division. If the French presence had won out over
the Spanish, ``Texas history, and Southern history, could've taken
an entirely different course.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Fort St. Louis has given much to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There are tales of shipwrecks, expeditions, famous explorers,
massacres. There are stories such as the one Bruseth likes to tell
when he's standing over a part of the site where, in 1689, the body
of a French woman was found, half-eaten by wolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That evening, over a fire, a Spanish soldier put together our
first Texas poem,'' Bruseth said, and it was an ode to the death of
the woman from France.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs in the ground still. The copper rivets found
close to the creek show how parts of the French fort were built.
The mortar found farther from the creek shows how the Spanish
presidio was built.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no signs of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the soil lay the bones of as many as 90 French
colonists. Archaeologists believe there's a cemetery near Fort St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows where, and time is running short. The $1.5
million in grants, donations and state money supporting the
archaeological project can sustain the work through fall, Bruseth
said, but the archaeologists have permission from the landowners to
stay for another year.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the archaeologists must go. And this secluded creek
bank of mesquites and mysteries will fall quiet again, just as it
did when the last colonists died and were buried, somewhere out
here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
