<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GUN-CHECKS22-COX     06-21 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CHECKS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD REIMBURSE STATES DOING GUN BACKGROUND CHECKS
 &HT;    450&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ States that perform their own background checks for
gun purchases could get federal compensation under a Senate bill
introduced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan legislation would authorize $150 million for the
next three years to reimburse ``point of contact'' states, those
that agree to conduct all background searches for gun purchases
themselves rather than relying on the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studies indicate that point-of-contact states do a better job
of conducting background checks than the FBI,'' Sen. Orrin G.
Hatch, R-Utah, a co-sponsor of the bill, said at a Judiciary
Committee hearing. ``States have advantages, including better
access to court records and a better understanding of state
firearms laws.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the number of states using point-of-contact systems has
fallen from 23 in 1999 to 15 this year. Several others, including
Florida, are considering terminating their systems due to
increasing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said at the hearing that Congress
needs to reimburse states that serve as point-of-contact centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illinois spends about $600,000 a year for its point-of-contact
system to run effective background checks,'' Durbin said.
``Congress needs to remedy this because Illinois pays the full cost
of these mandated background checks while other states pay nothing
and simply rely on the FBI to conduct the gun background checks.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first 18 months of operation since the Brady Act began
requiring background checks for gun purchases, the point-of-contact
states have conducted 7.7 million checks, more than half the nearly
13.4 million nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Max Schlueter, director of the Vermont Crime Information Center,
told the panel that states do a better job than the FBI because
they review more records of people in prohibited categories, such
as people involuntarily committed to a mental institution or under
a domestic violence restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Vermont, 80 percent of of our felony convictions are not
forwarded to the FBI because they are not fingerprint-supported,''
Schlueter said. ``In addition, Vermont does not contribute the vast
majority of wanted persons into the National Crime Information
Center data base.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Senate Majority leader and Republican presidential
candidate Bob Dole told the panel that the background checks need
to be improved because only 72 percent of the background checks are
done instantly.
</P>
<P>
   While 95 percent of the background checks are finished within
two hours, the other 5 percent can take more than three days, Dole
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, sales at gun shows also need to be
monitored. ``Criminals can circumvent the background check because
there aren't any at gun shows,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was introduced on the same day that the Treasury
Department's Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms reported that
large numbers of guns firearms are illegally distributed by corrupt
gun dealers and at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   For the report, which Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers
called the most comprehensive ever about the illegal firearms
market, ATF investigated 1,530 gun transactions involving 84,128
firearms over two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2,670 traffickers identified by ATF agents in those
investigations, 25 percent were convicted felons, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun shows accounted for nearly 26,000 trafficked firearms, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report shows that loopholes in our laws help make gun
shows and corrupt gun dealers major channels for gun trafficking,''
President Clinton said in a statement. ``Many of the diverted
weapons supplied by traffickers were later used to commit serious
crimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association said the study underlined the
importance of enforcing current gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: 
www.atf.treas.gov/pub/fire-explo(underscore)pub/pdf/followingthegun(
underscore)internet.pdf
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
