<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0810 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      06-21 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUITS Q &AMP; A: OF MODEMS AND E-MAILING LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Modems Fail to Stay Connected &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I often get disconnected from the Internet when I am trying
to download files from the Web. Is it my computer or the site I'm
on that's causing this?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are several things that could be causing the problem,
and you may want to start keeping track of the disconnection
incidents to see if you can spot any patterns. If other files of
the same size download with no problems, but you find yourself
repeatedly bumped offline when trying to download a particular
file, the problem could be with that file or the site it is on.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common causes of interrupted Internet
connections is telephone line noise. Static and scratchy sounds
that you may hear occasionally while you are on the phone can
really wreak havoc when your modem is using the line to communicate
with another modem. A sudden increase in line noise can sometimes
cause your modem to disconnect, no matter what you are doing
online.
</P>
<P>
   Your local phone company may be able to check your line for
excess noise that might be causing frequent modem disconnections.
Modems need far quieter lines to communicate than people do,
though, so the company may not be able to do anything if your line
doesn't sound consistently noisy.
</P>
<P>
   You might also check with the technical support department of
your Internet service provider to make sure you have the proper
settings in your communications software for your type of modem.
Some ISPs will also automatically log off users who are connected
for long periods of time, so you may want to ask about the
company's policy on the matter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I get off a software company's mailing list that I
never wanted to be on? I tried replying to the return address, but
my request to be taken off the list was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are different types of mailing lists and different ways
to get your e-mail address removed from one. Mailing lists can
range from academic discussion groups that you sign up for with a
specific moderator or ``list master'' to junk mail that fills up
your In box courtesy of programs that comb the Internet for e-mail
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent ``news'' updates from companies is a type of e-mail
that you may not have realized that you signed up for. It is not
exactly the same kind of unsolicited e-mail as spam, since you gave
the company your e-mail address at some point. A common way to
accidentally get yourself included on the mailing list is to fill
out a form on the Web to download a browser plug-in or free bit of
software.
</P>
<P>
   The site may ask for your e-mail address, but you may not notice
a small series of boxes elsewhere on the page relating to updates
about the company and its products. These boxes are usually checked
by default to request the e-mail updates, and it is up to you to
uncheck them if you don't want to receive the company's mail.
Software registration forms that you either mail in or fill out and
submit online are typical places you might see that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Before deleting the unwanted message from your computer, you
might try looking through the text to see if the sender has
included a specific e-mail address or Web site URL for you to use
if you have questions or problems with the mail or wish to be
removed from the company's mail list. A visit to the company's Web
site may also yield the contact information you need to get off the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the Reply button on the message often does not work. In
many cases, the address in the reply header of the message is
different from that of the address that sent you the message, which
might be the polite reason why no one responded to your request.
</P>
<P>
   If you find that your mailbox is filling up with junk mail and
want to learn more about how to avoid it, you can visit the home
page of the Coalition Against Unsolicited Commercial E-Mail at
www.cauce.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
