<HEADER>
A0817 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-LATINO-AID-HNS &LR;      06-21 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-AID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LATINO GROUP OFFERS SCHOLARSHIPS, BUSINESS OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new national self-help organization called Latino
Initiatives for the Next Century announced Wednesday that it will
provide college and trade school scholarships to Hispanics in
California, Texas, New York and Illinois, while helping other
Latinos start their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from LINC, a Chicago-based organization, made the
announcement here at its first news conference.
</P>
<P>
   LINC Chairman Rudy Mulder said the group's efforts ``will enable
Latinos to expand their horizons and achieve the American dream.''
He added that the organization will initially focus on the four
states because they contain about 72 percent of the country's
Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are planning a minimum of 500 four-year scholarships over
the next 12 months for first-generation Latinos,'' said Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   LINC, which is supported by Latino business groups, will also
provide tutoring and counseling services for students to help
ensure a low dropout rate, said David Lizarraga, the organization's
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   LINC said it is encouraging Latinos of all ages to apply.
</P>
<P>
   The group's officials said they are basing their educational
program on a successful model used by a California Latino
organization called The East Los Angeles Community Union.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to raise living standards among American Latinos by
creating new wealth and job opportunities, LINC also promised to
provide financing and entrepreneurial know-how so that Hispanics
can start their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has teamed up with 7-Eleven, which has 18,000
stores across the country, to help Latinos buy and manage their own
franchises. Other companies, including restaurant chains and car
dealerships, are expected to join 7-Eleven in the effort in the
next several months, Mulder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be able to put 150 Latinos into business over the next
few years, just with the 7-Eleven relationship,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Keyes, 7-Eleven's chief executive officer, said in a
statement that the program ``will not only benefit (Latinos')
economic and business knowledge, but it will also allow them to
employ other Latinos and teach them business and retail skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Hispanic population in the United States is 31
million. By 2050, it is expected to top 96 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
