</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0622-1STLED     06-21 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0622-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Changes July to August in reference to Democratic
Convention under item titled _ AND STILL KEEP MONDAY NIGHT SAFE FOR
FOOTBALL
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Oil on the political fire
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OIL ON THE POLITICAL FIRE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush voiced support today for the Federal Trade
Commission's probe of soaring gasoline prices, but he put most of
the blame on the White House's failure to convince foreign crude
producers to ``open the spigots.'' In Los Angeles, Bush said, ``I
do think it's fair to have the FTC investigate,'' adding that the
results would be ``healthy.'' Bush didn't accuse the Clinton
administration or Al Gore of demagoguing the issue by launching the
probe, but the former Texas oilman did insist that it's the
administration's job to pressure the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Nations to increase oil output.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO YOU CALL A NON-ENDORSING ENDORSEMENT?
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring his brawny union's disenchantment with Al Gore,
Teamsters chief James P. Hoffa will join Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader in Los Angeles on Thursday to make a ``special
statement ... concerning the 2000 presidential election.'' A
Teamsters spokesman said Hoffa doesn't plan at that time to endorse
Nader. The United Auto Workers has hinted it also may support Nader
for his opposition to ``corporate globalization.'' The Teamsters
and UAW pointedly abstained last October when the AFL-CIO voted to
give Gore an early endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   THE TRUTH, TEXAS-TOAST STYLE
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has issued a warning to George W. Bush: ``The Texas
Truth Squad is coming.'' The group of workers from Texas will
appear at labor-sponsored meetings around the country to try to
sully the governor's reputation by talking about problems in Texas
that include education, health care and the treatment of farm
workers. The union leaflet says the truth squad will note that
Texas ranks the lowest among all states in the percentage of people
who have health insurance and near the bottom in College Board
scores. The first event is to be held in Philadelphia on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   PLOWING FERTILE GROUND
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore went to Iowa today and proposed exempting more family
farms and small businesses from estate taxes. While attempting to
carve out his own piece of a Republican campaign issue, Democrats
warn that eliminating the tax would blow a hole in the budget and
mainly benefit the rich. Instead, Gore proposed increasing the
exemption for small businesses and farmers _ currently up to $2.6
million _ to $5 million, meaning, he said, that 90 percent of the
nation's farmers would not owe estate taxes. Gore: ``Some on
Capitol Hill believe we should completely repeal the estate tax and
give a massive tax break to the wealthiest Americans. They want to
give away the store to those who already own the shopping center.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS AND QUAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Political protesters are saying they won't foment a repeat of
violence that erupted after the Los Angeles Lakers won the NBA
title the other night, but they fear police may use the riot as a
pretext to bully them away from the Democratic convention. Shawn
McDougal of the American Friends Service Committee, a Quaker social
service movement, and other planners promise boisterous and
disruptive rallies, but maintain their groups won't try to hurt
anyone or destroy property. And the LAPD insists it won't impede
the protests as long as the activists remain peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-BUDGET CAMPAIGN COVERAGE . . .
</P>
<P>
   ABC News, citing cost concerns, has pulled out of a pool
arrangement where three networks had shared camera coverage of
George W. Bush and Al Gore. ABC had joined with CBS and Fox News
Channel to share camera coverage of the campaign. But with interest
in the candidates at an ebb now and relatively few public
appearances, ABC found it wasn't worth the expense, said
spokeswoman Su-Lin Nichols. ABC is using its own cameras to cover
some events and relying on affiliates for others, she said. The
network currently has just one producer, without a correspondent or
camera crew, traveling full-time with each candidate. CBS and NBC
have yet to announce their plans, but are expected to scale back,
also.
</P>
<P>
   . . . WITH A WAY TO STAY IN THE GAME . . .
</P>
<P>
   ABC has invited Al Gore and George W. Bush to participate in a
one-on-one televised conversation shortly after Labor Day. The
network said it wanted as little participation as possible from a
moderator so the event doesn't look like a formal debate. So far,
the two candidates have agreed only to three fall debates sponsored
by the Commission on Presidential Debates. But, ``if you can have
them talk to each other directly, it will become less adversarial
and less debate-like,'' said ABC News president David Westin.
Campaigns keep such tight control on all aspects of personal
appearances that Westin's idea might be a tough sell, said ABC
anchor Peter Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND STILL KEEP MONDAY NIGHT SAFE FOR FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   ABC, in its dialing down of convention coverage in prime time,
doesn't plan to pre-empt two preseason NFL games. The networmillion
in federal funds for the general election and cannot raise any more
money except to cover legal and accounting costs.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIST CHALLENGING BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   John Hagelin, the quantum physicist who founded the Natural Law
Party, is challenging Pat Buchanan for the Reform Party's
presidential nomination and the right to spend the party's $12.6
million in federal campaign money. In addition to running as the
Natural Law nominee, Hagelin said he's qualified to have his name
placed on Reform Party's mail ballot. Ever since Buchanan left the
Republican Party last year, he has been taking over the Reform
Party, winning the biggest share of delegates. But a two-thirds
majority at the national conven
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
