<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MUSIC-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY BRINGS ALIVE NEW ROCK 'N' ROLL MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash.)  (With CIR-MUSEUM-EXHIBIT-GUIDE, attached) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new museum rises from Seattle's streets like great, billowing
clouds of rippling aluminum and stainless steel, its shapes so
devoid of straight lines that it appears to have been grown rather
than built by human hands.
</P>
<P>
   Even the curvy steel superstructure of the museum, the
Experience Music Project, was designed with computer assistance and
fabricated to such exacting specifications that its manufacture had
to be guided by computers as well, note its builders.
</P>
<P>
   Frank O. Gehry, when designing the museum, used the same
computer tools that were originally developed to design Mirage
fighter jets. In the end, he has said, he likes to think of his
latest creation, its multicolored skin glittering in the famously
infrequent sunshine of the Great Northwest, as a
``three-dimensional floating puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more than any other museum, the Experience Music
Project, or EMP, owes its existence and operation to contemporary
computer technology. When the 140,000-square-foot interactive
museum officially opens Friday, visitors will encounter an almost
seamless array of digital technology engineered, its designers say,
to guide, track, entertain and enlighten visitors as they explore
and celebrate American popular music, mostly rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the perfect building for rebelliousness and innovation,''
said Paul Zumwalt, who managed EMP's design and construction.
``It's not meant to be conservative, and it's not meant for
everyone to like it. Not everyone likes the same music.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the museum's use of technology, Zumwalt added:
``It's going to change the way people move through museums.''
</P>
<P>
   The cavernous music museum is full of artifacts deemed by its
curators to be important to the rock era. On display are about
1,500 pieces _ from a collection of 100,000 _ including Gibson's
original, 65-year-old experimental electric guitar, the handwritten
lyric notebook that once belonged to Nirvana's Kurt Cobain, Janis
Joplin's velvet blouse and the white Fender Stratocaster guitar
that Jimi Hendrix, a Seattle native, played at Woodstock in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   There are collections that highlight the work of musicians who
came from the Northwest, like the Kingsmen, the Fleetwoods, Bing
Crosby and Quincy Jones. There are exhibitions that explore rock
'n' roll's roots by displaying genre touchstones like Bo Diddley's
1956 guitar, young Elvis Presley's leather jacket and a 1942
Wurlitzer jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more contemporary items from the hip-hop world
like turntables belonging to Grandmaster Flash, a drum machine used
by Dr. Dre to record his breakthrough album, ``The Chronic,'' and
original works by two New York graffiti artists, Dondi and Midg.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tons and tons of stuff in this building,'' said Dave
Leinweber, information systems manager for EMP. ``The trouble we're
going to have is getting people to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything in EMP has been tweaked or enhanced by
computer technology. A book of lyrics handwritten by Hendrix can be
found under glass in a traditional exhibit case, for example, but
in a special kiosk, not unlike an automated teller machine, the
entire notebook has been digitized and made accessible by means of
a touch-sensitive liquid crystal display screen. Slide a finger
along a section of the notebook and Hendrix's tortured scribble is
instantly rendered in easy-to-read text. The same touch screen can
toggle between demo versions and completed versions of Hendrix
songs or it can activate multimedia tours and tutorials on some of
the musical forms that influenced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals in the EMP is to get people to be better
listeners, to be more perceptive listeners,'' said Jon Kertzer, the
museum's director of multimedia and special projects.
</P>
<P>
   More extraordinary gadgetry can also be found, ranging from
flat, 42-inch display screens, made of gas plasma, playing music
videos and artists' oral histories to interactive lessons guided by
computers on automated drum kits, electric guitars and keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every vintage electric guitar in the museum's guitar
gallery can be heard in the form of a digital recording of its
being played by a master musician. Visitors can also perform in a
kind of virtual karaoke machine that simulates what it sounds and
feels like to play as a rock musician before an arena crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion ride through musical innovation and creativity,
called the Artist's Journey, 40 visitors at a time bump and glide
in seats that move by way of a hydraulically controlled platform in
front of a large, wraparound screen that features a digitized image
of James Brown. Beneath visitors' seats are air hoses designed to
fill the theater with appropriate smells to enhance the story.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every corner of EMP, which is the brainchild of the
billionaire Paul Allen, Microsoft's co-founder (and a Seattle
resident), and his sister, Jody Allen Patton, the museum's
co-founder and executive director, is crammed with cutting-edge
computer technology. Even for cellular telephones to work inside
EMP, which is basically a giant steel cage, special repeaters had
to be installed so that cell phone signals would not just haplessly
bounce off the museum's walls.
</P>
<P>
   The videos and music that play continuously in the museum do not
use conventional videocassettes, CDs or DVDs as a source (although
they can). Instead, everything is delivered by a custom-made,
high-speed local area network that pumps songs and high-resolution
images throughout the museum over miles of cables running to banks
of computer servers.
</P>
<P>
   The system is so flexible and so easy to customize, said Robert
Fitzsimmons, the director of technology for EMP, that the museum's
electronic sights and sounds can be reprogrammed with unprecedented
ease and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could change the experience based on time of day, by
visitor group, by all kinds of things,'' said Fitzsimmons, who is
senior project manager of technology at Vulcan Northwest, the
umbrella company that oversees many of Allen's endeavors and which
designed some of EMP's systems. ``You wouldn't have to run out and
change DVD's and all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kathy Scanlan, deputy director of museum services, cautions
that EMP is not about technology for technology's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that it's not a technology museum,'' Scanlan
said. ``The point is to enhance the experience with technology.
What you're really doing is experiencing music here and tapping
into your creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that leads you to be creative with a computer, that's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   (SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
