<SLUG> BC-CIR-MUSEUM-EXHIBIT-GUIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDHELD DEVICE IS MORE THAN A GUIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has visited an art museum in the last 10 years or so
has probably been confronted by someone on the staff proffering an
electronic contraption with headphones to ``enhance'' the gallery
experience.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, those devices have been little more than clunky
cassette players, and at best, clunky MP3 players. Each usually
provides a brief recorded narration, sometimes to the accompaniment
of light classical music or elevator jazz, about various paintings
and pieces in selected museum galleries.
</P>
<P>
   But MEG, the Museum Exhibit Guide, which makes its debut Friday
at the opening of the interactive Experience Music Project in
Seattle, appears to be something quite different.
</P>
<P>
   The device, which weighs a little more than two pounds, has the
processing power of a Pentium-class laptop. The heart of MEG is a
box that contains a Toshiba processor, batteries and an
8.3-gigabyte IBM Travelstar hard drive. It is worn with a shoulder
strap and sits on the hip. Another part of MEG contains a small,
handheld color LCD screen, numeric keypad and some buttons and is
connected to the main box by a cable. It is held in the hand much
like a palm-size organizer.
</P>
<P>
   MEG, which is equipped with an infrared transceiver, can pick up
signals from exhibits in the new museum. By aiming MEG at an item
and pressing a button or by typing an item's number into the
device, museum visitors can view text explaining the object on
MEG's screen. They can also hear audio in the form of music or
narration through the device's headphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of a juggle to get everything on, but once
you do a cruise around, it's lots of fun,'' said Robert
Fitzsimmons, director of technology for the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons' company, Vulcan Northwest, in Bellevue, Wash.,
developed MEG, and he said the company hoped to license its
technology to other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can also bookmark specific exhibits while they tour the
museum. When the device is returned to museum workers, the
bookmarks are downloaded to a museum database. They can then be
called up on EMP's Web site (www.emplive.com) by using an
identification number on the museum admission ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Because MEGs are built to be upgraded, Fitzsimmons said his
company is experimenting with adding video playback.
</P>
<P>
   Vulcan is also testing ways to use radio frequencies to reduce
the amount of information required to be stored on MEG's hard
drive. Using radio signals as well as infrared would allow MEG to
play back full versions of songs instead of fragments. More
up-to-date information, like museum show times, special tours and
classes and exhibition reminders, could also be beamed right into
the devices in vistors' hands, Fitzsimmon said.
</P>
<P>
   With MEG, he said, ``You get to be in charge of what you want
more information about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
