<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DORA GALITZKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shades for Bulbs
</P>
<P>
   Q. For several autumns, I have put in a lot of bulbs. They are
gorgeous in spring, but then there is the inevitable dying foliage
to look at. I've tried the obvious day lilies to come up and hide
it. Would other plants work as well as screens without coming up so
early that they would interfere with the blooms?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. As a reward for not cutting the bulb foliage down before it
yellows and depriving the bulbs of all the food-making ability they
need to prepare for next year's bloom, here are a few suggestions
for plants that will serve as great-looking minglers while hiding
the bulb foliage until it dies down: astilbe, Siberian iris, the
pale pink Geranium macrorrhizum Ingwersen's Variety or any of the
medium-size hostas, including Emily Dickinson, Dorset Blue, Happy
Hearts, Bright Lights and Gold Edger. You might also try Stachys
Countess Helene von Stein, also known as Big Ears (the plant, not
the countess).
</P>
<P>
   The Other Rhododendrons
</P>
<P>
   Q. I love rhododendrons, can't get enough of them. Someone told
me recently that there is one that actually blooms in midsummer. Is
this true? Is it as beautiful as the ones that bloom in the spring?
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you measure beauty by a flower's size and its ability to
blind through brightness, as so many rhododendron lovers seem to,
then the good news is tinged with bad. The really showy
rhododendrons seem to bloom themselves out in spring.
</P>
<P>
   But if you don't need that much candlepower to be impressed, and
you remember that azaleas are rhododendrons, you can extend the
flowering season by turning to some of the more subtle, delicately
refined native azaleas. They belong to the same genus, but their
side of the family hasn't been bred into circus clowns. In addition
to offering more variety of bloom time, the deciduous azaleas add
great fall foliage color to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet azalea (Rhododendron arborescens) is a large, informal
shrub with lustrous dark green foliage and, from June into July,
heliotrope-like fragrant flowers in white to light pink. Other
forms have smoky pink or yellow flowers. The exceptionally
sweet-smelling Florida hammocksweet azalea (R. serrulatum) also
blooms from June into July. The flowers are small and white to pale
pink. Finally, August brings the small orange-red to red flowers of
plumleaf azalea (R. prunifolium).
</P>
<P>
   Sources for native azaleas include Woodlanders, 1128 Colleton
Ave., Aiken, S.C. 29801, (803) 648-7522, catalog $2; and Whitney
Gardens and Nursery, P.O. Box 170, Brinnon, Wash. 98320, (360)
796-4411, catalog $4.
</P>
<P>
   Looking Like Mom
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do the progeny of weeping trees also weep, or is weeping
produced by some other means?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It depends on the tree, and on what you mean by ``progeny.''
Weeping trees, whose branches defy logic by hanging downward
instead of reaching for the sun, are mutations. The trees may be
grafted, but they are not, as a sculptor friend of mine slyly
insists, grafted upside down. Even novelty-hungry growers aren't
doing that quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   The mutations happen naturally on a single branch of a tree that
otherwise grows normally. Buds from these weeping branches can be
grafted onto hardier rootstock to extend their growing range, or
cuttings from the branches can be rooted on their own. Such
vegetative propagation will result in weeping progeny.
</P>
<P>
   Planting seeds, however, is problematic. The offspring of most
mutations revert back to the original form, so the odds of getting
a weeping tree are less than fifty-fifty. But there are trees, like
the weeping willow, whose seeds will reliably produce chips off the
old block.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
