<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV09-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 9, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My hobby is working with and repairing antiques and I need to
cut an oval shaped piece of glass to fit in an old picture frame,
as well as a circular piece to fit in a clock face.
 &HT;    I do not have any power tools _ just the usual assortment of
hand tools.
 &HT;    Is this something I can do myself using just a regular glass
cutter?
 &HT;    A: You will need a top quality glass cutter, preferably one with
a carbide wheel.
 &HT;    Clean the glass thoroughly and draw the outline of the shape to
be cut on the glass, using a marking pencil and a wood or cardboard
pattern to form the circle or oval.
 &HT;    Place the glass on a flat surface padded with several layers of
newspaper, then dip the cutting wheel of the glass cutter into
kerosene.
 &HT;    Score the glass around the circular or oval pattern marked on
the glass, holding the cutter between the forefinger and index
finger while gripping with the thumb.
 &HT;    Move it along with steady pressure in one direction to create a
tearing sound.
 &HT;    Then use the cutter to score additional marks radiating out from
this outline to the edges (as shown in the illustration).
 &HT;    Turn the glass over and tap along the score marks with the blunt
end of the cutter, causing the glass to crack along those marks.
 &HT;    You can then carefully break away the scrap pieces with a
flat-jaw pliers.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our kitchen was originally painted with an oil base
semi-gloss enamel, but we painted over this with a latex semi-gloss
paint about a year ago.
 &HT;    This paint tends to chip and flake off when nicked, so we plan
to repaint again.
 &HT;    What should we do to prevent this happening next time?
 &HT;    A: The last coat of paint is not bonding properly to the old
paint.
 &HT;    This could be because the old paint was still glossy when you
painted over it, or because the old surface was not clean.
 &HT;    Your only sure cure now is to remove all of the paint down to
the bare surface, using a chemical paint remover.
 &HT;    Then start from scratch by applying a first coat of a
stain-killing sealer before finishing with two coats of the paint
of your choice.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The stairs in my front hall make a squeaking noise when
stepped on. How can I correct this before I put down carpet on
these steps?
 &HT;    A: Stair squeaks are usually caused by loose treads (steps) that
move slightly when stepped on.
 &HT;    They need to be fastened down more securely _ usually by driving
screws down through the tread so they go into the top of the riser
under that tread.
 &HT;    Make certain you drill pilot holes for the screws first, and be
sure the screws go into the top of the riser.
 &HT;    Countersink the head of each screw slightly below the surface,
then fill the hole that remains with a matching colored wood
plastic.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My house has a shallow crawl space under it instead of a
basement.
 &HT;    Since this space is really unusable, I would like to build a
regular basement under the existing house.
 &HT;    Is this possible?
 &HT;    A: Yes, but it is usually a very expensive job that calls for
the services of an experienced contractor _ and possibly an
architect.
 &HT;    In some cases you may have to put in a whole new foundation, but
this is something that only an architect or engineer can determine.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``CUTTING CIRCLE OF GLASS'' goes with
this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: After scoring the circle and radial lines going out
from it, the small pieces of waste glass can be broken off with
flat-jaw pliers.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
