u l BC-SLEEPING-PORCH-NYT &LR;      06-21 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-PORCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET SUMMER NIGHTS ON THE SLEEPING PORCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By LUCIAN K. TRUSCOTT IV    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just outside the door of my writing room here in Hollywood there
is a collage of snapshots my mother put together for a family
reunion some years back. There's a photo of me in my high school
ROTC drill-team uniform, and one of my brother Frank splitting
wood.
</P>
<P>
   But the snapshot that catches my eye every time I walk by was
taken when I was about 6 and Frank was 4. We're asleep on a couple
of cots on my grandparents' sleeping porch, sheets thrown back
exposing our scrawny little bodies, the fetid darkness of a summer
night in Washington, D.C., visible through the screened walls of
the porch. We spent every summer sleeping on a screen porch in
those days, when air-conditioning was an exclusive feature of the
movie theater downtown, nowhere in evidence in our home or the
homes of anyone we knew.
</P>
<P>
   The sleeping porch was something we looked forward to, when the
heat and humidity would finally build to the point that the cots
would be dragged out and once again we'd be exposed to the elements
_ cooled, if only slightly, by an itinerant breeze, sung to sleep
by the insistent nighttime chatter of cicadas.
</P>
<P>
   The best nights were the ones when a sudden thunderstorm would
blow through, and our father or grandfather would lower the outside
shutters. We'd move our cots back against the wall of the house,
and the wind would whistle through the screens, and the rain, if it
blew hard enough, would come horizontally through the shutters, and
you felt like you were on a ship somewhere at sea, taking water
over the bow. After the second or third storm of the summer, the
excitement would wane, and we would awake in the morning to find
that our beds had been moved and the shutters lowered while we
remained asleep.
</P>
<P>
   When my wife and I bought a 1921 house in Hollywood a few years
ago, the last room our realtor showed us was at the end of the
house, above what had been the servants' quarters. As we walked up
the backstairs into the rather long and narrow room, the real
estate agent said in defense of the peculiar room, ``Now this room
has a very interesting history.''
</P>
<P>
   I felt the slant in the floor, picked up the corner of a
seriously deteriorated carpet, and sure enough, the flooring was
tin covered in canvas, necessary to allow the rain to run off. A
sleeping porch had been enclosed at some point in the past.
</P>
<P>
   One of these days we'll save up the money and file for the
permits and take out the exterior walls and find some place that
has still got good quality copper screening, and we'll return the
old room at the west end of the house to its rightful incarnation,
and we'll let our 6-year-old daughter, Lilly, have some friends for
a sleepover. We'll tuck them in and pray for rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0850 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      06-21 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, June 22, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-TRADE (Washington) _ The House is on the verge of allowing
food and medicine to be sent to Cuba for the first time in 40
years. A provision sponsored by Washington state Republican George
Nethercutt would aid struggling farmers by opening new markets. It
would remove barriers that have prevented shipments of food and
medicine to Iran, Libya, Sudan and North Korea as well as Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Pope. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT-MINES (Balmat, N.Y.) _ The tombstones of Talcville
and Balmat and Hailesville tell the story. Beneath them lie
generations of talc miners, and the numbers carved in the marble
and granite stones show that generations here run short. Many of
the men died young _ in their late 40s and 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Mining has always been a perilous profession, but few of these
men died from caved-in shafts or any of the multitude of accidents
that torment humans extracting minerals from the earth. Far more of
them died the excruciating death of suffocation _ from lungs made
uselessly rigid by scarring from deeply embedded mineral fibers,
lungs with cancerous tumors, lungs filled with muddy-yellow fluid
the consistency of honey.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT-MINE-NIOS (Washington) _ Two decades ago, a U.S.
government study concluded that workers at R.T. Vanderbilt Co. talc
mines were dying from asbestos-related disease. But an unauthorized
collaboration between Vanderbilt and two government scientists
attempted to discredit the study, and influenced a federal agency
to abandon efforts to regulate the asbestos fibers found in the
talc.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT-MINE-DOCTOR (Undated) _ George Wineburgh found
asbestosis in the lungs of hundreds of New York talc miners. He
lost his job and was blacklisted by local medical societies for his
pains.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVOR (Undated) _ From a Dumpster in Burbank, we've come
across discarded network plans to combat the success of CBS's
``Survivor.'' Among the ideas rejected: ``Imbiber,'' in which 16
people on a desert island must drink a six-pack a day but can't go
to the bathroom, and ``Godiva,'' in which 16 long-haired women eat
pricey bon-bons while riding naked on on horseback on a deserted
beach.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Mariners vs. Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   By John Hickey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Coming off a weekend when Tiger Woods
and Shaquille O'Neal established upper limits of greatness in their
sports, they are being pigeon-holed into their ``places in
history.'' But let's hold off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0854 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GUN-CHECKS-HNS &LR;      06-21 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CHECKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `INSTANT' CHECKS ON GUN BUYERS ARE NOT ALWAYS FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Instant background checks on gun buyers are causing
``needless delay'' because the FBI's computer system sputters and
breaks down, Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin G. Hatch said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The system is ``delaying one-quarter of the firearms purchases
in America,'' Hatch, R-Utah, told a Senate Judiciary Committee
panel that is examining the National Instant Criminal Background
Check System.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of an instant check, we have a system that too often
causes needless delay to law-abiding citizens who are simply
exercising their constitutional rights,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the Clinton administration launched the background
check system 18 months ago to stop gun sales to convicted felons,
fugitives from the law, people subject to court-issued restraining
orders or people who are mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   The background checks are done by licensed gun dealers who
access government computers.
</P>
<P>
   According to FBI data, 72 percent of all background checks are
completed within 30 seconds, 95 percent are completed within two
hours and the remaining 5 percent may take a few days. The system
has checked out 13 million applicants; 2 percent _ more than
116,000 applicants _ were denied the weapons they wanted to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the system suffered outages for more than 215 hours
last year.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Loesch, assistant director of the criminal justice
information services division at the FBI, agreed that the system
needs improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Loesch told the hearing that ``some kind of a bug or something
inside the data base'' caused the FBI's instant background check
system to crash last month for four days.
</P>
<P>
   He said the instant check system is complicated because it must
search three different databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is meld all these things together now and
we're learning as we try to make this better,'' Loesch said.
``We're looking at over 60 software fixes to make this system more
reliable The system is very complicatedWe're going to get there,
it's a matter of tweaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., said the system has been
``highly effective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the system slows down, it may be for a good reason,''
Durbin said, adding that gun applicants who are forced to wait more
than 24 hours for background checks are 20 times more likely to be
prohibited from buying a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   But Robin Ball of Spokane, Wash., a licensed gun dealer who owns
a shooting range, said 40 percent of her firearms sales were
delayed by background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not uncommon for a customer to cancel a sale because we
can't get a background check,'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., the top Democrat on the
Judiciary panel, introduced legislation Wednesday that would
reimburse states if they choose to do their own instant background
checks rather than rely on the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 15 states do their own background checks.
</P>
<P>
   They are: Arizona, California, Colorado, Connecticut, Florida,
Georgia, Hawaii, Illinois, Nevada, New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
Tennessee, Utah, Vermont and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Another 11 states help the FBI by performing their own instant
background checks for handgun purchases. They are: Iowa, Michigan,
Nebraska, New York, North Carolina, Indiana, Maryland, New
Hampshire, Oregon, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
