<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-REAL-ESTATE-RAGE-2TAK     06-21 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-ESTATE-RAGE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOILED HOME BUYERS TAKE TO THE COUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By TRACIE ROZHON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Yorkers are mad about real estate. So are
Californians. Texans, too.
</P>
<P>
   Boiling mad.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Kandel, 49, a costume jewelry designer in Manhattan, is
furious: no more apartment hunting. He is fed up with facing one
obstacle after another in a month of searching, in which all he
found were one-bedroom apartments that start at $400,000,
garbage-strewn backyards and brokers he described as arrogant and
unhelpful. ``You feel you have no allies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, Steve Cowan, 41, a hospital technician with two
children, angrily called his yearlong search ``a never-ending
battle.'' He thought he could find a house for $150,000 in the
neighborhood where his wife, Anne, grew up. But now, he said,
``prices keep getting jacked up to the point where people who work
real hard can't touch the house they want.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Oakland, Calif., Kevin Griffith, who works for a
developer of moderate-income housing, has been looking for a ``not
very extravagant 1920s bungalow _ two bedrooms, one bath on a
3,000-square-foot lot.'' He and his wife have lost five bidding
wars since April 1. They started looking in 1998, but dropped out
six months later because brokers told them the market was cooling.
Now, Griffith said ruefully, they would be forced to pay $100,000
more for bungalows they looked at then. ``Now they tell me the
market may be cooling again, but the house I wanted last week had
10 offers on it!''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of relentless price escalation, angry
customers are slamming down phones, brokers said, and picking
pointless fights with sellers. They are even stalking out of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Road rage, take a back seat. Make way for real estate rage. See
that page of glossy real estate ads _ with nothing less than
$800,000? Just lost your third bidding war? Join the crowd. House
hunters are suffering from battle fatigue brought on by the highest
real estate prices in history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the National Association of Realtors reported that home
sales in April were down 6 percent from March, prices are
continuing to rise, said Walter Molony, a spokesman for the trade
association. And competition in the country's hottest markets, like
Silicon Valley, Dallas and Manhattan, is still hot enough to ignite
bidding wars.
</P>
<P>
   The number of frustrated shoppers _ at all income levels _ is
growing, real estate brokers said. For house hunters like Griffith,
33, and his wife, Adrienne Oberstein, 34, their inability to find a
home is serious: Oberstein is pregnant, and the one-bedroom
apartment that they are renting is too small.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do if you are feeling powerless? One man spends
his Sundays tearing the real estate ads into very long pieces.
Others focus their ire on the sellers, branding them as greedy and
dishonest. Still others have turned on their brokers, saying these
bearers of bad news have betrayed them.
</P>
<P>
   Some even vent their frustration by the hour _ on the
therapist's couch _ one place they know someone will listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, I'm hearing, `I followed all the rules,''' said
Dr. Mark Levy, a psychiatrist in San Francisco, where median sales
prices have gone up 25 percent in 12 months to $365,300, according
to the National Association of Realtors. `` `I got 100 graduate
school degrees, and why can't I buy the house I think I should
have?'''
</P>
<P>
   One patient told Levy he watched ``an already inflated house
shoot up to $2.6 million in 10 hours and then sold to some
30-year-old dot-com guy.'' Levy added: ``There's a lot of
self-blame: What did I do wrong? How stupid was I?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dave Davis, a psychiatrist in Atlanta, where real estate
agents said house values in the most expensive neighborhoods had
doubled in five years, said real estate rage ``is a terrific
problem _ just about every day, one of my patients brings it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And although heartbreak happens in every income bracket these
days, real estate agents and therapists agree: The people who yell
the loudest are usually those with the most money.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has no problem identifying. He lives _ and works _ in
Buckhead, one of Atlanta's fanciest suburbs, and his clientele
includes lots of wealthy men and women in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of anger, a lot of disappointment here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, where prices are up at least 15 percent in the best
neighborhoods since the spring of 1999, Dr. Mark Unterberg says
home buyers are not exactly angry: They are despairing. ``Envy is
also a good word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Dr. Gail Saltz, an instructor in psychiatry at New
York Presbyterian Hospital, said her patients ``are certainly
outraged and disgusted and freaked out'' by New York City prices,
where the average apartment just hit $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't believe the market keeps going up,'' she said.
``They have a presumption about certain basic things they can
expect in life.''
</P>
<P>
   An inability to afford that Park Avenue condo, she said, can
lead to distress. ``They see a multimillion-dollar asking price
they can't afford,'' she said. ``They feel like losers. Here you
are making a pretty good salary, but in this crazy situation you
can't compete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, what are the most exciting things in life?'' she
said. ``Sex? Paying incredible amounts of money for real estate? If
you can't have the first, the second fills a lot of fantasy
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But even before they take their anger to the therapist,
embittered house and apartment hunters often take it to the broker,
who is usually the bearer of bad tidings: Outbid again. Turned down
by the co-op board. The sellers accepted your offer and then
reneged after they got a higher one. Or the simplest of all: Sorry,
you can't possibly afford what you think you should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of rage right now,'' said Diane Waller, a real
estate agent in Manhattan. ``People's homes are such emotionally
charged issues in the first place. It really is enraging to be out
there and keep missing.''
</P>
<P>
   The agents are angry, too. ``After all, we're out the
commission,'' said Frank Newbold, manager of the East Hampton,
N.Y., office of Sotheby's International Real Estate. ``We don't get
paid when a deal falls through.'' He said he spends hours
counseling angry millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them it isn't a car crash, it isn't cancer,'' he said.
``I tell them to get some perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency is to find someone to blame. ``It's never your own
fault,'' said Frederick Peters, president of Ashforth Warburg Real
Estate in New York. ``So you've got to slap the underling. You've
got to slap the broker around.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad behavior is rife right now _ especially among those
unaccustomed to hearing no. ``They went to Harvard Business School,
and they're making a starting salary of $175,000, and they think
they're little masters of the universe,'' said Clark Halstead, head
of the Halstead Property Co. in Manhattan. ``But guess what? With
that salary, they might be able to afford a studio!''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding like a psychotherapist himself, Halstead said the
run-of-the-mill bonus baby, faced with the Manhattan market, first
feels ``outrageous denial.'' This is followed, he continued, by ``a
quieter resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kandel, who has his own jewelry boutique at Bergdorf Goodman,
blames the brokers, not for the market's being so high, but for
their attitude. ``It makes me furious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents made him feel ``they don't want to bother with you unless
you have a spare million you want to spend,'' he said, adding:
``Then their attitude is: Well, of course it's not perfect. This is
New York. If you don't want it, somebody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he enlisted the broker, Kandel, like so many before
him, complained that the broker usually represents the seller
legally. ``They're always watching you for your reaction,'' he
said. ``They show you places with garbage strewn all over, and if
you react negatively, that's it _ they never show you anything
else. It gives you a feeling of hopelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   And what do the psychotherapists tell all these would-be
property owners, these frustrated masters of the half acre they
would like to survey?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them that's life,'' said Davis of Atlanta. ``Life's not
fair. Just like in high school, not everybody could have the
best-looking girlfriend or the most expensive car. They've got to
get centered.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
