</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MICHIGAN0622-COX     06-21 2406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michigan voters give Bush and Gore a run for their money
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ The next time Democrat Al Gore visits Michigan,
autoworker John McGrath might tell the vice president to shove his
presidential campaign right up the exhaust pipe of the nearest
Chevrolet, Chrysler or Ford.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath twice voted for Bill Clinton but Gore's blasts at the
internal combustion engine and support for normal trade relations
with China have soured the Delphi Automotive Systems tool designer
on the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, retired mortgage banker Carol Tomasi still smarts
about how Michigan Republicans have treated her candidate, Arizona
Sen. John McCain, since McCain gave George W. Bush a Texas-sized
thrashing in the state's
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential primary in February.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shouldn't count on Tomasi's vote Nov. 7, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath and Tomasi are reminders of the fences both Gore and
Bush must mend in Michigan before either can hope to capture the
state's 18 electoral votes. Neither candidate has captured the
electorate's fancy in a state both parties consider a ``must win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the two best we can find?'' asked John Ruggero,
corporate counsel for a real estate title company in Mt. Clemens, a
Detroit suburb. ``Neither one kind of thrills me.''
</P>
<P>
   After picking Republicans Ronald Reagan and George Bush in three
straight president elections, Michigan voters gave their support to
Bill Clinton in 1992 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won decisively enough to make it seem possible that
Michigan's so-called ``Reagan Democrats'' had abandoned their fling
with Republicans. In 1992, for example, Clinton got 44 percent of
the vote to 36 percent for President George Bush, the current
Republican candidate's father. Ross Perot got 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Ohio _ where Clinton beat Bush by just 2 points _
this was a Clinton landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's positions on the environment and China trade have chilled
his relations with some Democrats and swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   Third-term Republican Gov. John Engler, unable to deliver the
state for his party in the last two presidential elections,
believes George W. Bush is the right candidate to reverse the
results.
</P>
<P>
   To Engler's embarrassment, however, Bush was the wrong candidate
in the Republican primary, which was open to all voters. McCain,
with strong support from Democrats and independents, won. Despite
efforts by Engler and McCain's Michigan chairman, state Sen. John
Schwartz of Battle Creek, to patch things up, many McCain
supporters have yet to jump on Bush's presidential bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the country has barely begun to focus on the
election, the hotly contested Republican primary and controversy
over trade with China already have put the campaign on voters'
radar here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Michigan's U.S. Senate race _ pitting incumbent
Republican Spencer Abraham against U.S. Rep. Deborah Stabenow,
D-Lansing _ is considered one of the nation's most competitive. And
the fall ballot also includes a school voucher proposal that has
support from conservative Republicans and black pastors in
inner-city Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear which presidential candidate might benefit most
from these other ballot issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan could go either way,'' said Democratic pollster Ed
Sarpolus of Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Steve Mitchell of East Lansing, forecast a
close race as well, but said, ``I think ultimately Bush will take
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   CLEAN AIR, FREE TRADE AND AL GORE
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, 55, has worked in the automobile industry for 34 years,
first for General Motors and more recently for Delphi Automotive
Systems, a GM spin-off. McGrath lives in a suburb of Flint, the
city where General Motors was born and where sit-down strikes in
the 1930s established the United Auto Workers as a force to be
reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   There are 493,165 workers in Michigan with jobs related to the
automobile industry _ nearly as many people as the 495,817 who live
in the city of Cleveland _ according to the University of
Michigan's Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore came into the presidential campaign already suspect to
McGrath and many others because his 1992 book, ``Earth in the
Balance,'' talked about eliminating the internal combustion engine
in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore joined President Clinton _ as well as Bush _ in
backing normal trade relations with China, it was more than McGrath
and others like him could take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure the Democrats were going to get us out of
the cesspool of swirling down into world trade organizations,''
McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen auto-related employment plummet in Genesee County,
which includes Flint, from nearly 51,000 in 1984 to 21,300 last
year. To McGrath, normal trade relations with China sounds like a
formula for sending auto jobs
</P>
<P>
   overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a narrow focus _ my job and the jobs of a lot of people
in this area,'' said McGrath. ``We're talking long-term here.''
</P>
<P>
   His views were echoed by United Auto Workers President Stephen
Yokich, who lives in suburban Detroit, after the U.S. House in May,
with Gore's and Clinton's backing, voted for normalizing China
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``One moment, presidential candidate Gore is telling the labor
movement that he believes human rights, workers' rights and
environmental protections should be included in core trade
agreements; the next, Vice President Gore is holding hands with the
profiteers of the world,'' Yokich said.
</P>
<P>
   While the national AFL-CIO has endorsed Gore, the UAW hasn't,
and Yokich said the union will explore alternatives to the major
party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to forget about party labels and instead focus on
supporting candidates, such as (the Green Party's) Ralph Nader, who
will take a stand based on what is right, not what big money
dictates,'' Yokich said.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, who as a technical worker is not a UAW member, said
he's not likely to back a third party candidate, although Pat
Buchanan of the Reform Party, as well as Nader, is seeking votes in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't vote for idiots,'' said McGrath. ``That kind of
narrows the field to nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he's inclined to support Bush, even though Bush, like
Gore, supports the China trade agreement. He said he expected the
Republicans to take that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it's an anticipated evil,'' McGrath said. ``From the
Democrats we were hoping for a little help for the working
people.''
</P>
<P>
   While some autoworkers may sit the election out, McGrath won't.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports more gun control; Bush doesn't, said McGrath, a
hunter and fisherman. That's enough to put him, at least
temporarily, on Bush's side.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's trouble with autoworkers and the UAW hasn't gone
unnoticed by Republicans, including Engler. He and Bush are going
after those votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made one UAW (plant) gate stop,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   Engler said he's won election three times without the support of
labor leaders but with the backing of rank-and-file members. They
like the Republican emphasis on tax cuts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their better bet is the Republican Party to keep what they're
earning,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krell, UAW communications director, said Gore and the union
may not be through talking.
</P>
<P>
   Krell said the union agrees with the vice president on the
desire to produce cars that pollute less. The union's goal,
however, is to produce such cars in this country, not overseas.
</P>
<P>
   While they will continue to disagree on China, Gore must make
the case that he is better than Bush on other issues such as Social
Security, prescription drugs for senior citizens and workers' right
to organize, Krell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a case that he can make,'' said Krell. ``He's
going to have to work a little harder to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN WINS AND LOSES
</P>
<P>
   Retired mortgage banker Carol Tomasi, 61, cheered Feb. 22 when
her candidate, Sen. John McCain, defeated Bush in Michigan's
Republican primary, getting 51 percent to Bush's 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those cheers turned to disappointment a month ago when delegates
to the Michigan Republican Convention all but ignored McCain
backers in
</P>
<P>
   choosing delegates to this summer's Republican National
Convention. Instead, Bush supporters will dominate the Michigan
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain didn't like the way his supporters were treated and
cancelled two Michigan campaign appearances for U.S. House
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, when we began this crusade I told you I would
always tell the truth,'' McCain said in an e-mail to his followers.
``The truth is what is happening in the Michigan Republican Party
is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomasi agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to do any campaigning (for Bush),'' she said.
Worse for Bush, she's not even sure she'll vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still looking over the issues,'' said Tomasi, who liked
McCain's straightforward approach and his push for campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John Schwartz, McCain's Michigan chairman, believes
McCain ``did get the shaft,'' but he is working with Gov. Engler
and others to heal the wounds between McCain and Bush supporters.
Schwartz believes that by the time of the fall campaign, Republican
forces will be marching together.
</P>
<P>
   He also is thrilled at the response he has gotten to 5,000
bumper stickers he had made with the message: ``Bush-McCain
America's Choice.'' Although McCain has insisted that he won't
accept a position as Bush's vice presidential running mate,
Schwartz hasn't given up hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is exceedingly popular in this state,'' Schwartz
said.
</P>
<P>
   That would not sway Tomasi, however. In fact, she said it's a
lousy idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very upset,'' Tomasi said. ``I think (McCain's) too
important to the Republican Party. As vice president, he would be
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING ON THE BASES
</P>
<P>
   Not every voter in Michigan is miffed at Gore and Bush, longing
for McCain or already tuned out of what promises to be a very busy
fall campaign. Some McCain supporters besides Schwartz have come to
grips with what they consider political reality: Bush is the
Republican candidate and he's preferable to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to vote today, I would vote for an elephant if he
were running against Gore,'' said Virginia Butler, 67, a retired
accountant from Sterling Heights, a Detroit suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state in Ottawa County along Lake Michigan, there's
almost a frenzy for Bush. The county is considered the state's most
conservative and dependably Republican. It's part of one of only
two Michigan congressional districts that Bush carried in the
February primary.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Holmes, 59, doubles as party chairman and chairman of the
political science department at Hope College in Holland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time a Democrat carried this county was McClellan in
1864,'' Holmes said. Civil War Gen. George McClellan lost the 1864
election to a Republican incumbent named Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   This year, when Bush showed up for the county party's Lincoln
Day dinner, 1,200 people showed up, triple the usual turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do that if the people aren't fired up,'' said
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Clinton feelings help Bush in the county, dominated by
residents of Dutch descent, Holmes added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This county is very strong on family values,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blueberry farmer Kenneth Reenders of Grand Haven, a town of
12,000 in northern Ottawa County, is in that group. Reenders still
can't figure out how Clinton managed to stay in office after the
Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part that really gets me is that he lied,'' said Reenders.
``Everybody makes a mistake. If I would have done that, they would
have thrown the book at me. Any college president, he'd be out like
a light.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone judges Gore by Clinton's missteps.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Detroit remains a Democratic stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been voting since I was old enough to vote,'' said Rodney
Means, 54, a barber at Rayfield's Friendly Barber Shop on the
city's east side. ``I'm going with Gore because he is a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't care about what Clinton did or didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all doing it,'' he said. ``He just happened to get
caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt Grayson, who was getting a haircut in a chair next to
Means', said he likes Gore and plans to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been one of our most active vice presidents,'' said
Grayson, 51, an investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 miles north along Interstate 75 in the suburbs of
Flint, retired autoworker Van Williams, 93, also plans to back the
vice president. Williams was born in Tennessee, came to Flint in
1923 and participated in the UAW's seminal
</P>
<P>
   sit-down strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a Democrat all my life,'' said Williams, who chatted
briefly before getting ready to play golf. He doesn't like what
Bush has said about Gore. ``Bush has been putting out very
slanderous remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   Such ``go-Gore'' cheers are good news to state Rep. LaMar
Lemmons, a Detroit Democrat. Lemmons originally backed New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic nomination but is trying to
work up enthusiasm for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Democratic lawmakers hope for a strong turnout on
election day not only to help Gore but to help them take back the
Michigan House, which Republicans control 58-52.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons and state Rep. Kwame M. Kilpatrick of Detroit, who hopes
to become the first black speaker of the Michigan House if
Democrats gain control, hope to improve voter turnout in Detroit.
Clinton won in the city in 1996 with 95 percent of the vote, but he
got just 224,371 votes _ fewer than the 260,991 Democrat Michael
Dukakis got in his 1988 losing effort and far fewer than the
322,394 Walter Mondale got in his landslide loss to Ronald Reagan
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the vice president is going to rise to the occasion,''
Kilpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons hopes so, but he is wary of Engler. The Republican
governor want to make amends for what happened to Bush in the
primary, said Lemmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's wounded,'' Lemmons said. ``There's nothing worse
than a wounded animal. I don't agree with him. I have the utmost
respect for his ability. He's the smartest governor we've ever
had.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
