</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MICHIGAN-BAR0622-COX     06-21 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-BAR0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summing up the presidential campaign from Michigan: ``Everything
is so monotone.''
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. _ Democrat Al Gore got Maureen Franey's
attention but not necessarily her vote when he picked L'Anse Creuse
Middle School North in Macomb County to kick off his ``School
Days'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fabulous,'' said Franey, 48, an executive secretary at
Philip F. Greco Title Co. in nearby Mount Clemens. ``That went
along way with me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Macomb County, just north of Detroit, gained a
national reputation as home to thousands of so-called ``Reagan
Democrats.'' These were voters who historically had backed
Democrats in presidential campaigns but found the optimistic and
socially conservative Ronald Reagan more in tune than incumbent
Democrat Jimmy Carter with their political and cultural tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton helped get Democrats back to the White House by
moving the party to the center and appealing to voters in Macomb
County and similar counties across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Macomb County went with incumbent President George Bush
against Clinton even though Clinton won statewide in Michigan. In
1996, county voters backed Clinton over Republican Bob Dole as
Clinton again carried the state. While the voter trend here has
been Republican in recent presidential elections, the electorate
includes a mix of blue- and white-collar workers who, when
questioned, are likely to say they vote for the candidate, not the
party.
</P>
<P>
   With 787,698 residents, it's the state's third most populous
county after Wayne (Detroit) and Oakland, another suburban county
north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to the middle school on March 24 particularly
caught Franey's attention because her daughter, now 22, had
attended the school. Franey is also a big fan of Gore's wife,
Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a regular gal,'' Franey said.
</P>
<P>
   Franey said, however, that in the last two presidential
elections she stuck with Republicans. This year, she remains
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't a big Clinton fan. . . . There's something about
him,'' she said. There's also ``something about'' George W. Bush
that doesn't appeal to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got that smirk,'' Franey said.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that could turn her toward Gore is gun control. She
favors more of it and liked the recent ``Million Mothers' March''
on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to be collecting Uzis . . . automatic weapons,''
said Franey.
</P>
<P>
   Don Foley said he's closer to making up his mind. Foley voted
for Reagan once and for George Bush against Michael Dukakis, but
then voted twice for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaning toward Gore. I like what's been going on, not with
Bill Clinton's personal habits, but I like what's been going on
with the economy,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, 51, commutes every day from the county to Romulus, a
suburb south of Detroit, where he's an assistant high school
principal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore lacks political charisma, which hurts him, said Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (voters) want a Harrison Ford for president but they want
him with the morals of Al Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trish Shandor, 27, a student at Macomb County Community College,
is one of many Michigan voters still yearning for Arizona Sen. John
McCain, whom she supported in the Republican primary in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believed McCain had a voice,'' Shandor said. ``He had
a strong assertiveness I don't see in Bush or Gore. He's so in tune
with the people. He wanted to make government work for the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Messina, 30, also a student at the community college,
leans toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has family values,'' Messina said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she supports more gun control, which Bush
doesn't advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people should carry guns,'' she said. ``This is
not what the United States is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Philip F. Greco Title Co., Mary Brusseau, a
supervisor still is trying to make up her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Brusseau, 51, remembers being a ``Kennedy Girl'' when John F.
Kennedy ran for president in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hat, banner. . .,'' she recalled. She voted for McCain
in the Republican primary but isn't committed to either Bush or
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is so monotone,'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   In presidential elections she generally has supported Democrats,
including Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   This time she's just looking for a candidate with whom she can
connect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has me yet,'' she said. ``Nobody has me willing to go
out and vote for them.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
