<HEADER>
A0869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FALL-BOOKS0622-COX     06-21 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-BOOKS0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New fall books will knock your sandals off
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The arrival of wintry fashions in the stores
always makes me feel summer is ending too soon, but fall book
titles have the opposite effect. They always hold out the promise
of something better.
</P>
<P>
   One book worth looking forward to is former New York Times
investigative reporter Nicholas Gage's ``Greek Fire'' (Knopf,
October), an account of the romance between shipping magnate
Aristotle Onassis and the great diva, Maria Callas _ including how
the relationship survived his marriage to Jacqueline Kennedy. Gage,
who came to America as a child during the Greek Civil War in 1948,
wrote a powerful memoir about his mother titled ``Eleni,'' which
became a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth anticipating is a new book by Stephen Ambrose, the
historian best known for ``Undaunted Courage.'' In ``Nothing Like
It in the World,'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, September), he writes about
the men who built the transcontinental railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Two New York Times correspondents, Nicholas D. Kristof and
Sheryl WuDunn, provide a timely report on Asia and the way it's
reshaping the world in ``Thunder from the East: Portrait of a
Rising Asia'' (Knopf, September).
</P>
<P>
   Other promising nonfiction titles include Austin biographer H.W.
Brands' ``The First American: The Life and Times of Benjamin
Franklin'' (Doubleday, October). Brands draws on previously
unpublished letters. Other new biographies include ``Citizen
Greenspan: The Man Behind the Money'' by Justin Martin (Perseus,
November) and ``Hitler'' by Ian Kershaw (Norton, September).
</P>
<P>
   The great South American writer Jorge Luis Borges has a new
book, despite the fact that he died in 1986. ``This Craft of
Verse'' (Harvard University Press, September) collects lost
lectures he delivered in English at Harvard in 1967-68.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, ``Nightline's'' Ted Koppel becomes the latest TV
news anchor with a book: ``Off Camera: Private Moments Made
Public'' (Knopf, September). The same, but different, is columnist
Liz Smith's story, ``Natural Blonde'' (Hyperion, September)
Columnist Anna Quindlen departs from her usual territory with ``A
Short Guide to a Happy Life,'' (Random House, October), advising
readers on how to live fully, with awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Memoirs rule again this year. In ``No One's Perfect'' (Kodansha,
September), Hirotada Ototake writes about growing up in Japan _ a
country that traditionally shields people with disabilities from
the public eye _ without arms or legs and fighting for the chance
to lead a normal life. In ``Before I Say Goodbye,'' English
journalist Ruth Picardie (Holt, October) describes with wit and
precision the final year of her life. She died at 33 from cancer, a
month after her twins' second birthday. There's also a new photo
memoir of the expatriate writer and musician Paul Bowles,
``Yesterday's Perfume'' (Clarkson Potter, November) by photographer
Cherie Nutting; former Austinite Celia Morris' ``Finding Celia's
Place'' (Texas A&AMP;M Press, September), about growing up in the '50s,
ambitious but limited by the times; and African American journalist
Debra Dickerson's ``An American Story'' (Pantheon, September).
</P>
<P>
   A fun title is Sam Sifton's on-target ``A Field Guide to the
Yettie: America's Young, Entrepreneurial Technocrats'' (Talk
Miramax Books, Nov.)
</P>
<P>
   Texas photographer Keith Carter has a haunting new horse photo
collection, ``Ezekiel's Horse'' (UT Press, November), and Laura
Wilson, known for her photos of Navajos, has a new book called
``Hutterites of Montana'' (Yale University Press, October).
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of good fiction will find much to engage them. Watch for
Carlos Fuentes' novel ``The Years with Laura Diaz'' (Farrar,
Straus, October), featuring his first major female protagonist;
Margaret Atwood's novel ``The Blind Assassin'' (Doubleday,
September); Alice Walker's stories ``The Way Forward is With a
Broken Heart'' (Random House, October); National Book Award winner
Ha Jin's stories, ``The Bridegroom,'' (Pantheon, October); Caleb
Carr's novel, ``Killing Time'' (Random House, September); Jim
Harrison's novellas, ``The Beast God Forgot to Invent''
(Grove/Atlantic, October); Michael Chabon's novel, ``The Amazing
Adventures of Kavalier &AMP; Clay'' (Random House, September); and
Canadian Bonnie Burnard's novel ``A Good House'' (Henry Holt,
September). There'll be lots of first novelists, plus reliable
repeaters like Anne Rice, Bruce Sterling, Kinky Friedman, Joe
Lansdale and Stephen Coonts.
</P>
<P>
   So, look forward to the fall. This is just a sample.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
