<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-KOREA-CONTRASTS-$ADV2     06-21 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-CONTRASTS-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE KOREAS MOVE A STEP CLOSER, YET REMAIN WORLDS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 25)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Dozens of young people crowd around a stage
outside the high-rise, smoke wafting into the night sky as techno
music blares, a ring of red neon lights running up the building.
</P>
<P>
   This could be New York, Miami or Los Angeles, but it's the pulse
of another great city, Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   It's boomtown squared, a city of 11 million where cars and
motorcycles speed along packed streets by day, the din of horns
urging cars and pedestrians on. At night young people walk through
packed markets with a swagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work hard,'' said Michael Lee, an executive in Seoul.
``Really, we achieved no less than a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul is a showcase for the remarkable rise of South Korea from
the ashes of a war that began 50 years ago today and devastated the
peninsula. It is also the polar opposite of Pyongyang, North Korea
_ the hub of a nation where famine and economic stagnation are the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the historic summit earlier this month between
the leaders of North and South Korea _ two nations that are
technically still at war _ other contrasts stand out.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean exports include semiconductor chips, electronic
components, appliances, ships, cars, steel and machinery. Bereft of
such industries for the most part and geared to military
production, the insular north has long depended on subsidies from
neighboring China, and at one time, the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea, tuberculosis is at epidemic proportions,
striking peasants and the elite alike. United Nations health
officials have discovered severe malnutrition and stunting among
children.
</P>
<P>
   There is an energy crisis, too, in North Korea. Brownouts, once
scheduled to conserve power, now take place without notice and can
last days at a time, compounding the misery of the north's brutal
Siberian winters, said veteran Korea observer Marcus Noland, a
senior fellow at the nonpartisan Institute for International
Economics.
</P>
<P>
   An hour south of ``Propaganda Village,'' a North Korean ghost
town where giant speakers aimed to the south blast communist
slogans, downtown Seoul's busy Myong-dong district is lighted up
like Las Vegas in a style best described as Asian hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Korean in the south earned $8,551 last year, while
observers say his or her counterpart in the north pocketed less
than $1,000. South Koreans are more likely to own a cell phone than
an American, but they share the same taste in designer jeans,
dresses, shoes and music.
</P>
<P>
   A South Korean middle class has emerged since around 1960, when
the ordinary worker earned $79 per year. Growth has averaged around
8.8 percent since then, and today South Korea has reversed its
once-lopsided import-expert balance.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly on par with each other in 1980, the two Koreas have gone
in radically different directions in the intervening 20 years, said
L. Gordon Flake, executive director of the Mansfield Center for
Pacific Affairs, a think tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   As the south has grown wealthier, the north's economy has
shrunk. Young northerners are not as well off as they were 10 years
before, Flake said, ``and so they have no access to phones, no
international television, no knowledge of the outside world.
They're impoverished and in many cases on the brink of
starvation.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of reunification since the leadership summit ended June 15
has fired a new hunger in Seoul, where war memories are fading with
the aging veterans who fought it, and a new generation enjoys a
seemingly endless bounty of material wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The talk has included speculation that North Korean leader Kim
Jong Il and South Korean President Kim Dae-jung might win the Nobel
Peace Prize for their step toward reconciliation, the most
promising sign of rapprochement since the Korean war ended with a
fragile truce in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   While talk of eventual unification is at a feverish pitch,
practical matters remain, including the integration of two
economies and vastly different political systems. Those same issues
continue to plague a far more affluent Germany, a decade after the
unification of the communist East and democratic West.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the emerging, vocal middle class in South Korea,
observers say democracy is evolving but still immature, while the
north with Kim at the helm remains the world's only dynastic
communist state.
</P>
<P>
   Kim took power after the death in 1994 of his father, Kim Il
Sung, who had been the country's only leader since the peninsula
was divided in 1945. The government today ``in many ways remains a
theocracy with a divine leader at the top,'' Noland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
