<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CUSTOM-FURNITURE-ART-     06-21 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-FURNITURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST DESIGNS BY (YOUR NAME HERE) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are those who need furniture, and there are
those who like furniture. I count myself in the second category.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I commissioned a piece. I saw a small writing table
in a shop window in Paris, walked in on an impulse, negotiated a
variation in a different wood, and walked out with a remarkably
satisfying sensation. I now had on order a folding table for
working at my laptop, a beautiful burnt oak square on waxed steel
legs, as nicely turned as a phrase. Twelve weeks later, the table
arrived, and I was Lorenzo de Medici for the day. I even relished
the wait.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone unsatisfied by the styles, quality or similarity of
mass-produced furniture, or frustrated by the prices of vintage
furniture, commissioning a piece produces furniture specific to
your tastes and needs.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, it is an opportunity to work with an architect on
a project smaller than a house In other cases, it solves a problem
that can't be solved with existing furniture. Commissioning custom
work can be comparable to the cost and delivery time of more
expensive, mass-produced items. And it's cheaper than antiques.
</P>
<P>
   People interested in design come to the decision to participate
in it in a variety of ways. They include the New York City couple
who wanted innovative, not generic, furniture for their two young
children, and a woman in New Hampshire with a keen eye for
18th-century antiques who found most new traditional American
furniture devoid of grace and skill.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Woods, chairwoman and co-founder of J. Crew, who makes
style for a living, knew exactly what she needed to perfect her
Chelsea loft, and she knew she would never find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a picture in my mind of what I wanted, so I designed
it,'' she said. ``It's exactly what's sitting in my living room.''
Woods, whose 20th-century furniture collection includes a Charlotte
Perriand oak and steel table that in part inspired her commissions,
hired two young New York architects, Louise Harpman and Scott
Specht, to design a dining table and a sideboard. ``I didn't want
the place to be all old pieces,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   The first assignment, a monumental dining table with a companion
bench, was dictated by 100-year-old oak timbers Woods located in
Colorado. The architects presented over a dozen designs, in
drawings and models.
</P>
<P>
   ``She whittled through them and found the ones that seemed more
perfect for her,'' Specht said. The architects built a full-scale
cardboard mock-up, calibrating it by eye to fit the space
precisely. The table is 12 feet 4 inches by 3 feet 6 inches; a
steel undercarriage supports the sweeping span of oak that appears,
like a magician's assistant, to float.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also commissioned a sideboard. She showed the architects a
kitchen drawer neatly organized with silverware and asked for a
design as simple as that. The 9-foot-3-inch sideboard has 15 oak
drawers, framed in steel, with finger-width gaps that serve as
pulls. Because of difficulties in executing the design's length of
steel, the piece took three tries and seven months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's thin welded steel,'' Specht said. ``It can wave and warp
all over the place.'' The architect added a precautionary lesson:
that every original piece of design is in essence an experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can take as long to design a piece of furniture as it does
to design a whole house,'' Specht said. ``In order to do that, an
architect has to charge a fee that's commensurate with the amount
of work, so it can get expensive. And it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpman and Specht also worked recently on a project that
involved a low budget, a tight schedule and a different kind of
originality.
</P>
<P>
   James Schamus, a film producer and screenwriter, and Nancy
Kricorian, a writer, commissioned furniture for their daughters
Nona, 8, and Djuna, 4, only after shopping for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see anything that we thought was well made or
beautiful, or that suited the uses of our kids,'' Kricorian said.
Schamus asked the architects, who had designed his offices, to
submit ideas.
</P>
<P>
   What Schamus and Kricorian got was an inordinate amount of
architectural thinking for Nona's 12-by-16-foot bedroom and Djuna's
9-by-13-foot maid's room on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling carts with reversible chalkboard and Formica work
surfaces house art supplies. Nona's lower bunk bed has rolling
drawer storage below. Djuna's single bed has a rolling trundle bed
beneath for guests. Built-in desk tops can be raised as the
children grow.
</P>
<P>
   The project cost approximately $10,000, which included the gift
of a good carpenter, Anthony Sandkamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was meticulous,'' Kricorian said. ``That was my only
complaint. Something would take hours. I would say, `Tony, you have
to leave now _ my children have to go to bed.'''
</P>
<P>
   Compressing his crew into a single collaborator, Robert Cole, a
freelance art director, worked with a carpenter who was also a
designer, Eric Walton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the late 1950s, but I didn't want this to look like the
window of a SoHo shop,'' Cole said, speaking of his one-bedroom
Greenwich Village apartment, which includes furniture by Florence
Knoll and Hans J. Wegner. Instead of buying a bed, Cole had Walton
build it, for both aesthetic and practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to look like two planes floating,'' Cole said; he
also wanted handy storage and display for books. ``I did a drawing,
which had no basis in reality,'' he added,
</P>
<P>
   Walton recalled: ``I talked him out of exactly what he wanted to
do. It wasn't that structurally sound.'' Cole established his
budget, which was $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The two men exchanged several increasingly detailed sets of
drawings. Walton built a cardboard model to scale and suggested
materials. Cole chose cherry wood. The minimal-looking project
involved intricate joinery that Cole required be concealed. Walton
said that constituted much of the cost. The process took two
months.
</P>
<P>
   In Susan Cartun's case, a novel material provided the impetus to
commission. When Cartun saw the resin-topped tables designed by
Elizabeth Diller and Richard Scofidio for the newly renovated
Brasserie restaurant on West 53rd Street, she did what any New
Yorker would do _ she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Cartun played telephone: through the restaurant to the
architects, she contacted Karen Atta, at Atta Inc., who fabricated
the resin tabletops. Ten percent of her clients are individuals
with requests for residential commissions. ``The cost of custom
work is a little higher,'' Atta said, ``but it's in the same
ballpark with higher-end commercial production. We give the client
an estimate for the job right off the bat. We rarely have someone
walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartun commissioned a 10-by-4-foot dining table top, which cost
$7,000. (The $3,000 steel base was fabricated elsewhere.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed with the durability of it,'' she said. ``We
sat at the Brasserie with a fork and tried to scratch it. There was
nothing ready-made in this polyresin.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartun's tables were delivered last week after two months' work,
well within the client's grace period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You buy a piece of furniture from Europe and you wait 14 to 16
weeks,'' she said. ``And this is not what you're calling custom.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the issue ultimately is craftsmanship. David Lamb, a
woodworker based in Canterbury, N.H., and a member of the New
Hampshire Furniture Masters Association, has built furniture for
Harrison Ford, Ivan Lendl and Joan Farrel, who lives in neighboring
Concord.
</P>
<P>
   Farrel, who also collects 18th-century American antiques, has
commissioned three pieces from Lamb, including a $7,500 tiger-maple
Queen Anne-style table, which took eight months to execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go into a store and start checking it over, especially the
tables,'' she said. ``It's out of sight what they want for it and
the workmanship is pretty sad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0885 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JITNEY-THEATER-ART-$A     06-21 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JITNEY-THEATER-ART-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMBO OF ACTORS LEARNS THE JOY OF JAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Toward the end of August Wilson's ``Jitney,'' at the
Second Stage Theater off-Broadway, the drivers and other denizens
of Becker's Car Service return to their storefront office after a
funeral. As they enter one by one, you realize you have come to
know these characters so well that you feel you have shared the
loss with them, as though you, too, are a member of the mourning
party.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that final scene, the indelible performances of the
nine cast members in ``Jitney'' have made their characters so
familiar that you may believe you have lived in Pittsburgh's Hill
District all your life and that your own family has used Becker's
for years, to be ferried to the grocery store, washeteria or visits
to relatives.
</P>
<P>
   You know that if Turnbo shows up, he's going to grumble about
being kept waiting and start gossiping; if Fielding gets the call,
he's going to try to cadge a dollar extra for a pint of whiskey; if
it's Youngblood, he's going to complain about carrying anything in
his pristine trunk; if it's Doub or Becker himself, you're going to
get a little chit-chat with the ride. You know that Shealy runs the
numbers game and that Philmore is the doorman at the hotel. You
wonder whether Youngblood will finally be tamed by Rena and whether
they will ever get married, now that their boy is 2 years old. And
you will probably know all about Booster, Becker's son, who is due
to get out of prison soon.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of familiarity begins, of course, with the richly
poetic language of Wilson, a two-time Pulitzer Prize-winning
playwright whose Broadway hits include ``Ma Rainey's Black
Bottom,'' ``Fences,'' ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,'' ``Two Trains
Running'' and ``Seven Guitars.'' But while ``Jitney'' is very funny
in the idiosyncrasies of its characters, it is also a poignant
evocation of the aspirations of the late 1970s that cuts across
color lines, but that happens to be told from an African-American
perspective. That it is so full of hope against so much
disappointment reflects the indomitable spirit of all Americans
whether, as one actor in the cast put it, ``black, white or
green.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the play deals with the social and economic
troubles of the time through the impending forced closing of the
car service business, which will put the drivers out of jobs. But
as with all meaningful plays, ``Jitney'' operates on deeper levels
as well. There is the theme of forgiveness in the release of
Becker's son from prison, the sense of wasted lives and compromised
dignity in the stories of the older drivers and the dreams for the
future through the stormy relationship between Youngblood and Rena.
In the end, it is a play about the meaning of love.
</P>
<P>
   Just as composers must rely on musicians to convey the emotional
force of their music, playwrights depend on actors to bring their
characters to life. And the actors in Marion McClinton's staging of
``Jitney'' are pitch-perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons to music are not idle. In a recent conversation
with the nine-member cast at the theater, more than one spoke of
their performances and the play in musical terms, as did McClinton.
If the actors are the playwright's musicians, the director is the
conductor. And in casting the play, the quality McClinton said he
looked for first was the actor's ability to make the extra effort
to be an ensemble player rather than just another virtuosic
soloist.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell in auditions whether an actor is an ensemble
actor,'' McClinton said in a telephone interview from his home in
St. Louis. ``Often at an audition it's simply: `Look at me! Look at
me!' But when there's give and take between actors, you know you
have a team player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing `Jitney' is like listening to the Modern Jazz
Quartet,'' McClinton added. ``Each of the characters has his or her
solo, but they've also got to be there as backup for the others.''
</P>
<P>
   For Barry Shabaka Henley, who plays Doub, a middle-aged driver,
each performance ``is like a jam session.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You come in with your own instrument every night,'' he said,
``and you've got to be ready to jump in and play as hard as you
can. You get juiced up and feed off each other's riffs. You just
can't wait to get out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The references to soloists and sidemen are especially apt for
``Jitney.'' Each of the characters has a monologue that helps
define his or her persona. For Willis Burks II, who plays the
numbers runner Shealy, it's a hilarious story about a jinx a woman
has put on his love life; for Anthony Chisholm, who is the
alcoholic driver Fielding, it's a rueful tale about once being a
tailor for Billy Eckstein; for Paul Butler's Becker, it's an
account of his wife's death; and for Henley's Doub, it's about his
service in the Korean War, stacking dead bodies: ``Six high _ not
five, not seven. But always six high.'' It's a gripping speech,
splendidly delivered by Henley.
</P>
<P>
   B UT it is brought home to the audience with even greater force
by the attention with which Russell Hornsby, who plays Youngblood,
a Vietnam veteran himself, listens to it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first lessons in Acting 101 is that you have to
listen to the actor who is speaking (instead of, say, trying to
remember your own next line or listening for your cue or trying to
steal a scene by distracting attention from the speaker). It is a
lesson some actors learn better than others. Few do it as well as
the nine actors in ``Jitney,'' whose entire cast was cited for its
work with an Obie award.
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby listens a lot in ``Jitney.'' It is Youngblood, for
example, to whom the story of Becker's son's crime is related.
Hornsby must hear the tale eight times a week with a growing
amazement and anger that will transfer to the audience almost by
osmosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes all this work for me is the fellowship we have with
each other,'' Hornsby said. ``We're truly engaged onstage because
we're engaged in real life. I ask a question out there and listen
because I want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Burks agreed: ``It's something really quite extraordinary we
have here. It lets you go out there and hear each moment for the
first time every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Michole Briana White, who plays Youngblood's independent-minded
girlfriend, Rena, said she had been astonished at ``the amount of
professionalism in the cast'' from the first reading of the play.
``Ensemble work is not about ego,'' she said. ``It's all about
moving the story forward. Everybody puts ego aside in this group.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of having a cast that has been working
together for so long is the split-second accuracy of timing and
blocking with which the action moves. Each actor knows where the
others are going to be onstage and at what tempo each scene will
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Chicago Bulls during their championship years,''
Chisholm said. ``It's like you are dribbling down court full speed
and pass the ball behind your back without looking and you know
somebody's there to take it and dunk it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley interjected: ``That was the Harlem Globetrotters.''
Chisholm shot back: ``The Bulls did it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the metaphor is apt. In several scenes, especially one
toward the end in which an argument develops over a $10
contribution for funeral flowers, the entire cast moves with the
precision of a fast break in basketball or the intricacy of a
timing pass pattern in football.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
