<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0886 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ELLEN-DEGENERES-LADN &LR;      06-21 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLEN-DEGENERES-LADN </SLUG>
  
Survivor DeGeneres takes it back on the road 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, Ellen DeGeneres tuned into an early
episode of the TV show ``Survivor,'' a program the 42-year-old
actress/comedian is convinced represents ``the end of the world as
we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   And weirdly enough, she discovered a grain of truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew that woman (Sonja Christopher) was going to get
kicked off, but I think everybody related to that because
everybody's been kicked off at some point in their life,'' says
DeGeneres. ``So you know what that's like _ to be the one voted
out, and it's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell me about it. This from the woman who took it on the chin
more than a few times once her own television sitcom decided to
move in a different direction. This from the woman who said she
went into a profound depression after ``Ellen'' was canceled, and
still had to deal with the slings and arrows of being a gay rights
activist.
</P>
<P>
   But even after being ``voted out'' more than a few times, Ellen
DeGeneres _ survivor and ``Survivor'' watcher _ isn't looking for
sympathy. She's moving forward by looking backward, getting back to
her stand-up comedy roots with a cross-country tour. For the time
being, others can carry the advocacy duties. As in days past,
DeGeneres would rather stand onstage and spin out her loopy riffs
on animals and insects.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a week-long hiatus from her tour, a seemingly relaxed
DeGeneres banters with waiters, coos at babies at nearby tables and
waxes serious and humorous between bites of a salad at the Four
Seasons hotel. A few days later, she'll be back on the bus that
will return her to the road for another month, including at the
Universal Amphitheatre on Saturday. Her final show, at the Beacon
Theatre in New York, will be taped for an HBO special to air on the
cable TV network July 23. Fittingly, the one-hour program will be
titled ``Ellen DeGeneres: the Beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road, DeGeneres and her crew are contending with bad
food, questionable lodgings and life aboard a 45-foot bus. The crew
is sending back weekly diary and picture entries via the Web site
Ellen.z.com., and DeGeneres' companion, Anne Heche, is filming the
entire tour for a behind-the-scenes documentary. Then it's back to
L.A. and back to work on a new variety show she is starring in and
producing for CBS currently titled ``The Ellen Show.'' It's
scheduled to be a mid-season replacement during the upcoming TV
season, possibly airing as early as November sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   So far, life on the road has been nothing if not eventful. The
first leg of her tour had two bad shows, one in Atlantic City (``I
don't believe in heaven and hell, but if there's a hell, it's
Atlantic City''); the second in Wallingford, Conn. (``I was in a
place that should have had wrestling'').
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what goes wrong because every night the
audience has a different personality,'' DeGeneres says. ``To stand
onstage and it's you and 3,000 people, and that's a lot of energy
coming at you and you're orchestrating it. I don't alter my act. I
don't have cheap jokes I can go to and I don't like telling the
audience that they're misbehaving or they're too rowdy. I let them
figure that out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, her off-beat stories, observational humor and
mastery of the pregnant pause that earned her all sorts of comedy
accolades, a spot on the ``The Tonight Show'' and the ``Funniest
Person in America'' designation from Showtime in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   And according to executives at HBO, which has produced a couple
of comedy specials with DeGeneres in the past, she's still got it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you've been around comedy a lot, it's hard to
appreciate how excrutiatingly difficult it is for a comic to put
together a one-hour special,'' said Carolyn Strauss, senior
vice-president of original programming for HBO. ``Ellen is one of
the few premiere comics and she has a great sense on the stand-up
stage of what works for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Followers of DeGeneres' material will recognize the musings on
animals, fear of flying and the foibles of human behavior. A staple
from her early routines, the telephone conversation with God, has
become a visit to the almighty's house because, as DeGeneres notes,
``the more famous you get, you actually get to meet ... you know
... people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the visit with God I have, it's not really a political
thing so much as a positive thing,'' says DeGeneres. ``Just how I
think we're all capable of being so much more than we are, and we
don't use everything we have, mixed in with stories about cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   What Amphitheatre audiences won't get during ``An Evening with
Ellen DeGeneres'' is gay or overtly political humor. No jabs at the
Dr. Laura Schlesingers of the world or the ABC network executives
who were responsible for the demise of ``Ellen'' a year after
DeGeneres' character, Ellen Morgan, became the first openly gay
leading character on television.
</P>
<P>
   In creating her new stand-up act, DeGeneres, who publicly came
out as a lesbian at the same time her character did, said she found
herself working through some of the personal and political issues
she had faced during the past three years. Ultimately she decided
those topics didn't belong on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I didn't want to do that. It's not who I was,'' says
DeGeneres whose blue eyes don't come across nearly so clearly on
television as they do in person. ``The more I wrote, the more it
fell into the same pattern of long rambling ridiculous stories and
weirdness. It kind of just all fell back into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had started buying into the fact that I changed just because
my television show had evolved into something else. I didn't. That
was my character, and then my character was telling a story and
that was necessary. But I am the same person and I have the same
sense of humor and the same thoughts, and I'm not going to turn my
show into a gay show just because everybody knows I'm gay now.''
That kind of transformation was, of course, a charge critics
brought against ``Ellen'' after Morgan/DeGeneres came out. Now
DeGeneres says she simply wants to become ``the Artist Formerly
Known as a Lesbian.'' To that end, DeGeneres brings up the topic
early in the evening, but only to to get it out of the way.
Politics and sexuality may come around again after the show when
DeGeneres does an informal 30-minute question and answer session
with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   During that session, DeGeneres says people are asking anything
from ``help me name my dog'' to ``do you write your own material''
to questions about the upcoming television show.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get one more `What was it like to be with Sharon Stone,'
(with whom DeGeneres co-starred in a segment of ``If These Walls
Could Talk II'' on HBO), I'm going to bring a water pistol,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Twice DeGeneres said she was ready to scrap the tour and the HBO
special because she got cold feet at the thought of failing onstage
and suffering a different type of public humiliation. A 10-minute
segment at a benefit in San Francisco and an unscheduled warm-up at
the Improv convinced DeGeneres that yes indeed, the comedy muscles
are still in working order.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she says, audiences seem generally glad to see her.
It's a ``welcome back'' tour in the truest sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do have, sometimes, is people who are a little too
fanatic, just a little too happy to see me,'' she says. ``There's
lots of `I love yous' being screamed out, and it's fine as long as
it stops when I start talking. I appreciate that, but are you here
because you love me or because you get what I'm saying?''
</P>
<P>
   During the post-performance, Q-and-A sessions, DeGeneres says
the audiences tend to get protective of her, and will boo if
somebody asks an intrusive or personal question or criticizes her.
When that happens, DeGeneres says she simply tries to keep the
peace, letting the audience know that even non-supporters have a
right to their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Rowdy audiences will probably get theirs in Heche's documentary.
DeGeneres and her crew have compiled a flock of road anecdotes,
from trying to find a gym in a fleabag hotel (``Yes, we have
several,'' the clerk said. ``Who are you looking for?'') to
DeGeneres' unsuccessful efforts to pry a kitten away from a family
because she felt the animal was too young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this rescue complex. I just feel like I need to take
care of things and then the world will be a better place,''
DeGeneres says, adding with a laugh, ``so it's all on my
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   With a tour to complete and a TV show to build, DeGeneres says
she doesn't know what the future holds. She's just living in the
moment, which could quickly change. Even a career shift isn't
entirely out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had enough money to never work again, I'd probably just
work with kids and animals and eat salads at the Four Seasons,''
says DeGeneres, ``fly in a private jet maybe to an island that I
owned, have a bunch of dancers that would dance for me whenever I
demanded and play Boggle. That's what I'd do.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and never be voted off another island. &QL; 
---What: An Evening with Ellen DeGeneres. &QL; 
Where: Universal Amphitheatre, 100 Universal City Plaza, Universal
City. &QL; 
When: Saturday, June 24 at 8:15 p.m. &QL; 
Tickets: $30-$55. Call (213) 583-8700. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
