<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MEDAL-OF-HONOR-HNS &LR;      06-21 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDAL-OF-HONOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON AWARDS MEDAL OF HONOR TO ASIAN-AMERICAN VETS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, declaring it time to ``break the
silence on their courage,'' bestowed the Medal of Honor on 22
Asian-American veterans on Wednesday for battlefield valor during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Seven living veterans _ including Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii _
and the families of 15 deceased veterans received the nation's
highest combat honor at a ceremony carried out in a white tent
erected on the south lawn of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 22 recipients were honored for heroism during the
legendary rescue of the ``Lost Battalion,'' a Texas National Guard
unit that was trapped, starving and slaughtered by Nazi forces in
southern France in October 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Asian-American soldiers had overcome ``painful
prejudice'' against Japanese-Americans following Japan's surprise
attack at Pearl Harbor to enlist in the nation's armed forces and
``define America at its best'' by fighting valiantly in Italy,
France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Hysteria following the Japanese attack had prompted President
Franklin D. Roosevelt to order the relocation of nearly 120,000
Japanese-Americans from their homes and farms. The U.S. citizens
were detained in stark and desolate barbed wire encampments in the
West, Clinton recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not only fighting for freedom and equality abroad, we
were also in a struggle here at home over whether America would be
defined narrowly on the basis of race or broadly on the basis of
shared values and ideals,'' Clinton said. ``Rarely has a nation
been so well served by a people it has so ill treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``It is long past time to break the silence on
their courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has now awarded 34 of the 3,452 Medals of Honor
conferred since the Civil War. Only two of the medals have been
awarded to soldiers who died during his presidency _ two Delta team
snipers who died in Somalia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 32 medals have been awarded following reviews of
combat records, including reassessments to see whether minorities
were overlooked in the awards process.
</P>
<P>
   The latest awards _ upgrades of earlier combat decorations _
stemmed from a two-year review of combat decorations received by
Asian Americans required by legislation sponsored in 1996 by Sen.
Daniel Akaka, D-Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Akaka said he sought the review because he suspected that
``bias, discrimination and hysteria'' had robbed Asian-American
veterans of proper recognition. He took the action after an earlier
review led Clinton to award Medals of Honor to seven
African-American veterans of World War II at a White House ceremony
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 22 Medals of Honor bestowed Wednesday, 21 were upgrades
of the Distinguished Service Cross _ the nation's second highest
award for battlefield courage. The 22nd recipient had received the
Silver Star, the third highest award.
</P>
<P>
   The Army review that led to the upgrade of the earlier awards
found ``no evidence'' of official discrimination in the
distribution of military honors more than 55 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social and legal discrimination against Asian-Americans was
widespread in American society in the 1940s, ''conceded Army
command historian John McNaughton in his report. ``Nevertheless in
the Army awards process, we found no evidence of discrimination
against Asian-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in segregated Japanese-American unit commanded by white
officers, McNaughton found that ``white officers made sure that
their Japanese-American soldiers received full recognition for
their valor.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaughton added:.`` We found no evidence that award
recommendations were rejected or downgraded on the basis of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Military records showed that some 25,000 Japanese-Americans,
13,000 Chinese-Americans and 124,000 Filipinos living in the United
States or then-U.S. territories such as Hawaii served in the armed
forces during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the 22 recipients were members of the 442nd Regimental
Combat Team or the 100th Infantry Battalion _ segregated units of
Japanese-Americans cited by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The two Japanese-American units, operating with a ``Go for
Broke'' motto, became the most highly decorated combat units of
their size in American history, with eight presidential unit
citations, 9,486 Purple Hearts and 18,143 individual decorations
including 52 Distinguished Service Crosses, the second highest
combat award for valor.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of the soldiers enlisted from the relocation
camps.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the recipients were honored for their part in the
daunting rescue of 275 GIs in the 1st battalion of the 141st
Infantry Regiment, a Texas National Guard unit that was cut off for
a week without reinforcement or resupply on a ridge dubbed
``Suicide Hill'' overlooking La Houssiere in the forest-clad slopes
of the Vosges Mountains in October 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The desperate troops sent a coded message to regimental
headquarters warning: ``No rations, no water, no communications
with headquarters four litter cases.''
</P>
<P>
   John A. Hyman recalled in his edited history of Texas' 36th
Division that Army commanders ``threw in crack troops'' from the
442nd Regimental Combat Team, ``wiry little men who went into
battle carrying twice what they would need just in case _ tough
fighters who were fighting a war for a cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese-American troops were repeatedly repulsed by more
than 700 Nazi troops surrounding the trapped American unit.
</P>
<P>
   On the sixth day, a member of the stranded unit spied a
Japanese-American GI coming toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Army Pfc. Mutt Sakumoto ``just looked at him with a lump in his
throat,'' said the unit history. ``The first thing he could think
to say was: ``Do you guys need any cigarettes?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JITNEY-THEATER-ART-$A     06-21 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JITNEY-THEATER-ART-$ADV25-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in football.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another mark of the cast's distinction is the way the actors
build their characters through small personal traits _ a slight
tremor in Chisholm's hand or the way he fumbles with the cap on a
half-pint of whiskey; how Butler uses a fedora to create Becker's
aura of respectability; the way Burks and Hornsby consult the small
notebooks in which each keeps the figures that define their success
in life. It is through such specificity that the audience comes to
know them.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the cast's closeness, Leo V. Finnie III, who plays
the doorman Philmore, said: ``About 45 minutes before the show
every night, we all get together and talk about what we've been
doing. `What was your day like?' `What's been going on?'''
</P>
<P>
   Henley added: ``I love every member of this cast. Oh, we may
argue from time to time, but it's like family arguing. Some nights
we all hold hands before we go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm, who has appeared in four of Wilson's plays, said: ``In
all of August's plays something happens that puts you in a
different kind of place. But in this one, with this cast, there is
an intangible cohesiveness you don't find in the others.''
</P>
<P>
   McClinton, the director, also spoke of the ``intangible
element'' that has evolved in this production. ``It's not something
you can direct,'' he said. ``It doesn't often happen with a cast.
And with this one it's developed over the long period of time
they've been doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the reasons behind the success of this staging of
``Jitney'' is the length of time many in the cast have been
performing it. It has long been Wilson's habit that his plays tour
the country in various regional theaters while he polishes them
with rewrites before they land in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jitney,'' which was the first play Wilson wrote in his cycle
dealing with the African-American experience in each decade of the
20th century, was originally produced in 1979 in his native
Pittsburgh. The present version, for which the author made
revisions, was first staged in 1996 for the Pittsburgh Public
Theater, and four of the nine current cast members have been with
it since its inception. But it has not been a straight path to New
York. Along the way it has played in Baltimore, Boston, Chicago,
Washington and Los Angeles, among other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen McKinley Henderson, who plays Turnbo, said that some of
the actors had made sacrifices to stay with the play. ``We wouldn't
know where it was going next,'' he said. ``The Pittsburgh
production was supposed to be it. But just as we were winding up,
somebody else said they wanted to do it. We'd do that one, and then
another theater would want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burks said that some of the actors would take other jobs in
between productions. ``I worked on a couple of movies, but I would
always be available for the next time someone wanted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The dedication of the actors to the play had been there from the
beginning, Butler said: ``It evolved from the very first reading.
It was like we all looked at each other and said, `We gotta go! We
gotta go!'''
</P>
<P>
   The initial enthusiasm has been infectious for those who have
joined the cast since. Carl Lumbly, who plays Becker's son,
Booster, is the newest member. ``I just feel gratitude for being
part of this group,'' he said. ``To be with a cast that is
committed to meeting and then topping the bar every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The length of time in a role can have its drawbacks. Actors can
get tired of a character and end up delivering perfunctory readings
while walking through the part. In theater it's called ``mailing in
a performance.'' This has not happened in ``Jitney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The play itself is so exciting,'' Hornsby said. ``I look
forward to doing it every night. It's an emotional thing for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson agreed that the play was the main reason. ``We've all
sort of made a mission out of this,'' he said. ``Because of August.
And also because at some point you begin to realize that you're
delivering something that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   White said another factor was that the cast keeps working on
their characters. ``After every performance, Russell and I talk
about how our scene worked that night,'' she said, referring to a
confrontation she and Hornsby have in which White delivers a
virtual manifesto on behalf of black women. ``We discuss the
performance and ask ourselves how we can improve it. Do I need to
listen more? Should I put my foot down more? You can't play the
same notes every night. That's what keeps it alive and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Every season that includes a new August Wilson play is a
reminder of the vast mine of talent among black actors in this
country that one rarely gets to see onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Have opportunities increased over recent years for black actors?
Has the movement known as nontraditional casting _ using minority
and female actors in roles written for white males _ made any
difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes in cycles,'' Henley said. ``I think there were even
more black shows in the '70s than there are now. Black actors are a
reflection of black workers in other fields. When it's convenient
for us to be seen, we'll be seen. If Hollywood sees there's no
danger of losing money on a black project, then they'll do it. When
`Waiting to Exhale' did well, everybody thought, `Finally, a black
movie made money, now we'll finally see more.' But it doesn't
happen. The trend goes back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm said he saw more opportunities for African-American
actors on television than the stage: ``Today, because there are
more television channels, there are more chances to get something
done _ a miniseries or some project like that. But as far as the
theater is concerned, the chances are few and far between.
Sometimes you have to wait for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Regional theaters, Henderson said, ``are good for this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of theater between L.A. and New York,'' he
noted. ``Actors get work because of these companies. We need more
of them so we can have ensembles. Because, you know, for actors,
there are no unimportant roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm agreed. ``I'm an actor. I can play a lizard, anything.
I've worked in `nontraditional' theater. I did `Of Mice and Men.'
Played Slim. The great Joe Fields did a Willy Loman. We as actors
want to act. But first of all, I'm an African-American. And putting
all politics aside, what we need is more producers, more writers
and, as a people, more cohesiveness. We as black people have got to
support the theater. If people all came to see `Jitney,' it would
run for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who is on the faculty of the State University of New
York, Buffalo, said: ``It depends on what you mean by
`nontraditional' and `traditional.' I've had people say to me:
`You're a good actor. You should be doing Shakespeare or Shaw.' I'm
all for black actors doing those roles. But don't tell me playing
those roles has to be the goal of my career. This is a big country
and it is all of our stories that make it great. People should
listen to all the stories. If you don't get `Joe Turner's Come and
Gone' or are uncomfortable about it, still go out and see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley said that one of the reasons ``Jitney'' is ``so special
is the thread of universality in it that makes it more accessible
to white people.'' Some of Wilson's plays ``agitate a white
audience,'' Henley said.
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm, who appeared in ``Two Trains Running,'' compared the
audiences that came to that play and those at ``Jitney.'' ``You get
a very different feeling from the audiences for `Jitney,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For White: ``This play is so moving. Although it is set in the
1970s, it still applies to women today. I can totally relate to
Rena. She was ahead of her time. For her to have the kind of
courage she does _ to say `I love myself first' _ she was taking a
big risk.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the wide appeal of ``Jitney'' is the undercurrent
of hope and forgiveness that flows through the play, often even
unstated, as when two antagonists who have a bitter running feud
resume playing checkers in the final scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This play really reflects its time for black Americans,''
Lumbly said. ``It's the '70s. Vietnam is over and we black people
thought stuff was finally going to happen for us. Our dreams were
on fire. And then nothing happened. We saw our dreams start to
wither. This was also true for black actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lumbly recalled that when he and Butler made the movie ``To
Sleep With Anger,'' a 1990 black drama in which they also played
father and son, ``Somebody wrote that we were `underknown' actors.
But that implies that stardom is what I should be striving for. I
don't agree with that. As black actors, we should be concentrating
simply on becoming better artists.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. The cast members of ``Jitney'' are having
the time of their lives acting in it. ``We're all so excited about
this play,'' Burks said wistfully, ``that I sometimes wish I could
just sit in the audience and watch us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
