<HEADLINE>
STRETCHING THE SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers won the championship of America's premier
winter sport Monday night, less than 24 hours before the summer
solstice, which came at 9:48 p.m. on Tuesday. Everything else might
have been right, but the timing sure was out of joint. And so are a
lot of other things.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey, after all, barely beat basketball to its conclusion,
finishing its playoffs June 10. What can you expect from a
cold-weather sport now being played professionally in places like
Florida, Texas, and California, where ice is a curiosity? If the
calendar loses importance, why should the map make any difference?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has a long history of being slightly off its season by
starting spring training before March 21. But the big leaguers
always go to Florida and Arizona to thaw out their arms. Reports
from those sunny places are upbeat because they give hints of
warmth to come to the north. Now, however, the season has stretched
out so long that the end of the World Series could, with a bit of
bad weather, get pretty close to November.
</P>
<P>
   By then the football season is well under way, having started
its professional season with exhibition games following training
sessions that begin in early July. Football in July? Phew. Never
mind. By the end of the season it is so cold that the Super Bowl is
played either in a covered stadium or the Sun Belt, with the
all-star bash in Hawaii in February.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium football is designed to slake the thirst of those who
yearn for the sport year-round and have to travel no farther than
the couch in front of the television set. For them, the calendar
and the notion of seasonal sports is totally out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, basketball is done for now, and winter has been fully
put to rest. It's time to think about other sports and get ready
for the next transitions. A good thing, too, because (hard though
it may be to believe), there are only four months until the
hoopsters are back in full swing, while the leaves are still on the
trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
