<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DELAY ON TRADE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott is holding up a vote on the
China trade bill even though it is one of the top priorities of his
party. Business executives who support the bill ought to remind him
that congressional approval is essential for them and the country
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Senate passage was supposed to be swift after the bill's
tortuous journey through the House last month. Lott, however, wants
to move several appropriations bills through the Senate before he
allows it to consider the trade bill. He has delayed any action
until at least mid-July, when the Senate returns from the July 4
recess.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriations bills are among the most contentious the Senate
will face this year. Many are left to the last days of the session
in September or October. The China bill should not be held hostage
to the uncertainties of the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Senate minority leader,
suspects that Lott wants to prolong the agony for Vice President Al
Gore and the many Senate Democrats who support the trade bill but
fear a backlash from their allies in organized labor, most of whom
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   The longer Lott waits, however, the greater the risk that the
bill will not pass, especially if the Senate adds amendments that
must be reconciled with the House version. This is perhaps the most
important bill Congress will pass this year, and it deserves to be
treated with extra care.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would affirm US support for Chinese entry into the
World Trade Organization, which will tie the world's most populous
nation into the international trading community. It would reassert
the US commitment to free trade around the world, the prerequisite
to drawing hundreds of millions of people out of poverty. And it
would offer US companies the opportunity to compete in China
without the restrictions long imposed there.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee thought so highly of the bill that
it cleared the House version unanimously without amendment early
this month. Lott needs a reminder that vital national interests
should transcend politics as usual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
