r e BC-JESUS'-SON-REVIEW-LAD     06-21 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS'-SON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER A CLOUD, A GEM STILL SHINES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've seen the needle and the damage done, so the prospect of
another movie about the aimless wanderings of a heroine addict is
about as appetizing as a syringe jammed in the jugular. But Alison
Maclean's hauntingly beautiful ``Jesus' Son'' manages to transcend
its genre by perfectly capturing the dreamy, episodic insanity of a
junkie's life without relying on the cliches and unbelievably
quirky characters that typically populate these films.
</P>
<P>
   Much credit goes to Elizabeth Cuthrell, David Urrutia and Oren
Moverman, who somehow managed to adapt Denis Johnson's celebrated
collection of linked short stories into a compelling movie. It's a
rare film that manages to do justice to an acclaimed book, much
less one that doesn't have a direct narrative. Here, the
screenwriters have taken Johnson's fractured tales of living and,
aided greatly by Maclean and cinematographer Adam Kimmel, turned
them into lyrical images of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus' Son'' is also blessed with a gifted cast that clearly
understands the material. Billy Crudup stars as the lovable loser,
FH, who moves through life with a bemused grin and an insightful
eye. FH's initials stand for a nickname that we can't print here,
but it's a moniker that one character tells him ``will ride him to
the grave,'' given the way trouble and failure seem to follow him
around.
</P>
<P>
   The film moves back and forth in time during a five-year period
in the early 1970s that takes the hapless FH on a number of
adventures _ some exhilarating, some meditative, many howlingly
funny. FH helps a buddy (Denis Leary) rip out the copper wiring
from his ex-wife's house so they can buy some drinks and dope. FH
takes a job as a hospital orderly (giving him close proximity to a
variety of pills) where he meets a fellow junkie, Georgie (Jack
Black of ``High Fidelity,'' again stealing every scene). Georgie
believes his calling may be medicine, which may be true given his
finesse with a hunting knife in two of the movie's most memorable
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, FH remains true in his way to his tortured,
junkie girlfriend, Michelle (Samantha Morton, the mute from Woody
Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' again superb), even as she has
difficulty coping with her addiction and FH's woeful ways. As the
movie stumbles toward its resolution, it loses a bit of its edge
but none of its charm. Dennis Hopper and a splendid Holly Hunter,
in well-written supporting roles, round out the excellent cast.
</P>
<P>
   Crudup, who has made a career of starring in underrated movies,
captures his character's pathos and compassion with a precision
that would bring Oscar buzz if this were more of a mainstream film.
As it is, ``Jesus' Son'' stands as a small gem worth a look. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Jesus' Son'' (R; graphic drug use, strong language,
sexuality and some violent images). &QL; 
The stars: Billy Crudup, Samantha Morton, Holly Hunter, Dennis
Hopper, Denis Leary, Jack Black. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Alison Maclean; screenplay by
Elizabeth Cuthrell, David Urrutia and Oren Moverman, based on the
book by Denis Johnson. Released by Lions Gate Films. &QL; 
Running time: 1 hour 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
