<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0899 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-IDIOTS-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-21 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDIOTS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
  
Finding your inner lunatic 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Members of the mental health community who are getting worked up
about ``Me, Myself and Irene'' better not go anywhere near ``The
Idiots.'' Lars von Trier's film about a commune of middle-class
Danes whose members want to get in touch with their inner idiot is
about as insensitively incorrect as they possibly come.
</P>
<P>
   That such a distasteful exercise manages sharp insights into the
basic nature of ideology, support psychology, social protest and
other deep-dish matters is something of a miracle. A small one, it
must be said; this is another one of those stripped-down, Danish
Dogma 95 exercises, so there's nothing big about it. But if you can
make it through the piece's offensive, meandering first half,
rewards definitely await.
</P>
<P>
   What basically happens is that a bunch of relatively young
social dropouts squat in a large suburban home that their nominal
leader, Stoffer (Jens Albinus), is supposed to be refurbishing for
his uncle. They go out on group excursions where all but one of
them (that day's designated ``minder'') try to, as the subtitles so
delicately put it, ``spass'' as convincingly as possible among
unsuspecting citizens.
</P>
<P>
   This provides the characters and the filmmaker with many fine
opportunities for public nudity (hypocritically, only the men's
naughty parts are covered by digitized black boxes). It's also good
for getting out of restaurants without paying the bill _ which, in
fact, is the incident that introduces Karen (Bodil Jorgensen), the
newest, most delicate member, to the group. She questions, as any
decent person would, the appropriateness of mimicking conditions
that real people struggle with. Stoffer and company respond with
rationalizations about achieving purer states and happiness that
bourgeois life represses.
</P>
<P>
   And although they face prejudice from uncomprehending neighbors,
it's hard not to view this bunch as a collection of self-absorbed,
irresponsible twits. Yet von Trier, whose latest film ``Dancer in
the Dark'' recently won the Cannes Film Festival's top prize, is
after pretty interesting game here. As the movie wears on, the
emotional price of the Idiots' shenanigans becomes increasingly
evident. Attempts to build deeper relationships with pre-verbal
tools prove both difficult and rewarding, while returning to their
previous lives outside the communal womb with their behavioral
philosophy intact is an often devastating act of personal
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker incisively lampoons most forms of groupthink _
including, it must be assumed, the grungy, semi-satiric Dogma dogma
_ with a kind of hall-of-mirrors approach to that cantankerous
thing called individuality. In ``The Idiots,'' acting rationally is
oppressive, but so is acting irrationally according to some
prescribed definition, however vague and superficially freeing it
might be. ``The Idiots'' may be a movie about playing dumb, but it
is remarkably smart when it comes to how our minds work. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``The Idiots'' (R; nudity, sex, language). &QL; 
The stars: Bodil Jorgensen, Jens Albinus, Louise Hassing, Troels
Lyby, Nikolaj Lie Kaas, Louise Mieritz. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Lars von Trier. Produced
by Vibeke Windelov. Released by October Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 55 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
