<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-RELIGION-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW AMERICA,' BAD RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Local punkers Bad Religion are like that proverbial
post-apocalyptic cockroach _ they can withstand anything.
</P>
<P>
   The quintet, formed in the Valley 20 years ago, has survived
self- destructive pathology, creative battles, the defection of
founding singer- guitarist Brett Gurewitz, a much-criticized move
to Atlantic Records from indie Epitaph and the splintering of the
group's members to new homes across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bad Religion plugs on, sticking to its punk origins,
playing to packed houses of fans new and old while recording fresh
music every few years. The band's fifth and latest effort for
Atlantic, ``The New America,'' found Bad Religion teamed in Hawaii
with producer Todd Rundgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd was an underground sensation back in 1974,'' says Bad
Religion singer Greg Graffin. ``Here's a guy who was making pop
music but in a way that you wouldn't hear on the radio. He made me
sensitive to the concepts of popularity and underground ideology _
the idea that you can make popular music and yet not exploit it to
the extent that everyone has heard of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad Religion _ Greg Hetson (guitar), Brian Baker (guitar), Jay
Bentley (bass), Bobby Schayer (drums) and Graffin _ appears in a
matinee show Sunday at the Universal Amphitheatre, opening for
pop-punk trio Blink-182 (``Adam's Song'').
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, no band members are based in Los Angeles any longer.
Graffin lives in Ithaca, N.Y., where he taught laboratory courses
in zoology at Cornell University; Hetson lives in Texas; Baker is
in Washington, D.C.; Schayer lives in Seattle; and Bentley is based
in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have studios in our houses so we have the technology to
share music,'' Graffin, 35, explained. ``And we've never been a
tight unit, anyway. But there are factions within the band that get
together sometimes and do things away from the band. It's really
like family. We grew up together. We don't have to rehearse because
practice is something you do on your own anyway. You're expected to
stay in shape on the off season.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their music, the quintet sponsors its own Bad
Religion Research Fund scholarship program for budding geniuses in
the cultural or natural science fields. The program was launched in
1998 by Graffin, who holds a degree in evolutionary biology from
UCLA and is working towards his PhD. at Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pride in being able to support someone's research
endeavors,'' he said. ``The real reward for the whole band is our
being a part of higher education while perpetuating the idea that
Bad Religion has always stood for _ to question the prevailing
dogma. It's something you can do in science, the humanities and in
entertainment as well.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``The New America,'' Bad Religion adds fuel to the fierce,
inquisitive spirit and penchant for provocative examination that
took root with their founding in 1980 and continued to bloom with
such influential albums as ``How Could Hell Be Any Worse'' (1982),
``Suffer'' (1987), ``No Control'' (1989) and ``Against the Grain''
(1990).
</P>
<P>
   Through a dozen albums, Bad Religion has maintained a hard-edged
attack and righteously angry lyrics while refining its sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many bands are afraid to change,'' Graffin said. ``They're
afraid to step forward because they're in a comfortable spot with
their audience and they don't want to mess up a good thing by
offering them a challenge. Bad Religion and punk have always been
about challenge and if we can't do that on the new record, what
good are we anyways?''
</P>
<P>
   The new disc features Epitaph label founder Gurewitz's first
contributions to a Bad Religion album since 1994's gold-certified
``Stranger Than Fiction,'' the band's Atlantic debut. Graffin
hooked up with the band's former guitarist to co-write the telling
``Believe It,'' which also includes a guitar solo from the founding
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the song sounds like a long-lost friend _ there's an
almost indescribable familiarity,'' Graffin said. ``It's silly to
deny there's something special between us. We're connected and
always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album's reflective mood resulted from discussions
between Graffin and Rundgren, which took place even before many of
the songs were written. Previously, the band worked with such name
producers as Andy Wallace (Nirvana) and Rick Ocasek (the Cars).
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd is more philosophical,'' Graffin offered. ``When it comes
down to it, one of the most important things to have is some
internally consistent logic as to why you're making a record. That
was, from the get-go, Todd's most important role in this _ to
figure out how the songs should be put together on the album to
tell an accurate story of where our heads are at. And if you're
commenting on a social situation, how the material relates to
what's happening now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great education for me. It taught me so much about
the reason to make records and why certain records are great and
others fail.''
</P>
<P>
   ____ &QL; 
Who: Bad Religion, opening for Blink-182. &QL; 
Where: Universal Amphitheatre, 100 Universal City Plaza, Universal
City. &QL; 
When: 3:15 p.m. Sunday. &QL; 
Tickets: $27.50. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232.
</P>
</TEXT>
