<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-CHILD-KILLERS-ART     06-21 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CHILD-KILLERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER'S SLAYING FORCES DEBATE ON CHARGING CHILDREN AS ADULTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ The accused killer has a toy fire truck in
his closet. A sixth-grade photograph, signed ``To Grandma'' but
never mailed, rests on a desk beside a certificate that reads
``Most Improved in Spanish'' and algebra homework done in No. 2
pencil. He has mastered polynomials, the homework shows, but he
signed the paper ``Nate Wuz Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Brazill, 13, left his room that way on May 26, the
last day of classes before summer vacation at Lake Worth Middle
School, the day he took a stolen gun to school and pointed it at
the face of his English teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County prosecutors say he shot Barry Grunow to death
because the teacher would not let him into a classroom to say
goodbye to two girls. They charged the honors student and tuba
player as an adult with first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   In his room in a stark triplex on H Street, his mother, Polly
Powell, wondered how anyone could call him an adult when it seems
like only yesterday that her son, whom everyone calls Nate, was
playing in the dirt with a yellow Tonka truck.
</P>
<P>
   But while a mother's love is expected to be blind, others in
this Lake Worth neighborhood ask the same thing, how a seemingly
good and promising boy, who was never in trouble, could do this. It
happened, his mother says, because he is still a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a man,'' she said. ``He doesn't shave. He can't
drive a car, or go into the service. He can't buy cigarettes or
beer, or a lottery ticket. He's a child,'' she said, and like any
other he is impulsive, eager to impress friends, ignorant of the
long-term consequences of the things he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my boy back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nate, the carrier of his mother's dream that he would break
loose from her neighborhood of tiny houses and rumbling freight
trains, is charged with a slaying that demands harsh punishment at
an age that would seem to beg for some leniency, but in a state
where there is no middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged as an adult, which carries a maximum penalty of
life in prison, rather than as a juvenile, which might have ended
in his being remanded to a juvenile detention center for a few
years. Whether such a charge is appropriate is the same question
being asked in other states as a nightmare epidemic of school
shootings spread across the country, as courts decide how to punish
killers too young to see an R-rated movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the policy in this office,'' and in this state, for
youths charged in such violent felonies, said Michael Edmondson,
executive assistant to Barry Krischer, the Palm Beach County state
attorney. ``There is no selective application of that policy. That
way you don't discriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a grand jury in Palm Beach County took barely 15
minutes to indict Nate on a charge of first-degree murder. He is
being held in a special ward reserved for teen-agers in the county
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he did wrong, I know he should be punished,'' said
Nate's mother, who believes the whole thing was an accident, that
the gun just went off. ``But punish him as a juvenile. If any
parent tells you different, what they'd do if it was them, they're
telling a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has caused some Florida lawmakers to consider
legislation to create some middle ground. For now, defendants like
Nate can only be sentenced to hard time in a state prison for
adults, perhaps for the rest of their lives. But some lawmakers are
considering legislation that would allow judges to take age into
consideration, perhaps allowing younger offenders to serve time in
a juvenile center and then in a state prison _ rather than locking
them away in a state prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be some choice in the middle,'' said Ron Klein, a
state senator from Boca Raton, who is drafting a bill that would
allow the courts to consider all aspects of the case, including an
offender's potential for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow's family has been quiet since the killing, saying only,
in a statement, that they trust in the law.
</P>
<P>
   Nate's lawyers must convince a judge and jury that he did not
mean to kill the respected 35-year-old teacher, who left a wife, a
5-year-old son and infant daughter. Nate's best defense seems to be
his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been representing jerks for 20 years,'' said Bob Udell, a
lawyer from nearby Stuart who is representing Nate. ``They were bad
people and they'd cut your throat in a second. This isn't that.
This is payback for 20 years of jerks. This is a good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, as teachers at Lake Worth Middle School selected
students for offices for the coming year, they selected Nate as a
``mediator,'' a student who could be relied on to help others
resolve confrontation without violence.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher who sponsored him was Grunow.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nate grew up in a neighborhood where young boys were sometimes
expected to fight. The neighborhood, stucco duplexes and small
concrete houses squeezed between the railroad tracks and a
nondescript stretch of U.S. 1., trembles faintly under freight cars
loaded with crushed limestone. This part of Lake Worth, south of
Palm Beach, was once an enclave for blacks who drifted down from
the South, but now many people speak Spanish or Haitian Creole.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Powell planned on her son's life being much
better, much easier than hers, though the process of raising him
was less than ideal. Powell, who is the assistant food services
director for a retirement home, left Nate's father, and two later
marriages sometimes brought police to the door to stop the fights.
</P>
<P>
   But people here say she shielded him from that, that she spent
much of what she made on him, that she was a good mother, if overly
protective. She is full of stories, like the one about his first
haircut, how he touched his head and looked up at her with his eyes
really big and said, ``Put it back.'' In third grade, ``he got
straight A's,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She spent much of what she made on him, buying good toys _ not
those plastic things that break in a week _ and later a $1,700
computer for school work. ``He had more than most people here,''
said Powell, who also has a 2-year-old daughter, Ebony.
</P>
<P>
   She did not allow him to speak in street slang. She saw, around
her, boys who pretended to be gangsters, who dressed and acted as
gangsters, then one day vanished into the violence. Her son was a
junior usher who went to Bible study on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the kid you hope for,'' said Sharon Odums, who has
known Powell since elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Some students seemed to resent Nate, because he seemed so
goody-goody.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would make fun of him,'' said Shikeria Knowles, 13, who
was a classmate of Nate's since third grade. ``They would pick on
him, and he would just ignore them. He wouldn't do a thing. He had
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   He was popular with the smart kids. ``He was always helping
people with homework,'' Shikeria said. When he drew a role as a
woman in a play in Grunow's class, he did it good naturedly, and
students applauded.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bermudez, the band and chorus director at the school, said
Nate got an A in band, ``but I really don't remember when he
didn't. He switched from trumpet to tuba to help out our band. He
liked coming to practice. I had to throw him out of the room at
times, because he was so dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   He played video games where people blew up people and watched
movies of death and mayhem, but no more than anyone else, and never
acted any of it out, said friends.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The pivotal moment in Nate's life may have come the week before
the shooting. While visiting the home of a relative, he saw a tiny
Raven .25 caliber gun. Nate stole it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask what happened,'' said his mother. ``Life
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The man who had the gun bought it because he lives in a
neighborhood where, sometimes, a gun makes people feel more safe.
Her son saw it and, fascinated as boys are with guns, took it,
probably to show his friends, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of class, a teacher _ not Grunow _ saw Nate in a
water balloon fight, and he was sent home. A classmate told police
that Nate said he would seek revenge, that ``I'll be all over the
news.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He went home and got his gun, and came back just before the
final bell. He did not seek out the teacher who expelled him but
went instead to Grunow's class and asked to say goodbye to two
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow told him no, and, as the two stood in the hallway, Nate
pulled his gun, pointed it into Grunow's face and shot him, say
police.
</P>
<P>
   When another teacher came up to him, he wheeled and pointed it
at that teacher, but did not shoot or the gun did not fire, police
said. Nate ran, but flagged down a police car a few minutes later
and turned himself in.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect things like this,'' said Bermudez. ``We don't, from
a kid like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The why of it haunts people here. ``I think it was his chance to
scare people,'' to show he was more than a nice boy, said Shikeria.
``I think he kept it all inside, for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Balfour, a counselor at the Osborne Community Center near
Nate's neighborhood, said, ``No one ever had anything bad to say
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was it, that he wanted more attention than an honor
roll could give, more than playing tuba on a 50-yard line,
classmates said. Nate was, in the end, too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   But his mother says no, he was good, and will be good again.
``My baby is going to be somebody,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
