<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-BBC-DEATH-NYT     06-21 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BBC-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC SEEKS TO CHARGE ISRAEL WITH WAR CRIMES FOR DEATH OF EMPLOYEE IN
LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The BBC is charging that the killing of one of its
drivers in an Israeli tank attack in southern Lebanon last month
appears to have been a deliberate and unprovoked attack on a
civilian target, an accusation Israel strongly denies.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the BBC in London are investigating whether Israel
can be accused of a war crimes violation under the terms of the
Geneva Convention, said BBC correspondents here.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army acknowledged on Friday that Abed Takkoush, who
worked as a driver and news assistant for the BBC in Lebanon for 25
years, was killed by an artillery shell fired at his car by an
Israeli tank on May 23, as Israeli forces were hastily withdrawing
from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army spokesmen at first disavowed responsibility for the
incident, saying the attack might have been the work of the South
Lebanon Army, Israel's local ally in its since-abandoned border
security zone. The BBC then submitted its own detailed report on
the incident to Israeli authorities, including extensive video
footage from the BBC and four other television news organizations,
which appears to conclusively document an unprovoked attack on
Takkoush's blue Mercedes by an Israeli Merkava tank stationed about
4,000 feet away, inside Israeli territory.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Bowen, the BBC reporter whom Takkoush had driven to the
scene, witnessed the devastating impact from a few hundred feet
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Abed lurch out of the driver's side of the car and then
fall to the ground,'' he said. Bowen said that as he headed toward
the burning car he was met by a burst of machine-gun fire from the
Israeli border. A Lebanese Red Cross truck also came under fire as
its tried to approach the vehicle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no gunfire, no rocket attacks, no artillery
exchanges that day, as Bowen and his crew drove through the newly
abandoned security zone toward the Israeli border. Together with
his cameraman, Malek Kenaan, he walked about a hundred yards from
their parked car to set up equipment for a broadcast report, while
Takkoush stayed behind, talking to his son in Beirut by mobile
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen was close enough to the border to wave at local kibbutz
residents surveying the scene from the other side of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was quiet,'' he said. ``We had no idea that we were
in any danger.''
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Friday accepting responsibility for what it
termed ``a tragic accident,'' the Israeli army said the tank crew
had been warned of a possible Hezbollah attack and mistook the
BBC's tripod and camera for an anti-tank missile launcher.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with BBC correspondents, senior aides to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said the Defense Ministry has ordered a further
investigation into Takkoush's death. There is a ``possibility''
that the military army investigators might recommend financial
compensation for Takkoush's family, said Gadi Baltiansky, Barak's
chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new investigation is just now underway, Baltiansky
said the government is convinced that the tank crew and the
commanders who authorized the attack had legitimate grounds to
believe they were witnessing preparations for a missile attack. ``I
can understand the mistake, though I cannot justify it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC challenges the Israeli army's account, noting that at
the time and place the army now says it was anticipating a
Hezbollah missile attack, the army had permitted a crowd of Israeli
civilians to gather at the border fence and observe its evacuation
from the zone. They note further that the car was targeted, but not
the crew, which the Israeli army said it had ``mistakenly
identified as a terrorist group.''
</P>
<P>
   Most seriously, the BBC contends in its report that news film
from the scene shows that the Israeli army ``appeared to be
sporadically targeting vehicles'' driven by Lebanese civilians
along the same stretch of road earlier on May 23 and on May 22,
despite the absence of any ``retaliatory fire from the Lebanese
side of the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International independently reported that at least two
other Lebanese civilians were killed by Israeli tanks firing at
Lebanese cars in the same location on May 22 and 23. ``These
attacks appear to have taken place without warning, after the IDF
and SLA had already pulled back from the areas,'' the human rights
group said, referring to the Israeli army and the South Lebanon
Army.
</P>
<P>
   If evidence supports the charge that the Israelis were
``recklessly'' firing at civilian vehicles across the border, the
BBC contends, this would constitute a violation of the Geneva
Convention, which categorizes as a war crime any deliberate
targeting of unarmed noncombatants. The BBC's legal department is
planning to pursue the case, Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This claim is completely groundless,'' Baltiansky said. ``We
cannot do any more than we are doing _ investigating, apologizing
and offering compensation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
