<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, June 22 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-COLOMBIA (Washington) _The Senate on Wednesday was
ready to approve nearly $1 billion in aid to Colombia, nearly three
months after it passed the House. Final spending level will be set
by conference committee, and could still be held hostage to
congressional schedules. But House Speaker Dennis Hastert and
Senate backers of aid to Colombia say they may have devised a way
to get the aid measure to President Clinton's desk by end of next
week. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-INSURANCE (Undated) _ One of the country's biggest life
insurers, American General, said Wednesday that it was paying $175
million to settle claims that until as recently as early this year
black customers were charged more for coverage than were white
customers. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PLANTATION (Natchitoches, La.) _ At the south edge of the
old plantation, eight simple cabins stood in a field of clover.
Generations of whitewash were peeling in ugly patches from the
mud-brick walls. All but one front porch had rotted away, and there
were gaping holes where doors and windows used to be. Obscured by
rows of live oaks, the cabins had been forgotten by many and
ignored by most. There was almost nothing left _ except the stories
of the slaves who once lived in them. Will re-enactments of slave
life at a former plantation, now a national park, help to heal
racial wounds _ or open them? By Ginger Thompson. (6500 words, with
an abridged version of about half that length.)
</P>
<P>
   (The report has moved in `a' category; abridged version will
also move tonight.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT901-908.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-OIL (Nashville, Tenn.) _ The Gore campaign, worried that
the public blames the Clinton administration for the recent surge
in oil prices, is trying to shift attention to Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, a former oil company executive himself who the Gore camp
says still has deep ties to an industry that is gouging the public.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   DEAF-READING (Undated) _ Deaf Americans have gained a place in
the national consciousness. American Sign Language interpreters
seem to be everywhere, from the State of the Union address to the
Miss America pageant. But some advocates for the deaf say that a
politicized devotion to the exclusive use of sign language by many
of the deaf has helped foster a little known and surprising
problem: The average 18-year-old deaf American reads at a
fourth-grade level. These advocates are seeking to lead a
revolution in deaf education through a 34-year-old method called
cued speech. By Lynette Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,8, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Seoul, South Korea) _ The euphoria of last week's
summit meeting is wearing off to reveal the hard road ahead. In the
North, Kim Jong Il has urged North Koreans to hew to communism and
self-reliance, saying that market openings would be disastrous for
the country. In the South, the political opposition has jumped on
Kim Dae-jung, saying he got nothing and was taken in by Kim Jong
Il. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-WATER (Washington) _ The Mars Global Surveyor has
radioed data to Earth suggesting there is surface water on the Red
Planet, which could boost the possibility of finding evidence of
life, experts say. (Summary from wires) By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DRUGS (Washington) _ The House Ways and Means Committee
takes up legislation to establish Medicare drug benefits, and the
panel is expected to approve a Republican proposal on a party-line
vote after hours of impassioned debate. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
</TEXT>
