A0930 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PIPELINE-0622-1stLD-C     06-21 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-0622-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSTON CONGRESSMAN DROPS LONGHORN PIPELINE RIDER
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After keeping Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, on
tenterhooks for most of two days, a Houston representative on
Wednesday abandoned at the last minute his plans to introduce
legislation to block an environmental study of the proposed
Longhorn pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing the Environmental Protection Agency to conduct a
``comprehensive'' environmental impact study of the Longhorn
project has been one of Doggett's pet goals for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, a Houston Democrat, began circulating the text
of an amendment to block the study Tuesday, as a bill to
appropriate EPA's budget for next year was being debated on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment would have prohibited EPA from using any part of
its budget to fund the environmental study. As soon as he heard
Green planned to introduce the amendment, Doggett started lobbying
other members against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased that the amendment has been withdrawn,''
Doggett said Wednesday afternoon. ``I talked with Rep. Green on the
floor and he indicated to me he did not intend to offer it. I had
been mobilizing support to oppose it.'' Doggett said Green didn't
indicate why he changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Doggett wrote to President Clinton, urging
him to direct EPA to issue a formal environmental impact statement
before approving plans for the pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
   Known formally as the Longhorn Partners Pipeline, the proposal
would reopen a recently abandoned pipeline and use it to pump
gasoline from Houston to El Paso. The line passes through Doggett's
Austin district, where it has been criticized as a threat to
underground water resources.
</P>
<P>
   In a less comprehensive report issued earlier this year, EPA
consultants declared that the plan posed no significant threat to
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
