<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0932 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NUCLEAR-SECRETS-HNS &LR;      06-21 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SECRETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATORS LOB BIPARTISAN ATTACKS AT ENERGY SECRETARY
RICHARDSON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the wake the mysterious disappearance and
reappearance of two sensitive computer hard drives at the Los
Alamos National Laboratory, senators from both parties threatened
Wednesday to take control of America's nuclear weapons labs away
from the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.,
said he will introduce legislation ordering an examination of
whether the nuclear weapons programs _ including the Los Alamos,
N.M., lab and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in
California _ should be turned over to an independent agency or to
the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``After everything that has gone on, we have to wonder why these
incredibly sensitive labs are under the supervision of this
department,'' Warner said at a Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The session was marked by a number of attacks against Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson and his agency's security policies.
</P>
<P>
   He was verbally skewered by senators who charged that the
secretary, a former congressman from New Mexico, had failed to
implement security measures that could have prevented the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've lost all credibility,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby,
R-Ala., chairman of the Intelligence Committee, repeating his call
for Richardson to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said Richardson had ``thrown away the
confidence of the Congress'' and that he would not have support
from the Senate if he is nominated for another administration
position. ``There's a feeling that you have treated Congress like a
lap dog,'' Bryd told Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Strongly defending himself, the secretary insisted, ``I take a
back seat to nobody when it comes to security.''
</P>
<P>
   He assured the panel that employees would be held
``accountable'' for any security breaches and added that a grand
jury has been convened to investigate the disappearance of the
drives.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson repeated earlier statements that the FBI has found no
evidence of espionage in the case and no indication that the drives
had ever left the Los Alamos lab's top secret X-Division, where
some of the nation's most sensitive nuclear weapons research is
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department first announced June 12 that the hard
drives, which contain information on how to dismantle certain
nuclear devices, had been missing since at least May 7, when two
scientists went to remove them from a vault as a fierce wildfire
approached the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to find out what happened to the hard drives, the
FBI and Energy Department are seeking to determine why the two
scientists did not report the disappearance to lab security or
other officials for 24 days. Department rules require reporting
security lapses within eight hours. The FBI was not notified until
June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said all 26 individuals who had unescorted access to
the vault have taken lie detector tests and that the investigation
was focusing on ``a handful of X-Division employees who have
offered conflicting statements to investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the FBI continued to treat the area where the hard
drives were found as a crime scene and that investigators believe
the two drives disappeared at the end of March, although the exact
date remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, appearing for the first time on Capitol Hill to
discuss the hard drives' disappearance, said his department also
expects to complete a review later this summer of the University of
California's contract to run the weapons labs. Critics, including
many in the Energy Department, say university officials have failed
to implement security policies and to conduct proper oversight at
the labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that the University of California
does well, like science, and things it doesn't do well, like
security, and we're considering taking over some of the things it
doesn't do well,'' Richardson said.While acknowledging the
seriousness of the hard drives' disappearance, Richardson said that
in his two years as energy secretary he had ``done more on security
than has been done in the last 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But several senators questioned how his security measures could
allow the labs to completely lose track of the hard drives for
several months. The last written record showed the drives to be in
the vault of the X-Division at the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said the ``lack of inventory control
was simply inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he has changed security rules so that
information on the hard drives must be encrypted with secret codes
and the vault must have guards when someone enters. A formal log-in
and log-out procedure has been created, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-drive mystery comes a year after security questions at
Los Alamos arose in the wake of the Wen Ho Lee case. Lee was a
scientist there who was investigated amid allegations that China
had stolen nuclear data. He was fired in March 1999 for security
violations and was arrested in December on charges of mishandling
classified material after it was discovered that he had downloaded
and copied vast amounts of nuclear weapons data from Los Alamos'
classified computer network.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee was never charged with espionage, and the accusations
that China had stolen design information about America's most
advanced nuclear warhead have not been proved.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the Lee case, Congress created a semi-autonomous
independent agency to oversee the laboratories that was to report
to Richardson and Congress. Richardson resisted the plan, arguing
that he should remain in charge, and that he could guarantee the
safety of the nation's nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday Richardson said he would move quickly to get
the new agency up and running and that it would have his ``full
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said the semi-autonomous agency
was the department's ``last chance'' to keep the weapons facilities
from being taken away. ``This is too consequential to give another
free pass,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
