<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A complex weather system will continue to move through the
Northeastern states on Thursday, bringing rapidly changing weather
conditions to the area. In New England, morning showers will yield
to some sun, gusty breezes and very high temperatures in the
afternoon. However, showers and thunderstorms will again develop in
the mountains in the afternoon, then slide to the East Coast by the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, a front will become nearly stationary across the
Southeast. This front will provide a focus for repeated showers and
thunderstorms, some of which will contain brief bursts of heavy
rain. Storms are also likely along the Gulf Coast where sea breezes
will undercut and lift warm, humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the West will remain tranquil, though thunderstorms will
develop in the mountains of New Mexico and Arizona by late in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DESERT FLOODS
</P>
<P>
   Intense thunderstorms caused blowing dust, large hail and areas
of flooding around Phoenix on Tuesday. Although rainfall in these
thunderstorms was heavy, it only takes modest amounts of rain to
cause desert flooding. The desert floor does not readily absorb
large amounts of water because of its sandy soil and lack of
vegetation. So runoff from sudden brief rain can be very rapid. In
summer, an arroyo, which is a dry creek bed, can change from an
arid gulch to a raging torrent in a matter of seconds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1916EDT &QL; 
