<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LYING': IT COULD BE FACT OR FICTION ... OR SOMETHING ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end of review) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you've read my other books _ and I have written other
books, `Prozac Diary' and `Welcome to My Country,' which I suggest
you rush out and buy _ you would know that mental problems have
been issues throughout my life,'' Lauren Slater notes helpfully in
her third memoir. Nonetheless, though she has already cataloged a
full litany of complaints including depression, anorexia and
self-mutilation, Slater now locates a whole new vein of illness to
mine. In ``Lying,'' she presents her lifelong history of epilepsy,
but as the title suggests, there is a catch. Maybe this really
happened to her. Maybe she is making it up.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's bite: why? For what reason would she have concocted
this book's lovingly detailed auras and seizures? And if this
memoir is merely a feat of gamesmanship, what would induce the
reader to play along? Slater, who can be found posing on the front
cover of each autobiographical volume, maintains that the essential
truth of her story matters more than the particulars, and that the
figurative meaning of epilepsy _ the falling, auras, seizures and
memory lapses, not to mention the celebrity connections to van
Gogh, Dostoyevsky et al. _ makes her own life easier and more
interesting to explain. ``This is my tale,'' she says, ``and I have
written it over and over again, and, depending on my mood and my
auras, the story always seems to change, and yet it always seems
true.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't always seem true to anyone bothering to compare this
book with her earlier accounts. (Was she actually in a foster home,
or did she spend her teen-age years at home with her mother, whom
she blames for everything?) But that, as Slater repeats endlessly
here, is beside the point. The ``metaphorical memoir'' that she
attempts is a refutation of literal-minded storytelling, as well as
a response to the exaggerations that color many memoirs anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that a lot of memoirs have made-up scenes;
that's obvious,'' she writes, in a memo advising Random House on
how to market ``Lying.'' ``And everyone knows that half the time at
least fictions contain literal autobiographical truths. So how do
we decide what's what, and does it even matter?'' What she has in
mind, she continues, is ``a book that takes up residence in the
murky gap between genres, and by its stubborn self-position there,
forces us to consider important things.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, ``Lying'' flogs these important things to the
point where they cease being important. It is not likely that the
reader's interest in Slater's medical and philosophical condition
will rival her own. And this book winds up working best as an
imaginative coming-of-age memoir, one that exerts considerable
narrative pull even if it should turn out to be science fiction.
Only intermittently, as when Slater describes undergoing brain
surgery, is there a deeply compelling reason to wonder why she
might have chosen to invent such an episode, or what it means in
her larger story.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that epileptics have tendencies toward mythomania and
melodrama, Slater goes on to offer prodigious illustrations of
both. In her early years, she says, she lied about having cancer.
She stole things while in a state she regarded as a kind of
seizure. She learned to fake epileptic episodes in hospital
emergency wards all over Boston, and when she first began to write,
she says, she experienced sexual ecstasy at the keyboard. She
describes taking part in the Bread Loaf writers' conference in
Vermont under a fake name, at 17, and encountering the very famous
author with whom she had her first affair. Her writing, he told
her, made him feel ``like I need a long cool shower.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this enveloping section of her book tells a familiar
story, that of the young acolyte seduced by the worldly middle-aged
man, Slater succeeds here in vibrantly evoking the episode and
achieving the resonance she seeks. The link between sexual and
epileptic abandon is clear, and it is well used to illuminate her
ambivalent response to the affair. Also effective is the sense of
the author as an assured manipulator of the story she tells. ``I
didn't sleep with him,'' she tells a friend, soon after meeting
this literary lion. ``But you will,'' the friend replies. ``And it
will be such a cliche when it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, in an episodic book with sections named for the stages
of an epileptic seizure (``Onset,'' ``The Rigid Stage,'' ``The
Convulsive Stage,'' ``The Stage of Recovery''), Slater presents her
most creative and wry bit of dissembling. In keeping with the
spiritual and religious yearning that she says is also part of the
epileptic's personality profile, she falls into step with a chapter
of Alcoholics Anonymous even though she does not have _ or has not
yet chosen to write a book about _ a drinking problem. And she
finds, in the book's most natural illustration of metaphorical
sweep, that her own pathology and those discussed by A.A. members
are perfectly in sync. When it is time for her to offer a personal
history, she is perfectly equipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started, you know, doing it at home, at school, all the
time, just stumbling around and making a real fool of myself,'' she
tells the alcoholics. She speaks of relapses and petty theft and
life in a dysfunctional family. She talks of her illness and the
physical humiliation it brings. And when she is done, and her
speech has been greeted with applause and tears, she goes home, has
a drink and decides to confess her lie.
</P>
<P>
   But when Slater tries to tell the truth, her A.A. friends stop
her and decide that she is just in denial. ``Shhh,'' one tells her.
Says another, offering the perfect commentary on this book's
self-importance about blurring fact and fiction, ``We see this all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LYING' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Metaphorical Memoir  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Lauren Slater  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   221 pages. Random House. $21.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
