<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WILLIAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 18, WILLIAM CAN NO LONGER `CARVE FOR HIMSELF' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When the royal family partied Wednesday night at
Windsor Castle to celebrate a slew of birthdays, one of the guests
of honor was conspicuous by his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Prince William, second in line to the throne, passed up the
chance to celebrate his 18th birthday with his extended family late
into one of the longest days of the year and instead spent the
night studying for an art history test Thursday at Eton.
</P>
<P>
   Such discipline may hint at the seriousness with which the son
of the late Diana, Princess of Wales, regards his responsibilities
should his father, Prince Charles, succeed Queen Elizabeth II, and
should he succeed his father.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, William was entitled to be known as His Royal
Highness, a title his grandmother, the Queen, stripped from his
mother after Diana and Charles divorced. William has said he
doesn't want to be called His Royal Highness. William, he says,
will do.
</P>
<P>
   Palace officials confirm that William does not expect staff to
bow or curtsy to him, or to address him as sir, until he begins to
take on royal duties, probably years from now.
</P>
<P>
   But having control over what people call him may be one of the
few things William will enjoy in the coming years. As of Wednesday,
he is not only legally an adult, he is fair game, and the tabloids
and paparazzi are champing at the bit to get at him, to chronicle
his love life, to document how he and his friends relax, and to
photograph him doing every conceivable thing.
</P>
<P>
   The feeding frenzy over him last week, as official photographs
of William and authorized remarks by him were released to an
insatiable British press corps, underscored the media's obsession
with a handsome and by all accounts decent young man who bears a
haunting resemblance to his dead mother.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Prince Charles's press secretary resigned after she
failed to negotiate the copyright of the authorized photos
properly. The affair was dubbed a scandal by the press, and covered
with all the gravitas of a coup d'etat.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, William seems to be pleading to be left alone.
Before he goes on to university, perhaps to study art history, he
wants to take a year off, maybe travel a bit. When the pool
reporter chosen by palace officials to conduct an interview asked
him whether he had a girlfriend, William said only, ``I like to
keep my private life private.''
</P>
<P>
   A noble aspiration by a noble, but ultimately one that is
doomed. With the gentlemen's agreement to grant William privacy
until he was 18 now scotched, a cottage industry for Prince William
stories was officially opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   William referred to that privacy arrangement when he was asked
how he felt about all the media attention he receives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel uncomfortable with it,'' he said. ``The media have left
me alone while I have been at Eton, for which I am grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   But if William expects continued consideration from the rabid,
royal-obsessed press, he will be disappointed, according to media
observers.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Preston, a former newspaper editor and author of a new
novel whose story line is premised on the end of the royal family,
said newspapers here will inevitably lecture each other about
invading William's privacy, more out of jealousy than real
conviction. But he believes William's privacy is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intrinsically, now, William is our property,'' Preston said in
The Observer. ``We are stuck with him, and he has nowhere else to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the press attempts to be what it considers responsible
in its dealings with William, that becomes a subject of intense
scrutiny. The BBC recently edited from a documentary about William
some advice from a Liverpool teenager that the prince be more
careful in picking his friends, several of whom are reported to
have used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Hale was selected by the BBC to offer advice to William
because he, too, is turning 18 this summer. He grew up in a housing
project and attends a publicly-funded state high school. Although
William enjoyed a far more privileged upbringing, Hale said he
wouldn't trade places.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prince isn't free to live the life of a normal teenager,
and as he gets older the press will never leave him alone,'' said
Hale. ``He was born to be king, and I was born to be his subject. I
think it's ridiculous that in modern Britain, one person should be
thought of as being better than anyone else because of their
birth.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Britons share Hale's sentiments. A poll commissioned by
The Guardian newspaper found that only 44 percent of Britons think
the country would be worse off without the royal family, down from
70 percent just a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's why so much is riding on William. Like his mother, he
brings a touch of glamor to a mostly dowdy royal family that has
had its dysfunctions displayed for the world to see. William's
informality, like his mother's, may endear him to a larger segment
of the public, but such strong personalities can cause problems in
a royal family that wants to be seen as loyal and monolithic.
</P>
<P>
   William's uncle, Charles Spencer, remains bitter at the way his
sister was treated by the rest of the royals. Such family tensions
will always play a divisive role within the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen invited 600 guests to the party at Windsor Castle.
While it fell on William's birthday, the bash was meant to
celebrate the upcoming 100th birthday of the Queen's mother, the
70th of the Queen's sister, Margaret, the 50th of the Queen's
daughter, Anne, and the 40th of her son Andrew, the Duke of York.
Most of the extended royal family was on the guest list, as were
smatterings of royalty from other European countries, many of whom
are related to the Windsors.
</P>
<P>
   Palace staff are hoping that one legacy of Diana, who was
literally chased to her death by paparazzi in Paris nearly three
years ago, is that the press will treat her older son with more
sensitivity. Several have pledged to do so, but palace staffers
remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   As Shakespeare put it in ``Hamlet,'' William will find his life
privileged but tightly controlled, at the mercy of his relatives
and by media that often see him as a device to sell newspapers:
``His will is not his own, for he himself is subject to his birth.
He may not, as unvalued persons do, carve for himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
