A0950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     06-21 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOUTH SIDE GETS TO STRUT IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dispensing with Western Union, Al Capone sent a message to Bugs
Moran. It was delivered on Valentine's Day 1929, from Capone's
South Side headquarters in Chicago to his chief gangland rival in
the city, Moran, on the North Side. The word ``dispatch'' was
obviously taken in a literal sense by the South Siders, who lined
up seven of Moran's operatives in a garage on North Clark Street
and then riddled them with 90 bullets from submachine guns,
shotguns and revolvers.
</P>
<P>
   This comes to mind because the South Side of Chicago is again in
the news, as the White Sox _ whose home base, Comiskey Park, is
just a handful of fungo hits from Big Al's old headquarters _ are
wiping out the opposition, though, in a bloodless manner. The White
Sox are the hottest team in baseball, with the best record, and
play host to the Yankees this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of town, meanwhile, the Cubs continue in their
bewildered ways, finding that their struggle to reach .500 is as
daunting as Hercules cleaning the Augean stables, or at least
trying to find a public toilet in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet comparisons appear inevitable between the White Sox and
their century-old rival, the North Side Cubs. Fandom in Chicago has
traditionally been bitterly and passionately divided _ the way it
was with Dodger and Giant fans in New York. I grew up on the West
Side of Chicago, which might have been thought a middle ground, but
this particular pocket of Lawndale was very much tendentiously Cub.
Everyone there knew who the White Sox fan living in our midst was _
and Rosenfeld was rarely seen on the street after dark. In
contrast: the sister of the fine Chicago sportswriter, Bill
Gleason, from a South Side home, once accepted a free ticket to a
Cubs game in Wrigley Field. The Gleasons' father told her: ``It's
worse than if you left the church.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that the Cubs, on the leafy North Side, are
quiche and white wine, while the Sox, in the often less swanky
districts, are kielbasa and draft beer. Not completely. I am aware
of Sox fans who own yachts in Belmont Harbor, and Cub fans who work
outdoors for the Department of Streets and Sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Wednesday night's game, the Sox had won 14 of their
last 16 games, their record stood at 45-25, for a .643 winning
percentage, and they were seven-and-a-half games ahead of the
Cleveland Indians, the team they have been chasing for the last
five seasons without success, as the Indians captured the American
League Central Division each time.
</P>
<P>
   And before losing Tuesday night to Cleveland, 4-1, the Sox had
won eight straight games _ in remarkable fashion. They went to
Cleveland and swept three games, then moved on to Yankee Stadium
where they embarrassed the defending champs in a four-game sweep.
Back in Comiskey Park on Monday, they whipped Cleveland again.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacular, and unexpected, doesn't stop there. It is
virtually axiomatic in baseball that the teams that spend a lot of
money on players win the bulk of the games. The Yankees, for
example, the team with the highest payroll _ $92.5 million this
year _ won the World Series last season. Seven of the
highest-payroll teams were among the eight in the playoffs last
season.
</P>
<P>
   But the White Sox, with a payroll of $31 million, stand 26th out
of the 30 teams in the major leagues in cash doled to their
on-field laborers. The White Sox have some brilliant young players,
made some trades that _ heavily criticized at first _ proved a
boon, have a few veterans like Frank Thomas who have rediscovered
themselves, and a bespectacled, level-headed manager, Jerry Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the first day of their current homestand, and playing
Cleveland, the White Sox drew a near sellout crowd of 43,062. This
from a team that had been averaging about 21,000 a game. It helped,
obviously, that it was ``Family Half-Price Night,'' all tickets
selling for 50 percent of face value. The next night, at full fare,
20,000 fans showed up for the Indians' game, leaving half the park
empty. The Cubs are again playing to crowds of 33,000 a game, close
to capacity, with few promotions. Fact is, the attraction is purely
Wrigley Field, that ivy-dripping jewel nestled in a gentrified
precinct. The Sox play in a charmless new stadium located in an
industrial setting. They remain one of the poorest drawing teams in
baseball. The belief here is, if players changed ballparks and
beanies, attendance would remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   But now if fans in Chicago want something more thrilling than to
just watch ivy grow, Capone's old 'hood has become the place to
be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
