<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0951 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FIDELITY-SHAKEUP-BOS &LR;      06-21 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-SHAKEUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY MAKES MOVES AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments announced a top-level management
shakeup Wednesday that reflects the broadening reach for the
world's largest mutual fund company _ and suggests that chief
executive Edward C. Johnson III is finally getting ready to pass
the baton to his daughter, Abigail.
</P>
<P>
   The changing of the guard at Fidelity, which manages a
staggering $930 billion in assets, included the promotion of Robert
L. Reynolds, 48, and Robert C. Pozen, 53, who will both join
Johnson's trusted lieutenant James C. Curvey as vice chairmen.
Reynolds, credited with cultivating Fidelity's 401(k) business,
will take over from Curvey as chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the three-man team was seen as a power-sharing
arrangement to help keep a handle on Fidelity's core businesses:
the burgeoning retirement business, individual brokerage accounts,
and capital investing. But Fidelity watchers say the troika also
will help Johnson, 70, ease away from the day-to-day details of the
business. It could also serve as an intermediary link to a future
under Abigail Pierrepont Johnson, 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be the senior senators, all reporting to Caesar. But
Abby will need her own senior senators if eventually she takes
over,'' said James H. Lowell, editor of company-tracking Fidelity
Investor newsletter. ``They are in a generation between Abby and
Ned, and that makes a nice bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity also could be setting itself up for a sale or merger
with another major financial services company, some analysts said,
although Fidelity executives dimissed that notion Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the changes do not pave the way for a merger or the
anticipated succession, they are still seen as significant for the
investment giant. ``Today I think they are telling the world they
are a full-service financial institution,'' said Lowell. ``They are
tacitly acknowledging that the mutual-fund business has matured,
and that to grow, there have got to be other revenue pipelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The family-owned Fidelity has been one of the great American
success stories of the end of the 20th century, helping spark the
revolution that made investing America's favorite pastime over the
last two decades. The company made ``Peter Lynch'' and ``Magellan''
household terms and controls the money of millions of average
investors through individual or 401(k) accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity dominates the mutual fund market so completely that it
recovered quickly from investing stumbles and administrative snafus
in the '90s did not slow what Fidelity-watcher Eric M. Kobren calls
the ``mind-boggling'' flow of cash pouring into the company.
Management fees alone on almost $1 trillion helped spur record
profits last year of a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's built-in. The money just keeps on coming in day after
day,'' said Kobren, editor of the newsletter Fidelity Insights, a
money manager himself, and like Lowell, a past employee of
Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's assets under management increased 84 percent, to
$952.5 billion, from 1997 to 2000. Net sales, revenue, and
operating income also increased dramatically. During the same
period, the company grew from 24,000 to 30,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity also moved quickly to capture a significant portion of
the online trading business, creating its Powerstreet online
brokerage Web site and moving customer investment activity
seamlessly over to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment of riches has created its own difficulties,
however. One problem is employee retention, as money managers in a
bull market use Fidelity as a training ground and then leave for a
lucrative hedge fund. Another problem is the basic issue of
managing a high-growth business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has recognized it cannot rely on the retail mutual
fund business for its future, that they've got to cast a very wide
net,'' said Lowell. ``But that means a management nightmare. They
own 75 percent of the retirement sales market _ that's a huge
management issue. They've got a lot of management issues tied with
their desire to hold onto assets and to grow assets.''
</P>
<P>
   To guide the change in focus from mutual funds to a
broader-based financial services firm, Reynolds is seen as a
classic, lead-the-charge manager. Reynolds, a 16-year Fidelity
veteran who will oversee distribution and service in his new role,
also has expertise in the high-growth retirement business, as head
of Fidelity Investments Institutional Retirement Group since March
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement business that Reynolds headed will be
restructured, so that Peter J. Smail will run the separate Fidelity
Employer Services Co. and Ellyn A. McColgan will run the Tax-Exempt
Services Co., Fidelity also announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a business that has grown very rapidly,'' Reynolds
said in an interview. Fidelity handles the retirement accounts for
9,000 companies nationally and 9 million individuals.
</P>
<P>
   But Reynolds said his elevation to chief operating officer was
not a direct reflection of the importance of that part of the
business, and added that the three main segments of the business _
capital investing, retirement, and retail _ were all equally
important. ``The future of Fidelity and the success of this firm is
dependent on those three separate areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Pozen, a 13-year Fidelity veteran, will continue as investment
adviser for Fidelity's storied mutual funds _ still the foundation
of the business. Pozen, who will continue as president of Fidelity
Management &AMP; Research Co., is known for being direct, a balance for
Reynolds' consensus-building skills.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Curvey, who some thought might retire, will return to
manage Fidelity Capital and Ventures, which he ran before being
tapped by Johnson to be president and chief operating officer in
1997. Curvey will oversee that part of the business including the
successful telecommunications group; the real estate development
arm that has financed the renovation of Boston's World Trade Center
and the construction of a hotel and office buildings on the
burgeoning South Boston Waterfront; BostonCoach, the executive
limousine business; and Community Newspaper Co., which operates a
chain of daily and weekly newspapers in Eastern Massachusetts. At
64, Curvey is seen as being a steady voice of wisdom and an
important link to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The division of labor among Reynolds, Pozen, and Curvey reflects
the need to keep tabs on the sprawling and upward-spiraling aspects
of the business, analysts said. But another solution would be to
reach the next level in Fidelity's long evolution: a spinoff or
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Management complexities and pressure on the employee base
``could put pressure on them to go public with a Wells Fargo, spin
off the distribution arm and go public with a retail brokerage
entity,'' said Kobren. ``The other option is if Ned feels they
would be better off with a large international financial services
firm, a merger on the level of Smith Barney- Citigroup.''
</P>
<P>
   There have also been reports of strengthened ties with Lehman
Bros., but Fidelity executives downplayed that possibility. ``To be
successful today you do have to have alliances . . . we're looking
for new ones, but no acquisitions are planned,'' said Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to acquire anybody, we're not going to be
acquired, we're going to stay private, we're a very stable
organization,'' said Pozen. International expansion is being
accomplished through internal growth, ``not trying to acquire a
firm in the international market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for succession plans, Curvey said that there were ``no
present plans for Ned to retire. He's very much involved in the
game, very young, very energetic, and still has a good time.'' He
said that splitting the business into three parts would give
Johnson a convenient, ``broader coverage of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning Abigail Johnson, Pozen said she will continue as a
trustee and senior vice president at the investment arm, working
with portfolio managers, and that ``this . . . doesn't impact that
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Kobren said the changes could be seen as an intermediary step,
such that the father and daughter would not change their roles very
much at all _ at least not immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ned's not going to leave his baby,'' Kobren said. ``What he
has done is give Jim Curvey more responsibility as his trust grew,
and now he has show his trust in Pozen and Reynolds. Abigail has a
family to raise, is content to work on the investment side, and I
suspect will remain in that capacity, not putting in seven days a
week or becoming a leader on a day-to-day basis.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Kobren said, ``she doesn't have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
