<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DNA-INK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY OLYMPICS TURNS TO DNA INK TO MARK OFFICIAL SOUVENIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By DANIEL SORID    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   High technology is nothing new for the Olympics. From
finish-line computers to drug tests, the Olympic committee has
often been an early adopter. This summer, technology will come into
play where it really matters: the sale of souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the sale of counterfeit items at the Olympics, the
Sydney Olympics organizing committee is using ink containing DNA to
mark official merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   DNA Technologies of Los Angeles developed the ink, which
contains copies of DNA strands from an Australian athlete who has
not been identified as well as a chemical that can be easily
identified with an optical scanner.
</P>
<P>
   DNA Technologies has developed inks, invisible or colored, for
about a dozen companies; in some cases, the DNA strands used have
come from celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   For the Olympic souvenirs, the special ink is placed either
directly on the goods or on a tag attached to them. If an Olympic
official suspects that a product is not authentic, the product can
be scanned on the spot as a preliminary check. To check the DNA,
the product can be sent to the company for an analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike holograms, which can be copied, DNA ink is virtually
counterfeit-proof, said Chris Outwater, the chief executive of DNA
Technologies, because DNA, which contains a person's genetic code,
is so complex.
</P>
<P>
   Making the DNA tags is fairly straightforward. According to
Outwater, a DNA sample is taken with either a blood sample or a
swab of the mouth, and that DNA is copied many times. Some DNA is
kept as an identifier, and some is mixed into the ink that is
placed on the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need a small fragment,'' Outwater said, ``to give us
enough complexity to stop any counterfeiter or bad person from
trying to copy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Outwater said there was one chance in a trillion that a
counterfeiter would be able to duplicate a tag because each DNA
string used is made up of at least 20 ``beads''; each bead can be
one of four molecules. Even if counterfeiters knew that the pieces
of DNA in the ink were from a particular person's DNA, they would
still have to figure out what part of the DNA had been used as a
tag. Outwater gave this analogy: ``You're standing out in front of
the New York Public Library, and you say to the counterfeiter, `I'm
using one sentence out of one book in that library. You figure it
out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Or counterfeiters could presumably clone the DNA in the tags to
make their own version of the real ink. But Dr. Rick Tullis, a
consultant to the company, said that would not be feasible because
the DNA can be treated to make it hard to copy and other pieces of
DNA can be included in the solution to foil counterfeiters.
</P>
<P>
   Why go to so much effort? The sale of official merchandise at
the Sydney Olympics is expected to reach $36 million, according to
the Sydney Olympics organizing committee. That money, the committee
says, is used to finance Olympic programs. And in one example of
the severity of the problem with counterfeit products, the Customs
Service points out that counterfeit products cost the United States
economy around $200 billion a year, more than the annual gross
domestic product of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The technique used by Outwater's company, which received a
contract with the Sydney Olympics organizers in 1998, is not
perfected. While the company is making enough DNA tags to mark
about 10 million souvenir items for the Olympics, it does not have
a handheld device that can verify beyond a doubt that a product is
authentic. Authorities doing spot checks of vending areas cannot
test for the DNA itself, Outwater said. To do that, the inspector
must send the item to DNA Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Outwater says the instant checks have been adequate for the
company's customers in the last two years _ no customer has
actually sent an item to DNA Technologies for a DNA analysis.
</P>
<P>
   DNA Technologies has made DNA tags for more than just the
Olympics. It used DNA tags to mark Mark McGwire's 70th-home-run
ball and to protect movie props at Warner Brothers that ``tend to
walk off the lot,'' Outwater said. Warner Brothers hopes that the
tags will help the company identify stolen items that are offered
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   As more companies turn to the Internet to sell consumer
merchandise, there will be a greater push for anti-counterfeit
measures like DNA tagging, Outwater said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little more scary to be on the Internet in some virtual
store and not know exactly what you're buying,'' he said. With DNA
tags, he contended, ``you're going to know that this is an
authentic product.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
