$4.3 billion purchase of US Airways as a ``win-win for consumers''
that will usher in a glorious new era of global air service. But
many passengers see the proposed merger rather differently. For
them, air travel is already a grim reality of high fares,
interminable check-in lines, overcrowded planes, endless delays and
stingy in-flight meals. Those two visions are now on a collision
course in Washington. By Laurence Zuckerman.
