<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-STRATEGY-GAME-NYT     06-21 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STRATEGY-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING FOR POSSESSION OF PLANET KRIG-7B 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER OLAFSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ground Control; published by Sierra Studios; $49.95; for Windows
95 and 98; for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there is supposed to be half the fun, but in the popular
genre of real-time strategy games, getting there can sometimes seem
like work.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatched to a destination by the player, vehicles may bump up
against stationary objects encountered en route and stop. They
wander into cul-de-sacs and can't escape. They push against
unclimbable cliffs. They bunch up at corners, looking less like
fearsome military units than tourists consulting a map. This is
supposed to be fun?
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Studios' Ground Control, it is. This three-dimensional
strategy game, developed by Sweden's Massive Entertainment, offers
spectacular graphics, compelling weapons, simple controls and a
manageable structure. But Ground Control is equally instructive in
the importance of the routine but vital business of moving through
the game environment. It is so lifelike and seamless that simply
being in the game is its own reward.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 2419, Ground Control casts the player as Sarah Parker, of
the Crayven Corp., which is fighting the Order of the New Dawn for
control of the planet Krig-7b.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with a small force of lightly armored vehicles, Parker
performs tasks common to games of this type: Destroy a convoy,
level an enemy base or claim an alien artifact. Unlike games that
often require the player to collect resources and build new units,
the player in Ground Control is typically limited to the forces
deposited on the planet's surface at the start of a mission.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on fighting is realistic and helps keep the controls
blissfully simple. You select units with the mouse, indicate their
destination and off they go _ in a formation and with a combat
posture you assign.
</P>
<P>
   The main vehicle is the armored personnel carrier, from which
the player runs the show. It can re-charge depleted units nearby
and transport infantry. If it is destroyed, the mission ends and
you will have to restart from the beginning. (Progress is
automatically saved at the end of each completed mission, but no
provision is made for saving during a mission.)
</P>
<P>
   Combat is a vivid experience. The shells from a mobile artillery
unit arrive thunderously at their target, transforming durable
enemy outposts into blackened ruins with tilted defense turrets.
These bright detonations seem real and carry such a feeling of
omnipotence that I invariably stopped whatever else I was doing in
the game just to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I found myself watching Ground Control a lot. I found
it exhilarating just to see my units on the move _ whether
exploring a jungle or just trundling along an open plain. You can
jump to any unit _ indeed, you can adjust the game camera at will _
and there is always a sense of anticipation and threat.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the artillery unit moves like the real thing,
leaving a dust cloud and tread marks in its wake. It lumbers behind
the other forces and, unescorted, can fall prey to enemy patrols.
With each shot, the unit recoils and ejects a shell casing. The
shells leave a feathery vapor trail as they arc through the air.
Seeing them feels ominous, even when you are not on the receiving
end.
</P>
<P>
   And the unit goes where it is ordered. Ground Control's
``path-finding'' _ the artificial intelligence that instructs your
units how to negotiate terrain to reach a new location _ manages to
carry out its tasks with realism that is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the scenario in which Parker was assigned to defend the
approaches to a base. I broke my force into three groups, and sent
the personnel carrier with the weakest group. As I watched the unit
move into position, I saw another climbing a hill. It moved
speedily and with a smooth assurance, as though it had been born to
the task, and I wondered to whom it could belong. Then I realized
it was one of my units.
</P>
<P>
   All my units ran into trouble and were ordered to abandon the
base and withdraw with any usable equipment to a pick-up point to
the northeast. I panicked and, rather than micro-managing the
withdrawal, I just selected each unit and moved them en masse
toward their destination. The amazing thing was that, despite a
landscape rife with nooks and crannies with the potential to
ensnare units, most of them made it. (Some were shot up along the
way.) As enemy units poured into the base, the tattered remnants of
my forces, under a rain of fire, finally converged in a deep canyon
leading to the evacuation zone.
</P>
<P>
   In another game, that might have been an invitation to a traffic
jam. But there was no traffic jam. The units did not get lost. They
did not stop in unauthorized spots. They did not behave like
tourists. Instead, they rounded corners in smooth, continuous
movements. They followed each other at sensible intervals, and they
followed the terrain as though they knew it by heart. It made the
ordinary seem elegant and elegance seem easy. I cannot think of a
better definition of style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
