A0962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SHOOTING0622-COX     06-21 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SHOOTING0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    400 gunning for 30 spots in Olympics
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than 400 of the country's best shooters have
started arriving at the Tom Lowe Shooting Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, they will compete for the next week and a half
for 30 slots on the U.S. Olympic shooting team.
</P>
<P>
   Trials begin today with men's air rifle, women's sport rifle and
trap. The trials end July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 slots are:
</P>
<P>
   Three slots each for women's three-position free rifle and men's
trap.
</P>
<P>
   Two slots each for men's air pistol, men's free pistol, women's
sport pistol, men's air rifle, women's air rifle, men's
three-position free rifle, men's free rifle prone, men's running
target, men's double trap and men's skeet.
</P>
<P>
   One slot each for women's air pistol, women's trap, women's
double trap and women's skeet.
</P>
<P>
   No quota slots were earned for rapid-fire pistol, but a
rapid-fire competition still will be held.
</P>
<P>
   This trial is the second and final of two qualifying events. The
first Olympic selection match was held in April and May at Fort
Benning.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympians will be determined by the combined scores of the
two events.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the finals, Benning's U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit
has 10 competitors halfway to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are 1996 Olympians Capt. Glenn Dubis, free rifle
prone; SFC Theresa DeWitt, women's double trap; SFC Todd Graves,
skeet; and Sgt. David Alcoriza, men's double trap.
</P>
<P>
   The top local challenger is Stone Mountain's Cindy Gentry in
women's trap.
</P>
<P>
   The first finals will be Friday in men's air rifle and women's
sport. Trap finals will be Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
