A0963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TRAIN-COLLISION0622-C     06-21 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-COLLISION0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No serious injuries in truck, train collision
 &HT;    By Andy Adams
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A Union Pacific train derailed between Lufkin
and Burke on Wednesday morning after colliding with the trailer of
an 18-wheeler that was loaded with steel beams.
</P>
<P>
   The truck's driver, 31-year-old Herbert Orlando Echegoyen of
Houston, had pulled across the small Neyland Road railroad crossing
to turn the truck around, according to Texas Department of Public
Safety Senior Trooper Kevin Malone. Echegoyen was transporting the
steel to Lufkin Industries, but turned the wrong way off Loop 287
in Lufkin, the trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said witnesses to the accident claimed Echegoyen pulled
his truck across the tracks ``and just kind of sat there'' until
the train struck the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd backed up and kept backing, he'd have been OK,''
Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was seriously injured in the accident, although
47-year-old engineer Larry G. Cullins and 34-year-old conductor
Joseph T. Debruhl, both of Houston, were taken to the Memorial
Health System of East Texas for precautionary measures. Also, DPS
troopers said Echegoyen complained of back pains at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The train's eight locomotives piled up after they struck the
truck trailer, while Malone said the steel from the trailer ``kind
of looks like a roller coaster'' after it was bent in all different
directions from the impact. Sections of the railroad tracks also
were pushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cullins said he was standing when he saw the 18-wheeler across
the railroad tracks in front of him, but that he and Debruhl hit
the floor of the locomotive and looked for something to hold onto
before impact. Cullins said the estimated 15 seconds of the crash
felt more like a million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they tell you that your life flashes before your eyes _
it does,'' the engineer said. ``It scared me, because I did not
know whether we were going to go sideways or stay upright or what.
It was scary. I feel very fortunate to have survived.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no railroad crossing signals or gates at Neyland Road
where it crosses the railroad tracks. But Smith said the truck
driver had at least a small amount of warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The train was blowing his horn,'' she said. ``I mean, he was
sitting on that horn.''
</P>
<P>
   No chemicals were being transported by the train, although the
Lufkin Fire Department was called to spray foam on a large amount
of diesel fuel that spilled from the train's engines. The types of
rail cars being pulled behind the locomotives included box cars,
covered hoppers, gondolas and auto racks, but it was not
immediately known if any new cars were being transported.
</P>
<P>
   A railroad official at the scene said he could not comment on
the accident, but DPS Senior Trooper Bo Dunkin estimated that the
train was traveling upwards of 50 mph when it hit the trailer. He
said he believes locomotives have something that is similar to
black boxes in airplanes, and that railroad officials should be
able to determine train speed, its horn usage and other data about
the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The DPS troopers said Union Pacific officials were expected to
move some of the wreckage aside and fix the tracks as soon as
possible, since a high level of train traffic uses the rail line.
By early afternoon Wednesday, more than 100 employees of the
railroad and private companies were already working to clean up the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
