<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-LABOR0622-COX     06-21 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labor plans forums to rip Bush record
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a bid to aid Vice President Al Gore, AFL-CIO
President John Sweeney is scheduling town hall meetings in cities
around the country to criticize Gov. George W. Bush's record on
labor issues.
</P>
<P>
   Planned for key battleground states, the town hall meetings are
designed to dampen enthusiasm for Bush among rank and file union
members. Support from labor voters, who typically turnout in higher
numbers than the general public, will be critical for Gore in a
dozen or more states where unions are strong.
</P>
<P>
   The first town hall meeting is scheduled June 29 in
Philadelphia, the site of the Republican National Convention, and
will feature union members from Texas, Bush's home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a below zero rating with us,'' Texas AFL-CIO
President Joe Gunn said of Bush. ``He's earned it. It hasn't been
accidental.''
</P>
<P>
   The town hall meetings come as Gore faces several challenges
within sectors of the 13 million-member labor organization.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James P. Hoffa, representing one of the
AFL-CIO's largest affiliates, has invited Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader to the Teamsters' executive board meeting in Washington
today.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Nader nor the Teamsters is calling the meeting an
endorsement, but Hoffa plans to hold a news conference with Nader
afterward, giving Nader plenty of free publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hoffa has made clear that he feels that the Teamsters have
been burned by the administration,'' said Laura Jones, a
spokeswoman for Nader. ``Mr. Nader is continuing to meet with labor
to discuss his platform and his commitment to labor issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Few give Nader any chance of winning the presidency, but he
could damage Gore by siphoning away the votes of some liberal and
union voters, especially in battleground states such as
Pennsylvania, Ohio and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters and the United Auto Workers, whose members are
heavily concentrated in key Midwestern states, have declined to
endorse Gore. They also disagreed with Sweeney over the AFL-CIO's
decision to endorse Gore last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Both unions are angry with Gore because of the Clinton
administration's support for permanent normal trading relations
with China. The House voted to grant the trade status last month,
and a bill is awaiting action in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sweeney, Gore's most vocal backer in the labor movement, is
concerned that Gore's position on China could dampen turnout among
some union members. Labor leaders believe Democrats lost control of
the House in 1994 because union members, upset with the passage of
the North American Free Trade Agreement, voted in historically
lower numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said Gore's position on China would be an issue
throughout the campaign. ``We have members who are still bitter
over NAFTA, especially in the industrial states,'' Sweeney said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the AFL-CIO is devoting millions to a broad-based
political effort geared toward turning union members out to vote
for pro-labor candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message is to convince workers and their families that we
don't agree on everything with any candidate, and trade has been an
issue with Clinton and Gore,'' Sweeney said. ``But you have to look
at the total record, and you have to see how strong he is, in
Gore's case, on working family issues. . . . The thought of George
Bush, with his Texas record, is really horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Philadelphia, the AFL-CIO is planning town hall
meetings in Atlanta, Albuquerque, N.M., Chicago, Cleveland,
Hartford, Conn., Los Angeles and Louisville, Ky., with other cities
possible. All of the cities have significant numbers of union
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-21 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ARTICLE AS BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lately it seems as if the tables of contents in magazines are
becoming the nonfiction shopping lists for book publishers. Just
within the last week, for instance, this fascination with magazine
cover stories has had publishers thrashing over those in Esquire
and The Atlantic Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   In the July issue of Esquire, the cover article was about the
Worcester, Mass., warehouse fire last December in which six
firefighters died. The headline inside the magazine, although not
out front, was ``The Perfect Fire,'' an obvious knockoff of the
title of the best-selling Sebastian Junger book and George Clooney
movie ``The Perfect Storm.'' Within 24 hours the article was sold
to Warner Books for a sizable six-figure advance. Moreover, the
article, as it appeared in the magazine, was apparently considered
such a potent awareness builder for a full-length work that it was
sold without a book proposal or even an auction for potential
buyers. According to Variety the story is already ``sending
twitters'' around Hollywood. (The publisher, at least, promises the
book will have a fresh title.)
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Monthly's June issue had on its cover ``Harvard and
the Making of the Unabomber,'' and, after an auction, a book based
on it was sold to W.W. Norton for an advance of more than $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about turning magazine articles into books.
John Hersey's classic ``Hiroshima'' was first published as the
entire issue of The New Yorker in 1946 before becoming a Knopf
book; like it, Rachel Carson's 1962 book ``The Silent Spring''
(Houghton Mifflin) also first appeared in The New Yorker. More
recently, there is Michael Paterniti's soon-to-be-published
``Driving Albert'' (Dial Press), the true chronicle of conveying
Einstein's brain across the United States in a car trunk that first
appeared in Harper's; Jon Krakauer's ``Into Thin Air'' and ``Into
the Wild,'' (both Villard), grew from work in Outside magazine. But
The New Yorker still seems to be the best source. ``The Tipping
Point'' (Little, Brown), by Malcolm Gladwell, was an expansion of
an article in that magazine, and so, too, was Anthony Bourdain's
``Kitchen Confidential'' (Bloomsbury).
</P>
<P>
   The question really is whether these concepts would have as
quickly and as lucratively become books had they not been prominent
magazine articles and instead were peddled only through the
traditional method of authors' agents submitting written, often
lengthily, book proposals to editors and publishers. A book
proposal is the prospectus or the campaign map of a concept,
showing how the writer will attack the material, laying out in
almost diagnostic fashion what will be in the finished manuscript.
And it shows the author's mastery of material and writing style,
although it's not uncommon for a really good book writer to produce
a really terrible proposal. Which is one of the risks of the game.
</P>
<P>
   David Black, one of a few literary agents known for torturing
clients into writing the perfect proposal, sold Sean Flynn's story
of the Worcester inferno to Rick Horgan, an executive editor at
Warner Books without a proposal and without offering it to another
publisher. It's something he doesn't like to do. This was an
anomaly. ``Most magazines are running shorter pieces, rather than
longer ones,'' Black said, ``so you need a good proposal to develop
the blueprint for a book. In this case, the piece was long and
didn't need the transition. You got a lot of the framework.'' He
says a well-done proposal is not only a selling point but usually
leads to a well-done book: ``Most of my client list are
journalists, and most of them spend a lot of time developing
proposals before the book is sold.'' Often, of course, his clients
have both: a magazine article and a proposal. He said, ``With a
great proposal, you have a writer who has thought through the
larger themes; what they are presenting is a larger canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   Horgan of Warner Books said that ``the shorter magazine piece
makes the dramatic arch of the story visible, and sometimes the
conclusion you reach is that a magazine article is the best format
for that particular story.'' He said: ``Generally I want a
proposal, but this time it was obvious from the magazine article
that if the writer had more room to work with he could have layered
in more material, deeper characters. We did have a lengthy
conversation on how the book should be shaped.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing is a risk business involving, among many factors,
keeping one's eye on the competition. ``It's incumbent on editors
these days to take a flier once in a while,'' Horgan said. ``So I
decided to make a quick offer. I called David at 9:30 a.m. last
Tuesday, and we had a deal in principal in place by 2 p.m. We both
took a risk. You can get carried away in the fray of an auction
while you're evaluating the competition. We have a saying here that
sometimes he who wins the auction loses.
</P>
<P>
   Over at W.W. Norton, its editor in chief, Starling Lawrence, had
a proposal on Alston Chase's story of Theodore Kaczynski, the
Unabomber, from Chase's agent, Deborah Grosvenor. It elaborated on
the Atlantic article and offered material not in it, including
information about Kaczynski's sexual history that goes somewhat
beyond the court records of the case, which revealed that he had
considered a sex-change operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal also showed the direction in which a book would
grow from a magazine article, how Alston would attack the subject,
and what his insights are,'' Lawrence said. ``You always want to
see the thinking that makes a book from a magazine article.'' David
Hirshey, the executive editor of HarperCollins and the former
editor of Esquire, said that although ``it seems insane to pay out
so much based on a magazine piece, these articles can be very
seductive because it gives the book editor a tangible illustration
of what the book could turn out to be.'' But he added: ``It's much
like viewing a movie trailer. Often you see great trailers turned
into disappointing movies. The best of all possible worlds is a
great magazine piece and a proposal that says, `Here's what I
didn't say in the magazine and it's even better than what you
read.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are agents who encourage their clients to negotiate their
own magazine sales, because such sales take up too much time for 15
percent of relatively small fees. This will certainly change if the
trend from magazine cover into lucrative book deal gets even more
bullish. For if it does, the same material will then command not
one but two, more robust paydays; or even three, if there's a movie
at the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
