<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White, chafing in retirement, reportedly talks with Titans
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reggie White's career might have a second act.
</P>
<P>
   White, the NFL's career sacks leader who retired from the Green
Bay Packers after the 1998 season, has indicated interest in coming
back to the game.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in The Tennessean in Nashville on
Wednesday, White has spoken with Titans coach Jeff Fisher about how
he could be used by Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers hold White's contractual rights, but White's agent,
Jimmy Sexton, said Green Bay has allowed White to talk to other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that's happened is we've been given permission to talk to
a team,'' Sexton said. ``No offers have been made, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans media relations director Tony Wyllie said the team could
not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans look like a good possibility for a number of reasons.
White, 38, was born in Chattanooga and played for the University of
Tennessee. He played for Fisher when he was the Philadelphia
Eagles' defensive coordinator in 1989 and 1990. Perhaps most
important, the NFL on Tuesday upheld its suspension of Titans
defensive tackle Josh Evans for the season for a repeat violation
of the league's substance abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, however, don't have much room under the salary cap.
The team is $54,000 under the cap right now. Tennessee will have
Evans' $900,000 base salary because of the suspension, but the
Titans have not signed any of their draft picks and are negotiating
a contract extension with running back Eddie George. Furthermore,
White's 1998 base salary was $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   White's adjustment to retired life apparently hasn't been easy.
Sheri Tanner, a manager of Reggie White's All-Pro Shop in Green
Bay, said she wasn't surprised by the talk of a return.
</P>
<P>
   He has a home in Green Bay but didn't spend much time there last
fall because, Tanner said, ``He had a tough time'' being so close
to the game but not a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know at the time he did retire, he really wasn't happy about
retiring,'' she said. ``It was something his heart wasn't set on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
