<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-DEATH-CITY-HNS &LR;      06-21 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-CITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HUB OF TEXAS EXECUTIONS PREPAPES FOR THE WORST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY DORSETT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ With convicted killer Gary Graham scheduled
to be put to death on Thursday, the home of Texas' execution
chamber is taking no chances. State prison officials expect
thousands to come to the Walls Unit downtown to protest the
execution, and some fear riots and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Stores, restaurants and businesses, including the courthouse,
plan to close after lunch Thursday, allowing their employees to
leave the area in advance of any protests.
</P>
<P>
   Activists from the United States and abroad have protested
Graham's scheduled execution, contending he did not get a fair
trial and may be innocent of the 1981 murder that landed him on
Texas' death row.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, now 36, was sentenced to death for the shooting and
robbery of Bobby Grant Lambert outside a Houston supermarket. The
testimony of one witness led to his conviction and no physical
evidence linked him to the crime. Two grocery store employees who
saw the suspect have said Graham was not the killer. They were
never called to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's case has been through dozens of court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles is expected to announce a
recommendation on Graham's application for clemency at noon, six
hours before he is scheduled to be put to death by lethal
injection. It will then be up to Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential hopeful, to act on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   In Huntsville, a town of 35,000 north of Houston, the Cafe Texan
has served as a meeting place for locals since it opened in 1936.
People who grew up here meet daily over their morning coffee and
newspaper to discuss current events. On Wednesday, the Graham
execution peppered many conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Located on the courthouse square, about three blocks from the
Walls Unit where executions are carried out, the Cafe Texan will
shut its doors at 2 p.m., six hours earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel confident we're not going to have any major
catastrophe of any sort,'' said John Strickland, owner of the cafe.
``I'm doing this for the precaution and safety of my employees. I'm
not even taking a chance on endangering them. I will stay here to
protect my property.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Henry, 45, isn't as optimistic as Strickland and wonders if
the police and prison officials will be able to handle a large
crowd of protesters _ especially if it becomes unruly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my home _ they don't know anything about rioting,''
said Henry, who works in the automotive business. ``It'll freak
Huntsville out. They don't know how to do it. They're as lost as a
goose.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Williams, who owns a framing gallery less than two blocks
away from the Walls Unit, said she would like to see the death
chamber moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Texas needs to take the responsibility to take
the execution (chamber) away from the town square. It's two blocks
from the hub of town,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Fitzgerald, spokesman for the prison system, said law
enforcement officials will be prepared to deal with a hostile
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking every possible precaution,'' he said. ``We've
been aware of all the events. We're taking the steps necessary to
ensure public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the agencies that will be involved in security are the
Department of Public Safety, Texas Department of Criminal Justice
and the police and sheriff's department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate any unruliness,'' Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Groups expected to protest represent both sides of the
controversial execution. Among those expected to protest against it
are the American Civil Liberties Union, Rainbow Coalition and
Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials also are preparing to have another fight on
their hands _ Graham has vowed to physically resist the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not willingly participate in my lynching,'' he said in
a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said Graham would not be sedated, but officers in
riot gear would use tear gas if he resists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not treating Gary Graham any differently than we do any
other inmate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is what happens outside the prison walls that is of concern
to residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Huntsville will be outnumbered. I think it will be
lost,'' Henry said as he finished his morning coffee. ``Everyone's
on pins and needles. They want it to hurry up and be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
