<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ONDAATJE-NOVEL-NYT &LR;      06-21 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONDAATJE-NOVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEARTHING SECRETS, FICTIONAL AND REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MEL GUSSOW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Archaeology as a search for hidden truth is a central theme of
Michael Ondaatje's new novel, ``Anil's Ghost,'' and was very much
on his mind during a recent interview. ``Writing is a kind of
archaeological act,'' he said. ``In all my books there is a
discovery of a story. You're unearthing and you're learning. The
drama is to find out about the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   For him a novel is both intuitive and exploratory. He said that
when he begins a book he never knows the outcome or even the full
cast of characters. People suddenly appear, assume identities and
move the narrative forward. All this was true of ``The English
Patient,'' Ontaadje's Booker Prize-winning novel (and later an
Oscar-winning film), and it is true of ``Anil's Ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   In his novels Ondaatje writes about displaced persons, people
who are unsure of where they belong and to whom they owe their
allegiance: the title character and the Sikh demolitions expert in
``The English Patient,'' Anil Tissera and other characters in
``Anil's Ghost.'' Anil is a young forensic anthropologist who
returns from the United States to her homeland, Sri Lanka, on a
humanitarian mission. She joins forces with an archaeologist to
investigate possible war crimes. The principal subject of their
investigation is the skeleton of what appears to be a victim of
torture.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ondaatje is also a poet, his books are often called
poetic novels, a label he greets with dismay: ``I'm not sure I
would go out of my way to take poetic novels to a desert island.''
For him, the interplay between his poetry and his fiction is far
more subtle. ``William Carlos Williams talked about a poem as
something that didn't have any extra parts in it,'' he said. The
idea of distillation is carried over into his fiction. This means
that his novels are ``tighter, more contained, more suggestive.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time they are filled with haunting imagery. In
``Anil's Ghost'' Anil is told the story of the excavation of a
lacquered coffin of an ancient Chinese ruler, buried alongside 20
female musicians. The bodies were bones, but the musical
instruments _ drums, zithers, bells _ survived. In the fifth
century B.C. music was regarded as a moral and spiritual force.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense Anil is a stand-in for the author, who left Sri Lanka
at 11 and grew up in London, where his mother lived after
separating from his father. Later he emigrated to Canada. Now 56,
he is a Canadian citizen of Indian, Dutch and Sinhalese ancestry,
and the book represents his own homecoming to Sri Lanka. This is
the first of his four novels to take place in his native country,
he said, although he has dealt with it before in his poetry and in
his memoir, ``Running in the Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lanka is, in fact, the reason for the book. He began with a
place, a time and an event: a civil war in the mid 1980s. ``I
didn't want it to be a tract against Sri Lanka,'' he said. ``I
wanted to catch that state of the world, people in that kind of
situation, which was a nightmare.'' He intended his story to have
emanations of battles in other countries, like Bosnia and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not want to write about Sri Lanka from the point
of view of someone who lived there permanently. Instead he chose as
his protagonist ``someone who was a stranger but who had come from
that country.'' Anil's insights are shadowed by memories from her
childhood. To give an added perspective he decided to make the
protagonist a woman ``who had been liberated by living in the West
and was now in a country that was a male world.'' That choice, he
said, ``gave me an extra pair of glasses and allowed me to see the
place differently.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anil and the archaeologist, Sarath, investigate the mystery
of the unknown victim, they themselves and others in their lives
are revealed: ``The searchers, the detectives, are the ones who are
being discovered in the novel,'' Ondaatje said. ``We learn how they
have been created by their past.'' The ``real forensics'' in the
book are about these characters and Sarath's brother, and about an
artist who paints eyes on statues of Buddha but is forbidden to
look at the face of the deity.
</P>
<P>
   When Ondaatje began the book, all he knew about Sarath was that
he would be Anil's foil, that he would be more languid in contrast
to her enthusiasm and determination. At their first meeting, Sarath
is noncommittal, offering the equivalent of ``the Asian nod,''
which is a ``very hesitant head roll that means yes and no,'' the
author said. ``It's the kind of thing Henry James should have been
doing a lot of.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point the novel was a matter of accretion, growth and
constant revision. Ondaatje's own obsession is with revising, one
reason that it took him eight years to finish the novel, his first
since ``The English Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the incidents in the new book are drawn from fact;
others are invention, for example the astonishing adventure of a
surgeon who is kidnapped by rebels and forced to operate on the
wounded behind the lines. The rebels also kidnap a nurse and steal
medical supplies. The doctor soon finds himself totally caught up
in his rescue work.
</P>
<P>
   Everything of course is filtered through the author's
imagination, which often approaches that of such magic realists as
Gabriel Garcia Marquez. ``When I read Marquez for the first time,''
he said, ``it was like realism to me. It was like Sri Lanka.'' His
most Marquezian book is his memoir, a fanciful dream journey
through the lives of his parents and their relatives, eccentrics
including an uncle who was killed when a hunting companion mistook
him for a wild boar. In the memoir he says that from his mother he
received his sense of the dramatic, from his father secrecy and
reclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   He also writes of strange Sri Lankan traditions: it is believed
that if a child eats the tongue of a thalagoya, a crocodile-like
reptile, he becomes brilliant. Ondaatje did not partake of this
``repulsive creature.'' But in his own way, without artificial
intelligence or training as a writer, he embarked on a brilliant
career in which his literary reputation is matched by his
popularity. Both ``The English Patient'' and ``Anil's Ghost'' are
best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Ondaatje, who went to Canada because his brother Christopher was
there, did not start writing until he was in his early 20s. ``I
didn't know I wanted to be a writer,'' he said. ``There hadn't been
a burning desire.'' But in Canada he felt a sudden freedom and a
realization that ``I could attempt anything, I could be a writer or
a filmmaker.'' (He has made two documentary films.)
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by a teacher at the University of Toronto, he began
writing poetry, which ranged from the domestic to the mythological.
His first book of poetry was published in 1967. In 1970 he wrote
``The Collected Works of Billy the Kid,'' which was part poem, part
historical novel, and was subsequently dramatized onstage. Since
then he has alternated between poetry and fiction. He and his wife,
Linda Spalding, live in Toronto, where they edit Brick, a literary
journal.
</P>
<P>
   His first novel, ``Coming Through Slaughter,'' inspired by the
life of the jazzman Buddy Bolden, was, he said, ``a mental
landscape, where you put yourself and real people into an imagined
situation.'' ``Anil's Ghost'' was different: fictional people on a
real landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who has been very much a migrant in my life and as
a writer,'' he said, ``one of the things you envy is Faulkner's
postage stamp of Yoknapatawpha County or Alice Munro's southwest
Ontario. That is the opposite of me, but in some odd way in this
book, there is a landscape I knew very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
