<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SEEK DEPTH WITH NO. 7 DRAFT PICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the end of the regular season in April, when the
Bruins' year was mercifully over, assistant general manager Mike
O'Connell sat down with many members of his club and picked their
brains about what went wrong, about the future and what they think
about the present.
</P>
<P>
   He said it wasn't as bleak as it appeared from the pitiful
statistics that had Boston on the outside of the postseason for the
second time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   With the expansion draft on tap for Friday and the entry draft
scheduled for Saturday in Calgary, the Bruins will use the No. 7
overall pick as a chance to add depth to the organization.
O'Connell said they will use the free agency period, which begin
July 1, to boost their defensive corps.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, O'Connell said he sees this summer as a jumping-off
point to bigger and better things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked (the players), `If we can fill some of these holes on
defense, do you think we have a chance to compete with the other
teams that are in it?' '' O'Connell said. ``They all said,
`Absolutely.' Not one of them said, `No way. We need this or need
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Ray Bourque, who was traded to Colorado in
March, and the very possible loss of veteran Don Sweeney, who said
he will test the waters of unrestricted free agency, defense is
Boston's big need. The European-laden draft, however, has more
forwards to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To draft a defenseman who's going to come in and play, you're
asking a lot,'' said O'Connell. ``We think we have a good set of
forwards and through free agency or trades _ hopefully free agency
_ we can fill some of those holes. There are some good players
available through free agency. There are some defensemen who can
help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have the possibility of picking at No. 27 in the
first round as well. New Jersey traded the pick to Colorado in its
deal for Claude Lemieux that sent Brian Rolston to the Avalanche.
When Rolston came to Boston in the Bourque deal, the Avalanche sent
that pick to the Bruins, who can exercise it this year or take
Colorado's first-round pick next year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the immediate future is far brighter than it
appeared in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have solid enough goaltending and forwards and we do
have some good players on defense,'' said O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   If goaltender Rob Tallas isn't taken in the expansion draft,
it's likely the Bruins will deal him in order to shore up the blue
line. Other players left exposed, such as Steve Heinze, could also
be used as a way to add defensive help.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the No. 7 pick stands to be a player someday,
just not right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting time for our staff,'' said O'Connell. ``They
work very hard to identify the top players and it's a chance to add
to your organizational depth. Hopefully, you make the right choices
and in two or three years, we benefit. I think it gets harder and
harder to find players in the draft. I don't know what the
percentages are but as a way to build, it's difficult right now.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some good news. All of those Bruins who had surgery _
which was pretty much everybody _ are progressing well. O'Connell
said management believes the 2000-2001 season will be a far cry
from the one just completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a trying year,'' said O'Connell. ``You look at it and
three years ago, people gave us no chance for four or five years
and I think we turned it around pretty good. We went from an old
team to a young team faster than most people expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, it was a good year, we learned a lot. The
second year, we learned more. The third year, we just expected it
and that's easy to do with a young team. People picked us to go
far. I think our young players realized this year that it doesn't
just happen. It will be a different team this year. It will be
interesting to see how these players respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
