<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, June 22. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-COLOMBIA (Washington) _ The Senate votes to provide
nearly $1 billion to Colombia to equip and train security forces to
combat drug traffickers, whose booming trade in a country where a
booming narcotics trade has become intertwined with a guerrilla
insurgency. The Senate has now set aside a total of almost $1.3
billion for assistance to Colombia over the next two years,
including $300 million in an earlier military bill. By Eric
Schmitt. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center stories:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PLANTATION (Natchitoches, La.) _ At the south edge of the
old plantation, eight simple cabins stood in a field of clover.
Generations of whitewash were peeling in ugly patches from the
mud-brick walls. All but one front porch had rotted away, and there
were gaping holes where doors and windows used to be. Obscured by
rows of live oaks, the cabins had been forgotten by many and
ignored by most. There was almost nothing left _ except the stories
of the slaves who once lived in them. Will re-enactments of slave
life at a former plantation, now a national park, help to heal
racial wounds _ or open them? By Ginger Thompson. (6500 words, with
an abridged version of about half that length.)
</P>
<P>
   (The report has moved in `a' category; an abridged version has
also moved.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT901-908.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-INSURANCE (Undated) _ After decades of paying higher
premiums for life insurance than white customers, nearly five
million black customers and their families nationwide are going to
be compensated in a settlement reached with one of the nation's
biggest insurers. The insurance company, American General, says it
is making restitution of $206 million, mainly to the black
customers and their heirs who, until as recently as April, paid as
much as 33 percent more than white customers for small policies
intended to cover burial expenses. By Joseph B. Treaster.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   GORE-OIL (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Worried that voters will blame the
Clinton administration _ and Vice President Al Gore _ for the
recent surge in oil prices, the Gore campaign has begun an effort
paint Gov. George W. Bush, a one-time oil company executive, as a
tool of the oil interests it says are relentlessly gouging
consumers. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   DEAF-READING (Undated) _ Deaf Americans have gained a place in
the national consciousness. American Sign Language interpreters
seem to be everywhere, from the State of the Union address to the
Miss America pageant. But some advocates for the deaf say that a
politicized devotion to the exclusive use of sign language by many
of the deaf has helped foster a little known and surprising
problem: The average 18-year-old deaf American reads at a
fourth-grade level. These advocates are seeking to lead a
revolution in deaf education through a 34-year-old method called
cued speech. By Lynette Holloway. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3 and 8, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-WATER (Washington) _ A spacecraft orbiting Mars has
sighted grooved surface features suggesting a relatively recent
water flow on the planet, a finding that could redirect efforts to
find evidence of past or present life, experts say. By Warren E.
Leary. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Seoul, South Korea) _ The euphoria that followed
the summit meeting between North and South Korea last week has
started to fade as their leaders face the reality of trying to
reunite two countries with a common ancestry and language but
drastically different ideologies and fortunes. By Calvin Sims.
(Scheduled to move by 8:45 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-GENOME (Undated) _ After months of fitful negotiation
that seemed to flame out in a final angry exchange in February, the
two sides racing to decode the human DNA have contrived a
last-minute truce. The first element of the suddenly resurrected
pact is likely to be a joint announcement of the effective
completion of the genome. By Nicholas Wade. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHILD-KILLERS (Miami) _ Why would a child kill? Because he
IS a child and doesn't consider the consequences of his actions,
says the mother of 13-year-old Nathaniel Brazill, accused of
shooting his teacher to death. The state of Florida has no middle
ground in such cases: A child like Nathaniel, accused of a felony,
is tried as an adult. By Rick Bragg. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WAR-CRIMES (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The chief prosecutor
of the International War Crimes Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia
says she will not withdraw the indictment against Slobodan
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, and she opposes any action by
Washington or other governments to let him escape justice. By
Carlotta Gall. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 800 words.
</P>
