<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH REITERATES HIS UNWAVERING SUPPORT FOR CAPITAL PUNISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ One day before a scheduled execution in Texas that has
come under intense scrutiny, Gov. George W. Bush said he understood
and sympathized with the strong emotions of people who opposed the
death penalty, calling it ``a subject that needs to be debated in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor also said that his support for the death
penalty was firm, and would remain so, even if he sensed it was
hurting him politically. And he said that if the Texas Board of
Pardons and Paroles did not vote on Thursday to halt the execution
of Gary Graham _ convicted of a 1981 murder largely on the
testimony of one witness _ there was nothing he could do as
governor to spare the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it's a high-profile case, and I know there is a
lot of emotion swirling around this case,'' Bush told reporters
Wednesday morning in Los Angeles, where he wrapped up a campaign
swing through Western states before returning to Texas in the
evening. ``The death penalty is not an easy subject for a lot of
folks.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, it was part of Texas law, and it was his sworn
duty as governor, ``to uphold the laws of the land,'' a phrase he
repeated again and again. ``If it costs me politically,'' Bush
said, ``it costs me politically.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little reason to believe that it will, or that it has,
and it is possible that the opposite is true. But Bush nonetheless
seemed to be selecting his words and controlling his expression
Wednesday with care.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was his usual buoyancy; in its place was a subdued manner
and an almost whispery voice that alternately suggested seriousness
and weariness with the constant questions about the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   As both the Republican presidential nominee and the governor of
a state that executes more inmates than any other, Bush has become
a lightning rod for protests against capital punishment and a focal
point in the intensifying national re-examination of whether people
sentenced to die have received fair trials.
</P>
<P>
   At several points over the last three days, Bush was met at
events, or disrupted during them, by demonstrators imploring him to
stop the execution of Graham.
</P>
<P>
   In response to reporters' questions at a news conference
Wednesday, Bush struck a more ruminative note than he often had
when discussing the death penalty publicly. He said he did not
think that news organizations were paying too much attention to
executions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty is a subject that needs to be debated in
America, and cases come along that spark the debate, and this is
one,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed respect for people's rights to make their
disapproval of the death penalty known, but said that he, too, had
strong convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also keep in mind the victims,'' Bush said. ``And the reason
I support the death penalty is I believe it saves lives. That's why
I support it. It so happens the people of my state support it as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, the governor can accept or reject
recommendations from the Board of Pardons and Paroles that a death
sentence be commuted or that the inmate be pardoned. But,
typically, if the board authorizes an execution, the governor only
has the authority to grant the inmate a one-time reprieve of 30
days. It usually winds up extending much longer than that, as
courts reconsider the case.
</P>
<P>
   Graham received such a reprieve from Gov. Ann Richards in 1993,
and Bush said Wednesday that his interpretation of the law was that
he could not grant Graham another one. He said he would only be in
a position to make a decision about Graham's fate if the board
voted to halt the execution. The board's vote is expected to come
midday Thursday; Graham is slated to be put to death by lethal
injection on Thursday night. He would be the 135th person executed
in Texas since Bush became governor five and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was talking daily with the state's lawyers about
Graham's case and was doing what he always did: assessing whether
there was convincing evidence of Graham's guilt and whether Graham
received full access to courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to treat this no differently than any other case
that has crossed my desk,'' Bush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
