u f BC-COKE-KOREA0622-COX     06-21 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-KOREA0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola's in North Korea
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co., a symbol for capitalism around the
world, entered Communist North Korea on Wednesday, just two days
after the U.S. government lifted most economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went in today through an import company in North Korea,''
Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin said Wednesday. ``It's a first
step toward business development there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said a truck carrying a limited amount of Coke entered
North Korea through China, where the soft-drink was produced.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, it's possible the company will build production
plants and tailor marketing strategies for North Korea, a Coca-Cola
spokesman in Seoul, South Korea, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to monitor the business and see what makes
sense,'' Baskin added.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola becomes one of the first U.S. companies to enter North
Korea following a historic summit last week between the leaders of
North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly shows Coke's aggressiveness and responsiveness
to changing conditions,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of
Beverage Digest. ``Coke CEO Doug Daft talks about growing the
company by being agile and quick. This is a very good example.''
Before becoming head of the company, Daft was in charge of its
Asian operations.
</P>
<P>
   Sicher predicted that Coca-Cola would gain ``modest'' volume and
profit growth in North Korea over the long-term.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly half a century, Coca-Cola and other U.S. companies
were prevented from doing business in North Korea, a nation of 22.5
million people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Coke products made it into North Korea through
independent sources in China.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, however, Coca-Cola has been selling beverages
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   It has 53 percent of the soft-drink market there, according to
Beverage Digest. That compared with 13 percent for Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's move into North Korea is its second major entry into
a Communist-led Asian country over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   The company sold its products in Vietnam less than 24 hours
after the U.S. government dropped its trade embargo in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which does business in about 200 nations, is still
prevented by the U.S. government from selling its beverages in
about a half-dozen nations, including Cuba and Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
