<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CZECH-GLASS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-21 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-GLASS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: WHEN IT COMES TO GLASS SCULPTURE, A CZECH COUPLE THINK
BIG 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER S. GREEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZELEZNY BROD, Czech Republic _ ``Alchemy,'' answered Stanislav
Libensky. The question was how Libensky and his wife, Jaroslava
Brychtova, arrive at the sublimely pure colors that define their
work as glass artists, and it seemed an almost plausible
explanation for the genius that has made them among the most
respected artists in their medium today.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing mysterious about the Libenskys' work. They have
spent nearly half a century refining the art and technique of
casting huge chunks of delicately colored glass. A rare and
harmonious collaboration between husband and wife underpins their
work, which is having a major retrospective at the Heller Gallery
on West 14th Street in New York City through June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really the towering figures in the 20th century in
the realm of glass sculpture,'' said Robert Kehlmann, an American
critic, himself a glass artist. ``Libensky-Brychtova are really
dealing with sculpture, and they are dealing with it not on a
tabletop scale, but at the scale which sculpture has come to be in
the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Their scale was always big. ``The River of Life,'' at the 1970
World Exhibition in Osaka, Japan, weighed 13 tons and measured 14.5
feet high and 72 feet long, all of it cast glass, in three towering
sections. Other mammoth pieces include ``Big Conus,'' a
12.5-foot-high tower for the 1967 Montreal Exposition, and the
hauntingly translucent ``Green Eye of the Pyramid,'' now at the
Corning Museum of Glass in New York State. On a recent visit to his
studio here, the diminutive Libensky and Brychtova, who is slightly
taller than her husband, were dwarfed by the massive, 6.5-foot-tall
``Angel'' of smoky gray glass.
</P>
<P>
   Scale is half of their alchemy. The other half is light.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an illuminating space within this material that
doesn't exist in any other medium,'' said Libensky as he took a
visitor through the basement studio in his hillside house in the
foothills of the Ore mountains, where glassmakers have worked since
the 14th century. ``That is why we are attracted by glass and why
we can't leave it, really, even though glass has many
disadvantages.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hands of masters like Tiffany, Daum, Lalique and Galle,
glass teetered on what Libensky's teacher, Josef Kaplicky,
described as ``the boundaries where the sphere of creative spirit
ends and the empire of monotonous craft begins.'' Like their
predecessors, the Libenskys push glass work from the decorative
arts to the fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were willing to explore the inherent qualities of the
glass itself,'' said Katya Kohoutova Garrow, a partner in the
Heller Gallery. ``They said, `If we do a bas-relief, that's
interesting, but not as interesting as if you look at it through
the flat surface where you see its plasticity, and the density and
thickness of the glass create the sculpture's volume and color.'''
</P>
<P>
   Libensky paints and sketches, and Brychtova makes clay
sculptures from his designs. Master craftsmen follow with plaster
molds that are filled with glass shards and ``fired'': heated for
two or three days and slowly cooled for as long as a month. Garrow
says it is Brychtova who teases the genius out of Libensky's
drawings, endlessly perfecting the surfaces and the shapes.
</P>
<P>
   They were both married when they met in Zelezny Brod, and their
artistic infatuation soon led to a romance that scandalized this
small North Bohemian town. So Libensky returned to Prague to teach
at the Academy of Decorative Arts, while Brychtova stayed to direct
the architectural glass studio at Zelezny Brod. Five years later
they married.
</P>
<P>
   The political turmoil after the 1948 Communist putsch, and the
show trials and purges of important pre-World War II artists
virtually wiped out abstract art. But it allowed the Libenskys a
professional freedom. The Communist-era construction boom demanded
massive sculptures to beautify the new palaces of the proletariat,
a boon for glass artists, because, Libensky said, ``the state
didn't see glass as art.''
</P>
<P>
   Bereft of quality fine arts to submit to the 1958 Brussels
World's Fair, the Communists turned to decorative arts, and the
Libenskys designed a wall of flagstone-size colored glass blocks
with reversed reliefs of wild animals, reminiscent of Stone Age
cave paintings. Their work, innovative art that did nothing to
glorify socialism, slid in to the exhibition as a piece of
architecture. ``Art went in through the back door,'' Brychtova
said.
</P>
<P>
   The gradual liberalization of the Prague Spring reform Communist
movement in the mid-1960s encouraged the Libenskys artistically and
politically. Their 1964 windows for the chapel in Prague Castle for
the Czech patron saint, St. Wenceslas, are a melding of plates of
softly colored glass.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Prague Spring, they began work in 1967 on a
massive installation for the Osaka World's Fair. Made of clear
glass cast in vast chunks and strung together on a steel frame,
``The River of Life'' was meant, said Libensky, to show ``the
system of life in this country'' from birth through youth to the
dancing feet of freedom and then, finally, the deep imprints of
army boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The River'' was installed in Osaka just two years after the
1968 Soviet-led invasion crushed the reforms. In a moment of
inspired puckishness, a sculpture of marching soldiers by a fellow
Czech, Vladimir Janousek, was positioned so that it appeared to be
marching from the nearby Soviet pavilion to the boot marks of ``The
River,'' as if it were a representation of the Russian and Germany
armies that had occupied his homeland for most of his life. ``The
Russian and Czech potentates recognized what this was about
straight off,'' said Libensky, and he was forced to sand off the
boot prints from ``The River.''
</P>
<P>
   Osaka secured the Libenskys' international reputation, but it
also guaranteed that the Communists would never again allow them
such exposure. On their return to Czechoslovakia, the Libenskys
were interrogated, expelled from the party and for some years
forbidden to travel abroad, although he stayed at the academy,
training nearly all of today's prominent Czech glass artists. She
remained in Zelezny Brod. They won commissions for Czechoslovak
embassies and even for the Federal Czechoslovak Parliament, but
many more for such places as a Prague subway station, hotel lobbies
and government offices. The state kept most of the income from
whatever pieces they did sell abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Some Czech glass artists were able to study in Libensky's studio
and cast their work at Brychtova's atelier; today a generation of
them owe their careers to the couple. The Libenskys' influence has
been particularly strong in the United States, where they first
visited in the mid-1980s to teach at the prestigious Pilchuk Glass
School near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Now 79 and still recovering from lung cancer, Libensky is
reluctant to talk about the influences on his current work, or why
he has abandoned the bright pastel colors for somber grays and
browns. But Brychtova, who is 75, says: ``The last four years the
theme is inner space, and all the things he created while he was
ill and he was shown the X-rays of his own body. All this you see
here reminds him of his own body.'' She pointed to the stacks of
gray-and-black canvases spread around the studio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
