<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA TO CONFIRM LIQUID WATER EXISTS ON MARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been the greatest quest of planetary scientists for
decades, and Thursday the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration will announce that at long last it has been found:
water on the surface of another world. The clearest evidence ever
of liquid water _ the most basic prerequisite for life _ has now
been seen on the surface of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement will be made at a press conference at NASA
headquarters at 11 a.m. and will include new pictures taken by the
Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft that are said to show clear signs
of the surface water. A detailed report will be published next week
in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, while scientists had seen abundant signs that water
had flowed across the red planet in the very distant past and
remains frozen in the polar ice caps and occasional frosts, there
had never been direct evidence of liquid water.
</P>
<P>
   If liquid water exists on Mars, scientists say, that greatly
increases the odds that some form of life _ presumably in the form
of primitive microorganisms _ exists there now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever there's water on Earth, there's life,'' said one
planetary scientist who is familiar with the new results. ``No one
knows if there was life on Mars, but certainly, if liquid water
existed in even a few places for an extended period, that obviously
improves the chances of finding life.''
</P>
<P>
   That scientist, who insisted on anonymity because the findings
will not officially be made public until Thursday, added that the
new report is ``significant'' and ``a very nice analysis'' by
respected scientists. ``It's an important paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, research results published in a scientific journal may
not be discussed publicly until the date of publication, but word
of the exciting new findings leaked out this week, initially
through an Internet site called NASA Watch (www.nasawatch.com), and
the story was quickly picked up by other media. That forced NASA
and Science to hastily reschedule the press conference and release,
initially planned for June 29.
</P>
<P>
   But most reports that have circulated so far have been wrong
about many details, NASA officials said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the new findings noted that several
reports have erroneously said that the new findings were based on
pictures of Valles Marineris, the 3,000 mile-long, mile-deep canyon
system that is the largest known on any planet. Also incorrect were
reports that the new study was based on pictures of a crater taken
two years ago by Mars Global Surveyor, these sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Mars billions of years ago is thought to have been warmer and
wetter, similar to the early Earth, but now is colder than
Antarctica and its air is thinner than at the summit of Everest. As
a result, except under rare conditions, water can exist only as
solid or gas. It normally turns straight from ice to vapor without
going through a liquid phase. So the new findings suggest that
there must be a source, such as a spring, that brings water to the
surface continuously.
</P>
<P>
   Most researchers exploring the history of water on Mars have
focused on the first billion years of the planet's 4.6 billion-year
history, a time when the planet is believed to have been warmer.
Last year, a team led by James Head of Brown University found
strong evidence that Mars long ago had an ocean that spanned vast
regions of the planet's northern hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Another report showed that a vast underground reservoir of water
must have persisted through most of Mars' history, based on
indirect evidence gathered from meteorites that were blasted to
Earth from the Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   But, since the new findings show that water is present now, or
was there very recently, ``that's obviously very important,'' one
scientist said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who have long believed that there is water on Mars
found vindication in the new NASA findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's old hat to us,'' said Gilbert Levin, president of
Biospherics Inc., who was the chief scientist for one of the three
experiments sent to Mars in 1976 specifically to look for signs of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Levin has maintained ever since that mission that his experiment
showed clear evidence that living microbes exist on Mars today.
Levin's claims have never been taken seriously by other scientists,
though the final report of the Viking mission concluded that the
results of his experiment did indeed meet the conditions _ agreed
to in advance by all the scientists _ for a positive detection of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Levin has proposed a simple, low-cost experiment that could be
carried on a future Mars mission that he says would settle the
question, once and for all, of whether the Viking results really
did produce evidence of life. But so far NASA has not agreed to
include the experiment on any upcoming mission.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Donahue, professor emeritus of planetary science at the
University of Michigan also was delighted, but not surprised by
NASA's new findings. He published indirect results five years ago
showing that the ratio of certain gases trapped inside meteorites
that came from Mars show that vast amounts of liquid water must
have persisted there throughout most, if not all, of the planet's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly nice to see some direct physical evidence to
support the inferences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighborhood of liquid water,'' Donahue said, ``is the
neighborhood in which you want to look for life today.'' And, he
added, ``I don't think it would surprise anyone, either, to find
that there is indeed evidence for life'' on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ward, a paleontologist at the University of Washington who
has written about the possibilities of life on other worlds, said
Wednesday that ``the probability of microbial life'' on Mars ``has
just skyrocketed.''
</P>
<P>
   The finding of water, he said, provides ``a far stronger case
for NASA to get up there. . . . It gives you a better shot of
finding not only living organisms, but also fossils.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
