<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-WWII-VETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP HONORS COME BELATEDLY FOR ASIAN-AMERICAN SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Colo., Calif. Ariz.)   (Eds.: Term in last graf may be offensive to some readers.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some of the old soldiers were unsteady as they
stood at attention Wednesday while a bugler blew taps into a fresh
breeze in a wreath-laying ceremony at the Tomb of the Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of them were in their mid-70s, after all. Some had
come thousands of miles for this dress-blue ceremony under a gray
sky, so it was no surprise that their shoulders sagged under the
weight of years and, perhaps, of memories.
</P>
<P>
   There were seven old soldiers in Arlington National Cemetery.
One was well known, Sen. Daniel Inouye of Hawaii, the others much
less so. All have just been awarded the Medal of Honor, the
country's highest military award, for what they did more than a
half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The seven are among 22 Asian-Americans, most of Japanese
descent, who fought heroically during World War II as their
relatives endured prejudice, even internment, back home. Most of
the 22 belonged to the 442nd Regimental Combat Team, which
sustained heavy casualties in Italy, France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rose above any sense of personal injustice to sacrifice
all that they held dear in order to keep our country strong,'' Army
Secretary Louis Caldera said before the Arlington ceremony in their
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Heroism? Not really, said one of the seven, Barney Hajiro, now
83.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot myself in combat,'' Hajiro said. ``I couldn't run
backward. I had to run forward. That's the job of a soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Hajiro of the 442nd killed several German soldiers and helped
capture more than a dozen others in eastern France in October 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The 442nd fought in many campaigns and garnered many medals. But
as the years went by and prejudice faded, people in and out of the
military asked why only two Asian-Americans were awarded the Medal
of Honor for heroism in World War II. (No black soldiers received
the Medal of Honor.)
</P>
<P>
   The Army reviewed more than 100 instances in which the
Distinguished Service Cross, the second-highest medal, was given to
Asian-Americans. Last month, the Army concluded that in 21
instances the Medal of Honor should have been awarded instead.
(More recently, a member of the 442nd who had won another high
honor, the Silver Star, was found worthy of a Medal of Honor.)
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 22 were killed in action, and others have succumbed
to time. Many relatives of the dead were at the tomb Wednesday,
some leaning on canes or on the strong arms of honor guard soldiers
young enough to be their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   George T. Sakato, another of the seven, was a private with the
442nd. According to his medal citation, he killed five German
soldiers and captured four on Oct. 29, 1944, before his unit was
pinned down. Then he led ``a one-man rush,'' killing as many as a
dozen more enemy soldiers and capturing several others.
</P>
<P>
   Not particularly heroic, said Sakato, 79. ``Nowadays, they call
what I did `road rage,''' he said. His killing rampage for his
country was inspired by the death of a buddy, Saburo Tanamachi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died in my arms,'' Sakato said with a distant look in his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   As a 20-year-old first lieutenant in the 442nd, Daniel Inouye
led an attack in Italy in April 1945 in which two dozen enemy
soldiers were killed. His right arm was shattered and had to be
amputated.
</P>
<P>
   The seven old soldiers, their relatives and survivors of the
dead Medal of Honor recipients went to the White House Wednesday
afternoon to meet President Clinton and get their medals. On
Thursday, the 22 will be honored at a Pentagon ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Sakato lives in Denver and is a retired postal worker. He
recalled how, early in the war, his family was given three days to
leave their home in Southern California or face internment. They
went to Arizona to live with relatives. After he came home from the
war, Sakato felt the stares whenever he entered a restaurant,
``from people thinking, `What are you doing here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hajiro is from Waipahu, Hawaii, and went back to the islands to
work on a sugar plantation after leaving the Army. Memories of
Pearl Harbor were still vivid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after the war,'' he said, ``they called me a `Jap,' you
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
