<HEADLINE>
UPSIDE DOWN CAKE RECIPE COMES TO THE SURFACE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the Pineapple Upside Down Cake recipe using Bisquick that
was requested a while back. The original request inadvertently ran
with the incorrect name. U. Van Dam of North Hills is the reader
who was actually looking for the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen readers sent along the same recipe that came
from various Betty Crocker Bisquick cookbooks over the years
(dating back to 1964) and the Betty Crocker Web site. A couple of
the recipes included 1/2 cup shredded coconut with the Bisquick
batter, so add or not as desired. One used crushed pineapple
instead of slices and 1/2 teaspoon almond extract in addition to
the vanilla in the batter. A few of the recipes baked the cake five
minutes less while a couple baked it five minutes longer. Use the
baking time as a guideline and watch the cake carefully near the
end of the time specified.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to all who shared the recipe. No doubt Van Dam will be
pleased to whip up this easy creation once again. &QL; 
PINEAPPLE UPSIDE DOWN CAKE &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter OR margarine &QL; 
1/4 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
1 (8 1/4-ounce) can sliced pineapple, drained &QL; 
Maraschino cherries, drained &QL; 
Walnut OR pecan halves (optional) &QL; 
1 1/2 cups buttermilk baking mix (such as Bisquick) &QL; 
1/2 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
1 egg &QL; 
1/2 cup milk OR water &QL; 
2 tablespoons shortening &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Place butter in an 8x8x2-inch square pan or 9x1 1/2-inch round
layer pan in preheated 350-degree oven until butter melts. Sprinkle
brown sugar over butter.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange drained pineapple slices on brown sugar mixture.
Decorate with maraschino cherries and walnut or pecan halves, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, blend remaining ingredients in a large mixing bowl on
low speed 30 seconds, scraping bowl frequently. Beat 4 minutes on
medium speed, scraping bowl occasionally. Pour batter evenly over
pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 35 to 40 minutes or until wooden pick inserted in center
comes out clean. Immediately invert pan onto a heatproof serving
plate; leave pan over cake a few minutes before removing.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm, plain or with sweetened whipped cream. Makes 8 to 9
servings. &QL; 
Hawaiian-style pie &QL; 
A colleague was recently looking for something to take to a
Hawaiian-inspired potluck, and this replica recipe, a copycat of a
dessert served at Chin Chin restaurant in Studio City, came to
mind. It's a cinch to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   To speed preparation, use prepared pie crust dough, readily
available packaged in the refrigerated deli section of
supermarkets. Of course, if you have the time or inclination, your
favorite homemade crust would be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The filling is a mixture of brown sugar, eggs, butter, milk,
vanilla, chocolate pieces, coconut and macadamia nuts. For best
results, be sure to mix the ingredients by hand, with a fork or
wooden spoon rather than with an electric mixer. Otherwise, you'll
end up with a completely different result, which I found
unacceptable. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE MACADAMIA &QL; 
NUT PIE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon flour &QL; 
2 eggs &QL; 
2 tablespoons milk &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
1/3 cup butter, melted &QL; 
1 cup semisweet chocolate pieces &QL; 
1 cup shredded coconut &QL; 
1 1/2 cups dry-roasted macadamia nuts (one 7-ounce jar) &QL; 
1 (9-inch) unbaked pie crust
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine brown sugar and flour. With a
fork or wooden spoon (not an electric mixer), beat in eggs, milk,
vanilla and melted butter. Stir in chocolate pieces, coconut and
macadamia nuts. Turn into pastry-lined pie pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 30 to 35 minutes, until barely
set. Cool. Refrigerate (so pie sets up). Serve slices topped with
whipped cream, if desired. Makes 1 pie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Can you help &QL; 
If you have recipes that can help these readers, please send them
along to us at the address below to share in a future column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am looking for a really good (and relatively easy) salad
recipe to serve at a summer shower _ one that will rate raves. Any
ideas that you've made, served and had success with to share?
</P>
<P>
   _ A reader &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Oaks &QL; 
Cook's Corner welcomes recipe requests from readers. While we
cannot reply to them individually, we will answer those of general
interest in this column. Also, if you can help another reader with
a recipe request, write to Cook's Corner, Daily News Food
Department, P.O. Box 4200, Woodland Hills, Calif. 91365-4200.
Please be sure recipes specify exact package sizes, can and pan
sizes and baking times and temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes printed are from the source indicated and have not been
tested by the Daily News Food Department unless noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
