<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-CITY (Huntsville, Texas) _ With Gary Graham's execution
scheduled Thursday, the home of Texas' ``death house'' is taking
precautions as never before. State prison officials expect
thousands to come to the Walls Unit in downtown Huntsville to
protest, and some fear riots and violence. By AMY DORSETT. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTION (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Attorney General John
Cornyn says the execution of convicted killer Gary Graham should be
carried out. Meanwhile, a key lawmaker calls for a ``full public
hearing'' on the execution, scheduled Thursday in Huntsville. By
KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTION-POLL (Undated) _ Texans' support of the death
penalty has waned only slightly with an overwhelming majority still
supporting executions. More than 50 percent of those surveyed
believe innocent people have already been executed, but they still
support death sentences. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-TRIAL (Waco, Texas) _ Criminal defense lawyer Dick DeGuerin
tells a jury that he believes federal agents fired through a
windowless, steel door at targets they could not see when they
raided the Branch Davidian compound on the morning of Feb. 28,
1993. DeGuerin was called in the wrongful death lawsuit filed
against the government in an effort to show that agents fired
``indiscriminately,'' endangering the lives of unarmed women and
children who were followers of Davidian leader David Koresh. By
DICK J. REAVIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MARS-WATER (Houston) _ NASA plans on Thursday to present
photographic evidence that water may have existed on Mars. The
images were gathered by the Mars Global Surveyor, a satellite in
orbit around Mars since 1997. The evidence shows depressions in the
Martian surface that could have been made by water oozing out of
the ground or flowing from a canyon wall. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PRICES (Washington) _ The Clinton administration has
launched a full-scale investigation of the oil industry to
determine why gasoline prices spiked so high in the voter-rich
Midwest. Vice President Al Gore has called on regulators to
investigate whether the oil companies have colluded to raise
prices, while lawmakers are clamoring for answers. But while the
politicians hunt for a villain responsible for pushing pump prices
past $2 per gallon in some Midwestern cities, the federal
government's own energy analysts are providing a far-less-sinister
explanation. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SECRETS (Washington) _ Facing tough attacks from
senators, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson says the FBI has found
no evidence of espionage in the case of two computer hard drives
that were mysteriously lost then found at the at Los Alamos weapons
laboratory. He also says the FBI has discovered no evidence that
the hard drives ever left the lab's top secret X-Division, where
some of the nation's most sensitive nuclear weapons research is
conducted. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDAL-OF-HONOR (Washington) _ President Clinton awards 22
Asian-American veterans of World War II _ including Sen. Daniel
Inouye, D-Hawaii _ the Medal of Honor for combat heroism. Five
honorees are cited for valor during the Army's epic rescue of the
``Lost Battalion,'' a former Texas National Guard unit. Fifteen of
the awards are given posthumously. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ In a dramatic shift, House
Republican leaders have signaled a willingness to ease economic
sanctions against Cuba. Nonetheless, opposition to a rapprochement
with the communist island-nation lingers. Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas,
is among those opposed to a Senate-approved measure that would
relax restrictions on food and medicine shipments to Cuba. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CHECKS (Washington) _ Instant background checks for gun
purchases often cause ``needless delay to law-abiding citizens''
because the FBI's system breaks down, Senate Judiciary Chairman
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, charges at a hearing that his panel holds on
the problem. An FBI official admits that the system needs
improvement. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   LATINO-AID (Washington) _ A national self-help organization
called Latino Initiatives for the Next Century announces that it
will provide 500 college scholarships in California, Texas, New
York and Illinois, while helping other Hispanics start their own
businesses. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
