<HEADER>
A0998 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-530&AMP;ADD     06-21 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-NKOREA-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT GLOW FADES AS THE KOREAS FACE HARD TASKS OF REUNIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The euphoria that followed the summit
meeting between North and South Korea last week has started to fade
as their leaders face the reality of trying to reunite two
countries with a common ancestry and language but drastically
different ideologies and fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Although foreign diplomats and political experts say the
prospects of peace and reconciliation on the Korean peninsula
remain promising, antagonistic statements in both countries in
recent days underscore the inevitable difficulties that North and
South face in trying to overcome five decades as ideological
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the official North Korean news agency released
numerous provocative declarations, some old and some new, by the
country's leader, Kim Jong Il, admonishing North Koreans not to
stray from the principles of the communist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must create a self-sufficient and strong nation and not
yield to economic reforms and market openings that would certainly
lead to our destruction,'' Kim Jong Il said in a rebroadcast of a
1999 speech on Tuesday, a day after the United States had removed
sanctions on nonmilitary trade with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In a broadcast Wednesday, the North Korean Foreign Ministry
demanded that all sanctions be lifted and that the United States
stop being ``hostile.'' On Sunday, North Korea said the United
States, which has 37,000 troops in South Korea, had increased the
likelihood of war on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The diatribe, which political experts said was intended to
appease North Korean hard-liners and project an image of strength,
was a sharp contrast to the conciliatory gestures that Kim Jong Il
and President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea had traded at their talks
in Pyongyang. The two leaders signed an accord that called for
closer ties, economic cooperation and eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   But the North's shift in tone has been no more caustic than a
barrage of criticism that South Korea's main political opposition
has levied against the communist country and the agreement forged
there.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging the significance of the summit meeting,
leaders of the opposition Grand National Party said that North
Korea remained a dangerous state and that the talks had failed to
address important issues like the North's nuclear and missile
programs and the costs of reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim Jong Il is very good at putting on a show,'' said Chung
Hyung-keun, a legislator from the opposition Grand National Party.
``But he is an old-line communist leader who believes that he can
make the South his own at any time, and that is very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign and Korean experts said the verbal jabs had provided a
much-needed reality check to the mass euphoria after the summit
sessions and pointed to some of the difficulties ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that both sides are working hard to achieve peace, but
we can't expect them to abandon their political systems and
party-line rhetoric overnight,'' said a European ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects reunification of the peninsula soon. The stark
economic differences between the two Koreas and the astronomical
costs of merging them make reunification a distant prospect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fueled by foreign investment, open markets, advanced technology
and entrepreneurial spirit, South Korea has become one of the
world's most economically successful democracies.
</P>
<P>
   But North Korea, by all accounts, is in dire straits.
Inefficient agriculture and devastating floods have created severe
food shortages. Most of its factories are dormant. In most regions,
there are virtually no paved roads, telephones or public
transportation. Economists have estimated that it could cost
hundreds of billions of dollars to integrate the two.
</P>
<P>
   How fast the two countries unify would largely depend on what
political changes occur in North Korea. Because North Korea remains
closed to the outside world, little is known about what effects the
summit meeting has had there. South Korean envoys who attended the
sessions said it was widely reported in newspapers and on radio and
television in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   But political experts said because Kim Jong Il's government so
tightly controlled what North Koreans see and think and the country
has been isolated so long, the meetings were highly unlikely to
have significant political effects soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim Jong Il's power has never been stronger, despite his
people's dismal economic situation,'' said Jo Dong-ho, an economist
for the Korean Development Institute, a private think tank in
Seoul. ``For change to take place, North Koreans have to become
aware that their difficulties arise from bad governance. But most
of them still believe that Kim Jong Il is great and all people on
this planet worship him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting may have had some repercussions in the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support the notion that Kim Dae-jung's visit created a lot
of excitement in North Korea and that the recent broadcasts
reasserting revolutionary principles were designed to calm the
excitement there that reunification was near,'' said Yoon
Young-joong, who monitors North Korean broadcasts for the
Unification Ministry in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's propagandistic broadcasts are also being put
forward by South Korea's political opposition as evidence that Kim
Jong Il has not changed his ways. The opposition has criticized Kim
Dae-jung for not using the meetings to focus attention on the
hundreds of thousands of North Koreans who international aid
workers estimate have died because of famine and floods and the
government's failure to adopt agricultural and market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians also accused South Korean media of
presenting an unrealistically positive view of the summit meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just recently,'' Chung said, ``the South Korean media were
filled with images of starving North Korean children eating worms
from the ground just outside Pyongyang and elsewhere around the
country. But now the media have stopped showing these atrocities,
and the only thing they show are pretty images of Pyongyang.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
