<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-WATER-ART-NY     06-21 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-WATER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORBITER SPOTS SIGNS OF A RECENT FLOW OF WATER ON MARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT14 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A spacecraft orbiting Mars has sighted grooved
surface features suggesting a relatively recent water flow on the
planet, a finding that could redirect efforts to find evidence of
past or present life, experts said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Mars Global Surveyor, which has been conducting
photographic surveys of the planet for more than two years, has
spotted evidence of liquid water at, or near, the surface that
could have flowed a few hundred or a thousand years ago, a billion
years later than previous estimates, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration scheduled a
news conference for Thursday to discuss the findings after a day of
speculation about the discovery in the news media. A paper
describing the observations is to be published next week in the
journal Science, but the journal's editors decided to release the
information on Thursday because of the interest in the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Neither NASA nor the authors of the report, including Dr.
Michael C. Malin and Dr. Ken Edgett of Malin Space Science Systems
of San Diego, would disclose details of the study. But people
familiar with the report said high resolution pictures from Global
Surveyor clearly show channels and grooves on the steep, inside
walls of craters that indicate the downward flow of liquid water.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs appear to be evidence of water in the upper
crust of Mars that has seeped through and run down the channels,
said two experts familiar with the report who spoke on the
condition that they not be named. Contrary to speculation about the
findings, there is no clear evidence of standing pools of water or
gushing springs on Mars, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current climate of Mars would cause surface water to
instantly freeze and vaporize into the atmosphere,'' one expert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Water is crucial to plans for exploring Mars with robot
spacecraft to find evidence of life, and for possible visits by
humans in the future. The United States has ambitious Mars
exploration plans that focus on finding water. Those plans are
being revised after the failure of two spacecrafts last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward J. Weiler, NASA's chief scientist, said future
orbiting and surface craft sent by the United States would search
for water and the life it can sustain. ``To find life on Mars, you
have to follow the water,'' Weiler has said. ``Without water, there
was no life as we know it in the past, and there is no life now.
It's all about the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Water on Mars would also make human visits more likely and more
economical, experts said, because astronauts could drink it, and it
could be broken down into oxygen to breathe and hydrogen to fuel
rockets and electricity-producing generators.
</P>
<P>
   Water has previously been detected on Mars in the form of ice
trapped at the poles, but until now no evidence of it had been seen
elsewhere. Because of the planet's extreme temperatures, with
average surface temperatures of minus 60 degrees Fahrenheit, and an
atmospheric pressure less than 1 percent that of Earth's, liquid
water would not exist long on the surface before evaporating into
the air and drifting off into space.
</P>
<P>
   But there is ample evidence of past water on the planet,
including channels and canyons formed by flowing rivers millions of
years ago and indications of upswelling ground waters. And last
year, scientists from Brown University said they found evidence in
Global Surveyor pictures, which are more than 20 times more
detailed than any previous photographs, of a giant ocean that once
existed in the northern lowlands that left behind beach and
shoreline features.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
