<SLUG> BC-CHEFS-DINING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CHEFS EAT OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(ART AVAILABLE) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no secret that chefs and those in the food business around
town _ like all of us _ tire of their own cooking and need a break.
Even pressed for time, we'll often turn to little informal
neighborhood establishments to pick up a bite to eat.
</P>
<P>
   We asked some Los Angeles food professionals where they grab
takeout sustenance _ and what menu items in particular they favor.
</P>
<P>
   Once or twice a week Swiss-born Ueli Huegli, chef/owner of the
Matterhorn Chef, Valley Glen travels up the street to El Patron in
Van Nuys to pick up the tortilla soup. ``It's excellent as it is
nice and light _ not heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, he also picks up the seafood platter with marinated
octopus, shrimp, oysters and clams along with the restaurant's
terrific salsas, guacamole and chips.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally for lunch, he even grabs the imperial platter _ a
combination of teriyaki, tempura, sukiyaki and other items _ at the
Mikado in North Hollywood for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   A chef is very easy to please, he said. ``Give me a piece of
bread and some good quality cheese and I'm happy. I like plain food
and home cooking.'' High on his list of preferred cheeses is
cambozola _ a delicious combination of camembert and gorgonzola _
that he buys at Trader Joe's and eats with french bread.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Berk, co-editor of the Zagat Los Angeles/Southern
California restaurant and Marketplace surveys and co-owner of the
Seasonal Table cooking school, says she doesn't eat chain fast food
but will indulge in quick takeout food from time to time. When she
does, she likes something delicious and nurturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a good fix. If I'm going to go off my usual
healthy eating routine, then I want to pull out all stops and get
something that is satisfying and worth the calories, fat and
carbos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pizza is really good at Frankie &AMP; Johnnie's on San Vicente
in Brentwood _ and I can go there late at night and get takeout.''
She opts for a vegetarian pizza with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Another of her favorite takeout establishments when she's in a
hurry is California Chicken Cafe in Santa Monica (other locations
in Encino, West Los Angeles and Los Angeles) which has good wrap
sandwiches. She always orders them with mustard instead of
mayonniase including the Avocado Turkey Wrap, which is high on her
perferred list. Another good bet is Reddi-Chick in the Brentwood
Country Mart. ``I pick up whole rotisserie chickens there, but they
also have ribs, barbecued beef and baked potatoes.'' And in the
Valley, she raves about the rolled sandwich creations (``I get the
falafel stuffed sandwich when I'm feeling decadent'') at the
Tarzana Armenian Grocery. It's filled with pickled peppers.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to takeout for parties, Berk picks up Greek food
like moussaka, grape leaves, Greek salad and other traditional
items from Delphi in Westwood. When she's in the mood for Middle
Eastern fare on her entertaining menus, she purchases fattoush
(bread salad), tabbouleh and babaganoush from Marouch in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Berk is frustratated that Los Angeles has never been able to
support the kind of quality takout that is available in places like
New York (which has Zabar's, for instance) and San Francisco. ``I
think it is because we are a car culture _ not a walking culture _
and people are into one-stop shopping at supermarkets for
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Samson, executive chef, Posto in Sherman Oaks, likes to
dine in or takeout from Thai Original BBQ Restaurant in Studio City
on his days off. Although he grew up in Tarzana eating Northern
Italian food (his mother is from Bologna), he now enjoys spicy
food. He opts for some of the cold spicy appetizers such as spicy
grilled shrimp with red onions and cucumbers, or ground chicken
cooked and served as a salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often get a craving for spicy food and find the flavors
invigorating.'' He also orders a half grilled or barbecued chicken
which has a sauce with lots of honey and nice barbecue flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Samson is also an In-N-Out Burger fan. ``It's as L.A. as (it)
can be.'' His must-have favorite there is a double-double
cheeseburger with grilled onions and no sauce.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he routinely stops by Mel's Drive-In in Sherman Oaks
for breakfast and scarfs down whole grain pancakes, fruit salad,
fresh squeezed orange juice and coffee before heading a few doors
down to the kitchen at Posto.
</P>
<P>
   ``No city I have ever lived in _ including New York _ does fast
food as well as L.A. _ particularly the burgers at In-N-Out and
Mexican food.'' He loves tortas from little Mexican places.
</P>
<P>
   When Toluca Lake resident, Rodolfo Costella, proprietor of Ca'
del Sole in Universal City, wants to pick up a quick bite, he heads
to Poquito Mas on Cahuenga Boulevard in Studio City (other
locations in Burbank, North Hollywood, West Hollywood) for soft
beef and chicken tacos. He tops them with spicy green jalapeno
sauce from the salsa bar (offering numerous selections from mild to
hot).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then I have a craving for them. It gives me a
break from Italian food _ and they're fast and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he goes to Bob's Big Boy in Toluca Lake for a
cheeseburger and french fries which he dips in mayonnaise. ``I
picked up the mayonnaise habit when I was living in Holland,'' said
the native of Venice, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Naylor, executive chef at Granita in Malibu, makes a
trip once of twice a week to Pane Dolce on Montana Avenue in Santa
Monica for the fresh buffalo mozzarella, fresh tomato and fresh
basil sandwich on sourdough bread with garlic basil mayonnaise and
fresh lemonade. The neighborhood place makes all kinds of great
sandwiches to order. ``I like it because the place uses high
quality, fresh ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   Naylor said she never gets bored or tires of eating at the
restaurant because the creations are constantly changing and she is
contantly eating new things.
</P>
<P>
   She also frequents Il Sogno Dolce on Montana Ave. most mornings
to pick up one of their great giant blueberry scones. They also
have good antipasto salads and other items.
</P>
<P>
   When she is cooking barbecue items for July 4 dining at the
restaurant and for catered parties, she picks up a variety of fresh
chiles at a little Mexican place _ Gallegos Mexican Deli on
Broadway in Santa Monica. As a treat for her restaurant co-works,
she also picks up plenty of chicken chile verde tamales.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Scrimgeour, executive chef, Saddle Peak Lodge, Calabasas,
favors Pomodoro restaurant in Westwood and Nagao in Santa Monica.
He opts for picking up spaghetti with meatballs at Pomodoro (``the
restaurant has a really mean meatball sauce''), antipasto, salad or
penne pasta with vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the price Nagao (a neighborhood sushi bar) has the best
sushi in Los Angeles,'' said the Paris-trained chef who grew up
eating an eclectic and cosmopolitan mix of foods. ``I love eating
all kinds of different foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Peel, chef-owner of Campanile restaurant in Los Angeles,
frequents Zankou Chicken on Sunset Boulevard in Hollywood (other
locations in Van Nuys, Glendale and Pasadena) where he picks up a
whole chicken, grape leaves, hummus, tabbouleh, moutabal and plenty
of extra garlic sauce. His three children _ ranging in age from 6
to 17 _ love it. They also enjoy the plain cheese (he likes
pepperoni) pizza from Village Pizzeria in Larchmont village. Other
times he opts to have pizza and pastas delivered from Angeli Caffe
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Saverio Posarelli, chef/owner, Padri in Agoura Hills,
loves Italian food, he doesn't want to eat it when he has a day
off. Instead, the Westlake Village resident goes for barbecue at
Adobe Cantina in Agoura Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the tritip sandwich with extra hot and spicy barbecue
sauce (referred to as turbo) along with coleslaw and barbecue
beans. They also have good pork ribs and Mexican food.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's in the Encino area, he picks up curried chicken, pad
thai noodles, fried rice and thai ice tea at Thai 'N I in Encino.
</P>
<P>
   Italia Deli on Thousand Oaks Boulevard in Agoura Hills has a
terrific meatball sandwich. The rolls and meatballs are soft _ and
the sandwich is filled with mozzarella, parmigianas and marinara
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to eat a variety of food,'' said Posarelli, adding that
``when someone else is cooking, it's always better. It's fun to
take out food.'' Posarelli believes it's important for chefs to
keep their eyes open and have different food experiences _ and keep
in touch with what's going on foodwise.
</P>
<P>
   When time is short, Jackie Ravel Knezevich, owner, BakeAway, Los
Angeles, has Baja Fresh in Studio City whip up a custom low-fat
burrito for her two to three times a week to take home for dinner.
It's a flour tortilla filled with black beans, grilled chicken,
shredded lettuce and pico de gallo. She puts a little green
tomatillo salsa on top and eats it with knife and fork. ``That's my
meal _ it's about 600 calories total. I love the flavor _ and it is
healthy and delicious. I watch my calories whenever I go
anywhere.'' And even when she picks up a Chinese Chicken Salad at
Chin Chin in Studio City, she requests low-fat dressing.
</P>
<P>
   When Phyllis Vaccarelli, owner Let's Get Cooking, Westlake
Village, craves ribs, she picks them up at Wood Ranch BBQ &AMP; Grill
in Agoura Hills. When she's pressed for time, she might opt for the
Chinois Chicken Salad at Wolfgang Puck's takeout counter in
Gelson's Westlake Village store, poached salmon with mustard sauce
from the market's fresh deli or a cooked duck at Bristol Farms in
Westlake Village.
</P>
<P>
   So when time is at a premium and there's no time to cook, get a
taste of what the chefs and foodies around town enjoy. There are
plenty of options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
