<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1003 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-HNS &LR;      06-21 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Colored charts and graphs in hand, Vice
President Al Gore Wednesday compared his retirement savings plan
with Republican presidential rival George W. Bush's, telling Iowans
that his plan offers them twice as much retirement income as the
Texas governor's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the choice in this election,'' Gore told carpenters
union members and other supporters in Des Moines. ``Are you for
working people or not? That's the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his plan, which would provide government matching
funds to help those earning under $100,000 a year to build a nest
egg in addition to Social Security, would generate more than
$28,000 a year for an average retiree _ $15,877 from Social
Security and $12,345 from their own retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan, he said, would leave average workers retiring in
2037 with $12,663, less than the current guaranteed benefit from
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a study by the Center for Budget and Policy Priorities,
Gore said Bush's plan, which would allow workers to divert a
percentage of their Social Security payroll taxes into private
retirement investment accounts, would take $1 trillion from the
Social Security trust fund and bankrupt the system by 2023, rather
than the current estimate of 2037.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Gore said his plan would extend Social Security
through at least 2054 by shoring up the system with interest saved
from debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Los Angeles Wednesday, anticipated Gore's
attack and said he welcomes the debate on a crucial national issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the year 2037, there's not going to be enough payers to
support the retired baby boomers, and if nothing is done, no reform
is in place, we're either going to have to raise taxes or reduce
benefits,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his plan would allow younger workers to manage some of
their money in the private sector and take advantage of compound
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really important to make sure the system survives,''
Bush said. ``I'm strong on my position because it's the right way
to go in my judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to portray the Republican presidential candidate as
dedicated to helping only the wealthy and himself as the candidate
of working people, Gore also attacked pending legislation to repeal
the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Republican-backed plan, passed by the House earlier
this month with the help of some Democrats and awaiting action in
the Senate, would benefit only the wealthiest taxpayers, since
smaller estates are exempt from the taxes anyway. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A business or farm left to heirs by a couple is exempt from
estate tax if its value is under $2.6 million. Gore would raise
that exemption to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That would eliminate estate taxes for more than 90 percent of
family farmers and more than 70 percent of small business owners,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some on Capitol Hill believe we should completely repeal the
estate tax and give a massive tax break to the wealthiest
Americans. Under their plan, fully half the benefits go to less
than 3,000 families. That's just not fair,'' Gore said. ``These are
the priorities of Congress. Instead of just making it easier to
pass on a family farm, they want to give away the store to those
who already own the shopping center, and I'm not for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
