A1006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOUNDERS-MARKETPLACE-     06-21 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNDERS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SEC FINES FORMER OWNER OF FOUNDERS ASSET MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Calif.)   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regulators have suspended and fined the former owner of Founders
Asset Management, which manages more than $8 billion, for failing
to disclose that some of the firm's clients paid excessive
commissions on stock trades in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn Erik Borgen, the sole owner of Founders during the
three-year period in question, agreed to a 180-day suspension from
the investment business to settle the complaint by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Borgen will also pay a $590,000 fine, representing the profits
that Founders made on the affected clients during that time. Mellon
Financial Corp., which bought Founders from Borgen in April 1998,
will pay an additional $50,000, although the SEC did not cite any
problems at Founders since Mellon acquired the company.
</P>
<P>
   Borgen, who is now president of Borgen Investment Group, did not
admit or deny any wrongdoing under the settlement, reached last
week. A lawyer for Borgen said he had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The fine and suspension add to the recent spate of aggressive
enforcement actions from the commission. In the last 10 days, the
SEC has taken action against former officers of Cendant, who it
said participated in a fraud at what used to be CUC International
for more than a dozen years; a nationwide series of microcap fraud
rings, and several people who traded on insider information in a
Bay Networks acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said that Borgen caused some Founders clients, though
not the company's mutual fund clients, to pay excessive brokerage
commissions as a way to compensate a broker who had placed the
clients with Founders. The clients did not know that they were
being overcharged, according to the commission. In addition, the
trades were made later than those for other Founders clients, and
so were usually done at less favorable prices, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of this case is on disclosure, and the
responsibility of investment advisers to fully disclose their
commission policies and their execution policy,'' said Don Hoerl,
associate regional director of the SEC's office in Denver, which
brought the case.
</P>
<P>
   The commission charged that the excessive commissions were paid
to brokerage companies affiliated with William O. Foster, a San
Diego broker who persuaded more than 40 of his clients to invest
$123 million with Founders. ``Founders did so at Borgen's direction
in order to provide Foster with a prearranged amount of brokerage
commissions in exchange for Foster referring clients,'' the SEC
asserted in its complaint. By failing to disclose the practice,
Borgen violated securities law, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Foster, who simultaneously agreed to a $25,000 fine
and 30-day suspension from the industry in a similar SEC case that
did not name Founders, said Foster had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   A Founders spokeswoman said the company had changed its rules
and now treats all its clients fairly. ``In 1995, when these
practices came to light, Founders proactively addressed them,''
said the spokeswoman, Bridget Richards. ``This matter did not
involve the operations of our mutual funds. It was strictly a small
number of small private accounts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
