<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-VIENNA0625-COX     06-21 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VIENNA0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Advance story for Sunday, June 25.
 &HT;    A museum of a different color'
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA - Apart from the traditional sites of this seat of
onetime Austrian royalty is a quite-uncommon house whose courtyard
faces the Danube Canal in a neighborhood where there are no
palaces.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the building appear unusual are the windows.
</P>
<P>
   No two are alike.
</P>
<P>
   This is KunstHausWien, a privately-operated and sponsored museum
that pays homage to the art and architectural representations of a
most unusual man, Friedensreich Hundertwasser. ``Unusual'' might
not be adequate to describe him; ``eccentric'' likely is better,
``bizarre'' also fitting _ and ``creative genius'' perhaps most
precise.
</P>
<P>
   In KunstHausWien, you won't find any crown jewels, or chamber
pots some little prince used.
</P>
<P>
   Hundertwasser, who died in February at the age of 71, was a
contemporary artist much of whose prominence was attained through
architectural designs that turned ordinary into unique: a gruesome
district heating plant with a new skin of tiles, lights and bright
colors; a traditional church belltower renovated to include a gold
onion dome and exterior ceramics; a somewhat candy-striped roadside
restaurant that surpasses any unconventional equivalent in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   What also set Hundertwasser apart from others, in addition to
lecturing in the nude (flanked, of course, by two corresponding
unclad females), was his passion for the ``right of window.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own words, Hundertwasser proclaimed, ``Each individual
window has its own right to life.'' Translated, he was saying that
uniform windows on buildings were a manner of conformity from which
he felt the world should rebel.
</P>
<P>
   There's where the KunstHausWien comes in. In 1991, the already
internationally-recognized Hundertwasser took a commonplace former
furniture factory and recreated it as his legacy. Not only were all
the windows made to be different, but much of the floors were
reconfigured uneven; a rise here, a decline there _ like walking in
the woods but you are inside a house.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hundertwasser's position that people who lived inside
buildings have a right to stamp their cachet on those buildings.
Anything within arm's reach outside the window was fair game for
the occupant to design to his or her own desires. The window
casements even could be altered. As a suggestive template,
Hundertwasser designed the building that he described as ``a
``colorful spot in the cheerless, monotonous and sterile face of
the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Externally, the shape of the windows, the paint and/or tiles
around them, depict a cacophony of color and style that somehow
makes sense. On the inside, Hundertwasser's representative art, a
contemporary corollary to what fellow Austrian Gustav Klimt
expressed a century earlier, fills the walls and display cases, a
monument to his creativity and his adroitness for performing
cosmetic surgery on unattractive buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Hundertwasser's diverse talents even brought him to designing
postage stamps and redesigning national flags, none of the latter
having been accepted but which represented his utopian beliefs. As
an example, he designed a flag for the Holy Land; not Israel, not a
Palestinian State but for what he idealistically called the Holy
Land. It has a white background with a green Star of David sitting
atop a horizontally-drawn green Muslim-representative crescent, an
artistic wish that coexistence would be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   On the lower floors of this unusual building, Hundertwasser's
paintings, graphics and architectural prototypes are numerous. So
are his decrees: ``If we do not honor our past, we lose our future.
If we destroy our roots, we cannot grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``The straight line is godless.''
</P>
<P>
   It is to the latter that Hundertwasser most addressed himself.
Straight lines are difficult to find in KunstHausWien.
Nevertheless, his contemporary style can please even
tradition-bound devotees, among which included the Austrian critic
Wieland Schmiel who admitted that his original unfavorable
assessment of Hundertwasser was colored by the unusualness of the
artist himself rather than the hypothetical, yet controlled, images
he was painting.
</P>
<P>
   Hundertwasser's philosophy of life dominates. To attempt to
explain it, his theories of space, of mind, of environment, would
require much the space taken by those lower floors. He has a
philosophy about everything, not always in concert with his other
philosophies. That's what makes his house so exciting; so eclectic.
He takes us on adventures into multiple facets of life, all with
artistic creation.
</P>
<P>
   The upper floors, reachable via a giddy, lumpy staircase provide
exhibition space for other artists and artisans.
</P>
<P>
   Born as Friedrich Stowasser in Vienna of a Jewish mother and
Aryan father, that he and his mother came through the Nazi period
in that city is salient, if not mysterious inasmuch as more than 60
of his maternal side perished in the Holocaust. This is not a
hidden period of Hundertwasser's life (there is a photo displayed
of him in the museum, showing him as a school child posing in a
classroom with crossed Nazi swastika flags in the background) but
puzzling in that the mother and son (the father died in 1929) not
only survived but seemed to fit into the pattern of day-to-day
living in a Nazi-controlled society. He adopted his professional
name in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   A biographer, Pierre Restany, devoted but three sentences to
that period of Hundertwasser's life. A guide at KunstHausWien said
he was unable to answer my question as to how the Hundertwassers,
despite their Jewish linkage, endured _ not because of anything
protective but simply because he didn't know, that it wasn't an
issue to which he felt he needed answers.
</P>
<P>
   Hundertwasser was too young to be involved in anything political
then but his later blossoming as an artist brought worldwide
acclaim. In 1981, Austria awarded him the country's highest honor
for culture, the Austrian State Prize. He toured extensively and,
at times, lived in France and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   (According to Associated Press, Hundertwasser's first
architectural creation in New Zealand was a public toilet made of
colorful tiles and wine bottles, with no straight lines and a roof
that was covered with vegetation including marijuana plants.)
</P>
<P>
   It was on a cruise aboard the QE2 from New Zealand that the
outspoken critic of nuclear power had a heart attack and died
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   His endowment to the world of art and architecture is intact in
the strange house alongside the Danube Canal. In the course of
doing the Vienna thing, palaces, royal apartments and treasure
caches are plentiful. Take a break from the glitz of royalty, try
the unique KunstHausWien.
</P>
<P>
   (Find out more about KunstHausWien at
http://www.hundertwasser.at/english)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
