<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-REACT-(     06-21 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER-REACT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTRAGE IN A SMALL ILLINOIS TOWN OVER HIGH COURT RULING ON PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill., Texas)  By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANO, Ill. _ Out for breakfast in a small-town restaurant,
Wanda Huffman, 42, led her children in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Then she shook her head in dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how long it will be,'' she said, ``before they tell
us we can't pray in public places.''
</P>
<P>
   Huffman was outraged by the ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court on
Monday that student-led prayers at high school football games are
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In this conservative small town, 58 miles west of Chicago, the
court ruling was seen as another attack on homespun values by
sneering elitists. Of more than two dozen people interviewed here,
not a single person defended the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, people despaired of an emerging American culture that
allows for gay Boy Scout leaders, but grows skittish about students
who want to pray. And they often saw the curbs on prayer as part of
a greater effort to impose government regulations, like gun
control. But more than anything, they saw it as a lapse of common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the trouble we're in because there's not enough
prayer,'' said Denise Spooner, standing outside the Wal-Mart store
on Route 34, as storm clouds gathered. ``If people are bothered by
a bunch of kids getting together to pray before a game, well, I
just don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-3 decision, the Supreme Court strongly reaffirmed its
earlier rulings against officially sponsored prayer in public
schools, saying that prayers led by students at high school
football games are no exception. The majority opinion by Justice
John Paul Stevens said that even when attendance was voluntary and
when the decision to pray was made by students, ``the delivery of a
pregame prayer has the improper effect of coercing those present to
participate in an act of worship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't be coerced to pray,'' said Jim Wasson, an
electrician, ``but I don't think that's what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But people in Plano, a town of 5,100 in the farm country west of
Chicago's suburbs, said they could not fathom that young people
would succumb to prayer out of peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to feel like they have to pray,'' said
Stephanie Briggs, 18. ``People in school like to do their own
thing. Besides that, the players all know each other. They know
their religious beliefs. It's not like some pregame prayer is going
to mean that much, or change their views.''
</P>
<P>
   To Shane Shelton, a 30-year-old construction worker, the whole
discussion seems a bit silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The professional players are always praying on the field and
talking about God, and that doesn't seem to bother anybody,''
Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, who wore a bandana and shoulder-length hair, said he
was not a church-goer, and would not join in public prayer
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if somebody else wants to do that, what do I care?'' he
said. ``It's about freedom. Just let people pray, if that's what
they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Karen Wasson, 55, who owns the Tastee Treet ice cream stand in
Plano, lamented that American society had lost its moral bearings,
and that leaders were unwilling to speak the unvarnished truth
about right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is not respected,'' she said. ``Religion is not
respected. And authority is not respected. We won't stand up for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasson, who has been teaching Catholic religion classes for 18
years, said she was sometimes astonished at the cheeky behavior of
young people nowadays, even among those enrolled in religious
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things they say _ in my day, I would have been
smacked in the head so hard my head would rotate,'' she said.
``Some of these kids know more about the world at 12 than I did at
24. It's sad, really, that so many kids don't have the chance to
just be kids.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To Debbie Finley, 39, the court ruling seemed another example of
an extreme reaction. ``It's like all these schools getting rid of
their Christmas programs,'' she said. ``Everybody is afraid that
somebody is going to get offended.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Kelsey Finley, 16, plays basketball for the Serena
High School team, but said she saves her prayers for the Lutheran
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think praying before a game is going to help you
win,'' she said, with a smile. ``But if other people want to pray,
it doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Bildusas, a 34-year-old secretary, said her family
recently turned to home-schooling, in large part because it sensed
a hostility toward religion by the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be telling kids who want to pray, `More power to
you,''' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Spooner, the property manager, saw the court ruling as ``the
government stepping into your family's way,'' decreeing what kinds
of worship were permissible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, for the last 30 years, they've been reprogramming
us about what's right and wrong,'' she said. ``We're being watered
down in this country. But there's a higher power than the United
States government. We're all going to have to answer to God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
