<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-21 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN, EGYPT: DIRECT TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Presaging a possible warming of relations between two mutually
suspicious nations, the presidents of Egypt and Iran spoke by
telephone in what may be the first direct top-level contact since
their countries broke off ties after Egypt's peace treaty with
Israel in 1979. The occasion for the conversation was Iran's bid to
join the so-called G15 group of developing nations, which ended a
two-day meeting in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: 2 WOMEN FREED
</P>
<P>
   Two Iranian women who were jailed in May after attending a
Berlin seminar on democracy were released after posting about
$60,000 each in bail. Mehrangiz Kar and Shahla Lahiji, women's
rights figures who have been denounced by religious conservatives,
are charged with endangering Iran's security. Four others arrested
after attending the Berlin conference remain in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: CRISIS MOVE
</P>
<P>
   The leftist Meretz Party paved the way for a resolution to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's coalition crisis. Meretz said it would stay
in the coalition to support Barak's peace moves, but that its three
ministers, including Education Minister Yossi Sarid, would give up
their cabinet posts. That should help bring back the linchpin Shas
Party, which has been in a feud with Sarid and quit the government,
with resignations that do not take effect until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLER TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak said he had decided to open a
``continous dialogue'' with settlers, who have been protesting
regularly outside his residence and office. His office said he had
told his ministers and peace negotiators to visit settlements and
listen to settlers' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: BARGAINING CHIPS
</P>
<P>
   Parliament passed a preliminary bill enabling Israel to imprison
``combatants not entitled to prisoner-of-war status.'' The bill is
meant to enable Israel to continue holding two Lebanese militants
seized as bargaining chips for missing Israeli soldiers. After a
High Court ruling outlawed the practice the government sought to
create a legal justification for their detention.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA: U,N, MISSION EXTENDED
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council extended for one year a Bosnia mission that
includes a 1,600-member international police force sent to create a
multiethnic local force from Muslims, Serbs and Bosnian Croats.
Russia abstained in protest at the exclusion of Yugoslavia from a
conference in Brussels on Bosnia's future, China also spoke against
the exclusion of President Slobodan Milosevic's government from the
conference, but voted for the mission's extension.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: RIGHTISTS ADMIT KIDNAPPING
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the main right-wing paramilitary group has
admitted ordering the kidnapping of Guillermo Valencia, a member of
Congress who is the brother of one of the government's chief
negotiators in peace talks with leftist guerrillas. Carlos Castano
said the abduction was necessary ``to stop the continuing and
progressive handover of the country to the guerrillas.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: ANWAR TRIAL ADJOURNED
</P>
<P>
   After a year of hearings, a judge adjourned the trial of former
Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim and ordered lawyers to produce
written summations in advance of a verdict. Anwar, who is already
serving a six-year sentence for corruption, faces a sentence of up
to 20 years in the current case, in which he is accused of sexual
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: NEW KILLINGS
</P>
<P>
   At least 9 people were reported killed as fighting continued in
the remote Spice Islands after a massacre on the island of
Halmahera in which as many as 160 people were killed. Thousands
have died in 18 months of fighting between Christians and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: FOREIGNERS BARRED
</P>
<P>
   The government refused to accredit dozens of foreigners from
observing this weekend's voting in parliamentary elections. They
included observers from the National Democratic Institute, an
American organization, which was assailed by the government for
reporting that political violence had impaired prospects for free
and fair elections. Observers from the European Union, the
Commonwealth, the Organization of African Unity and southern Africa
will monitor the vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
