<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TAIPEI-ATLANTA0622-CO     06-21 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIPEI-ATLANTA0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sister cities have much in common
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Shhhh. It's a well-kept secret in both places,
it seems, but Atlanta and Taipei are Sister Cities.
</P>
<P>
   They have been since 1979, and, though the relationship is a
nominal one, as such ties often are, the fit in this case is better
than most.
</P>
<P>
   Mat Matich, a University of Georgia graduate who moved here a
couple of years ago, was discussing the similarities between
Atlanta and Taipei while nursing a drink at the Lai Lai Sheraton
Hotel one recent evening.
</P>
<P>
   Matich, who claims to speak Chinese with a Southern accent, came
here seeking adventure and now works as a writer for Topics
magazine, a publication of the American Chamber of Commerce in
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Like Atlanta, Taipei might not be a great place to visit, but it
is a great place to live, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say visitors can't find attractions amid the
bustling din of this densely populated Asian metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   John Flick, international spokesperson for United Parcel
Service, has visited the city off and on for a decade and thinks,
for instance, that it ``has probably the best museums in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, the National Palace Museum, houses the world's
finest collection of Chinese art, spanning nearly 5,000 years. It's
emblematic of the links between the island of Taiwan and mainland
China. The vast collection was China's national treasure until it
was carted here, in 4,800 crates, for safe-keeping when the
Nationalist government of Chiang Kai-shek fled the mainland after
being defeated in a civil war with the communists.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors with a taste for Asian cuisine can also find plenty to
whet their appetites. Taipei's food-loving residents take pride in
their city's reputation as a unique center for all styles of Asian
cuisine, and they boast that the variety is even greater than in
the international melting pot of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is the culture,'' said Fred Chiou, an Internet company
executive with a doctorate in engineering from Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Chiou, like Matich, sees many similarities between these two
cities which are a half-globe apart.
</P>
<P>
   Like Atlanta, Taipei, with a population of 2.7 million intown
and more than 4 million in the metro area, is a regional business
center with a love of healthy profit margins. And, like Atlanta, it
has boomed in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Atlanta's suburbs have sprawled over what were once
cotton fields, Taipei's glass-faced high rises stretch for miles
into what, in the 1960s, were rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   Both cities are also raucously democratic, and this week at
least you could make a case for comparing two of their most famous
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   One of Atlanta's best-known figures is a former U.S. president,
Jimmy Carter, who has made a reputation as a global peacemaker. One
of Taipei's _ immediate past mayor Chen Shui-bian _ was inaugurated
just last month as president of the Republic of China on Taiwan and
this week launched a peacemaking campaign of his own. Apparently
inspired by the example of the two Koreas, which met in a historic
summit in Pyongyang, Chen called Tuesday for a similar meeting with
China to ease the long-running tensions across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   The two cities also share a leading corporate citizen, United
Parcel Service. UPS, which is based in Atlanta, provided frenzied
support for victims of last year's devastating earthquake in
central Taiwan. It has operated out of Taipei since 1988 and has
made the East Asian city its key hub for the Asia-Pacific region.
Pictures of UPS planes _ which make 68 flights a week out of
Taipei's Chiang Kai-shek international airport _ are featured in a
multi-media production Taiwan's government proudly shows visiting
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese ``are very pro-business, and they've been very
good about helping us out,'' said Flick, adding that his company
has also invested heavily in related businesses in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal world, Chiou, who lived 15 years in Georgia and
expects to return once his son reaches college age, said he would
spend his days in Atlanta and his nights in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Even the nights here are not necessarily so different, however.
</P>
<P>
   True, at the crowded night markets, you can visit a Chinese
medicine practitioner or even watch a vendor tease a snake before
killing it to be eaten.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Atlanta bar scene is more to your liking, you can
find its equivalent by dropping in at the Hollywood Underground at
the Far Eastern Plaza, where on some nights patrons dressed as
movie stars are admitted free. Saturdays bring ``Saturday Night
Fever'' events at the TMC Disco, or you can stop by on a Monday _
Energy Night _ and get a free cocktail if you wear workout gear.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and Hong Kong rival or surpass the United States in
influence on popular culture, but there is ample American influence
if you look for it.
</P>
<P>
   Cable TV is widely available and provides a fair sampling of
American shows. Yah-chiTsai, an interpreter for English-speaking
visitors, especially likes decorator maven Martha Stewart's show.
``I think she is a genius,'' Tsai gushed.
</P>
<P>
   But if you prefer ball over decorating, you can take in a
baseball game, watching teams from one of two professional leagues.
In one of them, Taipei's Suns compete against the Braves _ of
Chiayi.
</P>
<P>
   Even the weather of the cities ``is very similar,'' said Chiou,
who moved back in March.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical sultry day, women stroll down the street carrying
umbrellas to block out the sun. And that typical Taipei weather
influenced one foreign visitor to propose a new slogan for the
city, Tsai recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to describe Taipei he would use three H's,'' she said.
``Hot, humid and hospitable.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan sums up her town well, Tsai thought. It might also
apply to that Sister community back in the American South.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
