</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEFONICA-VILLALONGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEFONICA CHAIRMAN UNDER PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chairman of the Spanish telecommunications giant that is
acquiring Internet portal Lycos Inc. is under investigation by
government regulators in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   The probe, reopening an old controversy, centers on the purchase
and quick sale of options in his company's shares by Telefonica SA
chairman Juan Villalonga. Shares of Telefonica, its Terra Networks
Internet unit and Lycos all fell Wednesday on fears the review
could disrupt the merger.
</P>
<P>
   American analysts Wednesday cautioned the new investigation
might be politically motivated, however, while its financial impact
is unclear. Telefonica would not comment, though a Terra executive
called the inquiry ``no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny at least seemed to underscore Villalonga's
controversial tenure at the head of one of Spain's largest
businesses and a former state-owned monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish newspaper Wednesday reported that Spain's National
Securities Market Commission is looking into whether Villalonga
acted improperly when he bought options on roughly a
quarter-million shares in Telefonica in 1998, then sold them two
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had previously investigated the trades and
declined to take action. But in a story confirmed by company
officials, the newspaper El Mundo reported the commission had begun
a new inquiry, which seemed to center on whether Villalonga bought
the options after he began talks about an alliance with WorldCom
Inc. (The two companies announced the alliance in March 1998).
</P>
<P>
   The probe is only the latest move by the Spanish government
against Telefonica. Last month, officials blocked Villalonga's
planned $58 billion merger with the Dutch phone company Royal KPN.
Members of the Spanish securities commission weren't available to
discuss their reasoning Wednesday, and it could be years before the
body issues its finding.
</P>
<P>
   Following the news report, Telefonica's American-share
equivalents shares fell $2.50 to close at $58.25 in Nasdaq trading.
Shares in its majority-owned Terra Networks unit, which would
technically acquire Lycos, shares slipped 13 cents to close at
$36.89.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos shares, meanwhile, fell $4.88 to $54, down from a high of
more than $72.63 the day the deal was announced. That's still above
the $38 at which Lycos traded in late April, before sales talk
began.
</P>
<P>
   Abel Linares, managing director of Terra Networks, said the
investigation wouldn't disrupt the proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no problem for Terra,'' said Linares, who is slated to
become chief operating officer of the combined company, Terra
Lycos. The company will be based in Barcelona but is planning to
expand the Lycos offices in Waltham, Mass. Linares attributed the
share declines to ``normal trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors are watching the share prices as Villalonga attempts
to use his company's stock to turn Telefonica into a global player
in the consolidating media business.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he announced an agreement in which Terra Networks
would purchase Lycos Inc. for stock then valued at $12.5 billion.
The combination would become a global competitor of other media
giants, including the company to be formed as America Online
proposes to buy Time Warner Inc. Germany's Bertelsmann AG, a
one-time ally of AOL, also pledged to buy $1 billion worth of
advertising and services from Terra Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   While Terra shareholders have approved the merger, Lycos holders
aren't expected to vote on the deal until later this summer. A year
ago, Lycos stockowners rejected a merger proposal as undervaluing
the company. Paul Noglows, analyst for Chase H &AMP; Q in San
Francisco, said he's heard from ``most institutional holders of
Lycos stock'' that they will support the merger, though he declined
to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is up to Villalonga to keep his backers in line. That
might be an accomplishment for the 47-year-old, who has riled
Spain's relatively closed business establishment even as he has
increased the company's market value. He spends much of his time in
Miami, where Terra threw a lavish party last week, worrying some in
Europe that Telefonica's center of gravity is shifting across the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Some Spanish Socialists have also suggested that the purchase of
Lycos would dillute Terra's Spanish character.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga tried to rebut that criticism earlier this month,
when he told shareholders that Terra Lycos ``is and always will be
a Spanish company.''
</P>
<P>
   But continued problems with the government could be Villalonga's
undoing. ``If the national commission keeps finding proof of
wrongdoing, then Terra might have a big problem and he (Villalonga)
should be moved out of the company,'' said Felipe Gomez-Serrano,
senior telecommunications analyst for the Caja Madrid Bolsa
securities firm and a columnist for El Mundo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
