<HEADER>
A1020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-BOS &LR;      06-21 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS STANDS BY TESTIMONY ON SKAKEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Under intense cross-examination Wednesday, a
former classmate of Michael Skakel's stood firmly behind his
allegation that the nephew of Ethel Kennedy told him more than 20
years ago that he had murdered a teenage girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I heard,'' testified Gregory Coleman, 38, who
attended a Maine facility for troubled adolescents with Skakel in
the late 1970s. ``I'm sure of that _ not 99.9 percent, but 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys also heard a childhood friend of Skakel's, Andrew
Pugh, testify that Skakel had said around 1991 he had been at the
murder scene on the night of Martha Moxley's death in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said Skakel told him he had masturbated in a pine tree
above the spot where Moxley's body was discovered the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh, who said he harbored suspicions about Skakel's guilt,
testified that he refused to cooperate with private investigators
hired by the Skakel family, who contacted him after Michael's
admission. Pugh said he felt that ``I shouldn't be helping defend''
Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Coleman, who attended the Elan School in
Poland Spring, Maine with Skakel, parried with defense attorney
Michael ``Mickey'' Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that Skakel had confessed to Moxley's murder, but he
conceded he mistakenly told the grand jury that the defendant made
the admission ``five or six times.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who is serving an eight-month sentence in a New York
state prison, testified that Skakel confessed twice in 1978 at
Elan.
</P>
<P>
   According to Coleman, the first confession occurred as he stood
night watch over Skakel. Although Skakel had just been returned to
Elan after an escape, he had not been beaten _ as Coleman said he
expected _ and was allowed the special privilege of keeping a
stereo on the dining-room stage where he was forced to sleep as
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the comment that this guy could get away with murder,''
Coleman said. Skakel allegedly replied: ``I am going to get away
with murder. I'm a Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman testified that Skakel then told him details of the
crime, including his golf-club assault on a girl who had spurned
his advances.
</P>
<P>
   The next confession, Coleman said, came during a ``primal
scream'' session in which students were forced to yell apologies to
a group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was common knowledge'' at the school, Coleman said of
Skakel's alleged link to the murder. ``It wasn't a hidden thing.
Everybody knew about it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, another former Elan student, John Higgins, testified
that Skakel also told him he murdered Moxley.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman described Skakel _ ``arrogant, cocky, self-serving'' _
as an unpopular student at a controversial treatment center that
routinely used physical abuse in the name of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Staff-sanctioned punishment at Elan would range from blows with
oak paddles, to open-fist assaults, to ``boxing'' matches in which
offenders were beaten to the floor, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   The authorization for such student-dispensed discipline came
from school owner Joseph Ricci, Coleman said. In one case of abuse,
he added, a thin teenage girl was beaten by several students into a
state of shock that required hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci has told The Boston Globe he never heard Skakel confess to
Moxley's murder, and that he believes his former students that
claim Skakel confessed are lying.
</P>
<P>
   According to a sealed police report obtained by USA Today,
Skakel pulled a switchblade on a family chauffeur in 1978 and had
to be pulled off the railing of the Triborough Bridge in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1993 police interview with the chauffeur, Larry Zicarelli,
Skakel is portrayed as wildly tormented. Zicarelli said he was told
by Skakel's father to drive Michael to a therapist's session in New
York after he tried to steal a family car.
</P>
<P>
   On the way, Skakel allegedly pulled a switchblade on Zicarelli,
jumped out of the car several times, and twice had to be pulled off
the bridge railing. Zicarelli described Skakel as ``absolutely
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the police report, Skakel allegedly told Zicarelli,
``I've done something very bad. I'm in a lot of trouble. I've
either got to kill myself or leave the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman had no comment on that report.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony before Juvenile Judge Maureen Dennis, Pugh said
that shortly after Skakel told him about being at the murder scene,
he was contacted about 30 times by the private investigators hired
by the Skakel family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael asked if I would meet with them,'' Pugh said of Sutton
Associates. The answer was no.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Pugh finally went to police with Skakel's comment that
he had been at the murder scene.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel had never given police that version of events. Until
being interviewed by Sutton Associates, Skakel had told authorities
he drove a cousin home on the night of the murder, returned to his
house, and went directly to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fuhrman, the former Los Angeles homicide detective who
wrote a book about the Moxley slaying, has suggested that Skakel
changed his official alibi to include masturbation as a way to
explain the presence of semen that might be traced to him through
modern DNA analysis.
</P>
<P>
   After Pugh's testimony, the prosecution rested its case in the
``reasonable cause'' hearing to determine whether Skakel, 39,
should be tried for Moxley's murder. Judge Dennis adjourned the
hearing until Wednesday, when Sherman will call former Elan
students and staff as defense witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   If reasonable cause is found, Dennis also must rule whether
Skakel is to be tried as an adult for a crime he allegedly
committed as a 15-year-old. A grand jury indicted Skakel in
January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
