<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACECRAFT PHOTOGRAPHS 
SIGNS OF WATER ON MARS 
 

</HEADLINE>
 WATER-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Cameras aboard NASA's sharp-eyed Mars Global Surveyor
spacecraft have photographed recent evidence of water flowing and
pooling on the arid world, an unexpected finding that if borne out
raises the odds of primitive life on the Red Planet.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency plans to unveil the imagery gathered by San
Diego-based scientists Mike Malin and Ken Edgett Thursday at a
Washington news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs show narrow V-shaped channels and large curved
and darkened depressions that resemble ponds in a range of features
on the Martian surface, including a 31-mile wide meteor impact
crater in the planet's Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will essentially turn many of our ideas about the current
state of water on Mars on their ears,'' said Steven Clifford, an
expert on the planet's hydrology based at the Lunar and Planetary
Institute in Houston. ``If the interpretation is correct, it raises
uncountable questions about the conditions under which liquid water
has been stored so close to the surface and released during recent
times. This is a complete mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the scientists involved in the discovery nor NASA
officials would discuss the findings Wednesday. Malin and Edgett,
who built and operate the camera on the Mars Global Surveyor, had
planned to publish their findings in the journal Science next week.
</P>
<P>
   However, sketchy reports in at least two Internet news sites and
the British Broadcasting Corporation earlier this week forced the
space agency to advance its plans to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Half the size of the neighboring Earth, Mars had long held a
fascination with the public as well as with scientists. Of the
solar system's nine planets, Mars is most Earth-like and the more
likely to host a primitive form of life.
</P>
<P>
   Now cold and arid with a thin atmosphere of deadly carbon
dioxide, Mars revealed what appear to be river channels, large
watersheds as well as shorelines to early American spacecraft,
especially NASA's highly successful Viking probes of the late
1970s. The features suggest water was once abundant on the Martian
surface.
</P>
<P>
   The failures last year of NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter and Mars
Polar Lander probes interrupted what began as an aggressive effort
by American scientists to find out where the water went.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing theory is that a dramatic climate change,
possibly associated with a slow but dramatic wobble in the axis of
Mars, caused the water that once flowed freely on the surface to
seep deep underground and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Mars could have dried up more than 3.5 billion years ago, some
experts believe.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature now rises above the freezing point on Mars for
only a few hours at a time during the warmest part of the summer at
the planet's equator, making any evidence of flowing water all the
more surprising, said Clifford.
</P>
<P>
   If the findings are borne out, they are all the more important
in the search for evidence of current or past primitive life on the
Red Planet.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Mars presentation that NASA plans today is
reminiscent of an announcement it made four years ago in Washington
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 6, 1996 scientists from NASA's Johnson Space Center and
Stanford University announced they had detected evidence of
fossilized bacteria in a 4.2 pound meteorite of Martian origin.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorite was collected in 1984 from the Antarctic, where it
fell 13,000 years ago. A microscopic examination of the rock's
interior produced evidence of bacteria-like structures in the
crevices of the rock that appeared to be 3.6 billion years old.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe the meteorite was among debris blasted away
from the Martian surface when it was struck by an asteroid 16
million years ago. The meteorite wandered around the sun until it
crossed the Earth's orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the claim by the NASA and Stanford scientists
remains hotly debated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
