<HEADLINE>
WAR CRIMES PROSECUTOR WILL NOT DROP CHARGES AGAINST MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The chief prosecutor of the International
War Crimes Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia said Wednesday that
she would not withdraw the indictment against Slobodan Milosevic,
the Yugoslav president, and that she opposed any action by
Washington or other governments to let him escape justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will not be stability in the Balkans if Milosevic is not
brought to justice in the Hague,'' said the prosecutor, Carla Del
Ponte, at a news conference during a visit to the Kosovo capital
Wednesday. ``I don't think that the man most responsible for what
happened here in Kosovo should have preference.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported on Monday that the Clinton
administration, with some NATO allies and Russia, was exploring the
possibility of letting Milosevic leave office with guarantees that
he would not be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. war crimes tribunal, based in the Hague, publicly
indicted Milosevic and four members of his Cabinet last year for
responsibility for the deaths and expulsion of ethnic Albanians
during the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte firmly rejected any policy change for the tribunal and
said her staff was proceeding with investigations against Milosevic
for crimes in Kosovo and in previous wars in the region. ``We are
investigating the criminal responsibility of Slobodan Milosevic for
Croatia and Bosnia,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They were also preparing additional indictments against other
lesser officials like police, military and political personnel,
both Serbs and others, including Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless in a comment that hinted at the overriding power of
politics, she said, ``I am a prosecutor, not a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte was visiting Kosovo to see the progress of forensic
teams that are exhuming bodies from hundreds of sites around
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   She has also visited Macedonia and will travel on to the
Yugoslav republic of Montenegro to ask for its cooperation in the
war crimes investigations. Her investigators are banned from Serbia
despite their repeated requests for access to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a new development, she said the tribunal has begun
investigations into whether the Kosovo Liberation Army had
committed crimes in the conflict, dating back to 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She said five episodes to which members of the now disbanded
guerrilla army have been linked were under investigation. No
indictments have been brought against members of the KLA but
certain allegations merit investigation, a tribunal spokesman, Paul
Risley, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are allegations that the KLA were responsible for crimes
in five areas, and we have an obligation to look at these serious
allegations,'' said Graham Blewitt, deputy prosecutor at the
tribunal. He and Del Ponte refused to discuss the types of crimes
being investigated, but there are widely known cases of Serbian
civilians abducted by members of the KLA. The Serbs have not been
found and their disappearance has fueled local hatred against the
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Tribunal officials estimate that 1 million Albanians were
expelled from their homes and the territory of Kosovo by Serbian
forces in the spring of last year and that thousands of civilians
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   There remains uncertainty about whether that campaign,
apparently orchestrated by the Serbian leadership, amounted to
genocide, since to bring charges of genocide, prosecutors have to
prove the intention to destroy a people or part of a people.
``There are other explanations, and we need to look at those,''
Blewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of KLA crimes could not be compared to the
organized campaign by Serb forces, Blewitt said. They involved
fewer victims and cannot be considered genocide, he said. ``The KLA
does not get anywhere near that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the announcement of an international investigation of crimes
by Albanians is bound to have some meaning here. It came the day
after a young Serb couple were shot and wounded near the main
street in Pristina on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte accompanied the chief of the U.N. mission here,
Bernard Kouchner, and local Albanian political leaders to lay
flowers at the spot of the attack. The two Serbs, a young bank
security guard and his girlfriend, a local radio reporter, were
found by peacekeeping officers and taken to a hospital, where they
were reported to be in stable condition. Both had been shot several
times.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting happened near the busy center of Pristina and
highlighted the impunity with which Albanians have conducted
revenge attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The divided town of Mitrovica also exploded into violence
Wednesday as a Serbian crowd stoned the Albanian driver of a
garbage truck and then set fire to cars with U.N. or foreign
registrations. Several people were injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
