<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-FAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOOLEY, 87, A FRIEND OF THE RED SOX WITHOUT AN EQUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dooley, who watched more than 4,000 consecutive Boston
Red Sox home games over 55 seasons from her front-row box seat,
died Monday in Boston, hours before her beloved Red Sox suffered a
22-1 beating from the Yankees. She was 87, a year younger than
Fenway Park, the home of the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Ted Williams, the greatest Red Sox player of them all,
said of Dooley: ``Forever, she's the greatest Red Sox fan there'll
ever be. Every time I get a chance to get around here I like to do
it, because she's really a big league gal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley shrugged off that accolade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not consider myself a fan,'' she said. ``I am a friend of
the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Lib Dooley was a faithful friend. She called Williams Theodore
and telephoned him on his every birthday. When Bobby Doerr retired,
she started sending him clippings from Boston newspapers. When
Mickey Mantle of the Yankees hit home runs against the Red Sox, he
would good-naturedly stick out his tongue at her.
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio was another of her Red Sox favorites. Upon learning
of her death, he told The Boston Globe: ``She was a perfect lady. I
remember so well when she presented us with our American League
championship rings after we won in 1946. She was so thrilled. The
Red Sox were practically her whole life, from what I could
gather.''
</P>
<P>
   They were indeed that. From 1944 until 1998, she did not miss a
home game and sometimes made road trips. Illness forced her to miss
some games in 1998 and 1999. This year, she made only opening day
and last month's Red Sox Hall of Fame dinner.
</P>
<P>
   She would sit in Box 36-A in the front row behind the Red Sox
on-deck circle, delivering Oreos and Starbursts to the players and
then watching the game intently. Despite her close seat, she said
only one foul ball came her way, by Carroll Hardy in the early
1960s. She caught it and broke two fingers.
</P>
<P>
   She never married. She attended Boston College at night, and
then, for 39 years, was a gym and health teacher in the Boston
public school system. In 1956, she moved to an apartment in Kenmore
Square. It was seven minutes from Fenway Park, she said, a little
longer as age made walking more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   She came by baseball naturally. In 1901, her father, John
Stephen Dooley, helped the new Red Sox team get a home at the
Huntington Avenue Grounds. According to her family, the father
attended every season opener from 1894 until 1970, when he died at
97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I despise bridge and I hate gossip,'' Lib Dooley said. ``I
wanted something where I could go by myself without anyone ruining
it by saying, `I can't do it this week.' Baseball gets you out in
the fresh air and keeps you from talking about your neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friendship with players did not alter her perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are really baseball, not the players,'' she said.
``You can always get someone to play ball. It doesn't have to be
someone who gets $4 million to work two hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   David Leary, her 24-year-old grandnephew, sat in her seat at
Monday night's game. Afterward, he got a game ball to place in her
coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Her survivors include four sisters, Winifred Dooley, Katherine
Dooley and Anna Martin, all of Milton, Mass., and Mary Jane Boyd of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
