<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BURIAL0622-COX     06-21 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURIAL0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    jMillions due Georgians
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Almost 200,000 Georgians could get a share of a $206
million settlement from one of the nation's largest insurance
companies, which overcharged black customers based on their race.
</P>
<P>
   American General Life and Accident Insurance Co. also agreed to
pay $7.5 million in fines to several states, including about $1.2
million to Georgia. The Nashville company is a unit of
Houston-based American General Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement stems from a multistate investigation led by
Florida insurance officials, who alleged that American General and
four other insurance companies charged black policyholders premiums
more than a third higher than white customers paid for small life
insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine estimated that more
than 176,000 Georgians will be eligible to share $31 million in
cash refunds, lower premiums or larger death benefits.
</P>
<P>
   American General said that about 600,000 out of about 9 million
living and deceased policyholders nationwide can expect to get cash
payments of at least $150 from the settlement. The policies were
sold during the 1940s through the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of paying weekly premiums, most policyholders by
now have paid in more money _ sometimes two or three times more _
than the $500 to $2,000 death benefit of most of the policies,
Oxendine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one lady who had bought a $500 policy . . . and
she had spent around a thousand'' to keep it in force, he said.
</P>
<P>
   American General acquired the companies that sold the policies,
said Carl Santillo, American General executive vice president of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we became aware of the problem, we had no hesitation''
about reaching a resolution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not sold industrial policies for at least 20 years,'' he
said, referring to the insurance usually known as ``burial
policies,'' sold door to door.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance officials involved in the investigation said about
108,000 African-Americans with active American General policies
sold at overtly discriminatory rates can expect refunds of at least
$150.
</P>
<P>
   Beneficiaries of deceased policyholders also may be eligible for
larger, retroactive death benefits in cash. About 3.7 million
policies have been terminated, have matured or have paid out death
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The other policyholders affected by the settlement are eligible
for larger future death benefits, reduced premiums or both. They
include about 5.7 million customers of all races who ended up
paying much more in premiums than their policies will pay after
they die.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement and a related class-action lawsuit resulted after
Florida insurance regulators and lawyers began investigating the
practices of five companies, including American General. The
investigators said some units of the companies not only charged
African-Americans higher premiums but also have continued to
collect the higher, discriminatory rates on old policies.
</P>
<P>
   The ``burial policies'' were sold generally in poor, black
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine said discrimination cases against the other four
companies, including Georgia-based Life Insurance Co. of Georgia,
are still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're next on the list,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials said African-American and other policyholders
with small life insurance policies _ generally less than $2,000 _
from several firms owned by American General may be eligible to
take part in a $206 million discrimination settlement announced
Wednesday. The companies are:
</P>
<P>
   Equitable Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Home Beneficial Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Home State Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Life and Accident Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Life and Casualty Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   National Life and Accident Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call American General at 800-681-4944 or
the Georgia Insurance Commission at 800-656-2298.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
