<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1033 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-OIL-NYT &LR;      06-21 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TRIES TO LINK BUSH TO BIG OIL AND HIGHER GAS PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Worried that voters will blame the Clinton
administration _ and Vice President Al Gore _ for the recent surge
in gasoline prices, the Gore campaign has begun an effort to paint
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, a onetime oil company executive, as a
tool of the oil interests the campaign says are relentlessly
gouging consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Wednesday for the Gore campaign, Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, said that Bush was ``getting all his money'' from the oil
companies, a reference to the industry's contributions to Bush's
presidential campaign. The oil and gas interests are the
eighth-largest industry donor to the Bush effort.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said he wanted oil executives to testify under oath on
Capitol Hill about the price increases.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush and Republicans on Capitol Hill blame the
gas-price increase on the Clinton administration, saying it has had
no coherent domestic energy policy and, in imposing regulations to
meet clean air standards, had allowed prices to drift as high as
$2.39 a gallon in the Midwest. Bush also said the administration
had failed to persuade the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to ``open the spigots'' to increase the supply.
</P>
<P>
   The group did decide Wednesday to increase oil production by
more than most experts had expected, a move that would presumably
push gasoline prices down in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been reticent to discuss the issue publicly, broke
his silence Wednesday and joined Gore in endorsing the
investigation by the Federal Trade Commission that was announced on
Tuesday. ``I do think it's fair to have the FTC investigate,'' he
said in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comment could undercut Gore's efforts to portray the
governor as part of the problem. In any case, the issue has jumped
to the top of the agenda in presidential politics as Americans
begin their summer vacations.
</P>
<P>
   The prices have hit hardest in the Midwest, the very
battleground states where the two campaigns are competing most
fiercely for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices in Illinois, Wisconsin and Michigan are substantially
higher than in other parts of the country for several reasons, but
chief among them, Republicans say, is the special kind of
reformulated gas the area must use under Environmental Protection
Agency regulations. Those regulations went into effect on June 1,
which is when prices began to rise considerably. The Midwest is the
first region, under the rules, to begin using this ethanol-laced
reformulated gas to prevent pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said that new polling shows that voters
believe the price of gasoline is far and away the No. 1 problem in
the country. The officials also say that voters blame American oil
companies most, then the OPEC oil cartel in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Gore officials see the emergence of this issue as an opportunity
to link Bush directly in the public mind with the oil companies and
portray Gore as on the side of working families. This has been a
longtime goal of the Gore campaign, but it has not succeeded so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for Gore, said: ``It all comes down to
who people think is on their side. People believe, and rightly so,
that the oil companies are in large part responsible for the price
of gasoline. They don't believe the government is responsible for
the price of gas. So what average people are deciding is, `Who do I
want in the government when gas prices skyrocket?' We think the
answer is clear: Vice President Gore is on their side, Governor
Bush isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself has ratcheted up his language on the price
increases, last week saying in selective interviews with Midwest
television stations that he wanted an investigation into possible
collusion. Wednesday, he said at the opening of a Social Security
speech in Iowa, one of the states most affected, that he was
concerned about the ``conduct of the oil companies'' and that they
might have been price gouging.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the issue deserved an investigation by the Federal
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that it will be thorough and hard-hitting,'' Gore said
of the investigation. ``If there's evidence of what I suspect
there's evidence of, it ought to be dealt with quickly and
harshly,'' he said. `'I think it's time to put our feet on the
brakes of what may well be big oil's price gouging.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin, speaking on behalf of the Gore campaign on a conference
call with reporters, accused the oil companies of ``outright
thievery.'' He went on to castigate Bush for his ``silence'' on the
matter, saying, ``What can you expect of someone who once claimed,
and I quote, `There's no such thing as being too closely aligned to
the oil business in West Texas.?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush uttered the quotation during a 1978 congressional campaign.
Acknowledging that the quotation was more than 20 years old, Harkin
said: ``The point is, the test of character and leadership is when
you're willing to take on your friends when it's in the nation's
best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed an emergency tax bill in 1999 that gave state tax
breaks to oil and gas companies. The Dallas Morning News reported
that the bill saved Richard Rainwater, a former business partner of
the governor, $1 million. At least 14 of Bush's ``Pioneers,'' his
largest financial contributors, have ties to the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign has received $1.5 million from gas and oil
interests as of April 1, while Gore had received less than $100,000
as of the same date.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore strategy of opening up fire on the oil front
carries some dangers for the campaign. For one thing, rising prices
_ and being reminded of them _ could undermine consumer confidence
in the economy at a time when Gore is boasting about the economy on
his ``progress and prosperity tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the majority leader, told reporters in
Washington on Wednesday: ``The vice president has a growing
political problem because his administration has been asleep at the
wheel when it comes to dealing with OPEC. Instead of acknowledging
that his administration has no energy policy, which leaves our
nation overly dependent on foreign oil, the vice president is
looking for a scapegoat.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said that Gore has obsessively lobbied for
so-called ``clean-air fuel,'' the kind that is now at the center of
the Midwestern price increases, without worrying about the
consequences. ``He is the one who pushed this whole idea of a
different type of gasoline,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore officials say the environmental standards leading to
the reformulation of gasoline have added only four to eight cents a
gallon to the cost of fuel and would not account for such a drastic
price increase.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1992 environmental treatise, ``Earth in the Balance,''
Gore himself proposed the idea of higher fuel taxes on oil
companies to help reduce pollution; as part of that, he suggested a
corresponding cut in corporate income and payroll taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
