A1036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SOC-INTL-NOTES0622-CO     06-21 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTL-NOTES0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Euro won't miss Germany, England
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the quarterfinals of the European Championships
this weekend are an improvement on some stirring group matches thus
far, then this could go down as one of the best major tournaments
in years. Breathtaking displays by Spain and Portugal, the
well-rounded skill of France and Holland, and the Cinderella story
of Turkey winning its first European match give Saturday and
Sunday's contests the kind of buzz that has been missing most of
the last decade, in previous Euros and the last three World Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of dull, safe and unimaginative soccer have gone
home. And so have the English hooligans, whose outbursts in the
streets of Charleroi, Belgium, on Saturday might have scuttled
England's bid to host the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a dreadful foul by England defender Phil Neville in
the final minute of regulation on Tuesday, Romania advanced to a
quarterfinal mathchup against Italy with a 3-2 victory. He was
called for a penalty kick while chasing Viorel Moldovan in the box.
Ioan Ganea converted the spot kick and England, needing only a draw
to advance, had a goat to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevastated,'' blared a tabloid headline Wednesday in The Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The English are just about the only ones mourning their
departure. UEFA threatened to send the England team home when
nearly 900 people, most of them English, were arrested before
Saturday's 1-0 win over Germany because of altercations in
Charleroi. Plastic furniture was thrown about, minor injuries and
property damage resulted, and many of the violators were sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Germany and Holland took strong measures before
Euro 2000 to control their own hooligans; even suspected
troublemakers had their passports revoked. The British government,
by contrast, keeps records only of hooligans with a clear record of
misbehavior. Most of those detained had no previous arrests and a
good number of them, having consumed strong Belgian beer, were
piling on in the frenzy of the crowd. Embarrassingly, officials
representing the government and the English Football Association
were left to point out that only a handful of their fans were
causing problems.
</P>
<P>
   But those tensions have been removed from the proceedings and
replaced with brilliance on the pitch. Wednesday's thrilling 4-3
victory by Spain over Yugoslavia to capture Group C was a
celebration of freewheeling, attacking soccer that has marked Euro
2000. The Spaniards, a favorite to win the title, got two goals in
second-half stoppage time to reverse a long history of early exits.
Yugoslavia, playing a man down most of the second half, took a 3-2
lead but allowed Spain to draw even on a penalty kick by Gaizka
Mendieta moments into stoppage time. The Spaniards kept attacking,
however, and Alfonso ripped a dipping shot from the edge of the box
for the victory in what has been the best match of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Holland joined Portugal with a perfect 3-0-0 record in group
play by defeating France 3-2 on Wednesday in what could be a
preview of the championship match. France, fielding mostly its
second team, gave up second-half goals to Frank de Boer and
Boudewijn Zenden before a joyous orange-clad home crowd at the
Amsterdam ArenA.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Germany, which turned out the second-worst
showing of Euro 2000 (ahead of only winless, goalless Denmark), was
eliminated from the group stage for the first time since 1984,
after a 3-0 loss Tuesday to a Portugal team missing nine starters.
Coach Erich Ribbeck, who inherited a substandard side after the
1998 World Cup team, promptly resigned Wednesday, as the German
press went into overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the soccer idiots of Europe! Germany is ashamed of
you!'' screeched the lead headline in Wednesday's Bild, a sports
daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Portugal meets upstart Turkey in Amsterdam, and
Italy takes on Romania in Brussels. On Sunday, Holland faces
Yugoslavia in Rotterdam, and Bruges, Belgium, hosts what should be
a classic between France and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep our feet firmly to the ground, despite the
euphoria we're feeling now,'' Spain's Alfonso said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
