<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPEC-OIL-ART-1000&AMP;ADD     06-21 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-OIL-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC AGREES TO 2.5 PERCENT INCREASE IN OUTPUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS and NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ In a grudging move to reign in soaring oil
prices, ministers at the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries decided Wednesday to increase their production limits by
about 708,000 barrels a day or 2.5 percent, beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The increase, OPEC's second in three months, is slightly higher
than had been expected. But analysts said it remains too modest to
bring down gasoline prices, which have reached more than $2 a
gallon in some parts of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Given that member countries are already overshooting their
official production quotas, analysts said that Wednesday's move
largely amounts to a ratification of existing practices.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, any increased production in crude oil
will take at least two months to work its way through the refining
system and will not reach gasoline pumps until after the summer
driving season is largely over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are officializing what they are already producing,'' said
Roger Diwan, an analyst at the Petroleum Finance Corp., an industry
consulting firm in Washington. ``It's the minimum that could have
been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, oil ministers meeting here went out of their way to
place much of the blame for high gasoline prices on regulations and
refining problems in the United States as well as extremely high
gasoline taxes across much of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``People in consuming countries point their finger at OPEC,''
complained Rilwanu Lukman, the organization's secretary-general.
``These people should tackle their own countries.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But many oil ministers have themselves been baffled by the
extent to which prices have remained high. One senior official here
complained that buying and selling in the petroleum markets has
caused unjustifiable price swings from as low as $24 to as high as
$33 since OPEC raised production at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Production has increased more than 2 million barrels a day since
the end of March, yet crude oil prices have rebounded and
inventories are still at their lowest levels in years.
</P>
<P>
   For all their caution, oil ministers meeting here displayed far
more solidarity than they did three months ago, when Iran angrily
rebelled against Saudi Arabian pressure to raise production by
about 7 percent, or a total of 1.7 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Iran on Wednesday signed on without any objections to the new
increase while also formally accepting the last one as well. By
avoiding a replay of the bitter rift in March, the OPEC ministers,
who control about 40 percent of the global supply of oil, easily
reached a consensus in one day.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Today everybody, I think, is of the opinion that an increase
was necessary,'' said Khelil Chakib, Algeria's oil minister, who
predicted that the price of crude oil would soon decline from more
than $30 a barrel to less than $28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was how big the increase should be,'' Chakib
added. ``I think this is about the right volume, because we have
got to consider manufacturers, the supply-demand behavior and the
growth of world consumption.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude reflects a significant change in the mindset
within OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As recently as three months ago, many producer countries were
still terrified that any increase in production would lead to a
catastrophic decline in prices similar to one in 1998, when oil
fell to $10 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   But when oil prices jumped back to more than $30 a barrel after
the last production increase, exporting countries became
increasingly more confident.
</P>
<P>
   As one official from a non-OPEC producing country remarked
Wednesday, ``When the price of crude on the market is $33,
everybody can afford to be friends.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, more countries now agree with Saudi Arabian
leaders that current prices are too high to be stable and would
over time cause economic slowdowns in consuming countries that
could hurt OPEC members by lowering global demand for their oil.
</P>
<P>
   World oil markets brushed off the production increase announced
Wednesday, sending prices up. Crude oil prices on the New York
Mercantile Exchange jumped about 2 percent or 72 cents to $31.37 a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC ministers essentially conceded Wednesday that they had
given up their plan for an ``automatic'' adjustment if oil prices
ranged outside a band of $22 to $28 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Member countries had agreed to the band in March, but when the
20-day average price of oil exceeded $28 a barrel two weeks ago,
the organization did not impose any increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about bands,'' Lukman told reporters after the oil
ministers adjourned their meeting. ``Focus on the fact that OPEC
wants a price of around $25 a barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC's influence on the global supply of oil is immense. It
plays a crucial role as a swing producer that can pump or withhold
additional oil.
</P>
<P>
   Many OPEC members are already at or near their own maximum
capacity. But the countries that still have extra capacity are
among its biggest producers: Saudi Arabia, which pumps about 8
million barrels a day; Kuwait, which pumps about 2 million barrels;
and the United Arab Emirates, which pumps about 2.2 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Iran, which produces about 3.6 million barrels a day, is
believed to be near maximum capacity. But Iran's oil minister,
Bijan Namdar Zangeneh, insisted Wednesday evening that his country
could meet its new quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough capacity,'' Sangeneh said at the start of the
minister's meeting. ``We can comply fully with our commitments
within OPEC.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A few important non-OPEC producers, mainly Mexico and Norway,
are expected to increase production as well. Both countries copied
the production cuts that OPEC members adopted in March 1999, which
helped prices more than triple to a high of $34, the highest in
nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Further non-OPEC production could add another 300,000 barrels of
oil a day, bringing the total supply of new oil to 600,000 or
700,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration greeted OPEC's
decision with cautious praise. The White House has kept a decidedly
low profile in the last few weeks, in sharp contrast to the
relentless and very public lobbying conducted by the secretary of
energy, Bill Richardson, before OPEC's meeting in March.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richardson's lobbying campaign, which included telephone calls
to OPEC ministers while they were meeting in Vienna, irritated many
countries and provoked especially loud denunciations from Iran
about ``external pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson expressed a measured endorsement of OPEC's decision
Wednesday, calling it ``a positive, though modest step that we hope
will lead to more stable oil markets and lower oil prices at the
pump.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary N. Ross, head of PIRA Energy, an energy consulting firm in
New York, was more skeptical and predicted that Wednesday's move
would do little to minimize U.S. motorists' anger, particularly in
the Midwest where gasoline prices have surpassed $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``World demand will go up by 1.5 million barrels a day in the
third quarter compared to the second quarter,'' Ross predicted here
Wednesday. ``So we are not going to get the supply to increase
stock-building. This is not going to make Al Gore or the U.S.
government very happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
