<SLUG> BC-CUBA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS DEBATE 
EASING CUBAN EMBARGO 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers moved closer Wednesday to easing the
40-year-old embargo against Cuba as support among farm state
Republicans and Democrats mounted for eliminating sanctions on food
and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders and Cuban-American lawmakers continued to
insist that a provision relaxing sanctions be rewritten to deny any
U.S. loans to Fidel Castro's communist regime that could be used to
purchase food or medicine from U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart of Florida and other anti-Castro
Republicans said they wanted language that would allow ``cash
only'' deals between U.S. companies and Havana on the sale of
agriculture goods and medical supplies. They also want a
prohibition of the import of Cuban goods to the United States. The
provision is included in the 2000 agriculture appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. agriculture interests contend that potentially billions of
dollars in U.S. sales to Cuba could be jeopardized if the Cuban
government is denied access to U.S. banks to help pay for
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting off all access to U.S. credits and loans would
basically make the lifting of these sanctions meaningless,'' said
one farm state lobbyist who was instrumental in helping to get
language placed in the agriculture bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba is not exactly the kind of country that has a lot of
cash-on-hand,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   However, critics of relaxing the embargo point out that Cuba is
unlikely to increase its import of food even if the sanctions are
lifted. They argue that easing the restrictions would force Castro
to loosen his control over the economy to accommodate private
investors who may be concerned about the Cuban government
interfering with their business activities.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the language in the agriculture bill would be the
most significant change in trade sanctions against Cuba since they
were imposed nearly 41 years ago when Castro came to power.
</P>
<P>
   The provision would also ease the embargoes on food and medicine
in place against North Korea, Libya, Iran and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders, including Majority Leader Dick Armey
and Majority Whip Tom DeLay, both of Texas, remain strongly opposed
to any change in the embargo. Along with House Speaker Dennis
Hastert of Illinois, they have tried since May to figure out how to
strip the Cuba language out of the agriculture bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Michelle Davis, Armey's press secretary, said Tuesday that
the leadership is now resigned to the fact there is growing support
within Congress for changing the policy toward Cuba. She said the
leadership is now trying to help negotiate a compromise that will
be acceptable to both Cuban-American and farm state members of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens in the negotiations, however, she
said the agriculture bill would likely be brought to the floor next
week for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the only question is what kind of language will be in
it?'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   If a compromise cannot be reached in the coming days, there
could be a floor fight over the issue. But opponents of lifting the
embargo would likely lose that showdown, given the fact that
support for lifting the sanctions has grown in both the House and
Senate. The Senate passed an anti-sanctions bill last year but it
died after the House failed to consider it. This year, the Senate
Foreign Relations and Appropriations committees have already
approved measures that would greatly ease the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY  &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
