<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1042 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-WATER-1STLD-     06-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-WATER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORBITER SPOTS SIGNS OF A RECENT FLOW OF WATER ON MARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A spacecraft orbiting Mars has sighted grooved
surface features suggesting a relatively recent water flow on the
planet, a finding that could redirect efforts to find evidence of
past or present life there, experts said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Mars Global Surveyor, which has been conducting
photographic surveys of the planet for more than two years, has
spotted evidence of liquid water at, or near, the surface that
could have flowed a few hundreds or thousands of years ago, a
billion years later than previous estimates, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration scheduled a
news conference for Thursday to discuss the findings after a day of
speculation about the discovery in the news media. A paper
describing the observations is to be published next week in the
journal Science, but the journal's editors decided to release the
information on Thursday because of the interest in the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Neither NASA nor the authors of the report, including Dr.
Michael C. Malin and Dr. Ken Edgett of Malin Space Science Systems
of San Diego, would disclose details of the study. But people
familiar with the report said high resolution pictures from Global
Surveyor clearly show channels and grooves on the steep, inside
walls of craters that indicate the downward flow of liquid water.
</P>
<P>
   These surface features appear to be evidence of water in the
upper crust of Mars that has seeped through and run down the
channels, said two experts familiar with the report who spoke on
the condition that they not be named. Contrary to speculation about
the findings, there is no clear evidence of standing pools of water
or gushing springs on Mars, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current climate of Mars would cause surface water to
instantly freeze and vaporize into the atmosphere,'' one expert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Water is crucial to plans for exploring Mars with robot
spacecraft to find evidence of life, and for possible visits by
humans. The United States has ambitious Mars exploration plans that
focus on finding water. Those plans are being revised after the
failure of two spacecrafts last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward J. Weiler, NASA's chief scientist, said future
orbiting and surface craft would search for water and the life it
can sustain. ``To find life on Mars, you have to follow the
water,'' Weiler has said. ``Without water, there was no life as we
know it in the past, and there is no life now. It's all about the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Future spacecraft would be directed to areas where there is a
high probablility of finding water. Data from orbiters and landing
craft would help researchers home in on those areas.
</P>
<P>
   Water on Mars would also make human visits more likely and
economical, experts said, because astronauts could drink it, and it
could be broken down into oxygen to breathe and hydrogen to fuel
rockets and generators.
</P>
<P>
   Water has already been detected on Mars in the form of ice
trapped at the poles, but until now no evidence of it had been seen
elsewhere. Because of the planet's extreme temperatures, with
average surface temperatures of minus 60 degrees Fahrenheit, and an
atmospheric pressure less than 1 percent that of Earth's, liquid
water would not exist long on the surface before breaking down in
the thin air and drifting into space.
</P>
<P>
   But there is ample evidence of flowing water long ago on the
planet, including channels and canyons formed by flowing rivers
millions of years ago and indications of upswelling ground waters.
And last year, scientists at Brown University said that they found
evidence in Global Surveyor pictures, which are more than 20 times
more detailed than any previous photographs, of a giant ocean that
once existed in the northern lowlands.
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing aspect of the newest findings is the possibility
of water near the surface, instead of miles below as some have
theorized. If water is a few feet below the surface, as early
characterizations of the new data suggest, landing crafts could
drill down to reach it, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Victor R. Baker, a hydrology expert and planetary scientist
at the University of Arizona, said that if there was evidence of
active water seepage in the new data, it would have wide
implications. Baker, who had not seen the report, said that if
water still flowed on Mars and escaped to the surface, it would
need an underground heat source to keep it thawed and provide the
energy necessary to force it to the surface. So far, no evidence of
active volcanic or thermal activity has been found on the planet,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
   If water was flowing on Mars, he said, it would produce a cloud
of vapor, as it dissipated under current surface conditions, that
spacecraft instruments should be able to detect from orbit. ``It
should be fairly easy to confirm if there is major seepage going on
now,'' Baker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
