<HEADLINE>
MOST TEXANS IN POLL STILL 
SUPPORT DEATH PENALTY 

</HEADLINE>
 POLL-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More than half of Texans believe innocent people
have been executed, but the vast majority of them continue to
support the use of the death penalty, a new poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Scripps Howard Texas Poll also found that even greater
numbers of Texans favor a moratorium on executions in cases that
might be affected by DNA testing and think felons should have the
right to obtain free testing of genetic material to prove their
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 1,000 adults was conducted between May 22
and June 16. Although the Texas Poll has looked at the death
penalty in the past, this was the first time questions were asked
about executing an innocent person or DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are similar to those being raised across the
nation as Texas' use of capital punishment comes under scrutiny,
due largely to Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he believes every one of the 134 people executed
during his 5 1/2 years in office was guilty. He reiterated that
Wednesday while campaigning in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, there has not been one innocent
person executed since I've been the governor,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Texans do not necessarily agree. Fifty-seven
percent of those surveyed said they believe Texas has executed
someone who was innocent of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, 73 percent said they support the continued use of
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The support is statistically the same as a year ago, but up 5
percentage points from February 1998. That 68 percent approval
rating was the lowest Texans have given the death penalty since
1988, according to the Texas Poll. It came after the highly
publicized execution of Karla Faye Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty support peaked in 1988 and again in 1994, when 86
percent of Texans said they agreed with it.
</P>
<P>
   Support of the death penalty among Texans varies significantly
among racial and ethnic groups, according to the poll. Survey
results show that while 81 percent of Anglos back capital
punishment, support drops to 55 percent among Hispanics and 44
percent among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether they thought Texas had ever executed an
innocent person, 71 percent of African-Americans said they believed
that to be the case. Only 55 percent of Anglos and 54 percent of
Hispanics believe someone innocent has been executed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Nearly 9 out of 10 Texans said they believe inmates should have
the right to obtain free DNA testing to try to prove their
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Three out of four respondents said the state should declare a
moratorium on death sentences in cases that might be affected by
DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Scripps Howard Data Center said its poll has a margin of
error of plus or minus 3 percentage points, meaning the results can
vary in either direction by that much. The margin of error is
slightly higher when poll results are broken down into smaller
categories such as race and ethnicity, according to the data
center. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
