<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CONGO-OAU-510&AMP;ADD-NYT     06-21 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-OAU-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO LEADER SHUTS DOWN AFRICA MEDIATION EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Laurent Kabila of Congo said
Wednesday that he was shutting down an effort by the Organization
of African Unity to open a political discourse among warring
factions in Congo and banning the coup's mediator because he had
openly criticized the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Kinshasa offices of the mediator, Sir Ketumile Masire, a
former president of Botswana, were sealed and his staff dispersed,
Kabila said. The move sets back hopes in the Security Council that
a political discussion among the Congo factions could take place
simultaneously with efforts to disarm them and prepare the way for
a United Nations peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department called Kabila's actions a ``clear
violation'' of a 1999 peace agreement and said that they
``undermine prospects for regional peace and development.'' It
called on Congo to permit the immediate reopening of the office and
to cooperate fully with the effort to start a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila made his statements in a telephone interview from
Kinshasa, the country's capital. While he was critical of the
efforts to start talks to end the civil war, Kabila was
surprisingly hopeful that he and President Paul Kagame of Rwanda _
allies until the Rwandans invaded Congo in 1998 _ could work out a
peace deal between them. Eleven days ago, the two men met for the
first time in more than two years at the Kenyan hill town of
Eldoret.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mr. Kagame I think we can find a solution to the problem
of the war,'' Kabila said. ``If he's serious. If he will recognize
the mistakes he made by invading the Congo. He seems to have
interest in really discussing peace with us. This was my
impression. I believe he was sincere. But we shall see.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila was dismissive, however, of President Yoweri Museveni of
Uganda, whose troops are also part of the conflict in Congo. He
said the Ugandans had no higher aim than to loot the country.
</P>
<P>
   The current phase of fighting in Congo began a year after
Kabila, with Rwanda's help, took power in 1997 after leading a
rebellion that overthrew Mobutu Sese Seko, whose long dictatorship
had bled the country dry. Since then, fighting has involved the
armies of six African nations and several rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
   In talking about Masire's ill-fated political mission, Kabila
showed his abiding irritation with South Africa, which he said has
long been a friend of his enemies. It was a remark that Masire made
on a South African radio program that incensed the Congolese more
than anything, the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His statement, openly on South African Broadcasting Corp.,
that he will go with the internal dialogue with or without Kabila _
that created the maximum point of discord,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila said he had written to the Organization of African Unity
asking it to find a replacement for Masire who would be impartial
and, moreover, could speak French. The organization is responsible
under the 1999 Lusaka peace accord on Congo for providing a
``facilitator'' for political talks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Masire made speeches everywhere against the government,''
Kabila said in the interview, which was arranged through his
American public relations adviser, John Aycoth, who was in
Kinshasa. ``He has an agenda very, very contrary to what we have
been believing he would be. We have decided that never will he be
accepted here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila said, however, that he had no problems with United
Nations officials in Kinshasa. He explained a mob attack last week
on the United Nations headquarters in Congo as the work of
disaffected easterners displaced by war who had heard about
fighting in the eastern city of Kisangani and thought the United
Nations should be doing something about it. United Nations
officials said they saw the attack as a reminder of how volatile
Congo is and how bad Kabila's relations with the outside world have
generally been.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a group of Security Council members, led by
Ambassador Richard C. Holbrooke of the United States, visited Congo
as fighting between Ugandans and Rwandans flared in Kisangani. The
ambassadors negotiated a promise from both the Rwandan and Ugandan
leaders to withdraw their troops from Kisangani, creating a neutral
city of about three million people where the United Nations could
deploy its first peacekeepers _ and perhaps find a base for the
discussion everyone hoped would soon begin.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila said he had no objections to the plan as long as his
government's sovereignty over Kisangani was recognized. But he
asked why the United Nations was thinking of sending a South
African battalion to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need other troops we can not suspect of being friends to
the aggressor,'' he said. ``That is the problem with the South
Africans. The South Africans have been assisting the other side
since the beginning of the war. I think the world is very wide. Why
can't they find other troops?''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila was skeptical about reports that Ugandans and Rwandans
were withdrawing from Kisangani, which would make a United Nations
move into the town more urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United States and Congo remain cool.
Kabila accused Washington of blocking disbursements from a $50
million World Bank trust fund, even if the money were to go
strictly to nongovernmental agencies in Congo. The United States
has not contributed to the fund, which was set up late in 1997,
more than six months after Kabila rose to power.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Kabila repeated his complaints that United States
support for the Rwandan president, Kagame, has prolonged Rwanda's
war in Congo, which began in 1998, ostensibly to pursue ethnic Hutu
militias that had carried out genocidal attacks in Rwanda in 1994.
Rwanda says that Congo is not doing enough to deal with this
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the State Department during the two years was not
supporting Kagame and Museveni, I think we would be talking peace
now _ and reconstruction,'' Kabila said. ``From the beginning we
wanted to have good relations with the United States. We thought
the United States will support us after the liberation, to
democratize the country, to reconstruct the country. We didn't
understand that a few people there had decided to support the
aggressors, and abandon the Congolese people. They give all the
money to Uganda and to Rwanda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
