u i BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-350&AMP;ADD-     06-21 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MEDIA EXECUTIVE, FREED FROM JAIL, FEELS NEW PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Gazprom, Russia's biggest company, began a campaign of
pressure Wednesday against the owner of the nation's largest
independent media conglomerate, demanding that his company repay a
large debt.
</P>
<P>
   The move came a week after Vladimir Gusinsky, the media tycoon,
was jailed on charges of embezzlement. He was released pending
trial. But he has expressed concern that he will face more
pressure, and President Vladimir Putin has called on Gazprom, a
financial supporter, to take a tough stand toward Gusinsky's
company.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom, the world's largest natural gas company, on Wednesday
seemed to confirm Gusinsky's fears. It said it would insist that
his company, Media-Most, make good on a large loan that Gazprom
guaranteed, which would subject Gusinsky's company to serious
economic pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The $211 million loan from Credit Suisse First Boston was
payable in March. Gusinsky put up 20 percent of his company as
collateral, and Gazprom paid the loan and now insists that he
settle the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was freed from jail after complaints from Russian
businessmen, politicians and journalists. Now the government, which
is Gazprom's main shareholder, appears to be looking for his weak
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the money first and foremost,'' said Alfred Kokh,
general director of Gazprom Media, a subsidiary that manages the
company's media assets. ``We haven't taken the collateral yet, and
we aren't sure that we want it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Gazprom has tried to pressure
Gusinsky. Earlier this year, Gazprom's chief executive, Rem
Vyakhirev, called for Media-Most to take a more pro-government
stance in covering the war in Chechnya, saying the critical
coverage gave Gazprom serious reason to reconsider extending
financial support.
</P>
<P>
   The government has indicated that Gazprom should halt financial
support to Media-Most. Putin, on an official visit to Europe last
week, wondered aloud why Gazprom ``should spend money on this.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Sergei Dubinin, deputy chairman of Gazprom,
indicated the company should get out of side businesses like media.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gusinsky's company has vulnerabilities. Media-Most is heavily in
debt to Gazprom, which now holds 14 percent of the company. But
because it paid the past loan, and is liable for a future loan,
Gazprom stands to own 54 percent _ a majority _ of Media-Most
stock, according to Kokh of Gazprom Media. Media-Most says the
figure is less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most is looking for a foreign investor who could help ease
the pressure from Gazprom. Media-Most's main television network,
NTV, holds about a third of Russia's television advertising market,
which totaled about $150 million last year. Still, the company ran
into a cash crunch after the 1998 financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Media-Most says it is worth $2 billion. Gazprom says the amount
is far less. ``This is a big fight over the valuation of his
companies and what he's prepared to give up,'' one market insider
said of Gusinsky. ``If his valuation is really that high, then why
doesn't he just extinguish the loan?''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Gazprom has guaranteed about $400 million in loans to
Gusinsky's company. The next loan matures in a year.
</P>
<P>
   In a live television broadcast on Tuesday, Gusinsky said his
company is not in danger of losing assets. But more pushing from
Gazprom will stretch its finances and hurt its chances of finding a
foreign investor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
