<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1054 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-CUBA-TRADE-SPI &LR;      06-21 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE CLOSE TO LIFTING SANCTIONS AGAINST CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House is on the verge of allowing food and
medicine to be sent to Cuba for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   As sponsor of the controversial provision aimed at helping
struggling farmers by opening new markets, Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., is tantalizingly close to a hard-won victory. He and
others are confident it will happen, but the complexities and
political delicacy of the situation mean it could be a week or more
away, and there is a slight chance it still could fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt has had to navigate the ferocious and emotional
cross-currents inside the House that accompany questions involving
Cuba and U.S. relations. In doing so he has irritated both the
House leadership and the Cuban American National Foundation, an
anti-Castro group with deep pockets, vast influence in Washington
and a long memory.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt's provision would remove barriers that have prevented
shipments of food and medicine to Iran, Libya, Sudan and North
Korea as well as Cuba, because those countries have been deemed
hostile to U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for the change, Nethercutt points out that the
sanctions have locked U.S. farmers and businesses out of markets
that are actively pursued by Canada, the European Union, South
America and other U.S. trading competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sanctions against Cuba were imposed in 1961, Cuba was
a huge market for Washington state crops, and was the top importer
of Washington dry peas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States stands alone in prohibiting sales of the
most basic humanitarian goods to these countries, leading to $1
billion in lost economic activity in rural America,'' Nethercutt
wrote in a column last month in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our farmers suffer from lost sales, but these sanctioned
countries freely purchase an estimated $7 billion of agricultural
commodities from our allies around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue carries major political implications for Nethercutt,
who is considered one of the most vulnerable incumbents in the
House. A win would be good news for farmers, which would translate
into good political news for Nethercutt. Agriculture is a major
industry in his district and opening markets to their commodities
is a major litmus test in November.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing his bill, Nethercutt has butted heads with powerful
leaders of his own party, absorbed bruising attack ads aired in his
Spokane district, and been doubted by his allies. He has had to
endure weeks of tough negotiations and posturing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, aides to Nethercutt and his allies in the
House say an agreement is imminent. The provision is likely to be
added to the agriculture-spending bill that the House is scheduled
to consider next week. Though no final agreement has been reached,
negotiators have narrowed their differences and believe a
resolution can be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe both sides are very hopeful for a positive
resolution,'' said Nethercutt's chief of staff Jim Dornan.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, who is
Nethercutt's most formidable opponent and a strident critic of
Cuban President Fidel Castro, offered a more cautious assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no agreement yet, either tentative or firm,'' said
spokesman Jonathan Baron. ``In matters like these, details matter
most and those details are still under discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest unresolved question concerns financing for
purchases. DeLay and his supporters insist that any sale to Cuba be
cash-only to preclude the possibility that U.S. tax dollars or tax
credits could be used to help an adversary. Nethercutt is willing
to include such a stipulation, but finding acceptable wording has
been difficult. DeLay is demanding wording that is ``air tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Nethercutt, however, are confident the problem can be
solved. And they point out that, after coming so far, it is a
relatively small matter.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt pulled together a unique coalition of farm-state
Republicans and Democrats sympathetic to human rights advocates who
believe liberalizing trade with Cuba is in the best interest of
both countries. Nethercutt says nearly 300 lawmakers in the House
support lifting sanctions if the GOP leadership would allow it to
come to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   His cause got a boost from the Elian Gonzalez case, which
improved Cuba's perception among the U.S. public, according to
polls. It also was helped earlier this spring when the House voted
to normalize trade with China, like Cuba a totalitarian country
that was once an adversary of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, negotiations are at such a fragile stage that
Nethercutt declined interview requests. In comments last month,
however, he laid out an argument that has proved effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logic is straightforward: support American farmers and
American values by allowing the export of food and medicine to
currently sanctioned countries,'' Nethercutt said in the New York
Times column. ``The amendment merely allows sanctioned states to
buy food and medicine on a commercial basis, nothing more. If a
normal trading relationship with China is a home run for America,
then lifting these sanctions is the equivalent of a grand slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone sees it that way. DeLay remains an ardent,
entrenched opponent. So do House members from South Florida and
especially the Cuban American National Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cardenas, director of the foundation's Washington office,
vows to punish Nethercutt if the sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they (the GOP leaders) going to allow a backbencher to
decide what legislation reaches the floor and what doesn't?''
Cardenas said in an interview. ``I'm not saying George Nethercutt
has to be crushed like a bug, but (House Majority Leader Dick)
Armey and Mr. DeLay have to maintain party discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the threat, the foundation began airing ads last
week in Nethercutt's district. The 30-second ads, titled
``Dictatorship,'' don't mention Nethercutt by name but condemn
Castro for allegedly allowing forced child labor and child
prostitution, sponsoring international terrorism and imprisoning
political dissidents. ``Lifting America's embargo on Cuba will
strengthen Castro and help the abuses continue,'' the ad says.
``The embargo is right ... because the abuses are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas would not disclose how much the ad campaign costs, but
he said the organization was prepared ``to spend whatever it
takes'' to publicize their opposition and Nethercutt's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Also watching closely are constituents such as Cary Janson, a
farmer in the Palouse who lives about as far from Cuba and
Washington, D.C. as you can get and still have an address in the
continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   For hard-pressed farmers like Janson who are coping with
historically low commodity prices and overproduction, the
opportunity to sell crops to five hungry news countries is reason
to cheer, even if one of those nations is governed by one of the
world's last Communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a record number of farmers going broke, it's kind of
comical that the government will lock us out of these markets,''
said Janson, a fourth-generation farmer who says he ``was raised to
feed people.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his farming neighbors, Janson is particularly
galled by the sanction against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a huge consumer of dry peas 90 miles off the coast of
the U.S. and all the market is going to Canada,'' said Janson, who
grows peas, lentils and wheat on 2,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   He is also the kind of voter Nethercutt needs if he is to win a
fourth term. But while Janson is fond of Nethercutt and has voted
for him in the past, Janson is approaching the election with an
open mind.
</P>
<P>
   And he offers some advice that Nethercutt is sure to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, he says, ``has kind of turned their back on us. ...
But if (Nethercutt) wins this one, he's got my vote back for
sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
