<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Insurer to Compensate Blacks Who Paid Too Much
</P>
<P>
   After decades of paying higher premiums for life insurance than
white customers, nearly five million black customers and their
families nationwide are going to be compensated in a settlement
reached with American General, one of the nation's biggest
insurers. The company said that it was making restitution of $206
million, mainly to the black customers and their heirs who, until
as recently as April, paid as much as 33 percent more than white
customers for small policies intended to cover burial expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments to Buy a Rival
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments said it would acquire Burr-Brown, which is
also a computer chip maker, for $7.6 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Stock Prices Rally as Bonds Fall
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft helped propel the Dow Jones industrial average and the
Nasdaq composite index higher. The Nasdaq composite index rose
50.65 points, or 1.3 percent, to 4,064.01. The Dow Jones industrial
average gained 62.58 points, or 0.6 percent, to 10,497.74, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index increased 3.18 points, to
1,479.13. Bond prices fell sharply, with the yield on the 30-year
issue rising to 5.96 percent from 5.89 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Uranium Enrichment Plant to Close
</P>
<P>
   The United States Enrichment Corp., the private company that
runs the nation's only two uranium enrichment plants, said it would
close one of them in a year, in Portsmouth, Ohio, because of high
costs and a depressed market for reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Money Manager Is Suspended
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have suspended and fined the former owner of Founders
Asset Management, which manages more than $8 billion, for failing
to disclose that some of the firm's clients paid excessive
commissions on stock trades in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   A New Standard for Internet Privacy
</P>
<P>
   Major Internet companies and the World Wide Web's
standard-setting body introduced long-awaited technology that would
alert computer users before they visited Web sites that collect
more personal information than they are willing to share. The new
standard was denounced by some privacy advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters Take Control of Nike Site
</P>
<P>
   Protesters took control of the Nike Web site and redirected
visitors to a site urging organizations to gather at and disrupt a
world economic summit later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments Shuffles Staff
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, which manages nearly $1 trillion, shuffled
its top executives and reorganized into three units headed by three
vice chairmen. James C. Curvey, 65, president and chief operating
officer, is leaving both posts and returning to his previous job at
the firm. He will remain a vice chairman. Robert Reynolds, 48, will
replace Curvey as chief operating officer and will also be a vice
chairman. Robert Pozen, 53, president of FMR, also will be a vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel Sentenced in Germany
</P>
<P>
   A German court sentenced Martin Frankel, the American financier,
to three years in prison for failing to pay custom taxes on
smuggled diamonds and carrying false passports.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring Shares Climb 35 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Handspring rose 35 percent in their first day of
trading after raising $200 million in an initial offering that
showed investors' enthusiasm for companies that make increasingly
popular hand-held computers.
</P>
<P>
   35 Years Later, Hiring Bias Remains
</P>
<P>
   More than three decades after the passage of the Civil Rights
Act, there is abundant evidence that it did much to improve job
prospects for blacks. But bias still persists, and policies aimed
at reducing discrimination would be sharper if they concentrated
more on opening opportunities than on redressing the grievances of
dismissed workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
