<SLUG> BC-SECRET6-21-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Secrets Of Success By Michael Bauer  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The An family have made their reputation on crab,
probably the best in San Francisco, and on garlic noodles prepared
in a separate kitchen by Helene An or one of her children.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their empire started at Thanh Long and has expanded to
Crustacean in San Francisco and a wildly popular branch in Beverly
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, people don't know what they're missing when they
head straight to the crab. One of the best starters around is the
Lemongrass Beef Skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Thin slices of beef are marinated twice, first in pineapple
juice and then in soy sauce, shrimp paste, lemongrass and toasted
sesame seeds. This marinade also is brushed on during grilling,
which adds even more character to the meat.
</P>
<P>
   At home you can make a meal of these wonderful appetizers, or
serve them before a grilled main course.
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1998, the family remodeled Thanh Long, adding more seats
and sprucing up the interior with restful murals, comfortable
chairs and banquettes. Cloths drape each table, and there's a wine
list that has some interesting selections to accompany the crab, as
well as other Asian-inspired dishes like the Lemongrass Beef
Skewers.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Thanh Long, 4101 Judah St. (at 46th Avenue), San Francisco; &LR; 
 &LR; (415) 665-1146. Dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bauer is The Chronicle's food editor. He is the author
of the recently published ``The Secrets of Success Cookbook:
Signature Recipes and Insider Tips From San Francisco's Best
Restaurants'' (Chronicle Books).
</P>
<P>
   SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tenderizing with pineapple. &LR;  This juice has an enzyme that
works as a natural tenderizer for the beef.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A second marinade. &LR;  Garlic, onion, soy sauce and fish sauce
form the base for an additional marinade. It's also used to keep
the beef moist during grilling.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; LEMONGRASS BEEF SKEWERS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds beef sirloin tips, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pineapple juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon shrimp paste (see Notes)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons powdered lemongrass root (see Notes)
</P>
<P>
   Bamboo skewers
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Toss the beef, pineapple juice and 2 tablespoons of the
vegetable oil in a large bowl. Cover and refrigerate for at least
30 minutes and up to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 1 tablespoon oil in a medium skillet over
medium heat. Add the onion and garlic and saute until tender, about
5 minutes. Stir in the soy sauce, sesame seeds, fish sauce, shrimp
paste, minced lemongrass and lemongrass powder. Bring to a boil.
Add to the bowl with the beef and toss to combine. Cover and
refrigerate for at least 30 minutes and up to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a grill (medium heat).
</P>
<P>
   Remove the beef from the marinade. Reserve marinade. Thread one
slice of beef on each skewer. Grill the beef until cooked through,
brushing occasionally with the reserved marinade during the first
part of cooking, about 2 to 3 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Notes: &LR;  Shrimp paste is available in Asian markets. To make it
at home, mash cooked shrimp with a small amount of water. Powdered
lemongrass root also is available in Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 185 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 0 carbohydrate, 7 &LR; 
 &LR; g fat (3 g saturated), 83 mg cholesterol, 79 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
