<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Wine Potpourri  
 Stupid Wine Gizmos  
 By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 SAN FRANCISCO  _ Late-night television viewers know all about
stupid pet tricks. David Letterman, the gap-toothed perennial
freshman, parades out a string of goofy humans and innocent animals
that proceed to embarrass everyone except their owners.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since this is a full-service wine column, Potpourri presents
Stupid Wine Tools, which are not exactly tricks, but if you fork
out good money for one of these tchotchkes, you might feel like
you've been tricked.
</P>
<P>
   Wine gadgets have been around for a long time. Who can forget
the Wine Crystal, a piece of cut glass, suspended from a faux-gold
chain that had a small hook on one end. Supposedly, if you dropped
the crystal into a glass of wine, securing it to the rim of the
glass with the hook, the wine would miraculously improve. It was a
sort of high-tech wine silk-purse-from-a-sow's-ear Stupid Wine Tool
(SWT).
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was pyramid power. Place a case of young wine under
a pyramid and faster than you could say Tutankhamen, the wine was
transformed into an aged treasure. Trader Vic, who placed wine
under a pyramid in his San Francisco restaurant many years ago, was
not immune to the lure of SWTs.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes The Deja Vu Wine Bottle Restoration Kit. This
unbelievably wasteful product stretches the limits of SWT.
</P>
<P>
   In a box too large for the meager contents lie the materials
needed to ``restore'' 12 bottles ``of rare vintages for display.''
Included are corks (not wine corks), cheesy-looking labels,
capsules and a small bottle of Deja Vu Extract. After washing out
the bottles, you fill them with water and add a few drops of the
extract ``to imitate the color of red wine,'' then cork the bottle,
put a capsule in place and paste on the label. All of this for the
extraordinary price of $34.95!
</P>
<P>
   Or, what about Scotch Rocks? OK, this example of excess out of
Scotland is more accurately a Stupid Spirits Tool (SST), but I
couldn't pass it up.
</P>
<P>
   Scotch Rocks is a box of 10 trays, each containing four
compartments filled with water from the Chapeltown Glenlivet Spring
in the Scottish Highlands. The ready-to-freeze trays are sealed at
the source. Single malt whisky distillers claim that their whisky
tastes best with a splash of pure water from the source at the
distillery.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, this Scottish tchotchke will cost you $8 a box,
including the Douglas clan blue-and-green tartan wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   I've likely missed some real jewels, favorites of wine drinkers
everywhere. If you have a favorite Stupid Wine Tool, let me know by
e-mail at  &LR; food &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Corks and Screw Caps &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Now that some of the dust has settled surrounding the expensive
Napa Valley red wine in a screw-cap bottle, I'd like to add my two
cents.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of background for those who haven't heard: Plump Jack
Winery, owned by Getty P &LR; e &LR; re&AMP;Fils and San Francisco Supervisor
Gavin Newsom, recently released 150 cases of its 1997 Reserve
Cabernet Sauvignon in bottles with a screw-cap closures.
</P>
<P>
   According to Newsom, the owners were tired of Plump Jack
customers complaining about corked wines. A corked wine is tainted
with a nasty-smelling chemical that is believed to come from the
cork-washing process or possibly occurs during bottling. Screw
caps, say the Plump Jack people, do not cause the corky problem.
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, the chemical causing the corky problem has
been found in bottled water with screw tops, as well as in other
beverages, including orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the gutsy move by Plump Jack Winery is
admirable. You could even say, it's about time somebody did it. But
the initial announcement was made at the Napa Valley Wine Auction,
not the place you're likely to see wine in screw-cap bottles.
Subsequent announcements were splashed all over the local media,
including two earlier mentions in The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   But what kind of a commitment is Plump Jack Winery making with
just 150 cases of wine?
</P>
<P>
   For years, the wine industry has been urging members to stop
closing bottles of inexpensive wine with a cork, a natural product
that eventually could become scarce. These wines normally are
consumed within a few days of purchase and not intended to age,
which is the sole reason for sealing a bottle of red wine with a
natural cork.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus needed to get the California wine industry moving
toward screw-cap closures for some wines is to have a large winery
like Gallo screwing caps on its inexpensive Zinfandel. Or to have
Kendall-Jackson putting screw tops on its popular Chardonnay. Or
Robert Mondavi can set the example with a screw-cap closure on his
Fum &LR; e &LR;  Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   A paltry 150 cases of a $135-red wine in a screw-cap bottle is a
publicity stunt, not an industry-leading statement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beringer Cooperage &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the highest costs of making wine is in cooperage, the oak
barrels and tanks that are essential for aging most red and some
white wines. French oak barrels cost about $650 each; American oak
barrels, a relative bargain, cost about $400 each.
</P>
<P>
   To help control these prices while enhancing wine quality,
Beringer Wine Estates will develop an in-house cooperage to supply
a portion of the increasing need for wine barrels. Heading up the
new cooperage is Master Cooper Keith Roberts, formerly general
manager at Mendocino Cooperage.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who expects to start producing barrels in time for the
2001 harvest, believes that cooperage is a winemaker-driven
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope, ultimately,'' he says, ``is to tailor-make our
barrels to the winemaker's specification for a particular wine.''
</P>
<P>
   The new cooperage will produce barrels only for Beringer Estates
wineries: Beringer Vineyards, Chateau Souverain, Chateau St. Jean,
Meridian Vineyards, Stags' Leap Winery and St. Clement Vineyards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
