<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKINGCOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKINGCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   The Working Cook  
 By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Bagged Shredded Vegetables Can Save a Cook's Bacon 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO &LR;  _ Because one can only eat so many chicken
breasts in a lifetime, I'm always looking for new varieties of
fast-cooking protein.
</P>
<P>
   Smoked tofu was new territory for me, but now I'm a convert _
and so are many of my colleagues on the Food staff. It has a
pleasant texture &QL; 
similar to the Indian cheese &LR;   &LR; paneer, and is delicious when paired
with peanuts and eggs in the Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe, Fried Rice with
Spicy Tofu &AMP; Vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Fried rice is a great way to use up leftovers from last night's
takeout, but you don't need that excuse to make it. You can prepare
a batch of rice the night before and then chill it. Don't use
freshly cooked, warm rice, which will get mushy. Fluff the rice
with a fork before refrigerating it to prevent it from hardening
into food sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this recipe so quick is using prepared vegetables,
which seem to be in every market these days.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Waters would never approve, but these ready-to-use
vegetables certainly go in that wok nice and easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Roast Halibut with Potato Coins &AMP; Red Pepper Coulis also
calls for prepared vegetables _ in this case, jarred roasted red
bell peppers, which are transformed into a coulis to dab on the
fish.
</P>
<P>
   When you sear the fish, use high heat to get a crispy, golden
crust, which will contrast well with the piquant sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bean Chili with Pork &AMP; Tomatillos is a great
summertime chili with fresh corn and light, acidic flavors from
green chiles and tomatillos. The spice level is medium-hot, but
garnished with sour cream, it barely raises a sweat. Add more
serranos if you prefer more heat.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FAST &AMP; FRESH &QL; 
Dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   FRIED RICE WITH SPICY TOFU &AMP; VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Smoked tofu is available at health-food stores and in the
health-food section of many supermarkets. Wildwood brand makes a
``Mild Szechuan'' version that is great in this recipe. Preshredded
cabbage and carrots are available in the produce section of many
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound sugar snap peas
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 (6.5-ounce) package smoked tofu, preferably ``Mild Szechuan''
style
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chile oil
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces preshredded carrots
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces preshredded green cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cold cooked long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup salted roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mince the garlic, string the snap peas and slice the green
onions. Cut the tofu into 1/2-inch cubes. Set aside in small bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the soy sauce and chile oil in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the eggs in a medium bowl; season lightly with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Assemble all the ingredients near the stove. Heat 1 tablespoon
of the oil in a wok or large heavy skillet over medium-high heat.
Add the eggs and quickly scramble, breaking them into bite-size
pieces. Remove from the pan and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 2 tablespoons oil to the wok. Place over high
heat. When sizzling, add the garlic; cook and stir about 30
seconds. Stir in the snap peas, carrots and cabbage. Add the water
and stir-fry until the vegetables are crisp-tender, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rice and stir-fry until incorporated, about 1 minute.
Drizzle in the soy sauce mixture and stir into the rice.
</P>
<P>
   Add the egg, tofu and green onions. Stir-fry until the rice is
completely heated through. Stir in the peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 545 calories, &LR;   &LR; 23 g protein, 53 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 29 g fat (4 g saturated), 158 mg cholesterol, 933
mg sodium, 5 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   30-MINUTE &QL; 
MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   ROAST HALIBUT WITH POTATO COINS &AMP; RED PEPPER COULIS
</P>
<P>
   You will need a food processor for this recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound baby potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Four 7-ounce halibut fillets
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (7.25 ounces) prepared red bell peppers, at room
temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cream, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Handful Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450.
</P>
<P>
   Fill a medium pot about halfway full of water and place over
high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Thinly slice the potatoes into coins (about 1/8-inch thick). Put
them in the pot of water (make sure they are submerged) and bring
to a boil. Cook until the potatoes are tender but not mushy, about
3 to 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Season the fish with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large heavy oven-proof skillet. Add the olive oil and
heat until sizzling. Add the fish and sear until browned on one
side, about 3 minutes. Transfer to a plate.
</P>
<P>
   Discard most of the oil in the pan, leaving enough to coat the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the potatoes and place them in the pan. Season with salt
and pepper. Top with the fish, seared side up, then place in oven
and bake until fish flakes, 5 to 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, roughly chop peppers and transfer to a food
processor. Add the stock and cream. Puree until smooth. Transfer to
a small saucepan and slowly heat until just warmed through.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the fish over the potatoes with a spoonful of coulis on
top. Sprinkle with parsley and garnish with lemon wedges. Serve the
remaining sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 405 calories, &LR;   &LR; 44 g protein, 23 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 14 g fat (3 g saturated), 74 mg cholesterol, 118 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NOW &AMP; LATER &QL; 
Dinner this week &QL; 
&AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   BLACK BEAN CHILI WITH PORK &AMP; TOMATILLOS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried black beans
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh tomatillos, husked
</P>
<P>
   3 red onions
</P>
<P>
   Two 7-ounce cans green chiles
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 serrano chiles
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds boneless pork butt
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 quart chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   3 ears yellow corn
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400.
</P>
<P>
   Soak the beans overnight in a large pot of water, or do a quick
soak: Place beans in a large pot and cover with twice as much
water. Bring to a boil, then immediately cover and take off the
heat. Let sit for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, place the tomatillos in a lightly oiled roasting pan.
Roast until soft, 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the onions and green chiles into large dice. Mince the
garlic and serranos. If you don't want too much heat, seed the
chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pork into 1-inch cubes. Season to taste with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place a Dutch oven over medium-high heat, then add enough of the
remaining oil to cover the bottom of the pan. When the oil is hot,
add the meat (work in batches) and brown well on all sides. Remove
meat from the pan with a slotted spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Drain all but 1 tablespoon oil from the pan. Add the onions and
cook, scraping up the brown bits on the bottom of the pan. Saute
for 8 to 10 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Add the garlic and serranos; saute for a few minutes. Add the
canned chiles and the tomatillos, crushing the tomatillos into
chunks with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Add the meat and beans to the pot, then add the broth and 3 cups
water. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to a steady simmer and cook for
45 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add the extra cup of water as
needed to allow beans enough liquid to simmer freely.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off corn kernels with a sharp knife. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes, check the beans _ they should still be
somewhat firm. Add 2 teaspoons salt, then simmer until the beans
are tender, 15 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the beans are tender, add the corn kernels. Taste for
seasoning. Serve garnished with sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 355 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 38 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; g fat (g saturated), mg cholesterol, mg sodium, g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
