<HEADER>
A1066 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKDINER-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKDINER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Cook's Books  
 By Andy Lax  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 SAN FRANCISCO  _ When I was 5 years old, my parents took me on
vacation to Niagara Falls. For breakfast one morning, we went to a
diner that served only desserts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not one to question my parents, I studied the display cases full
of layer cakes, custards and pies before settling on a wedge of
coconut cream pie. This was the delicacy of Gilligan's Island and I
figured if it was good enough for the castaways, it was good enough
for me. I ate my breakfast in ecstasy. Little did I know I was
participating in a great American tradition _ pie for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diner Desserts,'' by Tish Boyle is a book about such
remembrances. While many cookbooks celebrate exotically flavored
creme brulees and towering souffles, ``Diner Desserts'' cuts
through all confectionery pretension and takes us back to our
childhood innocence. These are recipes that remind us of times when
the important decisions were who you would take to the junior prom
and whether you'd have the cherry pie or a hot fudge sundae.
</P>
<P>
   With a lifetime of diner eating and a diploma from Ecole de
Cuisine La Varenne in Paris, Boyle knows her stuff. After
``learning some of life's most important lessons in diners,'' she
says, she is well equipped not only to provide quality recipes but
to share the deep-rooted emotions and memories embodied by these
sweets.
</P>
<P>
   But to ensure that these memories don't end up in frustration
over tough pie crust and runny pudding, Boyle offers tips and clear
instructions. Armed with tidbits of diner history and personal
reminiscing, you can proceed with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The book is well organized and as sleek as the chrome that
glints from the black-and-white photographs of America's diners. It
begins with chapters on selecting the correct ingredients and the
proper equipment and then moves to the goods. The recipes range
from pies to cakes, puddings and doughnuts, and end with favorite
recipes from the soda fountain. While a recipe for root beer floats
may seem unnecessary, this one comes with words of wisdom on
selecting the right root beer.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I was just 5, I have never forgotten my first taste
of coconut cream pie, and Boyle's lives up to my expectations. The
pie crust tended to stick to the foil that weighted it during
baking but it still turned out tender and flaky. The custard is
updated with coconut milk, and is topped with swirls of barely
sweetened cream.
</P>
<P>
   Humble as it is, Chocolate Malt Pudding is a conversation topic.
Those who weren't pudding fans as kids may not be captivated, but
those who were will be transported back to family dinners in
Michigan and cafeteria lunches in Kansas. Though the chocolate
flavor is mild, the pudding is rich and the malt notes are warming.
</P>
<P>
   Buttermilk Doughnuts are a real hit. Dressed up with a simple
dredge of powdered sugar, they are exactly what doughnuts should
be. Deep-frying imparts a thin crust that shelters a dense interior
spiced with cinnamon and nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon meringue pie and chocolate layer cake may never make the
menu in temples of  &LR; haute cuisine &LR;  but they have already earned
their place as symbols of Americana. These are the recipes on which
we grew up, over which life's lessons were learned and memories
made. In ``Diner Desserts,'' Tish Boyle opens up an American
institution and provides us a way to bring the diner back home.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Diner Desserts,'' by Tish Boyle (Chronicle Books; 179 &LR; 
 &LR; pages; $18.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Andy Lax is a student at the California Culinary Academy.
</P>
<P>
   DINER-STYLE POWDERED BUTTERMILK DOUGHNUTS
</P>
<P>
   From Diner Desserts, by Tish Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   31/2 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   1 cup powdered sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: In a medium bowl, sift together the flour, baking
powder, baking soda, salt, cinnamon and nutmeg. Add the sugar and
stir the dry ingredients with a whisk until combined.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, whisk together the buttermilk, melted butter,
egg and vanilla until blended. Make a well in the center of the
flour mixture and pour the buttermilk mixture into it. Using a
rubber spatula, stir until the mixture forms a soft, moist dough.
</P>
<P>
   Dust a work surface with flour. Scrape the dough onto the work
surface and lightly sprinkle the top of the dough with flour.
Gather the dough into a ball and knead it gently 5 or 6 times, or
until smooth. Roll or pat the dough into a round roughly 10 inches
in diameter and 1/2 inch thick. Transfer the round to a baking
sheet, cover it with plastic wrap, and place it in the freezer for
15 minutes, or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Using a 3-inch doughnut cutter (or a 3-inch round biscuit cutter
and a 3/4-inch cutter or pastry tip for the hole), cut out 7
doughnuts and holes from the dough. Gather the scraps together,
reroll 1/2 inch thick, and cut out 3 more doughnuts and as many
holes as possible. Place the doughnuts and holes on a baking sheet
or 2 plates, cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate while heating
the oil for frying.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the oil into a deep-fat fryer or large straight-sided
saucepan to a depth of 2 to 3 inches. Heat the oil to 370. Line a
baking sheet with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Fry the doughnuts and holes in small batches, turning once, for
2 to 3 minutes, or until golden brown. Using a slotted spoon,
transfer to the paper towels to drain, then place on a wire rack to
cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   When the doughnuts and holes are completely cool, place the
powdered sugar in a medium bowl. Generously dredge the doughnuts
and holes in the sugar, shaking off the excess. Serve the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 doughnuts and about 16 doughnut holes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER DOUGHNUT: &LR;   &LR; 130 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 26 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 2 g fat (1 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 182 mg
sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PER HOLE: &LR;  45 calories, 1 g protein, 9 g carbohydrate, 1 g fat, &LR;   &LR; 5
mg cholesterol; 61 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
