<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-CHERR-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   At the Source  
 By Karol Saekel  
 c. 2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Sierra Foothills Cherries  
 SONORA, Calif.  _ In the Sierra Foothills, life is a bowl of
cherries for just a short time, but now is that time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last weekend saw the first cherry pickers head for the orchards
at Sierra Glen Ranch in Sonora. That's several weeks later than the
beginning of cherry season in the Central Valley, but at 3,500-foot
elevation, the seasons get condensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had a frost on May 9 this year,'' says Gaye Wolf,
who, with her husband, Don, owns the old ranch, which began as a
1861 stage coach stop on the Tuolumne County road linking Columbia
and Twain Harte.
</P>
<P>
   When the Wolfs came to Sierra Glen 15 years ago, the ranch's
orchards were filled with apple trees, the area's historic main
crop. But the Wolfs diversified, planting Christmas trees, berries,
pears and some stone fruit, including cherries _ sweet Bings and
Rainiers and tart Montmorencys. Now they have 30 acres of cherries
under cultivation.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfs originally intended the sour cherry trees to be
pollinators for the others. But they soon found there was a market
for the sour fruit itself, primarily in restaurant kitchens, but
also at Berkeley Bowl and Monterey Foods, two Berkeley markets
favored by produce connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bings and Rainiers are best eaten out of hand, the
Montmorencys need to be cooked. In Europe, they are favored in cold
summer fruit soups, in preserves and, lightly stewed, as a garnish
to seared foie gras. In America, they star in old-fashioned pies.
</P>
<P>
   Gaye Wolf bakes a lot of cherry pies in the roughly three weeks
the Montmorencys are around, mostly for the small shop on the
ranch. She offers both open, single-crust pies and _ her favorite _
a version with a sweet crumb topping made with flour, butter, sugar
and oatmeal. The oatmeal, she says, adds a pleasantly nutty flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of modern preferences, the ranch baker uses vegetable
shortening for her pie crusts _ ``no animal fat, unless somebody
special orders a pie made with butter'' _ and pastry flour, which
she says makes for superior texture. She sells her pies both whole
and by the slice.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can also purchase stone fruit and berries _ either
heading into the orchards to pick it themselves or already picked
for them. In addition, the little shop sells jams and jellies,
muffins, turnovers and cookies and, come fall, apple dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the sweet eating cherries are available. The sour
Montmorencys are usually about three weeks behind, but Don Wolf is
reluctant to commit to an exact date, except to hope that they'll
be ready by the July Fourth holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's heat wave quickened the ripening, but a cold spell
could slow things down. Sour cherries, it seems, are really sweet
on sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Sierra Glen Ranch, 15665 Big Hill Road, Sonora; (209)
532-2534. &LR;   &LR; From Highway 108 in Sonora, turn left on Phoenix Lake
Road; &LR;   &LR; after seven miles, turn left on Big Hill Road. The ranch is
two &LR;   &LR; miles down Big Hill Road. Bake shop and do-it-yourself
picking, &LR;   &LR; 7:30 a.m.-3 p.m. Monday- &LR;   &LR; Saturday until Labor Day.
After Labor Day, the shop is open 9 &LR;   &LR; a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesday-Sunday.
Old ranch house is also available &LR;   &LR; for rentals. For more
information, log on to &LR;  www.sierraglen.com &LR; . &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
