<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-MORALES-COLUMN-LA     06-21 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MORALES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARUM TALKS OF DE LA HOYA-MOSLEY REMATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although Oscar De La Hoya hinted at retirement
following his loss to ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley on Saturday, it
appears he has decided to continue his career.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter, said in a story in Wednesday's
Las Vegas Review-Journal that De La Hoya will fight a rematch with
Mosley, the new World Boxing Council welterweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   A rematch clause in the contracts for Saturday's fight said both
fighters would be guaranteed $10.1 million for a rematch, which
will take place in Las Vegas in November or February.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following Saturday's bout, De La Hoya gave Mosley
credit for the victory. However, after spending a good hour in his
dressing room, De La Hoya came out to a post-fight news conference
complaining about the decision.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt he no longer could get a fair decision because
of the politics in boxing. He also said he thought he won by one
point.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, I spoke with at least 35 veteran boxing writers
after the fight. Only one had De La Hoya winning, by one point.
Another had it a draw. The rest had Mosley winning by at least two
points, many of them by three, four and even five points.
</P>
<P>
   This reporter had Mosley by four points, 116-112.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely not retiring,'' Arum said. ``It was a
tremendous shock to him because he didn't expect to lose, and it
was a tremendous disappointment, but he's going to fight again.''
</P>
<P>
   The rematch could take place at the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   Arum also addressed an issue that long has been debated - should
Robert Alcazar remain in De La Hoya's corner as lead trainer? De La
Hoya previously has brought in well-known trainers Jesus Rivero,
Emanuel Steward and Gil Clancy to ``assist'' Alcazar.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the boxing world, Alcazar gets little respect. He is
considered a good trainer for amateur boxers, but lacking enough
skills to guide a world-class prize fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Alcazar) was back, the outcome would be the same,''
Arum said. ``You saw one guy (Mosley) adjust midway through the
fight, and you saw the other guy doing the same thing round after
round after round.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcazar could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet)It was March 21, 1963, one of the biggest, and
ultimately saddest, nights in L.A. boxing history. Three world
championship fights were on tap, and they would be contested at
beautiful Dodger Stadium, still in its sparkling infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimino ``Sugar'' Ramos of Cuba squared off with Davey Moore of
Kentucky in the main event for the world featherweight belt before
26,142. In the 11th round, Ramos knocked down Moore, who hit his
head on the bottom rope. The fight was stopped by referee George
Latka, Ramos earning the knockout victory and taking Moore's belt.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the sorrow was about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been with Davey (Moore) in training camp,'' said John
Hall, former columnist for the Los Angeles Times and Orange County
Register. ``When the fight was over, he leaned through the ropes
and said, ``It wasn't my night.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we were starting to talk to him in the dressing room and
he just got drowsy, put his head down and went to sleep. And he
never woke up. Later at the hospital, we were all shocked when the
doctor told us he had only a 50-50 chance to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore died two days later from a brain injury suffered when his
head hit the rope, which, at that time was not required to have a
half inch of padding surrounding what is nothing more than a steel
cable, as is required today.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time boxing was held at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Furthering the agony of the evening, Hank Weaver, a popular
television sportscaster, was killed in an automobile accident
leaving Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet)An interesting doubleheader will take place Saturday on
Showtime. Mike Tyson will take on Lou Savarese in a 10-round
heavyweight bout. And Zab Judah will make the first defense of his
International Boxing Federation junior welterweight belt against
Junior Witter.
</P>
<P>
   The telecast, which will be on taped delay, will begin at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet)Locals Antonio De Santiago of Baldwin Park and Michael
Anchondo of La Puente will fight in separate undercard bouts
tonight at the Pond of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   De Santiago (9-2) will take on Nobohito Honmo (14-4) of Japan in
a 6-round junior lightweight bout. Anchondo (1-0) will square off
with Victor Guerrero (2-1) of Gilroy in a four-round featherweight
bout.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Gonzalez (22-0, 13 KOs), of Huntington Beach and the La
Habra Boxing Club, will fight Jacobo Garcia (12-21, 5 KOs) for the
Mexican light heavyweight championship in the main event.
</P>
</TEXT>
