<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-FOODNEWS-DIE-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-DIE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Food in the News  
 AWAITING FAD DIET FACTS 
 &HT;     DON'T EXPECT RESULTS FROM USDA-UC DAVIS STUDY ANY TIME SOON  
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO &LR;  _ Consumers waiting for the federal government to
referee the battle of the fad diets shouldn't stop counting their
calories anytime soon.
<P>
   In a widely reported proclamation last month, Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman said the government, working with
researchers at the University of California at Davis, had embarked
on a study of popular diets. But the researchers say they have yet
to get the approval or the funding they need to begin.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they do get the $3 million they are requesting,
Davis researchers say it will be as long as seven years before
results are released. By that time, the nation will have likely
moved past its fascination with today's high-fat, low-carbohydrate
fad diets.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman announced plans for the definitive study May 30 at a
Department of Agriculture national nutrition summit in Washington,
D.C. The story landed on the front pages of major newspapers,
including The Chronicle, and was soon fodder for commentators and
editorialists across the country.
</P>
<P>
   No one was more surprised than Christopher Gardner, assistant
professor in UC Davis' School of Medicine and the lead researcher
of the proposed study.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed study, which would measure the health of 240
dieters over five years, had only a week earlier been forwarded the
USDA for approval. And that was after Davis officials had denied it
funding, Gardner says. It would have been impossible for the USDA
to have reviewed the study by the time Glickman announced it.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Glickman got ``carried away,'' says one staffer who
works for USDA deputy undersecretary Eileen Kennedy, whose office
in charge of research for the agency. Media reports didn't help.
Some portrayed the study as a battle between only two diets or said
implied the study was already underway.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of how a mere proposal became a national news story
began in February, when Glickman presided over something called
``The Great Nutrition Debate'' on CNN. Cardiologist Robert Atkins,
who promotes a diet that allows unlimited fat and meat but
restricts carbohydrates, went head to head with internist Dean
Ornish, who is pushing an extreme low-fat diet, and Barry Sears,
whose complex diet is called The Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Caught up in the interest sparked by the debate, Glickman was
shopping around for some research into fad diets. Janet King, the
director of the USDA's Northern California nutrition research
center which had recently moved to the Davis campus, handed a
one-page summary of the proposed study to Glickman's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was only a proposal, Glickman told the nation the
study was about to be launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to do something about being overweight and from
what I've seen, they're willing to try anything,`` Glickman told
reporters at the time. ``Why these weight-loss diets remain so
popular remains a source of extreme curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Once word got out, reporters called the campus, people
volunteered to be in the study and colleagues asked Gardner what
was going on.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, nothing was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people in editorials saying the study we're doing is
wrong and we haven't even done anything yet,'' he said. ``It just
really snowballed after the announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The study proposes a look at four diets, including the USDA food
pyramid. Five researchers, including three Davis-based USDA
scientists, will work intensely with dieters, who will be divided
into groups of 60 to test best-selling diet books and USDA
guidelines. Then, the dieters will be sent off to see how well they
do on their own. In addition to any weight loss, researchers will
study the long-term effects of the diets on things like insulin
levels, bone loss and cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to learn what changes happen to hormones like insulin
in order to determine in the long run how effective these diets
will be,'' says Peter Havel, a Davis nutrition professor who is
part of the research team. ``We know most people can lose weight
but we've never looked at how the diets effect physiology and how
people can avoid gaining (weight) back.''
</P>
<P>
   But the study might never happen. The official word from the
USDA earlier this week is that no money has been approved.
Information on existing diet research is being gathered and will be
presented in the fall. The agriculture department will then
consider whether the Davis study _ or a study by some other team of
researchers _ should be funded. Money for the study to settle the
great diet debate likely won't be in place until the 2002 budget,
according to a spokesman for the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should have been funded a long time ago and I think it
ultimately will be,'' says Judith Stearn, Davis professor of
nutrition and internal medicine and one of the researchers poised
to study the diets. ``It isn't research on the human genome, but
it's information people need to help everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   There is good news. She and other members of the team think the
premature publicity might help the study's chances for funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how it happened, but as they say any publicity is
good as long as they spell your name right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
