<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-ELBOW0622-     06-21 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-ELBOW0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arms out of joint
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Until it hit home during spring training 1999, Kerry
Ligtenberg was unaware of the procedure, much less how prevalent it
has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what `Tommy John surgery' was till it
happened to me,'' the Braves reliever said. ``I'd see guys with big
scars on their elbows and say, `Whoa, that must be bad.' ''
</P>
<P>
   All Ligtenberg needs to do these days is look around the
clubhouse, or almost anywhere in the Braves organization. Big scars
abound, both big-league and minor-league scars. They are evidence
of an increasing number of Braves pitchers who have undergone Tommy
John surgery, reconstruction to repair the ulnar collateral
ligament in the elbow. Forget tennis elbow. Pitcher's elbow is
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 pitchers in Atlanta's major-league camp last spring,
nine have had or will have Tommy John surgery, named for the former
pitcher who underwent the procedure first, in 1974. The four
highest-profile Braves patients are Ligtenberg, John Smoltz, Odalis
Perez and now Rudy Seanez, the reliever who will undergo surgery
June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 71 pitchers in the Braves minor-league spring training
camp, 11 have had or will have the procedure. That's 20 Braves
pitchers out of 102. The numbers are alarming and somewhat baffling
to the Braves, but they are not unique to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   INJURY'S INCREASE PUZZLING
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something wrong, but I don't have an answer,'' said
Dick Balderson, the Braves director of player personnel. ``I don't
think there's a clear-cut answer. It's not just the Braves but
major league baseball that's being overwhelmed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what puzzles me,'' Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone
said. ``Who in that group has accumulated any (significant) innings
(pitched)? One. John. That's what befuddles me. You can explain
Smoltzie a little bit, the wear and tear over the years. But you
can't when somebody hasn't accumulated a significant amount of
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, this year we've had more high-profile people that
have needed reconstruction and raised people's eyebrows to say,
'Geez, what's happening?''' the Braves' team orthopedist, Dr. Joe
Chandler, said. ``But I think it's happening everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. James Andrews, the noted Birmingham orthopedic
surgeon who has performed the surgery on nearly all of the Braves
pitchers, at least two high school pitchers picked in the recent
free-agent draft had the surgery. One had it on draft day and awoke
to discover which team had drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   In the College World Series, at least three pitchers on one team
had undergone Tommy John earlier in their careers. Toronto's David
Wells, the winningest pitcher in the AL also has had the surgery _
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``A MULTI-FACTORAL PHENOMENON''
</P>
<P>
   Such success stories give encouragement to pitchers. So does a
somewhat false sense of security about the recuperative powers of
one of baseball's most serious surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest thing about this is (that) people have this
concept that you tear it, you fix it, it's better than ever. A
bionic elbow,'' Chandler said. ``And that's just not true. Nothing
is better than God's creation.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chandler and the Braves, what's of greater and more
immediate concern is, why 2K? Chandler, for one, has ``a whole
bunch of theories'' for what he calls ``a multi-factoral
phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One is pure bad luck,'' he said, ``the wrong (arm) angle at
the wrong time.'' Chandler and Andrews agree that it runs in
cycles. Some years, a number of injuries require Tommy John
surgery; other years, none does.
</P>
<P>
   Genetics. ``Genetically, everybody's made differently,''
Chandler said. ``It's definitely a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mechanics. ``Poor mechanics can pinch the elbow in throwing a
ball,'' Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Improved detection and diagnosis. ``One reason we think there's
an epidemic (in torn elbow ligaments and surgery) is we're able to
detect and diagnose it more,'' said Chandler, citing improved
magnetic resonance imaging and diagnostic and surgical techniques.
``We're more attuned to it, aware of it.'' Doctors and baseball
trainers and management also are more knowledgeable about the
rehabilitation process needed after the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Little League Learning Curve. Chandler, Andrews and their
colleagues have found that in many young pitchers requiring the
surgery the elbow damage initially happened when pitchers started
throwing breaking balls at age 12. Or even younger.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Smoltz watched a Little League all-star game in which
one pitcher had a remarkably full repertoire. ``He was throwing a
fastball, knuckleball, curve, something of a screwball,'' Smoltz
said. The pitcher was 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the kid,'' Smoltz said. ``I would change
everything I did as a kid. I would try to get an amendment that no
kid from the age of 12 down, at least, could throw anything but a
fastball and a change. From 10-12, I was snapping curveballs. I had
a nasty curve. Luckily, I threw them correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURIES ACCUMULATE OVER TIME
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz also recalls playing high school doubleheaders every
Tuesday and Friday in Lansing, Mich. He would pitch every opener,
then play shortstop in the second game. But Smoltz _ who had
arthroscopic elbow surgery in 1994 and 1998 before tearing his
medial collateral ligament this spring _ knows that his injury was
more an accumulation of pitching 2,414 1/3 big-league innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people will tell you, with this injury, it (happens) on a
fastball,'' he said. ``But it's an accumulation of torques and
stress on your arm.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an accumulation, Chandler says, that starts far too early
and cries out for better prevention at a very early age. ``I think
there's micro-damage that occurs through the years, from throwing
breaking balls when you're too young,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said many Little Leaguers not only throw curveballs too
early but incorrectly _ not overhead but with a more precarious
sidearm motion that simulates a slider. ``Slider mechanics put the
most stress on the elbow,'' he said. ``There's more of a snap, a
higher velocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors contribute to Tommy John. Chandler cites the use
of aluminum bats in high school and college; the bats force more
pitchers to throw more breaking balls at a younger age. And young
pitchers overdo weight training. ``Baseball is a flexibility
sport,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz realizes the big-league big-money allure, too. ``Part of
it now is what we make and what we do,'' he said. ``The emphasis is
so much stronger now at a younger age that it's just a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   NUMBERS CONTINUE TO GROW
</P>
<P>
   ``On the big-league level,'' Mazzone said, ``I can see where a
young pitcher might have a tendency to overthrow, to stay in the
big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are more and more _ and younger _ minor-leaguers
who've required Tommy John surgery. Chandler says that the majority
of those injuries in the organization are partial tears of the
ligament. ``On top of old wear and tear,'' he said. ``The acute,
new injury was probably the one straw that broke the camel's
back.''
</P>
<P>
   With improved diagnostic, surgical and rehabilitative
techniques, doctors are less hesitant to prescribe surgery, and
pitchers are more likely to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more concerned last year, about the stress fracture I
had in my elbow,'' said Seanez, who missed the last six weeks of
last season. ``I don't feel anywhere near as bad about my ligament
as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seanez knows that he will have to have patience during a
rehabilitation that takes anywhere from 12 to 18 months. He knows
it from several talks with Ligtenberg and Smoltz. What the Braves
don't know, however, is why they have been hit by a glut of Tommy
John surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not that our organization is encouraging any
pitch that's detrimental to the arm,'' Chandler said. ``On the
contrary, from the very beginning, we try to minimize stress on the
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
