<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-VANDERBILT-MINE-DOCTO     06-21 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANDERBILT-MINE-DOCTOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TROUBLE-MAKING' DOCTOR FIRED AFTER TRYING TO HELP MINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. George Wineburgh stood up for sick and dying New York miners
whose suffering was being ignored by most of the medical community.
For his efforts he was fired from his job and ostracized by doctors
in two counties.
</P>
<P>
   Wineburgh practiced at New York City's largest hospital for 16
years before moving, with new wife and four Labrador retrievers, up
to the peaceful North Country in March 1982. He was eager to start
his new job as the radiologist at Ogdensburg's Barton Hepburn
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was going to be a piece of cake, you know, no
stress, a handful of cases, a great change from the big city. Boy
was I wrong,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long before the skills Wineburgh gained becoming
a board-certified radiologist started generating questions within
the pile of X-rays waiting on his desk each morning. The films were
from the patients examined overnight, usually for assorted trauma,
aches and pains and heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cracked ribs, bruised kidneys and clogged arteries,
Wineburgh was finding something unexpected: the distinctive shadow
of a lung damaged by asbestosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept seeing four, five, six cases every single week, week
after week, classic asbestosis,'' Wineburgh says.
</P>
<P>
   He questioned the other doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the clinicians that I asked said, `Ah, they're just
smokers. Yeah, they're miners, but they're all smokers. That's the
reason, so we don't mess with them,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Wineburgh was sure that what he was seeing was asbestosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's distinctive. If you know what you're looking for there's
no way to confuse it with something else,'' he says.``Asbestosis is
one of 14 (X-ray) findings that is unique, that can be one thing
and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of cases of asbestos he was finding grew _ first 8,
then 19, then 37. By the end of three months he had X-rays from 50
patients in which he diagnosed asbestosis.
</P>
<P>
   Other doctors still insisted it was emphysema _ chronic
obstructive lung disease or COPD _ from smoking, and claimed they
had the pulmonary function tests _ the amount of air a lung can
hold _ to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the numbers were all wrong, completely opposite of what
they should have been for COPD,'' Wineburgh explains. ``Emphysema
is called an obstructive lung disease and the lungs are
over-expanded. With asbestosis the lungs are small - restrictive
lung disease - completely opposite numbers. There should be no
confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   He was uncomfortable about what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it. It smelled. Nobody wanted to stand up for
the miners, nobody was being clinically objective. It was like they
were under the thumb of the mining company,'' the 55-year-old
specialist recalls.
</P>
<P>
   As the numbers increased, Wineburgh's frustration grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``These miners were desperate. They weren't getting any better
and they weren't getting any answers. Some were dying,'' he says.
``Doctors were telling them to stop smoking, but some of them never
smoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Wineburgh asked the unions for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were supposed to stick up for the miners. But they said
they had been told that if they raised a stink, demanded that the
safety regulations be followed, management said they would close
down the mines,'' Wineburgh says. ``So they too did nothing. Just
breathe in, breathe out, and keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Wineburgh sent the 50 cases to the state health department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these guys are out of the mines. Asbestosis is a
reportable disease. You guys have got the authority,'' he told
them. ``So here you are.''
</P>
<P>
   The state shipped the X-rays to the Selikoff Institute for
Occupational Medicine in New York City. There, a specialist
confirmed that Wineburgh was right in almost all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Then the health department contracted with Wineburgh to lead the
examination of all the X-rays taken between April 1982 and March
1983 at six hospitals in a two-county area of people 40 years old
and older.
</P>
<P>
   About 22,000 films of 9,442 patients were examined. Wineburgh
and his team found chest abnormalities in 500 patients. Those
X-rays were evaluated by what the health department called ``an
internationally recognized'' expert.
</P>
<P>
   She found that 71 percent of the X-rays of Wineburgh's 500
``were indeed consistent with chest abnormalities indicative of
asbestos exposure,'' says Dr. Edward Fitzgerald, who co-authored
the state's report and is assistant director of the bureau of
environmental and occupational epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
   Lengthy interviews were conducted to pin down the work history.
The largest number of the patients who had diseased lungs worked in
talc mining or milling. The next highest group afflicted were
workers from the paper mills, which used large amounts of talc, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas DiCerbo, the associate director of the New York's
Division of Occupational Health, said the state ``jumped in
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   To address concerns that asbestosis was being undiagnosed or
misdiagnosed, he says, his department sent physicians to the north
country to meet with the medical societies and local physicians to
try to do some education, ``to alert them to what they should be
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners of the mine agreed to talk to us and we explained
our concerns,'' DiCerbo said, but he declined to discuss whether
his department thought there was asbestos in the mine's talc.
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Wineburgh lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contract with the hospital was canceled three days before
it was to be renewed,'' he says. ``Most of the medical community
thought I was a trouble-making traitor. Working with the Health
Department of New York State to try to get help for hundreds of
miners made me a traitor to the physicians of two counties.''
</P>
<P>
   Wineburgh is not alone in being ostracized for trying to help
miners exposed to asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Radiologists in Libby, Mont., who first raised the alarm that
vermiculite miners at a now-closed W.R. Grace and Co. mine had
asbestosis, left town soon after. Another specialist in Northern
Minnesota told the state about finding asbestosis and other
respiratory disease in taconite miners in the Iron Range. He soon
moved his practice to another state.
</P>
<P>
   Wineburgh is now practicing in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding those sick New York miners changed my life.'' he says.
''I'm a lot poorer now. I have to work a lot harder then I should
at my age. Would I stick my neck out again for those guys?. Of
course. That's how medicine should be practiced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOREA-SIDE-$ADV25-COX     06-21 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-SIDE-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. 'INTERFERENCE' STOKING ANTI-AMERICAN SENTIMENT AMONG SOUTH
KOREANS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOREA-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV25.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ When Christopher McCarthy, a 22-year-old American
soldier, escaped from U.S. military custody after he was accused of
murdering a South Korean bar hostess for refusing sex with him, it
fed the belief among South Koreans that Americans believe they're
above the law.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was apprehended eight hours later and was sentenced by
a South Korean court this month to eight years in prison. However,
that incident was the latest in a series of events, including the
surprisingly successful summit between North and South Korea, that
has stoked calls for less interference from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a very strong anti-American sentiment
right now, but I think it's growing,'' said Jung-Hoon Lee,
professor of international relations at Yonsei University in Seoul.
``The summit contributed to it because of its focus on independence
and autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reunification of the two Koreas is seen by some South Koreans as
an issue that can be resolved by Koreans only.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Kim Jong Il's new look ... (showing) he can be friendly,
smile, be jovial, a very confident leader, (some people) feel, we
can do some business with this guy and Americans only serve as a
possible roadblock,'' said Lee. ``So that sort of feeds on
anti-American sentiment that was already there. There's a sense
that we should do this alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have always been factions in Korea _ especially
among the left-wing and the younger generations - who believe U.S.
troops should go home.
</P>
<P>
   Massive student demonstrations in the 1970s and '80s are
characterized as anti-American but were more directed at the
military dictators who ruled South Korea, said Lee. But because of
the military alliance between the two countries, the United States
was seen as tolerating or approving of the dictatorships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many students still feel Korea is being used by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States thinks of Korea as their colony,'' said Soo
Jin Park, a 25-year-old student at Yonsei University. ``Not on
paper, but by the way they act, Koreans get that impression.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the 37,000 American troops in Korea should leave
``because we're not at war and I see no reason for them to stay in
Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   While such sentiments are common on university campuses,
analysts agree they do not represent the mainstream view in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a growing belief _ even among people who would
identify themselves as pro-American and have no desire to see
American troops withdraw _ that Washington needs to treat Korea as
more of an equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some sense, I must say Korea is controlled by the United
States in many ways,'' said Rev. Young Joon Cho, pastor of Chung
Dong First Methodist Church in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Pagoda Park in downtown Seoul is filled with elderly men playing
chess, practicing calligraphy or just passing the time. In one
corner, a retired sociology teacher who would give his name only as
Mr. Kim is holding court with an audience of at least a couple
dozen, lecturing on U.S.-Korean relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States shouldn't look down at Korea,'' he said.
``We're not the Korea of 50 years ago. They should respect Korea as
a full sovereign country and let us solve our own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Foreign Ministry believes it is ready for an adjustment
in the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, our relationship has been one of dependence on
U.S. aid,'' said Sung-Hwan Kim, deputy director of the Ministry's
North American bureau. ``Now I feel we're equipped with the
requirements (for a more equal partnership).''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. recognizes that the relationship is an evolving one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea has changed from the poorest country in the world in the
fifties and sixties to one of the richest,'' said a U.S. official
based in Korea who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``There's a
constant need to re-evaluate the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the displeasure towards Americans stems from the Status
of Forces Agreement, which in part governs how U.S. soldiers who
commit crimes or wrongdoings in Korea are handled. From little
things, like not paying traffic tickets, to violent crimes, such as
murder, Koreans feel Americans get away with too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (American soldiers) are outside of their campus, they are
not restricted by Korean law, and that's not right,'' said Byung
Chan Son, who owns a small energy consulting firm in Seoul.
``Korean people are very unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the agreement is currently being renegotiated, as it
periodically is. Kim of the Foreign Ministry said Korea has
proposed several changes, such as requiring indicted American
soldiers to remain in Korean custody instead of American military
custody and requiring American military facilities _ where air and
ground pollution are not subject to regulations _ to adhere to
basic environmental guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the United States must make an effort to ... give the
Korean public at least an appearance that it respects Korea, treats
Korea as an equal partner and that there's a balance in the
bilateral relations,'' said Lee.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on commemoration activities, see:
</P>
<P>
   U.S military Korea page:
</P>
<P>
   www.korea.army.mil/50anniv/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Korean War Commemoration Committee:
</P>
<P>
   www.koreanwar.go.kr/
</P>
