<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-MEXICO-$ADV25-COX     06-21 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. WATCHING MEXICAN ELECTION CLOSELY, EXPECTS LITTLE CHANGE IN
RELATIONSHIP
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With MEXICO-PRI-$ADV25.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The party that has governed Mexico for seven
decades has become as familiar to U.S. policymakers as the litany
of difficult issues dividing the giant neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling party is tossed out in July 2 presidential
elections, though, American officials would quickly praise the
result as a healthy development in Mexico's democratic evolution, a
badly needed breath of fresh air for the rough-and-tumble politics
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, though, turning the tables on 71 years of one-party
rule in Mexico would present new challenges to the United States,
even as it opened the door to a whole new chorus of long-stifled
political voices across Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be happy to have a new party, because there would be new
elites,'' said Mexico expert Louis Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, with those changes would come complications, countered
Robert Leiken of the Brookings Institution, a Washington think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten into the habit very much,'' he said, ``of
dealing with the ruling party.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, of course, the U.S. government takes no sides in
Mexico's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government must deal with whomever is elected, whether
the victor is Francisco Labastida Ochoa, banner carrier of the
long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish
acronym, PRI; or opposition candidate Vicente Fox Quesada, of the
National Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican people will vote and make their own decision,''
President Clinton told reporters earlier this month, when Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo (of the PRI) paid a visit to the White
House for his 11th bilateral meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the answer is little different.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Labastida nor Fox has promised any significant departure
from policies that have led to increasingly close ties between the
United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. diplomats and senior administration officials insist
that the bricks and mortar of U.S.-Mexico relations _ NAFTA, twice
yearly cabinet-level meetings on key issues and ongoing cooperation
on more than a dozen issues ranging from narcotics trafficking and
environmental concerns to illegal border crossings and water rights
_ are strong enough to withstand an overturning of the old
political order in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty about our relationship with Mexico is that it goes
so deep, from the local, federal and regional levels,'' said Mike
Hammer, a Latin American expert with the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``A change at the top will have some effect,'' Hammer said,
``but it won't alter what's already in place.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that U.S. policymakers aren't watching
Mexico's elections closely. An overthrow of the PRI, after all,
could have potentially huge impacts on the United States, simply by
dint of the deep and wide nature of U.S.-Mexican relations.
</P>
<P>
   The ties that bind the two nations are tightly woven.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the North American Free Trade Agreement wed the
two nation's economies, two-way trade between the United States and
Mexico hit $197 billion in 1999. That accounted for nearly 10
percent of this country's total global commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 60 percent of the cocaine, as well as much of the
marijuana and heroine, consumed by Americans flows into the country
through Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And American drug users pump more than $50 billion into the
narco-trade each year. Much of that winds up in Mexico, where it
stokes a ring of crime and corruption at the root of death,
destruction and the undermining of Mexican democracy.
</P>
<P>
   And, with Americans and Mexicans making 300 million legal border
crossings each year, not to mention illegal smuggling and
immigration, it's getting harder all the time to distinguish
between Mexican problems and American ills.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop of growing integration between two very
different countries that just happen to be neighbors, Mexico
analysts in this country have long regarded Mexico's one-party rule
as a mixed blessing.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it's brought stability _ of a sort _ to a
country with which the United States shares a 2,000-mile-long
border.
</P>
<P>
   That's no small achievement, given the vast disparities between
the two countries, the pernicious influence of druglords in Mexico
and the history of political violence and repression across much of
Central America and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   And the PRI has provided a known entity to U.S. policymakers.
They'd had years to get to know Zedillo. A Yale-trained economist,
Zedillo had held two cabinet positions under Mexico's former PRI
leader, President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, by the time Zedillo
took office in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's political predictability, though, has come at a price,
beginning, said Goodman, with a lack of imagination and energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just have one set of decision-makers, you end up in
paralysis,'' said Goodman, dean of international studies at
American University in Washington. ``That's been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The impact has gone far beyond questions of good governance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Zedillo's efforts to root out corruption and bear down
on drug kingpins, Mexico has made little headway against violent
and well-funded druglords.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the Mexican government) has not disrupted the activities
of the major drug cartels,'' the State Department reported three
months ago in its annual review of international counter-drug
efforts. ``Chronic problems of corruption, weak police and criminal
justice institutions, budget constraints and severe poverty in
rural areas where drug crops are cultivated hamper Mexico's ability
to combat drug trafficking effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   One-party rule hasn't helped, said Leiken, author of the
forthcoming book, ``Melting Borders,'' a look at the Mexican
community in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main impediment to change, in terms of corruption, is the
lack of alternacy in power _ the kind of immunity and impunity that
that has created among important political figures,'' he explained.
``When you have a one-party system, it lends itself to that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Fox victory wouldn't wipe out Mexican corruption, certainly,
nor would it run off the druglords.
</P>
<P>
   A government shake-up would, however, present a new
administration with the necessity to start with a clean slate. At a
minimum, that would force organized crime to dance the risky ballet
involved in courting contacts in a new government.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself could be a stride in the right directi so many
other endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's certain, said Goodman, no matter who wins on July 2:
``We really need them, and they really need us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnes.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   www.american.edu/media
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
