<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CONGRESS-DRUGS-ART-NY     06-21 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-DRUGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL REJECTS A DEMOCRATIC PRESCRIPTION PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., Mo., La., Ill., Calif., Del.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Ways and Means Committee on Wednesday
night rejected a Democratic proposal to let the federal government
offer prescription drug benefits to all 39 million people on
Medicare, as it considered legislation to help private insurance
companies offer such coverage with federal subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   By a party-line vote of 22-12, the committee defeated a proposal
by Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md., that would have authorized the
government to offer a standard package of drug benefits throughout
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no guarantee of any particular benefit that our
constituents will get if the Republican bill is enacted,'' Cardin
said. ``The Republicans say this would be an entitlement program,
but there is no specific benefit that seniors are entitled to.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for people who are elderly or
disabled, but generally does not cover drugs for people outside the
hospital. One-third of the elderly have no insurance to cover drug
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House Republican bill, the details of drug insurance _
benefits, premiums, co-payments and deductibles _ could vary from
one private insurer to another, so long as the total value was
equivalent to that of a standard policy defined by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Cardin's proposal encapsulated the differences
between the two parties. Rep. Jim McCrery, R-La., argued against
the Cardin proposal, saying: ``We don't want the government to
control health care. It has not done a particularly good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Republicans said it was unnecessary for the government
itself to provide drug benefits because private insurers would do
the job with federal subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Merck-Medco Managed Care, a unit of Merck &AMP; Co., the worldwide
drug manufacturer based in Whitehouse Station, N.J., said Wednesday
that it wanted to offer drug coverage under the House Republican
bill.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Congress, Per G.H. Lofberg, chairman of
Merck-Medco, said, ``We would work to develop a prescription
drug-only plan that we could offer nationwide in competition with
others in what we expect will be a highly competitive market.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Cardin said, ``I don't know whether my constituents in
Maryland will have this Merck plan available to them five years
from now.'' Cardin said he feared that insurers would move in and
out of the market for drug benefits, just as health maintenance
organizations have moved in and out of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders said they hoped the full House would
pass their Medicare bill by the end of next week, when lawmakers
leave town for Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Tarplin, an assistant secretary of health and human
services who attended Wednesday's session of the Ways and Means
Committee, said, ``We strongly oppose this bill.'' On the House
floor, Democrats will have an opportunity to offer a proposal of
their own as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether a Medicare drug bill becomes law this year
_ and no one can be sure _ House Republicans said they hoped that,
by taking up the legislation, they could inoculate themselves
against attacks by Democrats exploiting one of the most potent
political issues in this fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill says that all Medicare beneficiaries would
have a choice of two or more private drug plans. If insurers did
not voluntarily enter a particular market, the government could
offer financial incentives to draw them in.
</P>
<P>
   But a critique of the House Republican bill, prepared by the
Clinton administration, said: ``Insurers are unlikely to
participate unless bribed. The new Medicare bureaucracy could
increase payments to insurers to bribe them to participate. This
will make insurers hold out to get higher payments.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the administration said, the Republican proposal
``relies on a flawed trickle-down theory that would end up
subsidizing insurers, not seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimated that the Republican
bill would cost $39.7 billion over the next five years and $158
billion from 2001 to 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that beneficiaries would pay premiums averaging
$37 a month, or $444 a year, for drug coverage under their
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republican leaders have not shown any sense of
urgency, though they acknowledge that millions of low-income
Medicare beneficiaries cannot afford the drugs they need. The
chairman of the Finance Committee, Sen. William V. Roth Jr.,
R-Del., who is in a tight re-election race, has said he wants the
panel to vote next month on comprehensive Medicare legislation,
including drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republican leaders are wary, fearing that the cost of
drug benefits could explode.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican bill defines a model drug insurance policy,
known as ``standard coverage.'' Under this policy, a Medicare
beneficiary would pay an annual deductible of $250 and would pay
half of the next $2,100 a year in drug costs. Most patients would
then be responsible for their own drug expenses, but the
beneficiary's out-of-pocket costs would be limited to $6,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, each insurer would negotiate with drug companies to
obtain drug price discounts comparable to those now secured by
large purchasers like hospitals and HMO's. Medicare patients would
get these discounts regardless of whether they had reached the
limits of their drug insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's debate focused on the proper role of government.
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said: ``Democrats are
for an affordable, guaranteed benefit under the Medicare program.
Republicans want to basically privatize this benefit, as they've
always wanted to privatize Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat on the Ways
and Means Committee, said: ``The Republicans have no confidence in
providing assistance directly to our aged. Rather, they want to
subsidize the private sector, the HMO's, the insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said: ``The Republicans have been
trying to figure out how to shove money down the throats of
insurance companies who don't want to offer drug benefits. The
Republicans think that that's the only way it can be done. They
don't trust Medicare. They would like to see it wither on the
vine.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they would offer what the elderly want: more
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerry Weller, R-Ill., said President Clinton and
congressional Democrats were offering ``a one-size-fits-all plan on
a take-it-or-leave-it basis.'' A person who uses one or two
prescriptions a month should not have to buy the same insurance
policy as a person who uses 10 or 15, Weller said.
</P>
<P>
   Tillie Fowler of Florida, vice chairwoman of the House
Republican Conference, said: ``Unlike the Clinton-Gore plan, we
give all seniors and the disabled the right to choose an affordable
prescription drug benefit that fits their needs. Americans can
choose a Cadillac plan, or they can opt for a more affordable Honda
plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
