<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-LOUIS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-21 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOUIS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOE LOUIS: THE BOXER WHO BEAT HITLER': GOOD AND EVIL IN THE RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Budgeted earlier as TV-LEWIS-REVIEW)  
(Editors: production notes at end of review) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only were the boxers heavyweights in the 1938 match between
Joe Louis and Max Schmeling. So was the symbolism. Black versus
white. Freedom vs. Fascism. Good vs. evil.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to capitalize on the propaganda while commenting on it, a
new ``Biography'' on A&AMP;E on Thursday night has been titled ``Joe
Louis: The Boxer Who Beat Hitler.'' (Would that it had been so.)
</P>
<P>
   Louis' son points out the irony in his father's representing the
free world when at home he was denied equality. We hear that
Schmeling _ who was pelted with banana peels and paper cups at
Yankee Stadium _ was miscast as an evil Nazi. He wasn't a member of
the National Socialist Party and had been criticized at home for
having a Jewish manager.
</P>
<P>
   With its potent mix of racial politics, history and celebrity _
not to mention the thrill of boxing _ the Joe Louis story makes an
ideal candidate for the long-running ``Biography'' series. (This
month A&AMP;E is presenting 27 premieres on the series, including the
sublime, Mary Magdalene, and the ridiculous, Hulk Hogan.)
</P>
<P>
   Because of their straightforward and predictable format, the A&AMP;E
biographies work best when good film is available (not likely with,
say, the forthcoming presentation on Peter the Great). The Joe
Louis film is very good. There's an eerie beauty in old
black-and-white boxing clips, which seem balletic rather than
bloody. No ``Raging Bull'' viscera here.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Biography'' style (that is, an absence of style), the
Joe Louis story unfolds as an allegory, resonant with overt and
hidden meaning. ``In an era of prejudice and segregation Louis was
uniquely popular,'' we are told. Then, ominously, ``There was an
unexpected price to pay for being the torchbearer.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case allegory seems appropriate. Louis was an iconic
figure, as important symbolically in his day as Muhammad Ali would
be a generation later. Louis' life moved in a Hollywood arc,
beginning poignantly in in 1914 in a sharecropper's cabin in
Alabama and ending poignantly in 1981 with a celebrity-packed
funeral at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the times, and his personality and ambition, he was
designated the good Negro, the opposite of Jack Johnson, the black
boxer who terrified whites with his belligerence and open affairs
with white women. (Johnson's story was told, with perhaps more
noise than enlightenment, in the 1970 movie ``The Great White
Hope,'' based on the Broadway play.) Louis presented himself as a
clean-living, modest man and made sure he was never photographed
next to a white woman. (He kept his extramarital arrangements
quiet.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, he wasn't allowed to forget his place. In Pompton Lakes,
N.J., where he trained, he became a celebrity. Feeling warmly
toward the locals, he bought the town an ambulance with proceeds
from a fight but then was denied the opportunity to buy the
handsome house he wanted because he was black. Newspapers referred
to him racially, as the Dark Destroyer, the Sable Cyclone, the
Brown Bomber.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, comments his son, ``he was the only black man
who could legitimately beat up a white man and get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Hitler and Mussolini, Louis may have been just another
heavyweight champ. But his boxing ascent coincided with Fascism's
rise, and his fate was sealed. His 1935 defeat of the Italian boxer
Primo Carnera was Round 1 in the propaganda fight.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmeling was a shrewd fighter. When he faced Louis in 1936,
he had studied his opponent and knew his weak spot: a tendency to
drop his left hand after throwing a punch, leaving himself open.
Schmeling knocked him out. Next time, however, Louis was better
prepared. In their 1938 rematch, which would prove to be Louis'
apotheosis, Schmeling was hit so hard he wept.
</P>
<P>
   When World War II began, Louis became an icon for black
recruitment, helping to urge prospective soldiers to overcome their
doubts about serving in the white man's army. He was instrumental
in helping desegregate that Army, not only by encouraging
enlistment but by using his influence to combat racial bias on
military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Like many veterans, but for different reasons, he came home to
find his glory days diminished, even though he was still young. He
retired from boxing in 1949, then returned two years later to try
to pay off his enormous tax debt.
</P>
<P>
   His denouement was long and sad. He took up drinking and drugs
and began hearing voices coming out of air-conditioning units.
Muhammad Ali, representing a new era, refused military service and
otherwise rejected Louis' values, calling him an Uncle Tom. But in
the end Ali came to Louis' funeral to pay his respect. Respect was
due.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIOGRAPHY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Joe Louis: The Boxer Who Beat Hitler' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 pm ET Thursday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Paul Tilzey. A BBC/A&AMP;E Network
co-production. CarolAnne Dolan, executive producer for A&AMP;E.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
