r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LB     06-21 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS' JOHNSON TAKES CARE OF BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers remain a team without a coach with
the NBA Draft less than a week away and the contracts for their
assistant coaches expiring at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's bothering coaching candidate and current assistant
Dennis Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't worry about it,'' said Johnson, who talked about his
situation at USC on Wednesday after helping the Clippers work out
four potential draftees. ``I do my job and don't worry about
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a three-time NBA champion as a player, has spoken to
Elgin Baylor, vice president of basketball operations, and Andy
Roeser, executive vice president, about the position but said he
hasn't had talks recently.
</P>
<P>
   My job ``is to work the kids that are coming in and to do my
job,'' Johnson said. ``That can speak bigger volumes than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have also discussed the position with Denver
Nuggets assistant coach John Lucas and former Georgetown coach John
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have said they still hope to have a coach in place
before the June 28 draft.
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for a Clippers draft without a coach. In
1998, between the stints of former coaches Bill Fitch and Chris
Ford, the Clippers took Michael Olo wokandi with the No.1 overall
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Workouts
</P>
<P>
   Draft workouts on Wednesday included Syracuse defensive stopper
Etan Thomas, the Big East Defensive Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the 6-foot-9 shot blocker has come from mid-first
round teams. Both Houston (ninth) and Seattle (17) want a second
look and Dallas (12) might want a second workout, Thomas said. The
Clippers pick at No.3 and No.18 in the first round and No.30, the
first pick in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Thomas, the Clippers brought in 7-foot-1 center
Ndongo N'Diaye, who played for Delaware; 7-foot-2 center Soumaila
Samake, who played for Cincinnati in the International Basketball
League last season; and, 6-foot-8 forward Keniel Daniels from
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   N'Diaye, from Senegal, has received attention since a strong
showing in the Chicago pre-draft camp. He has visited Golden State
and plans to visit Dallas and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   It's been a busy week for the Clippers. LSU 6-foot-9 power
forward Stromile Swift worked out for the team last Friday. Swift,
a sophomore, has been projected by many draft pundits as the No.2
pick to Vancouver ... On Saturday, the Clippers looked at Morris
Peterson, Michigan State's 6-foot-7 swingman ... Among the players
the Clippers brought in on Sunday were Missouri point guard Kenyon
Dooling and Connecticut point guard Khalid El-Amin. Both are
possible selections at the 18th pick ... On Monday the Clippers
looked at UCLA's 6-foot-7 swingman JaRon Rush and Hidayet Turkoglu,
a 6-foot-8 forward from Turkey. Turkoglu has been compared to
Philadelphia free agent Toni Kukoc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
