<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS, WOOED BY GORE, FLIRT WITH ANOTHER SUITOR, NADER 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The labor movement's rocky relationship with the Gore campaign
takes a new turn Thursday when James P. Hoffa, the Teamsters
president, appears alongside Ralph Nader at a news conference and
is expected to shower praise on him.
</P>
<P>
   Teamster officials said Wednesday that Hoffa was not prepared to
endorse Nader for president but would urge that any presidential
debates include him and Pat Buchanan rather than being limited to
Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Democratic and Republican nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mathis, the Teamsters' political director, said the
union wanted the debates to include Nader, who seeks the Green
Party's nomination, and Buchanan, who wants to be the Reform
nominee, because they were likely to raise the issues the Teamsters
most care about: trade, globalization and their effect on the
American worker.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, the Hoffa-Nader appearance Thursday, in
Washington, will be a pointed reminder to Gore that large segments
of organized labor remain bitterly unhappy with him over his
support for the China trade deal, which cleared a huge hurdle with
passage in the House last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Clinton administration began pushing normalized
trade relations with China, Gore has been trying to placate labor
leaders and their rank and file, whose support is considered
crucial in November. But though he won the endorsement of the
AFL-CIO last fall, the Teamsters, with 1.4 million members, and the
United Automobile Workers, with 800,000, have so far withheld their
backing, largely because of their anger over the trade bill, which
the unions fear will speed an exodus of American manufacturing jobs
to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call to include Nader and Buchanan in a debate is all
about putting trade in the forefront,'' Mathis said. ``Part of the
idea behind the news conference is to highlight the fact that
Nader, and to some extent Buchanan, are the two presidential
candidates talking about these issues, and talking about them in a
way we agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader is to give a speech to the Teamsters' executive board in
Washington Thursday, before the news conference. Teamster officials
are lavishing more praise on him than on Buchanan, noting that
unlike Buchanan, he has often complained that shortcomings in the
nation's labor laws make it too hard for workers to form unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Hoffa has been on the record that there's no way we would
support Buchanan,'' Mathis said. ``Nader is top to bottom much more
in tune with labor, and he has a history of supporting workers,
while Buchanan is somewhat of a Johnny-come-lately. It's not out of
the question for us to endorse Nader.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Teamsters, the autoworkers have expressed interest in
Nader's campaign. Last month, shortly before the House approved the
China trade bill, Stephen P. Yokich, the UAW president, announced
that his union would explore Nader and other alternatives to the
nominees of the two major parties. He denounced Gore and President
Clinton, saying they had ``once again sided with multinational
corporations against workers here and abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, flew to Detroit to
have lunch with Yokich Wednesday, largely to discuss the
endorsement that the autoworkers have withheld from Gore, labor
officials said. Sweeney, one of Gore's most powerful backers, has
also been one of the most enthusiastic, saying that while labor
disagrees with the vice president over the China deal, they are
aligned on most issues.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Gore's efforts to mend fences with labor suffered a
setback last week when he named Commerce Secretary William M. Daley
chairman of his campaign. Many union leaders saw the appointment as
a slap in the face because Daley was the Clinton administration's
chief strategist in the Capitol Hill fight over the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Mitchell, the AFL-CIO's communications director,
acknowledged Wednesday that Nader's campaign was attracting labor
support. ``I hear a lot of people saying Nader has a very good
message,'' Mitchell said. ``But the practical matter is we have to
figure out how to elect a president who will stand up for workers
every day. No candidate's going to be perfect, and we don't have
the luxury of supporting a message candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yokich is facing considerable heat from within the UAW about the
reluctance to endorse Gore. Douglas Fraser, a former president of
the union, lashed out against Yokich's position in a speech last
week before an association representing thousands of retired union
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UAW should endorse Gore,'' Fraser said in an interview.
``The reason is there is no viable alternative. Nader is not an
alternative. Politics is not playing a game. Nader's done some
constructive things, but the simple fact is he has zero chance of
being elected president. The politics of the situation is every
vote Nader gets is a vote he takes away from Al Gore, not George
Bush. He shouldn't be playing around, because he has absolutely no
chance, no matter what his virtues are.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krell, the UAW's spokesman, said: ``We haven't closed the
door on Gore. We've just opened the door to Nader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
