BANGLADESH-ACID-3 -- Acid is thrown in the faces of nearly 200
women a year in Bangladesh. Most often, the culprit is a spurned
suitor. No one is sure why this crime occurs here at such a high
pace, for this nation on the Indian subcontinent is not so
different from many others in its poverty or its culture or its
treatment of women. Afsaruddin, left, and Moti Master, the latter
one of the most respected men in the village, who convened a
shaleesh, or informal court, to decide compensation for
Afsaruddin's wife who was attacked with acid. (Barry Bearak/The New
York Times)
