Highway safety activists charged Tuesday that a Clinton
Administration proposal would put more tired truck drivers on the
road and increase risks to other motorists. One regulation would
lengthen the maximum hours of consecutive driving from 10 to 12,
but then increase the mandatory rest time from 8 to 12 hours for
long-haul drivers. Steve Izer, of Lisbon, Maine, holds a photo of
his17-year-old son, Jeff, who along with three of his friends, were
killed in Maine in a 1993 collision with a driver who had fallen
asleep at the wheel of a big rig. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service
Photo)
