of finding evidence of life, experts say. This is a wide angle view
of the martian north polar cap as it appeared to the Mars Global
Surveyor (MGS) Mars Orbiter Camera (MOC) in early northern summer.
The picture was acquired on March 13, 1999, near the start of the
Mapping Phase of the MGS mission. The light-toned surfaces are
residual water ice that remains through the summer season. The
nearly circular band of dark material surrounding the cap consists
mainly of sand dunes formed and shaped by wind. The north polar cap
is roughly 680 miles across. (NASA/JPL/Malin Space Science
Systems/The New York Times)
