<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ELBOWS-MEDICAL062     06-21 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ELBOWS-MEDICAL0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBy Charles Anthony
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Replacing a ligament isn't as complicated as it
sounds. In fact, elbow ligament replacement surgery, known as
``Tommy John surgery,'' usually takes one to two hours to perform,
doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players make up 90 percent of those affected by elbow
injury, although golfers, football players and tennis players also
can be hurt. And serious tears usually require surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was performed first on then-major-league pitcher,
Tommy John in 1974. John seemed was on his way to his best season
in 1974 with the L.A. Dodgers when he injured his pitching elbow.
Dr. Frank Jobe of Los Angeles performed the surgery that ended up
saving John's career. John sat out the 1975 season and returned to
the field in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is done primarily on pitchers, who after throwing
some 200 pitches a week can develop serious pain in their arms,
said Michael Rooks, a metro Atlanta orthopedic surgeon. The pain
can become so severe that it can keep a ball player from throwing.
</P>
<P>
   During elbow ligament replacement surgery, the physicians takes
a ligament from another part of the body _ typically the wrist,
foot, forearm or calf.
</P>
<P>
   Then they drill small holes in the elbow's bones and weave the
new ligament through the holes, according to Dr. William Ross, an
orthopedic surgeon at the Emory Clinic. The ligament is tied
tightly to form a triangle, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about a year for patients to recover from the surgery,
said Dr. Matthew Levy, orthopedic surgeon for St. Vincent's Charity
Hospital in Cleveland. ``However, some players have been pushing
the envelope,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rooks said that pitchers usually need at least six months of
physical therapy after surgery, and it might take much longer for
them to regain their fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
