<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-21 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST CALLS THIS TITLE THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is early Wednesday morning, and I call an old
friend, Jerry West, mastermind of the Los Angeles Lakers' world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you feel?'' I wonder.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pause.
</P>
<P>
   As you might know, Jerry West has in recent days become the
Howard Hughes of the Lakers, a reclusive figure who failed to make
an appearance at any of their games in the NBA Finals against the
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are a lot of things to feel good about,''
says West finally. ``And there are some things I feel bad about
that have nothing to do with basketball that I don't care to
discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no one not Jerry Buss, not Phil Jackson, not Shaquille
O'Neal, not Kobe Bryant, not anyone who takes the goings-on with
the Lakers any more seriously, or stressfully, than West.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he has even admitted that physicians have advised him
that it isn't conducive to good health for him to watch Laker
playoff games, a recommendation he has ignored on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't Monday evening, and he relates he had no idea that
the team he built had won the seventh world title in its L.A.
history until he received a phone call from a friend who informed
him of such a development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say this was the best one,'' says West when I ask
him where this NBA title rates with the others he's been involved
in with the Lakers one as a player and six as an executive across
the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when the playoffs came, we were expected to win. And
anything less would have resulted in widespread criticism for a lot
of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was tremendous pressure on this team to win. I thought
from the start we had the best team, but the best team doesn't
always win in the NBA. You never know for sure what will happen.
Injuries can hurt you, and we certainly were hurt when Kobe Bryant
sprained his ankle and missed a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West lives in Bel Air with his wife and two sons.
</P>
<P>
   He earns $4 million a year from Buss, and has three more years
remaining on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   He has a secure legacy in his sport both as a Hall of Fame
player it is his likeness that appears on the NBA logo and as a
general manager with a keen eye for personnel and a deft
understanding of team chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   In the madhouse that was the Laker locker room after their
title-clinching 116-111 win over the Pacers, Jerry Buss made it a
point to pay tribute to Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have never happened without Jerry West,'' said the
Lakers owner, over and over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   And he's right, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But all the glowing tributes make Jerry West uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers to stay quietly in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   He detests attention.
</P>
<P>
   He constantly implores me not to mention the vital impact he's
had on the Lakers, the fact he had the courage to put his
reputation on the line at the NBA Draft in June of 1996 when he
traded a proven commodity, Vlade Divac, to Charlotte for a
17-year-old high school senior named Kobe Bryant, the fact he
coaxed Shaquille O'Neal to sign with the Lakers at a time when
O'Neal was seriously leaning toward re-upping with the Orlando
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see the way Shaq and Kobe have developed into two
of the most incredible players in the league,'' says West. ``How
good can Kobe get? Oh, Lord! Remember, he's only 21, and learning
all the time. And he wants to get better. That's the good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so does Shaq. I honestly think Shaq is going to get a lot
better. I know he's not that far away from becoming a better
free-throw shooter. He'll reach that point. I think before he's
through he has a chance to become the greatest center who ever
played the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't think some people realize how good Shaq is.
Not only does he have great athletic talent, but he's such a great
competitor. He's like your worst nightmare if you're an opposing
player. He's not only very big, but he's also very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West has been a sacred part of the Los Angeles scene since
he joined the Lakers as a rookie out of West Virginia in 1960, the
year the team moved here from Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   He has grown fond of the area, and has developed a bond with
followers of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't measure how good it makes me feel to see the
enormous community pride that has grown around the Lakers,'' says
West. ``I remember when I first played here, and we often had
crowds of three or four thousand. And now everyone seems to have
warmly embraced the Lakers. This is a special time in Southern
California. We've waited a long time for a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   It was too long for Jerry West, who admits the Lakers'
frustrations of recent seasons have taken their toll on him.
</P>
<P>
   He should now be rejoicing in the Lakers' epic achievement and
he is but there is a restraint in his gladness that leaves one
concerned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
