<SLUG> BC-NUKE-SECURITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY FACES TOUGH QUESTIONS ON LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout; change in byline; story grows by
about 80 words)  
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson weathered a
bipartisan storm of criticism Wednesday over his handling of the
latest security breach at Los Alamos National Laboratory, even as
he assured Congress that investigators now believed that the
mysterious case of nuclear lost and found at the laboratory was not
a result of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson told a Senate hearing that the FBI had determined
that the two computer hard drives that were found last Friday
behind a copying machine inside the laboratory were the same
devices containing nuclear weapons data that had been missing from
a Los Alamos vault.
</P>
<P>
   He and other officials said the FBI, which is working with a
grand jury conducting a criminal investigation of the security
lapse, had recovered fingerprints from the outer wrapping of the
drives and from the area where they were discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The two hard drives contained data on U.S. and foreign nuclear
weapons and were intended for use by the government's Nuclear
Emergency Search Team, a sort of SWAT team responsible for
disarming nuclear weapons in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The drives, stored in locked kits inside a vault in the
laboratory's X Division, which designs nuclear weapons, may have
disappeared as early as March 28, officials said Wednesday. But
their loss was not reported to the laboratory's director until May
31.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which was notified June 1 about the hard drives'
disappearance, is now focusing on a handful of the 26 employees who
had unrestricted access to the vault where the drives were stored.
Three people have already flunked FBI polygraphs and have given
contradictory answers about their knowledge of the hard drives,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI does not believe the hard drives were ever moved out of
the X Division, officials added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the FBI has authenticated'' the drives,
Richardson said Wednesday. ``I am pleased, too, that it appears
that they did not leave the X Division,'' he said. ``I am pleased
that there does not appear to be espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was very little about Wednesday that was pleasing
to Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance before the Senate Armed Services Committee
Wednesday morning quickly turned into a grilling. Lawmakers were
incredulous when Los Alamos and Energy Department officials,
testifying along with Richardson, said that there were no rules
preventing certain laboratory employees from signing the hard
drives out or from walking out with the hard drives. Officials said
the rules were being quickly changed for the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet officials also acknowledged that because the hard drives
were classified secret, rather than top secret, they could be sent
by regular mail to another government building.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of sending secret material through the mail led to
another security incident at the Energy Department about eight
months ago, officials said Wednesday, but they refused to describe
it in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was assailed by lawmakers of both parties Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans renewed their calls for Richardson to resign,
one of the most senior Democratic senators said the energy
secretary had shown contempt toward Congress by failing to appear
at a Senate hearing last week to explain the disappearance of the
hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in this Congress a long time, 48 years, and I have
voted upon several occasions for resolutions providing for contempt
of Congress,'' said the lawmaker, Sen. Robert Byrd of West
Virginia. ``And I wouldn't have any hesitancy about voting for such
a resolution concerning you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
