<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOCSEC-POLITICS-NYT     06-21 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: SOCIAL SECURITY, THAT RISKY ISSUE, IS ON THE
TABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore stopped here Wednesday
to talk about Social Security, and used charts and statistics to
lead a friendly audience to a predictable conclusion: that his
approach to retirement security was more prudent and a better deal
than the plan advocated by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   What may be more surprising, given the issue's long history of
political sensitivity, is that Social Security is being debated at
all.
</P>
<P>
   There are risks for both parties. It is still not clear that
Bush's decision to push for private investment accounts within
Social Security, the biggest change in the retirement program since
its inception, will not blow up in his face, as some Democrats have
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear either that deriding Bush's plan will help
Gore turn out older voters who could tip the scales in swing
states, or that he can avoid seeming out of step with younger
voters for whom stock investing is an opportunity rather than a
``risky scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   The rival presidential campaigns have largely avoided discussing
any of the potentially painful measures that might have to be taken
to ensure that Social Security remains solvent as the population
ages. Bush has focused instead on the rewards of investing, while
Gore has stressed that the fast-growing federal budget surplus
makes it possible to add new retirement benefits inside and outside
of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But Social Security is squarely on the agenda for the
presidential race, even if the two campaigns have not fully
determined the political calculus that surrounds it.
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone else, it was President Clinton who put the
issue on the table by calling two years ago for a national debate
on it. His effort did not find any bipartisan common ground, in
part because Republicans feared that he was leading them into a
trap where any proposals they made would be subject to demagoguery
by Democrats. But the debate inspired by his involvement helped
educate voters about some of the options, including individual
investment accounts. Because of the stock market boom, voters
proved more intrigued by the idea than some Democrats had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem for the campaigns is that voters do not seem
to have fully sorted out where they stand. A New York Times poll
last month found that 47 percent of voters felt Gore would do a
better job of dealing with Social Security, compared with 39
percent for Bush. But when asked about private investment accounts,
the centerpiece of Bush's plan, 51 percent said it was a good idea
and 45 percent said it was a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   The differences of opinion are most marked across generational
lines. Among 30-to-44-year-olds, Bush's personal accounts plan was
favored by 66 percent and opposed by 30 percent. Among people 65
and over, 27 percent favored private accounts, and 67 percent
thought they were a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Partly in recognition of the appeal of investing to younger
people, Gore rolled out a proposal this week to create savings and
investment accounts outside of the Social Security system. The plan
calls for the government to match deposits on a sliding scale, with
most of the government subsidies going to low- and middle-income
people.
</P>
<P>
   In making the proposal, Gore sought to reframe the debate as
being not over whether investing amounts to casino economics, which
he had occasionally seemed to suggest, but over whether it has a
place within Social Security, a program built on a guaranteed
government benefit unaffected by the ups and downs of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that Gore's scare-tactic approach played very
well,'' said Robert L. Bixby, executive director of the Concord
Coalition, a fiscal policy research organization. ``I'm being
hopeful here, but maybe the climate has changed enough that you can
have a substantive debate on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has seemed intent in the last two days on addressing the
issue not so much along generational lines as along class lines.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see Bush's Social Security proposal as a way to
cement their party's appeal to what they view as an emerging
investor class, made up of people across income levels who have
grown comfortable making choices about how to handle their money.
Gore, by contrast, is increasingly pitching his proposal at working
people struggling to take advantage of the good economy, and is
implicitly casting Bush's approach to Social Security and economic
policy as one designed for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put an end to the days when savings are a scramble,
if not an unaffordable luxury,'' Gore said before leaving Des
Moines for Minnesota and a meeting with Gov. Jesse Ventura, whose
popularity with independent voters has led the Gore camp to
cultivate him throughout the campaign. ``This is the choice in this
election: Are you for working people?'' Gore asked the crowd of
supporters at a carpenters union hall here.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of how the wealth amassed by many people
in the last decade is upsetting traditional political calculations,
Gore also set out his own plan Wednesday for reducing the federal
estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had long opposed reductions in the estate tax as a
giveaway to the rich. But 65 Democrats joined the Republican
majority in the House to pass legislation earlier this month to
repeal the tax, and the party has found itself on the defensive
over the issue. Democrats, including Gore, have become increasingly
sensitive to pressure from farmers and small-business owners, who
say the tax endangers their ability to pass their holdings along to
another generation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan, which his campaign said would cost $7 billion over
10 years, is similar to a plan backed by House Democratic leaders
and would focus its benefits on family farms and small businesses.
Rather than repealing the tax entirely, as the House Republican
bill would do, Gore's plan would increase the value of a farm or
small business that would be exempt from estate taxation. With some
minimal estate planning, a married couple running a farm or
business could eventually exempt $5 million of their estate under
Gore's plan; such planning currently allows the couple an exemption
of $2.6 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-21-00 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-NKOREA-NYT &LR;      06-21 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-NKOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA'S MISSILE PLEDGE PAVES THE WAY FOR NEW TALKS
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ North Korea has reaffirmed its pledge to the United
States to stop flight-testing its long-range missile, paving the
way for talks very soon with the Clinton administration on further
curbs on the missile program, a senior administration official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean announcement came after the administration
lifted some economic sanctions on Monday and was welcomed as a
``positive statement of their commitment,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the North Korean pledge did not alter the administration's
resolve to move ahead with its missile defense program, which has
been largely justified on the assumption that North Korea could
have the ability to hit the United States with nuclear or
chemical-tipped ballistic missiles by 2005, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Flight-testing is only one element of North Korea's missile
development and such concerns as engine-testing and improving
launching sites by the North Koreans will be addressed in the
coming talks, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking en route to China with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, the official said that in return for the reaffirmation,
announced in Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, on Wednesday, the
United States would announce specific dates for the resumption of
talks between North Korea and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   These talks could begin as soon as the end of the month,
officials said. The first round of talks took place in March last
year in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming session, the United States will deal with North
Korea's ``development, deployment, testing and export of
missiles,'' as well as the country's nuclear program, the senior
official said. One goal of the talks is to seek ``verification'' of
North Korean pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Since the summit meeting of North and South Korean leaders last
week, Pentagon officials have emphasized that although North Korea
agreed last fall to suspend the testing of the Taepodong 1 missile
it fired over Japan in 1998 _ a suspension it reaffirmed on
Wednesday _ the North Korean military has not suspended development
of a new generation of missiles known as the Taepodong 2.
</P>
<P>
   A national intelligence estimate last year concluded that by
2005 North Korea could complete development of the Taepodong 2, a
missile capable of reaching the United States with a nuclear
warhead.
</P>
<P>
   A new estimate is being prepared for President Clinton,
officials said last week, and is expected to reach similar
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   As Albright landed here to meet with Chinese leaders on a range
of issues, her aides sought to walk a fine line between lauding the
outcome of the landmark summit meeting between the two Koreas last
week and keeping a lid on what Washington sees as misplaced
euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   The officials were also anxious to make clear that the United
States had its own lines of communication with North Korea,
separate and apart from what went on at the summit meeting in
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the senior official, who briefed reporters on Albright's
plane, said that Wednesday's statement reaffirming the moratorium
of flight tests was part of a choreographed script worked out
between the United States and North Korea at talks in Rome at the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement there, the official said, was that Clinton would
formalize the easing of sanctions, the North Koreans would
reconfirm their moratorium, and then the United States would move
ahead with the dates of the missile talks.
</P>
<P>
   Behind these steps lies the overall strategy worked out by
Clinton's special envoy to North Korea, former Defense Secretary
William Perry. That strategy revolves around a finely tuned series
of moves to lift sanctions as North Korea begins to freeze its
nuclear arsenal and end sales of missile technology to countries
Washington suspects of sponsoring terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   But the three days of amiability at the Korean summit meeting
surprised the administration and left officials faced with
uncomfortable diplomatic pressure to ease up on its missile defense
program just as the U.S. presidential election is about to get
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Washington's NATO allies have questioned whether the
North Korean missile threat was serious enough to deploy a missile
defense shield that antagonizes Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the administration's unchanged position on North Korea's
missile capacity, Albright's aides said they noted that the tone of
the statement from Pyongyang was more generous than in the past.
For example, the senior official said that the statement used the
firmer word ``moratorium'' rather than ``suspension,'' which was
used by the North Koreans last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also said that the easing of sanctions would have
``a positive effect'' on plans for a senior North Korean official
to visit the United States for talks with the administration. Such
a meeting has been broached for some time but has yet to take
place.
</P>
<P>
   The statement concluded with an appeal to the United States to
honor North Korea's sovereignty and improve bilateral relations so
that North Korea could then ``work to clear the United States of
its worries.'' Asked what this phrase meant, a State Department
official said, ``It's nice, but we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   After her quick visit to China, which is scheduled to last less
than 36 hours, Albright will fly to Seoul to learn firsthand
details of the summit meeting from South Korea's president, Kim Dae
Jung.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
