<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-JOHNWAYNE-STOLEN-TEX     06-21 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNWAYNE-STOLEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET A ROPE! SOMEBODY'S NABBED THE DUKE!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Get a rope!
</P>
<P>
   In a crime that strikes at the soul of Fort Worth and Texas,
outlaws have stolen John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   When last seen, Wayne's portrait was in its exalted position
overlooking a dining-room corner at Angelo's Barbecue, the
definitive Fort Worth barbecue-and-beer hall for 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a daring midevening heist last Thursday, three young
desperadoes snatched the Duke off the back wall and Duke-napped him
out the front door _ all before a disbelieving and slow-reacting
happy-hour crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dadgummit!'' said an angry Skeet George, 49, son of the
restaurant's founder, Angelo George. ``Somebody's got to be pretty
durned low to take John Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Great Angelo's Caper. About 9 o'clock, just as the
usual Thursday crowd was nearing critical mass, a young woman and
two tattooed young men in baggy clothes stood huddling around
something in the restaurant's back corner.
</P>
<P>
   The woman and one of the men then rushed out the door, squeezing
something tightly between them with the second man close behind. By
the time nearby customers noticed the sudden absence of Big John,
they ran outside to see only a light-colored Infiniti sedan
speeding away in a cloud of dust.
</P>
<P>
   With the dining room full of witnesses, not one shouted, ``Hold
it, pilgrims!''
</P>
<P>
   They proved no more helpful than the stuffed bear at Angelo's
front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gets me,'' George said. ``They all saw it. But
they just kept on drinking beer. Nobody wanted to get up or get
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   With a laugh, he added, ``Heck, I'd have given them all another
beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The portrait rustlers now lead the list of Cowtown's Most
Wanted. If caught, they should be tied up and forced to eat
chain-restaurant barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   If I were Skeet George, I'd be watching eBay.
</P>
<P>
   He's offering a reward: ``It'd be worth a few rib dinners to get
it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The oval, lacquered Wayne portrait was given to the Georges in
the early 1980s by a regular customer from Oklahoma, Skeet George
said.
</P>
<P>
   He does not describe it as a likely target for art thieves.
``It's just a big drawing, mounted on wood,'' George said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's worth much. Somebody just wanted a real
cheap Father's Day present.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wayne portrait is not the first artifact lifted from
Angelo's dining room, which is lined with hunting trophies, fishing
keepsakes and such informative signs as, ``It's easier to SHOW your
I.D. than for ME to get out of JAIL.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, a giant buffalo's head vanished from a post high over
the dining room. A few weeks later, an anonymous call sent the
Georges searching miles away in Haltom City, a Fort Worth suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out back behind a garage,'' Skeet George said.
``Somebody felt guilty. Either that, or they just didn't have
anyplace to hide a buffalo head.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dukenapping is the latest in a series of jolts to tradition
at Angelo's, a barbecue hall immortalized in travel guides, author
Dan Jenkins' novels and ``Texas Monthly'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   First, after 30-plus years of relying on ceiling fans and
ice-cold beer for summer cooling, the restaurant relented and added
air conditioning. Then, to meet 1990s appetites, Angelo's began
smoking chickens and turkeys to go with its barbecued beef brisket
and pork ribs. The serve-yourself drink cooler now offers several
flavors of Diet Snapple.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1993 Van Cliburn International Piano Competition,
medalist Simone Pedroni of Novara, Italy, was quoted rhapsodizing
about Angelo's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italian food is Rossini,'' he said, naming the Italian opera
composer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angelo's is John Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wayne is gone.
</P>
<P>
   So is a little bit of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
