<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-WRESTLE0622-COX     06-21 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WRESTLE0622-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texan hopes to be first from state to make a U.S. Olympic
wrestling team
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. Olympic wrestling trials begin this week in
Dallas, a city historically better suited to hosting pro rasslin'
than big-time freestyle and Greco-Roman competition. Yet, there
figures to be one wrestler there who'll be cheered like he's a lost
member of the Von Erich clan _ Brandon Slay.
</P>
<P>
   The Amarillo native, seeded No. 1 in the 167-pound freestyle
competition, aims to become the first born-and-bred Texan to make
the U.S. Olympic wrestling team. If he can do that, he should have
a serious shot at winning a medal, even the gold, at the 2000
Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to be an Olympic champion. If I'm going to the
Olympics, I'm not going just so I can be there,'' Slay said earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas turns out Olympic wrestlers about as often as Nebraska
grows a great surfer or Mississippi churns out a champion ice
skater. It's not climate so much as history that's to blame for
Texas' shortfall on the mat. Most people have long since forgotten
it, but there once was a time, before World War I, when the
University of Texas not only had a wrestling team, it was one good
enough to whip Oklahoma State, then known as Oklahoma A&AMP;M. But when
Oklahoma left the old Southwest Conference in 1920 and Oklahoma A&AMP;M
followed in 1925, wrestling dried up in the SWC.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas high schools, the sport was an orphan. The University
Interscholastic League didn't sanction it until two years ago.
Until then, the sport found only a few spots where it gained a
measure of acceptance, including some suburbs of Dallas and in
Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Slay was six years old when his father, Doug, a former wrestler
for the University of Alabama, took him to the local YMCA for some
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year was really rough,'' Slay recalled. ``I never
won a match. The first match I finally won it was because the guy
didn't show up. I came home angry, hurting and I thought about not
going back, but I kept going back. Maybe it was because I set small
goals and continued to add to them. I wanted to be the best in the
city. Then, the best in the area. Then, the best in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A real boost for Slay came in 1990 when, as a 15-year-old, he
won the 182-pound weight class in Greco-Roman wrestling and made
the cadet national team. He finished third in the cadet-level world
championships in Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   Making international level teams exposed him to some top
coaches, and if you're going to be a wrestler in Texas, Amarillo is
as good a spot as any.
</P>
<P>
   Slay said, ``Texas is so big as a state. We'd go to other
states. Oklahoma is three hours away. In high school we went to
Oklahoma City, Santa Fe, N.M., and Liberal, Kan., for
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   FAR AWAY FROM HOME
</P>
<P>
   At Amarillo, Tascosa won three state titles and became one of
the nation's top recruits in his weight class. Yet, wrestling in
college was not a no-brainer decision.
</P>
<P>
   Slay said, ``A lot of people thought I was a better football
player than wrestler. They have a Super Team, from New Mexico,
Oklahoma and the Texas Panhandle. I was Super Team player of the
year. Zach Thomas had won it the year before. It was real tough to
make a decision. I was thinking about being a blocking fullback or
a middle linebacker in college. But I had the chance to be the best
in wrestling rather than just another good football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay was noticed as far away as the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good competitive spirt. He was very committed and he
was working on his skills year-round,'' said Roger Reina, Penn's
wrestling coach. ``It was a good fit between what he wanted to do
and what we offered.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay chose Penn as much for its noted undergraduate business
school, the Wharton School, as for its wrestling program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campus is beautiful. When you're on it, you're in awe of
the historic beauty. But three or four blocks away is one of the
worst areas of Philadelphia,'' Slay said. ``That was an eye opener.
I was born and raised in a conservative town and went from there to
the fifth-largest city in the U.S. Traffic was horrible. People
were everywhere. I was 30 hours from home. My folks weren't getting
a chance to see me wrestle, or even see me. Going from public high
school in Texas to the Ivy League was a big change. I was the only
Texan in my hall. Ninety-eight percent of the people I hung around
with weren't like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay had to learn some lessons they weren't teaching in the
ivy-covered halls.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``I'd always trusted everybody unless they gave me a
reason not to. But you can't trust everyone. You've got to watch
your back, take care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was his accent. Vowels could stretch out as long as
the Texas plains. Friends chuckled when he asked for iiice tea,
whiiite riiice or a Spriiite.
</P>
<P>
   ``My accent and my mind-set changed,'' Slay said. ``I'm still
extremely proud to be a Texan, but going to Penn opened my eyes to
different cultures, to diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   AIMING FOR SYDNEY
</P>
<P>
   At Penn, Slay twice reached the NCAA finals at 167 pounds and
earned a dual degree in management and finance. He was, however,
ready for a change of scenery. He moved to the Olympic training
center in Colorado Springs and has been training for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to get out of Philadelphia. Now I can drive
downtown and park for a quarter. I don't have to stand in long
lines,'' Slay said.
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest obstacles to making the team is Joe Williams,
a former University of Iowa star. Heading into this year Slay had
never beaten Williams. But Reina said, ``He has a track record of
beating opponents that had beaten him in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   This April, at the National Open, Slay upset Williams 5-3.
Because of that Slay gets to sit out of the trials competition
until Saturday, after the winner of a mini-tournament for Williams
and others in his weight class has been determined. Then, Slay and
the winner of the mini-tournament will wrestle best
two-out-of-three to see who represents the U.S. in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge advantage,'' Slay said. ``The other guys have four
matches to wrestle. The winner could be injured or tired.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Slay should have a huge home-mat advantage because
he'll be the only Texan for the Reunion Arena crowd to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it makes a huge difference in the popularity here,''
Slay said of the trials. ``Texas has one of the best crop of
athletes. I believe Texas can compete with any other state. We're
known for football and we're amazing at it. We put time, money and
effort into that. Sometimes other sports are left by the wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandon's been a real advocate of Texas wrestling,'' Reina
said.
</P>
<P>
   He, and others, have a growing number of believers. The National
Wrestling Coaches Association is having its meeting in Dallas prior
to the trials to show support for a state that's finally
recognizing the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited. We realize the potential,'' Reina said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
