<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-WORK-CONDITIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONS CUTTING AID TO THE JOBLESS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Seventy-five percent of the world's estimated 150
million unemployed workers have no jobless benefits, and even the
most generous countries have been cutting back on assistance to the
unemployed, the International Labor Organization said Wednesday in
its annual assessment of global working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the report said the cutbacks represent a
significant threat to economic development because they undermine
the financial security of employed workers.
</P>
<P>
   Worker protection in Wednesday's insecure job environment is
essential, said Roger Beattie, the report's chief author, ``because
people who are well protected are far more willing to accept such
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Somavia, director general of the Geneva-based ILO, said
that recalcitrant countries could ``eventually suffer a destructive
backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. agency's World Labor Report 2000 said workers in Europe
enjoy the most generous unemployment benefits, but even its wealthy
countries reduced them in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also trimmed back benefits, and has slipped in
a ranking of which countries offer the most generous worker
protection, the study reported. Australia, Canada, Ireland, Japan,
New Zealand and the United Kingdom, also provide a lower level of
benefits than countries in the top tier of the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Iceland,
Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Sweden and
Switzerland make up the top-tier countries with the most benefits
for the greatest number of workers.
</P>
<P>
   An entrenched system of benefits in much of Europe, and the
resistance to efforts to pare it back, have raised criticism that
the European countries are too burdened with social costs to
compete effectively with more free-wheeling economies.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie rejected such criticism as ``naive'' and said that the
study indicated that countries can put a secure floor under workers
while still growing their economies. The ILO study showed that the
most generous countries, such as Spain, replace between 63 percent
and 77 percent of wages to the unemployed. New Zealand is among the
lowest, at 23 percent wage replacement. Canada and the United
States provide about 58 percent of replacement wages.
</P>
<P>
   However, the two North American countries and the United Kingdom
also provide unemployment benefits for only 12 months, which is
described as short in the report. Also, neither the United States
or Canada provides a second layer of unemployment assistance when
initial insurance benefits are exhausted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
