<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1179 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-NBA-MARKETING-HNS     06-21 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-MARKETING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA hopes marketability grows off Lakers' title
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ When the Los Angeles Lakers won this year's NBA
championship, beating the Indiana Pacers in six games, there were
hugs all around, champagne showers and victory cigars being fired
up everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just in the league's front office.
</P>
<P>
   The Dream (Team) Factory that is the NBA is back in business,
and the Lakers are the product that is being pushed. It's Showtime
all over again _ at least everyone is hoping so _ with Kobe Bryant
and Shaquille O'Neal teaming to form the Magic Johnson and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar of the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Back when the latter two were in their heyday, the NBA achieved
a remarkable marketing fission _ appealing to both Madison Avenue
and the streets. There is the hope that Bryant, 21, and O'Neal, 28,
will have a similar impact on the blacktop and in the boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   But the only way that will happen is if they continue to win.
</P>
<P>
   Championships, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Bryant and O'Neal) work very well together,'' said
Johnson, who now has a minority stake in Lakers ownership, ``just
like Kareem and I knew each other's moves. At the end of the game,
we just looked at each other. We didn't have to say who wanted it.
We already knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have learned to coexist and finally learned that they
need each other to win championships. But they have gradually
matured and said, `You know what? We can both be stars and win
championships and be bigger stars after doing that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They can make each other be remembered, forever, by winning
championships,'' Johnson continued. ``They have to look at each
other and say, `You know what? Let's build our legacy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the potential is quite clear: Once you win this, build
on that. And keep on winning and keep on entertaining the fans, and
you'll have a legacy like Kareem and I have. People, when they say
your name, they instantly think of winners. They remember you.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys played this game. Only a few are remembered. And
the ones who are remembered are the ones who win. That's what it's
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite.
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson should have said is that the ones who win are the
ones who are marketed for mass consumption. And after a season when
the NBA's once-rosy television ratings plunged like Internet stock
prices, the search is on for the cure.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, which broadcast 34 regular-season games this season, drew
an average rating of 3.4 (each rating point translates to 1,008,000
homes), down 21 percent from last season. And Turner Sports, which
broadcasts games on TBS and TNT, claimed a drop-off of 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Pat Riley, who guided those Showtime Lakers to four
of their five championships in the 1980s, cited several possible
reasons for the downward spiral in television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, there were only one or two games on television
(per week),'' Riley said. ``There wasn't the Internet; there wasn't
DirecTV; there wasn't TNT. All of these people have games on now.
Maybe it's diluted.''
</P>
<P>
   But many around the league say the lag in TV ratings was
expected, especially with the echoes of the disastrous lockout
season of 1998-99 still being faintly heard throughout the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured this (downturn) could happen,'' said Wizards
majority owner Abe Pollin. ``This is a transitional season. We're
still feeling some of the effects of the lockout. Some people got
turned off by the NBA and decided to do other things with their
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that kind of disruption, things don't usually
return to normal right away. We're optimistic (that the increased
interest caused by the playoffs) will carry over to next season and
everything will be up next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   While this year's Finals featured many viewer-friendly games,
especially the aerobically paced 116-111 series ender, the biggest
problem facing the NBA is that so far there is no Michael Jordan to
have everyone wishing to ``be like Mike.'' The league and its
corporate partners hitched most of their marketing efforts to
Jordan's wagon, so why should they be surprised when no one is
interested anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than learning its lesson, however, the NBA has worked
itself into a lather trying to find a worthy successor to his
Airness _ Grant Hill, Bryant, Kevin Garnett, Tim Duncan or Vince
Carter. And while many of them have Jordan's camera-friendly good
looks, a touch of his charisma or his flair for the game, none has
really caught the public's fancy. Not yet anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because while they're all talented players, none has the
one quality that set Jordan apart from the rest _ an ice-cold will
to win. We admire ability, but we really love winners, and Jordan
was the ultimate winner.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the next Jordan is not driving the lane in your
nearest arena; he's instead driving a golf ball down the nearest
fairway. Tiger Woods has supplanted Jordan as the ultimate
big-stage performer, which is the biggest _ perhaps only _ reason
golf has usurped the NBA among the league's target demographic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports ratings are cyclical. It's not an unbroken line up or
down,'' said Neal Pilson, a former head of CBS Sports who now runs
his own television sports consulting company. ``You can't anoint
the next Michael Jordan. I think they stumbled a little this season
trying to do that (by putting Carter and Bryant on TV so often).
</P>
<P>
   ``The public will anoint the next Michael Jordan. In fact, the
public already has. His name is Tiger Woods, a guy who transcends
all sports, like Michael did.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has to be hoping that the Lakers, who look like they
could be winners for a long time to come, bring back many of those
viewers. And that Bryant will pan out to be the next Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget I was not even the focus and didn't get deep
into the playoffs the first six years of my career,'' said Jordan,
now president of operations for the Washington Wizards. ``The
public is going to see that the league is stacked with talented
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the players and teams need some maturing and
seasoning before they get to the level of the Lakers, Celtics and
Pistons of old. They set the standard for the modern game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the second half of the problem facing the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   While the league thrived during the heyday of Johnson's Showtime
team, the main reason was because of the intense rivalry the Lakers
had with Larry Bird's Celtics. The league now has to find a
comparable rival for these Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Many teams are gearing up for just such a challenge, making
overtures toward impact free agents like Duncan, Hill, Tracy
McGrady, Toni Kukoc, Eddie Jones, Jalen Rose, Reggie Miller, Brian
Grant, Rashard Lewis, Ron Mercer, Cuttino Mobley and Derek
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal scenario _ from the league's perspective, mind you _
would be for the New York Knicks to somehow find the fountain of
youth (``paging Alonzo Mourning please report to Madison Square
Garden''), matching the two biggest marketplaces in an annual
celebrity death match.
</P>
<P>
   Or having O'Neal's old team, the Orlando Magic, use its vast
salary-cap space to sign big-name free agents like Duncan and Hill,
immediately creating an Eastern Conference power capable of
challenging the Lakers both on the court and in Q factor.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe even having one of these new young stars emerge as a
genuine heir to Jordan, possessing the same ability to drive his
teammates to unimagined competitive heights.
</P>
<P>
   Anything to get the Dream Factory churning out a new set of
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new set of players and teams is going to give everyone the
effect that the league is not quite the same,'' Jordan said.
``Along with a lot of younger players coming in who don't have the
experience they possibly need to be put in the forefront as stars.
But they will evolve as their maturity matches their talent. So
will some teams. The league is going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
