<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ADDRESSES 
HISPANIC JOURNALISTS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday continued his quest
for Latino support by wooing the National Association of Hispanic
Journalists in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Urging the journalists to join him in making education their top
priority, Bush continued with a policy theme he trumpeted earlier
in the day during his 12th trip to California in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to make sure we close the gap of hope is to make sure
that every child gets educated,'' Bush said. ``For those of you who
are objective journalists, I ask you to look at the record in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the Hispanic heritage and traditions in the
state. I intend to take that attitude to the White House should I
be fortunate enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected president, Bush said, he would encourage small
business and free trade and support bilingualism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will pledge to you that I will welcome the Hispanic heritage
in America,'' he said. ``I will reject the English-only
movements.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP presidential candidate said he's hoping to dash
lingering stereotypes that his party is unsympathetic to immigrants
and uninterested in improving public schools as a way to help
struggling Hispanics in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an image that some have ascribed to the Republican
Party,'' he had said in Los Angeles. ``I'm setting a different tone
_ a different attitude toward the newly arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Houston visit spoke volumes about his campaign
priorities. Just a week ago, he skipped the GOP state convention in
Houston after saying his support in Texas was solid and his time
was better spent making new friends in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party of Bush's expected presidential opponent,
Al Gore, continues to be favored by most Hispanics, but Bush's
hopes of making inroads are riding high _ in part because of his
success in converting supporters in Texas, where he captured almost
half the Hispanic votes in his 1998 gubernatorial re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he paid his one-hour visit to the Hispanic
journalists' convention because he considered it important to meet
personally with its influential members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want their vote and I'm willing to come ask for the vote,''
Bush said, adding that his welcoming remarks were intended to show
that ``my vision for America includes everybody.``
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen protesters waved placards and chanted anti-death
penalty slogans in front of the Westin Galleria Hotel during Bush's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   At times outnumbered by the media contingent on hand to cover
Bush, the group paced up and down the sidewalk. One member carried
an upside-down American flag _ generally a symbol of distress _
while another kept time on a bongo drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush says `death row', we say `hell no,''' they demanded,
between warnings of ``no justice--no peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Graham's scheduled execution Thursday may have provided the
catalyst for the peaceful demonstration, but the protesters said
they oppose all capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters said the Democrats are just as culpable as the
Republicans when it comes to executions.
</P>
<P>
   Njeri Shakur said Gore was ``strangely silent'' over the Graham
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's letting Bush take all the heat for this, but he supports
the death penalty, too'' Shakur said. ``The Democrats and the
Republicans are very much in agreement with the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
