<HEADLINE>
CITY SHOWS ITS LOVE TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Please take a step back.'' The command was
directed at a convivial crowd surging to show its love for the
Lakers Wednesday, but we all would do well to heed it.
</P>
<P>
   For a few short hours on the longest day of the year, Los
Angeles showed us her most flattering profile. Her multiethnic face
was sunlit and serene. The residents of Greater Los Angeles who
shortcircuited their power lives long enough to soak in the Lakers'
NBA Finals victory parade were in for a shock, the kind transmitted
by the electricity we are capable of manufacturing when we're a
people united instead of divided along city and county and cultural
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew L.A. loved us,'' Laker reserve guard Derek Fisher said
at one point, his eyes wider than the patch of fans-free road ahead
of the motorcade. ``But I never knew L.A. loved us this much.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher could be forgiven for feeling as though he stepped onto a
double-decker bus on First St. and was transported back to his
hometown of Little Rock, Arkansas, where everybody knows his name.
Who knew L.A., a mega-metropolis with a well-documented mean
streak, was still small and neighborly enough to wrap its arms
around anything in a big, warm embrace?
</P>
<P>
   There were enough people camped along a dozen-block stretch of
Figueroa Street to fill a scrapbook of memories, not to mention a
couple of Rose Bowls. We haven't seen such thick columns of
advancing creatures since our house was overrun by ants.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people baked in the sun for hours without complaint
(or incident) just so they could catch a fleeting look at the 2000
NBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the well-heeled denizens of the Staples Center lost their
simple sense of wonderment while acquiring the kind of wealth
needed to afford those courtside season seats. But it would appear
their gilded insouciance is no more representative of L.A.'s
citizenry than were the hoodlums who marred Monday's
championship-clinching celebration.
</P>
<P>
   We caught a few people crying as the double decker buses
carrying L.A.'s newest champions lumbered up the street like
Arvydas Sabonis or Sam Perkins in the paint against Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Crying tears of ardor, mind you, not tears of disappointment or
disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew sports figures in this city still had the power and
grace to stir us out of our lethargy like that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Please take a step back.'' Even as we celebrated the beginning
of what looks to be a beautiful decade for O'Neal and Kobe Bryant
and Lakers basketball, we couldn't help sense we were seeing an
ending of sorts, too.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ron Harper, A.C. Green, Rick Fox, Brian Shaw, Glen
Rice, Robert Horry, Bryant and O'Neal step one-by-one to the
microphone and address the throngs outside the Staples Center, we
felt not unlike a parent on the day her child steps forward to
receive his or her high-school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a significant moment, but also sort of a sad one,
because the future inevitably will bring changes to a relationship
that is held dear.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with these Lakers, who won't all be back next season to
defend the title they won together. Fisher, as hard as he works and
as humble as he stays, is too short to fit coach Phil Jackson's
specifications for a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   And Rice, for as hard as he tried this year to fit in, might be
too selfish at heart to operate as a cog in Jackson's triangle
offense.
</P>
<P>
   We could see those two players packaged in a deal for a bonafide
power forward. We could see Harper retiring to rest his arthritic
knees and John Salley repairing (again) to the broadcast booth.
</P>
<P>
   In sports as in life, the only certainty is change. That's why,
when we caught all the players milling around the balcony stage at
the Staples Center, it was a frame we wanted to freeze in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please take a step back.'' Oh how we wish Lakers executive
vice president Jerry West would have been around to hear those
words, not that we can imagine him ever heeding them. West built
the team that united a city but hasn't been able to enjoy any of
the fruits of his labor.
</P>
<P>
   Far from completing him, the Lakers' success has depleted him,
draining him of his energy, his joy, his perspective.
</P>
<P>
   We're saddened to hear he's contemplating retiring because of
the public scrutiny, which is unrelenting. We know where he's
coming from when he says he gets beaten down by the steady stream
of feedback from people who can make his heart skip a beat with
their malevolence.
</P>
<P>
   We've been there, felt that.
</P>
<P>
   But as a wise friend once reminded us: Nobody can hurt us
without our permission.
</P>
<P>
   If West wants to retire because he's tired of the day-to-day
grind after all these years, fine. But he shouldn't let the public
or his own demons drive him out.
</P>
<P>
   We hope coach Phil Jackson kidnaps West this summer and subjects
him to hours of yoga in a room filled with aromatherapy candles.
Who knows? Maybe the same methods Jackson used to sharpen the focus
of O'Neal and Bryant could work the opposite on West's focus.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been so lovely if on this day West had been able
to see his Lakers through Los Angeles' eyes. We guarantee he would
have been moved to tears by what he saw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
