<SLUG> BC-TEXASINSTRUMENTS-BURRBROWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS INSTRUMENTS IS PAYING $7.6 BILLION FOR CHIP MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Instruments Inc., the semiconductor giant, said Wednesday
that it would acquire the Burr-Brown Corp., which is also a
computer chip maker, for $7.6 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Burr-Brown is a leader in analog chips, as is Texas Instruments,
but the two companies' product lines are complementary rather than
overlapping in most areas.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, which was announced after trading closed Wednesday,
Texas Instruments said it would issue 1.3 shares of its stock for
each share of Burr-Brown. That $113.425-a-share offer represents a
56 percent premium for Burr-Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments shares closed down $3.625, to $138.75, on the
New York Stock Exchange. Burr-Brown closed at $72.625, down $2.75,
in Nasdaq trading. In after-hours trading, Burr-Brown shares surged
to as high as $102.9375, while Texas Instruments shares were flat.
</P>
<P>
   The digital revolution has actually proved a boon to the makers
of analog chips, devices that process continuous electronic signals
rather than ones and zeros. This is because humans cannot see or
hear digital code, so analog chips have to step in to convert
digital signals into usable form for things like computer monitor
displays and speakers. Digital cell phones, DVD players and DSL
modems all use analog chips.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Burr-Brown strengthens Texas Instruments' position in the
data converter and amplifier segments of the analog semiconductor
market, where it has little or no market share. Data converters are
analog semiconductors used to convert signals from analog to
digital and back again. Amplifiers are used to detect and
strengthen low-level signals.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments, which is based in Dallas, is primarily strong
in digital signal processors, or DSP's, specialized chips often
used in conjunction with analog circuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as serious about analog as we are about DSP,'' Tom
Engibous, the chairman, president and chief executive of Texas
Instruments, said in a conference call with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Burr-Brown are elite developers of
high-performance analog products,'' Engibous said. ``This
combination means that TI will have a leading position in
essentially every high-performance analog category and the ability
to offer almost any analog component that touches a DSP.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr-Brown will become part of Texas Instruments' organization
devoted to catalog analog semiconductors, which are off-the-shelf
parts used in many products. This is the third acquisition by Texas
Instruments in the last 12 months to expand in this area. Last
October it acquired the Unitrode Corp., which makes chips that
extend a cell phone's battery life, for $1.25 billion in stock. In
November, it bought Power Trends, a maker of circuit board devices,
for $145 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Instruments' strength in DSP will introduce our
high-performance analog and data converter products into new
applications,'' said Syrus Madavi, Burr-Brown's chairman, president
and chief executive. ``The makers of Internet appliances and
communications systems will have the best of both worlds in one
company, with complementary components to optimally meet their
total signal processing requirements,'' he said in the conference
call.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments executives said they planned to retain
Burr-Brown's headquarters and one manufacturing site in Tucson,
Ariz., as well as two technology development centers in Atsugi,
Japan, and Livingston, Scotland. They also intend to keep
Burr-Brown's 1,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Producing analog chips cost less money than making digital ones,
because analog chips do not require _ and often cannot use _ the
latest process technology. One reason is that packing circuits ever
closer together, which increases the speed of digital chips, only
causes noise and heat problems for analog ones.
</P>
<P>
   Analog chip design is still as much art as science, and benefits
little from modern computer-aided design software. So analog
companies are dependent on design power of the human kind,
engineers with years of experience. Because these experts are hard
to come by, the barrier to entry in the analog business is
surprisingly high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
