<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., Calif., Texas, Mich., Conn., Mass., N.C., Mo.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH RESPONDS TO SENATORS
</P>
<P>
   Five moderate Republican senators who support abortion rights
sent a letter on April 12 to Gov. George W. Bush, the party's
presumptive presidential nominee, asking him to ``take the lead''
in changing the Republican platform's anti-abortion plank. They
also invited Bush to lunch. On Tuesday, they got a response _ to
the lunch invitation.
</P>
<P>
   One senator, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, said he still sought
a ``more specific response'' on abortion and remained hopeful he
would get it. Bush and platform leaders have said they intend to
leave the plank _ which calls for an end to legalized abortion and
the appointment of judges who ``respect the sanctity of innocent
human life'' _ as it is.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lunch, Bush indicated he would try to make one if his
schedule permitted, Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PROPOSAL ON COMPUTER EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush Wednesday proposed another $80 million
annually in federal grants to not-for-profit education centers in
low-income neighborhoods that help teach children and adults to use
computers. ``The great challenge facing America is whether all
people will have access to new technologies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The setting in which he introduced his plan, a Hispanic
neighborhood in Los Angeles, was arguably more significant than its
details. Bush has frequently appeared with minorities to bolster
his claim of being a new kind of Republican and is aggressively
courting the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, he flew to Houston to speak to the annual
convention of the National Association of Hispanic Journalists.
Last year, Bush provoked complaints from minority journalists at a
conference in Seattle when he declined an invitation to address
them.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CHOICE IN MICHIGAN RACE
</P>
<P>
   The already close Michigan Senate race between the incumbent
freshman Republican, Spencer Abraham, and his Democratic
challenger, Rep. Debbie Stabenow, tightened a bit further this week
with the entry of Mark Forton, a Reform Party candidate and
supporter of Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Forton, a 53-year-old former Republican leader in politically
powerful Macomb County, will probably not sway legions of voters,
but might cause Abraham problems by attracting Republicans upset by
the senator's efforts to help loosen immigration restrictions to
let companies hire more foreign workers. Forton said he would make
immigration a top issue.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SURGES IN CONNECTICUT
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush has erased the nine-point advantage Vice
President Al Gore had among Connecticut voters in April, a new poll
released Wednesday by Quinnipiac University showed. The two
presidential candidates are now in a virtual tie, with Gore at 43
percent and Bush at 42 percent, well within the poll's margin of
sampling error of 2.7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   THRESHOLD SET ON QUALIFIERS
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan panel supervising the presidential debates said
Wednesday that candidates qualifying for the first debate on Oct. 3
would be determined by results of five national polls on Sept. 26.
The panel's chairmen, Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. and Paul G. Kirk Jr.,
said that anyone with average support of 15 percent or more in the
polls would be invited to the debate, to be held at the University
of Massachusetts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the other debates, on Oct. 11 at Wake Forest
University in Winston-Salem, N.C., and Oct. 17 at Washington
University in St. Louis, are to be based on polls taken just before
them. Despite objections by Pat Buchanan, Ralph Nader and other
third-party candidates, officials said the threshold would not
change. Buchanan argues that Kirk and Fahrenkopf, respectively
former Democratic and Republican chairmen, should not decide which
third-party candidates qualify.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: No public events
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Minneapolis and Minnetonka, Minn.; Denver
</P>
</TEXT>
