<HEADLINE>
URANIUM ENRICHMENT PLANT IN OHIO CHOSEN FOR CLOSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ky., Md.)   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The private company that runs the nation's only two
uranium enrichment plants said Wednesday that it would close one of
them in a year, in Portsmouth, Ohio, because of high costs and a
depressed market for reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The other plant, which is in Paducah, Ky., would remain open.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to close the Ohio plant, which would eliminate
about 1,000 jobs, drew criticism from Congress. The Energy
Department, which sold the plants two years ago, has asked pointed
questions recently about whether a shutdown is advisable. Under the
privatization law, the plants were supposed to remain open until
2004, but there was an escape clause if the private entity, the
United States Enrichment Corp., fell into financial difficulties.
The Bethesda, Md., company told the Treasury Department earlier
this week that it had done exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   Until the company's board acted Wednesday, workers, managers and
elected officials in the area of both plants had been apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deeply regret having to take this action, but we clearly
could not continue to operate two production plants,'' said William
H. Timbers, the president and chief executive, in a statement. He
said he would ask the government to hire many of the workers for
environmental restoration at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department, however, issued a critical statement.
``The decision is just the latest in a series of shortsighted
decisions aimed at bolstering the corporation's near-term standing
on Wall Street,'' said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. ``The
decision announced today leaves unanswered fundamental questions
affecting the employees, the corporation's future and USEC's
ability to carry out important national security obligations to the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The security obligation is a reference to a deal struck between
the United States and Russia, to take highly enriched uranium from
the former Soviet weapons program and dilute it for use in reactors
in this country. The company, continuing to carry out the deal
after the federal government sold the factories, agreed to a price
that is now well above the market level.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ted Strickland, D-Ohio, whose district includes the plant,
said he would ask the Treasury Department to seek an injunction
against closing the plant. Among other problems, he said, if
Portsmouth is closed and the Russians prove to be an unreliable
supplier, the Paducah plant would not have sufficient capacity to
provide for the American nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he is preparing legislation to renationalize the
uranium enrichment business.
</P>
<P>
   Both the plants take in uranium in the two most common forms,
uranium-238 and uranium-235, and sort them to raise the proportion
of uranium-235, the type that is most useful in nuclear reactors.
The enrichment technology used at both plants was developed during
World War II, to make the bomb that destroyed Hiroshima. That
technology uses far more electricity than newer systems developed
in Europe and the former Soviet Union, which are now commercial
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   And the market for enrichment has also been depressed by the
deal with the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The Paducah plant, 16 miles west of the Kentucky city, was built
between 1951 and 1954 on a 5,000-acre site. The Portsmouth plant,
which is just south of Piketon, Ohio, in the southern part of the
state, was built between 1952 and 1956. A third Cold War-era
gaseous diffusion plant, at Oak Ridge, Tenn., was shut by the
government in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
