<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-EUROPE-WUERFFEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE MAY HELP WUERFFEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By DWIGHT COLLINS   
 Star-Banner, Ocala, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny Wuerffel was on top of the world in January 1997. He had
just quarterbacked the University of Florida's football team to its
second straight 12-1 season and, this time, the postseason produced
ecstasy instead of agony. The Gators were national champions.
</P>
<P>
   Wuerffel collected the Heisman Trophy and Florida collected the
Sears Trophy. It was a dream season.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans and the Louisiana Superdome _ site of the Gators'
52-20 national title romp in a Sugar Bowl rematch with Florida
State _ came into play again for Wuerffel. Three months later, the
Saints selected Wuerffel in the fourth round of the NFL draft.
Later that year, he started two games for New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three seasons in the NFL, Wuerffel participated in
a third of the Saints games, splitting time with the Billy Joes _
Tolliver and Hobert _ and a handful of others. He made six career
starts, but lacked the magic that surrounded him in college, where
he set records by the bushels and finished his career as the
second-leading passer in SEC history.
</P>
<P>
   With a suspect offensive cast at best, Wuerffel completed 126 of
258 pass attempts for 1,404 yards. In three years, he tossed nine
touchdown passes but was intercepted 16 times and sacked 46 times.
</P>
<P>
   Following the 1999 season, the Saints added free agent
quarterback Jeff Blake and drafted strong-armed Marc Bulger out of
West Virginia. Wuerffel was released.
</P>
<P>
   But, we haven't heard the last of Wuerffel.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to revive his career, the 6-foot-1, 208-pound
quarterback signed on with the Rhein Fire of NFL Europe and spent
the spring calling the signals for former Florida coach Galen Hall,
a fixture in the developmental league since its initial states-side
kickoff in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Wuerffel led NFL Europe in passing and threw for a
league-record 25 touchdowns during the regular season. On Sunday,
he will attempt to lead his Dusseldorf, Germany-based team to the
World Bowl title when the Fire faces the Scottish Claymores in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Small potatoes? Better than no potatoes. Wuerffel is back in a
championship game. He's sweaty again and feeling a rhythm. And he's
piling up numbers, just like old times.
</P>
<P>
   His NFL future is still in limbo. But, so too, were the futures
of Brad Johnson and Jon Kitna before their stints in NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Wuerffel's record-setting passing season comes one year after
Lawrence Phillips set NFL Europe rushing records. Phillips parlayed
his success into an incentive-laden contract with the San Francisco
49ers and had the Bay Area dancing with preseason expectation. The
new Phillips, however, reverted back into the old Phillips and the
49ers and Phillips parted ways at midseason following a run of
insubordination by the one-time, first-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Wuerffel may be able to generate some excitement following his
breakout season in Europe. He may be an afterthought on a team's
camp roster, but should he stick, Wuerffel could contribute more
than Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Capable, young quarterbacks are in high demand in the NFL and
Wuerffel has both qualities, as well as responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Collins writes for The Star-Banner, Ocala, Fla., which is
a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
