<SLUG> BC-NJ-ORANGE-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS CHARGED IN N.J. IN BEATING OF MAN WHO DIED AFTER ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A former lieutenant and four police officers in
the Orange, N.J., Police Department were charged Wednesday with
federal civil rights violations in the beating and assault of a man
who died an hour after being mistakenly arrested in connection with
the murder of another police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The five-count indictment handed up in U.S. District Court here
was the culmination of a 14-month federal and state investigation
into a case that was riddled with police mistakes, multiple charges
of police brutality and wrongful arrests following the April 8,
1999, murder of the police officer, Joyce Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   The case led to upheavals in both the Essex County prosecutor's
office, which supervised the initial investigation into the murder
of the officer, and the Orange Police Department. It eventually led
Gov. Christie Whitman to remove the county's first black, female
prosecutor, Patricia A. Hurt, who directed the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, one of the police officers beat the
man, Earl Faison, 27, when he was stopped on the street three days
after the killing.
</P>
<P>
   He was kicked and punched by the officer while handcuffed and
lying on the sidewalk, said Robert J. Cleary, the U.S. attorney for
New Jersey, and was beaten by four of the officers after being
placed in the back seat of a police car. One of those same officers
later robbed Faison at gunpoint in a stairwell at Orange police
headquarters, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that a fifth officer, Brian Smith, 30,
sprayed pepper spray in Faison's mouth and nose at close range
while he was being held in the stairwell area. The indictment
charges all five with conspiracy to cover up the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Faison, an East Orange resident and an aspiring rap artist, died
at police headquarters about an hour after he was initially stopped
by police. If found guilty in the case, the officers face a maximum
of 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the incident ``an act of vigilantism'' by police
officers, Joseph R. Lewis, the special agent in charge of the
Newark office of the FBI, added: ``It went against the fabric of
law enforcement and all that it stands for. A man, his family and
the law enforcement community suffered because these officers
served as judge and jury for Earl Faison.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Smith, an Orange resident, the others arrested
were his brother, former police lieutenant Thomas Smith, 35, of
Caldwell, who retired from the force in December on disability;
Andrew Garth, 31, of Bloomfield; Tyrone Payton, 34; and Paul
Carpinteri Jr., 36, of Orange. Four of the five officers were
arrested at their homes early Wednesday morning and Brian Smith
turned himself in to FBI agents later in the morning. They all
appeared before U.S. Magistrate Dennis Cavanaugh Wednesday, who set
bail at $150,000 for Thomas Smith and $100,000 for the others. An
arraignment was set for June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining their clients' innocence, the lawyers for all of the
men portrayed them as the victims of lies and ``outrageous
allegations'' by fellow Orange police officers who testified before
a federal grand jury, and of the powerful machinery of federal
prosecutors, the FBI and the Civil Rights Division of the U.S.
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure brought in this case,'' said Peter
Willis, a lawyer for Brian Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But for Earl Williams, Faison's father, who had contended from
the beginning that his son had been beaten, the indictments were a
vindication of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But until we find out exactly who was involved and what took
place, we will have a lot of folks dissatisfied,'' he said,
expressing his suspicion that others were involved in the death of
his son.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Carnegie was shot once in the stomach and once in the
head by a robbery suspect whom she chased in her patrol car. Her
death produced an adrenaline-fueled investigation that led to the
arrest of three suspects. Among them was Faison, who was in a cab
stopped by the police on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   When they sought to question him, he fled. When officers caught
him, they said, they found he had an illegal 9-mm automatic pistol.
Police had already recovered another gun which they said had been
used in the killing. Arrested on April 10 was a Newark man, James
Coker, who was said to have bragged about killing the officer, and
a 24-year-old East Orange resident, Terrance Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Faison died in police custody, Hurt, the Essex
County prosecutor, formally charged Everett, who appeared at his
arraignment with a black eye and a number of bruises. She defended
investigators and not only denied allegations by Everett's lawyers
that he was beaten by police, but said that her investigation of
Faison's death had found no evidence that he was beaten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
