<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EXPANSION EFFORT, FIDELITY REVISES MANAGEMENT AND UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the privately controlled financial giant
in Boston that manages nearly $1 trillion, shuffled its top
executives and reorganized its businesses Wednesday as part of its
effort to move beyond managing mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   James C. Curvey, 65, president and chief operating officer, said
he would leave both posts, but remain at the company. Curvey has
served for three years as the top executive under Edward C. Johnson
III, the chairman and chief executive of Fidelity and son of the
company's founder.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Reynolds, 48, will succeed Curvey as chief operating
officer, effective July 3, and will also be a vice chairman. He
currently runs Fidelity's institutional retirement plans. In his
new role, he will oversee that operation, as well as the brokerage
business.
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Pozen, 53, president of FMR Co., the unit that
includes Fidelity's vast mutual fund management operations, was
also promoted to vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   During Curvey's tenure, Fidelity was transformed from the
largest mutual fund manager into a full-service asset management
company where investors could trade stocks online or from pagers
and hand-held devices, invest in initial public offerings, manage
their estates, set up charitable contributions and open retirement
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In an acknowledgment of the organization's growing complexity,
Curvey said Fidelity would take a more traditional corporate
structure and create three operating units overseen by vice
chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned 65 a couple weeks ago,'' said Curvey, who is a vice
chairman. ``It's time to move some younger people into key
management spots. This is important for the company's long-term
management planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Curvey will return to his previous job running Fidelity Capital
and Ventures, which now includes Fidelity's venture capital
investments and a host of other interests, including life insurance
and telecommunications holdings, as well as the transportation
company Boston Coach.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that the reorganization does not clarify is the
question of who will one day succeed Johnson, who turns 70 this
month. Reynolds and Pozen will report to Johnson. The title of
president will not be filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tipped the title to Reynolds, but not the power,'' said
James H. Lowell III, a former employee of Fidelity and editor of a
newsletter that tracks Fidelity. ``That's very Fidelity. It's all
about competition. I think it's very healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   A third contender to succeed Johnson is his eldest daughter,
Abigail P. Johnson, 38, a senior vice president who is the largest
shareholder of FMR Corp., the holding company that owns Fidelity
Investments. While some in the industry say she will one day run
the company, Fidelity itself did not indicate that possibility
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll stay in the same role,'' Curvey said. ``This
organization doesn't change that at all.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
