<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONDAY NIGHT' DECISION IS NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The identity of Al Michaels' new boothmates on ABC's ``Monday
Night Football'' should be known soon, even by Friday. If Dan Fouts
is one of the choices _ he is at least the leak of the week _ who
is the other?
</P>
<P>
   One imagines that Don Ohlmeyer, who is producing the ``Monday
Night'' overhaul, wants to stun the television world. Decent as
Fouts is, he would be a safe, traditional choice as his TV career
at CBS and ABC has never been memorable.
</P>
<P>
   In this convoluted episode of ``Secret Star Search,'' Fouts
could be Coach Ohlmeyer's decoy, faking a move from college
football but going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   One move made by ABC Wednesday was cutting Lesley Visser as
``Monday Night's'' sole sideline reporter. Ohlmeyer plans to hire
two reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the booth, though, Ohlmeyer must create credible buzz,
although he can't hire John Madden, Phil Simms, Terry Bradshaw,
Howie Long or Cris Collinsworth, and Jimmy Johnson didn't want to
unretire for Monday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't pick a more difficult time to pull something like
this off,'' one industry official said.
</P>
<P>
   The silly suggestions that Ohlmeyer cast comedians like Chris
Rock or Billy Crystal presumes that they are qualified to offer
much more than one-liners or will devote more than a sliver of
their busy schedules to football.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer's choice is said to be someone ignored by the news
media speculation about his overhaul of the post-Boomer Esiason
booth. That talent pool still includes the Teletubbies, Monica
Lewinsky and Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   An inspired choice would be ESPN's Andrea Kremer. She is ESPN's
best football reporter and highly respected by players. Before
ESPN, she worked at NFL Films as a producer, where she built her
knowledge of football's intricacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her greatest strength was preparation,'' said Steve Sabol, the
president of NFL Films. ``She would never go into anything
uninformed.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not widely known, but she would undoubtedly generate
enormous publicity as the first woman to call NFL games regularly.
Gayle Sierens called one regional game for NBC in 1988. Certainly,
Kremer's hiring would raise the attention level and critical
scrutiny accorded 30-year-old ``Monday Night.''
</P>
<P>
   She would be held to a higher standard because she is a woman
and monitored for her chemistry with her partners and the strength
of her voice.
</P>
<P>
   But if she succeeded in making a strong transition from live
reports and taped features to booth commentary, she would most
likely rope in female viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But Kremer has been overlooked by Ohlmeyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't been contacted, although I recommended her for the
sideline job,'' Sandy Montag, her agent, said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the notion of Kremer in the booth ``is not the craziest
idea in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``She has as much football knowledge as many men in
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Football smarts may not be the ticket for the ``Monday Night''
job. Controversy and unpredictability look like the prerequisites,
although there are few such personalities with those qualities.
Even Madden, unpredictable on his best days, has never been
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   The gold standard for ``Monday Night'' controversy was Howard
Cosell, and he produced no known clones. When he quit the show in
1983, Cosell took all controversy with him as if he had invented
it.
</P>
<P>
   Rush Limbaugh auditioned for ABC, but his politics make him a
long shot, despite his Cosellian divisiveness. He also broke the
omerta by publicly discussing his tryout. Another disputatious
voice, Jim Rome, the host of cable's ``The Last Word,'' is locked
into a deal with Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   So as ABC operates under Ohlmeyer's cone of silence, we await
his bombshell _ if he actually has one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
