<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HAVE THEIR DAY IN THE SUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A championship season that was part Shaq thunder,
part Kobe lightning, produced a celebration Wednesday that was all
sun and fun, with vows of another title run.
</P>
<P>
   Just 48 hours after clinching the Lakers' first championship
since 1988, they were promising a repeat in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown L.A. was hot and bright for the midday parade and rally
- an appropriate setting for the hottest, brightest team in the
NBA. Sunglasses were needed just to protect from the bright glare
bouncing off the Larry O'Brien Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   But no cue cards were needed for the Lakers as they addressed
about 100,000 fans outside Staples Center on 11th Street. They knew
just what the city wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long 12 years,'' said Kobe Bryant. ``We finally
brought the championship back to where it belongs, and that's here
in the city of Los Angeles. We're looking forward to coming back
next year and trying to do it again. Thank you for your support. We
love you all.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, Bryant set it up, and Shaquille O'Neal finished.
</P>
<P>
   The theme from ``Superman'' played, O'Neal put out his arms in
mock flight, then stirred up the faithful once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caaan youuuu dig it?'' the NBA Finals MVP bellowed. ``Like
Kobe said, the trophy is home, and where it belongs, and we're
gonna get another one next year. Caaan youuuu dig it?''
</P>
<P>
   All 14 players attended, together for perhaps a final time.
Third- leading scorer Glen Rice is a free agent who seems destined
to play elsewhere, but he used the occasion to make a public
commitment to stay if the team will re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you all, I look forward to being back here next
year to do it again,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency and the need to infuse new, young talent could also
mean the end for Laker veterans Brian Shaw, John Salley, A.C. Green
and Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say I'm probably happier than anybody else on
this stage,'' Shaw enthused, ``because I took a different path to
get here. This is the seventh team I've been on. I finally came to
a team that won a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   He closed with a tribute to O'Neal, who helped Shaw come close
to the title once before, when the two were Orlando Magic teammates
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq, we would not be here without him - `The Big Champion,'
'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, O'Neal could not let the occasion pass without giving
himself one more Big Nickname in a season in which he adopted a new
one every few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, I am no longer `The Big Aristotle,' '' he said,
referring to the name he chose upon winning the regular-season MVP
award. ``I want to be known as `The Big Shakespeare.' Because it
was Shakespeare that said, `Some men are born great, some achieve
greatness, some have greatness thrust upon them,' and it was great
doing it this year for the city and for everybody else. And we're
going to try to get one next year. I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson recalled bringing this group together for the
first time in a gym at UC Santa Barbara at training camp in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it shows what a group of people can put together to make
this many people feel great about basketball,'' he said. ``My hat
goes off to you. These guys put it together, and my coaching staff
and the management, (owner) Jerry Buss and (executive) Jerry
West.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks, confetti and Kool and the Gang's ``Celebration''
closed out the party.
</P>
<P>
   And for the lone member of the team who wore the uniform for the
last celebration, in 1988, it was the perfect ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be here once again,'' Green said.
</P>
</TEXT>
