<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HATE-CRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH STAKES IN ANNUAL, LAST-MINUTE WRANGLING IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With an unusual number of important issues
hanging in the balance, state lawmakers will convene here Thursday
for what is supposed to be the last time this year, having almost,
but not quite, struck deals on hate crimes, gun control and sexual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   This is Albany's annual high-wire act, in which Gov. George
Pataki, the Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, and the Senate
majority leader, Joseph Bruno, each wait for the others to blink,
and much of the important business does not get done until the
last, frenzied days. But the stakes are higher than usual, given
the political and substantive weight of the issues under
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   On issue after issue, officials in one or two of the three camps
have reported in the last few days that after intensive
negotiations there was an agreement in principle _ though the
complex and contentious work of bill-drafting remained _ only to
have one side or the other steadfastly deny any such agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, some of the criminal justice issues have
been linked, so that there may not, in the end, be deals on any of
them unless there are deals on all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be surprised if all of it comes together, and I
would not be surprised if none of it does,'' a top legislative aide
said Wednesday, as negotiations among the three leaders and their
staffs continued into the night.
</P>
<P>
   There have been sporadic talks on a bill to change the
Republicans' much-maligned rules for holding presidential
primaries. All sides agree an accord is still possible, but none
consider it highly likely, if only because the negotiators are
dealing with so many other issues.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other highly charged proposals that have been
discussed appear unlikely to produce agreement, including raising
the minimum wage from $5.15 to $6.75; making information on every
doctor's history of malpractice suits, judgments and settlements
available to the public through a Web site; adding judges to the
New York City courts to relieve overcrowding; and easing
Rockefeller-era drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday was originally scheduled to be the last day of
the legislative session, but with so many issues unresolved,
Silver, a Democrat, and Bruno, a Republican, agreed to have the
Assembly and the Senate return for one day, Thursday. There is
nothing to prevent them from convening again later in the year, but
Bruno has ruled that out, saying that if there are no agreements
Thursday, the Senate will pass its own versions of several bills, a
take-it-or-leave-it gesture to the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of hate crimes, where there is no real disagreement,
has become mired in ego-driven squabbling, and while a deal still
seems likely, it is far from certain. The Assembly and the Senate
have passed similar bills providing longer criminal penalties for
crimes whose victims are singled out due to bias based on race,
sex, religion, age, sexual orientation or disability, an idea
supported by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that for some time, there has been agreement on a
package of gun controls, much like those proposed earlier this year
by the governor, that would be among the most restrictive in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But the gun bill has been tied to an overhaul of New York's
sexual assault laws, an issue that got new impetus with last week's
attacks on women in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, a Republican, and the Senate leaders are seeking
tougher penalties for a variety of sex crimes, and they want to
give prosecutors the right to appeal sentences and bail settings in
sex crime cases. The Assembly's version raises some penalties, but
focuses on improving services for victims, including ensuring
coverage of emergency room services and counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have made concessions, particularly the Democrats,
but there are still some significant differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
