<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-HEARINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING SPURS OPTIMISM AMONG DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON - Having finally had their day to speak, many of the
Dodgers players emerged from Wednesday's six-hour appeals hearing
optimistic their suspensions would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   In what was described as a tedious, detailed presentation of new
evidence and candid statements in support of the players' actions
during a May 16 fight at Wrigley Field, players union
representatives and players gave their versions of what happened
that night to Paul Beeston, chief operating officer for the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Beeston now must sort through the information before ruling on
the suspension appeals. Sixteen players, three coaches and an
on-field assistant were suspended a total of 89 games and $77,000
from the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players had a chance to say what they had to say,''
players association general counsel Gene Orza said from his hotel
room Wednesday night. ``I would not expect a decision within the
next 48 hours. There's a lot of information for Paul has to
digest.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Robinson, vice president of on-field operations for
baseball, handed out the suspensions and was at the hearing, but he
declined comment on the appeals.
</P>
<P>
   When the appeals were filed, the Dodgers and the union contended
many of the suspensions would be reduced or dropped once the
appeals were heard. After being given the chance to explain their
actions to Beeston, the overwhelming feeling was many of the
suspended parties, including many of the core players, would have
their suspensions dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you don't want to look bad and reduce the thing, but I
felt like I shouldn't get one day or get fined one dollar,'' said
Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield, suspended five games and fined
$5,000. ``Just by the fact that (Robinson) made the decision
without hearing everybody's views, are you going to put your pride
aside and say, 'OK I was wrong?' I know that's the million dollar
question, but if you don't put your pride aside, that's unfair
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, save Alan Mills (he was traded to Baltimore) and
attorneys for the players association each spoke. The players
explained to Beeston their thought process during the altercation.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence was presented on behalf of the central figure in the
case, Dodgers backup catcher Chad Kreuter. He was the first one in
the stands after allegedly being struck in the back of the head and
having his cap stolen. Kreuter's agent, Scott Boras, said Kreuter
was only trying to restrain the individual until security was able
to move in.
</P>
<P>
   Also presented during the hearing were the findings of director
of security for Major League Baseball, Kevin Hallinan, which stated
there was insufficient security at Wrigley Field. Also introduced
to Beeston was a doctors note stating Kreuter suffered a sprained
neck from the original slap in the head that triggered he incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the evidence, the film or video and the stills,
portray a very proper line of what went on, and I think they have a
very sound foundation and new evidence they didn't have before,''
Boras said. ``The reason that Chad was in the stands, and it's now
in evidence, is he was assaulted and not that somebody took his
cap. Chad's had his cap taken, as many major-leaguers have, many
times, but he was trying to prevent a perpetrator from leaving the
scene of a crime and there was no security around.''
</P>
<P>
   Each player got to go through their role, and their purpose, in
the altercation, which is what made the ordeal so laborious. The
hearing came nearly a month after Robinson ruled May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's finally coming to an end,'' pitcher Darren
Dreifort said. ``It makes you feel bad for all people that have to
go through murder trials that get dragged out for a year, two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez and F.P. Santangelo were each suspended five games.
Mike Fetters was suspended four games. Antonio Osuna, Chan Ho Park,
Terry Adams, Eric Karros, Shawn Green, Eric Gagne, Dreifort, Todd
Hundley, Geronimo Berroa, Onan Masaoka were each suspended three
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
