<DOCNO> NYT20000621.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-21 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-GAYS-NYT &LR;      06-21 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO FACES UPHILL ROUTE FOR GAY VOTERS' SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Think of running for statewide office in New York as
a series of treacherous political calculations. Especially if you
are a Republican in a Democratic state. Especially when it comes to
gay rights, at a time when your party wants to show a tolerant
face, as you collect support from conservatives not often
sympathetic to gay causes.
</P>
<P>
   Do you, for example, campaign through the dairy farms around
Saratoga, and thus shore up critical upstate support? Or march down
Fifth Avenue in Manhattan with thousands of gays and lesbians for
the Heritage of Pride parade and thereby show an effort to reach
out to voters not normally considered your base?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio _ he of conservative backing but a generally
moderate record in Congress _ is facing such choices in his bid for
the U.S. Senate, one of a number of decisions that gays and
lesbians within his party and out are closely watching. Not to
mention nongay voters, in a race that polls have indicated is
essentially tied. This time, he chose the cows. And now, naturally,
comes the noise.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, in a speech to Bronx
County Democrats on Wednesday night briefly mentioned his decision
not to march as an example of the differences between their
campaigns. And a group of gay advocates ridiculed his choice on the
steps of City Hall as proof that he was a conservative in moderate
clothing. And even some surprised Republicans questioned the
decision, albeit quietly, as something that, in the words of one,
``would not help Rick Lazio in the gay community, adding: ``Their
support is neutral at best. But it would not hurt him with his own
constituency. There was no downside to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, a spokesman for Lazio, said the candidate should be
judged not on attendance at one parade but on what he considered a
solid voting record in Congress on issues of concern to gays and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is not just the parade that has people worked up.
His decision not to march comes amid a series of tests in recent
days on gay rights, an issue that his party has long wrestled with.
</P>
<P>
   Gay supporters in his party are watching what stance he may take
_ none as of Wednesday night _ on a bill the Senate passed Tuesday
that would make hate attacks on gays a federal crime. House
Republican leaders are expected to try to kill it, though there is
some feeling that it may come up for a vote before Election Day.
McLagan said Lazio would wait to see what version, if any, came up
in the House before stating an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who has declined to co-sponsor previous legislation in
the House related to hate crimes, said he backed a hate crimes bill
that passed in the Republican-controlled New York state Senate two
weeks ago. It is expected to sail through the Democratic-controlled
Assembly and be signed by Gov. George E. Pataki, a moderate
Republican who is trumpeting Lazio's candidacy. Lazio declared his
support only after the bill passed and after first wavering on
whether he supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Gays make up an estimated 5 to 7 percent of the New York
electorate, sizable enough to influence a very tight race. But that
may not be the point.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, sensitive to charges of right-wing extremism, have
been moving toward the center in the last several years and have
taken steps to show tolerance as a way to draw independent and
``swing'' voters who hold no strong allegiance to either party.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tafel, executive director of the Log Cabin Republicans,
a gay political organization based in Washington, said a remarkable
shift has occurred in that candidates across the country now reach
out to a group they had previously shunned. Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas met with gay political representatives last year in what
Tafel termed an unprecedented meeting for a presumptive Republican
presidential nominee. The New York chapter of the Log Cabin
Republicans exulted last month over acceptance of its first
delegation to a state-nominating convention and has posted a
picture on its Web site of its chapter leader shaking hands with
William D. Powers, the state Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, Tafel said, has a mixed voting record on issues of
concern to gays, consistently supporting financing for several
federal AIDS programs, for example, while declining to co-sponsor
the hate crimes legislation in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, Lazio has faithfully attended Log Cabin
briefings and is generally seen as a friend to the group; the
president of the New York chapter said it had been promised a
meeting with Lazio within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay Democrats are attacking him more out of loyalty to their
party,'' he said. ``This is partisan politics and not gay
politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
