<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE-WEB-HIJACKED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS TAKE OVER NIKE WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Protesters took control of the Nike Web site on Wednesday and
redirected visitors to a site urging organizations to gather at and
disrupt a world economic summit planned for later this year in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, the footwear company, said the action made its site
inaccessible for up to 7 hours to some visitors starting at 10 a.m.
Eastern time Wednesday, and the company said it was working with
law enforcement officials to determine the origin of and group
responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it'll be too hard to find out who did it,''
said Corby Casler, a company spokeswoman, adding that it was
unclear whether the company or the government would be able to take
any action in response to the attack. ``Knowing who did it and
being able to prove it are two different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Casler said that Web site that was attacked is the main
e-commerce site for Nike, but said it was too soon to tell whether
the company lost revenue, and, if so, how much.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, though it has come under attack for its treatment of
workers at overseas factories, which critics allege are sweatshops,
is not the first to have its Web site redirected or defaced by
so-called hacktivists. Groups opposing a variety of corporate and
government activities have increasingly taken to cyberspace to put
their own messages in place of an institution's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Nike site was redirected to a site of an
organization called S11 Alliance based in Australia. On the site,
the group is described as a network of groups and individuals
concerned about ``the growth of corporate power and the direction
of globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if S11 was involved in the actual redirection.
E-mail inquiries sent to S11 were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's Web site calls for protesters to use
nonviolent means to shut down the World Economic Forum 2000, a
gathering of economists, academicians, executives and government
officials, to be held on Sept. 11 to Sept. 13 in Melbourne,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The site does not specify particular grievances against Nike,
except to include it on a list of World Economic Forum
participants, along with companies such as Exxon, Honeywell,
McDonald's, Phillip-Morris and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike is used to dealing with this type of thing,'' Casler
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
