<HEADER>
A1307 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-MCCOY-OLYMPICTRIA     06-21 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MCCOY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLER'S BEST MOVE MAY HAVE BEEN TO COLORADO
</HEADLINE>
 TRIALS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Kerry McCoy didn't want to chance any more near misses.
</P>
<P>
   He had already lost a berth in the super-heavyweight finals at
the 1998 freestyle wrestling World Championships, after a
controversial decision overturned his semifinals victory.
</P>
<P>
   He had already seen, too, a berth in the 1999 Worlds slip away
when he lost his final World Trials bout to Stephen Neal, after he
had become the only man to defeat Neal that year.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, a 1994 and 1997 NCAA heavyweight champion for Penn State,
didn't want another near miss when it came to the 2000 Olympic
team. So in September he decided he couldn't afford any near misses
with his focus. He left his job as a Penn State assistant wrestling
coach and moved to the Olympic Training Center in Colorado Springs,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   By moving to Colorado, McCoy has brought his Olympic goal
closer. He defeated Neal, who had gone on to win the 1999 World
title, at the USA Wrestling nationals in April. The victory earned
McCoy a berth in the finals of the U.S. Olympic Team Trials, which
start today at Reunion Arena in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be bitter and say, `Well, my time is gone,' or say,
`He's done it, but I can beat him.' I chose to look at it as the
latter,'' he said. ``The main thing is to make the Olympic team,
and \Rthe move\S has put me in great position.''
</P>
<P>
   With his berth in the finals, McCoy again has the upper hand on
Neal, whom he defeated in the 1997 NCAA finals. The past season has
provided a big boost of confidence for McCoy, who took full
advantage while Neal recovered from post-Worlds shoulder surgery.
McCoy has 2000 World Cup and Pan American Championships titles to
his credit, as well as a 16-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   His coach at the Olympic Training Center, 1992 Olympic champion
Kevin Jackson, believes McCoy will continue that dominance in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just needed to put himself in an environment where
he could get quality workouts, and also work on things that
opponents would try to do to him,'' Jackson said. ``I felt that
would put him over the top. He was very close on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   While on his own, McCoy let his freestyle training sometimes
take a backseat to other duties. In addition to his assistant
coaching job with the Nittany Lions, he also served as chairman of
the NCAA Student-Athlete Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, a 1992 junior world champion, did better than many
athletes despite his outside interests. In 1995-96 he took a
redshirt year at Penn State and finished third at the 1996 Olympic
Team Trials. After finishing fifth at the 1998 U.S. nationals, he
won the World Trials before his controversial loss at Worlds.
</P>
<P>
   At the Worlds in Iran, McCoy had defeated Alexis Rodriguez of
Cuba 1-1 on a referee's decision in the semifinals. The Cuban team
protested, and FILA, the governing body of the sport, reviewed the
match. Instead of having the two athletes wrestle again, FILA gave
Rodriguez a 4-1 victory. Rodriguez went on to win the world title,
while McCoy finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy just missed a chance at qualifying for the 1999 Worlds. In
the U.S. team trials finals in June, Neal won the first bout of the
best-of-three series, 2-1, in overtime. McCoy won the next bout,
3-1, in overtime, then lost the third bout 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The loss prompted McCoy to move to the Olympic Training Center.
Since then, with his room and board paid for, he has worked
full-time at wrestling, surrounded by top-level training partners
and coaches. He believes the extra training showed at nationals,
where he got the early jump on Neal in the finals and won, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to let him control the pace of the match. That's
the game you play,'' McCoy said. ``I've definitely gotten better on
the bottom, and learned to turn guys better. But when you're
training like this, the big thing is you don't tend to doubt
yourself as much.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's finals, McCoy will meet the winner of the
challenge tournament, which takes place today and tomorrow. He said
he cannot afford to assume it will be Neal he sees in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two to three guys who are really good. If it's
Steve, after nationals he's going to be coming that much harder,''
he said. ``But I've wrestled all the top guys in the world and
beaten them all. My time is not past.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
