A1310 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MP3SUMMIT-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3SUMMIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MP3 SUMMIT ATTRACTS TOP GADGET PRODUCERS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA  
 c. 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ While major record labels are fretting over how to
deal with the popularity of the file-sharing program Napster,
consumer electronics manufacturers are rushing to cash in on it.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known manufacturers such as RCA, Sony and Samsung showed up
at the two-day MP3 Summit here to promote a spate of new digital
players that are about to flood the market. In one measure of how
big the field is growing, Texas Instruments has designed digital
signal processors used in more than 30 portable audio players.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the original Diamond Rio MP3 player, which stored
about an hour of music, this new generation of digital jukeboxes
lets music fans take hundreds, if not thousands, of songs out on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   For example, HanGo Electronics Inc. of South Korea shipped a
second version of its Personal Jukebox this week. The $800 device
stores about 100 hours of music, the equivalent of 1,500 songs, in
a box that's about 6 inches long and 3 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our customers are travelers,'' said Mike Hamer, sales
director for MP3factorydirect.com, the San Diego Web site that
handles sales of the Personal Jukebox. ``You can fly from here to
Australia and never hear the same song twice.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar product set to go on sale later this year is Creative
Lab's Nomad Jukebox, a 14-ounce device the size of a CD player but
also capable of storing 6 gigabytes of MP3, WMA or .WAV files.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rapidly emerging jukebox categories cuts the desktop
computer out of the equation with an all-in-one jukebox plugged
into the home stereo or television to handle MP3s, CDs, DVDs,
e-mail and about everything else except the laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to get MP3 beyond just the tech community,''
said Dave Arland, public relations director for Thomson Consumer
Electronics, which makes products under the RCA brand. ``I want to
get my mother into MP3s.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson debuted five new versions this week of the Lyra portable
digital music player that it introduced at last year's MP3 Summit.
RCA plans to have the new models, including a $300, 2-by-2 inch
player and a $400 bookshelf MP3-CD stereo system, on retail store
shelves in various stages between now and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The last on the market will be RCA's Digital Media Manager, a
``computer dressed up like an audio component,'' that will cost
less than $1,000, Arland said. The device can store more than 2,000
MP3 songs and play DVDs and CDs. And using a regular TV set, the
unit can be used to organize songs by genre, along with accessing
data like TV program listings from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MP322 (79002 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The company has identified a certain class of consumers who may
be scared of computers, particularly older consumers who did not
grow up with a computer mouse in their hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've identified them as D.I.F.M. _ Do It for Me,'' Arland
said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a lesser-known company called ZapMedia.com Inc. of
Atlanta also displayed its ZapStation, another Internet-connected
device that can store 10,000 MP3-compressed songs, organize play
lists, plays CDs and DVDs and send and receive e-mail. ZapMedia,
which is trying to land deals with broadband providers that would
lower retail costs for consumers, signed a $270 million partnership
last month with the Gannett Co. to link the ZapStation to Internet
content, such as news from USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Another player in the field is Lydstrom Inc., a Boston company
that started selling its SongBank SL machine on the Internet last
week. The $800 unit can store a digital music collection of up to
7,000 songs. The product can also copy, or rip, songs from CDs in
one-quarter of the actual playing time without the need for a
desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, Diamond Multimedia's new Rio Receiver is able
to play music streamed from a home computer through existing phone
lines to other rooms in the house. The company also unveiled its
newest Rio 600 digital audio player, which sports a sleeker design
and the ability to expand from its base of 32 megabytes of storage
up to 340 MB.
</P>
<P>
   For a virtually unlimited supply of songs, a San Diego company
called Fun eBusiness displayed the prototype for an
Internet-connected jukebox that is designed like the old
1950s-style Wurlitzer that used to be the centerpiece of many a
malt shop.
</P>
<P>
   This modern Wurlitzer, which the company hopes to roll out in
August, has a catalog of more than 200,000 MP3 songs and will be
marketed to bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of MP322 (79002 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
