<HEADLINE>
HANDSPRING LOOKS GOOD TO INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY YAMANOUCHI  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Handspring Inc. saw its stock surge 35 percent
on its first day of trading yesterday, a signal of investor
optimism in the company's handheld product and the strength of that
market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Handspring rose $6.94 to $26.94 as the Mountain View,
Calif., company ended the day with a market capitalization of $3.37
billion. By comparison, Handspring's chief rival, Palm Inc., rose
to a high of $165 on its first day of trading before plunging to
yesterday's closing price of $27.75.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were undoubtedly impressed with the two executives
leading Handspring: Chairman and Chief Product Officer Jeffrey
Hawkins and President and Chief Executive Officer Donna Dubinsky.
The two founded Palm but left the company two years ago after it
became a part of 3Com Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, with Hawkins behind it, it was a good deal, and
investors know that,'' said Michael Falbo, an analyst with IPO Pros
in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   James Johnson, an analyst with A.G. Edwards, agreed. ``You've
got the founders of Palm in management, they do have a
differentiated product, there is a lot of movement in PDA (personal
digital assistant) space overall.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of HANDSPRI (70637 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  However, the path leading to yesterday's impressive performance
was not smooth. The company had initially planned to raise up to
$300 million but was advised to lower its prices after Palm stock
plummeted in April.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring eventually decided to sell 10 million shares at $20
each, raising $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring's Visor handhelds are similar to the Palm III line,
but they include a unique slot, called Springboard, that lets users
add devices such as cellular phones, MP3 players and digital
cameras. Handspring's lowest-priced configuration is also slightly
cheaper than Palm's entry-level models.
</P>
<P>
   Handspring's entry into the handheld market comes at a time when
consumers increasingly are turning to portable devices such as
notebook computers, handhelds and cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the company's filing with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission indicated that the number of installed handheld
computers will reach 32.5 million units in 2003, from 8.2 million
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Handspring is going to shake up retail a bit,''
Johnson said. ``They bring to the table another option.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of HANDSPRI (70637 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Analysts were impressed with Handspring's showing yesterday given
the shaky condition of the IPO market. ``The IPO market has been
relatively weak, and the fact that Handspring was able to do so
well actually was an exception rather than the rule,'' said Steven
Tuen, an analyst with IPO Value Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Handspring can successfully compete against Palm remains
to be seen. Thus far, it has gained 31 percent of the U.S. retail
electronic organizer market compared with 57 percent for Palm.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuen said Handspring will have its hands full. ``Palm is so
much larger and will prove to be a fierce competitor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the analyst said Handspring will not necessarily be in
for the roller-coaster ride that Palm has taken. ``I think the
investors that went into Handspring learned from the experience,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at kyamanouchi(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of HANDSPRI (70637 ) &QL;
</P>
