</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCRAMBLE TO SALVAGE SPRINT-WORLDCOM DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to correct wording at end of 10th graf, which begins:
Worldcom faces...)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Facing mounting opposition from regulators to its $115 billion
deal to acquire Sprint, WorldCom is considering selling broad
swaths of Sprint's operations, including Sprint's entire
long-distance unit, people close to the companies said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations continue between the company and the Justice
Department, which is reviewing the deal's antitrust implications in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Mario Monti, head of the European Commission's competition
ministry, now appears inclined to block the deal over concern that
the combined company would have too much control over the world's
long-distance telephone market as well as a stranglehold on
Internet traffic in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the deal involves two American companies, the
European Commission has the power to block it. The commission,
based in Brussels, Belgium, is the executive arm of the 15-nation
European Union. It claims jurisdiction over any merger involving
companies that do more than $200 million in business in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It has been clear since the deal was announced last year that
the combined company would at least have to sell Sprint's Internet
business, and the Justice Department appears to have accepted that
element of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the European regulators would prefer that the combined
company spin off WorldCom's UUNET Internet operation, the world's
No. 1 Internet carrier. WorldCom executives have said that they
would rather scrap the acquisition altogether than sell UUNET.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, meanwhile, is mainly concerned about the
power a combined Sprint-WorldCom would hold over the long-distance
telephone business in the United States, according to people close
to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard J. Ebbers, WorldCom's chief executive, has long been
prepared to sell off Sprint's consumer long-distance operation as
well as the Sprint brand. But the Justice Department appears also
to want a divestiture of Sprint's unit that sells long-distance
services to business customers. WorldCom was built on serving
business customers.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the approval discussions said Wednesday that
WorldCom expected its talks with the Justice Department to conclude
by the beginning of next week, at the latest. Monti is to meet this
week with regulators and officials in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom faces particular resistance in Europe, in part because
many European officials believe it failed to follow through
properly on a pledge to spin off the MCI Communications' Internet
business after WorldCom agreed to buy MCI in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   To win approval of that acquisition, WorldCom promised to sell
MCI's Internet business to Cable and Wireless of Britain. But Cable
and Wireless later complained to the European Commission that the
sale was incomplete, failing to include some employees as well as
some contracts. WorldCom settled the dispute privately, and the
European Commission did not pursue the issue. But the affair left a
bad taste with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once burned, twice shy,'' said Maurits Dolmans, an antitrust
lawyer in Brussels for Cleary, Gottlieb Steen &AMP; Hamilton. ``This
time the commission is going to make very, very sure that any
spinoff of Sprint's Internet business is carried out quickly,
fully, completely and will be entirely enforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the European Commission's rules, the case must be decided
by July 5. But the European and U.S. regulators are almost sure to
coordinate their demands.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps in recognition of the inevitable, WorldCom is now
considering a plan to sell off Sprint's entire long-distance
business, in addition to Sprint's Internet operation. Such a plan
would almost surely appease the regulators but would skew the
financial plan that underpinned the acquisition in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the deal is Sprint's wireless telephone
operation, one of the biggest in the United States. Neither
WorldCom nor the old MCI owned a significant wireless network, and
WorldCom hopes to generate a lot more revenue by adding Sprint's
wireless offerings to its portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   But while Sprint's wireless unit is growing quickly, it remains
highly unprofitable. Last year, it lost $2.5 billion on $3.2
billion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the main attraction of WorldCom's stock has long
been its robust growth in per-share earnings. With the exception of
its acquisition of the Wiltel communications network a few years
ago, WorldCom has shied away from acquisitions that would dilute
its per-share earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's wireless unit trades as a ``tracking stock,'' which
helps isolate its losses from the financial results of the parent
company. But in deciding to pay $115 billion for Sprint, WorldCom
was counting on billions of dollars of cost savings from combining
the Sprint and WorldCom long-distance operations.
</P>
<P>
   But if WorldCom is forced to sell Sprint's long-distance
operation, it will not be able to realize those savings, throwing
into question the financial structure of the original deal. One way
out of this quandary would be to sell Sprint's long-distance unit
to another company that could generate similar cost savings. But if
the Sprint long-distance unit were sold to, say, a foreign company
or a Bell local carrier, the cost savings that could be realized
would be far smaller.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, unless it could renegotiate the deal with Sprint,
WorldCom would effectively end up paying a lot more than it had
planned for Sprint's wireless operation. That raises the prospect
that selling off Sprint's long-distance business in exchange for
regulatory approval would end up a Pyrrhic victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
