u a BC-NY-STRANGLER-PLEA-NYT     06-21 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STRANGLER-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILTY PLEA IS ACCEPTED IN STRANGLING DEATHS OF 8 WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ A 28-year-old man admitted Wednesday that
he strangled eight women here over two years, entering a guilty
plea that will spare him the possibility of execution.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Kendall L. Francois, had confessed details of the
murders when he was arrested in 1998, police said, but he pleaded
not guilty to charges of first-degree murder at his indictment.
Later, when Francois tried to change his plea to guilty _ a step
that would avoid the possibility of execution _ the Dutchess County
district attorney, William V. Grady, refused to accept it, saying
he wanted to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Grady said Wednesday that he still favored execution, but that
he allowed Francois to plead guilty chiefly because some victims'
relatives did not want details of the crimes made public at a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the families do not want their children and
grandchildren needlessly exposed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grady added that although he believes that Francois was not
insane at the time, the defendant does have clear psychological
problems that might lead a jury to decide against the death
penalty. Theoretically, that would make it possible for Francois to
be paroled someday.
</P>
<P>
   Francois, who contracted HIV in 1995, said in court Wednesday
that he had received no medication during his 22 months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood before Judge Thomas J. Dolan of County Court,
Francois' one-word answers were murmured and barely audible. Dolan
and Grady asked him to speak up several times.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of detail in his answers enraged Heidi Cramer, the
daughter of a victim, Sandra Jean French. Outside court, she said
she had expected a full description of Francois' actions and
remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a public disclosure of everything he did to our
mother,'' she told reporters. ``His mother can go visit him in jail
any time. I can't go visit my mother, except in an urn in my
closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois has admitted storing the decomposing bodies of victims
in his home for two years. His mother, Paulette Francois, who lived
with him in the house, was never charged with any crime, and has
made virtually no public statements about the case since her son's
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in a written statement given to reporters by her lawyer,
she expressed sympathy for the victims' families and gratitude
toward prosecutors for accepting the guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed that death followed by more death is
not a solution and never will be,'' she wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
