<HEADER>
A1318 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-SFCHRON &LR;      06-21 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VERDE TURNS BROWN AND DRIES UP AFTER GOBBLING ITS GREENBACKS  &HT;     By DON FOST  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apparently, Kermit the Frog had it right: It's
not easy being green.
</P>
<P>
   Verde Media, a San Francisco Internet company devoted to all
things environmental, sent its employees packing last week, as
management said it had run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   The firm appears dead just after it got off the ground. It
launched in April, on Earth Day, seeking to provide a wide range of
green content, from healthy living to ecotourism to the science and
politics of global warming.
</P>
<P>
   It was launched by Ted Turner's son-in-law, Peek Garlington III,
and company press releases listed Turner among the funders. Reached
in Atlanta on Tuesday, Garlington was vague about the fate of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was at liberty to talk to you but I really can't,''
he said. ``We are in negotiations with two separate
counter-parties. I can't talk about the disposition or what we're
doing with our company.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not elaborate on what he meant but said he expected to
have an announcement next week.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Rickenbacker, the executive vice president of
programming, was one of the few staffers to remain on duty at the
company's Bush Street offices, but Rickenbacker did not return
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to other investors also were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Former employees _ there were an estimated 40 to 50 people
working there _ describe a company full of people passionately
committed to the environment, done in by overspending and a
problematic software system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Verde's problem may have been dreaming too big for the
market,'' said Michael Mechanic, an editor. ``We all had really big
dreams. We may have been better off starting a little bit
smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Lizette Wilson, a reporter, said even in the final weeks, the
company sent employees on a whitewater rafting trip. (When Wilson,
a former colleague of mine at the Marin Independent Journal, got
the call on her cell phone on St. Patrick's Day that she got the
job at Verde, she let out a loud whoop and yelled to editors,
``I've been dot-commed!'')
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and others also said the company spent millions on a
software system that proved too slow to post content at Web speed.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Neagle, a former news editor at The Chronicle, joined Verde
four months ago and said the end did not come as a complete
surprise, as it followed a series of ``disquieting rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great place to work,'' Neagle said. ``The editorial
product was really good. I'd go back if I thought there was a
chance to succeed. All of us would.''
</P>
<P>
   Verde's Web site still offers a place to apply for a job.
``Verde Media is looking for talented people to create and promote
our Web site!'' the site says. ``Verde staffers help the members of
our community make the planet greener, a shade or two at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad they didn't make enough greenbacks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SNAP SHUT: NBC Internet was, from its inception, a confusing
animal. It was formed when the NBC television network struck a deal
to hard-wire its Web properties with the Web portal Snap (developed
by Cnet) and the community-builder Xoom.com. When
business-to-business became the big buzzword, NBCi acquired B2B
software firm Flyswat.
</P>
<P>
   It's now paying the price for that diffusion: Its stock has
plummeted from $106.13 in January to $13.44 yesterday, it announced
an earnings shortfall last week and it has suffered through dot-com
advertising drops and management turnover.
</P>
<P>
   But Will Lansing, who joined as chief executive officer this
spring, is moving to straighten things out. Lansing is eliminating
the Snap and Xoom brands, pushing NBCi to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   He figures he'll spend $100 million a year during the next three
years in promoting that brand, and with $200 million in ``soft
promotion'' from NBC _ which owns 40 percent of the company _ the
total will come close to a half-billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   He's got big ambitions. ``We see Yahoo and AOL as our
competition,'' he said in a phone interview yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a risky gambit.
</P>
<P>
   Internet analyst Lowell Singer of Robertson Stephens says that
while NBC is a great brand to build on, Snap and Xoom also have
consumer awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Snap and Xoom were big enough to get them into the
top 10'' sites on the Web, Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing said only the names will go away; NBCi isn't eliminating
any jobs. He plans to keep the company at about 780 people, still
hiring talent but getting rid of some positions through ``selective
weeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The company may appear on the ropes, but Lansing holds a long
view. ``These are the early days,'' he said. ``There's still a big
population that has to choose how to access resources and content
on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JUST WONDERING: If dot-com mania constituted a ``new economy'' as
so many magazines and Web sites would have us believe, then do the
hard times befalling dot-commers in the wake of this spring's
Nasdaq downturn constitute the new new economy?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BREAKING THE MOLD: Never mind the stereotype of some
purple-haired, nose-pierced Webhead reading the riot act to old
media. On stage at this week's Newspaper Association of America
convention at the Moscone Center was burly silver-haired Shaun
Higgins, director of marketing and sales for the Spokesman Review
in Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins took part in a panel on newspapers and the Web, and
while other panelists had good if not groundbreaking ideas, Higgins
_ despite his old-media looks _ stood out for these unorthodox
comments:
</P>
<P>
   --``I want complete separation between print and online.'' (By
that, he means the online unit must be autonomous enough to move at
Internet speed, while maintaining the ability to post the
newsroom's content as soon as the paper goes to press.)
</P>
<P>
   --``It surprises me how much more our readers know than our
writers about topics our writers are writing about. We have to tap
into people who aren't journalists but who are better than our
journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   --``In online, the standards don't have to be as high, because
the costs aren't as high.'' (In other words, feel free to use those
amateurs, and to post at Internet speed, as long as you maintain a
good corrections policy.)
</P>
<P>
   That sort of blunt talk will almost surely cost Higgins his
friends in the newsroom, but he says it's making his Web site a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE GLASS PALACE, REVEALED: As the wraps come off Revolution
magazine _ a new title from Imagine Media devoted to dance music _
the secrecy shrouding the locale of the publication's launch party
has also lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's party will be the first-of-its-kind event at what the
mag's reps are calling ``the glass palace,'' a 15,000-square-foot
warehouse in the Presidio, across from the newly redeveloped Crissy
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Publicists imagine thousands of people dancing until 3 in the
morning, with contortionists, go-go dancers, models and
skateboarders doing their thing to films, slides, videos and the
funky beats provided by DJs.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch is: It's invitation only.
</P>
