<SLUG> BC-WELLSFARGO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Wells Fargo Hit With Racial Bias Suit  
 By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 THE San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An activist group filed suit yesterday in a
Texas federal court, charging Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. with racial bias in
the home lending section of its Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN, a national organization representing low-income people,
said a community locator feature on the San Francisco bank's Web
site refers prospective home buyers to neighborhoods based in large
part on their race. For example, the bank's Internet ``Community
Calculator'' feature refers people who live in predominantly black
communities to ZIP code regions with large black populations in the
area where they plan to move.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ACORN said, the Wells site classifies neighborhood
``lifestyles'' based on blatant racial stereotypes. According to
ACORN, the site says some inner-city, black-majority communities
have a ``distressed neighborhoods'' lifestyle, characterized by
single parenthood, high unemployment and a taste for ``urban/new
adult contemporary music, chicken takeout, bars and dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WELLS22 (98595 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I don't know how much more stereotyped you can get,`` said Mike
Daniels, a Dallas civil rights lawyer working for ACORN.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN wants Wells to drop the features it considers offensive
from the site. It also wants the bank to step up mortgage lending
in Dallas-area minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo spokesman Jon Ferchen said the bank hadn't had a
chance to review the lawsuit and couldn't comment specifically on
it. But, he said, the bank has a strong fair-lending record and is
the nation's leading mortgage lender to ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Community Calculator on our Internet site, for relocating
home buyers, is designed to help customers make informed buying
decisions using criteria such as education levels, housing
characteristics, household by type, crime index and population,''
Ferchen said. The service ``is not designed to use race as a tool
to guide home buyers' decision making.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo didn't write the neighborhood descriptions itself.
The bank buys the material from Internet startup HomeFair.com,
which, in turn, uses demographic data and lifestyle descriptions
supplied by CACI Marketing Systems, a Virginia market research
firm.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WELLS22 (98595 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Because this is a matter in litigation, we feel it is
inappropriate to comment,'' CACI Managing Director David Huffman
said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for HomeFair's parent, Homestore.com, said the
company's service ``does not violate the rights of any protected
class.''
</P>
<P>
   An unscientific test of Wells Fargo's community locator
suggested that people who live in predominately black neighborhoods
will be referred to other areas with large African American
populations.
</P>
<P>
   When the locator was told that a home buyer living in San
Francisco's largely black Bayview-Hunters Point neighborhood was
moving to New York City, the service steered the buyer to similar
communities in Brooklyn, Newark, N.J., and East Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of WELLS22 (98595 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
