<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REVIEW: Wireless Net Devices Still Need Work  &HT;     By HENRY NORR  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; Cell phones, pagers, PDAs _ think of a
category of portable consumer electronics and someone's racing to
turn it into a wireless Internet access device.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks I've been testing three of the latest
entries in this category: the OmniSky system, which adds a wireless
modem to a Palm V or Vx; a bundle from Compaq that combines a radio
modem with the company's new iPAQ Pocket PC; and the BlackBerry
957, a superpager from an up-and-coming Canadian company called
Research in Motion (a.k.a. RIM).
</P>
<P>
   For the handful of users who simply have to have constant online
access wherever they go, all three products are probably better
than any current cell phone. But they're all expensive, and the
OmniSky and Compaq products are slow and, at least in my testing,
riddled with bugs. For the average Internet junkie, they're just
not ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RIM BlackBerry 957
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the three devices, the only one that consistently worked as
advertised was the BlackBerry 957.
</P>
<P>
   This new $499, 5.3-ounce unit is the latest addition to a line
of two-way pagers RIM has offered for several years. But while the
Waterloo, Ontario, company's previous models looked like slightly
overgrown beepers, the 957 could pass for a Palm, except that it
has a miniature 33-key keyboard instead of Palm's buttons and
pen-input area.
</P>
<P>
   The 957's 2.2-inch-square screen is of the gray-green reflective
type, but it's exceptionally crisp and clear. I found it easier to
read than any Palm except the color IIIC model.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it's so good is that it's not a touch screen _ you
control the device not with a stylus but with a thumb-operated
wheel on the upper right side, which does double duty as an Enter
button, and a second button just below it that functions as an
Escape key.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, you choose among the many options the device offers
by scrolling, then picking from lists and menus. When you need to
enter text, you bang it out on the tiny keyboard, normally with
your two thumbs. It sounds awkward, but it's easy to learn and
surprisingly speedy.
</P>
<P>
   Built into the BlackBerry, in addition to e-mail software, are
the standard personal-information applications: address book,
calendar, alarm clock, memo pad and task list. The startup screen
has 13 icons, but the rest of the system is text-based. Visually,
it's a little like working on a DOS PC _ the system actually runs
on a vintage 1986 Intel 386 processor _ but without DOS' arcane
complexities.
</P>
<P>
   Like virtually every other personal digital assistant these
days, the BlackBerry comes with a cradle that attaches to your PC,
plus software for synchronizing data with just about all the
leading personal-information-management programs for Windows.
(There's no support for the Mac.)
</P>
<P>
   The cradle also functions as a charger for the BlackBerry's
built-in lithium battery.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the original Palm VII, the BlackBerry doesn't require a
special e-mail address _ it comes with software that forwards your
regular mail. (I used RIM's Desktop Redirector application for
Windows, which forwards messages from your inbox, but the company
also provides software that works with Microsoft Exchange server.
There's also a separate version available for Internet service
providers.)
</P>
<P>
   Messages are forwarded to a paging network that retransmits them
over the air. It operates at only 9.6 kilobits per second, but
since it transmits only bare text _ no fancy formatting, no
attachments and, so far, no viruses _ it feels surprisingly quick.
</P>
<P>
   When I first set up the BlackBerry, it refused to forward
anything but a small subset of my incoming mail, and it took a
couple of calls to RIM tech support to get the problem resolved.
Both times I called, however, technicians answered on the second or
third ring, and both were knowledgeable, patient and friendly.
Since they fixed the problem, the device has worked like a charm.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, I found the BlackBerry a remarkably effective e-mail
solution. My only real gripe is that it doesn't offer any way to
select multiple messages to delete in one operation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WIRELESS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Beyond that, the only serious drawback to the BlackBerry _ a
significant one in this day and age, especially considering the
price of the device and service _ is that for now it's limited to
e-mail; the standard version provides no access to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   That will change soon, to a degree _ RIM has contracted with a
San Francisco company called Neomar to develop a BlackBerry version
of its microbrowser based on the Wireless Application Protocol
(WAP), which offers access to a limited range of online information
and transactions from their phones.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, RIM this week announced plans to work with
Oracle on the new AskAtOracleMobile service, which will provide
free information such as flight schedules, stock prices and
directions through an automated e-mail system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OmniSky for Palm V and Vx
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OmniSky's product combines a radio modem from Novatel Wireless,
software from Aether Systems and service over AT&AMP;T's Cellular
Digital Packet Data (CDPD) network. You have to provide your own
Palm V or Vx ($329 or $399, respectively), but everything else _
hardware, software and service agreement _ comes in one $299 box.
Unlimited monthly service is $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Novatel modem latches neatly around the Palm, matching the
distinctive flaring base of the V and Vx. The combination is much
bulkier than the sleek Palm V models by themselves but not much
larger than other Palms or most Windows CE devices.
</P>
<P>
   (Novatel also makes a version of the same modem for the Palm
III, IIIe and IIIx; it's bundled with software and wireless service
by Go America _ see
www.goamerica.net/html/showcase/products/minstrelIII.)
</P>
<P>
   The hardware design is certainly elegant, and it's much sleeker
than Compaq's bulkier add-on, but it also has a significant
drawback Compaq managed to avoid: You have to remove the modem to
put the Palm in its cradle, which you have to do regularly because
that's the only way to charge the Palm V/Vx internal battery. And
since the modem relies on its own lithium battery, you have to
charge that separately, using a different AC adapter and cable.
</P>
<P>
   With the service, you get a mail account at OmniSky.net, but you
can also check mail at up to six other Internet (POP3) mail
accounts. Unlike the BlackBerry, which receives messages whenever
it's on, the OmniSky checks for mail only when you tell it to. By
default, it first gets just message headers and the first 500 bytes
of each message; you then select those for which you want the full
text, so actually getting to the substance of your mail involves a
number of steps.
</P>
<P>
   You can, of course, set the device to get the full text on the
first pass, but that exacerbates what's already the worst problem
with OmniSky mail: It's horrendously slow. In my testing it
retrieved only 15 to 25 headers per minute. It also gets the oldest
messages first, so if you haven't used it for a day or two you have
to slog through all the old stuff before you get to your latest
missives.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with already received headers and messages is also a
problem. You can select all and delete, but if you're not ready to
do that you have to file or delete each message one by one; as with
the BlackBerry, you can't select multiple messages.
</P>
<P>
   As for Web browsing, the good news is that the OmniSky lets you
get at a far wider range of content than the Palm VII: In addition
to working with sites that support Palm's limited Web Clipping
query format, OmniSky offers content optimized for its small screen
and modest bandwidth from more than 2,000 sites, including most of
the most popular destinations on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The OmniSky software steers you to these sites by building in
links to them, organized by category (Finance, Travel, Shopping,
News, etc.). But if you're not satisfied with the optimized content
and want to visit other sites, you can simply write in the URL and
take your chances. The software tries to reformat standard HTML
pages for the small screen, but the results are mixed at best: When
I checked ZDNet's AnchorDesk, for example, I had to scroll through
five whole screens of clutter before the real copy even appeared.
</P>
<P>
   At a maximum of 19.2 kilobits per second, all of this happens
painfully slowly.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WIRELESS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The worst problem, though, is the unreliability of the service. I
encountered frequent problems _ often the Palm couldn't find the
modem, or it would report that it couldn't find the site I'd
requested and politely suggest that I try again in a few minutes.
These problems occur at all times of the day and in a variety of
locations, including places where the service has worked
previously.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I can't see spending $300 up front plus $40 a month for
something as flaky as this service has been for me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Compaq iPAQ Pocket PC Wireless Bundle
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I received Compaq's new iPAQ Pocket PC handheld just a week ago,
and the wireless modem and software for it arrived only a few days
ago. Consider this a preview rather a review.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq hasn't even set pricing yet for the bundle it plans to
offer, although it announced the product more than two months ago.
Separately, the iPAQ itself is $499; the Compaq jacket that slips
over it and provides a slot for PC Cards plus an extra battery is
$149; and the Aircard radio modem Compaq is using, made by Sierra
Wireless, lists for $549. That's $1,197 without even counting the
software _ which comes from a Vancouver, British Columbia, company
called Infowave _ or monthly service fees.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even if Compaq offers a discount for the whole
package, as a spokesman says it will, it will almost certainly cost
much more than the two products reviewed above.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq says it's marketing the product mainly at information
technology departments seeking to offer wireless services for
corporate employees, rather than at individuals; the Infowave
software included in the bundle works only with Microsoft Exchange
servers.
</P>
<P>
   Simply as a PDA, without regard to the wireless option, the iPAQ
looks like a big winner, at least for those willing to give
Microsoft's Pocket PC software a chance. Compared with the
Hewlett-Packard Jornada 545 Pocket PC I reviewed in April, the iPAQ
is thinner and lighter and has twice as much memory (32 megabytes).
With a 206-megahertz Intel StrongARM processor, it's also far and
away the zippiest PDA I've ever tested, and it has the brightest
color screen _ much better than the Jornada, the Palm IIIC or even
my beloved Cassiopeia E-100.
</P>
<P>
   You use an Infowave utility to go online with the wireless
modem; it provides authentication, compression and encryption. Once
you're connected, though, you use Microsoft's Pocket Outlook and
Internet Explorer for mail and Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to any Web site, but it's pretty slow _ it usually
took more than 30 seconds to display a new page. And in my brief
testing, I ran into even more glitches than with OmniSky and the
Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   Pocket Explorer does a decent job at displaying some sites on
the small screen, but with others _ including, ironically,
Infowave's own front page _ it draws a blank, literally. And in
some cases, such as SFGate and even MSN.com, I could get to the
site's front page but not to subordinate pages.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the iPAQ looks like a terrific PDA, but the wireless
bundle, whatever its price turns out to be, clearly needs lots of
work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Bottom Line &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, I firmly believe, we'll all be carrying wireless
Internet access devices of some sort. Before that can happen,
though, prices have to come down and bandwidth has to go up _
dramatically. And the hardware, software and service providers will
have to make their offerings far more trouble-free than this year's
latest products seem to be. If not, RIM and its trusty 1980s-era
technologies may end up ruling the wireless roost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of WIRELESS () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
