<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ZIMBABWE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ZIMBABWE'S CAMPAIGN OF INTIMIDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 22:
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe's 20 years as an independent nation, one man has led
it _ Robert Mugabe. He has never faced a serious challenge. But
this weekend the country is to choose a new parliament, and polls
show that the opposition would win a fair election. Zimbabweans may
have decided that ``Mugabe'' and ``Zimbabwe'' should no longer be
synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has responded to the prospect of defeat with demagoguery,
violence and intimidation. Gangs of his thugs roam the countryside,
killing and beating opposition activists. The balloting and vote
count may be flawed, as the government is limiting the number of
election observers. The outside world, especially South Africa and
Zimbabwe's smaller neighbors, must press Mugabe to end the
violence, hold a clean vote and vote count and abide by the
results.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe began his presidency by providing schools and health care
to the poor, but over two decades he became an autocrat surrounded
by corrupt and brutal men. One reason Zimbabwe has sent 11,000
troops to war in Congo, it is alleged, is that his generals profit
from trading in Congo diamonds. The war costs Zimbabwe millions of
dollars a month, while half the nation is unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mugabe has the support of all but three of Parliament's 150
members, and no strong opposition arose until last year, when the
Movement for Democratic Change was born to take part in rewriting
the constitution. Mugabe's draft, which would have broadened his
powers, lost in a popular referendum in February. Shaken by the
defeat, he began exploiting the issue of land reform. All major
parties endorse breaking up large farms, owned mainly by whites,
and distributing the land to poor blacks. For 20 years Mugabe did
little. Now, instead of beginning an orderly process with
compensation for landowners, he has encouraged his supporters in
the violent takeover of white-owned farms. They have killed one
farmer and beaten dozens of black farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   The bloodshed has spread. The opposition cannot campaign in much
of the countryside. At least 29 of its candidates and backers have
been killed, and many others raped or beaten, often as police stood
by. Recently the government offered the opposition some air time
and has begun to denounce violence, but has still made no real
effort to stop the thugs.
</P>
<P>
   It is now impossible for the election to be free. But the
opposition is determined to participate and could win if Mugabe
allowed the vote and vote count to proceed without fraud. This
means calling off his thugs, sending out word not to meddle with
ballots, and allowing all observers access to polling stations and
the counting process.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Britain, the European Union and the
Commonwealth nations should warn Mugabe that he and his cronies
will lose visas for foreign travel and their overseas bank accounts
if Zimbabwe's democracy dies. But Western nations are not trusted
or beloved by most Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
   The most important voice is that of South Africa, which has been
disappointingly silent. President Thabo Mbeki and the rest of
southern Africa's presidents should speak out publicly, as Botswana
has done. Southern African nations have a powerful interest in
keeping Zimbabwe from political and economic collapse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
