r s BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPOR     06-21 1653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAHAL'S PLANS FOR CART INCLUDE TEXAS MOTOR SPEEDWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interim CART president and CEO Bobby Rahal can name-drop with
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   His partner in Team Rahal on the Championship Auto Racing Teams
circuit is late-night talk show host David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Rahal and his wife, Debi, joined President Clinton
and Hillary Rodham Clinton at the White House for a state dinner in
honor of His Majesty Mohammad VI, king of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say that CART is not looking at a race in Morocco,''
Rahal deadpanned yesterday morning, before leaving his business
empire in Columbus, Ohio, for a round of meetings at the
sanctioning body's headquarters in Troy, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal has been up to his mustache in greetings and meetings
since Friday, when he was chosen by CART's board of directors to
replace Andrew Craig as president and chief executive officer for
an undisclosed period. Rahal may not have any quick fixes for the
schism that exists between CART and the rival Indy Racing League.
But his rise to power _ and Rahal would cringe at that description
_ is likely to have almost immediate impact on the schedule at
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said he is eager to speak with longtime friend Eddie
Gossage, TMS' executive vice president and general manager, about
the possibility of bringing a CART race to the track in Fort Worth
as early as the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken to Eddie as friends,'' said Rahal, who knew
Gossage during his days as a public relations representative for
Miller Brewing Co. on the CART circuit. ``Both he and I believe we
could put on one hell of a motor race \Rat TMS\S. I will say there
have been discussions, but nothing is formalized. If we go and are
able to put something together, I would certainly hope it would be
in 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal said he had not spoken with Gossage about racing at TMS
since being promoted last week. And Rahal also issued this
disclaimer for the 1.5-mile TMS quadoval and its 24-degree banked
turns:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to restrict the horsepower output for next year.
That would be taken into account.''
</P>
<P>
   The horsepower and speeds generated by CART's turbocharged V-8
engines was a genuine concern for Gossage during the summer of
1996, when he talked sanctioning agreements with both Craig and IRL
founder Tony George. TMS was designed, first and foremost, as a
NASCAR-style racetrack, right down to those high-banked, 24-degree
banked turns.
</P>
<P>
   But in an effort to attract and accommodate open-wheel
Indy-cars, the track also was built with ``dual banking.'' That
concept featured 8-degree banking built into the turns below the
24-degree banks. The lesser-banked turns supposedly would prevent
CART cars _ which have been clocked at more than 245 mph at the
California Speedway _ from ripping through the corners at TMS at
230-plus mph. Gossage deemed those speeds unreasonable for a safe
and competitive show back in 1996, when he opted to sign with the
IRL.
</P>
<P>
   An engineering flop, dual banking was eliminated when the track
was reconfigured and repaved between April-June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But CART's four engine manufacturers remain married to the
turbocharged formula. Horsepower figures are one of the great
secrets of the motorsports universe. But a figure between 800 to
900 horsepower is a safe estimate for the current generation of
CART engines produced by American Honda, Ford Motor Company,
Mercedes-Benz and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the IRL is in the first season of operating with
downsized 3.5-liter engines. The IRL's normally aspirated
Oldsmobile Aurora and Nissan Infiniti V-8s crank out anywhere from
650 to 700 horsepower. That was more than enough to create an
afternoon of NASCAR-style side-by-side racing, and drafting, and
the closest finish in IRL history during the Casino Magic 500 on
June 11.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL formula is a proven perfect fit for TMS. How can CART
compete with that here, and on the other ovals where it already
races?
</P>
<P>
   Knock off horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be looking at a 150 to 200 horsepower reduction,''
Rahal said. ``We've tried to govern that by aerodynamically
`spoiling' the cars. And the reality is ... the engines just
produce too much power. We will push our manufacturers ... there
already has been a lot of good discussion on how we can govern
these engines more so for 2001, perhaps with \Rair\S inlet
restrictors. While it's going to be expensive to some degree, we've
got to get the product better on the racetrack. That will allow us
to run normal wings and see the racing we want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   And we all want to see CART racing at Texas Motor Speedway.
SPOTLIGHT ON...
Mayfield enjoying status after tapping Earnhardt
His bump-and-run victory at the expense of Dale Earnhardt
apparently has elevated Jeremy Mayfield into some kind of overnight
NASCAR Winston Cup cult hero.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield did beat ``The Intimidator'' at his own nasty game on
the final lap of the rain-delayed Pocono 500 on Monday at Pocono
International Raceway, using his front bumper to root Earnhardt out
of the lead. But overlooked amid Mayfield's chest-beating act is
this big-picture fact _ 15 races into the 34-race season, Earnhardt
remains a serious contender for an unprecedented eighth Winston Cup
championship.
</P>
<P>
   After the bump, Earnhardt recovered to finish fourth. He earned
165 points, picking up 41 points on series leader and native Texan
Bobby Labonte. With midseason approaching, Earnhardt is only 57
points behind Labonte in the chase for the one prize missing from
his life. Consider that after 15 races last year, Earnhardt stood
seventh, 475 points behind leader and eventual champion Dale
Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got beat. He \RMayfield\S got me,'' said Earnhardt, mindful
that he was crucified for a similar move against Terry Labonte at
Bristol Motor Speedway in August. ``All in all, it was a good day
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, meanwhile, has spent the week blowing stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I've blown up two answering machines and \Ram\S working
on a third,'' said Mayfield, who scored his third career Cup
victory. ``A lot of them \Rcalls\S came from friends and from
family, but I got a ton of messages from people I don't even know.
They were just excited. I can't blame them. I'm pretty excited
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's ``move'' also has proven popular in cyberspace. On
Tuesday afternoon, Mayfield participated in a live chat on NASCAR
Online (www.nascar.com), where a typical session draws
approximately 6,500 hits. Mayfield, however, logged 61,000 hits _
nearly 10 times the norm and a record for the popular site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nice that so many people are happy for us,'' said
Mayfield, driver of the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus. ``You call it a
`move' or whatever, but it's just hard-nosed racing. A lot of
people talk about Dale Earnhardt; he came up the hard way and
drives that way. So did I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnhardt ... he doesn't really race you, like, dirty, like he
used to wreck you all the time. He doesn't do that anymore. He just
races hard, and the same thing I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The fan who fired a can of beer at Mayfield's Ford from behind
the pit wall at Pocono (and missed) certainly disagreed with
Jeremy's self-assessment.
</P>
<P>
   So did the 50,726 fans (51 percent) who predicted in a NASCAR
Online poll that Earnhardt would win that elusive eighth
championship in 2000 and elevate himself to ultimate Winston Cup
cult hero.
PIT STOPS Cheever stays course Three races remain between Eddie
Cheever Jr. and an improbable Indy Racing Northern Light Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   But if form holds, Cheever will emerge as Indy Racing League
champion after the season-ending Mall.com 500 at Texas Motor
Speedway on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, driver of the No. 51 Excite &LR; Home Dallara/Infiniti,
ended the Oldsmobile Aurora's 34-race stranglehold on the series
and gave Nissan North America its first victory at Pikes Peak
International Raceway on Sunday. Cheever will take a tenuous
eight-point lead over Buddy Lazier into Atlanta Motor Speedway on
July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Every driver who has won the June race at PPIR has captured the
championship: Tony Stewart (1997), Kenny Brack (1998), and Plano's
Greg Ray, who won both races at Fountain, Colo., last season.
</P>
<P>
   Given that history and the current Infiniti V-8s reliability,
Cheever said it was unlikely that he would switch to the
next-generation Nissan 35-A this season. But Frank Honsowetz,
manager of Infiniti motorsports, said a second car could be entered
with the updated engine at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest enhancement is the engine is going to be at the
\RIRL\S minimum weight of 330 pounds. We're over that weight right
now,'' Honsowetz said. ``The center of gravity is going to be
lower. And it'll be two inches shorter at the rear, which is a
direct interchange with the competitor's engine. Everybody at
Nissan North America is ecstatic.'' Last laps The Toyo Tires Street
Legal Challenge will be added to the AAA Texas Friday Street Night
program at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis beginning tomorrow. The
series is open to any competitor with DOT street-legal tires, a
current inspection sticker and mufflers. For information, call
(972) 878-2641.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schumacher's victory in the waterlogged Canadian Grand
Prix on Sunday was the 40th of his Formula One career. The Ferrari
ace is only one victory behind the late Ayrton Senna for second
place on the career F1 list.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon will be gunning for an unprecedented sixth
consecutive Winston Cup road-course victory at Sears Point Raceway
in Sonoma, Calif., on Sunday. Gordon is tied for first in all-time
road-course victories with Richard Petty, Bobby Allison and Rusty
Wallace. The last word ``I did it. I did it. I don't believe, but I
believe it, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Helio Castroneves, after scoring his first CART victory in the
Grand Prix of Detroit
