<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-A&AMP;M-RECRUITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M SAVORS TWO RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Like most everyone connected with Southern
Laboratory High School, Kevin Augustine is sad to see Nick Anderson
move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss him. We'll all miss him,'' said Augustine,
financial-aid officer at nearby Southern University who does
volunteer work at the school. ``But you know who is going to miss
him the most? The babies. The little ones here at the school
idolize him.''
</P>
<P>
   At Southern Lab, grades kindergarten through 12 are on the same
campus adjacent to Southern University. And if the younger set at
the school is going to miss Anderson, a Texas A&AMP;M basketball
recruit regarded as one of the top college prospects this year,
then the feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss them, too,'' Anderson said. ``I like to clown around
on the court sometimes. I'll make a dunk and start dancing, just
for them, and they really love that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, but little kids just like me. I guess it's
something natural. Sometimes I'll go to their PE classes and play
basketball with them and let them beat me. It makes them feel
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand that there's reason for a warm feeling for anyone
besting the Southern Lab star. The 6-foot-6 Anderson and his
teammates won four consecutive Louisiana Class A state
championships while posting a 124-9 record. The Joel
Hawkins-coached Kittens have won eight consecutive titles during
his 12 seasons as basketball coach and dean of students at the
tuition-funded public high school.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was more often than not the leading scorer the past
four years, but guard Trayvean Scott was the point guard who made
it all happen. Both signed with the Aggies in November and are
regarded as key building blocks in A&AMP;M coach Melvin Watkins'
fledgling program, which boasted the Big 12 freshman of the year
last season in guard Bernard King of Gibsland, La.
</P>
<P>
   With Kansas recruit DeShawn Stevenson headed for the NBA,
Anderson ranks among the Big 12's most highly regarded freshman
recruits, along with Texas' Brian Boddicker and Missouri's Travon
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just an unbelievable talent,'' Watkins said of Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the 12 years, he is the one,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Anderson helps Watkins rebuild the Aggies' basketball
program, he must first get a high enough ACT score. Anderson said
he is only a point shy of achieving the NCAA minimum of 18 to be
eligible as a freshman. He should get results of a test he took in
April by the end of the month. He already has plans to retake the
test if necessary. Bryant is in a similar predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm right there,'' Anderson said of a passing mark. ``I came
out of the test in April with a good feeling. I'm going to pass it.
But if I don't, I'm going to enroll at A&AMP;M anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson can practice as a partial qualifier as a freshman and
have three years of eligibility remaining. Scott, with a typical
take-charge attitude, said his buddy is going to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we start practice in October, I want to see Nick
practicing to play _ next season,'' said Scott, who carried a 3.7
grade-point average this spring and passed a qualifying test as a
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Anderson's potential collegiate position, Watkins
shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick could be effective at three positions,'' he said, naming
off guard and both forward spots. ``But he's just going to play.
He'll make me play him, somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   An athletic player with an effective shot out to 15 feet,
Anderson averaged 23.7 points and 14 rebounds last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick is blessed with rare athleticism that you don't find in
many kids,'' Hawkins said. ``He is also one of the better high
school quarter-milers in the nation and doesn't even train for the
event. Things come easy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   While those who follow recruiting know all about Anderson, Scott
may be the sleeper in A&AMP;M's recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1 guard averaged 21.4 points and 9.3 assists last season.
But A&AMP;M didn't take him just to get Anderson. The two made up their
minds on their college choice independently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trayvean adds immediate depth to the backcourt,'' Watkins
said. ``The biggest value he brings is his court awareness. He will
come in and challenge for playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Pastner, the celebrated walk-on guard at Arizona who
coached Anderson and Scott on the Houston Hoops AAU team that won
the national championship last summer, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind he proved last summer he was the best young
defender in America _ period,'' Pastner said. ``Trayvean can shoot
the ball. He can handle \Rit\S. He takes great pride in his
defense, and not many kids do that. He will open up a lot of eyes
as a freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott is nothing if not confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams usually try to deny me the ball to keep me from
shooting,'' Scott said. ``But since I bring the ball up most of the
time, that's hard to do. If they get up on me, I'll go by them. Do
that two or three times, and they back off. Then, I'll shoot. But
playing with Nick, the defense has had to play honest most of the
time anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastner, meanwhile, calls Anderson the type of player ``you
build a program around.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott agrees, citing his friend's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is give Nick the ball and he will deliver.
He is a great finisher,'' Scott said. ``I've seen Nick jump
``over'' people. And all you have to do is have someone on the
other team who can compete. Someone who Nick knows or hears about,
and he is the man. I've seen Nick play against bigger guys and just
totally dominate a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson did just that in the 68-42 state championship victory
over Grambling High this year when he scored 25 points, pulled down
19 rebounds, blocked 11 shots and passed out seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick totally destroyed them,'' Hawkins said. ``And you
wouldn't expect to see that in a state championship game, because
there are two pretty good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said he once thought both would go to Houston. Then
Vanderbilt and Notre Dame got interested in Scott because of his
academic qualifications. But both players said they were won over
by A&AMP;M's coaching staff, the chance to play for Watkins and the
lure of being part of a resurgence of Aggies basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to get thrown into the fire,'' Scott said.
``The only question is how we respond. You say A&AMP;M is not used to
winning, but the players in the program now ``are'' used to
winning. You're going to be hearing a lot about A&AMP;M basketball in
the next two, three years.''
Nick Anderson
</P>
<P>
   Height: 6-foot-6
</P>
<P>
   Weight: 225
</P>
<P>
   Position: Forward
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Two-time Louisiana all-state player. ... Played on four
consecutive Class A state championship teams. ... MVP of the 2000
state tournament. ... Member of the gold-medal winning team at the
1999 USA Men's Basketball Youth Development Festival and the 1999
national AAU championship Houston Hoops teams. ... Ranked as high
as No. 8 prospect nationally by one recruiting service. ... Hobby
is bowling, with a high game of 230.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
