<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GLYNN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WAIT TOO LONG TO BRING BACK RYAN GLYNN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Hum along now, if you will, to that famous
baseball song from ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where have you gone,
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Glynn? A nation
</P>
<P>
   Turns its lonely eyes to you.
</P>
<P>
   Whoo, whoo, whoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I know, it doesn't have quite the same catchy rhythm as
Joe DiMaggio, but you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Where the ding-dong dickens has this kid been, for crying out
loud?
</P>
<P>
   Glynn returns today, finally, and not a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, give or take another Rangers' butt-kicking or
three, the young right-hander up from Triple-A Oklahoma slammed the
door on the Dodgers for eight impressive shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   No other Rangers' starter this season has strung eight zeros
together in the same game, but then, you didn't need me to tell you
that.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Glynn's timely conquest of the Dodgers, the
Rangers contritely handed him his bus ticket back to the minors,
telling him, in so many words, that there was no room at the inn.
</P>
<P>
   Shutting out the NL West contenders was fine and dandy but that
didn't mean he could just walk in here and crack this vaunted
Rangers' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   So, Glynn, who must have been privately asking himself what a
guy has to do win a job around here, quietly went back to Oklahoma
and the Rangers promptly went into the tank.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen days, five miserable combined starts from Darren
Oliver, Esteban Loaiza and Mark Clark and one nine-game losing
streak later, Glynn will finally get another crack.
</P>
<P>
   He's coming back because an orthopedic specialist told the
Rangers yesterday that there's something wrong with Oliver's arm.
</P>
<P>
   Duuuuhhhhhh!
</P>
<P>
   I could have saved them a lot of money. A few of us, including
Oliver himself, have been suggesting the same thing for a couple of
weeks now.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I've heard all the excuses why Glynn couldn't stay. I'm
just having a hard time buying them considering what we've seen the
past couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and Clark have fat contracts. Big money is on the line.
And for the Rangers to have any hope of defending their AL West
title, they need Loaiza to snap out of it and pitch as he did in
the second half last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do it, it has to be the right time,'' manager Johnny
Oates tried to explain again last night before the Rangers and
Twins met in the second game of a three-game series. ``It's easy to
tell people what should and shouldn't be done. Those people who
have all the answers don't have to deal with the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequences? You mean like another strong performance from
Glynn? Or one or two less from one or more of the scoreboard
assassins mentioned above? Yeah, that would be hard to live with.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, sometime over the past two wretched weeks, there had to
be a place where a guy with a 0.00 earned-run average could have
helped. Heck, in that time span, the starter who was listed ``No.
3'' in the Redhawks' rotation _ behind Glynn and left-hander Doug
Davis _ was traded to Florida for Dave Martinez and has made
back-to-back brilliant starts (1.95 ERA) for the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But I guess Chuck Smith couldn't pitch here, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Glynn, at that point, wasn't going to pitch but three
times in four weeks,'' Oates said, which begs one question: Why?
``It wasn't the right time to start revamping this club.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to make changes too quick. We made some big
mistakes if 10 weeks into the season we have to make major
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, so?
</P>
<P>
   ``For the investment we've made,'' Oates continued, ``how are
you going to know in 10 weeks?''
</P>
<P>
   Please. It's not as though the jury's still out on Mark Clark.
At $5 million a year, he's a bigger bust than Dolly Parton. Release
him and eat his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver has been complaining of a tired arm for weeks and should
have been rested two starts ago. Loaiza, who treats a lead like a
bar of soap, has been inexplicably ineffective. Maybe he needs a
few weeks in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put Loaiza out there on the market right now and see what
happens,'' Oates said. ``Teams would be lining up to try and get
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, they probably would, which is more a comment on the
state of pitching in the big leagues than any vote of confidence in
Loaiza. But in his three June starts before last night's outing
against the Twins, he'd coughed up 14 earned runs in 131/3 innings.
That just won't do.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand general manager Doug Melvin and Oates not
wanting to give up on the season in mid-June. They shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   I understand that they have $19 million invested in Oliver over
the next three years and that there are no guarantees that Matt
Perisho or Glynn are sure-thing, bona fide big-league starters.
</P>
<P>
   But it's definitely time to find out, before the season gives up
on the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, Ryan Glynn. You've been gone too long.
</P>
<P>
   {Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
