<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY PUTS SKAKEL AT SCENE OF MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn._ A boyhood friend of Michael Skakel's testified
in court Wednesday that Skakel admitted years later that on the
night their 15-year-old friend Martha Moxley was murdered in 1975,
he was in the tree directly above where her body was found the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The friend, Andrew Pugh, said that Skakel, then also 15, had
``an attraction, an infatuation'' with Moxley. Pugh lived across
the street from the Skakels and around the corner from the Moxley
family in the exclusive Belle Haven section of Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   He testified Wednesday that he believed that Skakel, a nephew of
Ethel Kennedy, had committed the murder. When he confronted his old
friend with that suspicion in a 1991 telephone conversation, he
said, Skakel denied that he killed her but admitted that he had
been in the Moxleys' yard the night she died.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh was one of the two final witnesses called by prosecutors
Wednesday in their effort to persuade a juvenile court judge to
refer the case to Superior Court, putting Skakel, 39, on trial as
an adult. He is now charged in the case as a juvenile. If convicted
as an adult, he could face 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's swift completion of its case in this
``reasonable cause'' hearing offered a striking contrast to the
investigation of the case, which dragged on for nearly a
quarter-century until Skakel's indictment early this year. The
hearing will resume next Wednesday with the defense witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual case against Skakel, in which an adult is charged
with murder as a juvenile, has already broken legal ground. It is
the first juvenile court proceeding fully open to the media and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's final witness was Judith Kallen, an official
with the State Department of Children and Families. The prosecutor,
Jonathan C. Benedict, sought to demonstrate that the Connecticut
juvenile justice system has no mechanisms for dealing with a
criminal offender over age 18, suggesting that Skakel must be tried
as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   By law, inmates in juvenile detention must be released at age
18, she testified, adding that state officials now use
psychologists and other experts to determine whether a juvenile
defendant should be tried as an adult, focusing on the child's
chances of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   But Skakel's lawyer, Michael Sherman, pointed out during
cross-examination that this case was like no other. He suggested
that the nearly 25-year delay in bringing the case to court had
provided state officials ``a crystal ball'' showing all they needed
to know about Skakel's chances of rehabilitation and becoming a
productive member of society.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman asked Kallen if that was sufficient evidence of
potential for rehabilitation. Under a 1975 law, one requirement of
transferring a juvenile case to Superior Court is a finding that
``the safety of the community requires that the child continue
under restraint for a period extending beyond his majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Kallen told Sherman that she did ``not have that kind of
expertise,'' adding, ``I have never had to look back at somebody's
behavior over a 24-year period.'' Sherman quickly replied, ``Not
until now.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sherman presents his case next week, Judge Maureen Dennis
will determine whether to transfer the case to Superior Court, to
allow a trial to proceed before her in juvenile court without a
jury, or to dismiss the matter entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has made it clear that the rules relating to a
``reasonable cause'' hearing allow her wide latitude, and she also
admonished both Benedict and Sherman, who have given frequent
interviews, to reread the ethics guidelines for lawyers about
talking to the media.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the first day of the pretrial hearing, two former
classmates of Skakel's testified that he confessed to the murder in
the late 1970s while at a school for troubled youths in Maine. One
of them, Gregory Coleman, completed his testimony Wednesday
morning. Coleman, who was convicted of a robbery in the 1980s, was
brought from a prison near Rochester, where he is serving a
yearlong sentence for criminal trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his testimony Wednesday came in response to questions
from Sherman about his requests for money and for help from
Connecticut officials. Coleman has received neither for his
testimony, though he acknowledged that he had made several mistakes
in his testimony before a grand jury in the Moxley case in 1998 and
that his abuse of drugs and alcohol over more than 20 years had
affected his memory.
</P>
<P>
   But Skakel's sister and brothers, who filled a first row in the
courtroom, seemed to pay most attention to the testimony of Pugh,
the former family friend. He said that he and Skakel had been close
when they were teen-agers, but had drifted apart after the Moxley
murder and had little or no contact during the 1980s. But in 1991
they bumped into each other at Christ Church in Greenwich, where
Pugh was attending an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed resuming their friendship, Pugh testified, but he
said he told Skakel in a subsequent telephone conversation that it
``could be difficult for me because I had some doubts as to his
involvement'' and asked if Skakel had committed the crime. ``He
said `No,''' Pugh testified. ``He told me that he had been on their
property,'' but that he had nothing to do with Moxley's death.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Pugh conceded that Skakel never
specified which tree he meant on the Moxley property, but the
witness said he believed it to be the tall pine in the Moxley yard
that he and Skakel had climbed frequently as children. Moxley's
body was found under it on Oct. 31, 1975, her head bludgeoned with
a golf club taken from a set that belonged to Rushton Skakel,
Skakel's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``That conversation kind of, shall I say, addled me slightly,''
Pugh testified Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
