<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL TO RETURN NEXT WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Ken Hill will return to the starting rotation next
Wednesday in Seattle, a little more than six since he slumped over
in pain on the Edison Field mound, the result of a strained
rib-cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   That means one of the pitchers in the starting rotation has to
go, and the likely candidate is Seth Etherton, whose start Friday
against the Twins will be his last here -- at least until the next
Angels pitcher goes down. Etherton is 2-1 with a 5.20 ERA in five
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Before his injury, Hill was 3-4 with a 7.41 ERA. In his final
rehab start for Triple-A Edmonton on Tuesday, he gave up three runs
(two earned) and seven hits in 5 fr 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tuesday) I felt pretty good,'' Hill said. ``With rehab, I
went at it pretty good. It's just different because of the hitters.
They have one thing in mind -- make the big leagues -- so they're
swinging. It's tough to evaluate how good your stuff really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill made 90 pitches Tuesday, and manager Mike Scioscia said he
believes Hill will be able to throw up to 100 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident he's ready to take the ball,'' Scioscia said.
``The command early was good, but it wasn't later in the game.
That's a battle a lot of pitchers have. But he came out of spring
pitching very strong, and we're looking forward to having those
results again.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hill, stepping on a major league mound for the first time
since May 9 will be like starting the season again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question it's going to be like that,'' Hill said. ``It's a
new season for me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hill is about to return, a couple others are not close.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI exam performed on pitcher Scott Schoeneweis confirmed he
has a strained oblique muscle in his right side. Schoeneweis said
he might have injured himself hitting when playing in Arizona under
National League rules on June 11. He had to leave his next start
last Friday when pitching in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   There is no timetable for his return, and consequently,
Schoeneweis is frustrated: ``I've got nothing to say. I'm not
talking to you guys until after I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jason Dickson was scheduled to start tonight for
Edmonton in his rehab assignment, but instead was in Anaheim
Wednesday having an MRI performed on his right shoulder. The MRI
showed further wear and tear on his labrum, and as a result he has
been shut down indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson originally went to the disabled list with a strained
hip, but later felt strain in his surgically repaired shoulder as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival has blown two of his last three save
opportunities, but Scioscia reiterated his faith in his closer.
Overall, Percival has 17 saves (tied for second in the league) and
five blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you something about Troy Percival,'' Scioscia
said. ``This guy is one of the premier closers in baseball.
Everyone in their career, everyone in a season is going to hit a
bump in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy was not effective (Tuesday) night or in Tampa (last
Wednesday). But this guy will be there in the end. That's why we
consider ourselves a championship-caliber ballclub. As long as his
arm continues to feel as well as it has, there's no question he'll
be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS VS. KANSAS CITY
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: FSN; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Tim Belcher (1-0, 1.69 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Kansas City's Jay Witasick (1-6, 6.19). The start will be
Belcher's second this season, and if it is anything like the first,
the Angels are in good hands. Belcher gave up just one run and five
hits in 5 fr 1/3 innings in an 8-3 victory over Baltimore last
Saturday. -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
